<HEADLINE>
BUSH WINS MORE DELEGATES IN SUPER SHOWING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Optional ending included) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush of Texas scored solid delegate victories across
the country Tuesday, making it all but impossible for the flagging
insurgent John McCain to deny him the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cruised to victory in delegate battles in California, Ohio,
Maryland, Missouri and Georgia, and appeared to have won more
delegates than McCain in the hard-fought battle in New York, the
second biggest prize on the richest day of primary voting in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had scattered successes and strong showings in the more
liberal Northeast, including victories in Massachusetts,
Connecticut, Rhode Island and Vermont, a state where a flood of
Democrats and independents outnumbered Republicans in the GOP
primary. But Bush denied McCain a New England sweep by winning
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, watching returns early in the evening at the Governor's
Mansion in Austin, Texas, seemed to shy away from claiming the role
as the Republicans' presumptive nominee. But he warmed to the job
in a statement to a victory party in an Austin hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a national victory,'' Bush said. ``Republicans and
conservatives from all across America have said they want me to
lead the Republican Party to victory come November, and I am ready
and eager to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, speaking to supporters in Los Angeles, was equivocal
about the future of his campaign, saying he and Bush ``may meet
again'' soon in future primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would ``take a little time to reflect on the
direction'' of his effort, which has been an attempt not only to
win the nomination but also to reshape the Republican Party as an
agent of political reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's statement came eight months to the day before the general
election in which he hopes to be the Republican to return the White
House to GOP hands after eight years of Democrat Bill Clinton and
his vice president, Al Gore, who became the presumptive Democratic
nominee by winning every contest Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon our party will unite and turn to the main task at hand _
ending the era of Clinton and Gore,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone will make history this November. Either we will ratify
the status quo, or we will have a new beginning in American
politics. I say: America must not give Clinton-Gore a third term.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the evening, McCain said he was ``optimistic that this
trend'' from New England would continue, but his hopes were dashed
when Bush's victory built as the vote-counting rolled west.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does it appear that we'll win an overwhelming number
of delegates, it also appears we'll achieve a few surprises,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Based on early returns and exit polls, the Texas governor
appeared to escape embarrassment by narrowly beating the Arizona
senator in the non-binding but perceptually important ``beauty
contest'' ballot in California that was open to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes remains in the
race but was not a major factor in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Six hundred thirteen delegates to the Republican National
Convention were at stake, by Associated Press calculations, and
Bush appeared on track to claim the lion's share, including the 162
in California's winner-take-all delegate battle.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the 170 delegates he had before Tuesday, that left
Bush in a much stronger position than McCain to eventually run up
the 1,034 needed to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Other delegate counts put Bush far closer to the magic number
already.
</P>
<P>
   McCain must now decide if he will press on; and, if he does,
what is his rationale in the face of Bush's mounting delegate
count.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has scheduled campaign stops later this week in Colorado
and Illinois but not before stopping Wednesday at his vacation home
in Cottonwood, Ariz., where he is expected to discuss his future
plans with senior campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   Some aides were prepared to tell McCain to pull the plug before
criticism mounts from party leaders that a continued campaign will
do nothing but soften Bush up for the contest against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign gave McCain plenty of room to maneuver but its
view of what should happen was unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be up to Senator McCain to decide how to proceed,''
Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, McCain and top aides had cast Tuesday's mass of
primaries as decisive, but over the weekend he backed off and said
he might be looking as much for momentum as for a string of
victories over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But without the victories, momentum may be hard to come by,
especially when coupled with next week's concentration of Sun Belt
primaries, including Texas and Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is
governor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain not only faces a treacherous calendar but a shrinking
bank account. Because he has accepted federal matching funds,
McCain can only lay out about $4 million more before hitting the
$40 million primary spending cap.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, because he has not accepted federal funding in the
primary, can raise and spend unlimited amounts until the Republican
National Convention at Philadelphia that begins in late July. He
had raised a record $70 million and spent $50 million through the
end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's strong showing in most of the big states was based on his
appeal to traditional Republicans, especially religious
conservatives who were likely perturbed by McCain's recent attacks
on movement leaders such as Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, despite his cross-party appeal, has ruled out an
independent or third-party presidential candidacy. But his strength
with voters dissatisfied with how government is performing was one
of the reeds he clung to as the size of his loss became apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly our message of reform has had a powerful impact,''
McCain said in a statement issued early in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The voting, which amounted to a national primary, came at the
end of six weeks of back-and-forth victories.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, long the GOP establishment's favorite, was the easy victor
in the season-opening Iowa caucuses, where McCain did not mount a
serious campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Next came New Hampshire, where McCain had camped for months and
scored a big victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rebounded in South Carolina, only to tumble to McCain three
days later in Michigan, where a majority of voters in the
Republican primary were actually Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   Again Bush bounced back last week with a triple victory in
Virginia, North Dakota and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign said Tuesday that the Federal Communications
Commission had launched an inquiry into television commercials
aired recently by Dallas multimillionaires Charles and Sam Wyly in
support of Bush's campaign under the banner of Republicans for
Clean Air.
</P>
<P>
   McCain operatives contend that the commercials, when delivered
to the stations, did not conform to FCC regulations because they
did not disclose the Wylys' financial backing for the spots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
