<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEWYORK-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE VICTORIOUS AS INSURGENT RIVALS FIZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs for complete rewrite; note new byline)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the fervent backing of New York's Republican
establishment, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas wrestled his way to
victory Tuesday over John McCain in a state that had once seemed
fertile ground for the senator from Arizona. Bush won a solid
majority of both the delegates and the total Republican votes in
the state's first contested presidential primary since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, New York: You have just pushed George W. Bush
over the top to be the next president of the United States,'' Gov.
George Pataki of New York declared at a victory rally in Manhattan,
looking visibly relieved as he celebrated an outcome on which
Pataki arguably had as much riding as Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, a presidential primary that had
uncustomarily been almost lost in the shadow of the Republican
fight fizzled to an end, as Vice President Al Gore swamped Bill
Bradley in a state where Bradley, too, once thought he had a real
opportunity to derail a candidate backed by the party
establishment. Bradley did not even wait for half the votes to be
counted, appearing before a somber audience of supporters in
Manhattan to both concede and signal his imminent withdrawal from
his race.
</P>
<P>
   The results in the Republican primary in New York offered a
dramatic conclusion to a political struggle that in the space of
two weeks revealed strains not only in the national Republican
Party, as Bush and McCain engaged in pitched and personal battle on
the state's airwaves, but in New York's Republican organization as
well. The differences in New York were at least momentarily set
aside in victory Tuesday night, as Pataki appeared on stage with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who had scorned Pataki for guiding a Bush
campaign in New York that was based on attacking McCain's voting
record.
</P>
<P>
   By initial indications, at least, that strategy _ combined with
a Republican primary system designed to help the candidate backed
by the party establishment _ appears to have served Bush well. A
series of public polls over the past few days suggested that
McCain, who presented himself as a moderate, was tied with Bush in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The final result was not that close. In New York, Republicans
vote not for candidates but for 93 delegates. With 42 percent of
the precincts counted last night, Bush had 67 delegates, compared
to 11 for McCain. A third candidate, Alan Keyes, had not won any
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A tally of the popular vote found that with 94 percent of the
districts counted, Bush had 50 percent of the votes cast for
delegates and McCain had 43 percent. Keyes had 3 percent and Steve
Forbes, whose name remained on the ballot, even though he has
withdrawn from the race, 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The percentages reflect the number of votes cast for delegates
supporting each candidate, and Republicans could select up to three
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain did better in New York City suburbs and wealthy areas of
the city than Bush, with McCain apparently winning four of the six
delegates in Suffolk County, according to the state Board of
Elections. In fact, a war horse of Republican politics in New York,
state Sen. Roy Goodman of the Upper East Side, lost in his bid to
become one of Bush's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   New York was the second-largest of the states holding primaries
Tuesday, and one in which Bush's strength had long been suspect.
The stakes were particularly high in the state for Pataki and the
state Republican Party, which had orchestrated a tough campaign
against McCain, first attempting, without success, to keep McCain
off the New York ballot, and then orchestrating a series of attacks
on McCain that many Republicans, including Giuliani, described as
overly negative.
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions of Bush's win was seized as something of a
vindication by Pataki and his aides, who made no effort to hide
their feelings at the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, I'm relieved,'' Pataki confessed after leaving the
stage. ``This was a tough one.'' His chief strategist, Zenia Mucha,
said that in watching the exit polls during the day, which
suggested at times suggested a dead heat, ``I must have died a
thousand deaths.'' Mucha made the sign of the cross as she made the
remark.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The vote brought an end to hectic contest that offered the world
a detailed glimpse at the complexity of a New York election system
designed, in ways obvious and not, to help incumbents and the party
leaders, which was to the clear benefit of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The first manifestation of this came when Bush's main supporters
in New York, Pataki and William D. Powers, the state Republican
chairman, marshaled obscure portions of New York's restrictive
election law to try to keep McCain from appearing on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy collapsed when a judge ordered the ballot opened up
to McCain and other Republican challengers. But once McCain won
that battle, a new one emerged in the form of the convoluted way in
which the Republican Party conducts its primaries in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a statewide vote on the candidates _ the customary
way elections are conducted in the nation _ Republicans cast their
votes in 31 congressional districts, and not for the candidates
themselves, but the three delegates and three alternates pledged to
them. The candidates' names appeared in tiny type under the names
of the delegates who, in Bush's case, tended to be well-known
elected officials selected to run by the state Republican machine.
Aside from the 93 delegates, party leaders select another eight
at-large delegates.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Democratic vote was much more clear-cut, with
the names of Bradley and Gore appearing in bold type at the top of
the ballot, followed by the names of their delegates.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The system was applauded by Bush's supporters, who said it
provided the Texas governor a major tactical advantage over McCain.
Whether or not that was true, it proved to be a matter of
frustration to Republicans, who found that the simple act of voting
for their preferred candidate was anything but easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insane!'' declared Joseph Goldman, 55 of Great Neck, flipping
his eye glasses off and on as he strained to figure out how to vote
for McCain. ``This was just horrific. I never in my life saw
anything like this. You had to look at at this itsy bitsy print.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are asking you to vote for the delegates for each
candidate but I never heard of the delegates,'' he said, adding:
``The candidates are in 6-point type.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to turn the machine to Bush's advantage, Pataki
and his advisers also orchestrated a campaign of attacks on McCain,
highlighting votes he took in Congress that might prove unpopular
with New Yorkers in mailings and radio advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   McCain repeatedly attacked the tactics employed by Bush in New
York as unfair and distortive, and exit polls found that a slight
majority of Republicans thought that Bush spent more time attacking
his opponent than explaining what he wanted to do. And in
interviews, several New Yorkers said they were concerned both with
how Bush conducted his campaign, and particularly with Pataki's
role in trying to keep McCain off the ballot.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I was all behind Pataki until that happened,'' said Norman A.
Ernst Jr., who added that he had once liked Bush but ended up
voting for McCain. ``This is the most undemocratic thing that can
be done. It's upsetting to me when the Republicans espouse very
democratic principles and here they are trying to keep McCain off
the ballot and there being this confusion on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of voters leaving the polls found that the patterns
that had shaped the Republican primaries across the nation these
past six weeks continued in New York. Among registered Republicans,
those who identified themselves as conservatives supported Bush,
while those who said they were moderate or liberal supported
McCain. Only registered Republicans were allowed to vote in the
Republican primary in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
