<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-STRATEGY-NY     03-08 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, GORE AND BUSH CAN CONCENTRATE ON EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, there were enough sweet victories Tuesday night so that
they could begin to focus on running against each other in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Each planned to treat his primary rival with respect to unify
his party. But neither worried about losing the nomination anymore.
</P>
<P>
   They have been toughened by a primary campaign that replaced a
mere party coronation. They now can try to correct some things,
like Bush's swing toward his party's right after losing in New
Hampshire. But there are also matters they can do little or nothing
about, like Gore's embarrassing fund-raising appearance at a
Buddhist temple in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has particular reason to worry about voters who supported
Sen. John McCain. A poll of voters in California Tuesday showed
that of those who voted for McCain in the Republican primary, about
two-fifths planned to desert the Republican Party and vote for Gore
in the fall. Only a handful of the Democratic primary voters who
backed Bradley expected to defect from Gore in November.
</P>
<P>
   The first steps toward courting the voters for McCain and, on
the Democratic side, Sen. Bill Bradley, were taken Tuesday night
when the victors praised the men who had made their lives
difficult. Gore said in Nashville, Tenn., that Bradley was a ``good
man for whom I have great respect.'' He said, ``Anybody who has
heard Bill Bradley throughout this campaign has come away from the
experience moved and touched by the strength of his commitment to
healing the divisions in our country, especially divisions based on
race.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges to Bush are more obvious. While the campaign
answered, in the affirmative, one question about him _ whether he
could take a punch _ it dislodged him from the stance he had taken
at the start of his campaign: that of the ``compassionate
conservative'' who could get votes from Hispanics and
African-Americans, the practical reformer who could offer something
different from ideology-bound congressional Republicans,
</P>
<P>
   Just on Monday, Bush tried to mend the tears in that robe,
speaking out for tolerance and softening his opposition to talking
to gay Republicans. But the necessity of winning in South Carolina
a few weeks ago forced a dependence in his campaign on the
Christian right, which scares suburban Republicans, whom the Gore
campaign can be expected to keep reminding of that link.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Bush went back to the message of his announcement
speech last summer, saying in his advance text, ``This campaign has
had a cause, a vision of change for our party and our country.
Republicans must expand our prosperity, and extend it to those who
still struggle. We must be a strong nation that also cares for the
weak and forgotten. We must welcome the new Americans _ Americans
by choice _ because legal immigration is not a source of national
weakness, it is a sign of national success. We are a party of
principle. We must also be a party of inclusion _ a party with a
gracious heart and an open door.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore was drawn to the left by Bradley's challenge, that
challenge involved no dramatic political change; and, except for
Gore's opposition to current military policy on gay soldiers,
nothing that Bush could really attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley challenge to Gore came earlier than the McCain run
at Bush. That gave the vice president the chance to sharpen his
approach last fall, and not, like Bush, in the heat of the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Another need Bush has is to broaden the structure of his
campaign to include both non-Texans and Republicans with national
experience. His is a campaign that has not looked smooth while
winning. The Bush campaign ignored the traditional style of open
campaigning in New Hampshire, where McCain won in a landslide, and
squandered its huge financial advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began Tuesday night to hammer Gore over the Buddhist-temple
and other campaign-finance irregularities, saying in his prepared
text, ``I will remind Al Gore that Americans do not want a White
House where there is no controlling legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore started on the obvious counterstrategy by saying,
``I've learned from my mistakes.'' His hope is that the public will
tire of the subject and prefer to consider the Clinton years in
terms of a booming economy. The Gore campaign knows that it has
been many decades since voters have thrown out the party in power
in good economic times.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign is hoping that this year will be
different, and that dismay over Clinton's personal behavior will
lead the public, as Bush put it, to deny ``Clinton-Gore a third
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have one other problem in common, the risk of
overconfidence. ``We've got to pretend that we're behind,'' said
one Gore ally.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the problem may be more severe for Gore than for Bush
because the vice president's manner of explaining things _ oh, so
patiently _already carries an air of condescension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
