<SLUG> BC-ONLINEVOTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE VOTING FALLS SHORT OF PERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JON KAMMAN AND LISA CHIU  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The world's first legally binding online election
arrived far from perfect Tuesday, March 7. But when it worked
right, thousands of Democrats were casting ballots as fast as one
every five seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But many would-be voters encountered roadblocks along the
Internet pathway of picking a presidential nominee. And when the
sought assistance, they found telephone help lines constantly busy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by 10 p.m. Tuesday, March 7, 22 hours into the first of
four days of remote online voting, more than 13,000 votes had been
recorded by Election.com, the private firm conducting the election
for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials expect the start-up bugs to be wiped out
quickly, and additional phone lines will be installed to help those
struggling with the technology. They expect about half of the
primary votes to be cast online, possibly more than 50,000,
although turnout could fall if Bill Bradley withdraws this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you're engaged in a project of this magnitude, and
you're beginning to forge ahead a new path in technology, there's
always going to be a few bumps in the road,'' said Bill Taylor,
vice president of sales for Election.com. ``We've been doing our
best to smooth them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet votes streamed in at a rate of 20 a minute at one
point, party Vice Chairman David Eagle said.
</P>
<P>
   One common complaint among first-day voters was an inability to
access the two Web sites where electronic ballots are available _
www.election.com and www.azdem.org.
</P>
<P>
   The sites sometimes loaded so slowly that computers ``timed
out,'' said Mark Strama, a company executive overseeing technical
aspects of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Other voters were thwarted because they did not receive or had
not saved the mailed personal identification number that every
Democrat needed in order to vote.
</P>
<P>
   One unhappy voter told The Republic she encountered a blank
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Another, describing himself as a casual computer user, was
bewildered by a message saying that for him to vote, ``your
computer needs to have cookies enabled,'' a reference to allowing
the Web site to install a small piece of information on the user's
computer. The ``cookie'' would be erased when the voter logged out,
the notice said.
</P>
<P>
   Phone lines to state Democratic headquarters in Phoenix were
swamped all day, and the toll-free number set up on the eve of
voting also produced a busy signal for many callers.
</P>
<P>
   Party and company officials said 10 more lines were to be
installed overnight, supplementing the 13 at party headquarters
handling calls coming in to (602) 298-4200.
</P>
<P>
   More lines also were ordered for the toll-free line,
1-877-377-8683, which rings in a call center in Texas, Taylor said.
He did not have a count of the calls handled.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said start-up bugs should largely disappear as online
voting continues. Balloting from remote locations will end at 11:59
p.m. Friday, March 10, but 124 polling places will be open from 10
a.m. to 7 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   One non-computer glitch related to early voting was that
employees at least two Phoenix area sites knew nothing about being
named among six early voting sites locally for minorities. The
sites had agreed to serve as polling places on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Isaac School District Welcome Center, which serves mainly
the Latino community in west-central Phoenix, secretary Debbie Diaz
said several would-be voters were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Leaflets listed the center as an early voting site, but ``we
have no idea why,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having voting on Saturday only,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least four people were turned away at the Roosevelt Community
Technology Center at Seventh Street and Southern Avenue in south
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Jon.Kamman(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-4816. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Lisa.Chiu(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8404. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The launch of the world's first legally binding online election was
far from perfect Tuesday. But when things worked right, thousands
of Democrats were casting ballots as fast as one every five
seconds. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
