<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-GOP-1STLDWRITE     03-08 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-GOP-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN'S MAVERICK STYLE MAY HAVE COST HIM WITH REPUBLICAN VOTERS 
 
(Eds.: This is an analysis) 
(Eds.: Story has been updated) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ John McCain's ``great ride'' for the
White House was sputtering Tuesday, largely because his maverick,
reform-oriented campaign still appeals more to independents and
Democrats than to his fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Arizona senator has spoiled early Republican front-runner
George W. Bush's ``coronation,'' and he was reluctant to throw in
the towel. But McCain's anti-establishment message hasn't caught
fire with most GOP voters, and speculation increased late Tuesday
that he would drop out of the presidential race before the end of
the week.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   McCain's history as a political renegade _ he likes to brag at
campaign rallies that he never has been voted ``Miss Congeniality''
in Washington _ may have been a particularly acute problem in
Tuesday's lineup. The elections were dominated by states, such as
Ohio, with strong Republican traditions or states, such as New York
and California, where only Republicans could vote or where ballots
cast only by Republicans counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stuck his finger in the eye of the (Republican)
establishment, and he did so at a time when they had already made
their choice (of Bush), which only further irritated them,'' said
University of Texas professor Bruce Buchanan, a specialist in
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   And, last week, McCain, never a favorite of many religious
conservatives, alienated even more members of that significant
Republican bloc by branding two major fundamentalist leaders
``agents of intolerance.``
</P>
<P>
   &UR; McCain planned to travel Wednesday to his vacation home in
Cottonwood, Ariz., where he said he would ``take a little time to
reflect'' on his political future.
</P>
<P>
   As the senator was still adding up the numbers late Tuesday
night, his campaign announced that he will campaign in Colorado and
Illinois on Thursday and Friday, in advance of upcoming primaries.
In remarks to supporters, he raised the possibility that he may
continue to fight Bush for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; But McCain fell far short of the 200 delegates that his
strategists had said earlier were the minimum he needed from Super
Tuesday to maintain a realistic chance at the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's losses Tuesday included California's 162 delegates, the
richest nominating prize. Although any voter could cast a ballot in
the California primary, only Republican votes counted toward
delegate selection, and Bush had the strong backing of the state's
GOP establishment.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was hoping to win the most overall votes in the state's
primary in order to claim that he would be the most ``electable''
candidate in California in November. But the Arizona senator's loss
of California's delegates, his loss in Ohio and a
less-than-hoped-for showing in New York may have made California's
so-called ``beauty contest'' moot.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech Tuesday night was much more conciliatory than
the remarks he leveled at Bush after losing the key South Carolina
primary to the Texas governor last month. But the senator assured
his supporters that his ``crusade'' for governmental reform and
efforts to broaden the Republican Party's appeal to all Americans
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud, so proud, that this message has struck a chord in
the hearts of so many Americans of every race, creed, and political
persuasion in this vast and diverse country,'' he said.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Martha Gibson, a University of Connecticut political scientist,
said McCain needed to reach out to non-Republicans to capture New
Hampshire and Michigan, states with open primaries where his
victories gave momentum to his underdog effort. ``But by doing
that, he certainly offends the traditional power base,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout in Michigan's Republican primary two weeks ago was
more than double what it was four years ago, and at least half of
the voters who cast ballots were Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said McCain's alienation of religious conservatives with
his attacks on Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell may have been a
factor in Tuesday's balloting but probably was not an overriding
one. She made a similar assessment of a TV ad that Bush supporters
ran in New York, Ohio and California, attacking McCain's
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pick off pieces,'' she said. ``I'm not sure either one of
those would be a key piece (by itself).``
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign said it already has spent $200,000 on
advertising in Colorado, which will hold its primary Friday. But
the senator's next major test will be March 14, when he faces a
difficult lineup of states, including Texas, Bush's home state;
Florida, where Bush's brother, Jeb, is governor; and other Southern
states.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll indicated that McCain is competitive in Illinois,
but that state won't hold its primary until March 21.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
