<HEADER>
A0146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ELN-CALIF-NYT &LR;      03-08 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-CALIF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH WIN IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If California's jungle primary was the first big
harbinger of the general election, Al Gore was the king of beasts
Tuesday, finishing first among all contenders listed on the same
blanket ballot regardless of party. But George W. Bush was a close
second, and the overall news for Gore was more good than great,
suggesting an advantage, not a lock, for him in the biggest state
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won the support of just of just over 3 in 10 California
voters overall, while Bush drew just under 3 in 10, John McCain
about one-quarter, and Bill Bradley barely 10 percent, according to
surveys of voters leaving the polls. Fully 20 percent of McCain's
support came from voters who identified themselves as Democrats,
and 30 percent from independents, and 4 in 10 of the Arizona
senator's supporters said they would support Gore in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Those were all positive signs for Gore, as were favorable
ratings 10 percentage points higher than those for Bush and a
15-point advantage among the self-described moderates who made up
almost 40 percent of the electorate here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has made scores of visits to the state in the last
seven years, spoke Tuesday night to a ballroom of supporters by
telephone, saying: ``I can't tell you how important it is to me to
win big in the California Democratic contest and to win the overall
California primary contest. That is a harbinger of things to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore ran well behind his fellow Democrat, Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, who drew the support of nearly 6 in 10 voters in her
race against a split field of contenders for the Republican
nomination to challenge her in November, and Gore just edged Bush
in a hypothetical general election match-up, while McCain ran 10
points ahead of Gore. Half of independent voters said they would
back Gore in the fall, but 4 in 10 favored Bush, and like numbers
said that Gore and Bush were both ``about right'' in terms of
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that Bush will be strong enough to be competitive
here and that there's plenty of time for healing to happen,'' said
Steve Kinney, a longtime Republican pollster here. ``It just shows
you that here in California there's not a lot of love for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one top Democratic strategist agreed, saying on
condition of anonymity: ``My sense of this is Gore did OK, but not
as well as he should have. It scares me that he doesn't have more
oomph on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing conclusions from Tuesday's results here posed particular
hazards, because this was California's first presidential primary
using the blanket ballot, and there were no comparable benchmarks.
All votes counted in the overall horserace, but under major party
rules, only the votes of party members counted toward delegate
selection, a fact that voters themselves seem not to have fully
grasped. Two-thirds of those surveyed said they would consider the
candidate who won the most total votes to be the ``real winner'' of
his party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gore won overwhelmingly among Democrats, taking 6 in 10
Democratic votes to just under 2 in 10 for Bradley, and Bush took
just under 6 in 10 Republicans to fewer than 4 in 10 for McCain,
political professionals in both parties quickly turned their
attention to handicapping the general election, and especially
trying to discern where McCain supporters might go.
</P>
<P>
   Among all voters, McCain drew his strongest support from
moderates, those with post-college education, those over 45 years
old, those earning over $100,000 a year, veterans and those who
decided to vote in the last week, a demographic slice much like
those that were crucial to the victories of California's last
Republican governor, Pete Wilson. When those voters were asked who
they would support this fall, Bush ran evenly with Gore among
veterans and those over 45, came close with those earning over
$100,000 and lost the others by margins of roughly 60-to-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush loses those people in the fall, he won't even be
competitive in California,'' said Bill Carrick, a Democratic
consultant. ``That's a group he has to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, McCain was most competitive in the Central
Valley, the vast agricultural swath that runs the interior spine of
the state, which accounted for a quarter of Tuesday's electorate
and often decides statewide elections. Tuesday, McCain, Gore and
Bush each took about 3 in 10 votes there; in the hypothetical fall
contest, Gore and Bush split the area evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers have long contended that he could translate his
appeal in Texas, a fast-growing southwestern state with a booming
high-tech economy, to California, which national Republicans have
not contested vigorously since Bush's father won in 1988. Bush has
also shown strength with Hispanic voters, who make up a growing
part of the electorate but have trended strongly to the Democratic
column in recent years, mostly in a backlash against Wilson's
strong campaigns against affirmative action and illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic voters accounted for about 10 percent of Tuesday's
electorate, and Gore won the votes of 6 in 10, with Bush and McCain
together taking about 3 in 10. In a hypothetical fall match-up,
Bush, who ran television advertisements in Spanish here, drew a
respectable 3 in 10 Hispanic voters, well above recent Republican
statewide showings, compared to two-thirds for Gore. In his victory
speech in Texas Tuesday night, Bush declared: ``Legal immigration
is not a source of national weakness; it is a sign of national
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 6 in 10 Hispanic voters, roughly the same percentage
as the electorate as a whole, supported a successful ballot
initiative to limit marriage to heterosexual couples, which
Democrats opposed by a like margin.
</P>
<P>
   Republican analysts called that a sign of Bush's potential
appeal on an issue of traditional family values.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Ross, a Democratic consultant in Sacramento who has
made a specialty of working with Hispanic candidates, said Bush's
opposition to gun control and abortion rights remained sharply at
odds with Californians' strong support for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what'll happen is Bush will compete in California for
about three weeks, and then we're going to keep talking about guns
and abortion, and he'll leave,'' Ross said. ``Three weeks ago, in
one of the most conservative assembly districts in the state, in
the Central Valley, I asked the following question: ``Do you favor
or oppose the government requiring mandatory registration of all
guns,'' and 73 percent said they favored it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
