<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-CO     03-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NOT BUYING AGING DEFENDERS IN SELLER'S MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been counting down the days until the NHL trade
deadline _ Tuesday _ then you know that the Stars are rumored to be
in the running for acquiring:
</P>
<P>
   A. Doug Gilmour
</P>
<P>
   B. Mark Messier
</P>
<P>
   C. North Dakota
</P>
<P>
   D. the vast thoroughbred empire of Wimp-Free Stables.
</P>
<P>
   In truth _ and some purportedly wise NHL minds may not believe
this _ but the answer could well be none of the above. Owner Tom
Hicks doesn't have a bottomless wallet, though it is a formidably
spacious one. Nor is every $6 million-a-year 39-year-old a perfect
fit for the defending Stanley Cup champion Stars.
</P>
<P>
   News of the latest superstar to swap jerseys for a stretch run
at the Cup _ this time, it was Boston's Ray Bourque going to
Colorado _ did not pass unnoticed at the Stars' compound. But by
the same token, the building yesterday wasn't exactly draped in
black.
</P>
<P>
   For 21 years, granted, Bourque has been a great player, a likely
Hall of Fame player. There were Aprils when some say that he
carried the Bruins single-handedly through the playoffs on his own
back.
</P>
<P>
   But when future Hall of Famers are on the auction block, it's
usually a seller's market. Boston general manager Harry Sinden,
instead of closing on a reported deal with Philadelphia, the team
that was Bourque's first choice, shopped the veteran shamelessly.
Indeed, sources say, he tried to use the Avalanche's offer to help
pry young center Simon Gagne away from the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Flyers had nothing else to barter, Sinden sent Bourque
two time zones and one full conference away. Colorado thinks it
just traded for a sure spot in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' silence, on the other hand, speaks volumes.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars don't need a Ray Bourque. It sounds blasphemous, but
there's no room. No room in Hicks' big wallet, probably, and no
room in the Stars' future.
</P>
<P>
   This team needs goal scorers, not 39-year-old defenders. It
needs somebody to share the offensive load until the aches, pains
and broken bones of this difficult season finally mend.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Bourque's contract will expire at the end of this
season. Detroit, which was also interested, reportedly wanted
Bourque to commit to a two-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars already have a corps of young and/or experienced
defensemen under contract. They need goal scorers. Stop me if
you've heard this before.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL deadline is next week _ hence, the headlines. But the
Stars actually fired a preemptive strike, of sorts, a full month
ago, when they sent Derek Plante and Kevin Dean to Chicago for
defensemen Dave Manson and Sylvain Cote.
</P>
<P>
   As Bourque now tries to fit in with the Avalanche, the way Chris
Chelios and Wendel Clark thought they would do so smoothly in
Detroit a year ago, Manson and Cote have had a four-week head
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the seven to 10 days preceding the March 14 deadline, the
activity usually increases,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey said
yesterday. ``But my own feeling is that if you can make your change
earlier, it allows time for those players to adapt and adjust to
your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often they are coming off teams where they haven't been in a
successful situation, and it takes a little while to shake those
cobwebs out.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unspoken by Gainey was something even more important. If
the Stars hadn't grabbed Cote and Manson early, somebody else _ the
Red Wings, probably _ would have.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need goal scorers. Did I forget to say that?
</P>
<P>
   But as history tells us, this is the time of year when NHL teams
habitually begin to think defense. Every contender thinks things
will be fine, if they can only get another big, nasty,
presence-asserting defenseman _ or two, or three.
</P>
<P>
   It's a seller's market. To get Bourque, the Avalanche gave up a
package of four players, including Sami Pahlsson, a talented young
forward currently playing out his contract in Sweden. He will move
right onto the Flyers' second line next season, reports say.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at trade deadline, Colorado surrendered another part
of its youth to get Theo Fleury from Calgary. When the playoffs
were done, Fleury signed with the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't miss the opportunity if we think there's a place
where we can improve our team,'' Gainey said simply, though
noncommittally.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque, in other words, great as he has been for 21 NHL
seasons, the Stars can do without.
</P>
<P>
   But another goal scorer? By all means.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
