A0152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ELN-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRI     03-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DECLARES HIS FIGHT A VICTORY FOR IDEALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Recasts lede, reorganizes, and adds more quotes and color.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT44 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no drama in the air as former Sen. Bill
Bradley's supporters began filing into the ballroom at the Sheraton
Hotel in midtown Manhattan Tuesday night. The polls had not even
closed, but they knew what the results would be. They had come to
bid him farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow I'm going to be depressed,'' said Stuart Kolbert, a
real estate broker from Westchester County, who had gone to New
Hampshire five times as a volunteer for Bradley. ``I'm depressed
now.''
</P>
<P>
   But like their candidate, the crowd collectively declared a
proud victory for idealism even as they conceded defeat in all of
Tuesday's primaries to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to walk away from the speech, so I wouldn't start
crying,'' said Susan Levine, 58, the travel agent for the Bradley
campaign. ``I'm so sad the world isn't ready for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing calm and not the least bit sorrowful as he entered the
packed room shortly after 9 p.m., Bradley declared that his long
insurgent campaign, now in its dying moments, had ``shaped the
national debate'' and returned ``core Democratic values'' to the
fore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember that the fact that we've not succeeded in
winning tonight's primaries makes the cause no less just, the fight
no less honorable, the goal no less reachable,'' Bradley told the
crowd of several hundred people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have called our goals unrealistic,'' he said. ``I call
them common sense. I call them Democratic. I call them American.
And I'm going to work for them until we win. And we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bradley said he would spend Wednesday at his home in
Montclair, N.J., resting and calling friends to talk about his
future. They said he was likely to hold a news conference on
Thursday somewhere in New Jersey to announce his withdrawal from
the race.
</P>
<P>
   But even as his supporters were waxing elegiac, Bradley spoke in
soaring tones about how he had brought young and idealistic people
back into politics and had forced a national debate on issues like
campaign finance reform, universal health care and child poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave voice to the voiceless,'' he said. ``When no one was
talking about the 13 children who die every day of gun violence, we
heard their cries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When no one was talking about the nearly 14 million children
who still live in poverty in this country, we said America can't be
America if they remain poor in a time of plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   There is already discussion among some of Bradley's staunchest
supporters about laying the groundwork for a Bradley campaign in
2004. ``There should be some time for mourning, but then it will be
time to go back to work,'' said a friend and informal adviser to
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   But close aides to Bradley said he had given absolutely no
thought to mounting another campaign in four years, and none would
hazard a guess about his intentions. ``I was wrong about his
running this time, so I'm not one to prognosticate,'' said Anita
Dunn, his communications director.
</P>
<P>
   The live rhythm and blues band, the red, white and blue balloons
and the free-flowing wine did little to add a festive air to the
Sheraton ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The news reports all day had been so unrelentingly gloomy that
there was barely a murmur or a groan from the crowd when CNN
projected Gore the winner in New York at precisely the moment the
polls closed at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a sense of deep pride among the people in room,
many of whom said they were first-time political volunteers who had
been drawn into the campaign by Bradley's idealism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good seeds planted and nurtured don't always come up when you
expect them to,'' said Chris Hansen-Nelson, 45, of Manhattan. ``But
they come up eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   At another corner of the room, Kolbert and Ed Gerstein, a
52-year-old accountant from Brooklyn, reminisced like old college
roommates about their volunteer days for Bradley in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did something good for this country,'' Kolbert said.
``I have to believe we elevated the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Pleasance, a 61-year-old retiree from London who met Bradley
at Oxford University in the mid-1960s, came all the way from
England earlier this year to help the Bradley campaign in Iowa, New
Hampshire and Washington state. He bought a plane ticket to Florida
several weeks ago, planning to help prepare for the March 14
primary there. He'll use it to take a vacation instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't always very good at speaking before large rooms,''
Pleasance said. ``But he really connected with small groups. I only
wish more people had been able to see that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
