<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0157 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-08 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS LACK BIG PLUG FOR GAPING OUTFIELD HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Maybe it was intentional that the Anaheim Angels
decided against parading Jim Edmonds and Garrett Anderson in front
of the Mariners Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two outfielders were on the bench at Diablo Stadium during
Seattle's 5-3 win, putting a crimp in the Mariners' window
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, the talk around town was that the Cactus League game
would provide the American League West Division rivals an
opportunity to peruse the goods, in case the urge to swap escalated
into a mandate to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels need pitching and the Mariners need someone they can
count on in the outfield _ and we mean (BEGIN ITAL) really count
on, (END ITAL) as in power, as in a threat, as in homers and RBIs
and 150-plus games this summer.
</P>
<P>
   While it seems unlikely either rival would help make the other
one better, stranger things have happened. And if the Angels and
M's can't or won't make a deal, then the Mariners no doubt have a
few aces in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   For the M's, spring training is revealing that the loss of Ken
Griffey Jr. may no longer be emotionally wrenching. But that does
not eliminate the cold, hard fact that without No. 24, the Mariners
outfield is, well, a mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a bunch of outfielders. Something definitely has to
be done, and that's too bad,'' said Brian Hunter, whose arbitration
win this winter makes his $2 million salary tough for the M's to
swallow if Hunter can't improve his on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of guys here who've worked hard to be here.
I know Lou (Piniella) is so good at putting in the best lineup to
win a game, but there are a lot of us here. I think that's why
they're still trying to make moves,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question of who's in the Mariners outfield as much as
who isn't: In Peoria are Jay Buhner, Stan Javier, Raul Ibanez, Mark
McLemore, Mike Cameron, John Mabry and Hunter, not to mention four
others with minor league contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Amassing such a horde, however, has not delivered a truly
durable, reliable and productive outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, the Mariners have so many outfielders in camp that
Piniella has already said it's time to farm some of the fellas out
to create adequate playing time among the core group of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   If the luxury of penciling No. 24 into the lineup every single
day didn't spoil Piniella, he has certainly realized that this
abrupt transition to outfield by committee is a less-than-perfect
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go with what we have, I can rotate guys in, keep them
fresh. I'm comfortable with what we have. and I'm willing to go
with what we've got,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would think that we could use one more outfielder that
can be what you would consider an everyday force in your lineup. I
think we would be better served.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment of an eventual deal for another outfielder is
percolating throughout camp. And it is tough to forget the delight
with which Mariners CEO Howard Lincoln a few weeks ago announced
that, in addition to all the moves made this winter, the M's are
not done yet.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the M's are spending these first weeks of
spring playing a shell game. They are trying to determine all their
spare parts, knowing that they need to make a move for an
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   John Halama, who pitched three strong innings Tuesday in a ``B''
game against the Milwaukee Brewers, has been talking about trade
rumors that would send him to the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But the M's have to guess right as to which pitcher to let go.
Tuesday, general manager Pat Gillick indicated that until he sees
Brett Tomko work a few games, it is too early to trade away
pitching, even if the M's appear to have an abundance of it right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the No. 1 need is undeniable. And it is out where a guy
named Junior used to help out Buhner in right field, where he
compensated for the 68 left fielders who played next to him during
Griffey's 11 seasons in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always open to getting better,'' Gillicks said. ``We could
get better with another left-handed hitter. But a lot of that
depends on what (Raul) Ibanez and (John) Mabry do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillick says a left-handed power hitter with a track record for
production who plays ``average defense'' is their top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'd feel safer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose some 130 RBI, we're going to have to replace
that. ... I think everyone can kind of lock into who the starters
are, the infield and the catchers, but one area of experiment, of
uncertainty, is what the outfield will be,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Griffey told the M's to trade him to Cincinnati, everyone
had had months to resign themselves to the reality of his
departure. But what to do in Griffey's absence is still a problem _
one the Mariners seem aimed at fixing.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to good guys like Ibanez and Mabry, Cameron and
McLemore and Javier, but so far it is clear the M's do not have
anything resembling Griffey's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
