<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ELN-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRIT     03-08 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CONSIDERS OPTIONS IN FACE OF SERIES OF LOSSES
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS to expand McCain quote in 2nd graf, sub quote from Hagel
for Khachigian.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT9,10,47,49 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sen. John McCain was left Tuesday night facing an
agonizing decision: how long and how far to prolong a campaign that
has evolved over 14 months from an underrated candidacy into what
he calls his mission to transform the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   With his rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, piling up enough
delegates and winning so many key contests across the nation,
including New York, that he was assured the nomination, McCain on
Tuesday night wished Bush well, and said, ``we may meet again in
primaries a few days from now and we have a little rest.''
</P>
<P>
   He left ambiguous whether his candidacy would continue, but not
his ``crusade'' to reform the party. He told cheering supporters
that ``our crusade continues tonight, tomorrow, the next day, the
day after that, and for as long as it takes to restore America's
confidence and pride in the practice and institutions of our great
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He planned to fly Wednesday to his vacation retreat in
Cottonwood, in the Red Mountain region of his home state of
Arizona, to rest and consider his options, which range from an
immediate pullout this week after his heady 14-month ride, or a
last-stand forward toward the Illinois primary two weeks from now
or even beyond. Mark Salter, a longtime aide, said the senator had
made ``no decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He staff, meanwhile, also fought to keep up an undaunted
appearance, releasing a campaign schedule for Colorado and Illinois
for Thursday, Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the question was, to what end? For weeks McCain has argued
strenuously that he and not Bush was the one who would be his
party's strongest standard-bearer to defeat Vice President Al Gore,
because of the senator's suddenly discovered cross-over appeal to
independents and conservative Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night left him lagging in delegates and with a
diminished ability to make that case, failing to meet his own
campaign's best case scenarios. While McCain swept most of New
England, he lost Maine. He won only a relative handful of delegates
in New York. The bellwether state of Ohio went strongly for Bush,
too, leaving McCain unable to say that his Michigan victory two
weeks ago signaled some larger appeal across the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   And the all-important state of California looked like it could
well disappoint his hopes of winning the popular vote, with exit
polls suggesting that both Gore and Bush could come in ahead of
him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has emphatically proclaimed the Republican party his home
and said he would support Bush should he become the Republican
nominee, even as he railed that Bush and his allies were trying to
win the presidency ``in the worst way.''
</P>
<P>
   But so bitter and personal has the struggle with Bush become
that not all of McCain's closest associates were willing to rule
out the possibility that the senator might yet, for all his
denials, follow the lead of his hero Theodore Roosevelt and make
some kind of third party bid.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., a close friend of McCain's, said,
however, that the Arizona senator needed time to study the delegate
count, but added: ``He won't put the country or the party through
any high drama.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as McCain has proclaimed himself on a ``great crusade''
to create a more inclusive, reform-minded Republican Party, fewer
and fewer of his fellow Republicans have been willing to join him
as his campaign has become more aggressively critical of Republican
orthodoxy on tax cutting, on campaign finance law, and on its open
arms to leaders of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The senator himself made an elliptical allusion to the problem
at his last campaign stop in San Diego late Monday afternoon when
he gazed out at a rally in the Old Town section outside a Mexican
restaurant and spotted a woman waving a placard, ``Soccer moms for
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer moms for McCain,'' he called out. ``Up in Santa Clara
this morning we had carnivores for McCain. In Cleveland we had
Ukrainians for McCain.'' Then he burst out laughing, and added,
``I'm telling you we are assembling a coalition never seen before
in the history of American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   All that he lacked was vast numbers of Republicans for McCain.
But Tuesday morning, as he continued to work the phone calling talk
radio host after talk radio host in New York and California, he
proclaimed his happiness at the independents he had brought to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am to have sparked this kind of
prairie fire out there that's getting people involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans unaffiliated with McCain's campaign said that after
a spectacular showing in New Hampshire, the senator had lost his
way from the moment he delivered a defiant speech after his South
Carolina loss, attacking Bush as a fraud. In the last few weeks his
more uplifting themes of public service, patriotism and great
causes have been nearly drowned out by his appeals to regional and
class resentments.
</P>
<P>
   His closing tactic in the past few days had been to attack Bush
for the fact that a Texas family, which has been a big contributor
to the governor, had poured $2.5 million into last minute attack
ads against McCain. ``We ask Governor Bush to do what he refused to
do,'' he said at rallies across California on Monday, ``tell his
sleazy Texas buddies to stop these negative ads and take their
money back to Texas where it belongs and don't try to corrupt
American politics with your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster, said: ``The John McCain
people saw since South Carolina is not the same John McCain people
saw in New Hampshire. Disciplined aggressiveness is essential in
politics. Undisciplined aggressiveness gets you in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact one voter Tuesday, Harold Noyes, pastor of the
nondenominational Christian Community Church in Athens, Ga., voted
for Alan Keyes and complained, ``McCain has been kind of whining a
lot lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear whether McCain's fiery speech last week branding
Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, prominent leaders of the
Christian right, as ``agents of intolerance,'' did anything but
backfire against him.
</P>
<P>
   Polls of voters in New York showed that those who said the
speech ``affected'' their vote _ about a third of the total
Republican vote _ went 3-to-1 for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's aides said that members of the Christian right
would not have supported McCain anyway and that his speech was a
stand on principle, not a tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a defining moment for our campaign,'' John Weaver,
McCain's political director, said. ``Our party is at a fork in the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver promised that no matter who wins the Republican
nomination, McCain and his supporters ``are not going to slip
quietly into the night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
