<HEADLINE>
EDMOND KAISER, 86, FOUNDER OF CHARITIES  
 RAYMOND W. ICKES, 87, SHIPPING EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GENEVA _ Edmond Kaiser, founder of Terre des Hommes and other
children's organizations, died Saturday on a visit to India, a
spokesman for one of the charities said. He was 86.
 &HT;    Kaiser organized Terre des Hommes in 1959, after having learned
of the condition of children in Algeria. It is now one of
Switzerland's best-known charities, with worldwide operations to
aid suffering from poverty, illness and war.
 &HT;    Born to a Jewish family in Paris, Kaiser lived in Switzerland in
his childhood. He returned to France to work with the French
resistance in World War II and had been condemned to death by the
Nazis.
 &HT;    In 1947, he returned to Lausanne, Switzerland, and he later
started his charitable work there. Describing his work in a
newspaper interview in 1994, Kaiser said, ``If someone is crying on
the ground, we try to pick them up, just like we would care for an
injured bird, love it and then help it fly again.'' 
 &HT;    In 1990, France offered Kaiser the Chevalier of the Legion of
Honor. He turned it down. ``Sitting in the middle of dead or
suffering Biafran children, out with the children of Vietnam whose
skin has been peeled away by napalm, it would be as if I found it
normal to be honored for their martyrdom,'' he wrote in a letter to
the French government.
 &HT;    He left Terre des Hommes in 1979 to work with Sentinelles, a
charity devoted to combating the prostitution, mutilation and
slavery of children in developing countries. He founded another
group, Families Without Borders, in 1992.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond W. Ickes, a retired shipping executive and a son of
Harold L. Ickes, who was President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
secretary of the interior, died Thursday at his home in Berkeley,
Calif. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes was president of the Natomas Co., the Pacific Far East
Line and the American President Lines. He retired in the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Wilmarth Ickes was born on June 23, 1912, in Evanston,
Ill. He earned a bachelor's, a master's and a law degree from the
University of Chicago and in 1939 became an assistant U.S.
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   He served with the Marines in World War II and was awarded a
Purple Heart and a Silver Star. He also helped gather evidence for
the Nuremberg trials.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes' half-brother, Harold Ickes of Washington, was a deputy
chief of staff under President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He is also survived by his wife, Janet; a son, Kyle Ickes of
Berkeley; a daughter, Andrea Ickes-Dunbar of Marysville, Calif.; a
half-sister, Liz Ickes of Walnut Creek, Calif.; a stepson, Ross Lee
of Sacramento, Calif.; four grandchildren and two
great-grandchildren. His first wife, Maralotte, died in 1978.
</P>
</TEXT>
