A0171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ELN-PRIMARIES-1S     03-08 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELN-PRIMARIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DECISIVE DAY FOR FRONT-RUNNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Changes headline, updates throughout) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 8:
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush won the sweeping
nationwide victories Tuesday that both had been counting on to
speed them toward their party nominations for president. Gore's
rout of former Sen. Bill Bradley in races all across the country
ended the Democratic contest. Based on exit surveys in California
and vote tabulations elsewhere, Bush was leading the race for
delegates in the major states, falling short only in New England.
Should Sen. John McCain decide to continue in the race and expand
on his showing in the Northeast, he will face extremely long odds.
The senator made a good effort in New York, but did not get the
turnaround victory he sought.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the voting Tuesday could be seen as both Bush
and Gore issued gracious compliments to the men they defeated and
immediately turned their sights on each other. Given the likelihood
that the vice president will be running against the son of the man
defeated by President Clinton in 1992, it was interesting that both
his and Bush's speeches looked back as well as forward. Gore, not
surprisingly, warned against returning to Republican rule. And
although Bush spoke of a new beginning, he also declared, ``I
believe our country is ready to return exiled honor to the White
House.'' More than most campaigns, this one is almost certain to
dwell on the past as well as the future.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate, Gore has clearly scored one of the most
impressive recoveries in many years. He started out only six months
ago struggling to overcome his image as an awkward figure running a
costly, uninspired campaign based on the idea of entitlement. When
Democrats started moving toward Bradley as a fresher candidate,
Gore junked his campaign plan, threw off the smothering cloak of
supposed inevitability and starting fighting for the nomination. He
emerged from his clashes with Bradley with a sharper debating
style, though still lacking the emotional connection with voters
that seemed to come so easily to McCain on the Republican side.
Gore's unbroken string of primary victories has made him no less
reviled by Republicans, but many of them admit that he will be a
tough competitor in November.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Gore was able to use the later primaries as a warm-up,
they have been a battle for survival for Bush. Despite his
victories Tuesday, the Texas governor is looking more battered than
anyone could have predicted when he began as a pre-emptive
favorite. Recent polls show him even with Gore, instead of leading
the vice president as he was a few months ago. Bush's performance
on the trail raised unexpected questions about his knowledge,
experience and debating skills. Even more damaging, however, has
been his ideological repositioning, accompanied by an embrace of
the party's cultural conservatives. As he now tries to move back to
the center, Bush will find Gore camped out there.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's performance Tuesday, on the most decisive day of the
young campaign year, plus his strong regional base in the Sun Belt,
give his supporters ample reason for optimism. His fund-raising
ability is another asset. But the real test for Bush will be
whether he can make warnings against eight more years of the
Clinton-Gore administration _ a theme unveiled in his victory
speech Tuesday night _ into a message that will last for eight more
months. Bush's gibe about ``no controlling legal authority'' gave a
hint of the tough rhetoric to come.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's concession speech had a valedictory tone. He clearly
fell far short of the scenario his team envisioned following the
New Hampshire victory on Feb. 1. It was then that his spokesmen
talked openly of igniting one state after another with McCain's
heroic story and his crusade for reform. When he was attacked
unfairly by the religious right in South Carolina, McCain returned
the fire. That decision to counterattack now looks like a costly
tactical mistake that damaged the aura of his campaign, revived old
worries about his temperament and unsettled many mainstream
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain promised a decision on his future in a couple of days.
Even if he drops out of the race, he pledged to continue to speak
out and espouse his appeal for moderation and campaign finance
reform. Whatever happens, McCain has opened a historically
significant debate among Republicans over the fundamental purpose
and direction of their party. That debate ought to continue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
