<HEADER>
A0175 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHR     03-08 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIOUS INVESTORS DRIVE DOWN THE DOW MORE THAN 374 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change percentage figure in 3rd graf and price of oil in
4th graf. In 10th graf, changes 2 companies to 3, adding United
Technologies; also changes figures for Exxon Mobil and Microsoft.) 
 
(Eds: Graphic being sent with PROCTER-WARNING may also be used with
this story.) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON and KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 374.47
points Tuesday on investors' fears that rising oil prices combined
with higher interest rates may do significant damage to corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   The fall began when Procter &AMP; Gamble, one of the nation's
biggest and best-known companies and one of the 30 stocks in the
Dow, said early Tuesday that its earnings in the current quarter
would come in well below the levels expected by Wall Street
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The warning, which came just a week after the company had
assured investors that its sales and earnings were on track,
shocked investors. They dumped P&AMP;G shares, wiping out $36 billion,
or nearly 31 percent, of the company's value. Adding to investors'
anxiety, oil prices soared to $34.13 a barrel, a price not seen
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, already troubled by the pinch on corporate profits
that will result from rising interest rates, now have to worry
about the ill effects of the higher costs of materials on company
earnings this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average took the biggest hit, falling
374.47 points, or 3.7 percent, to 9,796.03. Broader market averages
fared a bit better; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost 2.6
percent of its value, while the Wilshire 5000 Total Market Index
declined 2.1 percent. The Nasdaq composite index, the focus of
investor ardor in recent months because of its collection of
hot-growing technology stocks, lost only 1.2 percent of its value.
It closed at 4,847.84.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has been walking on eggshells because of the Fed,
but that was in an environment where they felt confident about
earnings,'' said Thomas M. Galvin, chief investment strategist at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``That has now been brought into
question because of P&AMP;G. Earnings worries, interest rates and oil
prices are often enough to unglue even the calmest investor.''
</P>
<P>
   The plunge in P&AMP;G was responsible for just under a third of the
Dow's decline, the fourth-largest drop in points ever registered in
the average. In percentage terms, Tuesday's decline was not
historic. For the year, the Dow is down 14.8 percent while the
Nasdaq has gained 19.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of rival consumer goods companies fell on Procter &AMP;
Gamble's news that its earnings would decline as much as 11 percent
in the quarter rather than gain the roughly 9 percent forecast by
the company previously. Drug companies also fell, as did the shares
of banks and financial services concerns. Shares of larger
technology companies favored by investors like Cisco Systems,
General Electric and Nortel Networks also sank.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 30 companies in the Dow average rose. Exxon
Mobil, a beneficiary of rising oil prices, closed at $80.50, up
$7.5625, and Microsoft jumped $2.25, to close at $92.875. United
Technologies rose 50 cents, to $50.50.
</P>
<P>
   While few investors own the Dow Jones industrial average, many
investors do hold mutual funds that mirror the performance of the
S&AMP;P index. After five years of double-digit gains, it is down 7.73
percent this year. It fell 35.66 points Tuesday, to 1,355.62.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in oil prices, which are at levels not seen since 1991,
put significant pressure on stocks Tuesday. ``Oil is responsible
for about two-thirds of the decline in the Dow,'' said Christine A.
Callies, chief investment strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston.
``The perceptions on inflation are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the reasons why Procter &AMP; Gamble's earnings in
the current quarter will be so grim is that its materials costs are
rising. The company said the creeping costs of plastics, many of
which are oil-based, and paper, to a lesser degree, have cut into
profit margins. Investors are clearly worried that these problems
are not limited to P&AMP;G and may be a harbinger of earnings
shortfalls at other old-stock-market reliables.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investors continue to pour money into shares of
fledgling technology companies whose growth seems more promising.
Reversing what had been a longstanding trend in the stock market,
small companies' stocks are now vastly outperforming those of large
companies. According to Salomon Smith Barney, as of the end of last
week, shares of the smallest companies _ those with market values
of $250 million or less _ were up 18 percent for the year. Stocks
of the biggest companies, those with market values in excess of $20
billion, were down 2 percent for the year as of Friday. That trend
continued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some strategists viewed the blue-chip selloff warily. ``This is
truly causing us to question the viability of the big bull market
that began in 1982,'' said Alan R. Shaw, head of technical research
at Salomon Smith Barney. ``There are still people funneling money
into Nasdaq stocks but common sense and history suggest that
eventually these stocks as well will suffer corrections.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors clearly see fast-growing technology companies as a
safe haven. But some strategists question whether these so-called
new-economy stocks will be impervious to a slowdown in the
old-world companies. ``It's as though you have one economy on earth
and the other on Mars,'' said David Dreman, head of Dreman Value
Management. ``Roughly 50 percent of capital expenditures goes to
technology spending on one form or another. If the old economy
turns down I don't think it's good for the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley, chief investment strategist at State Street Global
Investors, agreed. ``If there is a change in employment trends and
a slowing in income growth as a result of interest rates, the
demand for this new economy is going to slow down,'' he said. ``If
that happens, their growth rates will decelerate and these
companies will experience a closing of the gap between the old and
the new.''
</P>
<P>
   Most stocks are already in a bear market. According to Salomon
Smith Barney, 77.8 percent of the S&AMP;P 500 stocks are down 20
percent or more. And even though the Nasdaq is up, 62.1 percent of
its stocks have declined 20 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the slide in stock prices coupled with higher
oil prices may slow the economy and reduce pressure on the Federal
Reserve to push interest rates sharply higher in coming months.
Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, has clearly
warned investors that policy-makers will raise rates by one-quarter
of a point at their next meeting on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Callies said that while stock prices might soften a bit further,
underlying fundamentals remain positive. ``As far as I can tell,
commodity prices increases will be temporary, and the structure of
corporate profits is still quite strong,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
