u p BC-ELN-RDP-5THLD-WRITETH     03-08 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-5THLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH TRIUMPH NATIONWIDE, PUTTING NOMINATIONS IN THEIR
GRASP
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS to recast top to raise Bush-Gore comments looking toward
general election, drop references to rest of their speeches to 2nd
take.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT1, 18, 33, 3, 10, 11, 16, 19 _ have been
sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore crushed their
rivals from ocean to ocean Tuesday in powerful displays that
assured them their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   After claiming the two biggest electoral powerhouses of
California and New York, which account for more than 40 percent of
the delegates chosen Tuesday, Bush and Gore immediately turned to
each other _ and to firing the first salvos of the general election
campaign that lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush laid out several themes for the general election in a
combative speech that was devoted not to his challenger, Sen &UR; . &LR; 
John McCain, but to lambasting Gore. ``He is the candidate of the
status quo in Washington, D.C., and he has a tough case to make in
the general election,'' Bush said to supporters in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At a boisterous rally in Nashville earlier in the evening, Gore
did not mention Bush by name but called on the Republican nominee
to debate him twice a week and to spurn unregulated soft money
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will challenge the Republican nominee to hold joint open
meetings with me,'' he said, ``to make this contest of ideas and
not insults, a campaign conducted in full daylight and not through
secretly funded special interest attack ads or smear telephone
calls from the extremist right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, did not
win one state, a defeat so pronounced that his advisers said it was
only a matter of days before he withdraws. And McCain said he would
retreat to the mountains of Arizona to ``take stock of our
losses,'' and decide whether to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's victories were particularly impressive because he was
supported by a majority of every demographic group in the 16 states
with Democratic contests, and, significantly, by women, who backed
him in some states by margins of more than 2-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   In several states Gore held a margin of 3-to-1 or better. Gore
also racked up a double-digit margin in New York, a victory made
even sweeter by the memory of his dismal performance in the 1988
presidential primary, where he won a paltry 10 percent and quit the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not win one state, a defeat so pronounced that his
advisers said it was only a matter of days before he withdraws.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican verdict Tuesday was decisive, though not as
overwhelming. Bush prevailed by comfortable margins in California
and New York, as well as in the large Midwest states of Ohio and
Missouri and in the only southern state voting Tuesday, Georgia. Of
the 13 Republican contests, McCain captured four relatively small
New England states: Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island and
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Gore and Bush victories in California, the most
sought-after electoral prize of all, it was not clear which of the
four contenders would prevail in that state's popular vote, which
is not binding but could be a telling measure of a candidates'
potency in November.
</P>
<P>
   The voting Tuesday was tantamount to a national primary. Never
before have so many states, in every region, held contests on the
same day. Roughly a third of the delegates to the parties' national
conventions were up for grabs. The Democrat needs 2,170 delegates
to get the party's nomination; the Republican needs 1,034. By
Tuesday night, Gore roughly 300 short of the magic total; Bush's
actual delegate tally was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the primaries capped the most
contentious nomination battle in decades, a week-by-week electoral
see-saw in which Bush would win one round, only to be humbled by
McCain in the next. Bush entered Tuesday's voting with more
victories and more delegates. But no one could safely bet what
would happen because in the entire yearlong run-up to the
primaries, Bush had been widely viewed as the front-runner, only to
see his prospects grow far more precarious after McCain trounced
him in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But McCain, of Arizona, asserted in a brief speech at a late
rally in West Hollywood that he was not about to give up his
crusade _ but left open the possibility that he will quit the race.
``Our crusade continues, tonight, tommorow, the next day, the day
after that and for as long as it takes to restore America's
confidence and pride in the practice and institutions of our great
democracy.''  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race was far less climactic Tuesday because while
Bradley emerged as a threat last fall _ polls at one point had him
beating Gore in New Hampshire _ that spurt of popularity never
translated to the voting booth. Bradley, a former senator from New
Jersey, was shut out by Gore in every contest before Tuesday.
Bradley's campaign had so sputtered that even before the voting
Tuesday, many of his most prominent supporters said it would take a
miracle for him to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At a subdued gathering in Manhattan Tuesday night, Bradley said
he had called the vice president to congratulate him _ and he
insisted that his campaign was a worthy crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our lack of victory tonight, we've shaped the national
debate in this campaign,'' he said. ``We've brought core Democratic
issues to the fore. When no one was talking about the 44 million
Americans without health insurance, we gave voice to the voiceless.
When no one was talking about the 13 children who die every day of
gun violence we heard their cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has so fizzled that even on his signature issue, health
care, voters were more likely to say that the vice president had
the preferable plan. The sweep of Gore's triumph allows him to move
more quickly to patch up relations with Bradley's backers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was not as pronounced. The polls of voters
Tuesday, conducted by a consortium of the television networks and
the Associated Press, found that Bush and McCain continued to draw
from far different bases of support. Republicans backed Bush
overwhelmingly while independents and Democrats, in states where
they could vote for a Republican, favored McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The victors in each state depended largely on the proportion of
independents and Republicans in the electorate. In Ohio, for
example, more than seven in 10 voters described themselves as
Republicans and seven in 10 of them voted for Bush. By contrast, in
Massachusetts, nearly six in 10 of the voters described themselves
as independents, and seven in 10 of them backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that either candidate had cut into the
other's constituency. Those who described themselves as
conservatives, and those who want abortion to be illegal, voted for
Bush; those calling themselves moderates or liberals, as well as
those who favor abortion rights, favored McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his feisty speech Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, Bush repeatedly
cited Gore and struggled to contain a satisfied grin. ``American
must not give Clinton &UR; - &LR; Gore four more years,'' he said, reciting a
list of ills of the current administration. And, pointedly, he
raised Gore's fund-raising troubles, saying, ``I will remind Al
Gore that Americans do not want a White House where there is no
controlling legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   At boisterous rally in Nashville earlier in the evening, Gore
praised Bradley, saying he was ``moved and touched'' by his rival's
commitment to healing racial divisions.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gore put forth an unvarnished plea for the
independents and Republicans who backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   And in an unmistakable dig at Bush, the vice president also
depicted Republicans as intolerant. ``In this election, we are the
party of the mainstream,'' he said. ``We are the party of hope. We
appeal to hope, not anger, not to exclusion. We look to the future,
not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Tuesday night, Gore had begun concentrating his
assaults on Bush, while the governor had softened his conservative
oratory in recent days, positioning himself for the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   While the days leading up to Tuesday's primaries had been
dominated by McCain's repudiation of religious right leaders and
Bush's apology for his much-ridiculed appearance at Bob Jones
University _ an institution that is viewed as anti-Catholic _ there
was no sign in the exit polls that those episodes significantly
affected the voting. Bush held his own among Catholics, although he
did not do as well with them as with other groups.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain's attacks on the religious right appeared to be a
mistaken gambit _ or one that did not yield him new support among
more moderate voters. In New York and Ohio, people who said
McCain's criticisms mattered backed Bush; those who said they did
not matter backed McCain. In New York, six in 10 voters said
McCain's outspoken comments did not affect their vote; in Ohio,
nearly half said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the television evangelist who was harshly
attacked by McCain, said Tuesday night that he had been
``absolutely dumbfounded when Senator McCain had come to my home
town and launched that barrage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to destroy his campaign, and I didn't know
why he did it,'' he said in an interview with the Fox News Channel.
``To attack 25, 30 percent of your base just isn't smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he was opposed to a Bush-McCain ticket. Asked
whether he thought such an alliance were out of the question, he
replied, ``I really think so. That kind of anger, the concept that
there are people who are agents of evil, that kind of thing isn't
civility in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case throughout the contest, voters said they
were more concerned about candidates' morals than about issues.
While McCain was widely seen as someone who stands up for his
beliefs and tells people the truth, Bush was seen as having high
moral values.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio and Missouri, two pivotal battlegrounds in the fall,
Bush did extraordinarily well. In those states, Bush won the
backing of men and women, the young and old, voters who are
educated and those who are not, and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, where a quarter of the Republican electorate is
Catholic, Bush drew half their vote and McCain took just under
half. In Missouri, where Catholics account for a quarter of the
vote, more than half favored Bush and less than four in 10 backed
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's nationwide sweep was especially welcome for him since his
campaign has endured its share of traumas. While Gore has been
elected to two terms as vice president and served in the House and
Senate from Tennessee for 16 years, he was not prepared for
Bradley's sudden emergence last year. That led him to dramatically
retool his campaign from top to bottom, shifting his campaign
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, distancing himself from
President Clinton and significantly loosening up his style on the
stump.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was unrelenting in finding holes in Bradley's
record and in his proposals _ and put Bradley on the defensive for
several weeks before the former senator responded.
</P>
<P>
   The voters Tuesday gave Bradley high marks for saying what was
on his mind regardless of the political price he might pay; they
viewed Gore as more of a panderer.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bradley had little backing anywhere among any
demographic group and failed to leave his mark in any significant
way.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Republicans, Democrats said they were more
concerned with a candidate's standing on the issues than his
personal qualities. In a sign that the Clinton impeachment hearings
may still loom, Clinton was seen as doing a good job by more than
eight in 10 of the Democrats who voted. But only one in four rated
him favorably as a person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
