<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEWYORK-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE VICTORIOUS AS INSURGENT RIVALS FIZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to update; percentages updated in grafs 6 and 7; graf 10
mentions Giuliani's Senate candidacy; grafs 14-16 are new;
clarification in graf 17; 5 grafs at end of article have been
cut.)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the fervent backing of New York's Republican
establishment, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas wrestled his way to
victory Tuesday over John McCain in a state that had just last week
seemed fertile ground for the senator from Arizona. Bush won a
solid majority of both the delegates and the total Republican votes
in the state's first contested presidential primary since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, New York: You have just pushed George W. Bush
over the top to be the next president of the United States,'' Gov.
George Pataki of New York declared at a victory rally in Manhattan,
looking visibly relieved as he celebrated an outcome on which
Pataki arguably had as much riding as Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, a presidential primary that had
uncustomarily been almost lost in the shadow of the Republican
fight fizzled to an end, as Vice President Al Gore swamped Bill
Bradley in a state where Bradley, too, once thought he had a real
opportunity to derail a candidate backed by the party
establishment. Bradley did not even wait for half the votes to be
counted, appearing before a somber audience of supporters in
Manhattan to both concede and signal his imminent withdrawal from
his race.
</P>
<P>
   The results in the Republican primary in New York offered a
dramatic conclusion to a political struggle that in the space of
two weeks revealed strains not only in the national Republican
Party, as Bush and McCain engaged in pitched and personal battle on
the state's airwaves, but in New York's Republican organization as
well. The differences in New York were at least momentarily set
aside in victory Tuesday night, as Pataki appeared on stage with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who had scorned Pataki for guiding a Bush
campaign in New York that was based on attacking McCain's voting
record.
</P>
<P>
   By initial indications, at least, Pataki's strategy _ combined
with a Republican primary system designed to help the candidate
backed by the party establishment _ appears to have served Bush
well. A series of public polls over the past few days suggested
that McCain, who presented himself as a moderate, was tied with
Bush in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The final result was not that close. In New York, Republicans
vote not for candidates but for 93 delegates. With 98 percent of
the precincts counted last night, Bush had 67 delegates, compared
to 26 for McCain. A third candidate, Alan Keyes, had not won any
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A tally of the popular vote found that with 97 percent of the
districts counted, Bush had 50.4 percent of the votes cast for
delegates and McCain had 43.7 percent, according to unofficial
results. Keyes had 3.5 percent, and Steve Forbes, whose name
remained on the ballot, even though he has withdrawn from the race,
2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The percentages reflect the number of votes cast for delegates
supporting each candidate, and Republicans could select up to three
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
