<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS APPROVE OF BOURQUE TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Detroit Red Wings are disappointed they didn't
get veteran defenseman Ray Bourque from the Boston Bruins, but they
are happy he went to Colorado instead of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the Red Wings don't think they will catch the Blues
for the top spot in the Western Conference, entering Tuesday five
points behind St. Louis in the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Division winners are the first three seeds in the playoffs. The
Red Wings are fourth and would face No. 5 Phoenix if the postseason
began today.
</P>
<P>
   The Los AngelesKings, one point back at No. 6, could have moved
ahead of the Coyotes on Tuesday after Phoenix was shut out by St.
Louis 4-0. But the Kings weren't able to beat Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's new team, the Avalanche, came in seventh overall but
routed No. 9 Calgary 8-3 and moved ahead of Edmonton into first
place in the Northwest Division. The Avs and Oilers each have 73
points, but Colorado (31-27-10) has a better winning percentage
than Edmonton (25-27-15).
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was traded along with forward Dave Andreychuk for
forward Brian Rolston, defenseman Martin Grenier, center Sami
Pahlsson and Boston's choice of a first-round pick in either 2000
or 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a pitch for him,'' Detroit general manager Ken Holland
said. ``The price was a little too steep.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues would have teamed Bourque with Al MacInnis on their
second defensive unit. St. Louis' top defensive unit is Norris
Trophy favorite Chris Pronger and Marc Bergevin.
</P>
<P>
   First-round playoff victories, however would set up a showdown
between Detroit and St. Louis in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, 39, can be an unrestricted free agent after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Smolinski back: Kings second-line center Bryan Smolinski was
back in action Tuesday with two stitches near his left eye. He had
no problems from the corneal abrasion he suffered in the second
period Saturday against Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski spent more than a minute on the ice after he was
struck in the face by Nashville's Greg Johnson. Johnson received a
four-minute minor penalty and Smolinski was done for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The eye cleared overnight, but the Kings did not practice
Sunday. He worked out Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never was a problem, it cleared up right away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski does not wear a visor, which is standard equipment in
junior and college hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys get to the NHL and they take them off forever,''
Kings coach Andy Murray said. ``I'm not sure why.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles: Kings defenseman Mattias Norstrom often gets
overlooked because he is not a scorer. But Norstrom's plus-minus is
plus-20, the highest by a King since 1990-91 when Wayne Gretzky was
plus-30. . . . Donald Audette was a healthy scratch for the second
consecutive game. . . . Nashville ended Luc Robitaille's scoring
streak at 15 on Saturday by limiting his access to open ice. The
Red Wings did the same, holding Robitaille without a shot in the
first period.
</P>
</TEXT>
