   GORE-BUSH-STRATEGY (Los Angeles) _ For Vice President Al Gore
and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, there were enough sweet victories
Tuesday night so that they could begin to focus on running against
each other in the general election. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-GORE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ For someone who was embalmed just
last fall by a New York tabloid as ``Dead Veep Walking,'' it was a
stunning achievement. Twelve years after he embarrassed himself
with an ill-conceived and inept presidential campaign and only a
few months after he was nearly written off as a loser, Vice
President Al Gore has revived his fortunes. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-BUSH (Austin, Texas) _ Nearly five weeks ago, when Gov.
George W. Bush's grip on the Republican presidential nomination
looked tenuous, he indulged in the most controversial symbolism of
his campaign and appeared at Bob Jones University, a conservative
Christian school in South Carolina that still barred interracial
dating. But Tuesday night, as the Texas governor basked in several
key victories that put him in what he clearly felt was a very
different position, he turned that symbolism inside out. He chose
to be introduced at his celebration here by a black female educator
from Houston, Phyllis C. Hunter. By Francis X. Clines and B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
