<P>
   PUERTORICO-CUISINE (San Juan) _ Walking into the Casita Blanca
Restaurant is like walking into a country home, one with ceiling
fans, bare cement floors and live poultry _ in this case a turkey
named Gabino and a rooster known as Pancho _ roaming the indoor
patio. In this small restaurant in the working-class neighbhorhood
of Villa Palmeras, Jesus Perez has created something that is simple
yet rare: a place where you can taste the distinctive flavors of
Puerto Rican cuisine, the traditional dishes that are almost
impossible to find outside of a home _ even here on the island. By
Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-CREDITS (New York) _ There was a time when chefs were
anonymous. No one knew their names. If a restaurant was named Chez
Louis, chances were that Louis was not the guy behind the stove. He
was the owner. When anyone dared to ask Henri Soule, the owner of
Le Pavillon, who was responsible for the greatness of his
restaurant, he had a very simple answer: ``Le Pavillon,'' he would
say, ``c'est moi.'' I found myself thinking about those far-off
days while studying the menu at Thalia recently. Down at the
bottom, the name of the chef is printed. And next to the chef,
Michael Otsuka, his sous-chefs, Bill McDaniel and Robert Martin.
Sous-chefs? The United States has often been called a credit
society. It's true in two senses. Americans love credit cards. And
they love credit _ the recognition of accomplishment,
near-accomplishment, well-intended lack of accomplishment or merely
showing up. In a success-ethic democracy, it just doesn't feel
right unless everybody wins and trophies are handed out all around.
A critic's notebook by William Grimes.
</P>
