<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS &LR;      03-08 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The Suns couldn't contain themselves and didn't try. When
recruiting Penny Hardaway, they came up with a ``Backcourt 2000''
label for the combination of Hardaway and Jason Kidd and plastered
it everywhere Hardaway's wandering eyes might have strayed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It worked to woo Hardaway, and the combination has lived up to
that breathless billing. But for 42 minutes Tuesday, ``Backcourt
2000'' was outplayed by Backcourt 2001 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway and Kidd could not slow the Rockets' Cuttino Mobley,
Shandon Anderson and, especially, Steve Francis. The Rockets held a
lead heading down the stretch, and there did not seem to be
anything the Suns could do to stop the Rockets guards.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game on the line, the Suns who do not come with a
marketing slogan, shoe commercial or look-alike puppet suddenly
emerged from the backcourt shadow and carried Phoenix to a 108-101
win at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real frustrating,'' Francis said. ``We played them a good
game. We played hard the whole game. We went up a couple early. We
led throughout the second half. And we still couldn't close the
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis had a season-high 32 points. Anderson and Mobley
combined for 34. But the Suns' frontcourt would not let the Rockets
get a defensive rebound for the last six minutes as Phoenix came
back to literally take the win from the Rockets' grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those rebounds in the fourth quarter were ones we
should have gotten,'' Mobley said. ``They were tipping it to each
other and playing hard and came out and beat us in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last six minutes, the Suns scored as many points after
missed shots, eight, as the Rockets scored overall. As loaded as
the Suns are with scorers _ six hit for double figures while
playing their second game in as many nights Tuesday _ the Rockets
gave them extra shots until they were shot down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do that, they have so many different weapons,''
Anderson said. ``Every guy is capable of doing something to hurt
you. They exploited us.''
</P>
<P>
   The inability to stop the Suns late ruined an otherwise
spectacular showing by the Rockets' backcourt against the guard
tandem considered the league's best.
</P>
<P>
   A week after a shooting slump had made him 4-of-29 over three
games, Francis made 13 of 21 shots and six of 11 3-pointers. Facing
Kidd, a first-team All-NBA defender last season, he scored 17
points in the third quarter and collected eight assists and four
steals for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is the same,'' Francis said of his shooting
turnaround. ``I was just missing shots. Of course, when you're
slumping, you come in earlier and stay later, and that's what I've
been doing. And I think it's been paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, isolated through much of the first half, made five of 13
shots for 14 points. Anderson made nine of 15 shots for 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could take them every single time, every time,'' Mobley
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the ``Backcourt 2000'' label, Mobley responded, ``Is
that so? Yeah, well, OK. We respect them, of course. We're not
going to talk about that. But people know what we're building.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets led by four midway through the fourth quarter. But
they could not get a stop for six minutes, until there were 31
seconds remaining and the Suns held a 106-101 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say the Suns never missed. But for six minutes,
they rebounded each of their four missed shots to keep shooting
until the Rockets could not keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta, who finished with 23 points and 12 rebounds,
twice followed Suns misses inside. Hardaway beat the shot clock
with a running nine-footer. And with 3:40 left, Hardaway found
Cliff Robinson in the corner for a 3 and a 98-95 Suns lead.
</P>
<P>
   Francis set up cutting center Kelvin Cato for a slam. But
Hardaway, who had 24 points and 10 assists, came right back with a
drive to the hole to push the Suns' lead to 100-97 with 3:06 left.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of a timeout, the Rockets threw the ball away, giving
the Suns an opening to take their lead to five points, their
largest since the first half. As damaging, however, the Suns burned
a full minute doing it, with Gugliotta grabbing his third offensive
rebound in three minutes to allow Rodney Rogers to nail a tough
fadeaway on the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Francis quickly scored on a drive. But Rogers was fouled and
nailed two free throws to push the Phoenix lead back to five.
Francis then lost the ball on a drive, and Rogers grabbed another
miss and scored, giving the Suns a 106-99 lead with 55.8 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   The layup gave Rogers six points in a span of 71 seconds. For
the game, he made all five of his shots and all four of his free
throws to score 15 points in 32 minutes off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have many perfect games in this league,'' Rogers
said. ``When you come off the bench in the fourth quarter, you have
to make things happen. I scored some points and got some big
rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis scored on another drive. And the Rockets got a last
chance when Robinson stepped out of bounds. But Francis' 3 swam all
over the rim and fell out. Hakeem Olajuwon left his follow short,
and Kidd put the game way with free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good scoring game,'' Francis said. ``But it hurt us
to lose a game like that. We were not rebounding very well near the
end. We could have had control of the game, but we just didn't make
the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
