<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     03-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LACK BITE DURING HOMESTAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings could have moved into fifth
place in the Western Conference playoff race with a victory
Tuesday. The Detroit Red Wings had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   They smothered the Kings 3-1 in front of a sellout crowd of
18,118 at the Staples Center, avenging two February losses and
nearly giving the Kings their first shutout loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jere Karalahti broke that up with 7:17 left in the
game, his fifth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Kings a lift and stirred the fans, especially when
Detroit's Brendan Shanahan was whistled off just two minutes later
for interference.
</P>
<P>
   But they could not net the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings pulled their goaltender with 1:09 remaining for an
extra skater, and Rob Blake quickly took a slapshot from the point
that was gloved by Detroit's Chris Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings called timeout but lost the faceoff in the Red Wings'
zone. Shanahan and Steve Yzerman played with the puck before giving
it to Pat Verbeek who scored with 58.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are still sixth with 73 points, but they are just four
points from being out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They now are 1-2-1 four games into their longest homestand of
the year. The Kings' only road game until March 23 is at the Pond
in Anaheim. This was the time when they were supposed to eliminate
the suspense. But they clearly are not taking advantage.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1:47 stretch of the first period, the Kings allowed two
goals that decided the game. One was short-handed by Sergei Fedorov
with 15:16 gone in the period that beat goaltender Jamie Storr and
took the crowd out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Storr was replacing Stephane Fiset, who was placed on injured
reserve Monday with a strained right groin suffered Saturday
against lowly Nashville. The Kings won that game, 3-2 in overtime
on a goal by Jozef Stumpel, but it didn't hide that the club is
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which now has five consecutive victories, just drove
home the point.
</P>
<P>
   When the two met Feb. 18 in Detroit, the Kings won 3-2 to extend
their winning streak to a season-high five games. They withstood
the taunting of Red Wings muscleman Darren McCarty and were the
more disciplined team.
</P>
<P>
   Although they dropped the next two, they finished strong on
their longest road trip in seven years. The momentum hasn't carried
over.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Red Wings defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom made it 1-0 when
he took a pass from Mathieu Dandenault, skated through the slot and
fired it over Storr's right shoulder at the 13:29 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings weren't generating much offense, taking just seven
shots on Osgood in the first period. Three came from long range by
Rob Blake, but the first line of Stumpel, Luc Robitaille, Ziggy
Pallfy had just one combined in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   By taking away the Kings' first unit, Detroit also controlled
their power play, which was 0 for 4 through the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With few scoring opportunities, Fedorov's short-handed goal made
the Red Wings' two-goal lead seem almost insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up the puck from Lidstrom in his own end and skated up
the right side untouched. Fedorov closed in and beat Storr over the
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Detroit (40-20-7) still is five points behind
St. Louis in the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Their only loss during their winning streak was in the
acquisition of Boston's veteran defenseman Ray Bourque, who was
traded to Colorado instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     03-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TWO vastly different scripts will play out in America's hoops
heartland this week, although the stakes are virtually the same.
The Big 12's postseason exercise in maximizing revenue should
ultimately decide no more than Missouri's fate vis-a-vis the NCAA
Tournament, while Conference USA's one-thoroughbred race figures to
make or break Tulane's March Madness aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's about it in terms of hard-core significance. But at
least in Kansas City, the ball will be a blast. Memphis' C-USA
party is less a sports event than it is a coronation. It's
basically Hugs' monsters against a bunch of fellows who need hugs.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, C-USA ranks a lofty fifth among all conferences in the
power ratings, but that's greatly skewed by Cincinnati's No. 1
individual status. Bob Huggins' Bearcats, 16-0 during the league's
regular season, finished with six more victories than any of their
alleged rivals. And their three games at the Pyramid figure to be
the equivalent of a BCS-bound football team's full-contact
post-Christmas scrimmages. The idea is to work in a little extra
conditioning while making sure nobody gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-2 Bearcats' season of consequence starts the following
weekend in round two of the NCAAs, the round in which they have met
their demise the past three springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you in Indy!'' Cincy's fans chanted late in the Cats'
84-41 billy-clubbing of Saint Louis' Billikens on Saturday, and
that's exactly where they must wind up for the year to be judged
anything approaching a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the nation, nobody cares about Cincinnati,'' said Pete
Mickeal, circling the wagons on behalf of his fellow Bearcats.
``The perception is we'll just lose in the second round.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-deserved perception, until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   For Tulane, however, the trip to Memphis means more than just a
chance to drop by Graceland. Although the Green Wave ``won''
C-USA's National Conference with an 8-8 record and a tiebreaker
advantage over Marquette, considering the Greenies' triple-digit
RPI, it's surely RIP for them unless they beat Cincinnati to reach
the tournament final. And even that might not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   If not, then just three conference teams will go to the Dance.
Louisville, with an 8-1 finish, and DePaul, despite seven
conference losses, are both safely in on the strength of their
power ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical question: Shouldn't the No. 5-rated league merit
at least a quartet of Tournament spots? After all, the third-ranked
Big 12 is a lock for five, and Missouri, a much stronger bubble
team than Tulane, would make six.
</P>
<P>
   Pragmatic answer: No.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is look at the standings _ and the AP Top 25
_ to see why the discrepancy is justified. While C-USA's
second-tier teams (that is to say all of them relative to Cincy)
were busily beating each other up, the Big 12 clearly separated its
haves from the have-nots. Five teams went 11-5 or better in the
conference, and four finished comfortably ensconced in the top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, none of the latter was Kansas, a lowly 24th.
</P>
<P>
   For the previous three seasons of the Big 12's existence, the
mighty Jayhawks went to KC much as Cincinnati now marches into
Memphis. This week, their presence is somewhat plebeian. They're
even being required to play a first-round game Thursday afternoon,
an affront to Phog Allen's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, seventh-ranked Iowa State goes in seeded No. 1 on the
wings of its first conference title since the end of World War II.
In reality, however, Texas (13th), Oklahoma (15th) and Oklahoma
State (17th) are Nos. 1a, 1b and 1c _ you pick the order _ setting
up a Saturday-Sunday brawl certain to be as exhausting for the fans
as it will be for the players.
</P>
<P>
   That, ironically, is the only downside to the Big 12's emerging
democracy. The eventual champion may be so drained physically and
emotionally that it will have little gas left for the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   While Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy said upon the conclusion
of the regular season, ``The hard part's over,'' it's not. The
Cyclones have the league's strongest starting five but drop off
measurably in depth, making them seem badly suited for the
three-days, three-games battle ahead of them. Although they're
obviously good enough to make the final, you can argue they won't
have enough left to prevail should they get there, even with a
virtual free pass vs. Nebraska or Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   With Kansas, Colorado and Missouri likely first-day opponents
for the Big 12's three other big-four teams, it's going to be a
compelling dogfight _ but one laden with pedigree. In Memphis, on
the other hand, Elvis is more likely to sing the national anthem
Saturday than Cincinnati is to lose.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
