r a BC-ELN-PROPS-LADN     03-08 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-PROPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA   VOTERS OK MARRIAGE MEASURE, APPROVE INDIAN GAMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Gay marriage was overwhelmingly rejected in
early returns and Proposition 22 was projected in exit polls as a
clear winner Tuesday, as California voters approved barring legally
recognizing same-sex marriages in the state even if other states do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns showed Proposition 1A, the Indian gaming measure,
headed toward victory along with four public works bond issues and
an initiative that toughens penalties for juveniles who commit
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 25, the campaign finance reform measure, and
Proposition 26, a measure reducing the majority needed to pass
school bonds from two-thirds to one-half of votes cast plus one
vote, both were trailing, along with two measures easing
restrictions on ``bad faith'' lawsuits against insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican state Sen. W.J. ``Pete'' Knight of Palmdale, who
authored Proposition 22, said he was delighted by the affirmation
that state law defines marriage only as the union between a man and
a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy the people of the state of California decided they
didn't want to change the definition of marriage as the union
between a man and a woman, which has worked for civilization for
thousands of years and has been shown to be the best unit in which
to raise kids,'' said Knight, who is the father of a gay son.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Proposition 22, who argued that the measure was
anti-gay, were not officially commenting, said spokeswoman Tracey
Conaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, we're heartbroken,'' said Esperanza Macias, field
coordinator for No-on-22. ``But this is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the state ballot measure was intended as a
simple, 14-word formula for the protection and affirmation of the
institution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no intention to hurt anyone, no intention to be
divisive, no hidden agenda,'' said Knight, saying his relationship
with his son remains a private family matter and that the only
emotion he felt was joy over the measure's passage.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, however, kindled complex reactions among those who
viewed it as a symbolic, and therefore hurtful, affront to
homosexuals. It quickly became the year's flashpoint among the 20
propositions, overshadowing a series of fiscal measures.
</P>
<P>
   No other state recognizes same-sex marriages, but 30 other
states have passed laws much like Proposition 22 as a defensive
move after a case involving same-sex marriage reached Hawaii's
Supreme Court in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   All states currently recognize only marriage between a man and a
woman. California's law, however, requires the state to recognize
legally performed marriages in other states, including common-law
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   In other issues, voters indicated they were prepared to crack
down harder on juvenile crime, with Proposition 21 leading in early
returns.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed overhaul of the juvenile justice system, sponsored
by former Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, would give prosecutors,
rather than juvenile court judges, the power to decide whether
teens age 14 to 17 would be tried as adults for serious crimes, and
would limit judges' discretion in sending youths for treatment
rather than to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the propositions with the biggest impact on Californian
taxpayers - Propositions 12 through 16, authorizing $4.6 billion in
new bonds for water, park, library and other projects - were
winning in early returns. Only Proposition 15, which would provide
$220 million for new crime labs, was lagging.
</P>
<P>
   The bond issues, in total, are estimated to cost each state
resident about $10 a year for the next quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a series of school scandals in the Los Angeles
Unified School District, Proposition 26 - the measure that would
reduce from two-thirds to a simple majority the votes needed for
local school bonds - was failing.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns had the state's latest campaign finance measure -
which included limits on who can contribute to campaigns, and how
much - trailing. Proposition 25 would ban corporate campaign
contributions, and provide partial public financing.
</P>
<P>
   Voters were overwhelmingly turning down Proposition 28, an
effort to rescind a 50-cents-a-pack cigarette tax passed in 1998.
Ned Roscoe of the Cigarettes Cheaper! discount chain had challenged
the tax sponsored by film director Rob Reiner. The tax had been
estimate to generate some $650 million a year in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running debate over Indian gaming in the state took a
big step toward resolution, with early returns showing Proposition
1A, which would expand tribal gambling, ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A related measure, Proposition 29, was far closer, but tribal
representatives have said if 1A passes, the outcome of Proposition
29 will not matter.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also appeared to be rejecting two propositions, 30 and
31, that would uphold new state laws giving victims in an accident
the right to file ``bad faith'' lawsuits against the other party's
insurer for denial or delay of legitimate claims.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
