<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS BOUNCE DALLAS WITH SUBS SUPPLYING STIFF-ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dennis Rodman, with blue and blond streaks in his
hair, dove around, engaged the crowd and rebounded like a madman.
</P>
<P>
   The eccentric forward apparently is cutting back on the
technical fouls and suspensions that have characterized his brief
stint with the Dallas Mavericks. But that isn't to say that the
Sonics' 101-86 victory Tuesday night was a quiet foray up and down
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton blew his fuse, then Ruben Patterson made the place
go pop to start a lengthy home-stand the way the Sonics envisioned:
With a bang.
</P>
<P>
   The game also was bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was ejected in the third quarter, and the Sonics played
most of the second half without three starters. So Patterson used
the opportunity to score a career-high 32 points _ 16 of which came
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson did his damage mostly without Payton, Vin Baker and
Horace Grant on the floor. With Payton banished to the locker room,
Baker sitting in foul trouble and Grant hurt, Patterson deprived
the surging Mavs of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception that Ruben can't shoot. They were just
backing off him, and he was just shooting at the basket,'' Sonics
coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruben can shoot those open shots. We just don't want him
shooting a lot of shots off the dribble.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson attacked Dallas' defense and made six of nine shots in
the final frame. He shot 12-for-20 overall and had eight rebounds
and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a zone,'' Patterson said. ``I said to myself I had
to step up. I was telling the guys to get (the ball) to me, and
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   All Payton got was a hard time in the second half. He gave the
officials a hassle, too.
</P>
<P>
   Payton picked up his fifth foul _ an offensive infraction _ with
54.7 seconds remaining in the third. He went to the bench for a
substitution but didn't leave quietly. Payton's comments from the
bench led to his second technical foul and an automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had received his first technical five minutes earlier
after arguing another offensive foul called against him. He left
with a near triple-double (19 points, nine assists, eight rebounds)
in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was already out after he suffered a hyperextended right
elbow with 3:28 left in the third period. The Sonics were left to
count on the ability of their bench when Vin Baker picked up his
fifth foul with 7:20 left in the game. He did not return.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics led 83-73 at that point, and a lineup that
featured Patterson, Brent Barry, Emanual Davis, Greg Foster and
Rashard Lewis more than held off the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some guys on this team who are capable of having some
big nights for us,'' Baker said. ``Those guys work hard in
practice. They're dedicated, and it showed tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics broke two trends Tuesday night. They jumped on the
Mavs early instead of getting off to another of the slow starts
that have plagued them in five previous games. And the win over a
soft opponent bucked a trend of home losses to marginal teams.
</P>
<P>
   This is the result the Sonics are looking for this month as they
play 11 of their next 13 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is like us cashing a dividend check,'' said
Westphal, whose team moved back into sixth place in the Western
Conference standings because Minnesota lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked hard on the road, and we have a chance to make
our record very good now by taking care of business at home.When
you get a team like Dallas coming in ... you need to get those
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the Sonics had demoralized the Mavs in the first
half. Ahead 25-20 in the second quarter, they put together a 19-3
spurt and ran away from the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a barrage sparked mostly by Payton, Patterson and a
disruptive defense.
</P>
<P>
   Give the Sonics credit for aggressive ball-hawking, but the Mavs
committed several unforced errors during that stretch. At one
point, they threw the ball away on four consecutive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas committed seven of its 21 turnovers in the second
quarter, and the Sonics had a 55-33 lead just before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having good starts at home, so I really wasn't
worried about the start of the game,'' Westphal said. ``I was more
worried about Dallas getting hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, without incident, collected 15 rebounds, and the
Mavericks made a couple of runs in the second half. They got to
within eight points in the third and within nine with 9:25 left in
the game. Then Davis sank a 3-pointer to extend the lead, and
Patterson sealed the game by scoring the Sonics' final 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hitting everything,'' Patterson said. ``I'm glad I
got my career high.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics needed the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   TIP-INS: The Sonics activated guard Vernon Maxwell Tuesday and
placed forward Chuck Person on the injured list. Maxwell had missed
29 games because of arthroscopic surgery on his right knee. Person
has torn cartilage in his left knee ... The start time for a game
Sunday against Toronto has been changed to 3 p.m. to accommodate a
national broadcast on NBC ... Dallas forward Dennis Rodman was
charged Tuesday with misdemeanor drunken driving stemming from a
December arrest in Costa Mesa, Calif. Police said Rodman had a
blood-alcohol level of .15, nearly twice California's legal limit,
when he was pulled over Dec. 22. His arraignment is scheduled for
April 3.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
