<SLUG> BC-ELN-DA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES DISTRICT ATTORNEY RACE HEADED FOR RUNOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil
Garcetti appeared Tuesday to be headed toward a Nov. 7 showdown
with veteran prosecutor Steve Cooley, who was running a close
second.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt by the widening LAPD corruption scandal and a surge in
Republicans casting ballots for the officially nonpartisan post,
Garcetti was coming up short of the simple majority he needed to
avoid a runoff against the second-place finisher in the three-man
race.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti, a two-term Democratic incumbent, came under fire
throughout the campaign from Cooley, a top deputy in the District
Attorney's Office, and environmental lawyer Barry Groveman, a
former county and city prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting a runoff, Garcetti refused to participate in campaign
debates before Tuesday's election, shunned TV and radio spots and
reserved nearly all of his campaign treasury to give him an early
boost in an anticipated showdown in November.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley raised less money than the other candidates and chose to
only broadcast his platform over the radio. But he boasted some
advantages over Groveman going into the contest, including his
decades of experience as a county prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative, Cooley was expected to benefit as Republican
voters turned out to cast ballots in the GOP presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Groveman's showing in the primary was expected to be partly
helped by his campaign as a reform-minded outsider, which included
a recent television commercial that stressed his role in exposing
the Belmont Learning Center scandal. Groveman is a private attorney
from Calabasas.
</P>
<P>
   Following months of the public's seeming apathy toward the race
for the county's top prosecutor, Cooley and Groveman increased
interest in the contest largely by arguing that Garcetti is
partially culpable for the LAPD Rampart corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Garcetti's office has asked the Superior Court
to set aside dozens of convictions that his prosecutors won using
allegedly false testimony by cops, who also have been accused of
planting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political attacks, Garcetti remained hunkered down,
hoping his unwillingness to even acknowledge his opponents would
diminish their credibility. His camp became increasingly resigned
over the past 10 days to the likelihood that he would be forced
into a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Garcetti's future flashed before his eyes when
it took days to determine whether he bested another relative
unknown, John Lynch. While being outmatched financially, Lynch came
within 4,000 votes of winning the 1996 general election. More than
2 million ballots were cast. Lynch benefited greatly from voter
dissatisfaction over Garcetti's handling of the O.J. Simpson murder
trial.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Garcetti raised over $1 million and saved
almost his entire war chest for November. Cooley and Groveman have
spent nearly all the money they raised.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 0229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
