r a BC-ELN-PROPS-1stld-write     03-08 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-PROPS-1stld-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA   VOTERS OK MARRIAGE MEASURE, APPROVE INDIAN GAMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Updating throughout) 
 
 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Proposition 22, the controversial measure
affirming that only marriages between a man and a woman are
recognized as legal in California, won clear-cut passage Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 1A, the Indian gaming measure, also won passage
along with four public works bond issues and an initiative that
toughens penalties for juveniles who commit serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 25, the campaign finance reform measure, was
defeated, as were two measures easing restrictions on ``bad faith''
lawsuits against insurers, The Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 26, a measure reducing the majority needed to pass
school bonds from two-thirds to one-half of votes cast plus one
vote, was leading narrowly.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted by Voter News Service for The Associated
Press and TV networks showed Proposition 22 got strong support from
men and women and from voters of all races and income groups.
Democrats opposed it by 2-1 but Republicans backed it by about 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Republican state Sen. W.J. ``Pete'' Knight of Palmdale, who
authored Proposition 22, said he was delighted by the affirmation
that state law defines marriage only as the union between a man and
a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy the people of the state of California decided they
didn't want to change the definition of marriage as the union
between a man and a woman, which has worked for civilization for
thousands of years and has been shown to be the best unit in which
to raise kids,'' said Knight, who is the father of a gay son.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Proposition 22, the ``No-on-22'' campaign, said
they were disappointed, but were encouraged that the debate over
homosexual rights had been elevated by the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a step forward,'' said spokeswoman Tracey Conaty. ``It
changed the debate from if gays and lesbians and their families
should have the same basic rights as heterosexual couples to how
they should be afforded those rights and responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the state ballot measure was intended as a
simple, 14-word formula for the protection and affirmation of the
institution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no intention to hurt anyone, no intention to be
divisive, no hidden agenda,'' said Knight, saying his relationship
with his son remains a private family matter and that the only
emotion he felt was joy over the measure's passage.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, however, kindled complex reactions among those who
viewed it as a symbolic, and therefore hurtful, affront to
homosexuals. It quickly became the year's flash point among the 20
propositions, overshadowing a series of fiscal measures.
</P>
<P>
   No other state recognizes same-sex marriages, but 30 other
states have passed laws much like Proposition 22 as a defensive
move after a case involving same-sex marriage reached Hawaii's
Supreme Court in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   All states currently recognize only marriage between a man and a
woman. California's law, however, requires the state to recognize
legally performed marriages in other states, including common-law
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   In other issues, voters indicated they were prepared to crack
down harder on juvenile crime, with the passage of Proposition 21.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed overhaul of the juvenile justice system, sponsored
by former Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, would give prosecutors,
rather than juvenile court judges, the power to decide whether
teens age 14 to 17 would be tried as adults for serious crimes, and
would limit judges' discretion in sending youths for treatment
rather than to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five propositions with the biggest impact on
Californian taxpayers _ Propositions 12, 13, 14 and 16, authorizing
about $4.46 billion in new bonds for water, park, library and other
projects _ won. Only Proposition 15, which would provide $220
million for new crime labs, was lagging.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a series of school scandals in the Los Angeles
Unified School District, Proposition 26 _ the measure that would
reduce from two-thirds to a simple majority the votes needed for
local school bonds _ was leading by a small margin.
</P>
<P>
   The state's latest campaign finance measure _ which included
limits on who can contribute to campaigns, and how much _ failed.
Proposition 25 would have banned corporate campaign contributions,
and provided partial public financing.
</P>
<P>
   Voters turned down Proposition 28, an effort to rescind a
50-cents-a-pack cigarette tax passed in 1998. Ned Roscoe of the
Cigarettes Cheaper! discount chain had challenged the tax sponsored
by film director Rob Reiner. The tax had been estimated to generate
some $650 million a year in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running debate over Indian gaming in the state took a
big step toward resolution, with the passage of Proposition 1A,
which would expand tribal gambling.
</P>
<P>
   A related measure, Proposition 29, was closer, but tribal
representatives have said if 1A passes, the outcome of Proposition
29 will not matter.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also rejected two propositions, 30 and 31, that would
uphold new state laws giving victims in an accident the right to
file ``bad faith'' lawsuits against the other party's insurer for
denial or delay of legitimate claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 0332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
