u e BC-AUTHOR-KAPLAN-ART-BOS     03-08 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KAPLAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes tips sidebar.)  
 FOR BENJAMIN KAPLAN, TUITION MONEY IS A MATTER OF DIGGING  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Six years ago, Benjamin Kaplan was a high
school junior in Eugene, Ore., with a nice resume (student body
president, tennis jock) and a decent shot at getting into an elite
college like Harvard. He got into Harvard, all right, graduating
last year with honors in economics. But what Harvard taught Kaplan
about finances paled beside what Kaplan taught himself about
financing his education.
</P>
<P>
   It began that junior year, in 1994, Kaplan says, with a
scholarship competition sponsored by Discover Card. Applying on a
whim, he was surprised to win $2,500. A few weeks later, Kaplan
learned he had won another $15,000 in Discovery Card's nationwide
contest. Bingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, big lights went off,'' Kaplan, 22, recalls
during an interview in the Charles Hotel, part of a self-arranged
book tour that brought him back east from his home in Oregon.
``What else was out there? I thought you had to be a Michael
Jordan-type athlete or to have cured cancer in high school to win
these things. So I did more research.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouring bookstores, libraries, and guidance office shelves
(this was the pre-Internet era), Kaplan came up with three dozen
competitions worth entering. Two dozen of these eventually paid off
for him, providing a total of $90,000 in tuition money _ and the
basis for a new book titled ``How to Go to College Almost for
Free'' (Waggle Dancer Books), which is getting positive reviews for
its practical approach to digging for scholarship gold.
</P>
<P>
   One commentator on amazon .com's Web site says the competition
among how-to books ``wasn't even close,'' with Kaplan's easily the
most useful. Another Internet reviewer says, ``You can tell the
author has experienced firsthand everything he writes about.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, who rejected signing with an established publisher in
favor of launching his own publishing venture, concedes that other
good guidebooks are out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My book is more about the key strategies in winning these
competitions, not where to find them,'' says Kaplan, an intense,
engaging young man who does not noticeably suffer from false
modesty. ``It's about separating out the people who are successful
at doing this from those who aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The softcover book is divided into 12 chapters, bearing such
titles as ``Painting Your Own Portrait'' and ``Acing the
Interview.'' It includes a directory of scholarships and state
agencies, plus samples of winning entries. While crammed with
specifics, from grooming personal essay themes to tapping database
search engines, the book stresses one unassailably simple piece of
advice: Sow and ye shall reap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common denominator among scholarship winners comes down to
one thing. They apply; others don't,'' says Kaplan. ``It's not like
buying a lottery ticket, because what I did in some cases to win
money was a lot of hard work. But if you're willing to put in the
work, you will win scholarship money. There are hundreds of
millions of dollars out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan says it's a myth that only certain types of students win
these contests, or that mediocre grades or lack of an unusual
talent make it futile to apply for, say, the Ayn Rand Essay Contest
(top prize: $10,000) or Tylenol Scholarship (also $10,000). In one
case, Kaplan lost out to an applicant who was in jail at the time.
The winning essay _ touching on drugs, gangs, and the value of
freedom _ is reprinted in Kaplan's book as an example of
perseverance in the face of daunting odds.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Kaplan met a student who wanted to be an
airline pilot and who'd heard about a scholarship specifically
offered to aspiring pilots. ``This guy thought he had no chance, so
he decided not to enter,'' says Kaplan. ``Later, he found out that
since no one had bothered to apply that year, the money went to the
person who'd won the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of a self-selection process that goes on
here,'' he continues. ``What you want to be saying is, `I'm a good
investment of your educational dollars because I'm going to work
hard. Or, I'm going to give something back to society. Or, I have
this latent potential that I've never developed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Researching obscure sources is seldom wasted effort either,
Kaplan contends. ``The harder you have to dig,'' he says, ``the
higher the chances that others won't.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kaplan's experience is any guide, playing the scholarship
game can be life-transforming. An only child, he grew up in a
middle-class family that valued education but faced challenges
about how to pay for it, he says. At 13, Kaplan was a nationally
ranked tennis star who dreamed of playing Wimbledon someday.
Sidelined by a back injury, however, he was forced to channel his
energies elsewhere, in one case setting up a homework help-line at
his high school.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his senior year, Kaplan and his family were busy
reaping the rewards _ financial and otherwise _ of his
extraordinary scholarship bounty. They were flown all over the
country to attend award ceremonies, and Kaplan was interviewed
wherever he went. He was even featured in a short documentary film
produced by Discover Card. The once-shy teenager shed his fear of
public speaking, he says, and the more exposure he got, the more
emboldened he became.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to Washington, D.C., Kaplan decided on the spur of the
moment to call on Oregon Senator Mark Hatfield. Hatfield
immediately offered Kaplan a summer internship, which he accepted.
Needless to say, none of this hurt Kaplan's chances of getting into
Harvard, where he went on to write for The Harvard Crimson and to
co-write the 1999 Hasty Pudding Theatricals musical, a political
spoof titled ``I Get No Kick From Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' says Kaplan, ``one legacy of this whole process was
learning the kinds of skills that can help, whether you're applying
to college or going out on job interviews. It also forced me to
evaluate my own strengths and weaknesses, like a love of writing
that I'd never really focused on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another valuable legacy is that Kaplan managed to graduate from
college debt-free. Because of this, he says, he was able to finance
the launch of his own company, which his parents are helping to
bankroll. As conceived by Kaplan, the company, Waggle Dancer Books
(www .waggledancer.com), will become a multimedia purveyor of
materials themed to ``life milestones'' such as community service
and job searches. He has also started a related Web site
(www.winscholarships .com), where he's known as the ``Scholarship
Coach.'' What Dr. Ruth does for the human libido, Kaplan aims to do
for the tuition subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   He's also working on a screenplay _ and yes, he's prepared to
cold-call Hollywood studio execs if he has to.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned from doing the book is to go for it, seize the
initiative,'' says Kaplan. ``All the best things I've done are
things I've done for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   --Use Internet search engines to check other high school and
college guidance offices for scholarship listings.
</P>
<P>
   --Create reusable application materials. Recycle past essays on
perennial themes.
</P>
<P>
   --Use school writing assignments to flesh out application
essays. Old homework papers may contain hidden treasures.
</P>
<P>
   --Find past contest winners in your community and talk to them
about how they did it.
</P>
<P>
   --Pay attention to lead times, especially for competitions
requiring long-term strategies. Approach the process as an
extracurricular activity that can pay big dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ADAPTED FROM ``HOW TO GO TO COLLEGE ALMOST FOR FREE.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
