<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: There's nothing hard about
hardware, done right
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I don't know what I'd do without an
old-fashioned hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what I would have done just last week, after a hose
burst that I had connected to my swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's fault but mine.
</P>
<P>
   I had bought a device that's supposed to maintain the pool's
water level.
</P>
<P>
   When the water falls below a certain level, the device
automatically turns itself on.
</P>
<P>
   When the water returns to the proper level, the device
automatically turns itself off.
</P>
<P>
   That way the pump won't burn itself up when the water runs low,
like it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   That way I won't have to pay $250 to $300 for a new pump, like I
did last year.
</P>
<P>
   This device, which I hooked up to a garden hose, was to solve my
problem. The only problem was, I hooked it up to a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   The water pressure is constant. A garden hose can stand water
pressure for just so long. At some point, it will burst.
</P>
<P>
   At some point after that, your neighbor's yard will begin to
look like a swimming pool itself.
</P>
<P>
   I had tried two different hoses, each your garden-variety of
garden hose. Different hoses, same results _ instant rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I took my problem to the people at the hardware
store. I've been taking them my problems, and they've been taking
care of me, for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   It's operated by the same family that owned the store when I was
growing up. The fellow whose name is on the sign out front learned
the business working for his father. Now his sons work for him.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind if you need just a dime's worth of nails. You get
personal service.
</P>
<P>
   What I needed, I told them, was an industrial-strength garden
hose that would hold up under constant pressure.
</P>
<P>
   What they told me was that there was no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later,'' said the fellow whose name is on the sign
out front, ``it'll burst. If I told you different, I'd be telling
you wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But before I could ask ``What can I do?'' he was telling his
son, whose name is also on the sign out front, ``Here's what we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   What they did was take a length of PVC-type pipe _ an
extra-flexible variety _ and used clamps to attach garden hose-type
connections at either end.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile, a little longer than normal, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   I had first told them that I needed 10 feet, but then on seeing
10 feet of it _ this after it had been cut from the roll _ I saw
I'd made a mistake, that I'd need more like 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to pay them for the hose they'd already cut. They
wouldn't hear of it. They said they'd just save it back. Sooner or
later somebody would come along needing 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Total bill _ for pipe, clamps, connections, labor _ was about
$15. Problem solved.
</P>
<P>
   I say all of that to say simply this:
</P>
<P>
   Warehouse discount centers, with acres and acres of everything
you could ever think of, will never be able to give the kind of
personal service you find in an old-fashioned hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what I'd do without an old-fashioned hardware
store.
</P>
<P>
   I hope the day never comes when I find out.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
