   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ After five frenetic weeks, the
presidential campaign looks just the way the pundits, the pollsters
and the party establishment scripted it a year ago. Despite the
promise of a cliffhanger, the favored candidates, Vice President Al
Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, relied on their money,
connections and political machines to survive unexpectedly strong
assaults from the insurgents, Democrat Bill Bradley and Republican
John McCain. By ROBERTY SALLADAY and LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   US-HOUSE (San Francisco) _ Voters in California's open primary
on Tuesday gave Democrats reason to believe they will take back
control of the U.S. House of Representatives this fall. By CHUCK
FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-REFORM (San Francisco) _ Campaign finance reform may be
the hot topic of national political debates. But Tuesday,
California voters made it clear that they're not willing to accept
just any reform. Proposition 25, a complicated measure that would
have devoted up to $55 million in state money to providing public
financing for candidates, went down to an emphatic defeat,
garnering only 35 percent of the vote. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MANAGEMENT-LESSONS (San Francisco) _ Often bosses get so caught
up in the day-to-day frenzy that they don't stop to think about how
they are performing a lot of mundane tasks that ought to be
delegated. If you delegate, certainly your subordinates might not
handle tasks as well as you would. But you can teach them how to do
better, and then have time to concentrate on the important parts of
your job. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-WINE-WEEK (Undated) _ The 1998 Llano Estacado ``Cellar
Select'' Chardonnay is an excellent, spicy apple-pear fruit and
just the right amount of oakiness to complement the fruit. By
MICHAEL LONSFORD. (Already filed; for release Friday, March 10.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS (San Francisco) _ Can you imagine making $100,000 in a
month while working in the great outdoors in Alaska? That is the
fantasy that drives being a commercial crabber on the Bering Sea,
where you experience the marrow of life of the great outdoors while
getting a stake in the last great Alaskan gold rush _ king crab.
Well, it doesn't always turn out that way, says former Alaskan
crabber Spike Walker. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Many unsuspecting travelers have
become pawns in an ongoing feud between travel agents and one of
the world's fastest-growing cruise lines _ a relationship so soured
that most agents seem unmoved by a $1 million show of respect for
their embattled profession. It's a saga that transcends cruising
and sheds insight into the changing environment in which we plan
our travels. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SKI-DEALS (Undated) _ It's not too late to play in the
snow. Spring calendars at U.S. ski resorts are dotted with
fun-filled events. The cost is right, too. Ski resorts may
represent the only vacation destinations that lower prices when the
weather becomes more agreeable. So late season is low season with
price breaks on lodging and lift tickets. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In San Francisco, no person is an
island, not even a member of that smallest of local identity
groups, persons of Republicanism. My conspiracy to undo George Bush
by registering Republican not only failed miserably on Tuesday, but
I was outed as a fake Republican in the worst of all possible
places _ a gun store. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Thank heavens they come but once
a year and I have to drive across the Golden Gate Bridge to get
them. Otherwise, I'd weigh 300 pounds and need semi-annual bypass
surgery. I'm talking about FRITTELLE. Six years ago, on a winter
trip to Venice, Italy, I encountered a pastry that affected me as
no other had. Not big on desserts, I meet a cake, pie, tart or
creme brulee that tempts me past a couple of bites. But frittelle
is different. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   TUBERCULOSIS (San Francisco) _ Tuberculosis is an important
public-health issue in San Francisco because the city _ a perennial
magnet for immigrants and one of the world's most densely populated
places _ always has been tuberculosis country. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   DISCRIMINATION (Santa Maria, Calif.) _ With all the political
correctness crammed down our throats since the Great Society years,
probably no word has been so misused as ``discrimination.'' While
the practice of discrimination can, in some cases, be undesirable,
we cannot throw an all-inclusive blanket over the entire concept
and declare it an evil thing. By DONALD G. SMITH.
</P>
