<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves lose Smoltz for season
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Atlanta Braves pitcher John Smoltz's fragile
right elbow has given in. The right-handed Cy Young Award-winner
will undergo ligament transplant surgery on the elbow March 23 and
will be lost for the season, the Braves announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Though he could not pinpoint when the ligament was torn, Smoltz
experienced uncustomary pain for five hours after his first spring
outing last Sunday. Though the discomfort subsided the next day, a
precautionary MRI taken Tuesday revealed the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually more positive than I thought because after not
knowing what's going on, I know what I can do now in the next
three, four years with this one process,'' said Smoltz, who is 32
and has twice undergone arthroscopies on the same elbow for bone
spur and bone chip removal.
</P>
<P>
   The operation will be performed by a Birmingham specialist, Dr.
James Andrews, who did the same operation with reliever Kerry
Ligtenberg last year. The usual recovery period is 12 to 18 months.
Management was uncertain on Smoltz's replacement, though
left-hander Terry Mulholland and Bruce Chen, in competition for the
fifth starter's spot, now have two openings to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll do is examine who we have here,'' general manager
John Schuerholz said. ``See how comfortable we feel with how we
make things work in John's absence and then decide whether or not
we look outside the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
