<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last chance for pruning; get head start on mower
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Trees and shrubs that shed their leaves last fall
are on the verge of greening up again, so if you have any pruning
to do, you'd better do it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good time to get a head start on the grass cutting
season by getting your lawn mower ready.
</P>
<P>
   PRUNING PROTOCOL
</P>
<P>
   Pete Kossoudji, president of North Dayton Garden Center, said he
prefers to prune most trees and shrubs in November and December,
early in their yearly dormant period. But he said now is still a
good time to get rid of dead wood and troublesome branches.
</P>
<P>
   You should prune, though, before your woody plants start
sprouting new leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Kossoudji said the first step in pruning is preparing your
tools. Hand pruners are best for twigs up to about a quarter-inch.
Heavier lopping shears will handle medium branches, and a saw might
be needed for limbs an inch thick or more.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the pruning tools are sharp and in good working order.
Pruning cuts should be as smooth and even as possible; jagged cuts
can promote disease.
</P>
<P>
   Kossoudji said pruning tools also should be cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dip them in chlorine bleach to be sure there's no fungus or
anything on the blades,'' he said. ``You don't want to transfer an
infection from one tree to another.''
</P>
<P>
   If you aren't experienced with the characteristics of each of
the plant species on your property, you might want to visit an
arborist, a nursery or your county extension agent for tips on
care. If you don't know the name of the plant, a photograph and
clipping may help the expert pinpoint what you need.
</P>
<P>
   Start pruning by removing branches that are dead, dying,
diseased or defective.
</P>
<P>
   A common defect that should be corrected at this time of year is
the ``crossing'' or ``rubbing'' branch. A crossing branch is one
that is growing in such a way that its bark touches another branch
or the tree trunk. Failure to remove such branches can lead to
problems later.
</P>
<P>
   Prune branches by making a cut at the base of the branch, but
leave the branch collar intact. The collar is the rounded extension
at the point where the branch meets the trunk or its parent branch.
</P>
<P>
   Larger trees and trees approaching utility lines are often best
left to professionals. But if you think you can tackle a heavy
branch on a mature tree, use the three-cut method.
</P>
<P>
   Saw a notch on the underside of the branch a few inches out from
the collar. Then move the saw to the top of the branch a few inches
farther out and saw until the branch breaks. Finally, saw off the
stump of the branch at the collar.
</P>
<P>
   This method keeps the falling branch from tearing away bark on
the parent branch as it breaks free.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to seal the wound left when you cut a branch at
this time of year. In fact, sealing the wound can create an
incubator for infection and do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   Trim young shrubs to create a thicker, bushier appearance. In
most cases, you'll be removing one-fourth to one-third of the
branches at their bases. Remove the oldest, longest branches
</P>
<P>
   Another method effective with some plants is to remove the ends
of branches to encourage stems already sprouting along the sides to
grow. Again, check with an expert to make sure this technique is
right for your plant.
</P>
<P>
   Young trees that will be large at maturity must be trained while
they are young; their growth must be controlled and directed so
they have a sturdy, tapered trunk and well-spaced branches no more
than half the diameter of the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Prune by selectively removing branches at their bases. Never try
to round or otherwise shape a tree by cutting off the ends of
branches. The shaping effect will be short-lived, and you'll ruin
the health of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to consider while pruning is what you'll do with
all the twigs and branches you're removing.
</P>
<P>
   If you have access to a shredder, the solution is simple. Grind
up the sticks and save the resulting chips to use as mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a group of neighbors might agree to do their pruning and
lawn clean-up at around the same time so that you could split the
cost of renting a shredder for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Most trash-collection services have rules about yard waste. They
may not accept twigs and branches stuffed into bags and cans with
the rest of your trash.
</P>
<P>
   Check with the agency that collects your trash. You might have
to bundle your yard waste and pay an extra fee for its collection.
</P>
<P>
   LAWN MOWER MAINTENANCE
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't give your lawn mower a good cleaning before
putting it away for the season last fall, do it now. Start by
cleaning the mower's outside and handles with the same kind of mild
detergent you use to wash a car.
</P>
<P>
   Before cleaning inside the blade housing, remove the spark plug
to prevent accidental starting. Also, check your owner's manual for
restrictions on tipping the mower. Some engines can be damaged by
tipping.
</P>
<P>
   Use a paint scraper to clear any clipping residue stuck inside
the mower housing. Then scrape the inside of the housing with a
wire brush.
</P>
<P>
   While cleaning, examine and tighten all the screws and bolts and
make sure all the switches, levers, pulleys and other control
devices are moving properly.
</P>
<P>
   Before you use your lawn mower, sharpen the blade, change the
oil, replace the spark plug, clean or replace the air filter and do
other maintenance tasks the owner's manual suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Shops that sell and repair lawn equipment usually charge a few
dollars to sharpen and balance a blade. You can use a rotary
grinding tool to sharpen a blade yourself, but it's sometimes hard
to keep the weight of the blade balanced after grinding.
</P>
<P>
   Your owner's manual will tell you what kind of replacement oil
you need to put in the mower. Lawn mowers take special spark plugs
that are sold wherever lawn equipment is sold or repaired, and the
plugs are standardized for most models.
</P>
<P>
   When the mower is tuned up and ready for use, add a bit of
gasoline and start it up.
</P>
<P>
   If it starts quickly and runs strongly, you know you'll be ready
to go when it time to mow the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   If the mower acts up, you'll be able to get it into a repair
shop before the spring rush.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take a couple hours or days to get a lawn mower
repaired now, but in April or May it can take weeks to get a mower
serviced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
