<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-ETHNIC09-COX     03-08 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ETHNIC09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ethnic ingredients allow you to go global with your cooking
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Exotic ingredients for ethnic cooking have gone
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the bottle of fish sauce now found on most supermarket
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Fish sauce, as the name implies, is made from fermented fish. It
is a smelly sauce. Trying it has been likened to encountering
Camembert for the first time. But it is as essential to Vietnamese
and Thai cookery as soy sauce is to Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, adventuresome cooks had to seek out an Asian
grocery store to find fish sauce. But today's cooks have developed
an appetite for exotic cuisines and want to prepare authentic
versions at home.
</P>
<P>
   Make that today's busy cooks, who have no patience for driving
to ethnic stores looking for ingredients to cook Pad Thai.
</P>
<P>
   They want to buy the essential rice noodles and fish sauce at
the same place they buy their Tide and Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Grocers have responded by providing an ever-widening array of
specialty ingredients, often clustering them in a single aisle.
</P>
<P>
   To check what's available, I visited six area markets: Cub,
Chmiel's, Dorothy Lane Market, Kroger, Lofino's and Meijer. Some
stores offer only token staples. Others have expanded the selection
to include fresh produce.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ingredients such as cilantro and tomatillos, bok
choy and wonton wrappers, balsamic vinegar and radicchio are so
common shoppers take them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi rice, roasted seaweed and yes, fish sauce, also were
widely available. Some items were unique to one store. I found jars
of Indian garam masala among a Spice Hunter line at Cub Foods. Even
precooked, ready-to-eat Japanese edamame _ the soybean snack _ were
in the produce aisle at one Kroger store.
</P>
<P>
   There are notable differences between supermarket ingredients
and those found in ethnic groceries. Supermarkets favor
Americanized brands with high-style labels and user-friendly names
such as House of Thai or Thai Kitchen. And they target
English-speaking customers, unlike imported brands that may have no
instructions and often do not include a word of English. And the
supermarket brands are generally packaged in smaller quantities
suitable for cooks who don't use these ingredients every day.
</P>
<P>
   But going to the supermarket with a shopping list of ethnic
ingredients can be a crap shoot. To maximize your chances of
finding what you want, try a Meijer store; Second choice is Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   But not all stores in any chain offer the same ingredients.
Newer Kroger stores offer considerably more ethnic staples. But if
one store in a chain has an ingredient, the store where you shop
should be able to order it. Just ask.
</P>
<P>
   The Meijer in Kettering wins extra points for offering a
``Shopper's Guide to Fresh Produce,'' which provides descriptions
and suggestions for buying, storing and using everything from
plantains to blood oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Because these items are not everyday staples, pricing varies
widely. A bunch of cilantro may be priced as low as 69 cents and as
high as $1.99. Blood oranges may be as low as eight for $2 or as
high as two for $1. Fresh ginger may be as little as $1.69 a pound
or as high as $2.99. Baby bananas and red bananas range from 69
cents a pound to $1.49. If prices matter, remember that they are
invariably lower at ethnic groceries where the items are not sold
as specialty ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   TOP ETHNIC FOODS
</P>
<P>
   _ Blood oranges: This unfortunately named citrus fruit hails
from Italy and Spain, but is now grown in California. The rind is
splotched with burgundy color, and inside the edible fruit is the
color of red raspberries. In Sicily, a pitcher of the juice of the
blood orange is a breakfast staple. I found them found them at
Kroger, Lofino's and Meijer. To sample the sweet fruit, which is
less acidic than more familiar oranges, add sections to a spinach
salad with a raspberry dressing and toasted pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pancetta: When a recipe calls for this Italian cured,
generally unsmoked bacon, it usually requires a trip to a specialty
store. Ditto prosciutto. But I stumbled over slices of packaged
pancetta among the cheeses at a Chmiel's store in Washington Twp.
Pancetta is used in cooking and in the foundation of sauces and
soup. Bits can be browned and sprinkled over vegetables or used in
a variation of spinach salad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mangos: These call up sunny Caribbean images, and they are at
virtually all supermarkets. Meijer carries two kinds, the
traditional and another labeled ataulfo, which tasters found ``more
tropical'' and ``exotic.'' The fruit tenaciously clings to the
seed, and the best approach is to put a knife off center and slice
down the fat side, keeping the knife to the side of the pit. Take
each slice and score the fruit with a knife, cutting down to the
skin. Use your thumbs to invert the slice, pushing the flesh up.
Cut off the cubes. An easy way to enjoy mango is in a salsa with
some hot peppers and maybe cilantro. It's a wonderful accompaniment
to pork and chicken.
</P>
<P>
   _ Curry paste: Call this an Asian convenience food. You can make
your own curry paste. You could even make your own curry powder,
but few here do that, and there's good reason that cans of curry
paste are sold in ethnic markets, too. Those markets carry a wider
variety, but supermarkets usually stock red or green and
occasionally other blends. You usually only need a small amount in
any recipe, but once the jar or can is opened, the curry will keep
in the refrigerator for two months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chipotle chiles: These smoked jalapenos are the hot ingredient
of the new century. It's hard to open a magazine, whether it be
Better Homes &AMP; Gardens or Gourmet without finding a recipe calling
for chipotles. Though dried chipotle chiles are available, the
preferred ingredient is canned chipotles packed in adobo sauce.
Often some of the sauce is added, along with the chiles. Pay
attention to the labels. It's easy to pick up the pureed and more
mild canned chipotle sauce instead of the chipotles in adobo sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poblano chiles: Twenty five years ago, when Mexican cooking
guru Diana Kennedy wrote her first cookbook, she couldn't find
these peppers even in New York City. Now the black/green poblano
chiles and an array of others such as the fiery habanera and
serrano chiles are virtually everywhere. Poblano chiles are the
right ones for making chiles rellenos. First they need to be
roasted and peeled; then they're stuffed with cheese or ground meat
filling, lightly battered and fried. Strips of poblanos are used in
vegetable dishes and soups as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
