<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0384 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-RUSHHOUR-REMEDIES09-C     03-08 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSHHOUR-REMEDIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can cook without being a slave to the kitchen
 &HT;    By Carol Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's challenging to do it all: have a career,
pursue interests of your own, raise a family, take the kids to
activities _ and put home-cooked meals on the table day after day.
Frozen dinners, pizza delivery and expensive take-out have been
convenient substitutes but not the only answers to your dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   You could actually cook. You don't have to be Martha Stewart
with a professional kitchen and a staff of 20 to prepare
great-tasting dinners at home. Nor do you have to spend all night
making them.
</P>
<P>
   Following are three tasty meals that can be prepared easily in
15 to 20 minutes. Some of the recipes call for microwaving and
others employ a combination of little-used large kitchen appliances
like the broiler and the range top. Soon you can be on your way to
enjoying some real home-cooked food ``chez vous.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK AND HEARTY CHICKEN VEGETABLE SOUP WITH CHEESE CROSTINIS
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken breasts (boneless, skinless washed with all visible
fat removed)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups canned chicken broth or 4 cups bouillon made from
bouillon cubes according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled and grated
</P>
<P>
   1 medium zucchini, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 medium yellow squash, grated
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 baguette, sliced diagonally (2 to 3 slices per person)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Cheddar or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Cut the breasts into 1/2-inch strips then into 1/2-inch cubes.
In a medium saucepan, place the cubed chicken and the chicken broth
or bouillon and cook over medium heat for about 8 to 10 minutes.
Add the grated carrots, zucchini and yellow squash and cook 2 to 3
minutes (cook longer if you do not want the vegetables al dente).
Adjust the seasonings. While the vegetables cook, place the sliced
bread in the toaster or on a baking sheet under the broiler and
toast light to medium. If desired, drizzle or brush a little olive
oil on each slice of toast. Sprinkle the toasts with the cheese and
broil until melted. The crostinis can be dipped into the soup or
eaten as is. The soup holds well, and the leftovers make a great
lunch. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-SAVING TIPS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Double the recipe and freeze half for another meal or freeze
as individual portions for lunch or if dining alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ When buying cheese, shred or grate it all at once so its ready
to top main dishes, soups, toasts or put in omelets for a quick
meal. If you buy pre-shredded cheese, be aware that some brands
have salt added. And nearly all bags of pre-shredded cheese have
been tossed with powdered cellulose to prevent clumping. This is
not a problem for tacos, soups and salads, but cooks have
experienced problems when trying to use pre-shredded cheese in
recipes such as cheese straws.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grate all veggies together using a food processor.
</P>
<P>
   _ For an economy meal, reduce the chicken in the recipe to 1 or
2 breasts and add some cooked pasta.
</P>
<P>
   MUSTARD PINEAPPLE HAM STEAK WITH SWEET POTATOES AND GREEN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   2 large sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon favorite mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2-pound ham steak per person
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mixed salad greens, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Favorite salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream and butter, optional
</P>
<P>
   Place the broiler rack about 6 inches from the broiler. Turn on
the broiler to high. Scrub the potatoes and cut a 2-inch slit in
each. Place them in the microwave and set the timer for about 14
minutes (time may vary according to wattage). Microwave them until
the centers are soft when pierced with a folk.
</P>
<P>
   While they are cooking, place the ham steaks on a pan. Drain the
pineapple and reserve the juice. Combine the mustard, sugar and
cloves with the drained crushed pineapple. Spread it evenly on the
ham steaks. Place the steaks under the broiler until browned, about
8 to 10 minutes. Place the reserved juice in a small saucepan and
heat it until it reduces a little.
</P>
<P>
   Cut cooked sweet potatoes in half length-wise and mash them in
their shells adding sour cream and/or butter if you wish. Place a
half on each plate along with the ham steak and a cup of salad that
has been tossed with dressing. Spoon the reduced pineapple juice
over the ham and serve. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-SAVING TIPS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy the ham steaks pre-packaged or have the deli counter or
the butcher cut them to order.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a big batch of your favorite salad dressing and keep it
in a jar in the fridge for quick access.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash all salad greens when you buy them and keep them in
plastic bags for use during the week. The same goes for tomatoes,
carrots, cucumbers and other favorite salad additions.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a meal requires boiling water or using the oven, turn it on
as soon as you enter the house, before you take off your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED BELL PEPPERS WITH NEW POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   2 medium green, red or yellow bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   12 size C red new potatoes, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground lean beef, turkey or chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and coarse black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cooked rice or fresh breadcrumbs or 1/4 cup dry
breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mixed fresh minced herbs or 2 teaspoons mixed dry
herbs (examples: parsley, sage, oregano)
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter (optional)
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can tomato sauce or favorite spaghetti sauce
</P>
<P>
   Wash and dry peppers. Cut them in half from stem to bottom.
Remove stem, seeds and white ribs. Set aside. Scrub the potatoes
and cut them in quarters. Mix the rest of the ingredients except
the butter and the sauce. Fill each of the pepper halves with 1/4
of the meat mixture. Place the filled peppers and potatoes in a
microwave-safe baking dish just large enough to hold them. Sprinkle
the potatoes with salt and pepper. Pour the tomato sauce over the
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the dish with its own lid or microwave-safe plastic wrap
and prick about 3 holes in the plastic. Microwave on high for about
20 minutes. Time may vary depending on oven wattage. Carefully
remove cover or plastic wrap. Place a pepper on each plate. Spoon
some sauce over each pepper and coarsely mash the potatoes in the
remaining sauce, adding the optional butter at this time. Divide
the potatoes among the plates and serve immediately. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-SAVING TIPS:
</P>
<P>
   _ For a penny-saver dish, use only half the meat in the recipe
and substitute 1 cup of rice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep bags of chopped onions and bags of mixed fresh herbs
minced in bags in the freezer for quick access.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy garlic already minced in jars and keep in the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double the recipe and freeze half for another meal. (Cook each
recipe separately in the microwave oven before freezing.)
</P>
<P>
   For variety and another quick meal try the meat mixture as a
meat loaf or as meatballs. (Use bread crumbs for meatballs if
serving with pasta.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
