<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-OBESITY09-COX     03-08 1711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBESITY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH:
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Suppose obesity were an infectious disease, Lloyd
Laubach says. Imagine how many billions of dollars the government
would be spending to wipe out a health hazard that costs more than
$100 billion a year in medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people doing a lot of research in this field who
don't think we'll be able to turn this thing around,'' says
Laubach, who chairs the health and sport science department at the
University of Dayton. ``It's truly, truly scary. The numbers just
keep growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Half of American adults are overweight, as defined by a body
mass index of 25 or more, says Shape Up America!, an organization
dedicated to bringing down that figure. The 18 percent classified
in 1998 as obese, their BMIs at least 30, represented a 50 percent
increase in just seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``About one child in five weighs too much,'' Dr. Dennis Bier of
the Baylor College of Medicine told a national conference on
childhood obesity at Georgetown University last month. And
three-quarters of obese teen-agers will remain obese through
adulthood, says Mary Ellen Huelsman, the registered dietitian who
runs The Children's Medical Center's Body Shop class for weight
control and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity makes people more vulnerable to heart disease, cancer,
arthritis, asthma, sleep apnea and adult-onset diabetes. High blood
pressure is showing up in children as young as 2, the American
Heart Association reported last week. ``In terms of cancer
prevention, a healthy diet and exercise are as important as not
smoking,'' says Dr. Dennis Savaiano, chairman of the Food and
Nutrition Science Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's something we need to address early on,'' Huelsman
says. ``I'm talking about the kindergarten level. Healthy eating
habits need to be formed then.''
</P>
<P>
   First grade isn't too late, though, and neither is high school.
Schools could teach kids ways to enjoy physical activity for a
lifetime, Laubach and Huelsman agree. They just don't make it a
priority. Nor do parents help kids learn how the quick meals of
today's family lifestyles can also be healthy, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer is to move more and eat less, or at least eat
fewer calories. But that of course is no more helpful than saying
anyone can get rich in the stock market if they only would buy low
and sell high.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pratt always has known exercise and good nutrition were
good for her. The UD sophomore has decided several times to start
getting in shape. ``I'd be good at it for two or three weeks, and
then I'd quit,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now 19, she credits a UD conditioning class for helping break
that pattern. She learned getting in shape doesn't have to feel
like a punishment. It's OK to work out in 20-minute spurts instead
of an hour at a time. It's OK to lift weights three days a week,
run three days a week, then eat and do whatever she feels like on
the seventh day.
</P>
<P>
   To her amazement, she learned working out can be something she
looks forward to _ a better study break even than a snack and TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize that not only is it good for your body, but
it's good for your overall mental, physical and emotional health,''
Pratt says. ``It makes you feel better. It raises your
self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   She has more energy. Even studying isn't the drag it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   She feels better about her appearance. She's no longer hesitant
to join friends in a basketball game or something else that's
physical.
</P>
<P>
   She's more alert. She doesn't need as much sleep, and she wakes
up more refreshed from the sleep she gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised at how much easier it is to motivate myself to
go out there and work out,'' she says. Even if the day isn't going
so well, ``I have exercise to fall back on. It's something I know
is going to make me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose Pratt and millions of other teen-agers would learn that
at younger ages, Laubach suggests. His biggest beef is that nearly
every state has scratched physical education from its daily school
curriculum. ``A major problem,'' he calls it. Besides that, some
high schools and junior highs have done away with intramural sports
to free up field and gymnasium time for the varsity teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do that stuff and they forget to educate the masses,''
Laubach says. He says George DeMarco of his department is working
on a program to offer local schools called ACES, for ``All Children
Exercising Simultaneously.'' The idea is for several schools to
commit to two times a day when all their students will exercise for
10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise is no more optional than clean air, pure water and
nutritious food, says biologist Frank Booth of the University of
Missouri. Attributing 250,000 deaths a year to inactivity, Booth
has organized Scientists Against Inactivity-Related Diseases as an
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Even when schools have phys-ed classes, Huelsman says, ``They
don't really teach kids physical fitness that they can use for a
lifetime.'' They teach soccer, basketball and softball, phys-ed
advocates complained at the Georgetown obesity conference, with
some occasional lap running for punishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools should be teaching swimming, tennis, aerobics, weight
lifting, walking even,'' Huelsman says. UD offers that kind of
class. Self-defense and dancing classes don't even require special
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to call it movement rather than exercise,'' Huelsman
says. ``So many people think you need to do an hour workout for it
to be beneficial. Take a walk around the neighborhood with your
family, 10 or 15 minutes. Walk the dog. Mow the lawn. Rake the
leaves. Use the stairs instead of the elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   Have fun, says Laubach. ``I can say you need to run three or
four miles a day, but if you say, 'I hate to run,' I better be able
to give you an alternative to running.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the American Dietetic Association is giving exercise equal
billing in its National Nutrition Month campaign this month. ``Food
and fitness: health for a lifetime'' is the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Not that nutrition isn't a sizable problem itself. In a World
Health Organization survey last month of 28 countries, American
15-year-olds ranked in the top three for consuming sweets,
chocolate and soft drinks every day, and fifth in fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fast food is a big problem,'' Laubach says. ``They're easy,
quick and relatively inexpensive meals, but they're loaded with
fat.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that much harder to stock up at home with quick meals
and snacks, Huelsman says. Many low-calorie frozen entrees heat up
in a hurry. Ham and turkey sandwiches are healthier than hot dogs,
bologna or drive-through burgers. Fresh fruits and vegetables are
not only nutritious, ``but they also help to fill kids up,''
leaving less room for potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritionists stress variety in the recommended daily allotments
of three to five servings of vegetables and two to four of fruits.
But be realistic, many say. Broken rules are better than abandoned
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no 'good' foods or 'bad' foods,'' says Bier, the
Baylor physician. ``But there are good diets and bad diets.''
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY TIPS
</P>
<P>
   The Body Shop is The Children's Medical Center's weight-control
program for children 8 to 13 who are anywhere from mildly to
severely overweight. The 10 weekly sessions teach children and
parents healthy eating habits and exercises for one hour, then
separate the children and parents for the next hour to talk to
psychologists about weight-related issues and decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Parents should not put their children on diets, says Huelsman.
Consistent habits are better, such as these tips Children's offers
for healthy weight loss:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the reduced-fat versions of dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serve turkey, fish and chicken more than red meat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bake instead of fry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eat at least five servings of fruits and vegetables a day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bread, cereals, rice and pasta aren't fattening unless you add
fat to them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy lower-fat ground round or sirloin instead of ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some low-calorie snacks are light popcorn, pretzels, vanilla
wafers, animal crackers, low-fat wheat crackers, yogurt and frozen
yogurt, fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drink water or sugar-free drinks instead of high-calorie
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have three meals and two snacks a day for the family. Children
will have more energy and be less likely to be hungry enough to pig
out on the wrong things.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES
</P>
<P>
   _ Web sites: See www.eatright.org for the American Dietetic
Association, which also has a consumer nutrition hot line at (800)
366-1655, and gives referrals to local registered dietitians
between 10 a.m. and 5 p.m. weekdays; www.efit.com for an online
health and fitness network with sections on kids' health and teens'
health; www.shapeup.org for Shape Up America! and
www.navigator.tufts.edu/ for the Tufts University Nutrition
Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   FIGURING YOUR BODY MASS INDEX (BMI)
</P>
<P>
   Anyone past his 18th birthday is considered overweight if his
body mass index is between 25 and 29.9 and obese if it's 30 or
higher. BMI is based on height and weight but not sex.
</P>
<P>
   To figure BMI, first multiply your height in meters by itself.
Then divide that number into your weight in kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   To determine your height in meters, divide your height in inches
by 39.37. So if you're 5 feet 9 inches, that is 69 inches or 1.75
meters. Multiply 1.75 by itself and you have 3.0625.
</P>
<P>
   To determine your weight in kilograms, divide your weight in
pounds by 2.2. If you're 200 pounds, that's 90.91 kilograms. Divide
that by 3.0625 and you get a BMI of 29.7, roughly a double
cheeseburger away from obesity. (There are a number of BMI charts
on the Internet that do the figuring for you, including
www.efit.com.)
</P>
<P>
   A one-unit increase in BMI raises the medical charges of someone
older than 40 by 1.9 percent, according to a report in the Dec. 15
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association. That's
about 6 3/4 pounds if you're 5-feet-9.
</P>
<P>
   The same study calculated that each additional day of physical
activity per week reduces medical charges by 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
