   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Experts suggest starting your countdown to
retirement as much as 10 years before you expect to retire. Here is
a checklist _ by no means all-inclusive _ of things to do.(Ezell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ While much collective anxiety about traveling is
spent on plane crashes, food or motion sickness, overbooked hotels,
inclement weather, some concern is designated to the inevitable
question of what to pack. Equally important, however, and often
neglected, is what to pack things in. Everything you need to know
about purchasing luggage. (Gonzalez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
45. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
hard-to-fnd items. This week: (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-DESTINATION _ A weekly feature about fun places to shop
in the Southeast. This week: (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (EDS: Moving on l (Lifestyle) and a
(General News) categories.)
</P>
<P>
   NUTSNBOLTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Trees and shrubs that shed their
leaves last fall are on the verge of greening up again, so if you
have any pruning to do, you'd better do it quickly. It's also a
good time to get a head start on the grass cutting season by
getting your lawn mower ready. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   OBESITY _ Suppose obesity were an infectious disease, Lloyd
Laubach says. Imagine how many billions of dollars the government
would be spending to wipe out a health hazard that costs more than
$100 billion a year in medical expenses. Three-quarters of obese
teen-agers will remain obese through adulthood, says Mary Ellen
Huelsman, the registered dietitian who runs The Children's Medical
Center's Body Shop class for weight control and nutrition. Schools
could teach kids ways to enjoy physical activity for a lifetime,
Laubach and Huelsman agree. They just don't make it a priority. Nor
do parents help kids learn how the quick meals of today's family
lifestyles can also be healthy, they say. (Lamb, Dayton Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   RAYMOND-BRACIOLE _ Since last week's episode of Everybody loves
Raymond in which an Italian dish called braciole was featured
prominently, the food section has received numerous inquiries about
what it is. We tell them -- and share a recipe. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ Cyber Spice listing of websites for info on
braciole, to go with Betty Parham's story on braciole. (Parham,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _Marcia Langhenry's recipe swap column is not
available this week.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-ETHNIC _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Exotic ingredients for ethnic
cooking have gone mainstream. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN _ With winemaker Jean-Marie Guffens, everything is
I, I, I. Irascible, irreverent and iconoclastic. Guffens, a Belgian
who moved to France to make a broad line of high-quality,
competitively priced white Burgundy under the Verget label he
founded, dropped in for a quick luncheon last week during a
five-city, five-day whirlwind stateside tour. (Fisher, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RUSHHOUR-REMEDIES _ It is challenging to do it all: have a
career; interests of your own, raise a family; take the kids to
activities, and put home-cooked meals on the table day after day.
Frozen dinners, pizza delivery and expensive take-out have been
convenient substitutes but not the only answers to your dilemma.
Following are three tasty meals that can be prepared easily in 15
to 20 minutes. (Johnson, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CALORIE-QUIZ _ Do you know which foods have the most calories?
(Norris, Palm Beach Post)
