<P>
   BRIDGET-JONES _ ATLANTA _ She's back, and the good news (or bad,
depending on your perspective) is that she hasn't changed one whit.
Bridget Jones _ the ``Rainman''-esque counter of calories consumed,
cigarettes smoked and anonymous hangup calls to ex-boyfriends made
in 1998's bestselling novel ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' has turned up
just as flustered again in a sequel. When British author Helen
Fielding unleashed Bridget on America two years ago, the
comparisons to TV's Ally McBeal were too choice for many reviewers
and readers to resist _ pro and con. Indeed, for every female
reader who thinks of Bridget, ``She's just like me,'' there are
others who think she's set womankind back about 50 years.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
