<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-BABY-$ADV11-C     03-08 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BABY-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PREGNANCY HAS CHERIE BLAIR'S IMAGE AS 'SUPERWOMAN,' 'WORKING
MOTHER' POSITIVELY GLOWING
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Before her death, it was Princess Diana who beguiled
the nation, indeed the world.
</P>
<P>
   But now another British woman is moving precariously close to
filling the much-beloved princess' shoes: Cherie Blair, wife of
Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   The Blairs' domestic life has long appealed to the public. The
world was captivated, for example, by photographs of a scruffy
Cherie Blair bringing in the milk in her wrinkled nightshirt the
morning after her husband's election. But interest in the pair
soared to new heights last November when it was announced that
Cherie Blair, aged 45, was pregnant with
</P>
<P>
   her fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Blair baby has become the most talked about
pregnancy since those of Princess Di.
</P>
<P>
   It also has many celebrities here enthusiastically reciting the
virtues of late motherhood in the British press. Iman, the
44-year-old model wife of singer David Bowie, himself age 53,
recently gushed that she is to be a mother again.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Princess Di, though, Cherie Blair finds herself cast not
as an archetype of a charitable, yet jet-setting, young beauty, but
that of an older mother struggling to juggle career and family
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Already well-known around the world as a working mother, many
women are able to identify with Cherie Blair as she embarks on
another round of breastfeeding and sleepless nights, while still
working towards her long-time goal of becoming a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pregnancy is going to bring a new challenge,'' Maggie Rea,
an attorney and family friend, told The Daily Telegraph. ``But I am
sure she will handle it fantastically well. She is very fit and
well, and has already proved she can cope with motherhood, a
career, and supporting her husband too.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair seems to have fared better than her friend, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who has often expressed regret in public over
having had only one child.
</P>
<P>
   The Blairs already have three children: Euan, 15, Nicholas, 14,
and Kathryn, 11.
</P>
<P>
   But the expected birth in May of the first child in 150 years
fathered by a sitting British prime minister is sure to drastically
change the public and private lives of Britain's first couple.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the New Labour Party machine is not unaware of the
kick it will give Tony Blair's ``family man'' image with a general
election still more than a year away.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair, whose own actor father, Tony Booth, abandoned the
family for another woman when she was 21 months old, is likely to
become even more protective of her own family. Already Cherie
Blair, who does not give press interviews, goes to great lengths to
shield them from the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Blairs seem to have adopted an almost royal-like
attitude to being left alone.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week Tony Blair vowed to do ``whatever it takes'' to
protect the privacy of his family and prevent intrusion into the
lives of his children.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge came just after the family's lawyers sought _ and
were granted _ an injunction preventing The Mail on Sunday(CQ)
newspaper from publishing material based on a book about the family
by Ros Mark, 30, who worked as the Blairs' nanny from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherie and I are absolutely determined, no matter how unusual
our own lives may be because of the nature of my job, that our
children have as normal an upbringing as possible,'' Tony Blair
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, interest in the Blairs and their soon-to-be-expanded
brood is not likely to wane any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair has come to epitomize the successful woman of the
21st Century with her seemingly tranquil home life, glamorous
social life, and esteemed career as a barrister focusing on
employment law.
</P>
<P>
   Only last June she was made a recorder _ a junior part-time
judge. Within three years she could be eligible for a full-time
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``She certainly seems to have it all, and she's become a
powerful role model for little girls across the country,'' said Sue
Holmes, a secretary and mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   Like Princess Di, Cherie Blair receives hundreds of letters a
week. At the same time, she promotes the Malcolm Sargent Cancer
Care for Children, one of the princess' favorite charities.
</P>
<P>
   And, like the princess, Cherie Blair's wardrobe is heavily
scrutinized. Over the past year many pundits here have referred to
her as ``an excellent ambassador for British fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, experience has taught her to look her best.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, attention was distracted from the purpose of her
husband's visit to South Africa when the press criticized her on
the front pages as looking ``dowdy'' in a green floral dress.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the princess, though, Cherie Blair seems to have trained
her husband well. Tony Blair calls himself a ``nappy-changing new
man'' who doesn't mind staying up at night with a new baby. A
government spokesman said he will take paternity leave when his
fourth child is born _ though it will likely be less than the
maximum three months unpaid leave now allowed under government
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known how long Cherie Blair will take off, although _
in typical superwoman fashion _ she was back at work within two
days after the birth of her youngest, Kathryn.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LATAM-MACKAY-$ADV12-C     03-08 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-MACKAY-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON POINT MAN ON THE AMERICAS KEEPS FOCUS ON ISSUES CLOSE TO
HOME
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 12 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The view from Buddy MacKay's office is of the White
House. Behind his desk is a map stretching from the southern United
States to the tip of South America.
</P>
<P>
   This is Kenneth H. ``Buddy'' MacKay's world. For the past year,
the former Florida governor has been President Clinton's special
envoy to the Americas _ a territory covering the entire Western
Hemisphere, including Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The job has taken MacKay, 66, to an average of two countries a
month _ listening to their leaders and communicating their problems
on at least a weekly basis to the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, communications break down.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time MacKay participated in a news conference in Chile
speaking through an interpreter. The first question was
particularly tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa! That one was high and inside,'' MacKay quipped, hoping
to get a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone stopped and got very quiet,'' MacKay recalled. ``The
Chilean interpreter didn't have any idea what I was saying. I said,
'That's baseball.' He didn't have any idea what baseball was.''
</P>
<P>
   With the news conference rapidly disintegrating, MacKay tried
explaining the sport. Someone suggested he use a soccer analogy.
MacKay didn't know one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a good lesson that day,'' he said. ``Our culture
really is different. Some things we take for granted, they don't
have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Although MacKay is trying to learn Spanish, he described his
linguistic ability as ``rough and slow.'' Even so, he said the
people he deals with appreciate his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to judge my success in this office by how well
I speak Spanish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most surprising aspects of the past year, MacKay
said, is the lack of interest and information about the importance
of Latin America among U.S. business and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to try to get this country, and our government, to
face north and south for our future instead of east and west.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, much of his time has been spent lobbying Congress to
approve a $1 billion military aid package to Colombia and to pass a
trade bill expanding the Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI).
</P>
<P>
   It's a return of sorts. MacKay spent six years in the House of
Representatives where, among other posts, he served on the Foreign
Affairs subcommittee on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombia aid is necessary, MacKay said to counter the
alliance of guerrilla groups with the powerful drug cartels and
organized crime that threatens to plunge one of South America's
oldest democracies into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay said Miami has already experienced an influx of business
and government leaders from Colombia, fleeing the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Colombia destabilizes, we will get not only the leadership,
but a large number of immigrants, and that is tough on our
economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging he's concerned about a recent Human Rights Watch
report linking the Colombian military to right-wing paramilitary
groups, MacKay said many of the cases in the report may be related
to prior Colombian regimes and may not reflect the current
political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
   His other legislative priority, the CBI expansion bill, is
important to the United States because the Caribbean countries have
become such a large trading partner, MacKay said. Since the
original CBI was passed in the 1980s, U.S. trade with the region
has increased six-fold, becoming the United States' sixth-largest
trading partner and exceeding our combined exports to Russia, China
and India.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay's biggest long-range effort is to lay the foundation for
a hemispheric Free Trade Area for the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Creation of the FTAA was first endorsed at the 1994 Summit of
the Americas in Miami which MacKay _ then Florida's lieutenant
governor _ played a major role in organizing. Under FTAA, tariff
rates across the entire hemisphere (except Cuba) would be lowered
and eventually eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay also is working hard to have a U.S. city _ Miami and New
Orleans are top contenders _ picked as the permanent secretariat
for the Americas, a role similar to that of Brussels for the
European Union. Other major candidates include Mexico City and
Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay foresees a future in which the United States, despite the
overwhelming size of its economy, plays a major, but not dominant,
role in a hemispheric community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building a community of the Americas much like the
European community. It's more than just trade agreements; it's far
more than that,'' he said. ``I see our role as more of a
partnership and less of being the bully on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the administration job meant leaving Florida for awhile.
MacKay and his wife, Anne, live on the same floor of a building in
downtown Washington as another Floridian, Attorney General Janet
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, MacKay _ who was the Florida Clinton-Gore
chairman in 1992 and 1996 _ said he hasn't seriously looked past
the November election. If Vice President Gore is elected and asks
him to serve in the next administration, MacKay said he's
available.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
