<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0443 &Cx1f; tab-z
w d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-$ADV22     03-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-$ADV22-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV22 
 (FOR RELEASE WED., MARCH 22, 2000, AND THEREAFTER) 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: SEAFOOD STEW OVER LINGUINE, FENNEL SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For working people there are three ways to entertain guests for
dinner at home: Hire a caterer, stay home from work or prepare the
meal ahead of time over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Today's menu with a seafood stew and linguine is for the
cook-ahead crowd. It is the way I always entertain, taking several
nights after work to prepare the dishes and either freezing or
refrigerating them.
</P>
<P>
   I also set the table the night before. No matter what I serve, I
keep it simple. Then the evening of the dinner there is little left
to do.
</P>
<P>
   For this dinner it is a matter of cooking the pasta, reheating
the sauce and throwing in the fish for a few minutes. You can heat
up some nice crusty country bread while the pasta is cooking.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad the only work is to arrange the salad and cheese
on individual plates, drizzling on the dressing. The dessert calls
for spooning the wine sauce over the sorbet, which has already been
put into individual dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The seafood stew can be made two days in advance and
refrigerated or it can be made a couple of weeks in advance and
frozen.
</P>
<P>
   All of the components of the salad can be prepared the night
before, as can the dessert.
</P>
<P>
   SEAFOOD STEW OVER LINGUINE
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds finely chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds ripe plum tomatoes, coarsely cubed or 8 cups canned
drained tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups fish stock or clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 large bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh thyme leaves or 1 1/2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pound firm white fish fillet such as black sea bass or
cod, cut in large chunks
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound shrimp, shelled and left whole if small or cut in half
or thirds, depending on size
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh spinach linguine
</P>
<P>
   1. Saute the onion in hot oil in nonstick pan. When onion has
softened and started to brown, add the green pepper, celery and
garlic and continue cooking until pepper and celery begin to
soften. Add the tomatoes, wine, stock, bay leaf, tomato paste,
thyme and parsley and continue cooking for about 5 minutes.
Refrigerate or freeze.
</P>
<P>
   2. To serve, defrost if frozen; bring the water for the pasta to
a boil; reheat sauce until very hot. Cook the pasta according to
directions. Add the fish and shrimp to the tomato mixture for two
to three minutes. Serve seafood stew with the linguine.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   FENNEL AND PARMIGIANO REGGIANO
</P>
<P>
   6 small or 4 large bulbs fennel
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 very thin large slices of Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   1. Trim the bottoms and top stem leaves from the fennel. You can
reserve a few feathery leaves for garnish, if desired. Slice off
the bottom and discard the tough outer pieces. Slice the fennel
bulbs very, very thin. You can use a mandoline, the very thin
slicing disk of a food processor, the slicing side of a four-sided
grater or a very sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk together the oil and lemon juice and season with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wrap the fennel slices in plastic wrap; wrap the cheese
slices in plastic wrap. Cover the dressing and refrigerate these
three components overnight, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide the fennel among 6 salad plates in a single
layer. Break up the cheese slices and arrange over the fennel.
Drizzle dressing over each portion and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON ICE WITH WINE
</P>
<P>
   6 large scoops lemon sorbet
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup semisweet white wine like Riesling
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1. Spoon the sorbet into six individual serving dishes (glass
stemware would be nice.) Place in freezer.
</P>
<P>
   2. To serve, combine the wine and liqueur and pour over the
sorbet just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Onions
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil and extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   Tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   Dried thyme if fresh not available
</P>
<P>
   Lemon
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds green peppers
</P>
<P>
   Bunch celery
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe plum tomatoes or two 28-ounce cans no-salt-added
tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 bottles dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fish stock or clam juice
</P>
<P>
   Bunch fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Bunch Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh spinach linguine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds firm fillets of white fish such as black sea bass
or cod
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound shrimp
</P>
<P>
   6 small or 4 large bulbs fennel
</P>
<P>
   Medium wedge Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   2 pints lemon sorbet
</P>
<P>
   Bottle semisweet white wine, like Riesling
</P>
<P>
   Small bottle orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition Analysis per serving: 1,190 calories, 24 grams fat,
270 milligrams cholesterol, 900 milligrams sodium, 60 grams
protein, 150 grams carbohydrate
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Marian Burros by electronic mail. Her
address is: marbur(at)nytimes.com. The (at) represents the symbol
on your keyboard. Please include your name and daytime telephone
number. Questions of general interest will be answered in this
column. &QL;
</P>
