<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MANAGEMENT-LESSONS-HN     03-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGEMENT-LESSONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LESSONS FOR MANAGERS FROM `THE WEST WING' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There was a great scene in ``The West Wing''
television program a few weeks ago that a lot of bosses could have
learned from. The president was about to give the State of the
Union address, but the secretary of agriculture had to be left
behind at the White House so that someone from the presidential
line of succession would survive if the Capitol blew up.
</P>
<P>
   On the slight chance that something would go wrong, the
president told the secretary how to handle national security, and
that one of the toilets in the residence needs to be jiggled every
once in a while. They also had this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a best friend?'' the president asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' the secretary replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he smarter than you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you trust him with your life?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your chief of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with that picture? Not a thing _ except that too
many bosses will be oblivious to it.
</P>
<P>
   The scene offers several lessons: A few things can be handled
only by the boss. Just as the president has to have a strong hand
in national security, some life-and-death items in business can be
handled only by the chief executive. But often bosses get so caught
up in the day-to-day frenzy that they don't stop to think about how
they are performing a lot of mundane tasks that ought to be
delegated.
</P>
<P>
   The other danger is that they have become such perfectionists
that they can't let go of anything. If you delegate, certainly your
subordinates might not handle tasks as well as you would. But you
can teach them how to do better, and then have time to concentrate
on the important parts of your job. If you never delegate, nothing
will ever improve.
</P>
<P>
   You got a best friend? One of the first things a boss needs to
do is hire a reliable second in command, or at least make sure
you're happy with whoever already holds the job. At work, that
person will be your best friend, even if you never see each other
socially.
</P>
<P>
   Should he really be your best friend? Probably not. Too many
people will think he was appointed because of that rather than
because of talent. Besides, having a best friend away from your
office might at least give you some chance of balancing your work
with the rest of your life.
</P>
<P>
   But your second in command should at least be worthy of being
your friend. That doesn't mean you have to have a lot in common or
laugh at the same jokes, but he ought to be someone you like and
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Do other people seem to respect him? Do you? Would you be
embarrassed to have him represent you at an important meeting?
Would you trust him with your kids? If you don't like the answers
to any of those questions, you have the wrong person.
</P>
<P>
   Is he smarter than you? He ought to be, at least in some ways.
Even if you're a member of Mensa, you can find someone who's
smarter than you in many aspects of the job. Maybe he has better
people skills or is more organized or doesn't get as frazzled under
pressure as you do. Maybe he's more creative or more pragmatic or
better at seeing things as other people see them.
</P>
<P>
   Business guru Tom Peters says that if you are a chief executive
and your chief operating officer and your chief financial officer
agree on everything, you should fire one of them. They ought to be
seeing things from different perspectives because their jobs are so
different. If they always agree, one of them is superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   If you and your second in command always agree, you have the
wrong person. You have someone who is either dumber than you or
afraid to disagree with you. In either case, he's the wrong person
_ or you're the wrong boss.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're afraid to go outside your comfort zone. Are you
interviewing candidates from the opposite sex and different
ethnicities? Have you considered people whose backgrounds are far
different than yours? Do you encourage creativity or discourage it?
Remember: You're looking for someone to complement you, not a
clone.
</P>
<P>
   If you still can't find anyone, build a bigger office. You'll
need it for your ego.
</P>
<P>
   Would you trust him with your life? Maybe that's a bit
melodramatic, but you do have to trust your second in command in
two crucial ways: decision-making and back-stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Except for earth-shattering matters, you have to let your second
in command make a lot of decisions or you'll make yourself crazy.
If he has to ask your permission before blowing his nose, something
is seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Explain what you consider before making decisions and make sure
he understands your goals and concerns. Then let him handle a lot
of the minor things, and gradually move up to more major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   You won't always agree with everything that he does, but that's
all right. If he's following the ``wrong'' path, find out why.
Maybe he has a better strategy than you do. If not, gently correct
him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken cause of a lot of weak hiring is a boss's own
insecurity. If I hire a relative incompetent, the thinking goes,
I'll just appear even more useful to my own boss. When layoffs
come, I'll be safe.
</P>
<P>
   That might be true, but you'll also ensure that you never reach
your full potential. People who operate weak departments rarely get
promoted (except by insecure bosses, of course), and you will never
really be able to get away from the office because you know that
you've left an incompetent in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Trust works both ways, of course. Your second in command has to
trust that you will support him, even in tough times, and help him
achieve whatever career goals he has.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, you have to jiggle the toilet yourself. Your
second in command is not a flunky. Give him enough choice
assignments to keep him interested, and do a few mundane tasks on
your own to keep yourself humble.
</P>
<P>
   If you do it well enough, who knows? Someday you might be
president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
