<HEADER>
A0491 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     03-08 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-BILL-BRADLEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLOCK RUNS OUT ON BILL BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) 
 By GERALDINE FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's over.
 &HT;    Back in 1948, Missouri's favorite son confounded the pundits and
won the presidency in the face of discouraging polls. But in 2000,
another son of Missouri couldn't even carry the Show-Me State in
his own party's primary.
 &HT;    In short, Bill Bradley is no Harry Truman.
 &HT;    So how did the past year turn Bradley from the Democratic
Party's champion-in-waiting into a Super Tuesday also-ran?
 &HT;    Almost exactly a year ago, I watched Bradley wow 1,200 people at
Fordham Law School's annual alumni luncheon. It was the event's
biggest turnout since a speech by John F. Kennedy, and the audience
_ predominantly Catholic, heavily Republican but including many
``Reagan Democrats'' _ could not have been warmer.
 &HT;    At the time, it struck me as a coming-out party for a man who
might very well be president.
 &HT;    Bradley's first year with the New York Knicks didn't go well.
Labeled the team's ``great white hope,'' the former Princeton star
at first crumbled under the pressure of NBA play. The fans were
furious _ in New York, we take our sports and our politics
seriously _ and Bradley was stunned when fans threw coins at him,
and one even spat on him.
 &HT;    Needless to say, over time his play improved. He won over the
fans and earned a spot in basketball's Hall of Fame.
 &HT;    But presidential politics doesn't allow much time to grow. After
a year at least as frustrating as that first NBA season, the former
New Jersey senator is packing his bags and heading home.
 &HT;    What went wrong? Iowa and New Hampshire _ or, to put it another
way, organization and John McCain.
 &HT;    It's hard to get to the caucuses during an Iowa winter,
especially if the weather is bad. Television ads won't bring people
out. It takes friends calling friends, it takes a campaign
providing transportation for the elderly and disabled, it takes
prodding and pushing _ in other words, it takes organization.
 &HT;    Al Gore has spent the last 25 years making political friends,
and it paid off in Iowa, as the Democratic Party apparatus and
organized labor came through for him. After spending $2 million and
countless hours wooing Iowa voters, Bradley came in a distant
second.
 &HT;    New Hampshire, Bradley figured, would be better. In a primary
that allowed non-Democrats to vote, he could draw on
independent-minded Republicans who would respond to his fresh
ideas, demonstrating to the Democrats that he had the kind of
broad-based appeal to win in November.
 &HT;    But John McCain got there first, and those independents _ and
even some reform-minded Democrats, Bradley's natural base _ flocked
to the Arizonan's bandwagon. Bradley trailed Gore only narrowly,
but that wasn't nearly good enough.
 &HT;    The ship had sailed. For the next four weeks, every McCain win
garnered him more press attention, while Bradley's candidacy
withered on the vine. By last weekend, analysts were writing
Bradley's political obituary, marveling at the resiliency that let
him keep fighting even though tracking polls showed him losing by
bigger numbers each day.
 &HT;    Personally, I wasn't surprised. Bradley was a pro, and pros
don't quit. They know that anything can happen _ just ask Harry
Truman.
 &HT;    Besides, Bradley had to hang in until Super Tuesday at least. He
owed it to his supporters, if not to himself.
 &HT;    In May 1998 I left the New York State Democratic Convention
after securing a place on the ballot for the U.S. Senate race, but
I was devastated. Everything that could go wrong was going wrong,
and I soon became convinced that getting into the race in the first
place had been a mistake.
 &HT;    When I talked it over with my husband, he had a simple reaction:
``So quit.''
 &HT;    I couldn't. What could I tell my campaign staff? What kind of an
example would I be if, when things get tough, I bailed out? What
about the political people who went with me rather than one of my
opponents _ could I hang them out to dry? What about the thousands
of people who gave money to the campaign?
 &HT;    It's easy to say ``quit,'' but it isn't that easy to do it.
 &HT;    I like Al Gore, but after that law-school luncheon I was
convinced that Bradley was the Democrats' only hope of retaining
the White House.
 &HT;    I don't feel that way now. I think Gore has a good shot at
winning _ and, if he does, part of the credit will be due to Bill
Bradley.
 &HT;    Without Bradley's early success in fund-raising and in the
polls, would Gore have carried out the shakeup which has so
invigorated his campaign? Would he have had the motivation to
campaign as vigorously as he has, on television and in person?
Would the Democratic Party and organized labor be coming into the
fall with their political machines oiled up and ready for a
showdown?
 &HT;    No, Bill Bradley isn't Harry Truman. And he isn't a winner _ but
that doesn't make him a loser.
 c.2000 Geraldine A. Ferraro  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Geraldine Ferraro was the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate in 1984. A former member of Congress, she is a political
analyst for Fox News and president of G&AMP;L Strategies in New York
and Arlington, Va., a corporate consultancy on workplace and
diversity issues.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
