<HEADLINE>
A GAUDI MASTERPIECE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Antoni Gaudi's grandest dream _ a temple of faith that
wasn't finished in his lifetime and may not be finished in ours.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudi, the architect whose curvy, modernistic buildings give
Barcelona its distinctive look, planned a glorious cathedral in
that city, with heavily decorated spires shooting heavenward, and
three facades, representing faith, hope, and charity. Each facade
would have four towers, collectively representing the 12 Apostles.
And there would be a central dome, soaring some 500 feet high. The
name: Temple Expiatori de La Sagrada Familia (Exploratory Temple of
the Holy Family).
</P>
<P>
   The building was begun in 1882 but Gaudi got involved in 1891
and radically transformed the design. When he died in 1926 after
being struck by a trolley, most of only one facade was finished.
Construction began again intermittently in 1940, and today _ more
than a century after it was started _ La Sagrada Familia is perhaps
half-finished.
</P>
<P>
   That half offers much to see, however, with its brilliantly
colored tiles and mosaics, and sculpted art resembling balloons and
pinwheels. Some people are content to just gaze at the surreal
exterior, but most visit the interior of this wondrous
work-in-progress and the museum there that tells the story of La
Sagrada Familia. There is an admission charge, and an additional
fee to ride an elevator to the spires for spectacular views. (We
took the elevator up, then walked down the dark, winding, seemingly
endless staircase. It was eerie.)
</P>
<P>
   The work, and the controversy over the design and some of the
sculptures, goes on. Today's workers, though, have an advantage
over those who labored in Gaudi's time: computer-guided saws that
can chisel a granite column in one-sixth the time it takes by hand.
</P>
<P>
   (Barcelona, Spain's second-largest city, offers a lot more to
see than La Sagrada Familia. We enjoyed our visit immensely, even
if a cab driver did overcharge us on our return to the airport. For
more information on Barcelona and all of Spain, call the Spanish
National Tourist Office at 212-265-8822, fax 212-265-8864, visit
wwww.okspain.org, or write to the office at 66th Fifth Ave., 35th
Floor, New York, NY 10103.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Barcelona, the treasure house of courtesy, the refuge
of strangers'' _ from ``Don Quixote, Part II'' by Cervantes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Close your eyes and visualize a blue flag with a
yellow cross. What country does it represent? (Answer at end of
column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shamrocks and surf: Surfing in Ireland? You bet. A champion surfer
there tells us the waves are considered the world's second-best,
behind Hawaii, but the water is a tad cooler. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh, that Winston: The underground complex where British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill directed the Allied effort during World
War II is now open to the public. Among things a visitor learns
when visiting the complex, located on King Charles Street in
London: The underground offices and bedrooms were protected by a
3-foot slab of concrete. Yet when the city was being bombed,
Churchill was likely to be found not in his protected quarters but
on the building roof, watching the air raids. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A grape idea: Vinopolis is a $36 million interactive adult theme
park in London dedicated to the appreciation of wine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriotic pizza: Pizza margarita salutes the colors of the
Italian flag _ red (tomatoes), white (mozzarella), and green
(basil). &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Gibraltar tail: Europe's only wild monkeys live in Gibraltar. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: Henry Kissinger's rule of travel: Never visit abroad
what you would avoid in your own country. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oops, wrong guy: A recent quote in this column about German wedding
traditions should have been attributed to Frank Astheimer, sales
representative for the Hotel Nikko Dusseldorf in Germany. Jonathan
Orr-Ewing, to whom the quote was incorrectly attributed, is
actually general manager of the Montcalm/Hotel Nikko London. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
