<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BOURQUE-ART-BOS &LR;      03-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BOURQUE SKY-HIGH FOR NEW CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Few places in North America could be as
different from Boston _ physically, culturally, and geographically
_ as the place in which Ray Bourque found himself, inside the gates
of Stampede Park and in the visitors' locker room at the
Saddledome.
</P>
<P>
   But Bourque, wearing 77 on his back _ a strange 77, in maroon
and blue _ found himself here, on the ice for the opening faceoff
between his new team, the Colorado Avalanche, and the Calgary
Flames.
</P>
<P>
   He was paired on defense with Adam Foote, to provide stability,
the outlet pass, and so much more for a team lacking in leadership.
Not even a slight groin strain that took him out of the game in the
third period dampened the enthusiasm felt by all the Avalanche on
this day. The fact that Colorado won, 8-3, didn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   As Foote put it, ``What Ray does on the ice is not as important
as what he'll do in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque seemed excited, even wired, upon arriving in Calgary
after the long flight from Boston. He said he still wants to see if
he has ``it'' _ that intangible ``it'' that made him a great
defenseman but lately has been doubted. Perhaps even by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There (are) two reasons why I asked to be traded,'' said
Bourque, who was whisked from the airport to an immediate press
conference at a downtown hotel. ``One is obvious; I've never won a
Stanley Cup. I asked to go to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second reason is, at this point in my career, I need a
challenge. I really want to find out what's left in Ray Bourque. A
challenge like this is really going to bring out the best in me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional morning for Bourque's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They drove me to the airport this morning, and it was very
tough,'' said Bourque. ``But they're with me 100 percent. My
children know this is going to be a good thing for their dad, and
my wife is behind me 100 percent. The children know Dad's going for
what he always wanted to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Andreychuk, the other part of the Boston-to-Colorado
package, confirmed that it was emotional for Dad, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane ride was long and we had a great chance to talk,''
said Andreychuk. ``This is Ray's first move to another team so, of
course, I told him what to look for. But Ray was nervous _ he was
really nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was so nervous, so pumped up before the game ``that I
went too hard, too quick in the warmups,'' and slightly hurt his
groin, which put him on the bench for the third period. ``I didn't
want to aggravate it, so we kind of backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole day was surreal, with Bourque ``having thoughts all
day long'' of former teammates such as Don Sweeney and Steve
Heinze, ``and I'm sure I will have thoughts for many days to come.
I'll never forget the guys I played with.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the new teammates who welcomed him right away was former
Bruin Dave Reid, who gave him a hug and told him, ``The hardest
thing for you will be the warmups; you've run them in Boston for 21
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque conceded that the warmups were weird, but he was
surprised at how comfortable he felt in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be very tough,'' he said. ``But it
was real nice getting off to the start we did and winning like we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that ``77'' in maroon and blue hanging in his locker was
weird, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you just put it on and go out there,'' he said.
``Skating around in the warmups with it on was weird. But then the
game started and we began clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bourque showed a side of himself that the Boston media
rarely saw. He was psyched, and he said so. ``Coming to Colorado,
I'm psyched,'' he said. ``I'm thrilled and excited to be coming
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting dressed for those last games in Boston, it was a very
emotional time. That was real tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Bruins' sorry plight, Bourque would say only, ``We know
how Harry (Sinden) runs his business. He's consistent; you've got
to give him that. It's no surprise to anybody. Harry has always
gone about his business the same way and we all know it, so . . .
you live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk also was forthright, saying, ``No matter what people
tell you, money doesn't buy happiness. You can read that 19
different ways, but Ray stayed there because he was treated very,
very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say Harry didn't treat his players well? Bull. The
Boston Bruins were very good for Ray Bourque and he was good for
the team. It works both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   And Andreychuk went to work right away, stealing the puck and
feeding Adam Deadmarsh for a goal that gave the Avalanche a 2-1
lead. An errant pass by Bourque helped set up Calgary's second
goal, but Bourque picked up a point _ his first in the NHL that
didn't come as a Bruin _ with a typically nifty pass from his end
that sent Milan Hejduk and Alex Tanguay out on a break. Hejduk
finished the play for Colorado's sixth goal, at 11:40 of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bourque sat out the third period, he will play in
Colorado's next game on this Alberta tour, Friday night in
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Avalanche captain Joe Sakic said he would give up the
``C'' on his sweater if Bourque asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can comes in and asks for it, he can have it,'' said
Sakic.
</P>
<P>
   But will he? Sakic was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
