<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0503 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX     03-08 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson, Miriam Longino and Ryon Horne
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Monk's Dream''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lacy/Roswell Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ/Verve. 9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, soprano saxophonist Steve Lacy and
trombonist Roswell Rudd formed the core of a pianoless quartet that
played, almost exclusively, the complete works of Thelonious Monk.
The birth of the concept of a jazz repertory was still many years
distant, and the idea of an ensemble devoting itself to a single
composer _ in particular, to a colleague not universally
appreciated at the time _ resembled some insane spiritual exercise.
Monk's compo-
</P>
<P>
   sitions have, however, endured spectacularly, and the Lacy/Rudd
quartet, dissolved in 1965, became one of those mythic jazz
touchstones, like Paul Gonsalves' 27 choruses at the 1956 Newport
Jazz Festival. That only one obscure recording documented the
Lacy/Rudd band helped enlarge the legend. But Lacy and Rudd
reunited recently in the studio, with excellent support from
Jean-Jacques Avenel on bass and John Betsch on drums, to reminisce
about the time 30 years ago when they were Thelonious' monks.
</P>
<P>
   Only two selections on the resulting compact disc are by Monk,
but the missing pianist's spirit of economy informs the whole disc.
The delicate, precise and always tuneful Lacy finds his
counterweight in Rudd's burlesque glissandos, jungle growls and
earthy good humor. The two vocals provided by Lacy's significant
other, Irene Aebi, are not to my taste, but there are many
redeeming moments, including the prancing hip shaking of ``The
Rent'' and the sublime ``Pannonica.''
</P>
<P>
   _Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``I Was Born to Love You''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Carmen. Pyramid. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Eric Carmen is one of those pop stars whose image is so
ambiguous that it doesn't really stick in the mind, yet he somehow
manages to have a hook-laden smash radio hit every decade. In the
1970s, it was the lusty makeout classic ``Go All the Way'' (with
power pop group the Raspberries) and the solo weepie ``All by
Myself.'' Ten years later, he emerged from the polyester years with
the 1987 groin-grind single ``Hungry Eyes,'' from the
million-selling soundtrack to ``Dirty Dancing.'' Now, just as the
'90s fade away without a peep from Carmen, here he comes with an
album of new material, angling for a hit. This time out, however,
the 50-year-old singer may not score a comeback. Gone are the
anguished, McCartney-eseque screams and the buoyant pop tunes with
hypnotic melodies. Carmen, for the most part, has become Celine
Dion, with an album of mostly overwritten ballads and vocals laced
with exaggerated emotion.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``BTNHResurrection''
</P>
<P>
   Bone Thugs-N-Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthless/Epic Records. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Just when we thought one of the hard-core rap groups was calling
it quits, Bone Thugs-N-Harmony creatively splices together another
album that blatantly puts to death the rumors and resurrects its
authentic sound. Lyrically, the Grammy-winning group has combined
its most unapologetic poetry and life experiences, rendering a list
of tracks that negatively influences (``Ecstasy''), positively
inspires (``Change the World'') and forcefully paints a vivid
description of their world (``Mind on Our Money''). Although the
songs are contradictory at times _ rapping about changing the world
in one and then glamorizing drugs in another _ the album is
consistent musically, with an appealing R&AMP;B sound.
</P>
<P>
   _Ryon Horne
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson, Miriam Longino and Ryon Horne writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
