NYT-03-08-00 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BOURQUE-CAREER-BO     03-08 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-CAREER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENDURING LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The joke was that Ray Bourque would be the only Bruin
to have his jersey retired while he was still wearing it. Harry
Sinden, who goes back to the days of the NHL's Original Six, said
he couldn't remember the team without Bourque on it. Twenty-one
years, 1,518 games, nearly 50,000 minutes. More than twice as many
as Bobby Orr, the legend he conceded he could never be.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was hockey's Ripken, its Gehrig, its Havlicek, his
attendance as remarkable as his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a guy who shows up every night to play,'' Bourque said.
</P>
<P>
   He never missed more than 20 games in a season, and four times
he played in them all. He played with sprained knees, wrenched
shoulders, charley horses, bruised ribs, hip pointers, pulled back
muscles, broken fingers, and scratched eyeballs. This year, a
deflected slapshot tore open his upper lip and gums and knocked out
three teeth. Bourque nonchalantly showed up the next morning for
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was always a blue-collar player, the fourth of five
children of a maintenance man who lived in a working-class Montreal
suburb. His father put him on skates when he was 3 and stuck a
hockey net against a basement wall in their apartment house for
Bourque and his brothers to fire at.
</P>
<P>
   By 14, he was off to juniors, to Three Rivers, to Sorel, to
Verdun. ``We got us a champion here,'' said Sinden when he saw
Bourque in an all-star tournament, and he drafted Bourque first in
1979. Bourque was just 18, yet Sinden admitted to having goose
bumps the first time he saw him in camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who'd just missed making the Stanley Cup finals by
one game, were loaded with veterans that year, but they knew that
the quiet Quebecois would eventually be the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just play hockey,'' enforcer John Wensink told him, ``and if
anybody touches you, I'll be right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque set up a goal on his first shift and played 94 straight
games before Detroit goon Dennis Polonich broke his jaw in two
places with an overhand right. But Bourque made a point of winning
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give an inch,'' he would say, two decades later.
``If you do, then they've got the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque came to play every shift, every night. His greatest fear
other than horror movies (he woke up screaming after watching
``Terminator 2'') was doing something wrong on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid to make a mistake,'' he once said. ``Afraid to be
embarrassed out there, afraid that I won't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear drove Bourque to stardom immediately. He was the first
non-goalie to win the Calder Trophy (top rookie) and make
first-team All-Star in the same season. After three seasons, Sinden
was calling him ``one of our top, top players.'' After half a
dozen, he was considered the best all-around defenseman in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   When rival clubs asked about trading for Bourque (and most knew
better), Sinden would say he wasn't available. Not unless you could
guarantee him a Stanley Cup. The Bruins had a taste of it in 1988,
when they finally ended the Canadiens playoff jinx after 45 years,
beat the Devils in seven games, and got to the finals against the
Oilers for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   They were back two years later, and it was Bourque who got them
there, miraculously coming out for the seventh game in the opening
series against Hartford after missing the previous four with a deep
hip bruise.
</P>
<P>
   At noon that day, he couldn't skate. That evening, Bourque led
his club onto the Garden ice and played the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked at the way he played,'' marveled Mike Milbury,
then his fellow blue liner. ``This is big-league hockey. I don't
know how he got through it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game of the finals against the Oilers, Bourque
brought his mates back from the dead with two third-period goals
and kept them going through three overtimes and 115 minutes (he
played nearly 59) before they lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt this was the year,'' he said after Edmonton had wiped
out the Bruins in five. ``Another chance? I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   That was what kept Bourque in Boston, the thought of hoisting
the Auld Mug aloft and skating in triumphant circles with the men
who'd elected him captain. He would never be Orr (``a
once-in-a-lifetime player''), but Orr had never been captain.
</P>
<P>
   His mates saw the leadership in him before Bourque did himself.
It was his work ethic, his dedication, his loyalty, his grit, his
resilience, his humility, his balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life is in order,'' Kyle McLaren said.
</P>
<P>
   When Bourque was at his locker (and when wasn't he?), there was
a comforting sense of stability, of reliability, of harmony, of
camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to let that guy down,'' Don Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's longevity, his sheer everydayness, conferred authority
on him, as it had on Ripken, on Gehrig, on Havlicek, on the iron
horses of every sport. He had been blessed with a hockey player's
body, Bourque observed. Thick, sturdy frame. Natural strength.
Superb cardiovascular system. ``He really is a horse,'' Sinden
observed.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was a year-round horse, working himself hard over the
summers, following a day-by-day program laid out by his old high
school gym teacher Benoit Leduc, who coached Canada's distance
runners for years. During the season, Bourque rarely took days off,
even when practices were optional and he was hurting. ``Touching
the ice'' kept him in rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Bourque in uniform, day after day, year after year, made
it easy to take him and his exceptional skills for granted. It took
him eight years to win the first of his five Norris Trophies as the
league's best defensemen. He never won the Hart, which goes to the
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque didn't even rule his own town. Larry Bird, who arrived
the same year (``Who's Larry Bird?,'' Bourque wondered) and played
for championship Celtic teams, did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Bourque has never gotten his due in this town,'' Sinden
said time and again, ``and he probably never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque didn't even get to keep his own number. The 7 belonged
to Phil Esposito (``I never asked for it,'' Bourque insisted), and
Bourque gladly gave it up when Esposito came back to see it hoisted
to the rafters in 1987. ``It's all yours,'' Bourque told him.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque would wear 77, would wear it as long as it took to bring
the Cup back to Causeway Street. ``I think I'll go forever,'' he
mused puckishly at 31, but he already sensed the clock ticking.
</P>
<P>
   That year, he mistakenly walked into the old-timers' dressing
room at the All-Star Game and saw Guy Lafleur and Darryl Sittler
and Denis Potvin. ``I've played against almost every guy in
there,'' Bourque realized.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he knew, longevity would become as much a vice as a
virtue. When he hit a rough patch in 1993, Bourque began hearing
that he was trade bait, that he was on the downslide. ``I'm not too
old to be playing this game,'' he told himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was still logging 30 minutes a night, still playing all
but a handful of games a season, still making first-team All-Star.
He still had another Norris Trophy in him. He had everything but a
serious shot at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were becoming postseason patsies, one-and-out. In
1997, they missed the playoffs for the first time in 30 years. For
an ebullient couple of weeks last season, after he and his mates
ground down Carolina (with Bourque playing 53 minutes in the
pivotal double-overtime victory in Game 5), Bourque thought there
might be a chance.
</P>
<P>
   It was, finally, a false spring and Bourque's last one here. He
had hinted, then stated, that this campaign might be his last. When
the season unraveled in a sour mix of losses and injuries and
mayhem and pointed fingers, it became inevitable. So the captain
asked for the puck after Saturday's game with the Flyers and
essentially bade his blood brethren adieu.
</P>
<P>
   He has outlasted three presidents, 10 coaches, and 15 buildings.
Now, Raymond Jean Bourque goes to the Rocky Mountains to play in a
rink named after a soft drink for the young generation. The next
time he comes to the FleetCenter, he goes to the rafters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
