<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-NATURE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steely Dan's sound as polished as ever
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's just like they never left.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after releasing their apparent swan song,
``Gaucho,'' Donald Fagen and Walter Becker are back with a new
studio album that seamlessly picks up where the Steely Dan duo left
off in 1979. And here's the surprise: ``Two Against Nature'' trumps
``Gaucho'' on many fronts and, in places, approaches the sweep and
scope of the Dan's 1977 masterwork, ``Aja.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening strains of the effervescent ``Gaslighting
Abbie,'' it's clear that the trademark Fagen-Becker blend of
goes-down-easy pop, jazz and soul is still kicking. Other Dan
hallmarks are also evident: the top-notch musicianship, clean
production and cynical perspectives on oddball relationships and
urban weirdos. Yet somehow ``Nature'' sounds fresh and new _
perhaps because it contrasts so starkly with the schmaltzy noodling
that passes for so much smooth jazz today.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to Steely Dan's best works are inevitable. And while
``Nature'' doesn't surpass such masterpieces as ``The Royal Scam''
or ``Pretzel Logic,'' most tracks sound like box-set-worthy
outtakes from ``Aja'' _ they're that good. The standouts ``Almost
Gothic'' and ``Cousin Dupree'' cultivate irresistible in-the-pocket
grooves that rank with the best of the Dan catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature'' probably won't displace any longtime Dan favorites.
But if you liked them before, you'll go for this, too.
</P>
<P>
   'Two Against Nature'
</P>
<P>
   Steely Dan / Giant-Reprise Records / 9 tracks / Our critic's
grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
