<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-THETRUTH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Truth' be told, solo debut falls short of buzz
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, here's ``The Truth'' about Beanie Sigel's debut: Nothing on
it lives up to the hype that came before it.
</P>
<P>
   Here he was, a guy who'd made a memorable guest appearance on
``1000 Bars'' from DJ Clue's mix tape and the remix of Jay-Z's
single ``Money, Cash, (Expletive)''. That was it. Then _ as hip-hop
lore goes _ though he hadn't made a demo and wasn't even thinking
about leaving an admitted life of crime in Philadelphia for rap,
the record industry comes after him. Next thing you know, Sigel's
on Jay-Z's label and at Jay-Z's side in 1998 as he rode his 4
million-selling ``Hard Knock Life'' album to a Grammy and the
best-selling rap road show in history.
</P>
<P>
   For the encore, ``Life and Times of S. Carter,'' Jay-Z hands the
mike to Sigel on its first single, ``Do It Again.'' And his dynamic
lead verse only heightens the buzz. Granted, the momentum is
maintained by both muscular (``The Truth,'' ``Who Want What'') and
spare (``Raw &AMP; Uncut'') blaxploitation-inspired production, and his
menacing delivery always draws you in. But when it comes to subject
matter, it's like Sigel was never plucked off the streets because
the only truth he can talk about is that.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP: ``The Truth''
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Sigel. Roc-a -fella Records. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
