<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kubrick's voyeuristic voyage
 &HT;    Kubrick's erotic thriller not very exciting
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late Stanley Kubrick's final film is a letdown _ an often
frustrating peephole view at jealousy and sexual obsession that
confronts a rich New York couple (Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman).
</P>
<P>
   When she confesses to lustful feelings for a stranger, he
embarks on a tentative sexual quest, testing his marriage. And our
patience. While it has its moments, its much-touted centerpiece
orgy doesn't work. What you get resembles Cirque du Soleil as
performed by the cast of ``Showgirls.'' (By the way, the video
release still uses digital effects to mask some of the scene's more
graphic actions.)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   'Eyes Wide Shut'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Dog of Flanders'' (PG) _ Not a total dog but close. A
Dutch touch is about all that distinguishes this adaptation of a
19th-century children's book about an orphan boy who befriends the
titular canine and dreams of one day becoming an artist. Filmed in
Flanders, the movie abounds with windmills and picturesque town
squares. What it lacks, alas, are interesting characters and a
decent story line. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Windhorse'' (unrated) _ Shot guerrilla-style on a digital
camera, this political drama focuses on a Tibetan brother and
sister facing oppression from the Chinese police. Considering the
ingenuity and personal risk that went into the (illegal) making of
the movie, it's a shame it isn't a little sharper. Too often, you
find yourself wishing for a script as strong as the convictions of
the filmmakers. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The King of Masks'' (unrated) _ A charming fable about the
growing bond between a street performer and his adopted child. It's
also a good treatise on the treatment of females in 1930s China.
Though it suffers some lapses of sentimentality and melodrama, it's
held together by its emotional core. In Mandarin with subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
