<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSPICE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoy an Italian holiday with braciole of choice
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braciole has so many variations it begs to be experimented with.
If you would like to try this Italian Sunday specialty, which was
featured prominently in a recent episode of ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' check out these Web sites and find one that may become a
favorite in your own family.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See www.geocities.com/NapaValley/1745/Braciole.html for a
version with pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A good crockpot braciole recipe that uses sausage is at
fp.enter.net/(tilde)rburk/crockpot
</P>
<P>
   /newcrockpot/braciole.txt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get a glimpse of long simmering braciole sauces at
www.neosoft.com/recipes/pasta
</P>
<P>
   sauces/meat01.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you are new to braciole, you may want to see
www.foodstyles.com/Main%20Courses
</P>
<P>
   /braciole.htm and www.chefsauce.com/Recipes/ for two simple,
flavorful basic recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a southern Italian version using eggs and olives, see
www.theartisan.net/Braciole.htm
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Braciole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1-1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds flank steak, cut and pounded into thin slices about
4 by 6 inches (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese, plus extra for serving
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups basic marinara sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 pound favorite pasta, cooked according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   Note: We found the easiest way to do this is to cut steak into
six pieces, then butterfly them by cutting horizontally almost all
the way through, and pounding lightly to a uniform thickness. This
works best when meat is semifrozen.
</P>
<P>
   Season the meat on both sides with salt and pepper to taste. In
a bowl, combine the 1/2 cup Parmesan, garlic and parsley. Divide
the mixture among the meat slices, spreading it into an even layer,
and roll up each slice from short end to short end to enclose the
filling. Secure each roll with string or toothpicks. In a casserole
or Dutch oven over medium-high heat, warm oil. When hot, add meat
rolls and cook, turning, until browned on all sides, about 5 to 7
minutes. Add marinara sauce, bring to a boil, reduce heat enough to
maintain a simmer, stirring occasionally to prevent sticking, for 1
to 1 1/2 hours, or until the meat is tender.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer meat to a platter and remove the strings or toothpicks.
Return meat to sauce and simmer until heated through. Serve with
pasta and freshly grated Parmesan. _ From: ``The Men of the Pacific
Street Social Club Cook Italian'' by Gerard Renny (WilliamMorrow,
$23)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 698 calories, 38 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 75 grams carbohydrates, 66
milligrams cholesterol, 755 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
