<HEADER>
A0512 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-RAYMOND-BRACIOLE09-CO     03-08 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYMOND-BRACIOLE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dish featured on TV sitcom prompts queries
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the Feb. 28 episode of the popular CBS sitcom ``Everybody
Loves Raymond,'' the food department has fielded numerous inquiries
from readers about the guest star: the Italian specialty braciole.
</P>
<P>
   In the show, Ray's wife, Debra, makes fabulous braciole, which
everyone in the family raves about. Everybody, that is, but Ray's
mother, Marie, who deemed Debra's masterpiece a direct threat to
her self-proclaimed superiority in the kitchen and her role as
alpha-female in the dysfunctional but loving Romano clan.
</P>
<P>
   So what is braciole (pronounced bra-ZHOLE)? Basically, it's
sliced beef or veal that's pounded thin and then stuffed, rolled
and tied with string like a jellyroll. The rolls are then seared in
olive oil and put in a pot of gravy or sauce to simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Braciole is definitely a Sunday dish. There is no such thing as
quick 'n' easy braciole. My mother, Josephine, let her braciole
simmer in a huge pot of gravy for a couple of days, along with
meatballs, sausage, lamb and whatever else she put in that fabulous
pot. By Sunday, the braciole was fork-tender and meltingly
flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   Braciole is served all over the boot of Italy and has hundreds
of variations according to the region or even a particular family.
Particularly threatening to Marie Romano were the raisins Debra
used in hers. ``She used raisins?'' asks the astonished Marie.
Along with the fundamental ingredients of garlic, parsley and bread
crumbs, the stuffing might also include pine nuts, sausage, various
cheeses, olives, mushrooms, hard-boiled eggs (from southern Italy),
eggplantor prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we give you a basic braciole recipe, along with some Web
sites with recipes for those who are more ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
