r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL09-COX     03-08 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some devilishly good movies to check out
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles may be the City of Angels, but Hollywood has played
host to its share of devils on film. Roman Polanski doesn't ever
show the devil in his new picture, ``The Ninth Gate,'' which opens
Friday. But then, he's been there, done that. His quick-cut of
Lucifer having his way with a drugged Mia Farrow in ``Rosemary's
Baby'' is probably one of the most powerful satanic images ever put
on film.
</P>
<P>
   The list of devilish turns by actors is as eclectic as it is
lengthy, running the gamut from Tim Curry (``Legend'') to Bill
Cosby (``The Devil and Max Devlin.'') And let's not forget his
satanic majesty's cameo in last summer's ``South Park: Bigger,
Longer &AMP; Uncut.'' Here are a few other ideas for having a devil of
a time on your VCR:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Witches of Eastwick'': Jack Nicholson as the devil? Are
we talking typecasting or what? In this adaptation of John Updike's
satirical novel, Nicholson plays a devilish stranger who shows up
in a proper New England town and seduces three delectable divorcees
(Michelle Pfeiffer, Susan Sarandon, Cher) who then turn the tables
on him. The movie's subtext _ feminism as a form of modern-day
witchcraft _ is less than spellbinding, but you're in such good
company that it's hard to complain. Nicholson went about
researching his character in a typically offbeat way: Besides
reading the Updike novel, he studied Gustav Dore's illustrations
for ``Dante's Inferno'' and pored over St. Thomas Aquinas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Needful Things'': Things supernatural have always come
naturally to Stephen King. In this adaptation of one of his
ubiquitous best sellers, all hell breaks loose in the quiet hamlet
of Castle Rock, Maine, when a seemingly avuncular Max von Sydow
opens a curio shop named _ what else? _ Needful Things. His
inventory is slight but oddly on target. That is, he just happens
to carry your secret heart's desire, be it old baseball cards or an
amulet that cures arthritis. The inevitable disintegration into
over-the-top mayhem is a disappointment, but the movie offers a
frisky, tongue-in-cheek spirit and good performances. For those who
take note of such things, von Sydow may be the only actor to have
played the devil, Jesus Christ (``The Greatest Story Ever Told'')
and the Grim Reaper (``The Seventh Seal'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Angel Heart'': When it was released, there was an awful lot
of fuss over the prospect of a naked ``Cosby'' kid (Lisa Bonet).
But Mickey Rourke treats her a lot better than he did Kim Basinger
in ``9 1/2 Weeks.'' The movie itself is a kind of amalgam of Faust
and film noir. Or Sam Spade Meets Mr. Scratch. Set in the 1950s, it
stars Rourke as a seedy private eye hired by a mysteriously smooth
dandy (Robert De Niro in a goatee ... hint, hint) to help him in a
missing persons case. It's a Mephistophelean murder mystery
suffused with blood, sex and a touch of eye-of-newt nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Devil and Daniel Webster'': Director William Dieterle
(``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' ``Portrait of Jenny'') had just
left Warner Bros. and formed his own company when he filmed this
adaptation of Stephen Vincent Benet's famous story. Edward Arnold
plays Webster, the celebrated Yankee barrister, and James Craig is
the poor New England farmer so down on his luck that he
inadvertently summons Mr. Scratch (Walter Huston) when he swears
that he'd sell his soul to the devil for two cents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Damn Yankees'': It ran for 1,019 performances on Broadway
before being made into a movie by the same team that did ``The
Pajama Game.'' Based on the book ``The Year the Yankees Lost the
Pennant,'' the film is a variation on the famous Faustian bargain.
In this case, an aging Washington Senators fan offers his soul as
collateral for the chance to be transformed into a powerhouse
ballplayer in order to beat the unbeatable New York Yankees. The
stars are Tab Hunter (surprisingly good) and Gwen Verdon (always
good), but the movie is stolen by Ray Walston as a particularly
petulant devil.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
