A0514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-08 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS MAKE OVERHEATED MARKET BURN EVEN HOTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, the stock price of PMC-Sierra, a chip maker, jumped to
230 from 201. The main reason? An analyst raised his 12-month price
target on the stock from 200 to 250.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the stock price of Art Technology Group, a Boston
software company, jumped 25 percent in a single day when an analyst
at Credit Suisse First Boston initiated his coverage with a
``strong buy'' rating. The analyst predicted the stock, then
trading for 125, would reach 200 in the next year. It hit 156 that
day. It closed Tuesday at 185.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been recommending stocks forever. Price targets
are nothing new, either. But the market's huge and immediate
reactions to them is a ``new, new'' thing, according to veteran
money managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the latest manifestation of a market that is
taking everything to extremes,'' said Thomas O'Neill, chief
investment officer at FleetBoston Financial Corp. The price targets
are often based on questionable logic, O'Neill said, yet investors
treat them as if they were edicts from on high.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill may be a traditionalist, but he is clearly on to
something here. Is it really big news that an analyst has launched
coverage of a stock with a ``strong buy'' rating? In a world where
no one ever recommends selling a stock, is a ``strong buy'' rating
something to get excited about?
</P>
<P>
   And how real are these targets? ``In my years of experience, I
have not seen many people who can actually forecast a price of a
security,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment strategist at State
Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet day after day, technology stocks soar on news that analysts
have set targets somewhere above the current stock price. The
targets usually are one-year projections. But the stocks react
immediately, often reaching the one-year targets in no time flat.
It is as if investors are saying: ``Why should I wait for a whole
year for the stock to go up, when it can go up right now?''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the analysts setting the targets seem a bit
bewildered. Consider the experience of Sam May, an analyst for US
Bancorp Piper Jaffrey who tracks the fortunes of Alpha Industries,
a supplier to the cellular phone business.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, with the price of Alpha stock at 55, May recommended
the shares and issued a 12-month price target of 65. The stock hit
65 by mid-January. On Feb. 14, with Alpha stock at 115, May once
again recommended Alpha, but this time he set his 12-month target
at 155. Alpha closed Tuesday at 136.
</P>
<P>
   May still likes Alpha. He says the company has excellent
fundamentals and prospects. But he concedes that setting price
targets in today's market is an inexact science. ``With the
valuations getting pushed up so high, it is hard to keep targets
for more than two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm, another cellular stock, has also benefited from
analyst projections. In late December, Walter Piecyk, an analyst
with Paine Webber, said Qualcomm would reach 1000 in a year. At the
time, the stock traded for 500.
</P>
<P>
   Piecyk's recommendation, along with news of a planned stock
split, pushed Qualcomm shares up about 40 percent over the next
four days.
</P>
<P>
   Piecyk didn't just pull his price target out of the air. It was
based on his calculation of the money Qualcomm would reap in
royalty payments on its key cellular technology. Piecyk estimated
those payments would reach $20 billion a year by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   In a nifty piece of analysis, two Business Week reporters,
writing in the March 6 issue of the magazine, demolish most of
Piecyk's assumptions. They say he overestimated cell phone growth
and cell phone prices and underestimated the impact that
competition would have on Qualcomm's royalty revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: That $20 billion figure could be an awful lot
smaller. Qualcomm's stock price has dropped considerably from its
January highs.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a money manager with Loomis Sayles, said the
hyper-reactions to analyst recommendations may be the result of the
invasion of the stock market by day traders. Day traders are
momentum players, and they look for any bit of news which might
move a stock. In the absence of real news, analyst recommendations
can fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he and his colleagues take note of the
recommendations only when they come from analysts with track
records. ``Otherwise, we prefer to concentrate on fundamentals,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Us too. We have no problem with analysts making recommendations
and setting targets, but when those targets become self-fulfilling
prophecies, we get a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is just feeding on itself,'' said O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   We agree. And we have a question: When the whole technology
market starts to unravel, will analysts set lower price targets on
the way down?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
