<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD MANNERS CAN RUIN FOREIGN DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry M. Seals was appalled.
</P>
<P>
   After telling representatives of a US information technology
firm about the importance of Japanese etiquette and protocol, he
was stunned when they sabotaged what could have been a lucrative
deal by insisting a contract be drafted right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, when you and a group of Japanese businessmen have
the first business meeting, the point is not to negotiate,'' said
Seals. ``The point is to establish a relationship, to get to know
you, and to see what kind of person you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had explained that there would be many meetings before
negotiations actually began. I'd also explained that negotiations
always take place over dinner or drinks, but the US firm wanted to
fly out of Japan the next day, and it ignored my advice.''
</P>
<P>
   The American firm's brashness was seen as rudeness. Its
representatives' insistence on a contract, and their many
questions, were considered intrusive. Politely, the Japanese
businessmen promised they would soon be in touch. But they never
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do in Japan during a first meeting is
to try and pressure a potential partner or client into making a
decision,'' Seals said.
</P>
<P>
   The next worst thing? ``Not giving a business card the proper
deference and attention it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many US firms now involved in international business
deals, companies are finding that familiarity with the host
country's business protocol, language, mores, and customs is more
important than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, some US companies are turning to intercultural
specialists or consultants, such as Seals, for help. These new
gurus are not unlike the diversity specialists who in the 1980s
helped US companies understand issues of class, sex, gender, and
race in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Seals, chief executive of MG Technologies &AMP; Investments Inc., an
IT and consulting firm in Japan, spends much of his time helping
Asian high-tech firms form alliances with companies in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   His firm teams with a Nevada-based e-commerce company,
BiPacificLink Inc., which helps US firms use the Internet to market
their products in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the 25-year-old African-American consultant and
author of ``Making It In Japan: An Insider's Journey to Success,''
was a keynote speaker at the Harvard Club in Cambridge, Mass.
There, he offered the following tips:
</P>
<P>
   --Practice Japanese etiquette before a business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, it is disarming to the Japanese when a foreigner
sits across from them and demonstrates that he or she understands
the etiquette,'' Seals sid. ``It tells them that the meeting was
important enough to you that you took the time to learn
etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   --Never handle a Japanese business card lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese business card is equivalent to a person's face.
You are expected to take it with both hands, and give your own with
both hands. You look at it, you examine it, you touch it from time
to time. . . When a Japanese company invites an American service
provider to Japan, the company representatives feel that they have
extended to you the honor of meeting them. You are expected to show
you are thankful. This is done by showing respect for the card. To
take a business card and stuff it in your pocket or purse is an
insult. To write on a business card in the presence of the person
who gave it to you is also an insult.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't expect to make a deal right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most American companies and their representatives come to
meetings assuming that something will be decided right away. What
they don't realize is that the person or people you are talking to
can't make a deal. The person is simply there to determine what
kind of person you are. He will watch your body language, how you
speak, how you present yourself. Then, he will take the information
back to the people who run the company. Later, usually after
several meetings, the negotiations will begin.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handshaking is not a custom,'' Seals noted. ``People in Japan
are not used to that firm American grip. They would rather bow. The
bow shows deference and respect for the culture. . . . Even though
you may be the customer, the company representative from Japan will
bow deeply when you appear. Why? Because you are an honored guest
in his country and at his company. . . . This bow is almost 60
degrees, and it is done very slowly. The chief executive will bow
only 45 degrees. In either case, the American representative should
bow deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the Japanese, manners and etiquette are very important,''
added Seals. ``If you can perform correctly, if you know the rules
of etiquette, then the feeling is that you can be trusted to act
prudently in another environment, the business environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Seals learned those rules the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   As an undergraduate at Harvard College, he had immersed himself
in East Asian studies, particularly Chinese and Japanese culture.
He learned to speak Japanese and Mandarin Chinese fluently and
spent his junior year in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1996, Seals accepted a full-time job at a
midsize IT firm in Kyota, Japan. There, he learned that subtle
differences in style, tone of voice, behavior, even gestures, could
make or break a business deal. He also learned about the importance
of manners and that the primacy of the group is more important in
Japan than the individual's desires.
</P>
<P>
   But by his own account, Henry Seals is also an anomaly: Few
African-Americans do business in Japan. He maintains, however, that
his race was never an issue during the two years he worked for a
company identified in his book by the pseudonym Mitsui. Instead, he
said, coworkers and supervisors were more concerned about the way
he conducted himself _ his manners, his willingness to learn, his
ability to follow directions and accept without question the
demands of his supervisors and mentor.
</P>
<P>
   At Mitsui, Seals was assigned to a ``senpai,'' or mentor, who
was responsible for showing the new employee how to be a complete
member of society and adjust to the specific requirements of the
firm. A senpai taught the new recruit the inner workings of
corporate politics, how to write a business letter, how to deal
with stress on the job, how to handle the large amount of social
drinking expected in a typical work week, and how to take criticism
in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Seals's senpai tried to teach him how to handle criticism by
constantly criticizing his mistakes, an approach Seals was not used
to and that he bridled against.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this relationship, it was expected that there would be
disagreements, even conflicts,'' noted Seal. ``But that was
unsettling to me. I found a senpai could actually punish you.
Hazing could also occur in which you might see an adult male, 45
years old, being scolded, even slapped, by a superior. . . .
Although I was a freshman in the company with no ranking or title,
it helped that I spoke the language and could assist Mitsui in
setting up partnerships with overseas firms.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Seals recalled an incident in which
his hand was slapped by a supervisor because he had not found the
appropriate computer screen. When Seals questioned the supervisor,
he was told: ``To me, you are like a child, my child. I must do
this to help you be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Richmond, Va., Seals said a friendship with a Japanese
member of his high school track team sparked his interest in
Japanese language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran track together, and we talked a lot about the
differences in our countries,'' he said. ``But the more we talked,
the more I realized how little I knew about the world outside of
the two states where I had lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Seals now lives in Japan with his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
at 617-929-2069, or by e-mail at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
