<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMPELLING BOOK TELLS OF REWARDS, RISKS IN KING CRAB COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Can you imagine making $100,000 in a month while
working in the great outdoors in Alaska?
</P>
<P>
   That is the fantasy that drives being a commercial crabber on
the Bering Sea, where you experience the marrow of life of the
great outdoors while getting a stake in the last great Alaskan gold
rush _ king crab.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it doesn't always turn out that way, says former Alaskan
crabber Spike Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The money is like an intoxicant, compelling you to take
ridiculous chances in the face of advancing storms that can bring
25-foot seas pushed by icy 50-mph Arctic winds, he'll tell you. In
short order, you can discover that the romanticized vision of the
Alaskan coast often turns out to be a nightmare: For a greenhorn
from the mainland who actually gets such a job, the odds of
clearing $75,000 in a few weeks are about the same as dying at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of this life, the fast money and the elemental
danger, are captured in the book ``Working on the Edge'' by Walker,
published by St. Martin's Press. I found this is one of the best
outdoor books written in the past 10 years, capturing both the
danger and greed that breathes through the pores of commercial
crabbers.
</P>
<P>
   The tales ring true, and along the way, you feel as if you are
aboard the boats, working shoulder to shoulder with the crabbers,
trying to get rich quick.
</P>
<P>
   The chance for big money is real, Walker says, having himself
fished crab on a commercial boat for several years, making $80,000
to $120,000 in the one-month king crab season just as a hand on a
boat. At the same time, he tells of a poster at a Seattle ferry
terminal that reads: ``If You Don't Already Have A Job In Alaska
... Don't Go!''
</P>
<P>
   This also rings true. A friend of mine recently headed up ``to
get a job on a crab boat and make a ton of money fast'' and after
six weeks of unemployment, finally got a job delivering pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Walker dedicates a section of the book to the big money fantasy
called ``The Greenhorn,'' and then, in turn, puts the reader on
board with a series of staggering encounters of men against the
sea. In the end, the number of deaths certify that commercial
crabbing off Alaska is the most dangerous job in the world: 42
deaths in 1988 alone. In a typical year, Walker writes that 15
percent of all crab boats fishing in Alaska are either ``destroyed,
sunk, salvaged or in some way repaired.''
</P>
<P>
   What Walker manages to do is weave his own encounters with those
of the survivors of several disasters. In one story, he describes
how ``reezing spray'' creates ice blocks on everything it touches,
and how ice can quickly build a foot or higher on the deck of the
boat. That can create so much weight that it can make the boat
top-heavy and capsize it in a big swell. The icing phenomenon is
verified in one photograph where the crab traps look like giant ice
cubes.
</P>
<P>
   In another story, the author describes how fortunes can turn in
seconds:
</P>
<P>
   ``On board the Gemini, the leaden layer of ice continued to
build, thickening to a depth of several feet. ... As the boat rose
sluggishly up and over a large wave, the bottom of the wave trough
directly ahead seemed just to fall out from under them. The ship
plummeted right down into it and the full weight of the next wave
collapsed upon them. With the sound of a rifle shot, the spinnaker
window exploded backward into wheelhouse. ... Soon after the
skipper's Mayday call went out, the boat's engines died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going down.''
</P>
<P>
   In that episode, it turns out, the crew was saved. In many
others, they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A young crewman named Keith Richards had placed himself
between a crab pot and the handrailing in an effort to untie a pot
when the deck rolled sharply. The stack shifted and a loose crab
pot slid into the youngster, knocking him overboard. Richards was
unable to save himself, completely immobile (from the freezing
ocean), like a sack of potatoes, and started to sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker describes the biggest boom years of the Alaskan crab
fishery, its collapse and then the rebuilding of the fishery that
has occurred since. Most of the book describes the boom years, and
even though now nearly 20 years removed, the stories are well
crafted and full of fire ... and it remains relevant to anybody
who's fantasized a bit about bailing out on life in the Lower 48 _
and heading to Alaska based on the dreams of easy money and
adventure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
