<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0519 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      03-08 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CHAT; DARVA DEFENSE; SPIN RE-SPUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With some pushing of nostalgia buttons, Rolling Stone for March
16 chitchats about pop culture and the 1960s with Al Gore. The
interview, conducted by Jann Wenner and Will Dana, would be more
interesting if it turned out that Gore absolutely hated Bob Dylan,
but of course he worships Dylan, prefers the electric ``Highway 61
Revisited'' days, and even manages to quote from ``Blowing in the
Wind'' and warble out lyrics from ``Just Like a Woman'' before the
tape recorder has been shut off. The VP also fancies Bonnie Raitt,
John Mayall, and k.d. lang, just in case you're trying to envision
an all-star Gore inaugural event.
</P>
<P>
   The authors tell us Gore ``is neither wooden nor robotic'' but
``enjoys a hard-won sense of casualness,'' and the photos
accompanying the story are also meant to counteract the stiff rap.
Here's a mellow Al and Tipper afloat in a Native American-styled
canoe in 1973, he the sideburned dude manning the paddle, she his
Guinevere, lounging in a peasant shirt and bead necklace with what
could be a euphoric smile on her face. Here are the newlyweds
gazing at each other amid the hay of the Gore family farm in 1970,
Tipper looking rather mod in her Carnaby Street sunglasses. And
here's a literary-looking Al as a reporter in 1971, pensive, his
hands poised on the keys of his typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says the 1960s helped shape his commitment to civil rights,
equal rights, and human rights, but they don't seem to have
determined his views on pot. ``I think that drawing a hard line
against marijuana use is the right thing to do,'' he says, in the
context of the fact that he does not favor decriminalization. About
youth violence, Gore puts gun availability and the need for
emotional support systems higher on his list of contributing causes
than violent imagery in entertainment. And he says he plans to
raise environmental issues more, as the campaign proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't resist the cover lines on this week's People, which
has Madonna pronouncing, ``I'm going to be the mother I never
had.'' Mother, indeed. The story gives up all the details about her
non-spoiling approach to parenting, her decision to name daughter
Lourdes after the French town her mother wanted to visit before she
died, her continuing friendship with Carlos Leon, Lourdes's father,
and her love affair with filmmaker Guy Ritchie. Using her best
British inflection, she notes, ``Being in love, being loved keeps
you young. True, that.'' Pretentious, she.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, we may be heading toward adding yet another name to
the list of celebrities who are recognizable by first name only,
like Arnold, or Barbra. I'm speaking of Darva, of course, the
now-ubiquitous nurse who felt she might want to marry a
multimillionaire and is living to regret it. People has a
first-person story in which Conger passionately defends herself
against all the people who think of her as a gold digger and a
spiritual cousin to Linda Tripp. Basically, she thought going on
the show would be fun after a rough year. ``The possibility that he
was a multimillionaire didn't appeal to me,'' she says. ``Actually
it was sort of a negative. Because money doesn't buy everything in
this world.'' She reminds us that we shouldn't see her as a ``moral
compass,'' and she puts herself into a larger cultural perspective:
``What I did here didn't hurt anybody, I didn't kill anybody. I
didn't do bad things with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spin for April is a special issue in honor of the magazine's
15th anniversary. That means pages upon pages of old Spin article
excerpts on the rise of ``alternative'' music, including the old
Nirvana stories and the wacky wisdom of Courtney Love, who is shown
curtseying in one of her famous kinderwhore dresses; on the murder
of Tupac Shakur; on the advent of Beck; on the reports of violence
at Woodstock '99; on the spreading of AIDS; and so on and so forth.
It's not a bad issue necessarily _ the photos of object-icons like
Slash's top hat, Flavor Flav's clock, and Kurt Cobain's shirt from
the ``Smells Like Teen Spirit'' video are a little witty. But,
coming so close on the heels of the world's recent orgy of
decade-century-millennium views and reviews, it's a rather
redundant retrospective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
