<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUBERCULOSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TB IS SAN FRANCISCO'S OTHER DEADLY DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOCUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My interest in tuberculosis originated in
childhood, when my father had TB and was put in a sanitarium for
nine months. I remember waving through a window at a pale-skinned
man in a bathrobe and feeling frightened, lost and lonely.
</P>
<P>
   Illness is a great divider.
</P>
<P>
   My dad survived. I'm not sure I did. Mycobacterium tuberculosis
haunts me to this day. I imagine it lurking beneath my skin,
waiting for an opportunity to blossom into a horrid, devouring
ailment.
</P>
<P>
   TB is an important public-health issue in San Francisco because
the city _ a perennial magnet for immigrants and one of the world's
most densely populated places _ always has been tuberculosis
country.
</P>
<P>
   The number of new TB cases in San Francisco has dropped from the
early 1990s, when it peaked at 356 (in 1993), but it remains high:
4.5 times the national rate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Masae Kawamura, director of the health department's TB
control program, said, ``There are pockets of TB in our city where
the case rates are as high as Africa. As a whole, San Francisco's
rates are as high as Mexico's, 35 per 100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawamura said the Tenderloin, South of Market and Chinatown
neighborhoods are the ``pockets'' that concern her, along with the
city's homeless shelters and transient hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean it's dangerous for a healthy person to go there?
No, Kawamura said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come from a risk group where the incidence is high or
if you work with high-risk groups, you need to be tested, but TB is
not that easy to catch. The probability of getting TB from one
cough or one sneeze is very low,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be appropriate, nonetheless, that on Friday, March 24 _
the 118th anniversary of TB discoverer Robert Koch's presentation
of his findings in Berlin _ San Franciscans make a special effort
to observe World TB Day, sponsored by the World Health Organization
(WHO).
</P>
<P>
   Its purpose is to heighten awareness of the disease, which has
infected an estimated 2 billion people worldwide, according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the epidemic has taken on a new dimension with
the emergence of drug-resistant strains of TB, often the
consequence of failure to complete the standard six-month course of
drug therapy. Multidrug-resistant TB is fatal 60 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   This year WHO is pushing for World TB Day tie-ins with women's
groups, human rights groups and HIV/AIDS groups, which it calls the
``new TB constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   TB is the single biggest infectious killer of women in the
world, with about 1 billion females infected, according to WHO. Of
the estimated 2.1 million people who die annually from TB, WHO
says, a disproportionate number are women in their reproductive
years. TB takes their lives at more than twice the rate of war and
three times the rate of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Human-rights groups? They advocate for the masses of mistreated
people throughout the world _ the same people whose living
conditions, including
</P>
<P>
   homelessness and poverty, foster the spread of TB.
</P>
<P>
   But what about HIV/AIDS groups? Where do they fit in?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that one of every three AIDS-related deaths
is directly caused by TB. When AIDS came along, TB discovered a
partner in crimes against humanity. There is nothing more likely
than HIV to turn a dormant TB cell into an active one, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 million to 15 million Americans infected with TB
alone, an estimated 10 percent will develop active cases. For
people with HIV and TB infection, however, the risk of developing
active TB cases is 100 times greater.
</P>
<P>
   Groups working with AIDS patients are aware of the association.
Joel Rubinstein, a volunteer with Project Open Hand and the
citizens' lobby RESULTS, said he was required to take a TB test
before he was permitted to go into the homes of people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have it come out negative,`` Rubinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the San Francisco Bay, a 45-agency public and private TB
task force will make a presentation to the Alameda County Board of
Supervisors on March 21, in conjunction with World TB Day.
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, San Francisco health officials will hold a news
conference at the gates of Chinatown to announce a new outreach
program targeting TB in the Chinese community.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign-born Chinese have inactive cases of TB acquired
abroad, Kawamura said, that could become activated by the stresses
of life in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the initiative,'' Kawamura said, ``is to get
people
</P>
<P>
   screened and treated before they become reactivated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
