<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HMO-PEROT-BOS &LR;      03-08 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-PEROT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONAIRE, HMO EYE REVOLUTIONARY INTERNET-BASED SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Harvard Pilgrim Health Care sent out a distress call to
private investors in January, all who took a look at the HMO's
large losses walked away, except one: H. Ross Perot, who was
willing to risk $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Texas billionaire, silent during the
negotiations to pull Harvard Pilgrim out of state receivership,
told The Boston Globe this week that his offer, while ultimately
rejected by state regulators, was not just about helping to right
Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   It was about creating a whole new kind of HMO that could be
marketed around the nation _ and make him more millions.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's Dallas company, Perot Systems, which already has a
10-year, $700 million computer consulting contract with Harvard
Pilgrim, is negotiating a second contract with it to create an
Internet-based ``HMO of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim plans in April to unveil the first stage: a Web
site that will allow employers and employees to enroll online.
</P>
<P>
   Perot envisions a system where hospitals, doctors, employers,
members, and the HMO will by the end of 2001 be able to log on and
update patient accounts. Harvard Pilgrim would wire payments
directly to providers. Sources involved in the negotiations
estimate the cost at less than $20 million, which the HMO and Perot
will split.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have all these genius doctors practicing in all these
elite hospitals,'' Perot said from Dallas. ``What better place to
create a model for how medicine should be practiced in the 21st
century?''
</P>
<P>
   The one-time presidential candidate, who is used to negotiating
with straight-talking ranchers and cattlemen, said he hugely
admires Harvard Pilgrim CEO Charles D. Baker Jr., from whom he got
honest answers.
</P>
<P>
   Perot said it wouldn't have been appropriate to unveil plans for
the new system, called ``Healthbank,'' during the past two months.
But now that state regulators are asking the court to release
Harvard Pilgrim from receivership, the time may be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Charlie is ready to go, we'll go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said his first mission is to implement Harvard Pilgrim's
2000 turnaround plan, then to work toward a model HMO system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every health plan needs to figure this out,'' he said. ``The
amount of time and energy and effort that's spent dealing with all
these different administrative records could be devoted to
improving health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe working with Mr. Perot gives us an opportunity to
develop an Internet-based communication tool that could take a lot
of the administrative headaches out of health care for members, our
employers, and our providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot and Baker first got together in October, when Harvard
Pilgrim agreed to pay Perot Systems $700 million over 10 years to
oversee its claims and technology systems _ whose problems are
partly blamed for the HMO's $200 million loss last year.
</P>
<P>
   But when state regulators took over on Jan. 4, Perot got a
scare. He flew to Boston three days later to reassure his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Protecting you in Boston is a lot easier than trying
to rescue you from Tehran,' '' said Perot, referring to the time he
orchestrated a rescue of an employee jailed in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   During the second week in February, Perot came to Boston to
discuss another rescue mission: the regulators' search for
investors to bail out Harvard Pilgrim. They met in an
out-of-the-way conference room in a Boston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Like other potential investors, Perot asked that the state back
his $75 million investment _ $15 million more than he personally
spent on his 1992 presidential campaign _ in case Harvard Pilgrim
ultimately failed.
</P>
<P>
   Special Assistant Attorney General J. David Leslie traveled to
Dallas to make a counteroffer: Could Perot guarantee $75 million in
investments that regulators hoped to elicit from hospitals?
</P>
<P>
   Perot agreed.
</P>
<P>
   And as Massachusetts regulators requested, Perot kept the
proposal a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that impressed me with all of them was that they are
totally focused on making sure they preserve this precious thing
they have in Boston,'' Perot said. ``It's like a Faberge egg. You
don't want to drop it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly rejected Perot's
offer because the billioniare businessman wanted to ``assert
significant control'' over Harvard Pilgrim if it did not meet
financial goals and to extend the computer contract.
</P>
<P>
   Perot said he does not know the details of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he's familar with the vision behind them _ a
vision he believes can be achieved only in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is like a four-legged stool,'' said Perot, who often
uses the words Boston and geniuses in the same sentence. ``You've
got a nonprofit HMO that is focused on patient care, the finest
medical school in the country, world-class hospitals, and genius
doctors. Other places in the country, there is always a piece
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   He dodged a question about whether doctors are smarter in Boston
than in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's bigger in Texas,'' he said. ``If I go to a
hospital in Texas at least they speak Texan.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot, who pays for all of his family's health care in cash,
said the problem with the system is that each doctor's office,
hospital, employer, and insurance company is like a distant island
separated by sea, when they should be connected by software
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospital staff are still carrying around clipboards and
baskets of papers,'' he said. ``All that can be stored on computer.
Now we come to things like X-rays carried around because doctors
like to see film. But with digital technology even soft tissue can
be clearly seen on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time someone enters a patient's Social Security number or
birthdate, it increases the chances of an error _ and the chances
that the HMO's system won't recognize its own patients.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hughes, head of the Massachusetts Association of HMOs,
said the type of system Perot proposes is ``where we're going'' if
obstacles can be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is will there be triggers to make sure
people's privacy is protected?'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technical point of view, it's very doable. But it's
going to take a great deal of thrashing about in terms of
developing standards and privacy controls.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Perot was lampooned often for television
ads that featured him holding a wooden pointer in front of a chart
of the rising national debt. Even during a phone interview, he
spoke of bell curves and graphs.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he said, it will be a matter of convincing the
various constituencies he and Baker are onto something. ``The
problem is getting all of the groups deciding to do it,'' he said.
``Certainly if someone brings you a new idea then you would want to
see proof. But I'd really be surprised if they weren't on fire when
they hear about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
