<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIO'S OK, BUT GOAL'S AN ILLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is our current savings rate enough for retirement by age 60
and college for two? Are we being too conservative? Should we
invest in individual stocks? Do we have enough diversity? How much
should we be saving monthly?
</P>
<P>
   H.S., Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let me back into it, please. Suppose you calculate that you
could retire comfortably on the equivalent of $80,000 in today's
money. In 25 years, you would need $189,059 a year, if inflation
averages 3.5 percent a year until then. I bet you see where I am
going: You won't even come close.
</P>
<P>
   If you continue to add $500 a month to your savings for 25 years
and achieve 10 percent average portfolio returns, you would
accumulate $1,259,563 _ which would be depleted in less than nine
years if you maintain a standard of living equivalent to what
$80,000 in today's money buys. And presuming 10 percent growth is
probably unrealistic, in view of the fact that nearly 18 percent of
your current savings are in CDs and bank savings. And missing from
that calculation is the cost of college for your children.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has little to do with the portfolio's makeup; it's
simply that you're not saving enough money. That $500 a month is
just 6 percent of your income; simply stated, it's not enough,
especially since it seems that you have no prospect of a pension.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to triple your savings rate, the projection would be
a little less than $2.5 million, which might get you into the
ballpark, if Social Security is still around at that point. But
even then, chances are that you would look at the likely effect of
inflation once you reach age 60 and decide to keep working another
five years. Then, the accumulation would exceed $4.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   So the important thing is save a higher percentage _ and to
maintain that percentage whenever your income rises _ so you can
boost your accumulation beyond the projections I have made.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to look at specific accounts:
</P>
<P>
   All of your savings go into taxable accounts, which is likely to
generate significant tax liabilities as you near retirement. I
suggest that you immediately direct $2,000 a year for each of you
into Roth IRA accounts, and keep up that pace. If either of you has
access to a 401(k) plan, a deferred savings plan, a Keogh, or any
other vehicle that will defer taxes on your retirement savings, you
should explore these vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, you're risking too much by putting the largest
segment of your savings into the Munder NetNet fund. This vehicle,
which buys Internet-related securities, is quite risky, and
probably ill-attuned to long-term savings. Of this fund,
Morningstar Mutual Funds says: ``Eye-popping short-term results are
possible, as are big losses. Handle with care.'' This is a
speculative investment, appropriate for only a tiny percentage of a
retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   If you must contribute to this fund, I suggest you limit your
ongoing purchases to about $25 or $50 a month, focusing instead on
the more stable and proven Contrafund and, to a lesser extent,
Safeco Growth. I know results such as NetNets' 175.7 percent gain
for 1999 and its 32.09 percent year-to-date advance are dazzling,
but those kinds of bubbles pop very quickly. My suggestion would be
$400 a month to Contrafund and $100 to Safeco Growth. Let the
NetNet bet ride, but don't add to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I have been saving and investing all our lives,
hoping we will have enough to last us through our lives. Each of
the three segments of our portfolio, listed above, provides about a
third of our income (with pensions and such combining to bring the
income from the final segment up to a third). I plan to invest any
funds that come from the maturing or calling of individual bonds in
the bond fund. I do not feel it is wise to invest in the stock
market, due to our ages and limited knowledge of the market. I know
we are not diversified, but feel somewhat safe. Your thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   C.P., El Cajon, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if you rode out the municipal bond market of the last
year with tranquility, I guess you have the temperament to rely so
heavily on one market segment. Yes, by and large municipal bonds
are safe, and their only drawback is their capacity to lose market
value when interest rates rise. But they also gain in value when
rates fall _ and in the end, a good municipal bond portfolio should
be pretty stable, delivering a steady tax-free income stream in the
meantime. In the last 12 months, the median California municipal
bond fund had a negative total return of 3.5 percent, but it's
reasonable to presume the worm will eventually turn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'd look for a little more diversification, which you
could achieve by putting the proceeds from maturing bonds or
recalls of bonds into something like five-year CDs, which offer
pretty attractive rates (see the letter below). Of course, if you
are in an overall tax situation which would mean that you would
have less income after paying the taxes on the CD income, that
would be a mistake. And I agree with you about the stock market:
It's no place for a fellow of your age who is uncertain about his
understanding of equities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have no income, aside from my investments, and I collect no
pension. My wife is employed, but her $25,000 salary is barely
making it. I plan to start withdrawing from my 401(k) at age 60.
Where can I get a better return on my 401(k)? Can I withdraw from
the 401(k) without a penalty? Can my 401(k) be rolled over into
another account, such as an IRA?
</P>
<P>
   A.B., Monroe, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer is a fairly traditional and simple one: Buy CDs.
If all of your funds were put into five-year CDs, you could earn as
much as 7.59 percent, citing the highest five-year rate available
as this is written. That would bring you $24,288 a year _ just a
bit more than what you require. It would also require that you do a
lot of shopping around, since CD rates vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   You would be able to roll over the 401(k) money into an IRA
without penalty, although you would face the tax liability on your
withdrawals as they are made.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially important that you get out of your tax-free
bond holding, since I suspect that you are not in a sufficiently
high tax bracket to benefit from its tax-exempt feature. You would
probably be considerably better off taking the higher yield from
the CD and paying the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When the impending takeover of NEES is completed,
stockholders will receive a set amount for their shares. My shares
were acquired through dividend reinvestment over 25 years. Each
year I paid taxes on the amount the shares increased. When I
receive the buyout check, how do I compute the taxes due?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Shrewsbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The critical figure in determining your capital gain is
called base cost. Your base cost consists of your original
investment (including any brokerage fees), plus the dollar amount
of all of those dividend reinvestments, plus the dollar amount of
any additional cash investments you may have paid into the DRIP.
Then, subtract your base cost from the amount you receive from the
buyout to determine your capital gain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
