<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GOLDMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLDMAN STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes 10 favorite films list.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Goldman long ago earned a place in Hollywood
history, thanks to a trio of three-word sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't swim,'' Robert Redford tells Paul Newman in ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (1969). Moviegoers roared, and
Goldman took home his first Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow the money,'' Hal Holbrook's Deep Throat tells Redford's
Bob Woodward in ``All the President's Men'' (1976). Moviegoers
shuddered, many of them voted for Jimmy Carter (Ronald Reagan, for
one, ascribed Gerald Ford's defeat to the movie's success), and
Goldman had another Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   The third sentence, not nearly as well known, won Goldman no
Oscars. Yet among insiders, it is, if anything, even more
cherished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows anything,'' Goldman wrote in his best-selling
``Adventures in the Screen Trade'' (1983), revealing the movie
industry's deepest, darkest secret, that it's all just one big
crapshoot and they don't know why hits succeed and flops don't any
more than you or I do. Readers (or at least the ones who were movie
executives) couldn't decide whether to laugh, shudder, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, 68, has just published what any self-respecting studio
would have called ``Adventures II,'' but whose actual title is
``Which Lie Did I Tell?: More Adventures in the Screen Trade.''
Like its predecessor, ``Lie'' is a shrewd and beguiling blend of
Hollywood war stories, screenwriting shoptalk, and (the closest
thing Goldman has to a trademark as a writer) unstinting joie de
vivre.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of ``Lie'' extends what has been a Goldman hot
streak. In November he published ``The Big Picture,'' a collection
of articles on the industry he's written for New York and Premiere
magazines over the past decade. He shares the writing credit on
``The General's Daughter,'', which grossed more than $100 million
last year. And 1998 saw publication of a 25th anniversary edition
of ``The Princess Bride.'' ``Princess'' is Goldman's favorite among
his 16 novels, which include such best sellers as ``Marathon Man''
(1974) and ``Magic'' (1976), both of which, like ``Bride,'' Goldman
later adapted for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes you see the movie,'' says screenwriter Tony Gilroy,
who wrote ``The Devil's Advocate'' and ``Armageddon,'' and has
known Goldman for 30 years. ``He's fast, he's fertile, he's
versatile. . . . Who's working now who has more produced credits?
And then, to have credits that go back to `Masquerade' (1965,
Goldman's first screenwriting credit)? He's in the hall of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, who received the Writers Guild of America's Laurel
Award for Achievement in 1983, is a hall of famer with a
difference. In his longevity, as in his savvy and professionalism,
he's a descendant of such screenwriting legends as Ben Hecht and
Ernest Lehman. Yet unlike them, or his contemporary and fellow
grand master, Robert Towne, he's never directed or produced. He
also remains extremely active.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's current project is an adaptation of Stephen King's
``Hearts in Atlantis'' for Castle Rock Entertainment. The hope is
for a success comparable to his previous King adaptation for Castle
Rock, ``Misery,'' in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few screenwriters who stand out as people who have
done the job again and again,`` King says. ``Of that bunch, William
Goldman is clearly the star on top of the screenwriting Christmas
tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman in person very much resembles Goldman on the page:
animated, alert, effervescent. The strongest impression he conveys
is of a man of enormous enthusiasm. Get him going on one of his
passions _ the New York Knicks, say (he's a season ticketholder of
long standing), or the merits of his favorite movie, the 1939
classic ``Gunga Din'' _ and Goldman's like a teenager on a first
date. ``I don't feel like an elder statesman,'' he says with equal
parts pride and chagrin. ``I'm very immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it immaturity, or call it a sense of wonder. But it's an
essential ingredient for succeeding at movie make-believe. When the
lights go down, Goldman reaches for his popcorn just like anybody
else. ``When I go to a movie,'' he says, ``I want to love it. I
just saw `Toy Story 2.' It's terrific. When it's over, you say,
goddam, I'm glad I spent that 90 minutes. I'll remember a lot of
that movie. That's all we're doing: making memories for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman began his moviegoing in the Chicago suburb of Highland
Park, Ill., at the Alcyon Theater, which is where he saw ``Gunga
Din'' (he's seen it 15 times since). Show business got into his
blood early. He claims to have started reading Variety when he was
10. John Kander, the future composer of ``Cabaret'' and ``New York,
New York,'' was a boyhood chum. The two remain friends and, with
Goldman's older brother, James, collaborated on a failed Broadway
musical in 1962. (The elder Goldman, who died in 1968, won his
screenwriting Oscar for adapting his play, ``The Lion in Winter,''
the year before his brother won for ``Butch Cassidy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's writing career got off to a slow start. He likes to
joke that, despite being editor of the Oberlin College literary
magazine, he still couldn't get it to publish any of his stories.
He got the only C in his creative writing class, and his favorite
short story was rejected 69 times.
</P>
<P>
   He served two years in the Army, doing clerical work in the
Pentagon, then earned a master's degree at Columbia University. Not
interested in teaching, Goldman decided it was up or out on being a
writer. It took him all of 10 days to write his first novel, ``The
Temple of Gold,'' which a publisher promptly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, who'd resigned himself to going back to Chicago to
become an advertising copywriter, never looked back. Over the next
seven years, he published three more novels and collaborated on two
plays. He also married Ilene Jones. The couple, who have two
daughters, divorced in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman owes his screenwriting career to a case of mistaken
literary identity. He gave his fifth novel, ``No Way to Treat a
Lady,'' an unorthodox layout, with some chapters consisting of only
a single sentence. The actor Cliff Robertson saw a copy and thought
it was a film treatment. Impressed, he asked Goldman to do a short
story adaptation and later got him his first screen credit, for
``Masquerade.'' This led to ``Harper'' (1966), Goldman's first
unshared screen credit. Three years later, he sold ``Butch
Cassidy'' for a then-record $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman figures on a screenplay taking him six months from start
to finish. ``When I'm actually starting a movie,'' he explains,
``it's insane not to be able to write three pages a day. That's not
a lot _ there's a lot of space on a movie script page. If you do
that every day for 21 days, guess what, you've got half a movie.
The writing for me is never the hard part. The hard part is the
thinking. . . . When I say it takes me six months to do a movie, I
don't mean I'm writing for six months. I'm writing for a month. The
rest of it is research, trying to figure story, blah blah blah
blah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blah blah blah blah''? Full of himself Goldman is not. ``What
makes Bill great,'' King says, ``is he's a serious-minded person
who's kept his sense of humor.'' The one thing he brags about is
that he's missed just one screenwriting deadline in 35 years (``I
was two weeks late,'' he notes, ``but I got the next draft in two
weeks early''). Certainly, he has few illusions about the
arbitrariness of his profession. ``If (Michael) Douglas and (Val)
Kilmer had been in `Butch Cassidy' instead of Redford and Newman,
you would not remotely be listening to anything I might have to say
about Hollywood,'' he writes in ``Which Lie Did I Tell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's had too many flops to believe otherwise. His name was
on three movies released in 1992 _ ``The Year of the Comet,''
``Memoirs of an Invisible Man,'' and ``Chaplin'' _ a good year only
for productivity. Assignments he has turned down include ``The
Graduate,'' ``The Godfather,'' and ``Superman.'' Only one scene
from his script for ``The Right Stuff'' made the final cut _ and
for ``Papillon'' it was only one word. He also went through a
``leper'' period in the early '80s, with no screenwriting jobs for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
