<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-GOLDMAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     03-08 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GOLDMAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... five years.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a strange craft,'' Goldman says. ``If you're in books,
you tend to have a great deal of control. In the movies you have
none, but nobody gets what they want in the movies. In this ghastly
era of deifying directors, you assume the director gets what he
wants. But I don't think even Steven Spielberg gets what he wants.
Everybody's subject to budget, weather, crazy and difficult actors,
your own limitations. Everything's a compromise, I think, in
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, screenwriting is a recipe for frustration. Goldman's
way to protect against its becoming worse than that has been
twofold. He's long lived on Manhattan's Upper East Side, 3,000
miles, three time zones, and multiple states of mind away from LA.
The other defense is not to consider himself a screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a 30-year career as a novelist and in my head that's
what I am. But it's getting harder and harder to justify that. In
the last few years, I've started writing a lot of nonfiction books
and that's an attempt, I suppose, to do something else but movies.
I wrote in `Adventures in the Screen Trade,' `If you're going to be
a screenwriter, you must do something else or you'll go mad.' I
still believe that. It's like being a dentist: It's got a lot of
pluses but also a lot of minuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Marathon Man,'' in which a dental drill famously
ends up in the hands of a Nazi war criminal (played in the movie by
Sir Laurence Olivier), knows a thing or two about filling cavities.
He knows even more about screenwriting, though, and confesses
amazement at how interested the rest of the world has become in his
craft since ``Adventures in the Screen Trade'' was published 17
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The screenwriting interest then, which was phenomenal compared
to when I was a kid, is nothing now to compared to what's happened
in the past 20 years. When I was a kid, you wanted to write the
Great American Novel or you wanted to be (Eugene) O'Neill and write
the great Broadway play. That's over. I don't think anybody who's
18 and wants to write wants to do that. It's screenplays, or maybe
something for the Internet (that I don't know about). Those things
have changed so terribly. Movies are now the center of our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's as screenwriter, novelist, or journalist, Goldman
still sees himself facing the same problem. ``I'm terrified of
boring people,'' he says. ``I'm terrified you'll stop reading, I'm
terrified you'll stop looking. I'm no more confident (now) than
when I started out. Probably less. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I've been incredibly lucky. I never thought I'd be
here. I never thought I would be writing after 45 years. I never
thought I would have a career. I never thought I would be
successful. I still think I'm in on a pass. When I was a kid, I
wrote once that I came to battle with only two things: a sense of
story and an ear for dialogue. That's all I've ever had. . . . I
wish everything I've written was better, but I've never phoned it
in. I've always tried. What doesn't work is owing to my own
inability.''
</P>
<P>
   William Goldman doesn't have a particularly high opinion of the
movies Hollywood produced during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My list of the 10 best pictures of the decade doesn't have 10
pictures on it,'' he says, laughing, ``and only `Unforgiven' won
(the Oscar for) Best Picture!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOLDMAN'S FAVORITE '90S FILMS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Babe'' (1995) &QL; 
``Fargo'' (1996) &QL; 
``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' (1994) &QL; 
``Hoop Dreams'' (1994) &QL; 
``The Shawshank Redemption'' (1994) &QL; 
``Unforgiven'' (1992) &QL; 
``What's Eating Gilbert Grape?'' (1993) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
