<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD-FIGHT SHOWDOWN AT THE USDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he edited the American Mercury in the 1930s, H. L. Mencken
loved to invite doctors, primarily from the burgeoning field of
psychiatry, to contribute articles to his magazine. He was
especially delighted, for instance, when Dr. Henry Cotton wrote a
long article demonstrating that infected teeth and tonsils caused
80 percent of mental illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken loved the medicine men because they could always be
relied on to promote outlandish, mutually contradictory theories
buttressed by rock-solid scientific ``findings.''
</P>
<P>
   One so missed Mencken at last month's Great Nutrition Debate,
held at the US Department of Agriculture. All of the grand shamans
of modern nutrition and diet theory were present: Dr. Robert Atkins
of diet ``revolution'' fame; Marblehead's own Barry Sears, inventor
of The Zone; Dr. Morrison Bethea, the thoracic surgeon who
coauthored ``Sugar Busters!''; and Dr. Dean Ornish (``Eat More,
Weigh Less''), whose primary claim to legitimacy seems to be that
he has appeared on public television.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken would not have been disappointed. These educated men of
science offloaded much silliness during their three hours together.
Bethea said that carrots were too fattening. Sears called food
``the most powerful drug anyone will ever encounter.'' The
assembled cynical hucksters _ Ornish noted that his dieters enjoy
better sex _ felt comfortable denouncing Atkins as a cynical
huckster. Well, maybe, but he has 10 million books in the stores.
Let them throw tomatoes!
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes and other fruit, of course, do not figure large in
Atkins's diet revolution. His ``pork rinds and sausages diet'' is
ridiculed because he allows adherents to chomp down on fatty
snacks, as long as they are low-carb. The venerable, if not
venerated, 69-year-old Atkins managed to survive the food fight
without even playing his trump card: Al Gore is on his diet! (Gore,
who does not campaign on a bus called the Straight Talk Express,
denies this.) Sure, studies reveal that low-carb dieters suffer
from constipation, bad breath, body odor, and headaches . . . who
cares? Tipper's not complaining, and in those loose suits and those
earth-tone colors, Al's looking great!
</P>
<P>
   Sears, a PhD biochemist and pointedly not ``Dr. Sears'' to some
panel members, followed Atkins with his Zone defense. He even
offered up his ``Zone pyramid,'' which will probably not replace
the USDA's own ``pyramid'' of healthy foods anytime soon. Then the
sugar guy weighed in, followed by some lesser lights who offered
common-sense advice like ``you have to burn more calories than you
eat.'' They were duly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Comes now Dr. John McDougall, a veggie diet author who runs a
fat farm in California's Napa Valley. He dared to call the Atkins,
Sears, and Sugar Busters diets the ``make yourself sick diets.''
``You can't stay on these diets forever, because you can't stay
sick or hungry forever,'' he said, to the evident delight of the
crowded auditorium. Furthermore, he dared to praise the humble
potato as an efficient source of nutrition, and he reminded the
audience that consumers of the starch-based Asian and Mediterranean
diets look pretty good in bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   You can download the debate from the ``video highlights'' on the
USDA Web site, www.usda.gov, or send away for the $20 video from
vidtrans(at)erols.com. Alex's handy watching tip: Fast-forward to
the 2 1/2-hour mark, because that's when the real action begins.
Atkins trots out a Rent-a-Doc who announces some astonishingly
inconclusive ``research'' results about the diet revolution. Soon
afterwards, Ornish blasts the ``toxic'' diets of Atkins and Sears.
``I am not aware of any studies that Dr. Atkins or Dr. Sears have
published in any peer-reviewed journal, about anything, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Sears points out that two of the subjects of a vaunted
Ornish study died of heart attacks _ whose diet is toxic now, Mr.
Smart Guy? Somewhere, Mencken is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
