<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VICTORY IN DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In San Francisco, no person is an island, not
even a member of that smallest of local identity groups, persons of
Republicanism.
</P>
<P>
   My conspiracy to undo George W. Bush by registering Republican
not only failed miserably on Tuesday, but I was outed as a fake
Republican in the worst of all possible places _ a gun store.
</P>
<P>
   I was in Marin County, the beautiful landscape God created to
hold up the other end of the Golden Gate Bridge, finding a gun
dealer so I could get a couple of my family's antique guns moved
from Massachusetts to California for use as decor statements to
stimulate conversation with Bambi huggers.
</P>
<P>
   A woman with a .25 caliber semiautomatic in her hand said, ``You
look familiar. Aren't you the Democratic columnist who became a
Republican to mess us up?''
</P>
<P>
   I did some fast talking, and she turned out to be a very nice
woman who politely gave me a lecture about my responsibilities as a
journalist and a citizen. She also told me how hard it is to be a
pro-gun Republican in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invite my Democratic neighbors to dinner, and pretty soon
they aren't talking,'' she said. ``So I just feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing. Most Republicans and most gun owners are
terrific people, but in San Francisco and surrounding counties
they're often treated like subhumans.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't often you'll find a columnist conceding he made
mistakes, but I shouldn't have joined a political party just to
throw a monkey wrench into its works.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not just saying that because there's a lady with a Colt
who knows what I look like.
</P>
<P>
   No person is an island, not even a guy who can write pretty much
whatever he wants down the length of a newspaper page.
</P>
<P>
   I gained nothing from abandoning my lifelong love-hate
relationship with the Democratic Party but a couple of cheap
columns and the ability to make conversation with my conservative
cousin Sally by telling her I'd registered Republican.
</P>
<P>
   She thought I'd finally matured, but I hadn't. I was just
playing games.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the primary in California is over, I feel like my
close-mouthed New England parents, who never would tell me who they
voted for, even though I knew perfectly well it wasn't Barry
Goldwater or Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   No, I won't say who I voted for, except he beat Bush in San
Francisco but lost nationally _ and before his near-concession
speech told Maria Shriver, the wife of the Terminator, to get out
of his way.
</P>
<P>
   In the island-nation of San Francisco, we love gutsy and
slightly crazy losing causes, but don't push me on why I voted for
such a conservative one.
</P>
<P>
   It was for all the wrong reasons, and it was time to get back to
the liberal fantasy island.
</P>
<P>
   There I was listening to the millions of therms of natural gas
released by politicians and pundits on CNN and MSNBC. San Francisco
Mayor Willie Brown was talking about how he's spent thousands on
his wardrobe, and Al Gore has outdone him with a lousy earth-tone
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   That's our island mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Republican analyst Mary Matalin was talking about independents
and Democrats who voted for McCain, and said, ``They weren't
crossovers. They were cross-dressers.''
</P>
<P>
   I assume this wasn't a homophobic joke, but a reference to
wolves in sheep drag. Still, her use of ``cross-dresser'' as a
negative word made me realize how different it is inside the
Beltway vs. inside the isle of Yerba Buena.
</P>
<P>
   I headed immediately for the ``victory party'' of the No on
Knight campaign, the group that organized to fight state Sen.
William ``Pete'' Knight's Proposition 22, which would forbid the
legal recognition of gay and lesbian marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The No on Knight campaign got its butt kicked, but that never
shut down a good victory party in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While Knight and his friends whooped it up in a Sacramento hotel
room, the Green Room at the War Memorial Building rocked with a DJ
playing Aretha Franklin and gay leaders giving some of the best
we-didn't-really-lose speeches I've ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   No on Knight chairman Mike Marshall and San Francisco Supervisor
Mark Leno both made the point that the pro-Knight people were
careful not to bash gays, but recognized their humanity _ all
except their human urge to marry.
</P>
<P>
   This represents progress since the blatantly gay-baiting Briggs
Initiative of 1978. As Leno told me, ``It's a whole new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is. Five potential San Francisco mayors _ Leno, Kevin
Shelley, Carole Migden, Tom Ammiano and Susan Leal _ circulated
through the party celebrating a campaign against the Knight
initiative that raised $6 million, brought positive attention to
gay families and won the endorsement of almost every newspaper in
California.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing surprising about politicians on this island
supporting gay causes. The TVs in the Green Room were what opened
my eyes. Before the returns came in, they were tuned to ``Will and
Grace,'' an NBC television show about gays and the straights who
love them.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me there would be such a sitcom without Harvey Milk. Yes,
San Francisco is an island, but like Great Britain its influence is
disproportionate to its size. And we're democrats who love our
monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
