NYT-03-08-00 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0536 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA09-COX     03-08 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where the cowboys go to pray
 &HT;    by Rebecca McEntee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASTROP, Texas _ Way out in the sticks, down a long Highway 20
lined with oaks and empty fields, you take a right on Pleasant
Chapel Road. Before long, there's Walnut Creek Ranch and riding
arena, with a companion pavilion furnished with old church pews and
chairs. People come here to rodeo or rope on Tuesdays, Thursdays
and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, it's Cowboy Church.
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning, it was in the 30s. The faithful arrived
wrapped in blankets and ponchos, carrying hot dishes filled with
everything from beans and cornbread to raspberry cobbler. Everyone
knew Rusty Edwards, the owner of Walnut Creek Ranch, had been
cooking barbecue since the night before at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dishes went straight onto the stove in the middle of
the pavilion, where the coldest parishioners huddled. There's an
outhouse, horses and donkeys behind the fences, a collection of
horse trailers and a red canvas strung across the back of the
pavilion to block the wind. Smoke rose from the huge pot-bellied
stove, and children munched on doughnuts as they played.
</P>
<P>
   This church started when Pastor Bill Pearson of Manor, his wife
Audrey, and a few others used to pray before penning cattle out at
the ranch years ago, in an old shack used as a cafe (where you can
still get burgers and chicken-fried steak) steadily grew into the
100-member parish that's here today.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 30 other Cowboy Churches around the state,
and dozens more across the country, according to Christian Cowboy
magazine. Pearson says the interdenominational Penning for Jesus
Cowboy Church, Inc. is different from the rest. He doesn't know
why, but God just lets them come together each in their different
ways. For instance, he says, there are no set guidelines to operate
the different fellowships.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pastor Bill's white horse trailer _ with ``Penning for
Jesus'' painted on the side and ``Have Bible Will Travel'' on the
back _ brings sound and videotaping equipment to the pavilion. W.C.
``Dub'' Simms, in black chaps with fringe, black boots and a black
duster, videotapes the proceedings. (The tapes are available for
sale; cassette tapes of the sermon are mailed off each week to
former church members who have moved elsewhere.) Another black hat
runs the sound. On this particular Sunday, there's no long
preaching because it's Fifth Sunday Singing _ which means a special
music-only service.
</P>
<P>
   Voices and music filled the pavilion and echoed beyond to the
horses and burros in the surrounding fields. The Davis Gospel
Singers came, Charlie Niswonger came to play his saw, and
15-year-old Rick and 9-year-old Katie Barrera gave people chills as
they sang. Glen Drewan, here working on the new jail in a nearby
town, came to sing several pieces. And just before breaking for
grub, 15-year-old Kristal Walden sang as softly as a bird and had
several grown cowboys in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, three cowboys huddled at the back of a truck with a
Bible, immersed in conversation over certain paragraphs in
Galatians. Cowboy Church does have its distractions: Horse-crazy
12-year-old Derean, nicknamed ``Derrick,'' stole away to visit her
favorite horses a few yards away. Some of the boys rested their
voices playing football.
</P>
<P>
   While barbecue settled in bellies, the singing continued into
the afternoon. Some of the crowd was still wrapped in blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Then they hugged and bid their goodbyes, took their covered dish
pans, and started to thin out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
