A0537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-08 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD THAT WE KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Freeland e-mailed a while back _ that's journalese for
``more months ago than I want to say'' _ asking for help in a
dispute. Is it correct, he wondered, to say ``I would hope we'll
have this legislation passed before the break''? His friend thinks
I would hope is just as acceptable as I would like, he wrote, ``but
I think it should be I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it should be I should hope. That's the question the
usage authorities have worried to near-extinction over the past
century or two _ when to use shall and should, when will and would.
Anyone who wants to explore that quagmire will find willing guides;
Fowler (1926) is a good place to start, and perhaps to stop. (To
Fowler's ear, I would like was unidiomatic and redundant, since
would repeated the volition already inherent in like; I should like
was the proper version. Are you having fun yet?)
</P>
<P>
   But on the question Freeland poses _ why use I would hope when
the simple I hope says the same thing _ the language commentariat
is remarkably reticent. Once the basic grammar has been outlined _
don't say if I would have known, and so on _ the authorities
abandon these conditional constructions to the realm of rhetoric
and etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   And that may be the right call. Freeland's example _ I would
hope we'll have this legislation passed _ can mean different
things, but the meanings depend on context and delivery, not on
grammar. A senator might say it with a low-key delivery and a
skeptical eyebrow; the message would be ``I hope, but I'm by no
means confident, though of course I am doing all I can.'' Or he
might state it emphatically _ ``I would HOPE'' _ meaning ``It
should be a simple matter, but those cowardly foot-draggers in the
other party won't let it proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   (The I would hope locution, incidentally, is one of the few in
which Americans still often use I should: ``Lucy's doing the dishes
before she leaves.'' ``Well, I should hope so!'' That is, it's the
least she can do if we let her go out on a school night.)
</P>
<P>
   And political nuances are only the beginning. You'd like to
offer dessert? Let us count the ways. To a toddler just mastering
the language, you offer a simple interrogative: Do you want another
cookie? To anyone older, it's Would you like another cookie?
(Though that ``another'' would have been rude, once upon a time;
hosts were not supposed to notice which guests were wolfing down
the pork chops, and the polite way to offer seconds and thirds was
simply ``Will you have a pork chop?'')
</P>
<P>
   Among strangers or honored guests, more layers of caution or
deference may be appropriate. You want to ask the neighbors to turn
down the music, but you don't know how they'll take your request.
So you say Would you mind turning down the volume? Or I wonder if
you'd mind turning down the volume? Or, if you're really anxious, I
wonder if you wouldn't mind turning down the volume? (Though if
you're this worried, maybe you should just call the police.)
</P>
<P>
   Double negatives are not incorrect here; the more layers of
hesitancy, the more polite the request. In early editions of her
famous etiquette book, Emily Post decreed that the polite way for a
sleepy houseguest to address his hostess was, ``I wonder whether
you would mind very much if I went to bed?''
</P>
<P>
   To carry it one step further, you can use what David Crystal, in
the Cambridge Encyclopedia of the English Language, calls the
attitudinal past. Switching from present to past, he notes,
``reflects a tentative state of mind, giving a more polite
effect''; Did you want to leave is less pushy than Do you want to
leave. So for the full Monty, as it were, of linguistic deference,
you could say I was wondering if you wouldn't mind turning down the
volume a bit.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound ludicrously overcivilized, especially if you're
expecting an answer in words of one syllable. But you probably hear
variations on the theme more than you think, starting with I would
hope. And though I would like to offer an authoritative rule, I
can't tell you when to skip the would. If it's there, the speaker
has a use for it. It may be an ignoble use, like evading
responsibility, but in rhetoric as in politics, you go with the
strategy that works.
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
