<HEADER>
A0545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-DISCRIMINATION-HNS &LR;      03-08 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT ALL DISCRIMINATION IS BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DONALD G. SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. _ With all the political correctness crammed
down our throats since the Great Society years, probably no word
has been so misused as
</P>
<P>
   ``discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   While the practice of discrimination can, in some cases, be
undesirable, we cannot throw an all-inclusive blanket over the
entire concept and declare it an evil thing.
</P>
<P>
   There is, indeed, good discrimination. And there is a purity
about the word that elevates us above the level of the beasts in
the field. Civilized people discriminate, and this is the very
reason that they are civilized.
</P>
<P>
   I would not, for example, choose my friends from the ranks of
those who sell dope on the street, expose themselves in public
playgrounds or pray for the soul of Adolf Hitler to rise from the
dead and lead us all to glory. Nor would I be enthusiastic about
furthering an acquaintance with those who park old cars in their
front yards or include obscene T-shirts among their regular
apparel.
</P>
<P>
   This is discrimination in every sense of the word, but I cannot
list it in the evil column.
</P>
<P>
   There is actually no reason for an organization to exist if it
does not discriminate. Associations, clubs and professional
societies exist solely to bring together people of similar
mentality or type. This includes not only common interest but age,
gender, education, religious belief and even physical dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   In scanning a list of national organizations, I have noted more
than 60 that would not allow me to join. A few of these would be:
the Reserve Officers Association of the United States, American
Veterinary Medical Association, Screen Actors Guild, Knights of
Columbus, Professional Photographers of America, National
Association of Female Executives, National Federation of Federal
Employees, B'Nai B'Rith International, Catholic Daughters of the
Americas and Jewish War Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the accredited colleges and universities in this country,
I would only be allowed in two alumni associations: Cal State Los
Angeles and UCLA. The rest would not have me in their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The point to all of this is that we cannot declare that we are
against discrimination and be done with it. The best that a
reasonable person can do is oppose the idea in highly specific
cases involving drinking fountains, restrooms and the use of public
parks and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't collect stamps, they don't want you in the stamp
club. It is as simple as that. It is discrimination, of course, but
please tell me what is wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Donald G. Smith, a retired corporate communications executive,
is author of ``People I Could Do Without.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
