<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CHANGIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. -- In August, when the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles starts to bore the media horde,
the largest Buddhist temple in North America will be the most
photographed. Television crews will zero in on the site of Al
Gore's most notorious fund-raiser, the Hsi Lai Temple, in the hills
of this quiet town of 52,000.
</P>
<P>
   This leafy corner of Los Angeles County, the incubator of
``sunset'' legislation and term limits, once symbolized Republican
rule in Ozzie-and-Harriet land, the vast white-bread housing tract
known as Southern California. Its demographic changes reflect
California's _ and America's _ politics.
</P>
<P>
   Hacienda Heights is also the punchline of a favorite yarn of
Ronald Reagan's, told by one of California's jolliest and savviest
politicians. Bill Campbell, elected to the California Assembly in
1966 with the help of ``Reagan Democrats,'' went on to the state
Senate, where he was floor leader, until 1990, when he became
president of the California Manufacturers Association and moved to
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Hacienda Heights,'' he told Republican audiences.
``If you want to get there, go east on the Pomona Freeway, then
stop at a supermarket. `No, not here,' you'll say. Then back in the
car and go east again to another shopping center and another
supermarket. `No, not here, either.' Then east again until finally,
when you go into a grocery store and find Velveeta in the gourmet
food section, you'll know you're in Hacienda Heights!''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's timing and style were impeccable. In the 1970s,
Reagan laughed heartily every time. When I once asked him why,
Reagan said, ``I know we've all heard it before, but it's funny
every single time.''
</P>
<P>
   To those audiences, processed cheese was as distasteful as
process liberalism. Campbell's story saluted ``a down-home kind of
a town. It was actually very mixed, with a lot of Latinos and
Asians. Now it's probably more so. It's a suburb where it's hard to
find identifiable boundaries. When I moved there in 1964, there
were a lot of avocado groves and orange trees, now replaced by
housing.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Campbell first introduced ``sunset'' laws, which force
agencies to justify their continued existence. ``It came out of a
Reagan line, `The closest thing to eternal life is a government
agency.' We never got it totally applied to state government, but
at least to new programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schabarum, for whom a handsome park here is named, led the
successful fight to create a ``citizen legislature,'' limiting
lawmakers to two or three terms, although he served in office more
than 20 years himself.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas reflected the high tide of conservativism. In 1966,
when Reagan unseated Governor Pat Brown, his margin in LA County
matched his statewide total of 57 percent. In neighboring Orange
County, Reagan's total was 72 percent, and in San Diego County, 64
percent. In the 1998 gubernatorial election, Democrat Gray Davis
defeated Republican Dan Lungren by 20 points, winning 66 percent in
LA County.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren barely won Orange County, with 52 percent. In San Diego
County, a lot of retired admirals have switched their voting
addresses to Davy Jones's locker. Davis beat Lungren there by 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the decline in defense spending, we saw a large exodus of
engineers in the late '80s and early '90s,'' Campbell says of his
old hometown. ``There have been some major demographic changes as
well.'' The 2000 Census will likely show a nonwhite majority in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hacienda Heights is unincorporated, statistics are iffy.
But the San Gabriel Valley telephone book documents that 130
Campbells are outnumbered 4-1 by folks named Chavez. Kims and Chens
outnumber people named Smith and Jones. More than 1,200 people
named Hernandez have telephones and 1,300 Garcias.
</P>
<P>
   And when television crews get here and they get hungry, in every
supermarket they'll find a mountain of Velveeta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
