<SLUG> BC-CANNED-HUNT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE HUNTERS DEBATE `CANNED HUNTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AURORA, Maine _ Last spring, when Scotty Lambert's grades had
climbed high enough, his father drove him and two friends from
Brockton, Mass. to this spot east of Bangor, where, inside a
thickly wooded enclosure, he marked his 11th year by killing his
first Russian boar.
</P>
<P>
   The Lamberts left the Hillside Game Ranch with three proud young
archers and three boars ready for butchering, profoundly satisfied
with the ``very realistic'' hunt its proprietor, Scott Beede, had
provided, said Scott Lambert, Scotty's father.
</P>
<P>
   But Beede's business _ the only enclosed hunting area operating
openly in Maine, and one of seven in New England _ has been at the
center of a yearlong debate in Augusta. Several legislators say
``canned hunts'' run counter to the tradition of fair chase, and
are pushing for Maine to join the 12 states that have banned the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The principles here are simple: For $400 each, clients hunting
within two fenced-off areas of more than 200 acres apiece can
typically ``harvest'' a boar within two days, and those who don't
kill anything don't have to pay. A red stag costs at least $1,200,
Corsican rams are $300, and a small elk will set a client back
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   And the hunters come, half from out of state, at the rate of 25
to 60 customers a week, Beede said. Among them are bachelor
parties, father-and-son outings, nature-starved flatlanders, and
traditional New England hunters who are tired of stalking deer
through forests and coming back empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Beede has seen the future of hunting in the North Woods and, he
said, it is significantly more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't have the time to take weeks off and go hunting
and take a chance to get what they're after,'' Beede said. Inside
his fences, ``we have more animals, to make it fairer for the
hunters. Whereas in the wild, the animals have the upper hand.''
</P>
<P>
   To Senator Marge Kilkelly, a Wiscasset Democrat, the enterprise
has no place in Maine. Last year, Kilkelly sponsored a bill to ban
the practice, and her bill should finally come to a vote before the
Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry Committee by the end of the
week. Kilkelly said she senses little will in the legislature to
ban closed hunts, but hopes the Committee will create the first set
of guidelines regulating them _ how large the enclosures should be,
for example, or what species are permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there aren't any conditions about fencing and animals,
there's nothing to say someone couldn't bring in hybrid wolves, or
cats from a circus,'' Kilkelly said. ``There's no reason to be sure
that someday we might not be dealing with an escaped tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Kilkelly's bill churned up deep misgivings among
hunters in Maine. Reluctant to condemn any form of hunting on the
grounds of inhumanity, many also allowed that they would never hunt
that way themselves. There are hundreds of game ranches in Texas,
where landowners have always fenced their property. But the notion
of hunting an animal on fenced land is still strange to many in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``In northern New England, the pride is in the chase, not in the
kill,'' said Jeff Brown of Paxton, Mass., who as president of the
Northeast Big Buck Club will not allow members to register deer
killed in enclosed areas. ``When someone creates a situation where
the chase is not an important part of the process, they're
attacking the culture. I'm surprised they even opened a place like
that in Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Beede sees it, the old traditions are crumbling anyway.
Hunters' access to land is diminishing, as more property owners
post their land or sell it to developers. Meanwhile, people have
less time to stalk deer in the woods, especially during hunting
season, which Beede says is too brief. He argues that his business
could keep hunters in the sport who might otherwise drop out.
Without some gratification, he said, ``they'll stop hunting. If you
played a game all the time and never won, wouldn't you get sick of
it? Nobody likes to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   So Beede increases a client's chances of coming home with a
trophy _ while also giving him or her the sense of participating in
a true hunt. Inside a new, 400-acre enclosure he intends to circle
with an eight-foot fence, Beede has left the woods thick and dark,
``to make it a sport.'' Still, he said, about 75 percent of his
clients wouldn't succeed if he didn't help them. ``The bottom line
is, if you've killed, I've done my job, and that makes me happy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Lambert and his son, Scotty, visited the game ranch in
pursuit of boar last March, two of the three boys _ who were all
competitive archers _ sat in a tree stand for two cold days,
nervous and excited, before they could get a clean shot at a boar,
Lambert said. One had to pursue a boar on foot through the brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it seem like an enclosed hunt? No, because we never saw
the fence,'' said Lambert, who recommends Hillside to friends
regularly, in part because it allows hunting during off season.
</P>
<P>
   Beede has some powerful allies among Maine's 80 deer and elk
farmers, whose herds now number between 8,000 and 10,000. They can
sell animals otherwise headed to a slaughterhouse to an
enclosed-hunt business for three or four times what they are worth
as meat. Animals sold to be hunted are likely to live at least
twice as long as those sold for slaughter, said Henry Ahern,
director of the Northeast Deer and Elk Farmers Association. In a
good hunting preserve, where the animals might run free for years
before being ``harvested,'' they will probably have a much better
life than they would otherwise, he said. And if the closed-hunt
business grows _ as it has in other parts of the country _ it
``would probably create quite an opportunity for small family farms
to raise replacement animals,'' said James Neil, who runs a deer
farm in Cornish, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to Kilkelly's bill also has come from hunters worried
that making judgments about the humanity of hunting will come back
to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would be hypocritical to point fingers at people.
You just bring a firestorm of criticism on hunting in general,''
said state Senator David Trahan, a Republican from Waldoboro. ``I
personally do not like shooting a bear with his head in a bucket
eating a doughnut, but I'm not going to say someone else shouldn't
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   By Kilkelly's own account, her bill was more about hunters'
behavior than animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about Maine's culture and heritage,'' she said.
``This is not who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an argument that resonates with Jim Posewitz, author of
``Beyond Fair Chase: The Ethic and Tradition of Hunting,'' who
recently lobbied unsuccessfully for passage of a similar bill in
Montana. Posewitz sees enclosed hunts as a disturbing privatization
of wildlife. Unlike Europeans, who historically considered game
attached to private property, Americans have always regarded
wildlife as the property of the people. Out of that has grown the
world's most impressive record of wildlife restoration, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human beings have already demonstrated that we have the
capacity to liquidate wildlife,'' Posewitz said. ``There has been a
conscious process of restraint that has restored the game in
America. Man has all the advantages. That's why we have this
concept of fair chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the highway from Beede's ranch, at Aurora's general store,
Joni Archer, a cashier, said she supported his right to run the
business on his property. But she also said no hunter from Aurora
would shoot an animal inside a fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do that,'' she said. ``We're from Maine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
