<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMMUNE-EXPERIMENT-BO     03-08 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNE-EXPERIMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VERMONT, PRAGMATIC PLANNING FOR A UTOPIAN VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. _ They sat around a table last weekend _
the cleareyed lesbian carpenter, the dabbler in Old Order Mennonite
life, the passionate young woodsman, the urban child of divorce,
the cautious, fascinated family of four _ and asked themselves: Are
these the people I want in my utopia?
</P>
<P>
   It was not an idle question. Two months from now, a core group
of members plans to break ground on Meadowdance, an ambitious and,
they hope, long-term experiment in community living.
</P>
<P>
   As its members quit their jobs in other communities and prepare
to move to a stunning hillside in Plainfield, in north central
Vermont, Meadowdance's founders must convince skeptics that the
``intentional community'' they propose is different from the
unstructured communes that frequently self-destructed in the 1960s
and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Still driven by the same idealistic notions _ at Meadowdance
it's ``a child-centered, egalitarian community that welcomes human
diversity, ecological sensibility, mutual learning, and joy'' _
today's utopian visionaries are well aware of attempts that failed,
and resolved to build their worlds more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of people attracted by Meadowdance's Web site came to a
house in this Burlington suburb for a process that is part first
date, part college admission, and part job interview. The mutual
selectivity shows how far the movement has come since the 1960s,
said Laird Schaub, executive secretary of the Fellowship for
Intentional Communities, who likes to say that new communities,
like new restaurants, usually don't live to see their second
birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were communities that started out `hey, y'all come,
you're welcome,' '' said Diana Christian, editor of Communities
magazine. ``I tell new communities: You can't afford to do that.
Choose people as carefully as if you're going to marry them.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, the courting featured quantities of organic
macaroni and cheese, an introduction to the power drill, and
extensive powers of visualization. At present, Meadowdance is a
plan, not a place; Plainfield's Planning Commission could still
block the building plans, forcing them to push off their move-in
date by a year.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 adults and children who have committed to the idea have
$140,000 in cash assets and an option to buy the $240,000, 165-acre
parcel of land in Plainfield. They also have a fledgling software
testing firm whose income, they hope, will help pay for
construction of a $500,000 community building, members' food and
health care, and _ down the road _ contribute toward college
tuition for children.
</P>
<P>
   Income will not be shared, but members will be required to allot
an amount of time to work for the community. Although prospective
members will not pay to join Meadowdance, those seeking admission
will undergo a ``financial evaluation that must tell the community
whether or not it can afford to take on a person,'' according to
the group's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Among its nine adult founders are Sue and John Morris, ages 52
and 33, a long-haired couple fond of contra dancing. Sue Morris
describes herself as the collective's ``house grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders would like to start with 20 adults and add a few
people every year to a peak of 75. But with 70 interested visitors
and e-mail correspondents contacting the 3-year-old project, Sue
Morris confesses to being exhausted by the stream of people eager
to be accepted by the community. One woman, intrigued with the
concept presented on the Web site, drove from Connecticut to meet
the Morrises and was so astounded by their appearance that she
blurted out, ``Oh, my God, they're hippies.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, visitors who are not ready to join the group
opt out gracefully. In newer communities that are, like
Meadowdance, actively recruiting members, the task of marketing the
idea and meeting interested parties can be overwhelming. One
community, Dancing Rabbit in Missouri, had 150 visitors last year
and accepted 10 new members. Christian's magazine has coined the
term ``seeker fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Morris, sitting barefoot on a couch, said she tries to take
the comings and goings philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person said to me last night, `I want something more
austere, this is too middle class for me,' '' Morris said. ``In
general, I don't feel hurt about people who don't want to be in
this community, unless,'' she added, ``they're someone I really
like.''
</P>
<P>
   The tables turn as soon as would-be members declare their
intention to become either a provisional ``seeker'' who would live
at Meadowdance for four to six weeks while exploring membership, or
a fully committed ``founding member'' whom the core group would
accept or reject after several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the weekend, Jeff McKenzie asked to be considered
a founding member and climbed back onto a bus for a long ride back
to Gasport, N.Y., near Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, an amiable 45-year-old with a close-cropped beard, is
no stranger to communal living. He once wore the straw hat and
suspenders of the Old Order Mennonites, only to leave when he
finally understood that the sect he had joined believed that only
100 families from Scottsville, Ky., would be admitted to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he journeyed to California to join a 10-month
Peace Walk, but left, disillusioned, after five days with a group
of raucous twentysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's search for ``a sense of family'' is remarkably
systematic: In his bag is a letter of introduction detailing his
financial status, work history, and lack of ``special dietary
requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is waiting to hear whether he will be accepted at
Meadowdance, McKenzie is planning to visit Twin Oaks, a venerable
Virginia community founded in 1967, and East Wind in Missouri,
where members have shared profits from producing hammocks and
sandals since 1976. Failing those, he's interested in Sandhill
Farm, an eight-person collective in Rutledge, Mo., that hopes to
add four members; Dancing Rabbit Ecovillage, also in Rutledge, a
group of 19 who build their houses ``using alternative techniques
such as straw bale and cob;'' and Acorn Community, an
income-sharing group of 16, seven miles from Twin Oaks in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Quests like McKenzie's have become more sophisticated in recent
years, as information about the communities became centralized. The
new edition of the Fellowship for Intentional Communities'
directory will list 625 groups, up from 325 in 1990 and 540 in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more people are looking for an alternative to
``nuclear family life in the suburbs and commuting to and from a
job that they may or may not be interested in,'' as Christian put
it. With a surge of interest, especially from older people whose
children have left home, said the fellowship's Schaub, communities
that may have had vacancies 10 years ago are filling up.
</P>
<P>
   So both seekers and communities are learning to be specific
about what they are looking for. On the fellowship's Web site, one
prospective member posted a desire for landscapes that are ``curvy,
not rectilinear,'' and another requested ``the purposeful absence
of domestic animals and pet animals.'' One group looking for new
members advertised itself as ``clothing-optional,'' with plans for
``a hot tub, yurt, and a self-healing center.''
</P>
<P>
   And many lay out fine gradations of ecological purity, spiritual
principles, or independence from the American monetary system.
``Although we like nature, we are not necessarily into getting off
the grid and outdoor toilets (been there and done that),'' reads
one posting.
</P>
<P>
   Experience _ some of it bitter _ has pushed forward the science
of what makes utopian visions succeed, said Donald Pitzer of the
University of Southern Indiana's Center for Communal Studies. A
wave of academic scholarship has sprung up based on the American
communal experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is a group of people who are much more educated
in what's happened in the past,'' said Pitzer.
</P>
<P>
   But when John Morris recently led a small group of visitors
through thigh-high snow to the hilltop where Meadowdance proposes
to build, nobody was talking about the past. With his ragged
Cornell ski team jacket vivid against the snow, Morris showed them
where founders hope to build their community building, grow apple
trees, and tap a sugarbush for maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Torry, a 25-year-old from western Massachusetts who
dreams of breaking ground on her own organic farm, looked out at
Spruce Mountain and felt her skepticism about Meadowdance's
finances drift away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you notice how ever since I got here I'm saying, `Now what
are we doing?' '' she said, laughing and emphasizing the ``we.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the weekend, two men _ McKenzie and 25-year-old
Chris Chaisson _ had asked to be considered founding members. Three
adults asked to be seekers: Anna Flynn, a 20-year-old who wants to
start a ``free school'' like the one her father helped found in
Massachusetts; Bob Carlson, 46, who saw power struggles sink a
commune he helped found in the 1970s; and Carlson's wife, Franny
Huberman, 27, who hesitates to uproot their two small children from
Gould Farm, a service-based community in Monterey, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the type of person who necessarily easily makes a leap
of faith,'' Huberman said.
</P>
<P>
   For John Morris, like the rest of the founders, doubt is an old
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to say it's going to work because I know it
will,'' he said. ``But that's all I can say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
