<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-08 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STATUS QUO STEALS THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidential primaries settled one argument, at least.
Americans don't hate politics; it's governance we disdain.
</P>
<P>
   We love a campaign _ especially the nasty, upstart, insurgent
variety _ the way an earlier generation loved a parade.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the protests against negative advertising and the
chest-thumping about soft money. The high school band struck up the
theme from ``Star Wars'' and we were smitten. A paper shower
cloaked the fomer Navy pilot in red, white, and blue confetti and
we got a patriotic surge. The ``Straight Talk Express'' rolled into
town and we couldn't wait to hear whom the irreverent candidate
would skewer next.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted a show and, bless him, Senator John McCain gave us
one. Show's over. Exit stage right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Democratic counterpart in the maverick role never quite
lived up to advance billing, though. Maybe former New Jersey
senator Bill Bradley's problem was that he came out of the National
Basketball Association in an era when the NBA was still about the
basketball. No cheerleaders. No dancers, blaring rock music, or
gimmicky halftime entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted a show and, shame on him, Bradley refused to give us
one. Exit stage left.
</P>
<P>
   If it's true that we get the leaders we deserve, we deserve the
fall campaign we are about to face between two men who got their
political careers the old-fashioned way: They inherited them from
Dad. For all this primary season's talk of change, we will be
watching a campaign rerun come autumn. A (not too far) left-leaning
Democrat competes for the vast electoral middle against a (genuine)
right-wing Republican. Nothing bold, nothing new there.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Vice President Al Gore and Texas Governor George Bush will
agree to some form of campaign spending restrictions now that an
old Gore associate has been convicted of illegal fund-raising and a
current Bush ally has used millions of dollars to bludgeon McCain
with misleading primary ads.
</P>
<P>
   But the chance for real change, the type for which we claim to
hunger every four years, was lost in a wave of Super Tuesday
victories for the standard-bearers of the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the Bradley campaign, especially, confirms a
frightening unwillingness to take ourselves or our politics
seriously. Bradley was too professorial, said critics. He was too
dull. He failed to electrify a crowd. He had no fire in his belly.
Oh, he had good ideas, bold ideas, but his delivery! Didn't the man
ever take public speaking?
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ``in a good mood is a worse campaigner than I am in a
bad mood,''smirked Barney Frank, the ever-humble Democratic
congressman from Massachusetts and comedian in chief of the US
House.
</P>
<P>
   Is the ease of campaigning and the ability to lead the same
thing? It is easy to forget how many great presidents, from the
pre-television era, would have failed this kind of personality
litmus test. Abraham Lincoln comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quitter,'' complained Massachusetts Senator John Kerry
of Bradley's decision to leave the Senate after the Republicans
gained control of Congress. ``He left when the rest of us stayed to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the Senate the only place for a public man to advance a
political agenda? It is easy to forget that Bill Bradley was one of
many senators, of both parties, to walk away from secure seats in
``the world's greatest deliberative body'' in the last decade,
exasperated by the procedural stalemates and partisan gridlock that
thwarted even the most benign public policy goals. Maine Democrat
George Mitchell comes to mind. (So do Maine Republican William
Cohen, New Hampshire Republican Warren Rudman, Oregon Republican
Mark Hatfield, Kansas Republican Nancy Kassebaum, and Georgia
Democrat Sam Nunn.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My frustration with our inability to deal with things in
Congress is as frustrating as hell,'' Rudman said when he announced
his retirement in 1992. ``It seems that we can't work together
anymore. The president tries to do things. The Congress tries to do
things. The Democrats fight with the Republicans. The Republicans
fight with the Democrats. Everybody fights with everybody else, and
I sometimes wonder what the hell I'm doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that it was Rudman who stage-managed McCain's
insurgent campaign for change? The final curtain came down Tuesday.
Next up: Politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
