<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-08 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBASSADOR MONEYBAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year San Francisco businessman and philanthropist James
Hormel was finally sworn in as the US ambassador to Luxembourg
after a particularly disgusting fight with conservatives who called
him unfit for diplomatic service. His crime: He was openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   What Neanderthals like Trent Lott objected to was how Hormel had
used his wealth to fund gay causes. What no one objected to is how
Hormel used his wealth to buy himself an ambassadorship. That, of
course, is business as usual in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of rewarding political moneybags with choice
diplomatic posts is as old as the republic. Richard Nixon didn't
put a fine point on it in a conversation with H.R. Haldeman,
recorded in those infamous Nixon Tapes: ``My point is that anybody
who wants to be an ambassador must at least give $250,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, I want to know, is selling nights in the Lincoln bedroom an
outrage and selling ambassadorships OK? And if we can sell
ambassadorships, why can't we see what Cabinet posts will fetch in
the open market? Maybe we could auction them on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Our own James Daley, former owner of the Copley Plaza and the
Back Bay Hilton, is the latest businessman to secure a checkbook
nomination. While it hasn't been announced, Daley tells me he is
``honored to be under consideration'' to become US ambassador to
the Eastern Caribbean _ based in Barbados and also overseeing
relations with Antigua and Barbuda, Dominica, St. Lucia, Greneda,
St. Kitts and Nevis, and St. Vincent and the Grenadines. This is
good work if you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to pick on Daley. By all accounts he is a nice man
who actually earned his millions. Daley, now 58, literally grew up
living in the Roxbury nursing home his mother ran, thought about
becoming an undertaker, and went on to make his fortune fixing up
broken down nursing homes and later hotels.
</P>
<P>
   As a businessman and hotelier, Daley knows something about
tourism, the number one industry of the Eastern Caribbean. But he
is not in line for that ambassadorship because he knows hotels and
tourism. He is in line for that ambassadorship largely because he
and his wife, Kathleen, have donated at least $271,000 to President
Clinton and the Democrats since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he sees something he likes, price is not an issue,''
Daley's older brother, Michael, once told The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly interesting about the campaign finance
reports is that Daley is such a newcomer to the game. According to
the Center for Responsive Politics, the Daleys contributed zilch to
the Democrats in the 1994 and 1996 election cycles.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed bigtime in the last three years. When Clinton
came to Boston in January, Daley was one of five local rich guys
the president asked to his hotel suite to discuss fund-raising for
his presidential library. Call them the Boston Five, Clinton's own
Boston bank of deep-pocketed contributors. Daley's $271k doesn't
even include anything yet for the library, but my guess is he'll
manage an appropriate thank you to the president. (Note to the
other members of the Boston Five _ Alan Solomont, Jack Manning,
Howard Kessler and Fred Seigel: You, too, can be an ambassador if
the price is right.)
</P>
<P>
   Of 170 current ambassadors, 61 are so-called political
appointees, the highest percentage in recent history. How can we
talk about campaign finance reform as long as we are selling
ambassadorships to campaign donors? How do we square our commitment
to the new global economy with our old-fashioned practice of
selling ambassadorships to the high bidder?
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Our government should not be for sale. Not
the presidency, not an ambassadorship. If Daley and his wife want
to go to Barbados, they should _ they've earned it. Travel tip for
the Daleys: Garber Travel can get you into the Almond Beach Club,
an adults-only four-star hotel, for seven nights, all included, for
just $2,419.40 per person. It's not the American Embassy, but then
the rates sure beat what President Clinton is charging you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
