<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-PRESIDENTIAL-CAMPAIGN     03-08 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEXT UP FOR BUSH, GORE: COURTING THE RENEGADE ELEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY and LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After five frenetic weeks, the presidential
campaign looks just the way the pundits, the pollsters and the
party establishment scripted it a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the promise of a cliffhanger, the favored candidates,
Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, relied on
their money, connections and political machines to survive
unexpectedly strong assaults from former Sen. Bill Bradley and
Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a primary that stretched across 16 states, from California to
Maine, Gore won every Democratic contest over Bradley. Bush took
more than 75 percent of the Republican delegates on Tuesday,
virtually eliminating McCain, who carried four states in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's idealistic rhetoric about lifting up the poor and
fostering racial unity fell silent among the wealthiest, most
productive nation in the world. McCain's more effective ``iron
triangle'' message about the abuses of lobbyists, legislation and
money wasn't enough to beat the Republican establishment's chosen
candidate and its well-tuned machine.
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward November, the country will see Gore, the son of a
senator from Tennessee, and Bush, the grandson of a senator from
Connecticut and the son of a president. It's Harvard vs. Yale.
Southern aristocracy vs. the Yankee-with-a-Stetson peerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unusual story leading to the expected ending,'' said
presidential scholar Jack Pitney of Claremont McKenna College in
California.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a learning experience for the party blue-bloods.
Along the way, McCain ran over Bush's foot with his ``Straight Talk
Express.'' Bradley forced Gore and the centrist New Democrats who
talk about welfare reform and balanced budgets to recognize that
some people had been left behind by America's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began with a moderate, ``compassionate conservative''
mantra, but he sprinted away from it as soon as McCain caught fire
five weeks ago among independent and Democratic voters in New
Hampshire and threatened his Republican base. Bush gave an
ill-fated speech at a South Carolina college accused of bigotry,
shunned the gay and lesbian Log Cabin Republicans, defended
religious conservatives, and proposed a huge tax cut that few
voters embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he began hiking back to the center, and previewed
his challenge against Gore. Bush wants to paint Gore as old news,
stagnant, linked to his boss, President Clinton. Most importantly,
he wants back the more than 2 million people _ independents and
Democrats among them _ who voted for McCain nationwide on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone will make history this November,'' Bush told
supporters in Austin. ``Either we will ratify the status quo, or we
will have a new beginning in American politics. I say: America must
not give Clinton-Gore four more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, faces a tough race against Gore because of the
damage inflicted by McCain's renegade campaign. With Bradley
neutralized, Gore was able to capture more votes than Bush in
California and New York, the two largest states. Bush has started
atoning for his shift to the right in South Carolina, most notably
apologizing to Catholics in New York and speaking at the Museum of
Tolerance in Los Angeles on the eve of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made Bush's campaign stronger in many ways, but it also
exposed weaknesses that Gore will undoubtedly seize upon as they
campaign through November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has got some real work to do to establish himself as a
moderate,'' said Bill Carrick, a veteran consultant for Democrats
in California. ``The South Carolina primary did a lot of damage to
him, and it's not going to be repaired anytime soon. If you look at
who got hit with the most collateral damage, it was Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore must now figure out how to attract those who voted
for McCain and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's appeal was more to the left and I think Gore, being a
centrist Democrat, has a shorter journey to the center than Bush
does,'' said David Lee, executive director of the San
Francisco-based Chinese American Voters Education Committee.
``McCain's attacks on the far right appeal very much to the
moderate and conservative Democrats that Gore needs to capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls in the Super Tuesday states showed that Bush ran
especially well among religious fundamentalists, women and
Republicans of all stripes. McCain appealed in California and
elsewhere to independent voters, registered Democrats and
pro-choice voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attacks on the Rev. Pat Robertson and other Christian
conservatives _ he called Robertson an ``evil influence'' on the
GOP _ may have backfired, the polls indicated. Voters who
considered the remarks significant overwhelmingly favored Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls showed that Gore thrashed Bradley among every
segment of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primaries and caucuses took place in 16 states with
nearly 6 million voters, but it hardly seemed devoted to the issues
of education, health care and community that Americans say they
care about.
</P>
<P>
   It became a test of the fortitude and character of the
candidates. Extended debates over the Confederate battle flag, Bob
Jones University in South Carolina and conservative preachers
brought out larger issues about tolerance and how to appeal to
independent voters closed off from the Republican and Democratic
political machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that Gore can take a lickin' and keep on ticking,''
said Henry Brady, a political scientist at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``We learned that George Bush, when pushed,
will go to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bush machine stalled a bit in the snows of New Hampshire and
Michigan, where McCain won unexpected victories thanks to Democrats
and independents. Bush's ``Pioneer'' donors, who each helped raise
$100,000, convened strategy meetings and started to worry.
</P>
<P>
   But what didn't kill Bush made him stronger. Derided by McCain
and Bradley, the establishment candidates co-opted the maverick
message, hammered Bradley and McCain as fringe candidates and party
interlopers, focused their message, and spent most of their money.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned by Bradley's better-than-expected showing in polls and
fund-raising leading to the New Hampshire primary, Gore packed up
his campaign and moved it to Nashville, expressing astonishment at
himself for even thinking he could run his campaign from
Washington. He started wearing cowboy boots and knit shirts. He
started calling himself, over and over again, a ``fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush started talking about being a ``fresh voice'' and holding
town hall meetings. He offered to shake up the way national
campaigns are financed, McCain's signature issue, as he collected
and spent more money on a presidential campaign than anyone else in
U.S. history _ $65 million so far. He put his compassionate
conservative message away and became a 11reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the exit polls, Bush won huge majorities of voters
looking for a candidate who can win in November or who best
represents conservative values. McCain won among voters who were
looking for someone who is not a typical politician or someone who
stands up for what he believes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters didn't want to give McCain enough to win, but they
wanted to give him enough to scare Bush,'' said Georgia Sorenson, a
senior scholar at the Academy of Leadership at the University of
Maryland. ``They also wanted to send a message that they wanted
more authenticity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
