<SLUG> BC-DOOMED-BARAK?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S HOLD ON POWER SLIPPING BY THE DAY  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ First corruption allegations, then a stunning defeat
in parliament, and now a sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The ground under Ehud Barak, Israel's prime minister, seems to
be slipping by the day.
</P>
<P>
   The latest blow came Tuesday when a cabinet colleague, Yitzhak
Mordechai _ a former defense minister who now holds the transport
portfolio _ suspended himself from his post pending an
investigation into accusations that he sexually assaulted a
23-year-old woman civil servant.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged incident _ which has caused a storm in the Israel
media, despite the minister's denials _ would normally be chalked
up as a routine political setback, had it not coincided with a
lengthening list of signs that Barak is losing his footing, and
that this is undermining his role in the stalled Middle East peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week his parliamentary coalition fractured, allowing
his opponents to win the first reading of a critical bill.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barak faces a ``no-confidence'' motion after an uproar over
his education minister's plans to include the work of a nationalist
Palestinian poet, Mahmoud Darwish, on the school curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   If it ever comes to a vote, the signs are that his coalition
would betray him again.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, unrest and tension among the Palestinians
in the West Bank and Gaza have risen sharply _ with an historic
Papal visit less than two weeks away - fuelled by the endless
failure of their nationalist aspirations to make any progress.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few days, Israel has been living under a state of
heightened alert.
</P>
<P>
   Its security services believe Hamas guerrillas are trying to
step up operations, and claim to have averted a devastating city
center bombing by staging a raid last week in which four suspected
guerrillas were killed.
</P>
<P>
   If true, this is a measure of the current precarious mood; Hamas
leaders tend to approve attacks only when they believe the use of
violence will receive public support from Palestinians _ along with
a willingness to endure the Israeli reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Now the temperature has risen further with a decision by an
Israeli parole board to release a Jewish settler, Yoram Skolnik,
from prison after he served only seven years of a life prison
sentence for killing a Palestinian, who was lying on the ground
with his arms tied, by shooting him in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ taken against the advice of Israel's Attorney
General's office _ has infuriated Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   It has not escaped their notice that one of those who commuted
the settler's original sentence was Israel's president, Ezer
Weizman, who is now under police investigation for accepting huge
cash gifts from a French millionaire friend.
</P>
<P>
   This is not all. Israel's foreign minister, David Levy _ already
under fire for a speech in which promised to avenge future
Hezbollah attacks on Israel with a ``child for a child'' (a threat
that, fulfilled, would amount to a war crime) _ has caused more
havoc by announcing that he would never agree to withdrawal from
the Golan Heights to the border lines of June 4, 1967 _ Syria's
foremost demand, which Barak himself seemed to have accepted.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak's standing has been eroded by an official report that
found massive campaign finance violations by his electoral
coalition, One Israel _ now subject to a police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst all this, the country is agonizing over what will happen
when Barak carries out his pledge, confirmed by his cabinet on
Sunday, to withdraw forces from south Lebanon by July, if necessary
without a peace agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Fears abound that a unilateral withdrawal will make the Middle
East even more unstable, and that an escalating spiral of violence
will begin.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Barak will be around to see it is now becoming a matter
of genuine debate. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
