<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, March 9,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-GOPFOLO _ Follow on Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
overwhelming victory in Tuesday's Super Tuesday primaries. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman)/Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ His claim on the Democratic
presidential nomination all but official, Vice President Al Gore
wasted no time Wednesday launching his general election campaign.
Gore began a trip that advisers said was designed to woo moderate
and reform-minded voters in the battleground states of Michigan and
Minnesota. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ A post-mortem on the Bradley campaign. According to
Bradley advisers, the announcement from Bradley that he's leaving
the race and backing Gore will come tomorrow. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-REACTION _ Reaction to Super Tuesday results, other sides
as merits. (Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-RECAP _ Recap of night's results, including West Coast
numbers. (Sherman/Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VOTING _ WASHINGTON _ Arizona Democrats on Wednesday
began three days of voting in their presidential primary via
personal computers and the Internet. How the voting works and what
it may mean for the future. (Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-RESEARCH _ WASHINGTON _ Plans to get a bigger share of
federal research dollars for Texas universities are polished at a
summit Wednesday of university presidents and a majority of the
members of the Texas delegation, including both senators.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-AUDITS _ WASHINGTON _ Some 20 conservative groups who have
criticized the Clinton adminstration have wound up audited by the
Internal Revenue Service. Are politicians using the tax service to
punish enemies? More than three years since that Watergate-era
question made a comeback, neither Congress, the IRS nor the courts
have provided a comprehensive answer. Now aides on Capitol Hill say
an almost forgotten probe begun in 1997 will yield a report in the
``next few weeks.'' (Malone, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-TERM-CARE _ WASHINGTON-Groups representing the elderly and
the insurance industry who have frequently battled each other in
Congress join to support a bipartisan bill being introduced to
provide tax credits for people who need long-term care and their
care-givers. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VIOLENCE _ WASHNGTON _ The most important contributing
factor to youth violence is the absence of a nurturing home
environment, a group of House members says in a report released
Thursday. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POPE _ JERUSALEM _ ``Operation Old Friend,'' the code
name for the Papal visit to Israel, is Israel's largest VIP
security detail ever. It will employ 18,000 police, about $6
million, a papal Black Hawk helicopter and a special mini-Pope
mobile for the narrow streets of Jerusalem's Old City. The project
is overseen by Brig. Gen. David Tsur, an Israeli police official
who consulted for a year in security for Atlanta's 1996 Olympics.
``During the Pope's visit, it's going to be more safe than any
other time,'' he vows. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY-NUREMBERG _ Samuel Grossman of Lake Worth, Fla., covered
the Nuremberg World War II war crimes trials and saw the men ``just
following orders.'' Eyewitness to history on the Nuremberg trial.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). 38.
</P>
<P>
   ORISSA-RECOVERY _ ERSAMA, India _ Choice is no longer a part of
people's lives in cyclone-ravaged Orissa. India's worst storm of
the century changed the face of the state for years to come and
left the poorest of the country's poor with nothing at all.
According to Atlanta-based CARE, the state's cash crops _ coconut,
betel, papaya _ suffered millions of dollars in damage. Rice
paddies were either swept away by the wind or rotted under water
one month before the December harvest. And 40,000 fishing families
lost their boats and equipment. ``People are still struggling. They
are struggling very much,'' said Orissa's CARE director Basant
Mohanty, who traveled to Atlanta last December to make a personal
appeal for money. (Basu, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   CONFEDERATE-SYMBOLS _ RICHMOND _ Confederate symbols in the home
of the Old Confederacy government are getting even less respect
than the Confederate flag flying atop the South Carolina
Statehouse. The Sons of Confederate Veterans are demanding that
last month's torching of a banner of Gen. Robert E. Lee on a
holiday in his honor be treated by police and prosecutors as a hate
crime against Southerners. Meanwhile, the city council is
considering a proposal to rename two city bridges that honor
Confederate generals J.E.B. Stuart and Stonewall Jackson, replacing
them with the names of two civil rights activists. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
