<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, March 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ What the coming weeks hold for Al
Gore and George W. Bush. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bush, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PROPOSITIONS (San Francisco) _ Folo on California's
approval of proposals against gay marriage and for a crackdown on
juvenile crime. And a look at what this may say about the state. By
Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-COLO (Denver) _ Sen. John McCain is still in the running
in Colorado's primary, which is Friday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-SUPPORTERS (Washington) _ Bill Bradley's presidential
bid enlisted many who were new to politics, a largely privileged
and idealistic group alienated by the interest group politics of
the Democratic party and the tactical centrism of President
Clinton. In the aftermath of Vice President Gore's bare-knuckled
primary triumph, some of these Bradley supporters express dismay
and disillusion with the state of American campaigns and say they
will do nothing to help Gore defeat Gov. George W. Bush. Their
loyalty, it seems, is to Bradley alone, not to party or process. By
John M. Broder. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING (Undated) _ Looking at fundraising plans by Gore and
Bush. By Don Van Natta and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (Washington) _ A day before House is to take up
bill to increase minimum wage, President Clinton wades into the
congressional battle, saying he favors $1 increase in two years and
would veto a competing plan for a $1 increase over three years.
Current minimum wage is $5.15 an hour. He emphasizes opposition to
tax provisions congress wants to include in its wage bill,
including a reduction in some business taxes and in the inheritance
tax. By Marc Lacey. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KY-POLICE-SHOOTING (Louisville, Ky.) _ A police shooting
incident with eerie echoes of New York City plunges Louisville into
debate about the loyalty of its police force. After the mayor fired
the police chief, his nine field commanders threw down their badges
in protest. There is a standoff with rank and file's police union
which followed the chief decision to give departmental awards to
two cops who shot an unarmed suspect 22 times. By Francis X.
Clines. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-AUTO-PILEUP (Wellborn, Fla.) _ At least 19 vehicles crashed
on an interstate highway obscured by smoke from a wildfire today,
killing three people and resulting in an acid spill, the Florida
Highway Patrol said.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASIA (Washington) _ President Clinton gives a major
speech at 3:30 p.m. on China, trade and Asian security. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Dateline to kum) _ Interview with the presidential
candidate excoriated by China for independence views. He says the
attacks will help him, but they seem to be scaring voters. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CORRUPTION (Beijing) _ To try to show it's serious about
cracking down on corruption, China executes the former vice
governor of a province. But many say he's small potatoes. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israel and the Palestinians agreed
Wednesday to resume peace negotiations later this month in
Washington, ending weeks of deadlock. Yasser Arafat and Ehud Barak
meet for a second time in 14 hours, and are expected to meet
Thursday with Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MIXED-COUPLES (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Supreme Court
ruled Wednesday that an Israeli Arab couple could not be barred
from living in a community that had been built solely for Jews. By
Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SOUTHASIA () _ India and Pakistan react to Clinton's
decision to stop in Pakistan after he visits India. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXTINCT-RECOVER () _ The history of the Earth is pocked with
episodes of mass extinction _ including the present, apparently _
in which large numbers of species have died out. New research
suggests that, contrary to what you might think, it takes about 10
million years for the ecosystem to repopulate itself, regardless of
the magnitude of the extinction. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENOME (Undated) _ An inside look at how and why a
proposed collaboration between Craig Venter and the NIH _ the two
players in the race to sequence the human genome _ fell apart last
week. By Nicholas Wade. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-PHONES (Richmond, Mass.) _ Richmond Telephone, which
serves tiny Richmond, a former mining town in the Berkshires, is a
little different from most phone companies. Its corporate
headquarters is a green-shuttered, white clapboard house on Route
41, just shy of the New York border. It has nine employees,
including a one-man repair crew named Maurice. Its phone book
listings are 12 pages long. And it has been handling the calls for
the 1,168 residents of exchange 698 for the last 96 years. As
archaic as it may seem, more than a thousand small, independent
local exchange companies like Richmond Telephone still do business
in the United States. Many are family-run companies, most dating to
the turn of the last century, that were never part of the Ma Bell
system, never bought out by competitors, and basically were left to
their own devices all these years. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Blue chips stocks were steady, but computing
stocks were down sharply in early trading. At 11:15 a.m., the Dow
Jones industrial was up 0.25 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 down 0.05
percent, while the Nasdaq composite index was down 1.70 percent,
led by declines in Intel, Cisco Systems and JDS Uniphase. The
Nasdaq had been down as much as 2.6 percent. Treasury prices were
little changed. European markets were lower: London was down 1.15
percent and Frankfurt down 0.36 percent. The Nikkei closed down
0.89 percent, while the Hang Seng ended up 0.48 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SHELTERS (Washington) _ The Senate Finance Committee holds a
hearing on corporate tax shelters. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-MARKET (Singapore) _ An escalating scandal over
insider trading leaves the Philippines Stock Exchange in turmoil,
unnerves investors and sends the nation's currency to its lowest
level this year. President Joseph Estrada dismisses his top
securities regulator for trying to close the stock exchange after
its entire compliance department resigns. The market is open for
business Wednesday but share prices plummet 3 percent and nobody is
on duty to monitor possible cheating. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
