<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE LOSES AS FEUD CONTINUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many unsuspecting travelers have become pawns in an ongoing feud
between travel agents and one of the world's fastest-growing cruise
lines _ a relationship so soured that most agents seem unmoved by a
$1 million show of respect for their embattled profession.
</P>
<P>
   It's a saga that transcends cruising and sheds insight into the
changing environment in which we plan our travels.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Cruises, a self-styled renegade, has infuriated
travel agents over the past two years with its heavy emphasis on
direct-to-the-consumer marketing _ a bold strategy in a business
where agents sell about 95 percent of the overall cruise product.
</P>
<P>
   The line's approach _ based largely on direct mailings and sale
pricing on its Internet site _ led to Renaissance's expulsion from
the American Society of Travel Agents. Many agencies refuse to sell
its cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BECOMING A MAJOR PLAYER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, by outward appearances at least, the cruise line _ whose
passenger capacity is more than doubling this year _ wants to kiss
and make up. At the heart of a $1 million advertising campaign in
trade publications, Renaissance vows to become the most travel
agent-friendly line. It touts a 50 percent increase last year in
agency bookings. (``Tomorrow, it will be more,'' ads promise.) And
it claims to now offer ``the fastest, and surest, commission
program of any cruise line.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that thousands of travel agencies have folded over the
past five years because of declining revenues, you'd think this
would serve as encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the immediate reaction included this:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Renaissance's Big Lie,'' headlined Cruise Week newsletter.
``The company's spinmeisters ... don't address the real reasons
agents aren't booking this line.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Deeds, not words, are the order of the day for
Renaissance,'' editorialized Travel Weekly, an industry publication
that reported several subscription cancellations from travel agents
upset that it printed the line's new ads.
</P>
<P>
   I would dismiss this bickering as a private argument except for
its impact on the traveler. During a 12-month period, Renaissance
is introducing four new 680-passenger ships. By 2001, its
ultra-modern fleet will include eight vessels _ with a combined
5,440-passenger capacity _ deployed from Europe to the South
Pacific. The line's itineraries are innovative, its prices
attractive. It's evident that Renaissance is becoming a major
player in the industry, but don't bother asking most travel agents
for a brochure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RETHINKING ITS MARKETING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why such antipathy?
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance's marketing approach is the main issue. While other
travel entities _ especially airlines and tour packagers _ have
made increasingly effective use of the Internet, most cruise lines
continue to rely almost exclusively on travel agents for sales.
Renaissance has represented not just a singular villain _ but the
threat that if it succeeds, others may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance's commission structure also angers travel agents who
say they are rewarded for cruises booked with the line but not for
air arrangements and pre- or post-cruise lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Of more significance to the traveler, one longtime Houston agent
says Renaissance's strict cancellation penalties make it difficult
to obtain recommended third-party insurance.
</P>
<P>
   This last point is a valid concern (although one I suspect
Renaissance would be willing to address if a better rapport were
established). But as for the other areas of disagreement:
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents have repeatedly told us that their main value to
consumers is in providing unbiased service _ that in an era when
individuals are evaluating various alternatives, traditional
agencies are the most viable outlet for true comparison-shopping.
They also have stressed that their main allegiance is to the
traveler, not a specific cruise line or airline or tour packager.
</P>
<P>
   Do these pledges not apply if a customer wants professional
advice in comparing _ without prejudice _ Renaissance with, say,
Carnival or Princess or Radisson Seven Seas (Renaissance's major
competitor in the growing Tahiti cruise market)? Some agents urged
a boycott of United when it initiated the most recent round of
airline commission cuts. Who's next?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Renaissance precipitated this dispute by saying to
travel agents, in effect, ``We don't need you; we can attract
customers ourselves.'' That would sting me, too. But even as it
continues to court direct bookings, a $1 million investment in a
campaign to woo back agents seems a pretty clear indication that
the cruise line _ with so many more berths to fill _ is rethinking
its position. At the least, it's a first step toward
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Renaissance's new strategy lends support to travel
agents' insistence that they can compete effectively with
direct-to-the-consumer booking concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agencies need all the support they can get, too. A recent
study released by the Travel Industry Association of America found
that Internet travel planning rose 1,500 percent between 1996 and
1999, and that online bookings increased 206 percent during that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Will these trends continue? Probably. This much is certain: In
planning our travels, we don't care about commission structures or
grudges. We just want the best available service for the best price
_ and we're willing to shop around until we find it.
</P>
<P>
   I was intrigued by one California travel agent's comments as
quoted in Cruise Week. ``Renaissance,'' he urged, ``must be avoided
by retail travel agents at all costs.'' Why? ``The efforts of any
travel supplier to encourage the consumer to book directly is the
main cancer to the health and vitality of the retail travel
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The health and vitality of travel agents _ or Renaissance
Cruises or any other aspect of the travel industry _ depends on the
consumer. It's our decision which products to buy. And where to buy
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
