<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-DEALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING FLINGS: IT'S NOT TOO LATE TO GO ON A SKI BREAK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missed winter?
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late to play in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   And play is the operative word. Spring calendars at U.S. ski
resorts are dotted with amusements such as St. Patrick's Day
parades and ``big air'' contests.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is right, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ski resorts may represent the only vacation destinations that
lower prices when the weather becomes more agreeable. So late
season is low season with price breaks on lodging and lift tickets.
</P>
<P>
   First, an advance peek at some fun-filled events:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wayne Wong World Hot Dog Skiing Festival &AMP; Championships
are scheduled April 14-15 at Alpine Meadows on the California coast
of Lake Tahoe. This psychedelic '70s-inspired event features two
days of outrageous freestyle ski competition, cool shades, lots of
sunshine and plenty of bell bottoms. Event proceeds benefit the
Juvenile Diabetes Foundation. For information, call 800-441-4423.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bust 'n' Burn'' is the name of a mogul competition April 1-2
at Sunday River in Maine. The contest pits the top amateur and pro
bump skiers in the country. Spectators enjoy barbecue, live bands
and watching some brutal skiing. Call 207-824-3000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family fun is the focus of TubaPalooza March 25-26 at
Purgatory Resort near Durango, Colo. Activities are centered on the
resort's snow-tubing hill, where a ``snowcoaster'' whisks tubers to
the  &UR; s &LR; ummit. Call 970-247-9000.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Steamboat Springs in Colorado, the resort celebrates the
close of the ski season with its campy Cardboard Classic on April
1. Now in its 20th year, this contest pits race crafts made
strictly of cardboard, string, water-based paint, duct tape and
masking tape. Call 970-879-6111.
</P>
<P>
   _ You'll need swim attire to participate in Telluride's Surf the
Rockies celebration March 25-April 9. Decked out with pink
flamingos, the Colorado resort offers snow volleyball, concerts,
dance parties and some seriously silly contests. Call 970-728-7485.
</P>
<P>
   _ Snowmass hosts its Spring Jam March 31-April 2. A rite of
spring in Colorado, the event features ski and snowboard
competitions, live music and pro snowboarding demonstrations. Call
800-525-6200.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beaver Creek resort in Colorado hosts the largest snowshoe
race in the country each year with more than 1,200 participants.
The 2000 Snowshoe Shuffle on April 1 will feature 10K and 5K
competitive races and a one-mile fun stroll. Call 800-622-3131.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the season's most elegant events is Taste of Vail,
which combines spring skiing with superb cuisine and wine. More
than 50 winemakers will participate in the April 6-8 event, which
also spotlights more than 35 of Colorado's best chefs. Participants
enjoy seminars, vintner dinners, mountaintop picnics and apres-ski
tastings. Call 888-311-5665.
</P>
<P>
   Can't make any of these special attractions? Many resorts'
bargain packages cover other late-season dates, and the best
include discounts on both lodging and lift tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Take for instance, Aspen and Snowmass in Colorado. Area lodgings
are offering packages for April that provide seven nights' lodging
and a six-day lift ticket for prices starting at $457 per person,
based on double occupancy. The newly renovated Aspen Club Lodge,
located steps from Aspen Mountain's Silver Queen Gondola, touts
similar packages starting at $639. Call 877-282-7736.
</P>
<P>
   Look for these packages via travel agents, the resorts' 800
numbers, newspaper advertisements and Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The best rates are for midweek stays. Also, when comparing
prices always consider whether extras such as breakfast, lessons
and equipment rentals are included.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other late-season deals. All are subject to
availability. Unless otherwise specified, all prices are per person
based on double occupancy, and air fare is not included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vail, consistently mentioned as one of the country's best ski
resorts, offers a Spring Break special throughout March that
features air fare from Houston and three nights' lodging for prices
starting at $460 per person. The deal is good for four persons
sharing a two-bedroom condominium. Call 800-404-3535.
</P>
<P>
   _ Late-season skiers and snowboarders heading to Heavenly on
Lake Tahoe can take advantage of a ``Snow Dreams'' package that
pairs three nights' lodging, a two-day lift ticket and breakfast
daily for rates starting at $157. The deal is good April 2 through
the end of the season. Call 800-243-2836.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steamboat's ``Spring Snowsaver'' deal is good through March 31
and starts as low as $318 for four nights' lodging and a three-day
lift ticket. Call 800-922-2722.
</P>
<P>
   _ A March Millennium Madness package at Telluride includes five
nights' lodging and a four-day ski pass for fares starting at $630.
Call 800-854-3062.
</P>
<P>
   _ Experience an up-and-comer among ski areas and save some cash
with the Canyons' ``Late Season Value Package.'' For prices
starting at $315, skiers and snowboarders get three nights' lodging
and a two-day lift ticket good at the resort in Park City, Utah.
Call 888-226-9667.
</P>
<P>
   That deal is good March 26 through the end of the season. Plan
your visit right and you can ski for cheap and take in one of those
loopy end-of-season traditions. On April 8, the Canyons hosts its
annual Pond Skimming Contest, where participants try to cross a
100-foot pond on their skis and snowboards. Last season 15 people
made it across the 37-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling lucky? &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
