<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, March 9:
</P>
<P>
   PLASTIC-FURNITURE (New York) _ Plain-jane no more, plastic
furniture is coming in from the patio. Not everyone thinks that's
good news. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER-SHOW (Philadelphia) _ On the Philadelphia Flower Show,
which opened on Sunday under the banner ``Gardens for the New
Millennium.'' By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   FULTON-PHOTOS (New York) _ In 1932, as a young architectural
student, Robert Edison Fulton Jr. set out from London on a
motorcycle and circled the globe, visiting 20 countries and
traveling 40,000 miles, arriving home to his parents' apartment in
New York City on Christmas Eve, 18 months later. He filmed the trip
on a 35-millimeter camera that looked more like a sextant. He had
six flat tires. He ran out of gas only once, just outside of
Munich. ``The Long Journey Home,'' a selection of stills from the
4,000 feet of film Fulton shot, is being published next month by
August Press. His first exhibition of stills, photographs and
sculpture opens at Exhibit A in Manhattan on April 6. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH-BARN (South Egremont, Mass.) _ Buying an old English
barn seemed like a good idea at the time. Richard and Stephanie
Stern wanted to add a great room onto their too-small summer
cottage in the Berkshires. By Julie Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   NY-UNDERGROUND (New York) _ In most mythology, the underworld is
a serious and not necessarily pleasant place. It's a place you want
to get out of. Hell, for example. An analogy might be drawn to the
New York subway rider, who, let's face it, wants out. Even today,
when a vast capital improvement program has made the subway system
significantly cleaner, safer, more efficient, more comfortable and
even more attractive than it has been in decades, life underground
resists cheeriness. So when a bright, playful design element
blossoms in our municipal netherworld, it deserves notice, even
gratitude. By Peter Edidin.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
