<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA RESULTS POSE CHALLENGE FOR GOP CONTROL OF HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Voters in California gave Democrats reason to
believe they can take back control of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Assemblyman Mike Honda was the top vote-getter
in the swing 15th District in Santa Clara and Santa Cruz counties,
where most voters are Democrats but have a history of supporting
Republican candidates. Honda captured his party's nomination and
finished ahead of the Republican nominee, Assemblyman Jim Cunneen.
</P>
<P>
   Honda and Cunneen will go head-to-head on Nov. 7 for the seat
being vacated by Republican Tom Campbell, who is running an
underdog campaign for U.S. Senate against incumbent Dianne
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic challenger in the 27th District in Los Angeles
County won more votes than Republican Rep. James Rogan in a beauty
contest in which neither candidate faced competition for their own
party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Darrell Issa, a Republican who lost the 1998 primary
for the U.S. Senate, knocked off state Sen. Bill Morrow for the GOP
nomination for Congress in the 48th District, setting up a
potentially inviting target for Democrats in what historically has
been a Republican stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats need to pick up six seats nationwide to reclaim
control of the House, which they lost to the Republicans in 1994.
So both parties have plenty riding on the 52 California contests to
be decided Nov. 7, particularly in a half-dozen or so races that
are expected to be close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state as a whole has turned Democratic in recent years
with the election of Governor (Gray) Davis and Senator Barbara
Boxer. We have four to six Republican seats that are very
winnable,'' said Jon Del Cecato, spokesman for the national
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. David Dreier, a Republican, said he likes his party's
chances to at least stand its ground in California.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier said he thinks Cunneen will run strong in the 15th
District, a relatively affluent bastion of independent-minded
voters that is represented by Campbell, but formerly by Democrat
Norm Mineta.
</P>
<P>
   ``His basic fiscal conservatism and moderation on social issues
falls right in sync in that district,'' Dreier said of Cunneen.
</P>
<P>
   In a field of nine candidates, however, Honda beat Cunneen 39.6
percent to 33 percent, according to the California secretary of
state's office.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's primary system, the top Republican and
Democratic vote-getters win their party's nomination. Democrat and
Republican voters can cross party lines and cast their ballot for
candidates from the other party.
</P>
<P>
   In another potential trouble spot for Republicans, the 27th
District in Los Angeles County, Rogan was edged by the Democratic
challenger, state Sen. Adam Schiff, 49.1 percent to 47 percent. The
balance of the vote went to Libertarian and Natural Law party
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan served as a House prosecutor during the impeachment of
President Clinton, a role that some analysts expect could hurt the
incumbent with independent voters in November in a state where
Clinton is viewed favorably.
</P>
<P>
   In the military-minded 48th District in northern San Diego
County, Issa, a car-alarm magnate, led Morrow and Mark Dornan, son
of former Rep. Robert Dornan. Issa, Morrow and Dornan are vying to
succeed nine-term Republican Rep. Ron Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Issa had 35 percent to Morrow's 23 percent. Issa would face
Peter Kouvelis, a Marine from Dana Point who was the top Democratic
vote-getter with 11 percent among all voters.
</P>
<P>
   The contest could represent an unexpected opportunity for
Kouvelis and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 Republican Senate primary, Issa confronted questions
about the veracity of autobiographical claims about his Army
career, which were exploited by his opponent, then-state Treasurer
Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Kouvelis could take a page out of Fong's playbook in a district
that hosts Camp Pendleton Marine base.
</P>
<P>
   Another key battleground figures to be the 36th District in Los
Angeles County, where former Rep. Jane Harman hopes to reclaim a
seat from incumbent Rep. Steven Kuykendall. Harman vacated the job
in 1998 for a failed bid for the Democratic nomination for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Kuykendall outdrew Harman 42.2 percent to 40.7
percent, according to the secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, where the GOP hopes to compete for the
Democratic seat held by second-term Rep. Loretta Sanchez, the
results Tuesday won't encourage them.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez had 58 percent and two Republicans on the ballot had 38
percent combined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
