<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATIRE SO TAME IT TAKES THE FUN OUT OF `GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone's a critic. At least two NBC affiliates, one in Salt
Lake City, the other in Pocatello, Idaho, say they will refuse to
air ``God, the Devil and Bob'' when it premieres Thursday night.
Each station is in a community where the Mormon Church dominates
the spiritual side of life (and a lot more), and where irreverence
goes down harder than an aspirin without water.
</P>
<P>
   They'd probably get less notice if they just said the show isn't
airing because it isn't funny. But stations that pre-sanitize for
their viewers' protection probably don't have the greatest senses
of humor and most likely wouldn't know funny from fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't have stations worrying about bruising their
feelings, ``God, the Devil and Bob'' may be remembered as the
dullest example of irreverence since Sister Maurice jabbed me in
the nose during my altar-boy days and I bled like an ``ER'' goner
all over my white surplice.
</P>
<P>
   Sister's initial reaction to the playful jab was priceless. But
when I explained that I could get a nosebleed just by thinking
about it, she seemed strangely disappointed, almost let down that
the moment wasn't as funny/dramatic as it started out.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get the same feeling from ``God, the Devil and
Bob,'' especially after knowing that James Garner is doing the
voice of God in this animated series. There could be no better
voice to give life to an all-knowing, all-seeing, all-laconic deity
than the guy who was both Bret Maverick and Jim Rockford. The fact
that God looks like Jerry Garcia is also a cute fillip, but Garner
doesn't get the necessary support from writers who are obviously
holding back for network TV. Thus, what we get is satire so tame it
wouldn't bite even if it had teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this midseason entry, which launches after
``Friends'' Thursday but moves to Tuesdays at 8:30 next week, is
that God is thinking of ``chucking the whole thing and starting
over,'' to use the big guy's own words.
</P>
<P>
   The devil, delighted at this news, tries to goad God into
pulling the plug right now, but God decides to give humankind one
more chance. He says if one person can prove to him that the world
is worth saving, he'll back off. To be fair, God lets the devil
choose the unwitting schmo who must save the world: a
beer-drinking, porn-watching guy named Bob Alman (voiced by French
Stewart).
</P>
<P>
   God admits Bob isn't a showroom-floor sample of his best work,
but he relents: ``OK, a deal's a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The devil replies: ``And if he fails, you'll destroy the whole
thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tease me,'' the devil warns, ``like with the
flood.''
</P>
<P>
   God replies: ``When are you going to let that go?''
</P>
<P>
   This is about as irreverent as ``God, the Devil and Bob'' gets,
unless you count the part where Bob is in bed explaining this
impossible mission to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna, this is serious,'' he says. ``God has literally put the
fate of mankind in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And these would be the same hands that are inching up my
nightie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a little confidence builder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good night, Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, when in doubt, go with the sex joke. Just like
every other lame sitcom of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The show, created by a former seminary student who had a hand in
two truly forgettable series ``Men Behaving Badly'' and
``Townies,'' kept me thinking of ``The Simpsons,'' as in, ``This
would be so much better if `The Simpsons' people were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Nancy Cartwright, the voice of Bart Simpson,
lends her voice to Bob's rebellious daughter, Megan, but the
``Simpsons'' magic hasn't rubbed off, despite a mother lode of
irreverent possibilities. On cable, in fact, ``God, the Devil and
Bob'' would probably be funny as hell. On NBC, it's more like
purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   God, the Devil and Bob. Half-hour animated comedy about an
average guy chosen to redeem mankind. Voices by James Garner,
French Stewart, Alan Cumming, Laurie Metcalf, Nancy Cartwright and
Kath Soucie. Series premieres Thursday night on NBC, moves to
Tuesdays next week. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
