<HEADLINE>
U.S. FOREIGN POLICY LIKELY TO REMAIN UNCHANGED  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Analysis)   (This 450-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``For goodness sake don't quote me,'' a very senior
Clinton administration official said recently. ``Frankly though,
even if George W. wins the White House, judging by the people
around him, I think the foreign policy he conducts won't be very
different from what you see right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Such of course will not be the impression conveyed as the U.S.
presidential election campaign moves towards its climax later this
year, and accusations of incompetence, bias and pusillanimity fill
the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   But this week's de facto coronation of Vice President Al Gore
and George W. Bush as the Democrat and Republican standard-bearers
in November sets up a choice which, for America's allies, could
hardly be more reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have been mocked for his mangling of the English
language and his inability to name various world leaders in the
news. It is also true that his direct foreign policy experience is
next to nil. But his pedigree is impeccable.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, Sr. too was famous for the malapropisms known as
Bushisms. But by common consent he was one of the most skilled
foreign policy presidents of recent times, and several of his close
aides are helping behind the scenes with his son's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are wise old retainers like Brent Scowcroft, National
Security Advisor between 1989 and 1993, and Condolezza Rice, a key
policymaker on the Soviet Union for George Sr. She is respected by
Democrats as well as Republicans, and tipped as a possible NSA
chief for Bush Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And when thoughts turn to potential Republican secretaries of
state, the name that trips first off almost tongue is that of Colin
Powell, chairman of the Joint Chiefs under Bush, the presidential
dream candidate-who-never-was in 1996, and everybody's favorite
American statesman.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore, his credentials could hardly be better. No vice
president has been more closely involved in foreign policy-making,
with special responsibilities in key areas like Russia.
</P>
<P>
   On many issues, notably the Balkans, his instincts are more
hawkish than those of the current president. For the first time,
too, since Teddy Roosevelt 90 years ago, the U.S. would have a
president interested in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens in November, we're not very worried either
way,'' one British diplomat says, summing up the prevailing mood.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the one discernible frisson is over the man widely
tipped to be Gore's secretary of state, the redoubtable Richard
Holbrooke, current U.S. ambassador to the United Nations and
architect of the Dayton peace accords in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Holbrooke's talents _ only the mixture of
self-promotion and diplomatic thuggery with which he projects
them. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word analysis piece from THE INDEPENDENT
