A0698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POPE-0309-COX     03-08 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POPE-0309-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE'S VISIT, 'OPERATION: OLD FRIEND,' ISRAEL'S BIGGEST SECURITY
CASE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Calling it ``Operation: Old Friend,'' Israeli
officials are planning the biggest security detail in the country's
history for the visit of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most complicated, largest and most sophisticated
security operation of VIP protection that we've ever had,'' Israeli
Police Brigadier General David Tsur told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tsur, 40, is an anti-terrorism specialist who spent a year
consulting with the Georgia Department of Public Safety for the
1996 Olympics in Atlanta. He oversaw Israeli security on the turn
of the millennium and is lead coordinator for the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   He said the visit is a much tougher case than visits of U.S.
President Bill Clinton. Clinton, Tsur said, moves quickly and
usually just attends closed meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, on the other hand, will hold public masses and travel
at low speeds so he can be viewed in his so-called ``Pope mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit is also tougher for its duration. The pope is
scheduled to visit Israel and the Palestinian Authority for six
days. It is the first visit by a pope to the region since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   During his stay, the 79-year-old pontiff is expected to fly to
events in an Israeli Black Hawk helicopter. He is to move in the
narrow stone streets of Jerusalem's Old City in a specially made
mini-Pope mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are currently constructing ramps to smooth out the
stepped paths of the Old City. They are also rushing to finish
seating and staging for an outdoor mass the pope will conduct near
the Sea of Galilee. About 100,000 people are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Tsur said 18,000 police will work during the visit, out of the
national force that has just 26,000 people, including
administrative staff. About 4,000 Israeli soldiers will join them.
</P>
<P>
   He said the visit will cost Israel nearly $10 million, not
including salaries for those involved.
</P>
<P>
   Tsur came to Marietta, Ga., in 1995 with his wife and three
children to consult in the Olympics security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics were bigger, larger, more complicated,'' he said,
``But the pope is a target.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tsur said that police had no knowledge of any specific
threats against the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
