<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-`GOD'-IS-DULL-TEX     03-08 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`GOD'-IS-DULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB' COMMITS CARDINAL SIN OF COMEDY: IT'S NOT
FUNNY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was prime-time animation, and it was
good. But with networks rushing to cash in on the kind of lucrative
'toon trade that helped propel and cement Fox's ``real network''
status (thanks partly to shows such as ``The Simpsons, King of the
Hill, Futurama'' and ``The Family Guy'') the quest for high-quality
material hasn't necessarily kept pace.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if anybody with a home-computer animation program
and an idea that network suits think is edgy and provocative could
score their own series these days. If you still have doubts, check
out the series premiere of NBC's entry into the cartoon cacophony,
``God, the Devil and Bob'' at 7:30 p.m. Thursday. Tackling the
topic of religion (See? Controversial already; in fact, two NBC
affiliates have said they won't air the show.) the show's
pretentious premise would have us believe that God (glumly voiced
by James Garner _ wouldn't George Carlin have been really cool in
this part?) is a sunglasses-wearing hipster who decides one day _
while kicking back with the Devil, no less (given voice by Alan
Cumming, who really should have known better) _ that Earth and all
its problems have grown tiresome. Perhaps, God thinks, it's time to
end his own version of reality programming.
</P>
<P>
   God decides to hang the fate of the world on the shoulders of
one man. To make it sporting, he lets the Devil do the choosing.
Enter Bob (French Stewart, who's getting more annoying every day),
a lazy, inattentive, working-class schlub _ in other words, the
same moron-with-a-heart-of-gold stock character that passes as the
father figure on almost every family cartoon series on TV. (Look up
``Simpson, Homer'' or ``Hill, Hank'' for the best-known
examples.'')
</P>
<P>
   As anyone knows who has been trusted with, say, the
responsibility of sitting next to an emergency-airplane exit,
putting lives in your hands is not a pleasant burden. The premise
seems as though it could generate some comic heat. No such luck. In
fact, things go predictably: God reveals his purpose to Bob, who's
none too pleased with his responsibilities. Neither are Bob's wife
(Laurie Metcalf) or his two children, but he is determined to save
the world in spite of any trickery on the Devil's part. Hilarity
does not ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's because the humor is so forced that you can
almost hear the marketing team telling the writers, ``This sort of
stuff always works on `The Simpsons.' '' Sure, there are lots of
biblical puns and contemporary pop-culture references, but
everything is so safe and bland that it wouldn't offend Steve
Allen. The occasional off-the-cuff church-related remarks on ``The
Simpsons'' are based on compassion for religious principles but
hatred for religious hypocrisy. It's that honesty that makes the
remarks funny. Example: In one episode, Bart Simpson tells his
friend Milhouse that the ``soul'' is something grown-ups invented
just to scare kids, ``like the bogeyman, or Michael Jackson.''
Milhouse then asks Bart what the church would have to gain by such
sleight-of-hand. Cut to the Rev. Lovejoy pouring money from the
offering plates into a coin separator. That scene is more
insightful than three episodes of this ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   The animation fares no better. It's barely a notch above the
``squigglevision'' technique on Comedy Central's ``Dr. Katz,''
which at least has characters that are engaging and likable. And
Cumming's Devil is reduced to a mere annoyance _ not that any
animated Satan will ever come close to matching the dark-comic
hilarity of the ``South Park'' rendition of the Prince of Darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the Devil and Bob'''s most unforgivable trespass is that
it just isn't funny. Future episodes are a little better
(especially when Satan begins dating Bob's daughter while disguised
as the perfect boy) but they unfortunately don't rise above
chuckle-worthy. With luck, perhaps even prayer, NBC will soon smite
this one from its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
