<HEADLINE>
OVEN-FRIED SWEET POTATOES A CANDIED TREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   K. Haby of Granbury, Texas, saw our request for sweet potatoes
``fried'' in the oven. She sent in a recipe from a collection by
the Texas Sheep and Goat Raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Prater of Paradise, Texas, sent the requested slaw
recipe that includes gelatin in the dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gunn clipped a soup recipe from this section several years
ago. He made it, loved it and lost the recipe. Here it is again,
courtesy of Craig Claiborne's ``The New York Times Cook Book''
(Harper &AMP; Row, $25).
</P>
<P>
   CANDIED YAMS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   4 medium-sized sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Dash of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon or nutmeg or 1/2 teaspoon of each
</P>
<P>
   3/4 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   4 slices lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Peel and cut potatoes as for thick french fries. Place in
8-by-12-by-2-inch baking dish. Cover potatoes with sugar and salt.
Sprinkle spices over sugar (more spice can be used). Cover with
pieces of butter. Twist slices of lemon over this and place peel in
with the potatoes. Sift flour evenly over the potatoes. Add water
to mixture. Bake at 400 degrees for 1 hour or until potatoes are
done and sugar-butter mix has become thick. Baste frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 307 calories, 10 grams fat, 54
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 26 milligrams cholesterol,
152 milligrams sodium, 29 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SPICY COLE SLAW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded or coarsely chopped red or green cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, seeded and chopped coarsely
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped cilantro or parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   Red or green cabbage leaves, optional
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle gelatin over cold water in a medium saucepan; let stand
1 minute. Stir over low heat until gelatin is completely dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk thoroughly to blend gelatin, sour cream
and mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in all remaining ingredients except cabbage leaves. Pour
into 6 1-cup bowls or molds lined with cabbage leaves, if desired.
Chill until firm, about 3 hours. Unmold onto a serving platter.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 245 calories, 24 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 34 milligrams cholesterol,
425 milligrams sodium, 86 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COCK-A-LEEKIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-10
</P>
<P>
   1 (3 1/2-pound) frying chicken, cut up
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 parsley sprigs, tied together
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon peppercorns, crushed
</P>
<P>
   8 to 12 leeks
</P>
<P>
   6 medium potatoes, peeled and cubed, or 1/2 cup uncooked rice
</P>
<P>
   Simmer chicken, covered, in water with next 5 ingredients for
about 1 hour, until tender. Remove chicken and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Split leeks lengthwise and wash thoroughly. Cut into 1-inch
lengths, using both the white and green portions. Add to chicken
stock. Add potatoes or rice and boil for about 20 minutes, until
tender. Remove parsley and bay leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, remove skin and bones of chicken and cut meat into
large bite-size pieces. Add to soup, adjust seasonings, and reheat.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For an updated version, the soup can be pureed in a
blender (in small batches) after the parsley and bay leaf have been
removed. Add chicken pieces (shredded is better in a pureed soup)
and reheat.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 237 calories, 5 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 52 milligrams cholesterol,
307 milligrams sodium, 18 percent of calories from fat. Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Renee Schwarz was recently visiting Fort Worth. She saw a ``cake
in a jar'' in a craft mall and remembers also seeing them in New
Hampshire and Massachusetts at craft fairs. Does anyone have the
recipe for these cakes that are baked in pint-size canning jars and
then sealed, making them last for up to six months?
</P>
<P>
   Judy Spaeth would like a recipe for molasses cookies that an
aunt made in the 1960s. They were soft, and she thinks they were
rolled in sugar and then flattened with a fork before baking.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
