<HEADER>
A0711 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DYSON-KINGBOOK-TEX     03-08 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYSON-KINGBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT, NOT PERFECT: MARTIN LUTHER KING AN ANCESTOR OF RAP, AUTHOR
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Eric Dyson thinks Martin Luther King Jr. is the greatest
American ever, greater than Washington or Jefferson or any other
contender.
</P>
<P>
   But part of his respect for the late civil rights leader is a
belief ``that (King) proves God uses deeply flawed human beings to
do great things.'' So in ``I May Not Get There With You: The True
Martin Luther King Jr.'' (Free Press, $25), Dyson, a professor at
DePaul University and author of several books about
African-American leaders and culture, reflects candidly on what he
says is King's occasional penchant for plagiarism, extramarital
affairs and militantism even as he praises him for eloquence,
leadership and courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to know why there had to be yet another
biography of Martin Luther King, well, he's wrongly been made out
over the years as a simple icon,'' Dyson said on a recent visit to
the Star-Telegram. ``And when he has been simplified, his legend
and words have been twisted in support of people and causes he
would never, ever have embraced. Now when he is remembered, people
forget how he was a radical threat to the status quo. He would not
only have approved of, he would have stood alongside, Jesse Jackson
and Al Sharpton today. His sanitation, as I call it, reduces him,
and I don't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, 41, an ordained Baptist minister, said his fascination
with King began in 1968, when he was 9. ``He was assassinated that
year, and I really didn't know who he was,'' Dyson said. ``As, over
the years, I learned more about him, I kept wanting to know more.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson eventually began to write books _ ``Making Malcolm: The
Myth and Meaning of Malcolm X'' (Oxford University Press, $10.95);
``Race Rules: Navigating the Color Line'' (Vintage Books, $12);
``Between God and Gangsta Rap'' (Oxford University Press, $27.50) _
which earned him recognition as an eloquent spokesman for black
Americans. But ``I May Not Get There With You,'' he said, isn't
doing as much for his reputation, at least among African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this book tour I'm doing lots of call-in (radio) shows,''
Dyson said. ``Those calls offer me a lot of resistance, especially
from black people. I knew, in being candid about this man, who is a
sort of sacrosanct ideal, I would encounter resistance, but I
didn't anticipate the virulence. I'm being accused of trying to
hurt his legacy, when all I want is for people to truly understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dyson's view, Martin Luther King Jr. was a militant, a
committed economic socialist whose focus in his last days had
expanded from civil rights to deepening concern about economic
injustice and the Vietnam War as an outgrowth of mainstream
America's desire to keep lower-income citizens of all races out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dyson said, King is a direct ancestor of rap music and
hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting Tupac Shakur or Snoop Doggy Dogg are the
moral equivalent of King, but, like him, they are trying to address
great things,'' Dyson said. ``They are very young; Martin Luther
King burst on the national scene as a very young man. He was 39
when he died, remember. That is not great old age. So when I see
the modern voices being denigrated for personal mistakes these
young people make, I would like them to think of King and know they
can surmount obstacles that hinder their success.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Dyson contends, ``in a way, his death at 39 saved him.
His popularity was down, way down, especially in the black
community. Other leaders _ Stokely Carmichael, (H. Rap) Brown, were
calling him soft. He was labeled insufficiently radical, in some
ways as insufficiently black. Had he lived, he probably would not
have been remembered later as a holy celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, of course, you can't find a white person who claims to
have hated him or a black person who claims not to have marched
with him. Everybody now says they loved him then. It wasn't so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I May Not Get There With You'' is explicit in recounting
King's ``borrowing'' the words of others in speeches, sermons and
books. It documents King's constant womanizing. But Dyson believes
there are explanations, although not excuses, for King's flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preachers always borrow ideas from each other,'' he said.
``That's just the way it was always done. And (King) understood he
was wrong to have women other than his wife. He acknowledged his
weaknesses. In sermons he would emphasize he was not a saint, but a
sinner like everyone listening to him. He was, in fact, a
chauvinist, though I think he would have learned better had he
lived longer.''
</P>
<P>
   King's heroism, Dyson believes, comes from ``pushing the status
quo, pointing out wrongs and insisting things be changed, carrying
on in spite of hate and personal weakness and surely feeling
overwhelmed with the burden of it all. He was an authentic voice
for blacks, and not just with the `I have a dream' speech. I
recommend we take a 10-year moratorium on repeating words from that
speech, so people can see all the other things \RKing\S had to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic, Dyson said, that Ronald Reagan signed papers
mandating King's birthday as a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``King was deeply critical of Reagan,'' who was then governor of
California, Dyson said. ``He represented what Martin Luther King
found reprehensible in public life: a failure to oppose forces
undermining minorities and lower-income Americans. But now
conservatives use (King's) words to support ideas he would have
scorned, portraying him as colorblind and claiming he would have
opposed affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Dyson said, King should be remembered ``as a strong
voice, and evolving voice, that spoke for black Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, however, Dyson said he has no misgivings about
pointing out King's flaws. ``If it makes people think about him,
truly understand him a little, even if their response is to attack
me, then to an extent I've succeeded,'' Dyson said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
