<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISITINGTHEDOCTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RX FOR MAKING THE MOST OF A DOCTOR VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never go to a doctor's appointment alone, and always insist on
getting out of that floppy paper exam gown before attempting any
meaningful discussion.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bottom line from two health-care experts who advise
patients to prepare for a medical appointment with a specific list
of questions and rehearse what they want to ask the physician _ out
loud, in front of a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Better communication spells safer medicine, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Half of people who visit their doctor return home poorly
informed about what ails them and ill-equipped to play a
constructive role in their own healing, say the authors of
``Surviving Modern Medicine: How to Get the Best From Doctors,
Family &AMP; Friends'' (Rutgers University Press, $17 paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Adverse drug reactions, which the health system can prevent by
carefully taking medical histories, have grown into a leading cause
of deaths: 45,000 last year (about equal to highway fatalities).
</P>
<P>
   ``And, they are completely avoidable,'' says Peter Clarke,
professor of preventive medicine at the University of Southern
California School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   He and Susan Evans, research scientist with USC School of
Medicine's Institute for Health Promotion and Disease Prevention,
have written ``Surviving Modern Medicine'' to help patients
navigate the dangers inherent in a system in which microbiology,
immunology and genetics have gained tremendous ground, while the
arts of listening to a patient and doing a thorough physical exam
have deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure your doctor knows all your prescription drugs and
the herbal and nonprescription drugs you are taking,'' Evans says.
``Aspirin can interact with prescription blood-thinners. People say
herbals are `natural,' but so is poison ivy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The authors were in Fort Worth recently to promote the book,
which throws out a lifeline to help consumers survive and perhaps
even thrive on modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of medical consultations end with prescription
drugs, but half the time drugs are prescribed, the patient doesn't
take them according to how the drugs were prescribed,'' Clarke
says.
</P>
<P>
   Between one-half and two-thirds of patients do not adhere to
prescribed treatment plans, largely because they leave the doctor's
office without understanding what they are supposed to do, Clarke
contends.
</P>
<P>
   They don't pay attention to the timing between doses, the time
of day they take drugs or whether they are supposed to take them
with or without meals. Too often, consumers underdose and overdose
and suspend taking the drug before the prescription runs out, or do
not get a refill in time to prevent running out of an ongoing
medication, so there's a gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seriously compromise treatment by not complying with our
doctor's orders because we haven't asked the questions that nail
down what the doctor actually said,'' Evans says. ``If you are
diagnosed with diabetes or hypertension, you will likely be on oral
medication the rest of your life, but a lot of people take one
round and think they are cured.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Surviving Modern Medicine'' offers tips on how to avoid common
mistakes in choosing among treatment options; how to mobilize
effective support among relatives and friends; how to make certain
your end-of-life wishes are respected; and how to get your doctor
to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   It advises patients to get second opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, when a patient goes into the exam room, he goes
into information shutdown, especially if it is for a serious
diagnostic exam,'' Evans says. ``And, it's accelerated when you put
on that floppy paper gown.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell the doctor you want to get dressed and then talk, she
advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a quota system and are under intense pressure to put
patients through the system quickly, but it's a nicety to let you
get dressed before you talk so you don't feel exposed and
vulnerable, subconsciously,'' Clarke says.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a companion. It changes the dynamics. You have a second
voice and a second brain. More questions get asked, more clinical
options presented. You are more secure, so your heart rate is more
normal and more information is processed. You get more physician
time. Quality skyrockets. Never go to the doctor alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great gift we baby boomers can give our parents: go
with them to the doctor,'' Evans urges.
</P>
<P>
   She and Clarke say they wrote the book to help consumers unravel
their confusions and to increase the quality of their medical care
_ indeed, to survive modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to produce an interactive, online version in the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   When you go to the doctor:
</P>
<P>
   Write down your questions and rehearse them beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Bring someone with you for an extra pair of ears.
</P>
<P>
   Take notes so you remember the important stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Don't leave until you ask:
</P>
<P>
   1. What is wrong with me?
</P>
<P>
   2. What tests do I need?
</P>
<P>
   3. What will happen during the procedures?
</P>
<P>
   4. What treatments do I need?
</P>
<P>
   5. What should I do to help myself?
</P>
<P>
   6. When will I feel better?
</P>
<P>
   7. When should I see you again?
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Surviving Modern Medicine''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
