<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING OUT YOUR LANDSCAPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The landscape around your home is important because it can
enhance the home's appearance, and add as much as 15 percent equity
to its value, real estate agents estimate.
</P>
<P>
   A good landscape starts with a wellthought out ground plan.
Before attempting to set anything down on paper, you must first
consider the terrain, the size and shape of the house, the soil
composition and the climate. You should also consider the needs and
requirements of your family.
</P>
<P>
   Start inside the house. Go from room to room and look at the
views from each window. Decide which ones can be enhanced with
greenery and which ones should be hidden. Move outside and walk
around your property. Look carefully at the terrain and evaluate
its good and bad features. Choose areas you want to leave open for
recreation and sections where you want shade. Do you want to set
aside some property for a vegetable garden?
</P>
<P>
   Consider the slope of the land. Ground with a steep pitch is
subject to erosion, and it can be difficult to maintain. In these
areas, it is best to use plants with a spreading root system so
they can hold the soil together. As an alternative, you can terrace
the land by installing retaining walls. Retaining walls are a lot
of work to put in, but they can prevent soil erosion and help cut
down on yard maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Next, consider the house itself. Try walking across the street
and looking at your house and property from a distance. What
features would you like to accent and which would you like to hide?
Does your house reflect a particular architectural period? If so,
you should choose shrubs and designs that complement that period
(this may require some research).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consider what various shrubs can do for you and how you
want to use them. It is obvious that they can be used to control
soil erosion and create shade, but they can be used in other ways
as well. Shrubs like barberry or escallonia are dense enough to be
used as a windbreak for cold winter winds, or they can be arranged
to funnel breezes toward the house during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some shrubs with thorny leaves, like the purple-leaf Japanese
barberry, can be used as a barrier against trespassers or as
channels to direct people and animals to areas where you want them
to go. Thick shrubs can also be used to insulate the house from
street noises.
</P>
<P>
   Shrubs can be used aesthetically to frame an area, and to create
mood and atmosphere. A shrub like the red-twigged dogwood has
colorful red branches that can add color to a drab winter
landscape. Colorful plants and flowers are especially effective
around the entrance to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Shrubs can be used to accent driveways and walks or to call
attention to a particular architectural feature of the house. You
can add dramatic accents by setting dark green masses against
light-colored flowerbeds. Large shrubs and trees can be used to
ease the transition from the hard lines of a house to the softer,
natural lines of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few things to avoid when drawing up your ground
plan. Driveways and walkways can be accented with shrubs, but these
plants should be low _ hostas are a good choice _ so they do not
obstruct sightlines. This is particularly important at the end of
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid planting trees too close to the house. As they grow, they
will develop overhanging branches that may provide a pathway to the
roof and chimney for squirrels and other small rodents. Also,
leaves falling from the branches in the fall will collect in the
rain gutters and clog them. For security reasons, do not plant
large clumps of dense bushes near the house. They can provide
effective cover for a burglar attempting a break-in.
</P>
<P>
   When you have your basic plan on paper, visit a nursery and
discuss your plans with specialists. They can analyze the strengths
and weakness of your plan, estimate costs and offer suggestions on
the type of plants that will thrive in your soil and which shrubs
are best for your design.
</P>
<P>
   You can, of course, begin landscaping anywhere on your property,
but it's best to start close to the house because it is the most
important element. Start with foundation plantings. Plant a few
species in repetitive arrangements to create a unified design and
eliminate a cluttered look.
</P>
<P>
   Ground cover like pachysandra, vinca minor and periwinkle are
good choices for the foundation because they absorb runoff from the
roof before it can seep through the foundation into the basement.
When time and money permit, move to adjacent areas to complete your
landscape plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
