<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. If the Universal Serial Bus is so universal, why are there
both powered and nonpowered hubs available for adding USB devices?
</P>
<P>
   A. Most current PC's and Macintoshes have only two USB ports
available. To plug in more than two USB products at a time, you can
attach a hub _ a small, multiport connection device _ to one of the
existing ports to add four, six or however many more USB ports you
need. Most basic hubs have four USB ports, and you can add up to
127 USB devices to your computer by linking hubs upon hubs.
</P>
<P>
   The type of hub you need, either a powered one that also has to
plug in to an electrical outlet or one that doesn't, depends on the
types of devices you are using. Some USB peripherals, like mice and
keyboards, are low-power additions and can draw the energy they
need to operate directly from the USB port. If you have a bunch of
low-powered devices (check your products manual if you're not
sure), you can get away with using a cheaper, nonpowered USB hub to
connect them all.
</P>
<P>
   Things like digital cameras are usually high-power devices and
need more electricity than what the USB port can provide. In such
cases, you will need a powered hub that also plugs into the wall as
well as into your computer to give you the power you need.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two PC's at home and would like to connect them so
they can both use the cable modem. What do I need to create a basic
home network?
</P>
<P>
   A. Creating your own network, which may sound like a rather
ominous task, can be as simple as connecting two computers together
with a direct cable connection or by their USB ports. That type of
network tends to be slow, and the computers have to be fairly close
together.
</P>
<P>
   The home-network market is booming, and there are several
options available that might give better results with your cable
modem. Computer stores sell a variety of home-networking starter
kits that include enough hardware to connect two computers, plus
specific instructions on the set-up process for the type of network
you've chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Ethernet is one of the most frequently used technologies, and
many companies use it for their office networks for both Windows
and Macintosh computers. A Home Ethernet starter kit costing $80 to
$100 will usually include the Ethernet hub, the proper cables and
the Ethernet add-in cards to hook up two computers.
</P>
<P>
   If your computers are scattered through the house, creating a
network through your home telephone wiring might be a smart choice.
With special adapter cards and software, Home Phoneline Networking
allows you to plug your computer into telephone wall jacks (without
interfering with the use of the telephones) and create a network
that can rival Ethernet speeds. Prices vary, but you should be able
to find a kit for $100 to $150.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless technology is also making inroads into the
home-networking market, although a cable-free network is still a
little pricier than one with wires. Some cost around $400 or more.
Plugging a wireless card into your computer means it does not need
to be near either an electrical outlet or a telephone jack, and
people with laptop computers may enjoy the freedom of being able to
be networked from up to 150 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Home Free Networks (www.homefree-networks.com) from Diamond
Multimedia sells both wireless and phone-line kits, and the site
has a section for frequently asked questions about home networking
for PC's. Linksys.com (www.linksys.com) sells both phone-line and
Ethernet starter kits. Other resources you may want to check out
for general information include the Home Networking home page
(www.home-networking.org) and Cable-Modem.Net's page on home
networks at www.cable-modem.net/tt/networking.html.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
