<HEADER>
A0720 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DRIVER-LICENSES-N     03-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DRIVER-LICENSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES TRY ONLINE OPTION FOR DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the scourges of modern life _ waiting in line at the
motor vehicle department _ may soon be a thing of the past as
states begin to make driver's license renewals, along with motor
vehicle registration and other types of licensing, available
online.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is leading the way, having put its driver's license
renewal program online in January. Colorado, Arizona, Texas and a
handful of other states are expected to have similar programs
operating before the end of the year. Some already offer online
registration of motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Online license renewal not only eliminates the chore of waiting
in long lines, but it also makes the service available 24 hours a
day, 7 days a week, and to residents who are living out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first person we got to renew his license online was
stationed in Fort Benning, Ga.,'' said Richard Holcomb, Virginia's
Department of Motor Vehicles commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of person we want to help. Otherwise, he would
have had to get a military extension or taken a day off to come to
Virginia to visit one of our offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Holcomb said, the state handles about 30 online license
renewals every day. The cost for renewing online is the same as it
is for renewing in person, and the fee can be paid with a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan to keep adding to the list of services available
online, things like ordering a personalized license plate, filing a
change of address or replacing a lost or stolen license or
identification card.
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility requirements for online license renewal vary
slightly from state to state, but typically a driver with
outstanding traffic violations or anyone who needs to take a
driving test must visit an office for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, anyone who has a medical condition like epilepsy or
a significant vision impairment would have to come into an office
for renewal. About 1 million of the 1.5 million drivers whose
licenses are up for renewal each year are eligible to use the
state's online service.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia, which requires license renewals every five years,
will not allow license holders to renew online twice in a row.
``Every 10 years you'll need to come in and get a new picture and
your eyes examined,'' Holcomb said.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, about a dozen of the state's 711 licenses _ for
things like driving, fishing, camping and real estate sales _ will
be available for online renewal later this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern about the length of time between eye
examinations for some drivers. Marc Holtzman, the state's
technology secretary, and the Colorado Department of Motor Vehicles
are looking into several options for eye exams. One option could be
to have a driver visit an eye doctor for an exam, then have that
doctor also send the file online.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility might be to conduct the eye exam on the
Internet. ``We would have to know whether or not the person taking
the test is the person applying for the license,'' said Don Burton,
program director for driver's licenses services with the Colorado
Department of Motor Vehicles, citing one of the problems with that
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado and some other states require that a driver renewing a
license be fingerprinted. But Burton said that problem might be
resolved by using another method to confirm a person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to provide information the driver needs to know,
like a confirmation number or other verifiers that people trying to
renew would have to know,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   He compared it to calling a bank for account information and
being required to give a mother's maiden name or a Social Security
number.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid fraud, Virginia assigns a personal identification
number, or PIN, to a person and mails it to his or her home. ``We
have had a couple of situations where we had to investigate,''
Holcomb said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in Texas called Virginia officials when she got the card
with her PIN, which she had not requested. It turned out that the
woman's Social Security number and birth date had been used by her
sister to get a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to have instances where people can abuse
the system,'' Holtzman said, ``and unless we can be persuaded that
the risk of these abuses is higher over the Net, then we are going
to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem that concerns Burton is the ``motor voter''
registration, the piggybacking of voting registration on top of
motor vehicle licensing or registration. Voting registration
requires an individual's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see if the county clerks will recognize and accept
an electronic signature,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia has dealt with this problem by creating a voter
registration form that can be filled out online but is then printed
and mailed to a person, who signs it and mails it back.
</P>
<P>
   While online renewals are motivated in part by budget
considerations, it is unlikely that state government jobs will
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers' renewing online, Burton said, ``helps us by having them
not come into an office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one less person we have to deal with or that has to
wait in line,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
