<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOIC-MCCAIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN STOIC AS BLOWS RAIN DOWN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This 325-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If everything had gone according to the script, it
would have been a truly arresting venue for a victory bash.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that John McCain would emerge triumphant from his
``Super Tuesday'' showdown with George W. Bush, then crow about it
in the sort of setting most Republicans wouldn't approach if their
lives depended on it: a funky design center in the hottest area for
gay nightlife in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But, as became increasingly clear in the closing stages of the
campaign, that wasn't what the script portended at all.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did McCain fall far short of his rival, he stumbled
particularly badly in the state where he had hoped for his greatest
popular triumph, California.
</P>
<P>
   And when he appeared beneath the glass and steel atrium of the
Pacific Design Center on Tuesday night, he was met not by a
seething mass of ardent supporters but by a small band of hard-core
cheerleaders vastly outnumbered by the serried ranks of the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hosting a rowdy party, the best McCain could do was
to sound stoic about the body blows Bush had inflicted and try not
to pay too much attention to the echoing empty corridors that
surrounded the small frenzy of attention immediately around him.
</P>
<P>
   The disco music was cranked up to full volume, the silvery
streamers were released and the red, white and blue plastic
pom-poms were distributed to anyone interested.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been convincing but for the forlorn outlying
tables lined with unopened bottles and the hot plates stuffed to
the brim with kosher hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my friends, we won a few and lost a few today,'' McCain
began. The crowd didn't seem too maudlin about the bad news,
cheering and whelping ``Go, John, go!.'' For his part, McCain vowed
that his ``crusade'' to clean up public life would carry on
regardless. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 325-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
