<SLUG> BC-ADIEU-MCCAINBRADLEY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VS. GORE: WHAT A CRASHING BORE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This incisive 600-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``p'' political
news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So at least we now know where we stand. Following the electoral
fireworks of ``Super Tuesday'' _ ``Mega Tuesday,'' as some
commentators took to calling it _ we now know that it is George W.
Bush and Al Gore who will confront each other in the U.S.
presidential elections in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, who put the liberal cat among the cautious
pigeons, and John McCain, the Vietnam veteran who was unafraid to
call a spade a spade, are both out for the count.
</P>
<P>
   California and New York were among the states that gave the
all-round thumbs-down to Bradley and McCain, who both now look set
to acknowledge the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the two outsiders is a loss for American
politics. Both provided alternative voices that needed _ and need _
to be heard. We are now left with the old Establishment, scarcely
shaken or stirred.
</P>
<P>
   This exciting stage of the primaries will, however, leave at
least a trace. The waters are likely to close over the now-drowning
Bradley, whose main legacy will be a reminder that one has to be
seriously tough in order to become a presidential candidate. Nice
man though he was, he failed that basic test.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, by contrast, may have done U.S. politics a lasting favor
with his successes in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, he is not quite the liberal he is sometimes
purported to be. He is a classic conservative on many issues, from
abortion to gun control. But he has shown a sense of morality,
which is in itself to be admired.
</P>
<P>
   He has displayed a conviction that he lives for his beliefs,
rather than because of a craving for power.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments of recent weeks would suggest that this could be
the death of caring conservatism. Bush appears to have thrown his
lot in with the religious right. But there is little evidence that
Bush will prove some intolerant monster.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, he may well be as liberal as McCain would
have been. Nor, despite his apparent eagerness to please the
redneck right in recent weeks, will he necessarily stay painted
into that corner.
</P>
<P>
   This stage of the primaries is notable for forcing people to
define themselves in opposition to their opponents, and to target a
particular niche. Once the field has thinned out, the candidate can
afford to become more all-embracing.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never seem to change. The most notorious moment in
the campaign waged by George Bush (senior) was when he tried to
paint his opponent, Michael Dukakis, as soft on a convicted rapist.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect (as in so many others), George W. appears to be
ready to follow in daddy's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's recent radio ads, McCain stands accused of voting
against research funds for breast cancer _ though even Bush, it now
emerges, does not claim to believe this line. (In reality, McCain's
track record on the voting was at least as good, probably better,
than that of Bush himself.)
</P>
<P>
   It is a pity if straight lies are considered an acceptable form
of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   One source of regret must be that the excitement of the election
has now been punctured. Now that it has turned into a two-man race,
the voters can afford to get truly bored.
</P>
<P>
   Short of unexpected dramas or some especially vile mudslinging,
this may become a wooden campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore or Bush: two dependable pairs of hands on the tiller. The
course looks set to be steady as she goes. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 600-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
