<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0727 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     03-08 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILLING TALE OF `DELICIEUX' MEAT PIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATCHITOCHES, La. _ There are a few questions that quickly pop
to mind when you pull off the Interstate and travel deep into the
wooded canopy of historic downtown Natchitoches. The foremost
question is, ``How in the heck do you pronounce this place?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is Nack-a-tish, a pronunciation that neither sounds
like nor looks like Natchitoches, an Indian name that means there
are some really good meat pies just this side of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not a river that runs through it. The Red River
once changed its course and meandered past this northern Louisiana
hamlet, but then the river changed again, leaving a narrow lake.
</P>
<P>
   The second question here is, ``Why all the French influence this
far north?''The answer is that this community is the oldest
permanent settlement in Louisiana. It was founded in 1714 by the
French to promote trade with the local Indians and the Spanish in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the really important question: ``Where do I get one of
those meat pies?''
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone around and they'll direct you to Second Street and
Lasyone's Meat Pie Kitchen and Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   There are other places to get meat pies, but Lasyone's was the
first and it remains the most celebrated. The walls in the entryway
are blanketed with framed magazine covers from Southern Living, The
New Yorker, Gourmet and Glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Columns by prominent food writers such as Calvin Trillin share
the precious space, along with autographed photos of Lorne Greene,
Vanna White, Daryl Hannah, and the cast and crew of ``Steel
Magnolias,'' which was filmed here.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kuralt brought his ``On the Road'' to James Lasyone's
place. ``Good Morning America'' followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been fortunate,'' Lasyone said of his restaurant's
reputation. ``It was a hit the day it opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Just where meat pies began, no one seems to know. Lasyone said
he has tried to trace their origin, without success. Some people
place their beginnings at the time of the Civil War; others guess
much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I grew up around here, in the country, and
when we came to town we would buy them off of street carts that had
wood burning in the bottom to keep the pies warm. The pies were a
nickel apiece back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasyone began his business on Second Street in 1967 after 25
years in the grocery business right next door. Things were changing
in Natchitoches. A mall was opening and many of the downtown
businesses were moving. ``They kept telling me I was crazy to stay
here, but I thought it would work.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried to borrow money for his new venture, but no one would
go the loan, so he gathered up $3.95 for a small burner and $3 for
a ``little black pot'' and began cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have that pot. It's hanging over the salad bar,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasyone's Meat Pie Kitchen was the first place in Natchitoches
to offer meat pies. Street vendors and family cooks had made them
for years, but they were never available over the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a doctor who was a customer at the grocery store, and I
sold meat to his mama every week for meat pies,'' Lasyone said.
``She is really where I got the idea to make them in a
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   He finagled the local recipes and tweaked them a little here and
there; he won't say exactly what goes into a Lasyone meat pie.
</P>
<P>
   While other makers use machines to turn out manufactured pies,
Lasyone proudly insists that his are made by hand. It takes time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a lot of them during our Christmas festival,'' he
said. ``We begin making them in August, freezing them and getting
them ready. We'll make between 12,000 and 14,000, and that will
barely get us midway through December.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't do mail order _ although he says he could get rich
just selling off the Internet _ but if you bring your own cooler,
he'll help pack it with a little ice and a lot of frozen meat pies.
Texans, he said, are among his most frequent customers.
</P>
<P>
   Lasyone won't give up his recipe, but other locals will share
theirs. Here is one from one of the area's most heralded cookbooks,
``Cane River Cuisine.'' It is a popular recipe (submitted by Mrs.
Charles E. Cloutier) that has been requested time and time again.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NATCHITOCHES MEAT PIES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 28
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground pork
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green onions, tops and bottoms
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarsely ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Crust:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 heaping cup Crisco, not melted
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Combine ground beef, ground pork, onions and seasonings in large
Dutch oven. Cook over medium heat, stirring often until meat loses
its red color. Do not overcook the meat. Sift the flour over meat
mixture, stirring often, until well-combined with meat. Remove from
heat and cool to room temperature. Place meat in a large colander
to drain off excess grease and juice.
</P>
<P>
   For crust, sift flour and cut shortening into flour. Add beaten
egg and milk. Form dough into a ball. Roll about 1/3 of the dough
at a time on a lightly floured board or pastry cloth. Cut dough
into 5- to 5 1/2-inch circles and place them on a cookie sheet,
separated by wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Place a heaping tablespoon of filling on one side
of the pastry round. Dampen edge of pie containing meat with
fingertips, fold top over meat and crimp with fork dipped in water.
Prick with fork twice on top.
</P>
<P>
   To fry: Fry in deep-fat fryer at 350 degrees until golden brown.
These meat pies freeze beautifully if enclosed in plastic sandwich
bags. When frying frozen meat pies, do not thaw before frying.
Cocktail meat pies may be made the same way, using a biscuit cutter
and 1 teaspoon of meat filling.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 210 calories, 14 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 44 milligrams cholesterol,
401 milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
