<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEXAS-RESEARCH09-COX     03-08 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RESEARCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXANS UNITE TO FIGHT FOR FEDERAL RESEARCH FUNDS
 &HT;    Attn: Texas points.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Texas congressional delegation pledged
Wednesday that it would try to help the state's universities and
colleges scoop up a bigger share of the fast-rising tide of federal
research dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned when I learned that, with the excellent research
facilities we have, and with Texas as the second largest state,
nevertheless, we rank sixth in research dollars to our universities
from the federal government,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, sixth is not good enough,'' Hutchison said at the
end of a 90-minute ``higher education summit'' she convened for
Texans from Congress and educators led by the chancellors of the
University of Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, the University of Houston and Texas
Tech systems.
</P>
<P>
   During their strategy session in the Capitol's Lyndon B. Johnson
Room, they agreed by consensus to pursue a common goal: ``The
chancellors and the delegation will strive to place Texas among the
top three states with regard to participation in federal research
activities by the year 2005.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bipartisan effort,'' stressed Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, a
Democrat from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Between the 1991 and 1998 fiscal years, Texas got $846 million
of the $16 billion that federal departments and agencies spent on
university-based science and engineering research, according to the
National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   It ranked sixth each year, far behind behind California ($2.3
billion) and New York ($1.3 billion). The three states most
vulnerable to a surge by Texas are Maryland ($993 million),
Pennsylvania ($961 million) and Massachusetts ($939 million), which
jockeyed back and forth between third, fourth and fifth places in
those years.
</P>
<P>
   Together the six states sucked in 54 percent of the federal
government's university-based research funds. Texas officials have
estimated that every federal dollar spent on research generates
more than three dollars in economic activity within the state.
</P>
<P>
   As a first step, the educators agreed to assemble an inventory
of the research capabilities of all Texas colleges, research
centers and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said they would arrange for the educators to get
briefings from federal agencies with similar research priorities.
Since the squeaky wheel often gets the grease in Washington, that
could help them get more of the agencies' discretionary grants.
</P>
<P>
   Direct lobbying can't increase the state's share of competitive
grants, because those grants are awarded on the basis of the
recommendations of panels of senior researchers at prestigious
institutions in each field.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, the lawmakers plan to fight for higher funding
of grant competitions in which the unique research capabilities of
Texas institutions would give them an excellent chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Among the examples mentioned at the meeting:
</P>
<P>
   _ Because Texas has world-class medical research centers, it
would benefit from plans to double the $7 billion in annual
research spending by the National Institutes of Health over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ More emphasis on research into bioterrorism and chemical
warfare could help Texas A&AMP;M, the University of Texas and Texas
Tech, which have expertise in areas ranging from biochemistry to
counter-terrorism training for fire and police departments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extra funding in their specialties could help research by
Prairie View A&AMP;M on goats, Texas A&AMP;M on carrots, and the University
of North Texas on high school math.
</P>
<P>
   The past fund-grabbing success of researchers in California and
New York helped them elbow Texas aside in the scramble for more
federal dollars, Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the chicken and the egg,'' Hutchison said.
``California hired the best people, who got more federal funding,
which was used to hire more of the best people.''
</P>
<P>
   Public universities employ eight Nobel laureates in Texas and 19
in California, the Chronicle of Higher Education reported last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has two top-tier research institutions (University of
Texas at Austin and Texas A&AMP;M at College Station), while California
has 10. That status is based largely on the number of doctoral
degrees awarded in different fields and the amount spent on
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston, San Antonio and Dallas are the only cities among the
nation's 10 largest that don't have a Tier One research
university,'' Arthur Smith, chancellor of the University of Houston
System said at the summit. He said that states with more top-tier
research universities attract more federal research funds.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
