<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      03-08 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 Dealing with guns at a child's level   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does a boy become a man? According to news reports, one way
is to take a gun and kill someone.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old boy shot and killed a 6-year-old girl in Michigan,
and became known in news reports as ``the youngest gunman in a
series of deadly school shootings.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that what he wanted to do? Be a gunman? Was he playing
grown-up? Or was he just playing ``Bang, bang, you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you read how he aimed the pistol at one classmate and then
``whirled and fired'' at the little girl? It's like a scene out of
a movie and sounds like the little boy knew the pose.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of kids do, even those whose parents don't allow guns,
real ones or toy versions, in their home. It's almost like they're
born to it, said one mother who was startled to watch her
5-year-old grab a stick, wrap his two hands around it, stretch his
arms out straight and squint at a target.
</P>
<P>
   They're so quickly acculturated to gunplay. They don't know how
to tie their shoes but they know how to whirl and fire like a
character on ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time kids pick up guns, we wring our hands over how often
they're exposed to violent images. And while it sounds like this
little boy lived in a more perilous environment than most, all kids
are early learners in gunplay. They get it from movies, TV and
computer games, and they're great copycats.
</P>
<P>
   Kids play ``guns.'' They always have, people say, fondly
remembering their own Davy Crockett rifle. But you know,I think
people were smarter then. Either that or we've allowed kids to
become terribly confused. Now that there's been this horror in
Michigan, what will we do?
</P>
<P>
   Probably the usual. We'll speak of our shock and outrage and
then get into a nowhere debate over gun control. Children shoot
children, a couple of politicians declare it ``a wake-up call'' and
then we all go to sleep again.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not confident anymore that adults can fix this problem. I
think our generation is beyond learning. We're a gun-happy society.
Since we obviously can't separate adults from their guns, we'll
have to try re-educating our kids.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a radical idea, taken from the anti-war stalwarts who
every Christmas try to encourage parents not to buy toy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   We ban toy guns. We take a stand against all forms of gunplay.
We say that pretend violence is messing up our kids and we do what
we can to make all guns, make-believe and otherwise, unattractive
to kids.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen? A lot of kids would probably throw a fit
about giving up their plastic pistols, but they'd get over it.
Children are more flexible than adults. Right after the Michigan
shooting, one expert remarked on how kids can be squabbling one
minute and hugging each other the next. Except that this time a
real gun intervened.
</P>
<P>
   The toy gun lobby would protest but on what grounds, that every
American child has the right to play shoot-em-up?
</P>
<P>
   Think about this. We allow kids to play with toys guns, but
expect them to not go near the real thing. But, still they do. They
don't grab our car keys from the table and take the mini-van out
for a joy ride, but they itch to grab a gun. They're mimicking the
adult world's own fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Would we let them play with toy condoms? Would we give them
pretend cigarettes to smoke and make-believe booze bottles to swill
from? Absurd, of course, but why tantalize them with a toy that
looks like it could wipe out the neighborhood? Out of curiosity I
went to a gun show not long ago and visited a booth full of toy
guns. They were bright, big and very believable. They were not for
shooting pretend squirrels. They were for shooting pretend human
beings without having to reload for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman told my companions and me that kids love them. Why,
we asked, and he said because they look so authentic.
</P>
<P>
   The small suspect in Morris Township, Mich., hardly seemed to
know what had happened, authorities said after the shooting. The
county prosecutor said the first-grader probably understood that
what he did was ``naughty,'' but didn't understand ``the gravity or
seriousness'' of his act.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he didn't understand that real guns really kill or what
killing means. Death is a pretty difficult concept for a
6-year-old. Parents find it hard to tell small children that when
people die they don't come back.
</P>
<P>
   This little girl is never coming back. And this little boy isn't
either. We want to protect our children. But we encourage their
fascination with killing. If we're going to let this go on we
better come up with an age appropriate term for ``gunman.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunbaby? I guess we'll get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
