<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY WILL DROP OUT OF RACE, AIDES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: May be updated.) 
(lh) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Campaign aides said Wednesday that Bill Bradley has decided to
end his quest for the Democratic presidential nomination after a
string of primary losses to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said that senior officials with the Bradley campaign
were spending the day drafting an announcement and a speech for
Bradley that would sum up his campaign and the goals he set.
Bradley is to deliver the speech on Thursday, but his campaign
officials said they had not decided the place or the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has said that he will support the vice president's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's decision comes a day after Gore wrapped up his party's
presidential nomination with a sweep of primary and caucus
victories from New York to California.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley began his challenge for the Democratic Party nomination
in January 1999 and, to the surprise of many, quickly matched Gore
in both money and message. But he never came close to overcoming
the vice president's advantages _ the power of incumbency, the
support of a popular president and a solid following among the
women, minority groups and labor unions that are the bedrock of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign was also hurt by the rise of Sen. John
McCain, who, in his bid for the Republican presidential nomination
against Gov. George W. Bush, attracted a solid following of
independents and some Democrats _ voters who might otherwise have
gravitated toward Bradley _ in the early open primaries.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Bradley hammered away at Gore over campaign
finance reform and abortion rights, while putting forth his ideas
on health care, fighting poverty and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that at this moment in history we must create a new
politics in America,'' Bradley said in a speech last month in New
York City. ``We must sweep away the old politics of distortion and
money and special interests and create a new politics of honesty
and conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   But his message failed to gain traction with the masses of
voters, and much of his popularity was drawn from his previous
pursuits: as a U.S. senator from New Jersey from 1979 to 1996 and
as a star in the National Basketball Association with the New York
Knicks from 1967 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's decision to drop out came after he was pummeled by
Gore in a series of primaries on Tuesday. But for most observers,
including some within the Bradley camp, that outcome was pretty
much shaped a week earlier _ on Feb. 29 _ after Bradley gambled and
lost badly on a popularity vote in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to break Gore's undefeated streak and to gain some
momentum, Bradley spent an unusual amount of time and money in
Washington, trying to win a race where there were no delegates at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   On most of the Democratic Party's core issues _ abortion rights,
support of affirmative action, environmental protection and gun
control _ voters felt that the 66-year-old Bradley and Gore were in
sync. But Bradley attempted to undercut the vice president by
questioning his level of commitment to some of those issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
