 ART ADV.: Photos with AUTHOR-KAPLAN and HKN-BOURQUE are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNE-EXPERIMENT (South Burlington, Vt.) _ Two months from now
ground will be broken for Meadowdance, an ambitious experiment in
community living. The founders want to avoid the mistakes of the
communes of the 1960s and 1970s, when idealist was often
overpowered by interpersonal conflict. By Ellen Barry. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANNED-HUNT (Aurora, Maine) _ Maine is considering banning the
``canned hunt,'' in which a wild animal is released into a
fenced-in area and paying customers can then ``hunt'' it. By Ellen
Barry. 1340 words.
</P>
<P>
   CUBICLE-CHOKE (Undated) _ If American bosses want more employees
to think outside the box, they may have to give them a different
box _ or maybe no box all. The drab cubicle, according to new
research, is stifling the creativity and memory recall of today's
workers. By Patricia Wen. 1360 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAILEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why, I want to know, is selling nights
in the Lincoln bedroom an outrage and selling ambassadorships OK?
By Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) _ The presidential primaries settled
one argument, at least. Americans don't hate politics; it's
governance we disdain. By Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   VENNOCHI-COLUMN (Undated) _ People so wanted a healer and a
hero; and McCain, at first, seemed so perfect for the role. By Joan
Vennochi.
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ The real significance of
California and New York was for the contest that began late
Tuesday: the general election. By Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Hacienda Heights, Calif.) _ This leafy corner of
Los Angeles County once symbolized Republican rule in
Ozzie-and-Harriet land. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- H.L. Mencken would have loved last
month's Great Food Debate. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-KAPLAN (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Scouring bookstores,
libraries, and guidance offices, Benjamin Kaplan found $90,000 in
tuition money _ and the basis for a new book. By Joseph P. Kahn.
1375 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-GOLDMAN (New York) _ Oscar-winning screenwriter William
Goldman's book is a shrewd and beguiling blend of Hollywood war
stories, screenwriting shoptalk, and unstinting joie de vivre. By
Mark Feeney. (Includes 10 favorite films list; 2 takes.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-KAPLAN (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Scouring bookstores,
libraries, and guidance offices, Benjamin Kaplan found $90,000 in
tuition money _ and the basis for a new book. By Joseph P. Kahn.
1375 words.
</P>
