<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0744 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VIDEOGAMES-REVIEWS-TE     03-08 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAMES-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP, ALL YOU HOCKEY PUCKS!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
.MDNM/By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the most part, hockey fans _ goooooooo Stars! _ have been
playing the same hockey video games for a few years. Except for the
overlooked, incredibly animated Wayne Gretzky titles for the
Nintendo 64, most of 'em have been pretty been-there-played-that,
and that goes for EA's onetime influential NHL series, which hasn't
seemed to change since the Colorado Avalanche won the cup.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Dreamcast did with its groundbreaking/shaking NFL
and NBA2K titles, Sega has again changed the rules, pushed the
envelope, blown everyone else away with NHL 2K (Sega for Dreamcast,
$55, all ages). Simply put, there's not a better hockey vid game.
</P>
<P>
   First, the graphics are impeccably detailed, right down to glass
reflections, ice scrapes and skate sprays. The players look like
their real-life counterparts: goatees, beer bellies and all. And
all 27 arenas are perfectly reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   The play-by-play commentary by Hall of Famer Bob Cole and color
commentary by former NHL coach Harry Neale is consistently
accurate; Cole's voice rises and falls as the gameplay does, and
Neale's rattling of NHL factoids is as interesting as it is
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   And if you like options, NHL2K's got plenty, from the usual
(building your own player) to the unusual (playing in a 1920s
uniform). Other options include speed adjustment, camera angles and
a bunch of other stuff that I can't think of right now because I
have five minutes to turn this thing in.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, a few problems. When a player is penalized,
sometimes the jersey name doesn't match the player. I was playing
as the Stars' Mike Modano and I checked that Colorado wimp Joe
Sakic. When the whistle got blown, it wasn't Modano's name on the
jersey of the player being sent to the box. This is a technical
glitch, but one worth mentioning _ and, hey, Sega, fixing!
</P>
<P>
   There's also a problem with automatic line changes. Two things:
If you're letting the computer do the changes, chances are they're
gonna happen at the most crucial moments, like during a breakaway.
Also, when the computer does the changes, a box letting you know
what line's coming in appears on the screen, way too often getting
in the way of the action. And, believe me, you don't wanna miss a
second.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems as if all I write about are games in which players
drive around in souped-up cars and blow stuff up, well, it's
because that's all game companies send me. Add to that list
Vigilante 8: Second Offense (Activision for N64, $60, ages 13 and
up), another seek-and-destroy game, but one with an interesting
twist.
</P>
<P>
   And that is: This takes place during the '70s, which means you
get to race around and maim Bee Gees-era cars. There's a goofy
future-meets-past story line, but trust me, it's not worth getting
into. Just keep hitting ``start'' until the explosions begin, just
like you always do.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
