A0745 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-OFFICE-OLD-NEW-NYTSF &LR;      03-08 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-OLD-NEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE CHANGING OFFICE: FROM FEUDALISM to FAMILY  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax, By CHARLES McGRATH  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    I sometimes miss the old days, when offices operated on the
feudal system. There was the boss, or liege lord, who occasionally
dispensed favors _ raises, that is _ but more often withheld them.
For his gaze to fall upon you was supposed to be reward enough.
 &HT;    There were the knights, in their three-piece armor of worsted
and sharkskin, and beneath them the courtiers _ the toadies and
rumormongers who pored over the entrails of the wastebasket, in
hope of clues to the lord's disposition.
 &HT;    There were the executive ladies-in-waiting, with their white-out
and their carbon paper _ this was really back in the dark ages,
before the Xerox machine even _ and there were the handmaidens,
recent graduates of Seven Sisters colleges, dewy and bright-eyed
and as renowned for their pulchritude as for their ability to type
60 wpm.
 &HT;    The whole system depended on everyone's knowing his or her
place, and on not presuming to rise above it. As a newly enrolled
serf, I once made the mistake of speaking in the elevator to one of
my betters, a man with the rank, roughly, of baron.
 &HT;    ``Nice day,'' I said.
 &HT;    He looked at me in silence while the elevator ascended with
excruciating slowness and then, just as he was getting out, he
turned and said to me over his shoulder, ``Young man, you certainly
have a way with words.'' It was two years before he spoke to me
again.
 &HT;    That was nothing. This same man had not spoken to one of his
fellow barons for so long that no one in the office, including the
two of them, could any longer remember what had occasioned the
rift.
 &HT;    The higher-ups didn't need to speak much _ they ruled by means
of the death glance: a look so withering and severe that it would
bore right through you.
 &HT;    I remember the old hallways, in fact, as a place of almost
churchly quiet, punctuated by an occasional mighty door slam or
wastebasket kick. (Unlike the wimpy vinyl receptacles of today,
feudal wastebaskets were made of galvanized metal, and when an
executive wingtip connected, they rang like bells.)
 &HT;    But oppressive though it was, the feudal office was a place you
could rely on. If you were patient and kept your nose clean, you
could slowly, almost effortlessly, rise from serf to squire and
maybe even all the way to knight, in which case you too would be
entitled to quaff bowl-size martinis at midday.
 &HT;    The great secret back then was that nobody was expected to work
very hard. And feudalism was for life: People were almost never
fired.
 &HT;    On my first job, I knew of only one person who had ever been let
go, and it was because he had bitten someone (not, thank goodness,
a member of the firm). A senior lady-in-waiting was once gently
ushered doorward with a retirement party and a silver tray. The
very next day she reported for work as usual, and as usual no one
said a word.
 &HT;    The longevity and durability of the old system was such that it
fostered self-replication. I was so often on the receiving end of
the death glance that in time I mastered it myself. Only by then it
was too late; feudalism was over.
 &HT;    Almost overnight, it seems, the operating model has changed. No
longer a place of vassalage, the office is now a family, a home
away from home, where communication is almost constant and meanness
and hurtfulness are frowned upon.
 &HT;    Memos and e-mail messages flood in like the tide, many of them
generated by the newly empowered Department of Human Resources _
formerly the personnel office, a place where paper went in but
never came out.
 &HT;    Upon boarding the elevator, you are now practically obliged to
remark upon the weather. Before disembarking, the well-adjusted
worker will also wish that all and sundry ``have a good one.'' In
between stops, people actually carry on conversations. They
exchange medical information of sometimes astonishing frankness,
and they also talk a great deal about food and where they're going
to have lunch or dinner.
 &HT;    In feudal days, the topic of food seldom came up and people
didn't really go to lunch in the modern sense of the word _ they
just just slipped away at noontime.
 &HT;    The new candor and friendliness go only so far, however. There
are still things that are never to be spoken of: money, for one, a
subject especially fraught now that cyberbucks have so thoroughly
destabilized the paycheck.
 &HT;    And it is not good form to worry out loud about the most
essential truth of the office family: namely, that it is temporary
and provisional. Whole branches of it could be gone tomorrow,
grafted on to some other family somewhere else or sent home to
become ``consultants.''
 &HT;    Of course, despite the 401(k)s and the profit-sharing plans and
the presence of on-site coffee bars, pool tables and rec rooms, it
is still OK to complain about the boss. Or it would be if only we
knew who he was.
 &HT;    The most unsettling thing about the modern office is the way
that what used to be a hierarchy has turned into a flow chart, with
lines of command so various that they resemble circuit boards.
 &HT;    The guy with the sharp suit and the alligator briefcase might be
written off for his hopelessly corporate mind-set, while the
janitor who has been around since the start-up days might be
sitting on a stack of stock options.
 &HT;    And the most successful and important people, you can't help
noticing, are the ones who, tethered only by laptop and cell phone,
don't actually come into the office very much at all. They clearly
know something that the rest of us don't.
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles McGrath is the editor of The New York Times Book
Review.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
