just just slipped away at noontime.
 &HT;    The new candor and friendliness go only so far, however. There
are still things that are never to be spoken of: money, for one, a
subject especially fraught now that cyberbucks have so thoroughly
destabilized the paycheck.
 &HT;    And it is not good form to worry out loud about the most
essential truth of the office family: namely, that it is temporary
and provisional. Whole branches of it could be gone tomorrow,
grafted on to some other family somewhere else or sent home to
become ``consultants.''
 &HT;    Of course, despite the 401(k)s and the profit-sharing plans and
the presence of on-site coffee bars, pool tables and rec rooms, it
is still OK to complain about the boss. Or it would be if only we
knew who he was.
 &HT;    The most unsettling thing about the modern office is the way
that what used to be a hierarchy has turned into a flow chart, with
lines of command so various that they resemble circuit boards.
 &HT;    The guy with the sharp suit and the alligator briefcase might be
written off for his hopelessly corporate mind-set, while the
janitor who has been around since the start-up days might be
sitting on a stack of stock options.
 &HT;    And the most successful and important people, you can't help
noticing, are the ones who, tethered only by laptop and cell phone,
don't actually come into the office very much at all. They clearly
know something that the rest of us don't.
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles McGrath is the editor of The New York Times Book
Review.) &LR;
</P>
