<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-HISTORY-NUREMBERG09-C     03-08 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-NUREMBERG09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida man covered Nuremberg and men `just following orders'
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Samuel Grossman looked straight into the
eyes of evil and saw the frightening truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked like ordinary men, like the corner butcher,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   They were butchers _ the loyal underlings Hitler left behind
when he committed suicide at the end of World War II. Grossman, a
young newsman working for the American government, watched from
across the oak-paneled courtroom in Nuremberg, Germany, as they
were called to answer for the Nazi regime's crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trial without precedent, but it was intended to set one
that would stand for all time. The mystery at its core was far
deeper and more disturbing than any whodunit. It was the mystery of
how these ordinary-looking people and others like them could be
responsible for inhumanity on a scale never before seen.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a scale too vast to capture public attention in
the splashy style of far more common murder and kidnapping cases
that vie for Trial of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``20 Nazi Leaders
</P>
<P>
   Hear War Crime
</P>
<P>
   Charges Recited''
</P>
<P>
   That headline from the opening day was squeezed into one column
on the front page of The Palm Beach Post on Nov. 21, 1945. It got a
bit more prominence than a story about the cost of Thanksgiving
turkeys but less than a story about a stock battle for control of
the FEC Railway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war had come and gone,'' observes Grossman. ``It was
already becoming yesterday's news.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, now 89 and retired to Lake Worth, was in a unique
position to understand. He became a newspaper reporter after
graduating from Yale in 1931, first for the old Newark Ledger and
then for The New York Times. ``My claim to fame is that I was the
last reporter to interview Thomas Edison,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He later became Newark bureau chief for The Times, covering
stories such as the gangland murder of mobster Dutch Schultz and
the sabotage sinking of an Italian merchant ship in Newark's harbor
at the beginning of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Already married and a father of three, Grossman was deferred
from the draft, but he was still eager to go overseas. He'd dreamed
of being a foreign correspondent since childhood. The Times seemed
content to keep him in Newark, but Grossman got word of an opening
in the government's Office of War Information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quasi-propaganda operation,'' he says of the
government agency.
</P>
<P>
   He took the job in 1943 in exchange for a promise that it would
lead to a foreign assignment. In the fall of 1945, soon after the
war ended, Grossman got a quick Berlitz course and a ticket to
Germany. He was to help organize a German-language wire service
that would provide news in the American-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon after I arrived, I was asked to write a memo about how we
should cover the (Nuremberg) trial,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The memo won him the job of coordinating the agency's coverage.
Grossman went to Nuremberg in southern Germany to begin hiring
German-speaking clerks, rounding up teletype machines and lobbying
the military occupation authorities for other supplies as well as
rooms and food.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was scarce in the war-ravaged region. Other news
organizations, including American newspaper correspondents, would
come to rely on Grossman's logistic arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists came from around the world,'' Grossman says. ``I
had a sense that this was going to be an enormous event.''
</P>
<P>
   International law held governments responsible for atrocities,
but no individuals had been tried for such crimes. Some scholars
questioned the legality of a trial in the absence of specific
statutes. Although there was broad international support for the
idea of punishing Nazi leaders, many (such as Winston Churchill)
thought they should simply be rounded up and shot.
</P>
<P>
   The American government began pushing for a trial even before
the war was over, and the other Allies finally agreed in August
1945 to create an International Military Tribunal with
representatives from each of the victorious powers.
</P>
<P>
   A 24,000-word indictment targeted a range of Nazi leaders from
the obscure (Hjalmar Schacht, minister of economics) to the
infamous (Rudolf Hess, Hitler's deputy). They were accused of
directing and carrying out the murders of millions in the
Holocaust, as well as waging war on their European neighbors. It
took five hours just to read the charges as the trial opened in the
Palace of Justice on Nov. 20, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began without two of the 22 defendants. Ernst
Kaltenbrunner, chief of secret police, was hospitalized with a
brain hemorrhage. Martin Bormann, Hitler's private secretary and
confidante, was still at large.
</P>
<P>
   The rest sat silent and expressionless, except for Hess, who
doubled over and complained of stomach cramps, and the former
foreign minister, Joachim von Ribbentrop, who collapsed. Both were
back the next day when the defendants all pleaded not guilty and
the prosecution began.
</P>
<P>
   The trial continued for more than eight months. Grossman stayed
for just a few weeks; once the coverage was set in motion he moved
on to another assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against the Nazis included thousands of documents,
photographs and films as well as testimony and artifacts.
Grossman's impression of several defendants remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   Hess: ``A very intense man, a little bit crazed. He was staring
into space all the time. There was an intensity in his eyes that
struck me as what you might expect from a deranged man.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Seyss-Inquart, whose many Nazi positions included deputy
governor general of occupied Poland: ``He had a scar down his face.
He looked like a crook. One day they put on a film of a burning
building in the Warsaw ghetto. Germans had set fire to the building
and Jews were leaping out the flaming windows. I looked over at
Seyss-Inquart. He was ducking his head. He was squirming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermann Goering, chief of the air force and once Hitler's
designated successor: ``People think of him as a fat slob, but he
was an impressive man. He was orating from the floor. He put on a
spirited defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The common defense of the Nuremberg defendants became
sickeningly familiar in the years afterward: They were only
following orders. The outcome of the trial ensured that it would
never be heard again, except as a comedic punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial laid down the law that there are some orders so
heinous that it's a crime to carry them out,'' Grossman says.
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts came down in July 1946. Nineteen defendants were
convicted. Twelve were sentenced to death, including Bormann, who
had been tried in abstentia. He was never found. Goering committed
suicide by swallowing a cyanide pill two hours before his scheduled
execution.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the condemned were hanged Oct. 15, 1946, including
Kaltenbrunner, who had recovered from his hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, who gave up newspaper work for public relations after
he returned to America in the late 1940s, was working at a news
bureau in Austria when the trial ended. He remembers reviewing wire
photos of the hanged men. The images were shocking: Blood ran from
the mouths of the dead Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made sure all of our Austrian employees saw those
pictures,'' he says. ``I wanted them to understand what had
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Another view of Nuremberg
</P>
<P>
   Ed Bowley, 82, of Boynton Beach was an Army corporal stationed
in Bamberg, Germany, when the Nuremberg trial began. Bowley had
studied shorthand and typing in high school, a lucky decision that
got him assigned to a clerical job instead of a foxhole. That, in
turn, led to assignments as an editor and writer for various Army
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   His staff credentials from the Lightning Bolt, newspaper of the
U.S. Constabulary, allowed him to wangle a two-day press pass into
the packed and tightly guarded Nuremberg courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Bowley watched as Adm. Karl Doenitz testified about his role as
commander of the German navy and Hitler's successor as head of
state in the final days of the war. Doenitz appeared calm as
prosecutors insisted his submarines refused to rescue American
sailors after sinking their ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a slim man,'' Bowley recalls. ``I bet he didn't weigh
more than 150 pounds. He wasn't that aggressive. He seemed more
complacent than the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence showed Doenitz was an enthusiastic Nazi who knew that
slave labor was being used in shipyards and who continued to wage
war after he knew it was futile. He was sentenced to 10 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SPRINGSTEEN09-COX     03-08 1747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The new Boss packs same power, emotion into music as the old one
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ They step out one by one, like actors in a
streetwise drama. There's the man with his hair wrapped tightly in
a bandanna, playing the part of an urban vagabond. There's the
woman with the killer eyes. There's a big, beefy guy whose sharp
suit and shiny shoes tell you he's ready for business. And a few
more characters, wise, knowing, ripe with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the boss. Make that The Boss.
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about family _ a family on stage and a family in
the audience. It's a story about growing old but refusing to give
up the dream. But most of all, it's a story about rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band's
reunion tour _ or at least one night of it. Call it a snapshot of
classic rock's last great stand, taken Saturday at a concert in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Well hold still now darlin'
</P>
<P>
   Hold still for God's sake
</P>
<P>
   Cause I got me a promise
</P>
<P>
   I ain't afraid to make
</P>
<P>
   My love, love, love, love, love, love will not let you down
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``My Love Will Not Let You Down''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your point of view, it has taken Bruce Springsteen
three decades to arrive at this concert _ or one year. Three
decades because that's how long this marvelous career has extended,
starting in the beach bars of New Jersey in the early '70s, peaking
in an unforgettable stadium tour in the mid-'80s with the E Street
Band and then quietly subsiding with a mid-'90s solo acoustic tour.
One year because that's how long the E Street reunion tour has been
running.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell the story. Springsteen drew 1.8 million fans
worldwide for the 87 shows he played in 1999. When the 2000 dates
were announced, Boss fever continued. ``There seems to be this
sense of community'' building around the tour, observes Rolling
Stone contributing editor Anthony DeCurtis, who covered the first
U.S. dates. ``People have made an investment in what this music
is.''
</P>
<P>
   So, you'll have to excuse the fans from Orlando _ and countless
others from various cities who travel with the tour Grateful
Dead-style _ if they're a little excited. At a pre-show party in a
downtown Irish pub, about 50 fans have gathered, trading Bruce
T-shirts and memorabilia and singing their Springsteen-inspired
version of a Disney theme song (''Heigh ho, heigh ho, it's off to
Bruce we go... ``).
</P>
<P>
   The excitement even extends to George Ellis, 49, a computer
salesman from Virginia who's been to more than 100 Springsteen
shows, including 12 on this tour. ``No one puts as much passion day
after day, week after week, month after month in a tour as Bruce
does,'' he says unequivocally.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-CLASS CHAMPION
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Springsteen is playing in a basketball arena
that boasts a corporate sponsor's name, a far cry from the
working-class spirit of rebellion that pervades his music. And
never mind that this city, home to Mickey Mouse, is all about
entertainment as a packaged commodity, the place where the
Backstreet Boys got their start. Even if he's now a 50-year-old
multimillionaire, you'd like to believe that Springsteen, the
Jersey-born son of a bus driver and secretary, still knows the real
backstreets.
</P>
<P>
   And there he is, looking sharp in a pair of black pants, blue
shirt and black vest, a guitar strapped to his back. The crowd
roars its approval. Singer Island's own Clarence Clemons, the
football player-turned-gritty saxophonist _ yes, he's the beefy one
_ begins the evening on a note of reverence. ``Brothers and
sisters, all rise,'' he says, as if anyone was going to stay
seated.
</P>
<P>
   It's 8:24 p.m. when Max Weinberg's power-drum beat sets the
night in motion. The song is ``My Love Will Not Let You Down,''
which creates the right opening mood. The lyrics refer to the love
between a man and a woman, but on this occasion, Springsteen could
just as well be speaking of his love for the fans. For the moment,
his differences with the E Street Band, whose big-bodied sound
defined Springsteen to the point it nearly confined him, have been
set aside. After an 11-year absence, Bruce and the guys (and a
girl, his wife Patti Scialfa, the background vocalist with the
killer eyes) are back.
</P>
<P>
   E STREET BAND STILL HAS PUNCH
</P>
<P>
   The set continues with more uptempo material _ ``Prove It All
Night,'' ``Two Hearts,'' ``Darlington County,'' songs that
practically need a guardrail to keep them from crashing into the
audience. Any questions about whether the band still has it are
immediately forgotten: The rhythm section alone, consisting of
Weinberg, keyboardists Roy Bittan and Danny Federici and bassist
Garry Tallent, might be the greatest that rock has ever produced.
And with the bandanna-wearing Steve Van Zandt and more subdued Nils
Lofgren, two virtuoso guitarists from different E Street eras, on
stage together for the first time, the band has even more
flexibility: Anybody can fill in a lick, including Springsteen. But
The Boss saves his better self for his singing: The voice, still
equal parts sandpaper and soul, carries the night.
</P>
<P>
   Now those memories come back to haunt me, they haunt me like a
curse
</P>
<P>
   Is a dream a lie if it don't come true
</P>
<P>
   Or is it something worse that sends me
</P>
<P>
   Down to the river
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The River''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: A Springsteen concert is a party. And this
party, filled mostly with revelers in their 30s, 40s and 50s,
carries the heavy burden of nostalgia. Springsteen's fans have
grown old with The Boss; they look to this reunion tour as a chance
to rekindle memories. Pam Thompson, 41, a schoolteacher in suburban
Atlanta who's traveled here with her husband, says if she ever met
Springsteen, she'd have only one thing to say: ``Thanks for keeping
us young.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, this tour is no different from the ones the
Rolling Stones regularly mount _ a chance for geezer rockers and
rock fans to get their jollies, to spit in the face of the
teen-agers who say their music is dated and meaningless. But
there's a difference between Springsteen and the Stones, who favor
elaborate productions and stage antics. Springsteen's concert has
no backdrop or props and the energy that's generated on stage
during his three-hour uninterrupted show is of the honest,
sweat-soaked variety. He also charges about $300 less than the
Stones for his top ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there's the music.
</P>
<P>
   It's only about an hour into the Orlando show when Springsteen
makes it clear that the party must be placed on hold for something
more serious. After a smoky sax solo by Clemons, he offers a
version of ``The River'' that's all pain and regret, as if he's
pouring more salt in the wound of the 20-year-old song. The tale is
classic Springsteen: a factory worker's lament that his best years
have passed him by. But it resonates on a deeper level _ and not
merely because Springsteen has brilliantly reworked the song, as
he's done with many others on this tour. This is no longer about
factory workers: It's about us, how we've grown old, how we've
changed and, yes, how we've come back to the river this night.
</P>
<P>
   As the evening progresses, he offers more of his sparser
material, dedicating ``The Ghost of Tom Joad,'' the title song of
his last studio album, to a group of Florida farm workers fighting
for better pay. Some of Springsteen's fans shift restlessly in
their seats during these quieter moments. But that's the genius of
Springsteen, his ability to blend the power of Elvis with the
thoughtfulness of Dylan. ``He makes music that cannot be denied,''
says Dion DiMucci, the Boca Raton-based Rock and Roll Hall of Famer
who counts Springsteen as a friend. ``Let me put it this way:
There's a difference between being entertained and having a true
emotional experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, before you know it, Springsteen is back in arena-rock
mode, speaking to the crowd like a Pentecostal preacher _ he calls
his religion ``the ministry of rock 'n' roll'' _ and jamming with
the band on numbers such as ``Light of Day'' and ``Born to Run.''
He plays the latter, the song that sparked his early career,
exactly as he recorded it: He's willing to keep the faith.
</P>
<P>
   This train
</P>
<P>
   Dreams will not be thwarted
</P>
<P>
   This train
</P>
<P>
   Faith will be rewarded
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Land of Hope and Dreams''
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen used to end his E Street concerts with a gas-guzzler
like ``Born to Run.'' But that was more than a decade ago. These
days, the band is older and more mature _ and the separation from
Springsteen has allowed the members to pursue different dreams. Van
Zandt, a rocker-turned-actor, stars in TV's hot show, ``The
Sopranos.'' Weinberg leads the band on ``Late Night with Conan
O'Brien.'' Scialfa, who's had three children with Springsteen, has
recorded a critically acclaimed solo album.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate that Springsteen brought them back because he
wanted to take care of them financially. The theory goes that
they'll head their separate ways once the tour wraps, which has
prompted the Springsteen faithful to buy every ticket available.
``Fear is a big part of it. I'm afraid I'm never going to see Bruce
and the E Street Band together again,'' says Scott Johnson, a beer
importer from Minneapolis who's traveled with the tour from Fargo,
N.D., to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   A TESTAMENT TO LOVE, FRIENDSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Even if the money counts, the band is having too much fun
tonight for a fast buck to be the only motive. No, this is about
something more intangible. You feel as much when Springsteen
gathers them for the evening's penultimate song, ``If I Should Fall
Behind,'' letting each take a turn singing a lyric in this
testament of love and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the closer, ``Land of Hope and Dreams,'' a
gospel-tinged song about the future. The metaphor here is a train
driving into the distance, carrying with it ``saints and sinners''
and ``losers and winners.'' It stands for everything this night has
represented _ this man, this band, these fans, all gathered
together in the belief that the music must go on. That in this age
of sweeping cynicism, rock can still speak volumes. That the dream
continues.
</P>
<P>
   It's 11:21 p.m. when Springsteen sends the crowd home, reminding
them to contribute to a local food bank collecting money in the
lobby. This train has finally left the station.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
