<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was mentioned on TV that the deepest known spot on Earth
is a trench in an ocean. What ocean? How deep? How was it explored?
</P>
<P>
   A: The deepest known point is the Mariana (sometimes spelled
Marianas) Trench in the western Pacific, near Guam. Sources differ
on the depth, with some putting it at 35,840 feet below sea level,
others at 36,198, and still others at 37,800.
</P>
<P>
   The trench was explored in January 1960 by researchers Lt.
Donald Walsh of the U.S. Navy and Jacques Piccard, a Swiss
scientist, in the Navy's bathyscaph Trieste. The two set a world
ocean-diving record of 24,000 feet Jan. 7 of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few weeks later, they descended to the botton of the
trench in the Trieste. The descent required four hours, 48 minutes;
the ascent, 3 hours, 17 minutes. Facts on File reported that the
later dive broke their own previous record when they reached a
depth of 7.15 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The bathyscaph was a boat-shaped, 75-ton craft 50 feet long and
12 feet wide. A spherical crew chamber 6 1/2 feet in diameter was
attached underneath. At the 37,800-foot depth, the craft withstood
pressure of 16,883.2 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I would like to write members of Congress, is there a
general address to use after their name?
</P>
<P>
   A: To send regular mail, after the name, write: (for
representatives) U.S. House of Representatives, Washington, DC
20515; (for senators) U.S. Senate, 20510.
</P>
<P>
   To send electronic mail, visit http://congress.org/elecmail.html
and enter either your ZIP code or the person's name where
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The other day, I heard Regis Philbin begin a quote:
``Monday's child is fair in face; Tuesday's child is full of
grace.'' Can you finish this for me?
</P>
<P>
   A: It goes like this: Monday's Child is fair of face, /
Tuesday's Child is full of grace, / Wednesday's Child is full of
woe, / Thursday's Child has far to go, / Friday's Child is loving
and giving, / Saturday's Child works hard for a living, / But the
Child that is born on the Sabbath Day, / Is bonny, and blithe, and
good, and gay!
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, the IRS considered making airline
employees pay income tax on the free airline tickets they received.
Whatever happened with that? Now Delta Air Lines, Ford Motor Co.,
and American Airlines are said to be providing computers to their
employees. Will they be taxed as income?
</P>
<P>
   A: Two subjects, two answers, according to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Free or discounted flights offered to employees and their
spouses, dependents and parents by airlines are considered non-cash
fringe benefits, and therefore are excluded from an employee's
gross income, said IRS spokesman Mark Green. Details can be found
in IRS Publication 535, Business Expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Computers might be a different story, he added. If they're given
as a gift, they must be included as extra salary or wages unless
they meet the rule of ``De Minimis (Minimal) Fringe Benefit.'' This
benefit is any property or service an employer provides to an
employee that has so little value _ taking into account how
frequently the employer provides similar benefits to its employees
_ that accounting would be ``unreasonable or administratively
impracticable.'' Details on this general topic also can be found in
IRS Publication 535.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I collect the new state quarters, and I've noticed that those
from the Philadelphia Mint seem to be more plentiful in supply than
those from the Denver Mint. The coins from Philadelphia also seem
to be issued first. Is there a reason for this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Coins produced by the Philadelphia facility are distributed
mainly east of the Mississippi, those from Denver mainly west of
the Mississippi, said Jennifer Arnold of the U.S. Mint. So it's to
be expected that consumers in the East would see more P marks on
their coins than D marks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coins are produced simultaneously by both mints, Arnold added,
so your contact with them is simply a result of their geographic
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard that the world has enough oil reserves to last 100
years or longer. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Estimates about petroleum resources vary considerably, so we
can't say with absolute certainty.
</P>
<P>
   One resource hedges by saying that if present rates of
consumption continue, petroleum may become scace sometime in the
mid 2000s. They key words here are ``may become'' and ``scarce,''
not ``will be'' and ``exhausted.'' This report goes on to say that
the world's oil reserves total about 1 trillion barrels, with some
geologists predicting that additional reserves remain to be
discovered in such places as China, offshore seabeds, and on
Canadian islands.
</P>
<P>
   Another source, meanwhile, reports that the ``most likely''
world oil endowment is 1.7 trillion barrels, of which 32 percent
already has been produced and consumed. If this estimate proves to
be reasonably accurate, current relatively stabilized world
oil-production volumes could be sustained to about 2035, at which
time a shortage of conventional oil resources would force a
production decline.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another resport, published in 1996, said Saudi Arabia alone
had some 260 billion barrels of proven crude oil reserves, ``enough
to satisfy U.S. oil demand, at current consumption levels, for a
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that predictions are often proved wrong. In 1972,
for example, a report made by an organization called the Club of
Rome predicted exhaustion of the world's oil supplies by 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent item reported that Franklin D. Roosevelt, before his
inauguration as president, had been shot in Miami. I don't remember
ever hearing anything about that. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: It happened on the night of Feb. 15, 1933, just after
Roosevelt had finished speaking to a crowd at Bay Front Park in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting in his open touring car when Giuseppe Zangara, an
unemployed bricklayer, fired six shots at him from about 12 yards.
The president-elect wasn't hit, but the bullets struck five other
people, including Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak, who was standing next
to the Roosevelt car.
</P>
<P>
   Cermak died March 6, and Zangara was indicted the same day.
Zangara pleaded guilty on March 9, and was sentenced to death March
10.
</P>
<P>
   Zangara, who said he had visions of killing ``a great ruler,''
told the court that he would make another attempt to kill Roosevelt
``at once'' if he were freed.
</P>
<P>
   He was electrocuted at the Florida state prison at Raiford on
March 20, 1933. News reports at the time said he was defiant toward
capitalists to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article said the January full moon is known as the
``wolf moon,'' and the one in September is the ``hunter's moon.''
Do those in other months also have names?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. These are commonly listed as the ``traditional names,''
from Native American lore, for each month's full moon: January,
wolf; February, snow; March, worm (or full sap); April, pink; May,
flower; June, strawberry; July, buck (or thunder); August, sturgeon
(or green corn); September, barley (or harvest); October, hunter's
(or harvest, again, because the full moon sometimes falls in
October); November, beaver; and December, cold.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online, check this Web site _
www.7almanac.com/eye/fullmoons.html _ for more detailed, and
colorful, explanations of the names.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I read that Ted Turner bought two more ranches in
Kansas with a total of 38,239 acres. How many acres in all does he
own in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: About 1.7 million, according to Russell Miller, general
manager of Turner Ranches. His major land holdings are in New
Mexico, Montana, Nebraska and the Dakotas, in addition to some in
the southeastern United States, and total about 1 1/2 times the
size of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as January, Turner bought 90 acres of land along the
Soque River in North Georgia to use as a trout-fishing retreat for
his family.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
