<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Belgian Guffens doesn't waffle on vintage news
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ With Winemaker
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Guffens, everything is I, I, I.
</P>
<P>
   Irascible, irreverent and iconoclastic.
</P>
<P>
   Guffens, a Belgian who moved to France to make a broad line of
high-quality, competitively priced white Burgundy under the Verget
label he founded, dropped into the Winds Wine Cellar in Yellow
Springs last week for a quick luncheon during a five-city, five-day
whirlwind stateside tour.
</P>
<P>
   Disheveled and a bit bleary-eyed after a late-night wine dinner
at the Maisonette the previous night, Guffens stoked up on coffee
and quickly hit his verbal stride.
</P>
<P>
   _ On his frequent clashes with French government officials who
insist that only certain grape varietals be allowed in wines from
certain regions: ``It's only forbidden when you get caught ... I
always prefer to be wrong my way than right someone else's way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Comparing the quality of the current vintage with past
vintages: ``Here's my definition of a good vintage: It's in stock
and for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Upon hearing that the Wine Spectator had declared one of his
1997 white Burgundies one of the best of the vintage: ``I went down
into the cellars and told some of my assistants, `We must be doing
something wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has attracted worldwide acclaim for the chardonnays he
produces from Burgundy, Guffens is a restless man, so he recently
purchased property in the south of France and has begun bottling
wines under Verget du Sud and Chateau des Tourettes labels.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of rich, oaky, tropical-fruit-scented California
chardonnay, Verget's Burgundy bottlings might not suit your tastes.
But if you're a fan of French whites, Verget's wines are worth
seeking out. Should you see any 1997 or 1996 Vergets still on
shelves, they're worth snapping up. His less expensive 1998s _
bottlings in the $12-$20 range _ are a bit lighter than the
previous two vintages, though a '98 Verget St. Aubin ($23) was
first-class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wine of the Week: Beringer 1996 North Coast Pinot Noir,
$14.99. California pinots have zoomed in price over the last
decade, though they're still cheaper than gasoline (and most of
them taste better). This offering from Beringer is a great buy,
with plenty of fruit, oak and a hint of candy-apple sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
