 &HT;    
 By ADRIAN WOOLDRIDGE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    A decade ago, corporate America tore up the social contract that
bound employees to their companies. Downsizing and re-engineering
made it clear that employees were expendable commodities, not
valued resources. Today, many bright workers are getting their
revenge by fleeing their fickle employers for better-paying rivals
- or dot-com start-ups.
 &HT;    Indeed, quitting has become so fashionable in Silicon Valley
that the turnover rate for companies there has reached an estimated
25 percent a year. The average American 32-year-old has already
worked for nine different companies.
 &HT;    Workers today fantasize not about landing a ``dream job'' but
about having a ``portfolio career'' _ one dream job after the
other.
 &HT;    Is the death of the Company Man something that should be
lamented or celebrated? We asked three leading management experts
to offer their thoughts on loyalty in a virtual age.
 -0- 
 &HT;    JEFFREY PFEFFER
 &HT;    STANFORD GRADUATE SCHOOL of BUSINESS
 &HT;    If loyalty is dead in some companies, it's mostly because it has
been murdered by business practices like downsizing at the first
sign of trouble and subcontracting out all ``nonessential''
positions.
 &HT;    The message of ``employability'' _ that a company's only
responsibility to its people is to get them qualified for their
next job _ has clearly registered with the work force. Who can
blame them for acting accordingly?
 &HT;    Today's rapid-turnover arrangements may seem good for the
corporate bottom line, but in fact they make it difficult to build
long-term, sustained success. In an economic environment in which
capital and the latest technology are widely available, the only
hope for building sustained competitive advantage resides in
companies' management of their people.
 &HT;    Thankfully, a few companies like Southwest Airlines, Toyota and
Cisco Systems have retained the wisdom of building profits by
taking care of their people.
 &HT;    Consider SAS Institute, the largest privately held software
company in the world (with annual sales of more than $1 billion).
It has a turnover rate of less than 4 percent. SAS does not
contract out very much of anything, use many part-timers or tell
people they need to think about their next job _ in fact, the
company says that people will have three or four careers during
their working lives and it hopes all will be at SAS.
 &HT;    Nor does it offer stock options, dole out big bonuses or do any
of the other things that companies with toxic workplaces have to do
in order to bribe people into staying.
 &HT;    What SAS does instead is provide generous benefits like on-site
day care, a full-indemnity health insurance plan (bet you thought
this didn't exist any more), a 35-hour business week, recreational
facilities _ as well as something much more important.
 &HT;    While lots of companies say that ``people are our most important
asset,'' SAS actually believes it. People are trusted rather than
monitored and controlled, given great equipment to work with,
permitted to try new things, allowed to have a life as well as a
job and, in short, treated with a respect all too rare in today's
high-stress workplaces.
 &HT;    For SAS, being nice is good business. What happens when you work
while exhausted?
 &HT;    You make errors. SAS actually prefers to ship software that
isn't full of bugs _ what a unique idea! It needs fewer checkers
than other software companies because its employees are awake on
the job.
 &HT;    The organization's low turnover saves it an estimated $70
million annually. Too many companies think that laying people off
or reducing wages is the best way to turn a profit. But loyalty is
central to achieving success.
 -0- 
 &HT;    ROSABETH MOSS KANTER
 &HT;    HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
 &HT;    We are currently experiencing nostalgia for a golden age of
company loyalty. Yet in too many organizations people were
``loyal'' not because they really cared but because they had no
choice.
 &HT;    Seniority reigned. Status, influence and big pay increases were
tied to promotion. People didn't have stock options _ they had
pension plans that handcuffed them to the company.
 &HT;    The ``loyalty'' that workers seemed to demonstrate by sticking
around was illusory; many of them secretly dreamed of escape and
retired on the job.
 &HT;    Old-fashioned corporate loyalty in which all status and rewards
accrued to seniority stopped being good for the economy when global
competition heated up; productivity and wages stagnated under the
old corporate bureaucracy.
 &HT;    Now that the economy is characterized by high work-force
mobility, productivity is up and wages are rising. With a tight
labor market, the shoe's on the other foot, and in many industries,
it is employees who have numerous opportunities and companies that
are desperate to retain them.
 &HT;    Companies today must offer great jobs in a great environment
with great amenities _ and constantly improve on them. They must
earn loyalty.
 &HT;    Razorfish, a digital design firm, holds people who could go
anywhere by offering exciting work for top clients, a hip corporate
ambiance and larger-than-life amenities, like a Las Vegas trip for
everyone in December.
 &HT;    ``I'd never leave such a cool company,'' a 30-something Web site
producer told me. That is, not until a cooler company comes along.
Razorfish has to think every day about how to stay the coolest.
 &HT;    I think it's a good thing that companies today have to work
harder to keep the best people. The benefits they add make work
more rewarding. Stock options make more people act like owners of
their companies, and that can only benefit performance. And it's
wonderful that companies now recognize that people have lives
outside their work.
 &HT;    Discovering high rates of turnover among female professionals,
Deloitte &AMP; Touche, an accounting firm, took steps to add flexible
schedules and control travel. These changes, useful for men as
well, landed Deloitte in Fortune magazine's Top 10 list of best
companies to work for in America _ helping the firm attract still
more talent.
 &HT;    Some companies earn employee affection by making people proud to
work there. IBM gets high marks from employees because of its major
financial commitment to public education innovations. Timberland
offers its employees 40 hours of paid company time per year to work
on community service projects.
 &HT;    You can't buy loyalty with just a paycheck. Building long-term
commitment depends on four things: the nature of the work itself,
the opportunity to grow, the chance to speak up and be listened to
and the feeling of making a difference.
 &HT;    Members of the new generation in the work force don't want to be
subordinates; they want to control their own fate. They want to do
meaningful work that has redeeming social value without sacrificing
the chance to get a life. Give them that and they'll give you
loyalty in return.
 -0- 
 &HT;    TOM PETERS
 &HT;    AUTHOR of ``THE BRAND YOU 50''
 &HT;    Loyalty is the glue that holds society together _ including
commercial society. That said, corporate loyalty is rubbish.
 &HT;    If you apply for a job at the Tom Peters Co. and imply that
you'd like to make a life of it, I'll unceremoniously throw you out
of the office. Suppose you are a would-be Michael Jordan of my
trade, consulting? I'll still toss ou out.
 &HT;    Here's my New Social Contract. I want my company to be so
attractive, so laden with talent, so energetic it makes your head
swim. I want to give you an exciting work environment, peerless
teammates and a string of challenging projects with top clients you
could not match anywhere else.
 &HT;    In turn, I demand that you give your all to these hot projects.
And I demand that you be loyal _ to your teammates, to the client,
to yourself. You must perform and grow as you've never performed
and grown before.
 &HT;    However, I also demand that you not be ``loyal'' to me or my
company. If you do turn out to be a Michael Jordan-type superstar,
don't I want you to stick around? No! (And yes.) That is, I do not
want you to stick around out of misguided allegiance. If I can
provide you with exciting new challenges, and if you respond
accordingly, well, then I hope we do indeed grow old together _ one
project at a time.
 &HT;    Mindless corporate loyalty _ the essence of '50s Babbittry _ was
always a rotten idea.
 &HT;     c.2000 Adrian Wooldridge  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Adrian Wooldridge is a Washington-based correspondent for The
Economist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
