<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER09-COX     03-08 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Back to square one
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind the calendar. For Al Gore and George W. Bush, the
general election contest is under way. After earlier election night
surprises, bumps in the road, thousands of miles traveled and
millions of dollars spent, the presidential race is back to where
it began _ a fall campaign between Gore and Bush _ and both are
turning their full attention to each other.
</P>
<P>
   `BATTLE-TESTED' AND READY FOR WAR
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, after his Super Tuesday blowout over GOP
presidential rival John McCain, says he's ``battle-tested'' and
ready to take on Al Gore. Bush derided Gore as ``an agent of
Washington'' and partner in an administration that set the wrong
tone for America. Bush said he was strengthened by the fight with
McCain and would be ``reaching out to the people he energized.''
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY HEADING FOR THE BENCH
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's Democratic presidential rival has turned into a
supporter. After a coast-to-coast defeat in Super Tuesday contests,
Bill Bradley intends to drop his White House bid and endorse Gore
today. ``He won, I lost,'' Bradley said. The two waged a heated
battle that stretched for more than a year, and both men praised
one another in public comments after the results were in. Bradley's
staff says their man plans to stay active in public life, but would
not want the vice president job.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN ROCKET ABOUT TO FALL TO EARTH
</P>
<P>
   Aides to John McCain say they expect him to quit the race, but
that no firm decision has been made. A list of options being
presented to the candidate at his Arizona retreat reportedly
included staying in the race to further his political reform
agenda, getting out and supporting the Republican ticket, and
leaving to mount a third-party bid. McCain has said he would not
leave the GOP, and a senior McCain adviser told The Associated
Press he had no reason to believe the senator would do so.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS PUT ON JUDGMENT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says that in the marathon presidential race, the
biggest hurdle he sees is simply this: ``Convincing the American
people that I've got the right judgment to be the president.'' His
challenge, he said in an interview with The Associated Press, is
``convincing the American people that I'm a good, sound
decision-maker, that I'll make decisions of peace and prosperity
that will not only be well thought out, but lead to results.''
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING OUT THE REST OF THE SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   The next big primary day is Tuesday, when six states award 566
Democratic and 341 Republican delegates. Texas _ George W. Bush's
home _ will allocate 194 Democratic and 124 Republican delegates.
In Florida _ governed by Bush's brother, Jeb _ there are 161
Democratic and 80 Republican delegates. In Al Gore's home state of
Tennessee, 68 Democratic and 37 Republican delegates will be
awarded. There also will be voting in Mississippi, Louisiana and
Oklahoma. Before then, though, there will be various contests of
minor importance in South Carolina, Colorado, Utah, Wyoming,
Arizona, Michigan, Minnesota and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN WRITES OFF GEORGIA; GEORGIA WRITES OFF MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain poured enough political firepower in South Carolina
last month to take down Fort Sumter, if not win the Republican
primary, but he chose to bypass neighboring Georgia altogether.
Perhaps he assumed his failure next door would cross state lines.
And it did. McCain has set foot in Georgia only once _ for a
two-hour book-signing event in Atlanta. That left the state open
for George W. Bush to get all 54 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ANGLING FOR A SHOT ON TICKET
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole once gently griped about George W. Bush's
bankroll, but then she bolstered his drive for the GOP and sealed
her place on his list of vice presidential prospects. With legwork
and thousands of campaign calls, Dole made it clear that she was
willing to work hard to help Bush achieve dominance over John
McCain. She also has been hinting that Bush could use a female
running mate to bridge the traditional gender gap that usually
helps Democrats in presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   HOW NOT TO CONNECT WITH VOTERS
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley stood on the south side of East 77th Street, eager
to meet commuters at the entrance to the subway. But many New
Yorkers _ concerned, perhaps, by the crowd of police and media
around him, not to mention the spectacle of seven shirtless male
aides with B-R-A-D-L-E-Y painted on their chests _ simply crossed
the street Tuesday morning to use an alternate staircase.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO CONNECT WITH ONE VOTER
</P>
<P>
   Across Manhattan, Bill Bradley enjoyed a little more success
outside a polling place. Louis Gonzalez Jr., 57, was so excited
after shaking Bradley's hand that he changed his schedule and went
right in to vote at P.S. 9. When he came back out, he said to
Bradley: ``I just voted for you. I pulled the thing.'' Bradley lit
up and replied, ``Let me shake the hand that pulled the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   HEY, WE'VE GOT PROPOSITIONS FOR YOU
</P>
<P>
   Californians, voting on ballot questions, slammed the door on
gay marriage, gave prosecutors a mandate to lock up more teen-age
criminals, and reaffirmed their support for casino gambling on
Indian land. But Californians rejected an attempt to repeal the
tobacco taxes championed by movie director Rob Reiner, and defeated
a campaign finance reform proposal that would have allowed for
partial public financing of campaigns and banned corporate
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER WAY TO RAISE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who set a ``hard money'' record by raising more
than $70 million, quietly collected an additional $5.2 million in
two months through a new account that accepts both hard and ``soft
money'' contributions. An analysis of Federal Election Commission
records, according to the political funds Web site FECInfo, showed
the account, called the 1999 State Victory Fund Committee, has not
yet reported any spending. (Go to www.fecinfo.com)
</P>
<P>
   REBEL FLAG DISPUTE HITS BUSH AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says he's studying a request to take down a a
plaque bearing an image of the Confederate battle flag from the
Texas Supreme Court building. The NAACP and others want it removed,
saying it's offensive to minorities and doesn't belong in the
state's highest courts. ``I'm looking at that issue right now,''
Bush told a news conference. Earlier in the campaign, he refused to
say whether he thought the Confederate flag should be removed from
the South Carolina Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   COMING OUT FROM UNDER THE SCANDAL
</P>
<P>
   Four in 10 Democratic voters said they disapprove of President
Clinton as a person, but the backlash for Al Gore was not as severe
as it had been in New Hampshire. Gore won a slim majority of those
who disapprove of Clinton as a person, but he took an overwhelming
majority of those who approve of Clinton personally, according to
exit polls conducted Tuesday for Voter News Service. Eight out of
10 Democrats approve of the job Clinton is doing, and
three-quarters of them voted for Gore. In New Hampshire, 54 percent
of Democratic voters disapproved of Clinton as a person, and 58
percent of them voted for Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   YOU COULD HEAR THE BLUES WAFTING
</P>
<P>
   The music captured the mood at Bill Bradley's campaign party
Tuesday night. As the first polls closed at 7 p.m., blues echoed
through a nearly empty room. The Harlem-based Real Deal Soul Band
had been told by campaign staff to be ready to break into ``Ain't
No Stopping Us Now'' if the night took a surprising turn for the
better. The cue never came. Some supporters were there with Mardi
Gras beads, determined to celebrate Fat Tuesday if not Super
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   WELL,THAT'S THE BIG CITY FOR YOU
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff, daughter of Al Gore, wandered into a New
York City twilight zone Tuesday night: She couldn't get a cab home
from her victory gig. Schiff thanked supporters on her father's
behalf at a Greenwich Village union hall, schmoozed with scores of
backers, and left the building with two Democratic aides shortly
before 11 p.m. The trio tried to hail a taxi in a drizzling rain,
but a steady wave of yellow passed them by. They had to hoof it;
four blocks before, with a little persuasion, managing to snag an
empty black limo.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news services
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
