<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HYPER-HYPESTER-TEX     03-08 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYPER-HYPESTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERKY PITCH WOMAN FOR NET COMPANY GOES WITH HER INNER GOOFBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably seen her _ especially if you watch late-night TV
_ hyping Internet America, an online service provider. She's the
energetic, girl-next-door blonde whose perkiness accompanies
fast-moving images, reminders that we live in a wired world that
just won't settle for being put on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   We call her the Internet America Girl. She calls herself the
Geek Girl, a nod to Dallas-based Internet America's phone number:
1-800-BE-A-GEEK. But in real life, she's Natalie Austin,
26-year-old aspiring actress and self-professed geek _ although not
a geek in the way you may be thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, if a half-hour phone chat is any indication,
aren't deceptive. Austin is gregarious and upbeat, laughing
frequently, often interrupting herself to refine her focus on the
points she's trying to make. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her approachability comes across onscreen _ so much that she has
an e-mail following, which has included at least one marriage
proposal. And it comes through in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was in Dallas, I tried to go for a walk,''
says Austin, who is based in the Los Angeles area but flies to the
Metroplex several times a year to film the commercials. ``I tried
to go find Walgreens from my hotel room, and it was just completely
surreal. First of all, I got lost. I'm literally lost for two hours
in Dallas. ... and I'm probably the only person who could get lost
for two hours on foot _ people would just come up to me: `Oh,
you're the Geek Girl. Hi! How ya doin'?' They'd come introduce me
to their boyfriends, or to their mom or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin says she didn't know what she was getting into when she
showed up at an audition for the Internet America commercials. She
was just an actress looking for a job, and her biggest gig to date
was a Ford commercial in which she sang about Ford pickups with
Alan Jackson (the two never met; her voice was digitally mixed in
with the country superstar's). And the events leading to the
audition didn't give her much reason to be hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very bizarre day,'' says Austin, who has been doing
the spots for about two years. ``They had auditions in Dallas, I
guess, but they still wanted someone _ I don't know, more hyper or
something. So they came out here. I don't even know why I remember
this day, but there was a full moon, and (the producers) were late
to the audition because their plane was late and it was a good
thing, because someone had run into (my car) with their car. It was
just ridiculous; people are running into each other, everything's
running late, and so I was just completely like, `Hi, what's up,
how you doin', just got hit by car' _ just actin' like a dork, and
I guess that was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the audition _ like the first commercials _
stuck her behind a steering wheel. ``And it's just you, looking
like a big dork, with this steering wheel, talkin' to a camera,''
she says. But Austin's energy and personality got her the gig.
</P>
<P>
   Austin doesn't know where the energy comes from, but she's had
it since she was a little girl growing up in Russellville, Ark.,
near the Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a total tomboy,'' Austin says. ``I was always
making mud pies with the neighbors, just head-to-toe dirt. I was
always ready to fight; I was horrible, just horrible! I've always
been hyperactive, like my teachers have always had a problem with
me. Then came sports and cheerleading. So as corny as it is _ and I
know cheerleading is just hilarious _ but at least it gave me
something to do with all my energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin sang country and folk music growing up, which helped her
land the Ford commercial with Jackson. She wasn't so much a
country-music fan, though, until she moved to LA and started
missing home. And despite her increased visibility and her energy,
she remains fond of the simple life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really a typical 26-year-old in LA,'' Austin says.
``My friends out here call me `Geritol Woman.' I know that doesn't
sound like a hyperactive nickname. But because of all the partying,
y'know, there's a lot to do out here for young people out here. And
I'm just so not _ like, I was the designated driver on New Year's
Eve. I'm just like _ I'd much rather sit around and just blab, and
have a good talk with everybody and laugh our (tails) off than go
out and party. In that way, I'm a total geek out here 'cause I'd
much rather go hiking.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the Internet, Austin doesn't consider
herself much of a geek. She's more pitch-person than cyberwoman,
and that has made for some odd surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be just on the Internet, just writing e-mails or
something,'' Austin says. And ``I'll just get an instant message
from someone who has somehow figured out my e-mail. And I have no
idea how they've done it. And they'll be like, `Hey, what's up?'
You know, it's just `so and so from ... Texas, I see your
commercials, do you wanna blab?' And it's a little bit freaky!''
</P>
<P>
   Austin calls Charles Richardson, Internet America's director of
quality assurance, her Internet bodyguard because he protects her
from scarier messages and forwards more positive notes, along with
e-mails to Austin's agent. But so far, the commercials haven't led
to any higher-profile acting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   They have led to on-air appearances at such radio outlets as
Dallas' KTCK/1310 AM ``The Ticket;'' Austin did a guest shot on the
morning-drive Dunham and Miller show. And Austin says she loves the
Metroplex, and the reactions she gets when she visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to lunch with Craig Miller and we had the best
conversation,'' she says. ``I just forgot how great it is to have a
conversation. You peel off less fake slices of onion. And out here
(in LA,) it's much more guarded, much more makeup, much more
everything to get through.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin, on the other hand, hardly seems guarded at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``On shooting day, it's hilarious, because I'm like, `OK, y'all,
if you want some energy, I'm going to be hyper,' '' she says. ``I'm
always dancing, and we'll play music in the background _ and it's
just good that that comes across. And it comes across so much that
people feel comfortable saying, `Talk to my daughter,' or `Write my
son a note,' or `Leave a message on my grandfather's machine.' It
just feels good _ like the feeling that I'm just, y'know, a big
goofball is coming through enough for people to feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
