<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0759 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-JOB-EMPLOYEES-MARKET-     03-08 2272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-EMPLOYEES-MARKET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZERO PERCENT UNEMPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DAVID BROOKS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Karl Marx spent all those years dreaming about the worker's
paradise. Yet he never got to sit in the conference room at Berbee
Information Networks Corp. and listen to Jim Berbee rattle off all
the luscious perks he offers his employees.
 &HT;    They get stock options, of course, but also Palm Pilots, cell
phones and a $1,000 bonus to help with the down payment on their
first homes. If they want to work in their pajamas, the company
pays to install and maintain high-speed ISDN lines in their
bedrooms.
 &HT;    Two years ago Berbee took everybody in the company and their
families to Disney World. Bagels and muffins are free on Fridays,
the sodas in the office machine are free all the time (consumption
went up 400 percent after that change), and if employees want to
use the office copiers for personal use, no problem.
 &HT;    An auto-repair service comes to the employee parking lot every
other Wednesday to do oil changes and tire rotations. There's
dry-cleaning delivery four days a week and pizza at least once a
month (which for some reason employees still have to pay for).
 &HT;    Marx would have looked at all the cushy benefits and figured
that the dictatorship of the proletariat had finally come to pass.
But there's a simpler explanation. Full employment.
 &HT;    Berbee is located in Madison, Wis., which has a microscopic 1.2
percent unemployment rate, second lowest in the country after
another university town, Columbia, Mo. Jim Berbee is desperate to
attract and retain workers. He has 220 employees and an amazing 94
percent retention rate, but his company is growing so fast he also
has 110 job openings. ``We're losing ground every week,'' he cries.
 &HT;    And it's not only the tech geeks who are in short supply. The
employment classifieds in the Madison paper land on porches each
Sunday with Richter-scale thuds.
 &HT;    One company offered free maid service for new employees.
No-skill, entry-level jobs carry wages of $8 or $9 an hour, blowing
away the federal minimum wage of $5.15. Burger chains are beginning
to offer health benefits to grill workers, and still some
franchises have closed for lack of staff.
 &HT;    Wisconsin Dells, a nearby resort area, has been forced to fly in
summer help from Lithuania, Zimbabwe, Russia and New Zealand.
Lands' End in nearby Dodgeville has given Green Bay Packers tickets
to employees who recruit friends.
 &HT;    Figi's, a mail-order company, offers free bus service and free
breakfast at Burger King. (Talk about killing off your work force.)
Carlson Company, which makes cosmetic counters, built a $750,000
day care center so staff members can visit their kids at story
time.
 &HT;    Hubert Humphrey used to go to bed dreaming of conditions like
this. But they're not celebrating in Madison.
 &HT;    I bounced around talking to businesspeople, politicians and
workers, and I kept trying to introduce the phrase ``full
employment'' into the conversation, because it sounds so happy and
satisfying. But they'd come back with the phrase ``labor
shortage,'' and then their brows would furrow with that expression
of grave concern people used to wear when talking about exploding
federal deficits.
 &HT;    ``Employers are have a very tough time finding workers,''
laments Madison's mayor, Susan J.M. Bauman. We sit in her office,
looking gravely concerned.
 &HT;    The other thing you notice is that the locals aren't behaving
like rational economic actors. With all these openings, workers
should be hopping from job to job, taking advantage of all the
perks and lures, boosting their income to the max.
 &HT;    Yet a survey done by the QTI Group, the largest local staffing
agency, found that the job-turnover rate has been dropping even as
the unemployment rate has plunged. QTI has 48 people in Madison
trying to find mostly lower-skill workers for clerical and
industrial jobs.
 &HT;    Every so often, the company offers $10 to anyone who comes in
and completes a job application. In Madison, in other words,
they're paying people just to look for work.
 &HT;    But no one's jumping at the opportunities. Nor are wages
skyrocketing. Salaries are rising, especially among low-end workers
and up top among the techies. But salaries are rising nowhere near
as fast as you'd expect in such tight labor conditions.
 &HT;    You get the impression that even in flush times most people are
still pretty conservative when it comes to work and job hunting.
 &HT;    I keep hearing the same things. People don't like to jump
around. People like to work at places that are familiar, or where
some member of their family already works. Nepotism reigns.
 &HT;    Melster Candies Inc., the country's leading manufacturer of
circus peanuts _ those orange puffy things made from sugar _ solved
their staffing problems when they sent job applications home with
some of their workers, asking if they had any underemployed
relatives. Berbee boasts that he has had daughters recruit fathers
and husbands recruit wives.
 &HT;    This isn't the free-agent nation that our futurologists are
always predicting. This isn't the land of rampant, loyalty-is-dead
individualists. There's a little more caution and communitarianism
in the air here.
 &HT;    One is reminded that Wisconsin is said to outstrip most of the
rest of the nation in Tupperware use per capita. This is the kind
of state where people save their leftovers. And that basic sense of
ballast colors the local reaction to prosperity. There aren't many
people riding around in Lexus or Mercedes SUV's.
 &HT;    The job center in Madison, which coordinates state and county
jobless, housing and other benefits, is just in the shadow, and
definitely within the aroma range, of the Oscar Mayer
meat-processing plant.
 &HT;    Inside, it looks like a high school library, with rows and rows
of computers, where people can page through the online job
listings. I plugged in my profile and came back with 442 executive
openings, 403 clerical openings, 292 sales openings and so on,
including some career options I'd never really considered, like
boar-semen collector, TV weatherman and wooden-pole inspector.
 &HT;    The people at the keyboards around me were diverse, a couple of
young Asian and Hispanic men (there has been an influx over the
past two years as word of the hot job market has spread), a
middle-aged white guy in a hunting hat, a few seniors and
miscellaneous young people.
 &HT;    There was some sarcastic chatter among terminals: ``Work on
Saturdays? Are you kidding me?''
 &HT;    Mary Witt, the director of Dane County Job Service, says that
most of the people already have jobs, but would like to find some
place where they can advance. A basic problem for employed and
unemployed alike is that people are too cautious when looking for
work.
 &HT;    ``Most people select the line of work they've done before,''
Mary Witt says. ``People think small.''
 &HT;    In contrast to greater Madison's relentless optimism, the mood
in the employment office is sober, if not gloomy. And why not? This
is about the only place anyone hears any bad economic news.
 &HT;    ``I can get anyone a job,'' says Tom Swoboda, a counselor, ``but
will it pay the bills?''
 &HT;    Madison's real estate prices have risen with the economy, so
about a third of the people in the homeless shelters have full-time
or more than full-time work. The saddest cases, the counselors tell
me, involve extraordinarily well-educated people - men and women
with Ph.D.'s and law degrees _ who have propelled themselves into
an elite stratum where job competition is still fierce.
 &HT;    Job experts are urging employers to begin looking for workers
among formerly marginalized groups, like criminals and liberal arts
majors, but apparently it hasn't helped these folks.
 &HT;    I've driven a few miles from the job center, and it is as if I
am standing at the source of the Nile. I am here at the midway
point of the assembly line for the Sub-Zero Freezer Company. From
this very spot, high-end refrigerators flow out to overendowed
kitchens around the globe _ to Santa Monica, Fifth Avenue,
Bethesda, Boca, Winnetka and across the whole fertile crescent of
upscale squash-court-size kitchentopia.
 &HT;    It is humbling to be here, at the source, knowing that the
shelves being installed in front of me will one day hold organic
chutneys, frozen free-range prawns, Florentine pestos and all the
other delicacies so pleasing to the nation's bull-market gourmets.
 &HT;    If there is any place in Madison where people have a right to
feel puffed up by their economic success, it is here at Sub-Zero,
the makers of the quintessential chichi '90s product. Yet I'm not
sure I've ever been in a more unpretentious and tradition-conscious
corporate culture.
 &HT;    I've just had a meeting with three executives, genial
conservative white men in their 50s in blue or gray suits, white
shirts and muted ties. These guys are proud to be making a
top-of-the-line product, but it could be top-of-the-line turbines
or diesels, to judge by their complete lack of fabulousness.
 &HT;    Sub-Zero tried to use robotics to put together its machines. But
the robots made too many mistakes. So they went back to making the
machines by hand. The workers look like classic assembly-line
labor, former high school football stars now wearing Packers shirts
over slightly bulging waistlines. They have old-fashioned
Harley-Davidson tattoos, not newfangled Nirvana-inspired tattoos,
and high school degrees or an equivalent.
 &HT;    Sub-Zero, though it is growing quickly, doesn't have much
trouble finding workers. Fathers bring in sons and daughters; some
are third-generation Sub-Zero families. Once in place, workers tend
to stay. And newcomers are drawn by the company's reputation at the
rate of about 10 to 15 applications a week.
 &HT;    That's the final striking feature of the Madison job market. If
the average worker were strictly Homo economicus, he'd choose an
employer on the basis of salary and benefits, and jump when he's
offered something better.
 &HT;    But time and again, people mention the importance of reputation.
They want to be able to give a satisfying answer to the
cocktail-party question ``Where do you work?''
 &HT;    Status companies seem to have a big advantage finding workers,
and that is true in the manufacturing sector as well as among the
biotech and high-tech start-ups.
 &HT;    In the heart of downtown Madison there is a tech company that
has a corporate culture several galaxies removed from Sub-Zero.
Sonic Foundry is a software firm that makes it possible to convert
audio and video for the Web. It is located in a string of renovated
warehouses.
 &HT;    There's an iron rule of office design. The more beaten and
industrial the look, the more likely the firm is a high-tech
start-up looking for a patina of gritty industrial authenticity. If
the headquarters are clean, quiet and sedate, with tranquil carpets
and serene watercolors, then you know the company is in
manufacturing.
 &HT;    Sonic Foundry, with its factorylike office design, is at the
cutting edge of the information age.
 &HT;    I should confess straight out that I'm probably not cool enough
to even write about Sonic Foundry. There are 20-somethings with
bleached-blond surfer haircuts, pierced noses, Smash Mouth goatees,
baggy pants and office nameplates with tags like Dirtforker on
them. The hipness rolls off them in waves.
 &HT;    ``Our business is one of the sexiest industries you can be in,''
says Rimas Buinevicius, the company's CEO, lounging back in his
black turtleneck on the couch next to a retro steel coffee table.
``It's the nexus of new media and music.''
 &HT;    The hiring process sounds like the velvet-rope scrutiny you
might get at a downtown club. Each potential employee is
interviewed seven or eight times, to make sure the person is
``going to fit in culturally,'' Buinevicius says.
 &HT;    Sonic Foundry has a growth rate of about 100 percent a year. But
once you're in, there's no cooler place to be. There are about 60
computer engineers on staff, and over the past five years only one
has left. So there's even stability among the stock-option rebels
at Sonic Foundry.
 &HT;    In fact, the affluence feels a lot more stable here than in the
Silicon Valleys or Alleys or the rest of the Fast Company
corridors.
 &HT;    Economists have been puzzling about how the recovery has been
able to surge for so long without inflation. Many have been
wondering when the nation is going to have to pay for all the
gilded-age excess.
 &HT;    But maybe Wisconsin is more typical of America than Palo Alto or
SoHo or any of the other Next New Thing zones.
 &HT;    Maybe even where the economy is hot, most Americans have
remained cautious, conservative and cool.
 &HT;     c.2000 David Brooks  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (David Brooks is a senior editor at The Weekly Standard and
author of the forthcoming ``Bobos in Paradise: The New Upper Class
and How They Got There.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------ &QC;
</P>
