<SLUG> BC-CIR-WESTERN-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MUSEUM, ONLINE WAY IS ONLY WAY, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of planning, the Women of the West Museum
has finally opened. At least virtually.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's backers could not get enough financing for a
``real'' space, so they opened an online museum. They are holding
their first exhibition, the LoDo Mural Project, which combines a
public mural project in downtown Denver with corresponding online
images and text.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally the museum was going to be a bricks-and-mortar
stand-alone facility,'' said Marsha Semmel, president and chief
executive of the Women of the West Museum, based in Boulder, Colo.
``What we are doing is what many businesses are doing _ adapting to
the changing ways people spend their time and get their
information. We can serve a much larger audience if we take
advantage of online opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The current exhibition can be seen on the streets of Denver
along a temporary construction walkway. Two local artists, Tony
Ortega and Sylvia Montero, created colorful paintings of women, who
have contributed to Colorado history. Above the 250-foot mural is
the museum's Web address, www.wowmuseum.org, which invites
passers-by to visit and learn more about the paintings and the
women portrayed in them.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the site can learn about pioneer and contemporary
women who helped shape the West, like Molly Brown (the unsinkable
Titanic passenger) and Teresita Sandoval, one of the founders of
Pueblo, Colo., in the 1800's.
</P>
<P>
   Other features of the site include a virtual story quilt and a
neighborhood walking tour organized by Denver grade-school pupils.
</P>
<P>
   Each patch of the quilt represents a different person or story,
like ``1940s High Country Bride,'' an excerpt from a diary by Janet
Roberts, who moved from Massachusetts to the mining town of Climax,
Colo., with her husband of five weeks: ``For us, the next seven
years would be filled with exploration of new frontiers of science,
and new frontiers in our own lives, getting to know the beauty of
the mountain wilderness just outside the camp, learning to ski from
our own front door, and making new and fascinating friends whose
lives were so different from that with which we were familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the focus of the museum is on women and their
experiences west of the Mississippi, Semmel does not believe that
will limit its reach. ``When our site was named a Yahoo
pick-of-the-week, we heard about it from a male engineering student
in Shanghai who e-mailed us,'' she said. ``I think that's very
symbolic. It shows there is this interest in the American West that
exists way beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Semmel said the goal was to someday have a
permanent space. For now, the museum is preparing for its next
exhibit _ a traveling show that will be hosted by libraries,
shopping malls and schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
