<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0764 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-STATUS-JOB-SYMBOLS-NY     03-08 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATUS-JOB-SYMBOLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 PARKING SPOTS, CORNER OFFICES and PC PASSWORDS  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax, By MAX FRANKEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By their media shall ye know them.
</P>
<P>
   That has always been my test for whole societies.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind whether they call themselves Democracy or Republic:
free press means free country; controlled press, miserable tyranny.
The same goes for individuals. My media test also works for sorting
out people, especially office workers. Never mind the title on the
door or the workplace habitat, media power is what denotes true
rank, clout and worth.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Washington that I first realized that medium is not
just message but also identity. Obviously, not every civil servant
of rank could command a corner window or private toilet. So the
telltale sign of superiority became a pen _ a government-issue
tapered pen that stood erect in a holder originally designed for
quills.
</P>
<P>
   A mere stenographer might also accidentally qualify for a window
or coat closet instead of rack. But only a boss had one of those
pens beside the blotter and water pitcher. Federal regulations
required that token of status, no less rigorous than the Pentagon's
dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, I have come to expect workers' media of
communication to define their hierarchical worth. After elegant
desk sets became commonplace, corporate and government strivers
acquired intercoms to summon subordinates. Next appeared dictation
machines, and then portable recorders whose content could be tossed
to underlings for typing and brought back for signing with those
executive pens.
</P>
<P>
   Later down the chain of command came multibuttoned telephones
with one-touch connection to different layers of the bureaucracy.
And later still managers got silent buzzers to alert a secretary to
overhear and transcribe a conversation. Eventually, inspired by the
White House, the highest ranks achieved voice-activated recorders.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, these functional media spread to hoi polloi, forcing
the invention of supplementary definitions by decor _ notably rugs
on the floor, art on the walls and keys to private toilets,
elevators and dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But ranking by media remains the most reliable status index.
Indeed, it seems to be surviving even the centrifugal force of the
Modem Rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-modem world, the passkey to privilege is the PC
password. In communal offices, whosoever is enabled by secret code
to read into another's files _ without being read in return _ is
well on the way to sizable bonuses and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   And even the least powerful password leads to a corporate
support system of benefits, counselors and technological expertise.
Walls, windows, carpets, paintings _ all the old physical
attributes of rank and power have been supplanted by a virtual, and
portable, medium.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional passwords unlock undeniable privilege. Few
individuals cruising alone on the Web can long compete.
</P>
<P>
   There are young techies who persist in believing that the
Information Revolution is destroying all hierarchy and rapidly
democratizing the means of creation and expression. They sound much
like the last century's revolutionaries who thought they could
democratize (i.e. communize) the means of production.
</P>
<P>
   Wired magazine, the liberationists' bible, would have us believe
that every wired person on the planet will soon have an equal voice
in things _ except, of course, that Wired itself is empowered by
the lush advertising of corporate behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   The modem explosion has indeed produced a great dispersion of
the work force. And many of America's more than 20 million new
home-office laborers proudly proclaim themselves ``independent''
contractors, ``free agents'' and ``self-owned'' businesses. Many
delight in their flexible work schedules, with time for the kids
and for errands, and their escape from supervision.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that a great many of today's independents,
temps and self-employed are the downsized of yesterday, cast adrift
without community, benefits or unemployment insurance. Never mind
what they call themselves; by their media shall ye know them.
</P>
<P>
   Look past the deceptively egalitarian cell phones, faxes and PC
keyboards. Truly secure, insured and tax-code favored Americans are
wired into networks and propelled by corporate engines. And their
speech is amplified by a collective. They get group health and
pension plans that are subsidized by taxpayers as well as
employers, plus numerous workplace amenities, sometimes even
including child care.
</P>
<P>
   Equally well served are some ``outsourced'' workers who may
labor at home or on the road but are authorized by higher authority
to use SecurID cards and passwords to scale institutional fire
walls and tap into networks of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of home workers who cruise alone in the Internet
without these corporate keys or community are discovering that
their vaunted autonomy comes with a large dose of ignominy. They
labor in fear of illness or recession, or both, and they lack
protection against discrimination, most notably in taxation.
</P>
<P>
   They must pay an employer's share of Social Security as well as
their own. They do not qualify for group insurance or benefits.
They must fight the government to deduct office expenses. Only a
few professionals among them enjoy the power to bargain
collectively.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a worker who hacks at home without a corporate password
and I'll show you an underprivileged citizen. To be sure, communal
office workers _ is there no better term for the old
``office''-office? _ are bound to routines and schedules that
interfere with domestic bliss and duties. And they are intensely
scrutinized, most gallingly by WatchDog, a software that lets the
boss track your every movement on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But the home-office worker must watch the dog _ and greet the
repairman, pay bills, chase accountants and lawyers and cry out
constantly for technical help. That's multitasking with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, most unincorporated individualists will be
corralled into unions that bargain for benefits and provide shared
services. The MacArthur genius finders have already embraced the
farsighted Sara Horwitz, the founder and leader of Working Today, a
nonprofit lobby for nearly 100,000 free-agent members.
</P>
<P>
   Effective representation, of course, will require taxation and
incorporation, then elections, politics and varied ranges of
influence _ in other words, hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The reward will be benefits collectively achieved and
individually coded, duly accessed by some password, the key to
social worth, your place in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. Frankel now writes this ``Word &AMP;
Image'' column for The New York Times Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
