<P>
   &UR; BIG BROTHER IS WATCHING YOU! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BARBARA EHRENREICH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Today more than ever, American workers check their freedoms at
the office door. Employers have taken to monitoring employees'
workplace behavior right down to a single computer keystroke or
bathroom break, even probing into their personal concerns and
leisure activities. In the area of privacy rights, workers have
actually lost ground in recent years _ from purse searches to
genetic testing to the chemical and electronic forms of snooping
adopted by many companies in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Ehrenreich is author of the coming ``Nickel and Dimed:
Surviving in Low-Wage America.'' slugged: BC-WORKER-PRIVACY-RIGHTS,
priority code r, category codes k,l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CHANGING OFFICE: FROM FEUDALISM to FAMILY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES McGRATH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, offices operated on the feudal system. There
was the boss, or liege lord, who occasionally dispensed favors _
raises, that is _ but more often withheld them. For his gaze to
fall upon you was supposed to be reward enough. There were the
knights, and beneath them the courtiers _ the toadies and
rumormongers and ladies-in-waiting. Everyone knew his or her place.
But the office is now a family, a home away from home, where
communication is almost constant and meanness and hurtfulness are
frowned upon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles McGrath is the editor of The New York Times Book
Review. slugged: BC-OFFICE-OLD-NEW, priority code r, category codes
l,k)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COME BACK, COMPANY MAN! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ADRIAN WOOLDRIDGE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With today's workers careering from one job to the next, is
there any way of breeding loyalty? Or was blind workplace loyalty
always a bad thing? Here's what three top management theorists _
Tom Peters, Jeffrey Pfeffer and Rosabeth Moss Kanter _ think.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Adrian Wooldridge is a Washington-based correspondent for The
Economist. slugged: BC-WORKPLACE-LOYALTY, priority code r, category
code k,l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZERO PERCENT UNEMPLOYMENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID BROOKS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has a job in Madison, Wisc. Some companies even pay
money to those who come in and fill out job applications. So it
follows that workers should be hopping from job to job, taking
advantage of this ``employee's market,'' demanding more perks and
lures, boosting their income to the max. But people aren't behaving
that way. The job-turnover rate has been dropping even as the
unemployment rate has plunged.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Brooks is a senior editor at The Weekly Standard and
author of the forthcoming ``Bobos in Paradise: The New Upper Class
and How They Got There.'' slugged: BC-JOBS-EMPLOYEES-MARKET,
priority code r, category code a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PRICE of `FREEDOM' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By NINA MUNK &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: March 5 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the much-hyped, much-romanticized free-agent nation, workers
are liberated from routines, dress codes and office politics. As
well as benefits, vacations and regular paychecks. So where's the
advantage?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Nina Munk contributes frequently to The New York Times
Magazine. slugged: BC-MYTH-JOB-INDEPENDENCE, priority code r,
category code a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREE AGENTS UNITE! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MAX FRANKEL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There are young techies who persist in believing that the
Information Revolution is destroying all hierarchy and rapidly
democratizing the means of creation and expression. But the truth
is that a great many of today's independents, temps and
self-employed are the downsized of yesterday, cast adrift without
community, benefits or unemployment insurance. Never mind what they
call themselves; they are far from ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. slugged: BC-STATUS-JOB-SYMBOLS,
priority code r, category code k) &LR;
</P>
