<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0783 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MODULAR-ROBOTS-AR     03-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MODULAR-ROBOTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAPE-SHIFTING ROBOTS FROM XEROX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Ill., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Circuits) 
(af) 
 By DANIEL SORID   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In wars of the future, intelligent, morphing robots slither and
hop along battlefields, scoping out enemy lines and even rescuing
fallen soldiers. They come by land, by air and by sea, doing
dangerous work in place of humans.
</P>
<P>
   And the unlikely heroes in these robot wars may be no farther
away than your photocopier.
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox Corp., known for its innovations in document handling,
has developed a modular, shape-shifting robot. The Xerox
researchers envision their work with this robot leading not only to
battlefield scouts or medics, but also to rescue devices,
self-configuring, modular furniture, toys that can change their
appearance and function and, perhaps, even a fold-up photocopier.
</P>
<P>
   The robot, named Polybot, is novel because it is many robots in
one. Small modules link with one another to form larger structures
and to shift into new shapes like snakes, loops and spiders, each
with its own method of movement.
</P>
<P>
   The modules are packed with things like sensors to note location
and environment, computers to control actions and actuators to
provide movement. The set of modules takes its power from a cable
that plugs into an outlet, although portable batteries will
eventually be used.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of Polybot, and robots like it, is versatility.
``The one advantage of the system is the ability to be very mobile
through unstructured environments,'' said Mark Yim, a researcher at
Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center in California and the inventor of
Polybot.
</P>
<P>
   Robots that can adapt their shape and movement to suit the
environment _ whether on a mountain, in a desert or even underwater
_ will have a leg up over robots with a single, fixed form.
</P>
<P>
   Such a robot, for instance, could take the shape of a loop and
roll over flat terrain. Encountering an obstacle, the loop could
break, become snakelike and slither around it. In rough terrain,
the snake could curl into a figure 8 and break apart again to form
a four-legged creature that resembled a spider. Currently, Polybot
can change form but not in response to changes in its environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fantastic idea,'' said Roger Quinn, a professor at Case
Western Reserve University who is developing a robot that jumps
like a cricket. ``In robotics now, you don't even have commercially
viable legged robots. If you could do it in a modular way so it
could transform itself into different modes of mobility just based
on the terrain, that would be really much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Polybot has 24 identical modules, each about six
centimeters on a side. In a year and a half, Yim said, Polybot will
have hundreds of modules, allowing it to take on even more forms
and handle new tasks.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of adaptability is a major advantage over traditional
robots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to build robots to solve particular tasks, and when
the task changes we need to plug in a new robot,'' said Kevin
Lynch, an assistant professor of mechanical engineering at
Northwestern University. ``By the time we've figured out how to
install them in this particular task, they've become outdated. It
would have been easier to use humans.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be enough to use robots that simply change shape.
On-board computers will have to understand the laws of physics.
``You want your structure to take into account the dynamics of
motion,'' said Daniela Rus, an assistant professor of computer
science at Dartmouth College. ``You don't want the robot to fall
flat on its face while it's moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, Case Western Reserve and nine other organizations are
being financed by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency,
the research and development arm of the Department of Defense, to
develop revolutionary robot designs.
</P>
<P>
   The military has set goals and deadlines for each project. By
2001, for example, Polybot will have to be larger and more
responsive to its environment.
</P>
<P>
   Yim is optimistic, but he said that modular, self-reconfiguring
robots must clear some hurdles before they become a viable
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will be difficult,'' Yim said, ``will be programming them
_ how to get them so they don't fight each other, so they all work
toward the common goal. When you have a lot of modules, the
computational aspects become exponentially more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Handling flawed modules will also be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you have a million modules,'' Yim said. ``You're
almost guaranteed that some of them will be broken. It's no longer
a catastrophic failure, but some proportion of the system will be
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The field of modular and reconfigurable robotics dates back to
the 1980s, with early research in Japan and the United States. Only
four groups of American researchers and a few in Japan are
currently studying the technology, Rus said.
</P>
<P>
   Pradeep Khosla, a professor of engineering at Carnegie Mellon
University, developed reconfiguring robotic arms more than 10 years
ago. Today, Khosla studies the problem of writing software for
robots that change shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1988 there was a notion that robot arms had a very
specific architecture, and once you built an arm it stayed that
way,'' he said. ``What we did at that time was put forth this novel
idea, this modular and reconfigurable technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Yim, who was studying for his PhD at the time, got hold of the
idea, Khosla said. ``What he's demonstrating is what we did for
robotic arms can be done for mobile robots,'' Khosla said.
</P>
<P>
   Applications for modular robots extend far beyond snakes that
can become spiders. In rescue operations, groups of robots could
link together to form support structures for falling buildings. As
modules can be made smaller, robots will morph into objects with
more complex shapes, like hammers, wrenches and pliers.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are always toys. A robot that forms
different shapes and objects on command might make an exciting
gadget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've showed this,'' Yim said of Polybot, ``they
all say this would be a really cool toy. The toy market is one that
we might start looking into.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
