<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a puzzle freak and was recently given a 1,000-piece
jigsaw puzzle that I know will take weeks to finish. At one time, a
manufacturer made a mat on which you could work on a puzzle, then
roll it up and store the partially finished puzzle. I have tried,
without luck, to find such a mat at toy stores and bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jacqueline Seamans, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: We puzzled for a time over this question but eventually found
your mat in the Bits &AMP; Pieces catalog. With this felt mat, you
simply roll up your partially finished jigsaw and all the assorted
pieces around a tube. Then you attach the elastic bands and file it
away for later use. The mat, which measures 36 by 48-inches, is
$14.95 and fits puzzles up to 2,000 pieces. 1-800-544-7297; (item
No. 12-K7762).
</P>
<P>
   Q: My family and I have fallen in love with Yorkshire pudding.
The only time we can get it is when my mother in-law goes to Canada
and brings back packages of it. Is there any place in Atlanta where
we can buy these mixes? _ Barry Winkler, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: This British treat of flour, eggs and milk is often baked in
the drippings of roasted meat. ``It is a popular accompaniment to
roast beef in Britain, and the two together compose the
`traditional' Sunday lunch,'' writes Alan Davidson, author of ``The
Oxford Companion to Food'' (Oxford University Press, $60). We found
a 4.5-ounce box of Whitworths Yorkshire Pudding &AMP; Pancake mix,
$2.59, at Taste of Britain, 73 S. Peachtree St., Norcross
(770-242-8585).
</P>
<P>
   Davidson also writes, ``sometimes the batter is poured into
smaller round tins to make individual puddings, but this is not the
authentic Yorkshire method. Strictly speaking, the pudding, cut in
squares, should be served with gravy before the meat, to take the
edge off the appetite.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for a kitchen timer in the shape of a cow. I know
they exist, but I've tried a number of stores, with no luck Can you
help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kaelie Crews, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Attention, fans of bovines. We located your cow timer in the
Harriet Carter catalog for $7.98 (item No. C5464); 1-800-377-7878
or www.harrietcartergifts.com. The timer, which gives a country
look to any countertop, is a snap to use. Simply set the timer and
when the time elapses, it sounds off with a loud ``moo.'' A battery
is included with each order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a clock that shows the time on the ceiling,
although I think the clock is also capable of ringing an alarm.
This would be a great clock for the deaf, so can you tell me where
I can locate one?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anneice Capple, Riverdale, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Ceiling Time II clock by Howard Miller will light up your
night. This black matte-finish model, which also travels well, is
$53.99 at Champ's Clock Shop, 3834 King Drive, Douglasville
(770-942-2128). Simply position the swiveling projector to project
the time on the wall or ceiling. Then see the five-second
illumination with a touch of the light button. The clock also
offers an alarm and a snooze button.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find a store that still carries Lilt home
permaments. The last place I saw a kit was at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nola Hinson, Conley, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: You will soon be a curly head with a Lilt Home Permanent. We
found the perms (Lilt Foam, $5.99; Lilt Lotion, $5.49) at Drug
Emporium, 2625 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-233-1201). Each kit contains
waving foam or lotion, neutralizer and sponge end-wraps. Note: The
manufacturer warns, ``Do not perm if your hair has been bleached or
double-processed, treated with a cream relaxer, streaked or if you
have shown a negative reaction or sensitivity to perm products.''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
