<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     03-08 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 2 NEW CHIPS, THE GIGAHERTZ DECADE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The era of gigahertz computing has arrived. Advanced Micro
Devices this week became the first semiconductor company to mass
produce a personal computer microprocessor with a speed of 1
gigahertz, or 1,000 megahertz, or a billion electronic heartbeats
per second. Intel Corp., which had not planned to introduce its own
gigahertz chip until the second half of the year, quickly followed
with its own high-speed Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq and Gateway, using Advanced Micro's Athlon chip, are
already taking orders for new gigahertz PCs and expect to deliver
them by the end of the month. Hewlett-Packard, Dell, IBM and others
will catch up quickly with gigahertz machines based on the Intel
Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Like the four-minute mile or the arrival of the year 2000, the
milestone is mainly symbolic, and life will pretty much go on as
normal, which is to say faster and faster. The arrival of the first
mass-produced gigahertz chips is significant mainly for bragging
rights among computer engineers and power-hungry consumers who want
the extra speed for manipulating graphics and disintegrating their
opponents in three-dimensional shoot-'em-up games.
</P>
<P>
   As is almost always the case when newer and faster processors
are introduced, the real significance of the arrival of gigahertz
chips is that computer makers will now cut prices on existing PC's
to make room for the new speed demons at the high end. To make room
for its gigahertz Athlon, for example, Advanced Micro Designs
recently slashed prices of ``older'' chips like the 800-megaherz
Athlon, introduced just two months ago, by as much as 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new AMD and Intel processors mark the beginning of an era
when we start measuring PC performance in gigahertz (a billion
computational cycles per second) instead of megahertz (a million
cycles per second), but what does that really mean for consumers?
Faster performance, obviously, for processor-intensive applications
like games and graphics, including digital photography, digital
video editing and Web page design.
</P>
<P>
   But for most consumers, computers in what can now be called the
half-gigahertz range (500 MHz) are more than adequate for standard
applications like word processing, e-mail and Web browsing, where
the speed of the user's fingers, eyes and brain are the controlling
factors. And those computers are going to become more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   It is compulsory at this point to note that processor speed is
simply one measure of a computer's performance, and an often
unreliable one at that. One company's 500-MHz computer can
outperform another's 700-MHz computer, for example, and one
chipmaker's gigahertz chip may perform better than a rival chip
rated at the same speed.
</P>
<P>
   Other system components, including the memory subsystem (RAM and
cache), the graphics card and the hard disk, also affect the
overall speed of a computer. In the Internet era, a faster modem or
a high-speed cable or DSL connection will almost always have a much
higher payoff in overall system performance than a few extra
megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   And spending a few hours studying a computer or software manual,
or a couple of hundred dollars for a good computer class, will
almost certainly improve your productivity much more than a
processor upgrade. A computer that sits idle while you try to
figure out what button to push has an effective speed of 0
gigahertz.
</P>
<P>
   One of my first personal computers had an Intel 8086 processor
that clocked out at what was then a stunning 4.77 MHz. When Intel
later came out with a 33-MHz 80286 processor, the occasion left me
breathless and dizzy with power. ``It will leave scorch marks on
your desk,'' I wrote, which today leaves blush marks on my cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   If Moore's Law that processing power doubles every 18 months
holds true, a measly gigahertz may seem laughable a decade from
now. Even as it announced the new 1-GHz Athlon chip, Advanced Micro
was showing off a prototype of a 1.1-GHz chip code named
Thunderbird, which is based on a copper manufacturing process.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the gigahertz chip is hot stuff.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, the first computers built around a
gigahertz processor are going to be expensi chips will
initially cost PC makers more than $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's Athlon-based Presario 5900Z system with the new
gigahertz chip will have a base price of $2,499, plus tax and
shipping. The system will include a conventional 17-inch monitor,
128 megabytes of system memory, a 30-GB hard disk, a 40X CD-ROM
drive, a 56K modem, a 16-MB Diamond Stealth video card with 2X AGP
graphics, JBL Pro Speakers and Firewire ports for digital video
editing.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 5900Z-1000 is offered only through Compaq's
build-to-order Web site or telephone sales line. Compaq says it
will be able to deliver a system within 10 days of an order.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate screamer appears to be Dell's Special Edition
Dimension computer featuring a gigahertz Pentium III chip from
Intel. The system includes 256 megabytes of Rambus-based high-speed
memory, a 30-GB hard drive, a ``dual data rate'' geForce AGP 4X
graphics card with 64 megabytes of video memory (the equivalent of
128 megabytes with dual data rate), a 12X DVD-ROM drive, an 8X
CD-RW drive, a Soundblaster Live sound card with four Altec Lansing
THX-certified speakers and a subwoofer the size of a small
suitcase, and a 17-inch flat-panel display screen. A Dell spokesman
said final pricing had not been set, but would be ``less than
$6,000,'' which in marketing code means $5,999.99.
</P>
<P>
   Dell has been troubled recently by parts shortages that have
delayed some orders of high-end computers for weeks or months, and
the company said it would not set a date for availability of the
Special Edition Dimension, other than ``when it's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, 1-GHz computers are creeping closer to the level
of power needed to do speech recognition, which will allow people
to operate their computers by voice instead of keyboard and mouse
commands. But experts say true speech recognition is still several
years away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers at International Business Machines'
research center in Austin, Texas, took time this week to show me a
prototype of their new Power4 processor system, which effectively
combines a couple of gigahertz-level processors on a single chip
along with a supporting infrastructure that feeds them bits at a
rate of 100 gigabytes per second, a monstrous amount of data that
IBM says is the equivalent of 20 full-length DVD movies. The Power4
system will appear first in the high-end computers known as
servers, which operate behind the scenes as the main engines for
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In the networked world of the Internet, a server built around
Power4 chips is likely to have much more of an impact on your
personal computer than a gigahertz chip on your desk, because it
will enable, for example, faster response times on eBay auctions or
speedier delivery of search requests.
</P>
<P>
   One final technical note: After failing to persuade the rest of
the world that the 21st century and the new millennium do not
really begin until Jan. 1, 2001, I am very reluctant to note that
the proper pronunciation of ``gigahertz'' is with a soft G, as in
gigantic and gee whiz, instead of a hard G, as in grumble and
grouse. Obviously this is another losing battle, so I guess I'll
just have to get giggy with it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
