<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE09-COX     03-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE REPORT FOCUSES ON FAMILY FACTORS IN YOUTH VIOLENCE
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The best way to deter youth violence is to focus on
family factors such as good parenting and the mental health of
children, according to a bipartisan congressional report being
released Thursday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   ``The family unit is really where it starts,'' said Rep. Bob
Etheridge, D-N.C., one of 22 members of a House group that studied
youth violence last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems come to schools ... in a lot of cases from
dysfunctional homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group was appointed after several shootings last year,
including the massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton and others have focused on stricter
gun-control measures to reduce school violence, the report
recommends teaching parenting skills as they were previously taught
in home economics and personal health classes.
</P>
<P>
   It also advises creating a parenting television channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fishing channels, shopping channels, home repair
channels, old movie channels, science fiction channels ...but there
are no parenting channels,'' the report says. ``Arguably, the
information most important and precious to society cannot be found
on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge said the group agreed not to address gun control in
their research, instead focusing on other aspects of youth
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a broader issue,'' he said. ``This document is about
creating good citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge, a former superintendent of North Carolina schools,
said one of its recommendations has already proven effective in his
state _ character education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely is working. You have discipline problems going
down. You have academics going up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report advises block grant funding for character programs
that teach subjects such as honesty, citizenship, courage, justice,
respect and personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, who span the ideological spectrum in the House
from Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., to Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas,
also examined media violence.
</P>
<P>
   On this front, they recommended ``encouraging'' video game
producers to make ``trailers'' for violent games to remind users
that violence in the real world has consequences. In addition, the
report favors the Motion Picture Association of America's efforts
to create videos and other materials to ``teach basic values that
are shared by all religions as well as secular philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also puts a high priority on increasing mental health
services to help children and teenagers work through depression and
aggression. It advises juvenile justice officials to provide mental
health screenings for every young person entering the system.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1993 Justice Department study, 73 percent of
juveniles in the system reported mental health problems and 57
percent reported past treatment, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report is being released at a Capitol Hill news conference
Thursday. A copy was provided to Cox Newspapers this week.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also recommend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing grants to state and local education agencies to
recruit, train and hire high school-based counselors, psychologists
and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Launching a national public health campaign to raise awareness
of the importance of raising healthy children and the key role of
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Continuing mental health services for juvenile offenders while
on probation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing grants to state and local agencies for case
management and information-sharing efforts between jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing more money for programs that bring police officers
into schools as mentors and instructors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helping educate parents about the existing rating systems for
video games and television, including teaching them to use the
V-chip, which can screen out certain TV programs. This information
should be available in Spanish and other languages, the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
