<HEADLINE>
OSCAR BALLOTS MISROUTED, BUT SHOW WILL GO ON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The motion picture academy says some of those missing Oscar
ballots were found Tuesday making their way erroneously through the
slow-motion third-class mail system.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's is going postal over the mistake, but the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences has extended the voting deadline
until March 23 because of the snafu.
</P>
<P>
   Academy spokesman John Pavlik said about 1,100 of the 4,200
wayward envelopes were found, and it's possible the rest are on
their way to recipients.
</P>
<P>
   However, California Oscar voters are being instructed to use the
reissued ballots with yellow return envelopes instead of the
originals with white envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles postmaster Kerry Wolny personally picked up the new
mailing Tuesday evening to ensure its proper first-class handling.
And, in keeping with the tradition of pre-Oscar hype, that handoff
was yet another photo opportunity announced with a news release.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the biggest Oscar-related concerns for academy
officials have been preventing vote tampering and keeping the
winners' names a sacred secret until the envelopes are torn open
during the big show.
</P>
<P>
   Now it seems they'll be sweating over whether the postal service
will pull through.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting firm that tallies the
ballots, is bracing for a crunch because of the deadline extension.
But Pavlik said the accountants are asking voters to try to get
their ballots back by the original date, March 21, hinting that
their confidence in the U.S. mail has been shaken a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express, anyone? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
