<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 9, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the temperature soared past 80 degrees in Washington,
D.C., shattering the previous record of 77 degrees set in 1921.
While readings hovered at early summer levels across the Middle
Atlantic states Wednesday, an early spring chill gripped the
Northeast coastline where onshore breezes off the still cold ocean
suppressed readings in the 40s and 50s. Thursday, as winds veer to
the southwest, the exceptional warmth will spread to the Northeast
coast with record highs expected in both New York City and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, heavy snow and strong winds will buffet the
northern Great Lakes Thursday as a jet stream disturbance
intercepts a cold and damp flow of air from eastern Canada.
Meanwhile, clouds and spotty showers will form along a cold front
sweeping east through the eastern Great Lakes. Showers are also
possible near the Tennessee and upper Ohio Valleys as the front
undercuts and lifts humid air over the area. Behind the front,
winds from the north will direct colder air into the central Plains
and upper Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Strong high pressure near Georgia will continue to sponsor
unusually warm weather across a large area from the lower
Mississippi Valley to the Southeast and Middle Atlantic coasts as
daytime readings average between 15 and 25 degrees above normal.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will continue over portions of the West Coast
and interior West as several weak disturbances spiral ashore from
the Pacific Ocean. Locally heavy snow will affect the Sierra and
Watsach ranges while spotty rain showers occur in California.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Records Happen &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The temperature record books are being rewritten this week in
many cities from the Midwest to the Northeast as the mercury has
surged into the 70s and 80s. Scores of daily maximum temperature
marks have been established while some spots had their highest
readings so early in the season. Of course, weather anomalies are
constantly occurring across the globe. While the unusual warmth in
the northern United States has occurred where many millions of
people live, countless weather anomalies go unreported because they
happen over sparsely populated land or oceans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Extended Forecast &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday _ Low pressure will cross the Eastern States
accompanied by showery rain. Wet snow will fall in northern New
York and New England. Farther west, breezy and cooler weather will
cover the Mississippi Valley. The northern Plains will be chilly
with some flurries. The interior West will be partly cloudy with
near seasonal temperatures. The Southwest will turn drier, but rain
will arrive in the Northwest as a front approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday _ The Northeast will be rather cool with
variable clouds. Generally dry and seasonal weather will occur near
the Southeast Coast. Weak disturbances will bring flurries to the
Great Lakes while patchy clouds and showers develop in the western
Ohio and southern Mississippi valleys. The Plains will be dry with
milder air returning to northern sections. Unsettled conditions
will linger in the Northwest. The Southwest will be dry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
