<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-GOD-THE-DEVIL-REVI     03-08 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOD-THE-DEVIL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB' IS IN THE DETAILS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Thursday, March 9; tonight is THURSDAY in
this story. Fact box below.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Old Testament book of Job, God and the Devil make a
friendly wager over the fate of a good and pious man. God strips
His poor guinea pig of his belongings, offs his sons and covers his
body with boils and sores, just to see if he will still love and
praise God. Job prevails, of course (otherwise, the story probably
wouldn't have made it into the Bible), but you have to wonder how
Job's dead family felt about being treated like mere chattel for
God and Satan's amusement.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone through their respective Old Testament
fire-and-brimstone phases, God and the devil have mellowed a bit,
but they're still placing bets with one another. In ``God, the
Devil and Bob,'' God (who looks like Jerry Garcia but is voiced by
James Garner) and the devil (Alan Cumming) meet at an auto show to
stroll around and admire the new models, and get into their usual
theological bickering. The devil picks out Bob (French Stewart), an
underachieving auto worker trying to pick up some free beer in a
seamy pub, and the game is on: Can Bob (``Not my best work,'' God
sighs) redeem the world, or even himself? At stake: our entire
planet.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not a new premise _ the Bible can't exactly sue for
plagiarism. ``God, the Devil and Bob'' is an often highly amusing
lark that sugar-coats its parody of religious beliefs with some
feel-good secular humanism and an occasional dollop of sentiment.
Visuals are whimsically modest, and the animation is pretty much
what we've come to expect from network TV. Though series creator
Matthew Carlson, himself a former seminary student, treads upon
hallowed ground with a light, and lighthearted, foot, a couple of
TV stations _ including one in Salt Lake City _ have already,
predictably, declared they won't air the series.
</P>
<P>
   God is in the details in this series _ in order to prove to Bob
they are who they say they are, God pulls the old magic trick where
he pulls egg after egg from the mouth of his unamused assistant
Satan. ``Hmmm! How many are in there?'' He marvels to Himself. This
is also a world where UPN has been reconfigured into a cynical
religious network (which couldn't be any worse than it is now), and
in the underworld, Guy Lombardo and his orchestra perpetually
serenade the bummed-out guests with ``Auld Lang Syne.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob's family disregards his portentous announcement as just more
random confused babbling; only his son believes him, since he, too,
can see God. That's part of a deal he cut with the devil, the
Almighty explains _ God has relative control over them until
they're 12, and Satan takes over during the teen years. Turns out
the devil is too successful at corrupting the minds of our youth _
in episode two, the devil dates Bob's daughter to get the poor
guy's goat, but even he finds her callow nattering too repellent to
endure. God observes, ``That's why I never had any girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's pseudo-theological musings are amusing, as well, and
not afraid to address the Big Questions (the Big Answers, on the
other hand, are another matter). Of a rainbow God creates in
episode two, He explains, ``The trick is to inspire wonder without
being heavy-handed, so the atheists won't feel left out.''
</P>
<P>
   That line is indicative of ``God, the Devil and Bob's'' deadpan
fun. Its cleverness may be a little too nuanced and low-key for
mainstream audiences _ the show probably belongs on a cable
network, where it would be a programming highlight _ instead of a
broadcaster like NBC. But it's good fun to see our deity and demon
bicker over minutiae while Bob looks on without comprehension. At
one point, Bob grouses to God, ``You're so inscrutable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Creator shrugs. ``I get that a lot.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``God, the Devil and Bob.'' &QL; 
What: Animated series about a deity, a demon and the regular guy in
whose hands they place the fate of our planet. &QL; 
Who: Voices of James Garner, Alan Cumming, French Stewart. &QL; 
Where: NBC (Channel 4). &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight; then moving to its regular slot, 8:30 p.m.
Tuesdays. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
