<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-LONG-TERM-CARE09-COX     03-08 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-TERM-CARE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLAN OFFERS DOUBLE-BARRELED RELIEF FOR LONG-TERM CARE COSTS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For two years, President Clinton has sought to help
roughly 2 million American families who need or provide long-term
care by offering them a tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Republican congressional leaders have suggested
that offering people tax deductions to purchase long-term care
insurance is a better way to address the burgeoning issue.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of lawmakers put the two ideas together
Wednesday and predicted Congress would approve the proposal this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that on this issue we have so much agreement in
Washington,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa, chairman of the
Senate Select Committee on Aging and the second-ranking Republican
on the tax-writing Senate Finance Committee. ``An aging nation has
no time to waste preparing for long-term care.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-term care now costs the nation about $116 billion a year _
$43 billion spent by individuals and $73 billion by government,
primarily the federal-state Medicaid program. By 2020, the cost is
expected to jump to $207 billion a year, including $82 billion by
individuals and $125 billion by government.
</P>
<P>
   Noting there will be an additional 20 million Americans over age
65 by 2020, Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., also a member of the Finance
Committee, said the bill was needed now ``to begin to prepare for
the time when America will look as Florida does today.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of combining the competing proposals _ a tax credit for
current long-term care users, and a tax deduction for potential
future users _ grew out of a meeting between John Rother,
legislation and policy director of AARP (formerly the American
Association of Retired Persons) and Chip Kahn, president of the
Health Insurance Association of America (HIAA).
</P>
<P>
   For years, AARP has supported the tax credit, which would help
its elderly members, while HIAA has supported the tax deduction as
a way of boosting the long-term care market.
</P>
<P>
   The bill adopts Clinton's proposal for a phased-in, $3,000
non-refundable tax credit for those who purchase or provide
long-term care, either within a community care center or in a
nursing home. A non-refundable tax credit means that if the credit
exceeds a person's tax liability, the government does not refund
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes a phased-in 100 percent annual tax
deduction for long-term care insurance up to a cap of $200 for
people 40 or younger, $375 for those 41 to 50, $750 for those 51 to
60, $2,000 for those 61 to 70, and $2,500 for persons 70 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would help roughly 250,000 Americans under the
age of 18, 500,000 between 18 and 64, and 1.2 million 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are expected to cost the federal government about
$35.4 billion over 10 years. A companion to the Grassley-Graham
bill was filed in the House by Reps. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., and
Karen Thurman, D-Fla., both members of the tax-writing Ways and
Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   An HIAA study predicted the tax deduction would spur a 14 to 24
percent growth in the long-term care market. As of June 1998,
roughly 5.8 million long-term care policies had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of such insurance would reduce state Medicaid
spending on long-term care nationwide by about $3.5 billion a year,
according to the HIAA study.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
