<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MONEY-LAUNDERING-HNS &LR;      03-08 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-LAUNDERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. CITES FOUR AREAS AS MONEY-LAUNDERING CENTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, declaring war on money
laundering, designated four regions Wednesday as ``high risk''
zones for financial crimes and promised additional law enforcement
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money laundering is a growing threat to the United States,''
Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat told a news conference
as he announced the program of stepped-up law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The four areas are the Texas-Arizona border with Mexico, New
York City and northern New Jersey, the Los Angeles metropolitan
area and San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   `Money laundering undermines the confidence in the integrity of
our financial systems, facilitates crimes and corruption and allows
criminals to savor the rewards of their illegal actions,''
Eizenstat added.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said focusing law
enforcement efforts on the four areas and helping local authorities
strengthen their money-laundering surveillance efforts ``will
significantly raise the stakes for those who would profit from
crime and try to erase the taint of their criminality.''
</P>
<P>
   Money laundering is the term used to describe efforts by
criminals to infuse the proceeds from crime _ typically narcotics
and arms trafficking, bank and securities fraud and counterfeiting
_ into the mainstream economy.
</P>
<P>
   Money laundering has two steps. First, a criminal must place the
illegally earned funds into the financial system. Second, because
large amounts of currency deposited at banks usually raises red
flags, a launderer must do what is called ``layering'' or breaking
the funds into smaller chunks so as not to attract the attention of
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Wednesday's announcement, the officials said the
federal government plans to launch special money laundering teams
in these regions. The teams will include personnel from U.S.
Attorney's offices, state and local law enforcement and financial
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Treasury Department official said the program also will
provide additional money to local jurisdictions _ about $2.5
million in federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a start,'' said James Johnson, undersecretary of the
Treasury Department for enforcement. The federal aid can help local
governments buy computers or obtain technical assistance to get
their counter-money laundering operation up and running, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that the four designated areas also would be
eligible for a share of $15 million that the administration is
requesting from Congress to counter money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law enforcement officials don't have a clear picture of
how much illegal money moves through the four regions. The
International Monetary Fund estimates that some $600 billion is
laundered through financial institutions worldwide each year.
</P>
<P>
   `In light of American financial institutions prominent role in
the international financial system, a substantial portion of the
$600 billion is likely laundered thorough the United States,'' said
a joint Department of Treasury and Justice report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four regions has particular attributes that make
them attractive to criminals seeking to launder criminal proceeds,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-Mexico border and the Arizona-Mexico border were
designated because of ``large volumes of currency'' mainly derived
from drug proceeds smuggled over the border to Mexico, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The New York region is the world's leading financial center and
serves as headquarters for 44 of 50 leading banks.
</P>
<P>
   New York also is a hub for illegal activity because of its three
major airports and the Port of New York/New Jersey, the largest
such complex on the East Coast. The region is the main distribution
center in the Northeast for cocaine and heroin.
</P>
<P>
   New York area banks reported some $33 billion in suspicious
financial transactions in 1998 and 1999, more than any other region
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, the second largest city in the country after New
York and also a major financial center, is located only 150 miles
from the Mexican border. Los Angeles has the largest number of
financial institutions in the country. The seaport of Los Angeles
is the largest container port in the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angles financial institutions reported $7 billion in
suspicious transactions in 1998 and 1999, second highest after New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's location in the Caribbean means that the island is
considered strategically important for drug traffickers and money
laundering. San Juan is the most active point of entry in the
Caribbean and the closest U.S. entry point for South American drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added federal government would concentrate on beefing up
the U.S. Customs surveillance along the border to watch for the
large cash transfers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
