<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0847 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TRUMP-BOOK-TEX     03-08 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE DESERVE' BETTER, DONALD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trump: The America We Deserve'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Donald Trump with Dave Shiflett &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political essays &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Books, $24.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If one is compelled to consider billionaire developer Donald
Trump, the Yiddish word ``chutzpah'' leaps to mind. Meaning
shameless audacity, ``chutzpah'' fits Trump like a Hugo Boss suit,
summing up the Promethean ego that has motivated him to plaster his
name on Manhattan skyscrapers and up and down Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Having emerged from the brink of bankruptcy, Trump has found a
renewed sense of Caligulan self-worth, giving him the hubris to
right all the country's political wrongs. Perhaps predictably for
someone so estranged from humility, Trump has published his formula
for a better nation in ``The America We Deserve.'' We might
``deserve'' some of what Trump has to say, but few merit hearing it
from him.
</P>
<P>
   In this postmodern political world where former pro wrestlers
become governors, ``The America We Deserve'' is part of Trump's
bizarrely coquettish bid for the presidency. (On Feb. 13, Trump
announced he was giving up his campaign in light of Reform Party
turmoil. But it's not unheard of for departing Reform Party
candidates to reconsider their campaign farewells; recall Ross
Perot in 1992.) But medication more deleterious than the ailment
comes to mind when reading Trump's prescription. Whenever ``The
Donald'' stumbles upon a nugget of insight, his browbeating
delivery obliterates the point well taken. And it's certainly not
advisable for a political neophyte like Trump to come across as a
smug know-it-all. Unfortunately, Trump can't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   Through 11 chapters and an epilogue, ``The America We Deserve''
gambols across the political landscape, making shrink-wrapped
assessments of business, education, foreign policy, health care and
something called ``The American Way.'' It's a political issue cheat
sheet one might pocket before heading out to a local bar. There,
Trumpisms can be tossed off like so many beer nuts. To wit: New
York is ``the hottest city on the planet''; politics is a
``special-interest cesspool''; Pat Buchanan has ``totally lost
it''; and Bill Bradley is ``a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump's ``buck-stops-here'' solutions, often buttressed by
informative statistics, might ring truer were they not delivered in
such a patronizing tone. To be sure, Trump serves up some real
whoppers among the occasional sound judgments. For North Korea,
Trump advocates an aggressive disarmament. Great, but how?
Dilapidated schools, he opines, could be completely refurbished by
diverting the $50 billion spent on armed forces in Europe. So much
for NATO. As for crime, Trump would gladly carry out the death
penalty in public.
</P>
<P>
   Although inspired by Minnesota's new governor, Jesse Ventura,
Trump's views skew less toward the Reform Party and more toward the
Grand Old Party. His Republican loyalty shines through ad nauseam
praise of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and a severe case of
Ronald Reagan hero-worship.
</P>
<P>
   Trump musters great passion about the need to eradicate
inner-city crime and improve education. Unfortunately, these
moments of lucidity get lost in the braggadocio that has kept Trump
in the boardroom, and, so far, out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is the ``Star-Telegram'' arts critic and a
transplanted Easterner. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0848 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SCANDALMONGER-REVIEW-     03-08 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDALMONGER-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACT, FICTION MINGLE IN TALE OF OLD WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE KASKOVICH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Scandalmonger'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by William Safire &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historical fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $27 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When news of President Clinton's affair with a young White House
intern flooded newspapers and airwaves in 1998, it launched a
lengthy season of national hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   With the Clinton administration in public denial, salacious
details of sexual escapades seeped out of Washington through
unidentified sources and high-placed leaks. Defenders of the
president decried the media for hitting a new low, and pundits
accused editors of unchecked sensationalism and misplaced
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a fascinating historical novel revealing that scandals
involving the private lives of national leaders are as old as the
Founding Fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scandalmonger,'' written by Washington columnist William
Safire, tells the story of early American newspaperman James
Thomson Callender and his vitriolic attacks against Alexander
Hamilton, John Adams and Thomas Jefferson. A critic of Federalists
Hamilton and Adams, Callender eventually turns his poison pen to
Jefferson. Callender smells a hot story: Jefferson's secret affair
with, and progeny by, a black slave named Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Safire mixes a little fiction with a lot of history to make ``a
serious look into the long-ago more fun to write and more
interesting to read.'' That is accomplished. ``Scandalmonger'' is
well-paced and well-written; the novelist's approach breathes
humanity into characters usually presented as antiques in stiff,
dense histories.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even a careful reader is left to wonder: What is real here,
and what is made up?
</P>
<P>
   Safire goes to great lengths to provide disclosure. There are 40
pages of footnotes, and a bibliography. In an opening note to the
reader, he says that the characters and major events are real, save
for a concocted affair between Callender and the female
protagonist, Maria Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Many conversations are based on letters and diaries, and trials
have been reconstructed from transcripts and newspaper accounts.
Still, it is a bit much to ask readers to check the footnotes for
each chapter to see what has been enhanced. The line between
history and fiction remains a blur.
</P>
<P>
   Still, readers discover an early American society laden with the
same problems that pervade Washington two centuries later:
political manipulation and financial chicanery, moral failings and
government leaks to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a high-mindedness that sets this republic
apart from the Old World. At its core is a populist push to freely
criticize leaders and expose their shortcomings for public debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton case best exemplifies the nation's willingness to
air dirty laundry. His political ambitions are cut short after his
questionable dealings as treasury secretary are publicized by
Callender, and his extramarital affair becomes common knowledge.
But the conclusion finds Hamilton defending freedom of the press
when it is under attack from Jefferson, a political rival.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing fact with fiction, Safire is not unlike a Hollywood
director who takes liberties with a real story to bolster its
impact for a mass audience. ``Scandalmonger,'' while entertaining
and enlightening, should not be viewed as history.
</P>
<P>
   But if it gives readers a new perspective on national politics
and the role of the press, it is indeed worthwhile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Kaskovich is senior editor for projects at the
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
