<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-''PUBLICLIFE''-REVIEW     03-08 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-''PUBLICLIFE''-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SELF-PROMOTING WOLF IN `NEW DEMOCRAT' CLOTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In Praise of Public Life'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Sen. Joseph Lieberman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $21 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't let this be a trend. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a
Connecticut Democrat, just published a news release in hardback. A
164-page news release.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that presidential contenders feel compelled to
release books as part of their campaign. But if we also have
potential future candidates simultaneously publishing their
memoirs/manifestoes, we'll be flooded with books such as
Lieberman's ``In Praise of Public Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's book is offered under the pretense that the senator
is greatly concerned that too few young people are interested in
government service.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but I suspect he has an ulterior motive. The book reads
like the autobiography of a wannabe president eager to get a head
start on promoting his prospects before the next time his party
seeks a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is in his second Senate term. He serves on the Armed
Services and Governmental Affairs committees, so, at least in
theory, he is positioned to offer intriguing insights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lieberman tells us only the most obvious things about public
life. It's hard work. Personal life is closely scrutinized. It's
tough to raise enough money. It's hard on marriages. Occasionally,
some legislation is passed that brings about incremental change for
the good, and that makes it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal more ink is spilled by Lieberman explaining
Lieberman. He takes pains to defines himself as a ``New Democrat.''
That breed of politician is one who recognizes that Americans hold
shared values which eclipse partisan politics. He votes, he says,
based on his recognition of the common agreement on what is good.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``In Praise of Public Life'' is an object lesson in
how an ambitious politician can use the publishing industry as a
tool in a still-undeclared campaign. The presidential election of
2000 is far from over, but here, depending on that outcome, we have
the first printed salvos for 2004 or 2008.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
