<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PLASTIC-FURNITURE-ART     03-08 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-FURNITURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ORIGINAL! HOW VILE!   PLASTIC IN THE PARLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT3, has been sent to New York Times clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Terence Conran Shop last week, plastic chairs
were as much in evidence as plastic money. For a moment, you could
even believe they were the obvious accessories for the middle-aged
woman, impeccably coordinated in cashmere and leather, who was
dragging one gigantic specimen across the floor. She had bought a
concave thumb-shape chair ($295) in six colors and was headed for a
glass dining table to admire the fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved plastic,'' said the woman, Monique Knowlton,
an art dealer. And there was plenty to choose from, opalescent as a
rain slick or brittle as a lunch tray, from $49 to $495. ``They're
very cool, as my son would say,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Plain jane no more, plastic furniture is coming in from the
patio. Not everyone thinks that's good news.
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Corsuti didn't even break stride as her fur coat brushed
past a $241 plastic armchair by Philippe Starck, shaped like an
open-petal tulip. ``Never!'' she said. ``It's a matter of taste.
I'd put a plastic chair in the yard, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Kempner, the socialite, was even more succinct on the
subject of plastic furniture at her Park Avenue home. ``The only
plastic I want is plastic surgery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   First among modern high-tech materials, plastic has become a
lightning rod for conflicting attitudes about the domestic
environment. How innovative, how fab, how vile!
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   From a symbol of industrial innovation in the 1940s to an emblem
of grooviness in the '60s and a byword for fakery in the
herbal-essence '70s, plastic has finally arrived as the It
material. Obviously, bell-bottomed Benjamin Braddock in ``The
Graduate'' blew it.
</P>
<P>
   From Martha Stewart, the queen of populism, to avant-garde
newcomers like Karim Rashid, the most influential names in design
endorse plastics in stylish products at Kmart, Target and
high-concept SoHo stores. Last week, the maharajah of mahogany,
Ralph Lauren, bid fair to become the pasha of plastic with a
$12,585 acrylic console at his Polo shop on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   At these prices, you'll be signing it up for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But will plastic be more than a fad? Lighter in weight, thinner
in profile, turned out in softer colors and body-hugging shapes,
plastic furniture aspires to a dignified place in the home. If it
succeeds, it could change our notions of enduring domestic beauty.
``It has broken the glass ceiling already,'' said Paola Antonelli,
a curator for architecture and design at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   William Leeds, an architect, said his friends were appalled that
he had considered leaving two plastic chairs by the English
designer Jasper Morrison out of doors at his new Southampton home.
``They're too good for the deck,'' he recalled their saying.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Today's plastics are a far cry from the earliest ones developed
in military experiments toward the end of World War II. Designers
like Buckminster Fuller, Charles and Ray Eames and Eero Saarinen
were attracted to the new material for its adaptability and
potential as inexpensive mass-produced furniture.
</P>
<P>
   By the '50s and '60s, Verner Panton of Denmark and Eero Aarnio
of Finland were experimenting with Fiberglas-reinforced plastic,
sometimes painstakingly hand-laminating, as in yacht making. The
'60s introduced injection-molded plastics _ and an endless
possibility of quickly produced, frankly cheap patio furniture,
along with plastic plates, plastic tableware and, ultimately,
plastic overload.
</P>
<P>
   New chemical formulas and injection technologies render the very
word ``plastic'' obsolete. Try polycarbonate, batch-dyed
polypropylene or translucent scratch-resistent thermoplastic
technopolymer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more sophisticated product now,'' said Paul Rowan
of Umbra, the manufacturer of Karim Rashid's $50 Oh! armchair.
``It's lightweight, saturated with color. It has a translucence,
and it can take shapes that you can't get with wood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oh! is made of 100 percent recyclable polypropylene with
steel tube legs and cutouts like a paper doll. It wiggles with you
when you sit on it. So is that good? ``I wanted to make a chair
that responds to the movement of your body,'' Rashid said. ``It's
more ergonomic.'' He varied the thickness to create flexibility,
especially around the back and lumbar.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 Oh! chairs have sold since the product's
introduction in June. It was featured in Fortune magazine, and this
week it will appear in the Triennial exhibition of the
Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum among the best of show in
contemporary design.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People are finally relaxing about what furniture can look
like,'' said Ron Arad, a London-based designer who loves the
flexibility and technological derring-do of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee Mindel, an architect with Shelton, Mindel &AMP; Associates, was
not squeamish about integrating a contoured bench of white
surfboard fiberglass into a Fifth Avenue living room. He says
plastic introduces a note of sculptural refinement to a formal room
without being distracting, comparing it to a form by Hans Arp or
Brancusi. ``It's not ye olde furniture, that's for sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of ye olde $60 billion furniture industry, based in
North Carolina, plastic barely registers on the Richter scale. ``To
most people it still means cheap, and they aren't ready to accept
it in their homes,'' said Lee Buchanan, the furniture editor at
Home Furnishings News, a trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Oliver Gropp, editor in chief of House Beautiful, put a
plastic molded rocking chair by the Eameses, a gift, in the living
room. ``I moved it out,'' he said. ``You slip out of it.'' He sees
plastic furniture mostly for early nesters. ``You don't see people
trading up to it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to the dotcom set, the plastics that came out in
the '60s are enjoying a revival, as copies and reinterpretations.
The 1960 Panton chair is still in production; advances led to the
more durable polypropylene version bought by Knowlton.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek lacquered Ball chair and acrylic Bubble chair by the
Finnish designer Eero Aarnio never looked better. (Last June, it
was on the cover of Harper's Bazaar.) Aarnio still works the
material in Helsinki, most recently designing a prototype for a
plastic mesh rocking chair. Noting that plenty of plastics are
hidden in the joints of today's plushest upholstered furniture,
Aarnio said philosophically: ``Today's generation is born in the
midst of plastic. Their first night is spent in a plastic bed in
the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Kartell, the Italian manufacturer, which has a store on Greene
Street, has been working in plastics for 50 years. In 1988, the
company decided the time was ripe to line up the new talent.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic furniture may be the only way that most consumers can
afford products by high-style designers like Philippe Starck,
Antonio Citterio, Vico Magistretti and Arad. Kartell says it has
sold hundreds of thousands of translucent stacking drawers on a
metal frame by Citterio since they were introduced for $659 in
1995. Last April, Kartell introduced La Marie by Starck, a $185
chair of polycarbonate (the Veuve Cliquot of plastics). The company
has steadily sold about 1,000 of them a month in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic is interesting to me because it is not made by God,''
Starck said. ``It is created by human intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He is working on products made of gel packets adapted from the
medical supplies industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the resistance to plastic is not only psychological. John
Ryan, the floor manager at Kartell, said that consumers sometimes
go into shock when they see the high prices. Much time is spent in
the store explaining why designer plastics cost so much.
</P>
<P>
   The short version goes something like this: First there's the
research into new methods, like nitrogen injection, or vacuum
molding, which might take a year or two. (Kartell encourages its
designers to pursue new technology as if it were some kind of
extreme sport.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the mold itself, a ballroom-size machine, which has
to be custom built for each furniture piece and which could easily
cost $1 million to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not polypropylene shampoo bottles here,'' Ryan said.
(Don't forget to include in your budget an allowance for Windex to
erase fingerprints.) Even Mindel, for whom a glamorous image is
all, conceded that plastic furniture can look like something from
``The Outer Limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Nan Kempner gamely contemplated an orange
injection-molded armchair design by Ron Arad in her perfectly
appointed Park Avenue living room. Amid the velvet-covered Italian
Rococo antiques, the gilt Chinoiserie mirror and a pair of Moorish
figurines, the chair stood out like a lollipop stuck in a lobster
salad. But Kempner managed to be generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good room isn't a good room,'' she said, ``until it has
something crummy in it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
