<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE09-COX     03-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE LAUNCHES HIS BID FOR CENTRIST VOTERS
 &HT;    Eds: May be updated with quotes from Michigan event this
evening.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ His claim on the Democratic presidential
nomination all but official, Vice President Al Gore wasted no time
Wednesday launching his general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He began by reaching out in television interviews to the
independent voters who have fueled Sen. John McCain's campaign in
the Republican contest against Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and
have swelled the primary voting ranks.
</P>
<P>
   And after visiting his elderly mother in nearby Carthage, Gore
began a trip that advisers said was designed to begin wooing
moderate and reform-minded voters in the general election
battleground states of Michigan and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Gore planned a Wednesday evening meeting with undecided voters
at Wayne State University near Detroit. On Thursday, he will be
joined by former Vice President Walter Mondale in a visit to a
Minnesota high school to promote his education reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask all of those who have supported (McCain and
Bradley) to look at this campaign as their cause,'' Gore said
Wednesday morning on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, swept by Gore in all 16 Democratic contests
Tuesday, is expected to withdraw from the Democratic race on
Thursday and endorse Gore. That gesture is designed to solidify
Democratic ranks against Bush, the presumptive GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   That means Gore, in the coming days, will begin his courtship of
``McCainiacs,'' as thousands of first-time voters have come to be
known in the wake of Arizona senator's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain voters are much closer to Al Gore on issues
than they are to George Bush,'' Bob Shrum, one of Gore's senior
media strategists, told reporters after Gore's sweep of the Super
Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, McCain and Bush share the same view on some of the key
issues separating Republicans and Democrats. Both oppose abortion
and gun control measures, and both support taxpayer-financed
competition between public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's tax cut proposals resemble Gore's more than Bush's.
And like Gore, McCain has proposed using part of the federal budget
surplus to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McCain and Gore support campaign finance reforms
that would eliminate soft money, large donations to the parties
that are largely unregulated by federal campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   To win in November, both Gore and Bush ``have to come up with a
way of attracting the pro-reform, pro-change voters who were
attracted to John McCain and Bill Bradley,'' said Stuart
Rothenberg, a political analyst for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls in Tuesday's California primary illustrate
Rothenberg's point. Of voters questioned Tuesday as they left the
polls, Gore was preferred by 36 percent, Bush 28 percent, McCain 23
percent and Bradley 9 percent. To carry California and its 54
electoral votes, the largest number of any state, Gore and Bush
have to attract the McCain vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists believe they have the advantage because McCain
forced Bush to rely on the most conservative members of the
Republican Party to win the GOP nomination. Consequently, Gore, in
his victory speech Tuesday night, declared the Democratic Party the
``mainstream'' party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists also believe they can paint Bush as out of the
political mainstream on key issues while contrasting uninterrupted
economic prosperity during the Clinton administration with the
recessions that occurred during the two previous Republican
presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out of step with America,'' Gore campaign spokesman
Chris Lehane told reporters. ``George W. Bush is right and wrong.
He's far to the right on issues like gun control, a patient's bill
of rights and the environment, and he's wrong on the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
