<HEADLINE>
NIGHT LIGHTS A PROBLEM? NOT REALLY, SCIENTISTS NOW SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new studies suggest that parents who leave night lights on
will not night make their children nearsighted, contradicting a
report in May indicating an association between night lights and
myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups of researchers report in the current journal Nature
that they were unable to duplicate the results of an earlier study
suggesting that children who sleep with a night light until age 2
are three times more likely to develop nearsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This night light question has been the biggest question that
some of my colleagues have gotten from parents. It has worried
thousands of parents unnecessarily,'' said Jane Gwiazda, director
of the Children's Vision Laboratory at the New England College of
Optometry in Boston, one of the two centers that conducted the
follow-up studies. The other was done at Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   The original study, also published in Nature, was conducted by
scientists at the University of Pennsylvania and the Children's
Hospital of Philadelphia. It raised the possibility that too much
light during the first two years of life prompts the rapidly
developing eyes to grow excessively and throws them out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   The follow-up studies found no difference between the rate of
myopia for children who slept in the dark and those who slept with
a night light.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the real explanation may be _ at least indirectly
_ heredity, the researchers said. Myopic parents are more likely to
have myopic children. And myopic parents may like to leave night
lights on so they can see better at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it made it easier to find their baby at night,'' Gwiazda
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston group studied 213 people ranging in age from 2 to 24,
with a mean age of 11. It found that 20 percent of the children who
slept with night lights developed myopia, exactly the same
percentage as the youngsters who slept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio State study, which involved 1,220 children with a
median age of 10, found the percentage of children who became
nearsighted after sleeping with a night light as babies was about
17 percent. Statistically, that was the same as the 20 percent of
the children who slept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the percentage of children who slept in a fully lit
room and later became nearsighted was essentially the same, at 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest link the Ohio State study found was between the
number of nearsighted parents and their use of night lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprise, surprise: Those of us who can't see like to leave
the lights on,'' said Karla Zadnik, an Ohio State optometrist.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Stone, an ophthalmologist and coauthor of the
Pennsylvania study, said in a response published in Nature that
widespread publicity may have led parents in the follow-up studies
to underreport night light use out of guilt for possibly
contributing to myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Andres, 35, of Cambridge, Mass. and her three children
participated in the study at the New England College of Optometry.
She said she stopped using night lights when she heard about the
association between the lights and nearsightedness. Andres, who is
not nearsighted, said her children _ 7 1/2, 5, and 18 months _ have
no eye problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
