<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashes and Lace &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By B.J. Hoff &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tyndale House, $11.99) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in B.J. Hoff's ``Ashes and Lace'' has a secret, and
those secrets that didn't come out in her previous novel, ``Cloth
of Heaven,'' are coming out now. And when they do ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashes and Lace'' continues the Ohio author's 19th-century
Irish-American saga of the successful, roguish immigrant Jack Kane;
widow Samantha Harte, who is drawn to the publishing magnate
despite his lack of faith and her previous husband's abuse;
teen-ager Terese Sheridan, who falls desperately ill during her
voyage to the United States; artist Brady Kane, sojourner in
Ireland and the ne'er-do-well father of Terese's illegitimate
child; and the devout Gabriel Vaughan, who is determined to keep
his deaf ward, Roweena, from being Brady's next conquest.
</P>
<P>
   Hoff's prose is emotional and evangelistic and provides Edgar
Allan Poe with a cameo appearance. Even though fire, snow, death,
rage and rape all figure into the story (onstage or off), Hoff can
hardly be accused of sensationalism, and ``Ashes and Lace'' has
about as many happy endings as one could want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Home'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Ortega &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Myrrh Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Ortega is, first and foremost, a storyteller. His songs
are compelling not because of melodies, harmonies or fancy
musicianship, but because they tell tales: of faith, family,
triumph and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   That's the standard he set on his 1997 Myrrh album ``This Bright
Hour,'' his first release on a major label, and continued on 1998's
``The Breaking of the Dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   He remains faithful to it on ``Home.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories include uplifting tales of creation and a neighbor's
daughter; sad tales of a homeless woman and a man with Alzheimer's;
a bittersweet tale of earthly suffering before heavenly glory; an
introspective tale of life on the road away from family; a prayer
of blessing for his new home, written by friends (the inspiration
for the album title); and two plaintive, heartfelt hymns, ``Pass Me
Not'' and ``Give Me Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   The words are poetic, thoughtful, insightful. Ortega's
expressive voice breathes life into them. Clearly, this is what
Ortega does as well as anyone singing Christian music today.
</P>
<P>
   That is what ``Home'' has in common with Ortega's first two
Myrrh albums. Where it differs is in the music, and it's a change
for the better.
</P>
<P>
   The album was recorded ``live'' in a studio with a band, giving
it a more energetic feel. There's even a couple of upbeat cuts,
allowing Ortega to have two songs _ ``This Good Day'' and ``Give Me
Jesus'' _ getting radio play simultaneously on Contemporary
Christian and Inspirational formats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
