<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PINK-GRAPEFRUIT-NYTR &LR;      03-08 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINK-GRAPEFRUIT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIANS HONOR `MILLION-DOLLAR MISTAKE'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DALE WHITE   Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Next week, the Manatee County Historical
Society will officially celebrate a so-called blunder by nature _ a
crop mutation known as pink grapefruit _ by marking the spots where
the once-peculiar fruit was discovered nearly 90 years ago.
Generations of citrus growers have called pink grapefruit ``the
million-dollar mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a freak event,'' said Andy Reasoner of Oneco,
great-grandson of the nurseryman who first marketed the pink
grapefruit. ``It happened purely by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1913, R.B. Foster, manager of Kimball C. Atwood's grove east
of Palmetto, noticed a biological mutation on a limb of a tree
otherwise laden with seedless, yellow grapefruit. He wondered if
the thin-skinned grapefruits on that limb were similar to
discolored fruit he found earlier and suspected of being diseased.
</P>
<P>
   He cut into a sample fruit from that limb and found rosy pink
flesh instead of the pale pulp of ordinary grapefruit. Atwood
marked the limb with a red neckerchief, so he could find it again
in the 25,000-tree grove.
</P>
<P>
   Also that year, Samuel Collins, an employee at W.B. Thompson's
grove in Oneco, noticed the same biological mutation in grapefruit
on a single tree limb there.
</P>
<P>
   Both groves took budwood from the trees to the Reasoner Brothers
Royal Palm Nurseries in Oneco. Nursery owner Egbert Reasoner
grafted the budwood onto orange stock, creating trees that produced
the Foster Pink Grapefruit and Thompson Pink Grapefruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mutation in the plant world takes an act of God or Mother
Nature,'' Andy Reasoner said. ``But it's not just that the pink
grapefruit was a mutation. What made the difference is that someone
recognized this mutation, on one limb of one tree out of hundreds
of acres of trees and millions of fruit harvested, and recognized
that the mutation was significant and was able to propagate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, pink grapefruit received poor reviews. Growers at the
Florida Horticultural Society joked that it was ``suitable only for
ladies' pink teas.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Egbert Reasoner was its lone advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Then a freeze devastated Florida's citrus groves. Growers asked
Reasoner to supply them with trees. They bought every citrus tree
he had in stock _ except for the pink grapefruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   After the same freeze devastated groves in Texas' Rio Grande
Valley, growers there came to Reasoner looking for stock. All that
Reasoner could provide was pink grapefruit trees. The Texans bought
a railcar full. By the 1920s, the Texas citrus industry had
capitalized greatly on making the pink grapefruit a breakfast-table
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Reasoner and other descendants of the nursery man who first
promoted the pink grapefruit plan to attend the marker dedications.
``It wouldn't be correct if we weren't there,'' Reasoner said.
</P>
<P>
   (Dale White writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla. The
Herald-Tribune is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
