<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DOCTOROW-CITY-ART-2TA     03-08 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOROW-CITY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOROW'S LATEST NOVEL SAMPLES THE MODERN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The novels of E.L. Doctorow are known for their riffs on
American history.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Welcome to Hard Times,'' published in 1960,
was set on the 19th-century American frontier and used the creation
of a small town as a metaphor for the rise and corruption of
civilization. His best known work, ``Ragtime'' (1975), depicted a
nation on the verge of World War I, at the genesis of the
celebrity-saturated, ethnically mixed and behaviorally volatile
society it has become. His gentle semiautobiographical novel
``World's Fair'' (1985), which he has called ``a portrait of the
artist as a young boy,'' was set in the Bronx in the 1930s. ``The
Book of Daniel'' (1971) dealt with the radical politics of the
1960s within a fictional account of the time by the son of a couple
based on Julius and Ethel Rosenberg. His recent book ``The
Waterworks'' (1994) was something of a detective story set in 1870s
New York, involving a missing newspaper reporter and an evil
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   If a theme runs through them all, it is the past as progenitor
of the present. The persistent suggestion of Doctorow's fiction is
this: From there, we got here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you set a book in the past, you're inevitably writing
about the present,'' Doctorow said in a recent interview on the
campus of New York University, where he is teaching this semester.
</P>
<P>
   In his new novel, however, his 10th, he has taken a reverse
tack. Set in the present, again in New York City, which it uses as
a teeming representation of the modern world, the book looks back
on the 20th century, probing the circumstances of its three main
characters _ a priest, a rabbi and a writer _ in such a way that
the weight of history is brought to bear on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated in an experimental mode, with a jumpiness meant to
mimic what Doctorow calls the attention deficit disorder that
afflicts the entire culture, the novel has a brazen millennial cast
that is evident in the title: ``City of God.'' And its bravado has,
perhaps predictably, polarized critics. Writing in The New York
Times, Michiko Kakutani called it a ``novel of ideas that may be
packed with ideas but that fails as a satisfying work of fiction.''
In Newsweek, Peter Plagens wrote that it all hangs together
``brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``City of God'' focuses its jittery eye on many things _
birds, the Holocaust, the poetry inherent in song lyrics,
cosmology, the movies and adultery, to name a few. But its central
subject is the search for faith in a dangerous and cacophonous age.
Recapitulative, with a sense of conclusive authority, it addresses
more directly than his previous novels the nature of contemporary
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said to me once that my books can be arranged in rough
chronological order to indicate one man's sense of 120 years of
American life,'' Doctorow said. ``In this book, it seems I've
finally caught up to the present. I've been very slow about it, but
I finally made it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 69, a man of wry and avuncular mien dressed in dapper
professorial mode, he was speaking in his characteristic fashion, a
soft, insistent voice with a hint of conspiratorial invitation. Yet
he was also hesitant, as if, because of the novel's spiritual
subject matter, he felt shy. A Jew, his own spiritual inquiry is
mirrored, he said, in that of one of the book's leading characters,
a woman rabbi, ``but I like to think that, finally, religion is a
private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there is a wicked side to the novel; it ends with an
emotionally and intellectually fraught mixed-faith wedding and
includes a toast, a challenge to God, really, that also seems
likely to challenge readers who have the delicate sensibilities of
the traditionally devout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do You not find it an unforgivable lapse of Yours,'' the
bridegroom says, with a raised glass, in one of his tamer
locutions, ``that after these thousands of years we can no more
explain ourselves than we can explain You?'' Doctorow seemed ill at
ease at the suggestion that the wedding, the novel's climactic
event, was planned provocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never ducked controversy,'' Doctorow said. ``Why would
any writer do that?'' What worries him, though, he said, is that
viewing the book as merely inflammatory is to diminish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of it as a big kitchen sink of a book, with a lot of
surprises and riffs and all sorts of things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding speech, he said, ``is just a portrayal of hell. The
book turns out to cover a kind of struggle for faith, a spiritual
crisis of one sort or another of these two people, both of whom are
historically aware. And I don't think people who are secure in
their faith can feel anything but compassion for this sort of
struggle, which many people have gone through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also feel that an enormous number of people, perhaps most of
the people in this country, partake of both ways of thinking and
being without ever landing in one way or another. A lot of the
Judeo-Christian ethic is now instilled in civil life. It is
possible for people who are not particularly pious to live just as
ethically as people who are pious. As far as a critique of
traditional religion, that's nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   The structure of the novel is complex. The narrative takes the
form of a writer's notebook in which Everett, the protagonist (
Doctorow has frequently created a creator to narrate his tales)
records observations and ideas of all kinds _ the scattered life of
his mind. In search of a subject for his own new novel, Everett
reads a newspaper account of how a large cross was stolen from an
Episcopal church in Lower Manhattan and placed, ostensibly by the
thieves, on the roof of a small synagogue on the Upper West Side.
Neither the motive nor the perpetrator of what Everett calls ``the
heist'' is ever uncovered (the mystery hovers symbolically through
the book) but as he investigates the case, Everett befriends Pem,
the church rector, and the synagogue's two young rabbis, who are
husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories begin to take shape in Everett's notebook, along
with meditations on the origins of the universe; ideas for movie
scripts; descriptions of sexual affairs; recollections of
bird-watching expeditions; monologues in the voices of, among
others, Wittgenstein and Einstein; biographical sketches, in
faux-Homeric verse, drawn from his family's experiences in the
century's wars; jazzlike improvisations on the lyrics of popular
song standards; even a comic fantasy about a frustrated former
reporter for The New York Times (``ex-Times guy,'' Everett calls
him) who seeks murderous justice for unpunished war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, Doctorow said, is ``not only a writer, he's kind of an
Everyman.'' He continued: ``In his mind is the cultural detritus of
all minds, the controlling ideas of the culture that are in
everybody's mind. He has certain preoccupations he comes back to.
He's a bachelor and lives a life of his own appetites and
interests. But the wonderful thing I discovered is that all these
free-ranging themes, these leitmotifs, all of them relate to the
central quandary caused by the mystery of the missing cross.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the stolen cross came to him, Doctorow said, long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have been in a church for some reason, someone had
died, or I was participating in a panel, and I saw a large brass
cross behind the altar,'' he said. ``Someone had recently painted
the church _ it was somewhere in the city _ and it had not been
done well, and there was a kind of shadow, an outlining around the
parts of the cross, and I imagined, `What if the cross were taken
down? You could still see the shadow.' It was from that image I was
able to create Pem.''
</P>
<P>
   The story stands as an illustration of how Doctorow's novels
grow. It is an organic thing, as he describes it, the channeling of
subjects that interest him through the searching voice of a
fictional persona. Never an exhaustive researcher (``I stand by the
fallibility of Everett's research,'' he said of the science and
history in ``City of God,''), he concocts his worlds from the
probing of imagination. That one theme of the book is the artist as
a God-like figure is not accidental; it jibes with the idea that
God's earth is not entirely within his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every act of creativity is a puny human imitation of grand
Creation,'' Doctorow said. And if ``City of God'' deals with
profound issues provocatively, that wasn't the point, he added,
merely the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever begin a book with a grand intention,'' he said.
``Or any intention. I write to find out what I'm writing. Before
you do anything, you have to find a voice, a diction that makes
certain things possible and some things not. This fellow Everett,
and his daily work habits, and his attraction, he doesn't know why,
for these religious people allowed me to find this subject, this
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``It's starting from some private excitement,
usually having to do with language and trying to discover what is
so evocative about it. What's so evocative about a stolen cross
being found on the roof of a synagogue? And you've got this person,
and he's got all kinds of problems, his own interests and
ambitions, he's living a profane life and he attaches himself to
these righteous people. You don't find yourself asking, `Do I
deserve to talk about these issues?' You find yourself asking, `How
can I make this work?'''
</P>
<P>
   Doctorow warmed to his discourse; he had found the way to talk
about his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found here was this book mimics the rhythm of the mind
as we have it today,'' he said. ``We're all hopping around buzzing
from information. The whole culture is full of that. If I write a
book that gets its tension from discontinuities, I've found a
template for the way we're thinking. When I find Everett doing
riffs on song lyrics, that makes me happy. In fact, songs are
immensely powerful things in our culture, and it turns out as I'm
doing this, all these things, these seeming discontinuities,
converge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes to the hospital at the end, and they're sitting, the
dying people, singing standards, waving their hands in time to the
music. Well, you discover the popular song is the equivalent of a
hymn in what is basically a secular culture, with the same ideals,
the same romantic possibilities of real life and real love that you
find in the hopes and pieties of hymns.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the novel, he recalled, Everett puts a monologue
in the voice of Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he has Sinatra say, `Here is the whole world falling
apart, Hitler is killing Jews, Stalin is killing Russians, the
Japanese are beheading Chinese coolies, the whole world is pouring
blood, and here I am singing in my bel canto.'''
</P>
<P>
   Doctorow smiled. ``Speaking of offending people,'' he said, ``I
think I'm more likely to offend true Sinatra fans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: OF LOYALTY OR ROYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It often happens that an author who has produced a best seller
(or a near best seller) for a small publishing house immediately
jumps to a big publisher for the next book.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing is an ambulatory business, with the players popping
from house to house, but upon first reflection the vigorous
desertion of writers from the publishers who have propelled their
career seems _ even nasty. But is this disloyalty, or does the
getaway serve a very understandable self-interest? Do you have to
leave the dance with the one who brought you? It's an old debate in
publishing. Writers have frangible careers, publishing is a harsh
business, and it seems only fair that they follow the cash when
that decision is most comfortable for them. Perhaps the role of the
small publisher is to discover and create careers, particularly
those of fiction writers.
</P>
<P>
   What brings this to mind is Susan Vreeland's ``Girl in Hyacinth
Blue,'' a concise novel that follows the influence of what may have
been a lost Vermeer portrait on several generations of lives
starting in present day America and hurtling back to the
17th-century Netherlands. Vreeland's agent, Barbara Braun, said it
was originally rejected by about 15 New York publishers before it
was bought for an insignificant $5,000 advance by MacMurray &AMP; Beck,
a small Denver publishing house, which put it out it in December
with a first printing of 8,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   There are now about 40,000 hardcover copies in print, and the
novel is on the extended best-seller list of The New York Times and
is being sold in eight countries. Meanwhile, Vreeland has left her
publisher, having been trawled in for two new books with a
mid-six-figure advance from Viking (for hardcover rights) and
Penguin (for softcover), both of which were among the 15 that first
shunned her. In fact, Penguin had an epiphany about the merit of
``Girl'' and bought the paperback rights for $55,000. (Viking and
Penguin are imprints of Penguin Putnam Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Koffler, editorial director of MacMurray &AMP; Beck, said:
``I don't enjoy it, but it is a small press reality, and authors
must do what's best for them. We probably can't compete on the same
level as a larger house.'' Compete is not only about cash for
advances, but also about the drapery of distribution, marketing,
advertising and public relations that must fold around a book for
it to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Vreeland has nothing but praise for MacMurray &AMP; Beck _ ``They
had faith in me when I was an unknown writer'' _ and most
particularly for its publisher, Fred Ramey, and editor, Greg
Michalson, both of whom resigned recently. Vreeland said that ``one
of the features I will miss is the tremendous marketing and public
relations people at MacMurray.'' Anyway, she said she was fearful
that MacMurray &AMP; Beck would be sold. The more likely outcome is
that Penguin Putnam, ever on the lookout for rainmakers, will hire
Ramey and Michalson.
</P>
<P>
   Jane von Mehren, the associate publisher of Penguin, who
gathered in Vreeland, said: ``Smaller houses are wonderful at
establishing new writers, sometimes better than bigger houses
because they have smaller lists to focus on. But there's that
moment that an author, to keep growing, has to jump to a big
publisher for better distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always on the lookout for writers that we can grow,''
she said. ``Or looking at books that have never been published or
for writers previously published by someone else.'' Perhaps
predatory, but nonetheless mostly author-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   There are writers who want to stay at small houses, even after
they have written best sellers. In 1995, Walker &AMP; Co., a small New
York City house, published Dava Sobel's ``Longitude,'' a
60,000-word book about the invention of the chronometer. It turned
out to be a joyous yet thoroughly perplexing publishing experience.
It was on the best-seller lists of The Times for a total of 41
weeks. It was Book One of a two-book deal, for a total advance of
about $25,000. The second book was ``Galileo's Daughter,'' which
spent 18 weeks of The Times' hardcover nonfiction list. Both books
have been optioned for the movies. Meanwhile Sobel has been
borrowed by von Mehren to write ``The Planets'' for an advance in
excess of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   I say borrowed because the writer and her agent, Michael
Carlisle, would like to remain with George Gibson, publisher of
Walker &AMP; Co. If possible, that is. Sobel said: ``People say that
now that you've had these big successes you could go anywhere else.
With `Galileo's Daughter,' George didn't think it was right. He had
me rewrite it. It took a whole extra year. He was right. I feel
strongly that at a big house they would have pressed me to get it
out anyhow, because people were expecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   So the question is how big a risk she is willing to take to stay
with a small publisher. Gibson said that a $100,000 advance was the
largest he has given at Walker, but he indicated that he would go
higher to hold Sobel after ``The Planets.'' But seven figures? For
Sobel the risk of returning to Walker is giving up a huge advance
at the start in the hope that the book will leap onto the
best-seller lists when it is finished and she will earn the big
money then. It's a gamble she's willing to take. ``You get the
money later, rather than sooner,'' she said. ``For me, what matters
is who you work with and what the relationship is.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually to do this, a writer must have an agent who supports
the leap of faith, since agents, quite naturally, like to see as
much cash as possible, and quickly. But in Carlisle, she does. He
said: ``The experience she has had with George Gibson has not only
been extraordinarily remunerative and supportive, but it's been for
her like the old-fashioned enjoyable publishing experiences. I
don't win bragging rights for selling two books for so little
money, but what's been important is that George published her as if
he had spent a lot of money. Here's a man who drove six hours in
the middle of the night to make sure she had a pile of books at a
book signing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle added that ``it works as long as she is writing best
sellers.''
</P>
<P>
   There are authors who have gone from large to much smaller
houses, although most of the time the author who hits it big with a
first book published by a small house feels the need for the
security and the money that the bigger house provides. So in book
publishing, it's not a gauche or even stupid to go home from the
dance with a stranger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
