<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-ORISSA-RECOVERY-COX     03-08 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORISSA-RECOVERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indians still reeling from cyclone's punch
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERSAMA, India _ Fourteen-year-old Kailash Swain watches intently
as the villagers of Jappa celebrate for the first time in four
months. It is a small festival to honor Sarna, a Hindu goddess of
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Children and saffron-clad priests wend past damaged mud huts,
fallen palms and stagnant pools of water. Kailash's gaze falls on
the flower-adorned picture of Sarna. He wants to go to school, but
he knows he will probably have to set his dreams aside and work the
land instead.
</P>
<P>
   The second of two powerful cyclones last October brought 165-mph
winds to Jappa and the rest of coastal Ersama district in the
eastern Indian state of Orissa. At least 10,000 people died; 7
million more were left homeless. In Jappa, the cyclone made orphans
of Kailash and his three younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things will never be like before, but what can I do?'' Kailash
said.
</P>
<P>
   Choice is no longer a part of many people's lives in
cyclone-ravaged Orissa. India's worst storm of the century changed
the face of the state for years to come and left the poorest of the
country's poor with nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Atlanta-based relief and development agency
CARE USA, the state's cash crops _ coconut, papaya and betel nuts,
which are chewed as a stimulant _ suffered millions of dollars in
damage. Rice paddies were swept away by the wind or rotted
underwater a month before harvest. More than 40,000 fishing
families lost their boats and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one thing on everyone's minds these days, and
that is our next meal,'' said farmer Kedar Kuanar. ``We were
dependent on our rice paddies, which were totally destroyed. We
have no housing, no schools _ everything collapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell it has been four months since death and
destruction came ashore Oct. 29. Aid workers say the recovery
process has been further hampered by government bureaucracy and
inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Entire villages, including Jappa, still lie flattened. Dried up
palm fronds and mangled trees line the roads. Among the patches of
still standing greenery are smatterings of blue tarpaulins handed
out by relief agencies to act as roofing on the skeletons of mud
huts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still struggling. They are struggling very much,''
said Orissa's CARE director, Basant Mohanty, who traveled to
Atlanta and other U.S. cities in December to appeal for money. ``We
are facing so many logistical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mercy for Ersama, just south of the super-cyclone's
landfall. The high gusts of winds were followed by a tidal wave
that rose to 20 feet. People saw family members and neighbors fly
through the air or be washed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental ward in the Cuttack hospital doubled in size after
the cyclone,'' said Girish Swain, one of CARE's relief workers.
``Some people hoot like the first sound of the wind they heard.
Others saw their parents die in front of them. The damaged
infrastructure can be rebuilt, but what about all these people who
went mad?''
</P>
<P>
   Salt left by the tidal wave destroyed soil in the rice paddies
and slowed decomposition of human bodies, making the cleanup more
gruesome.
</P>
<P>
   Decomposing corpses still lie in the fields and ponds of Ersama,
said Narayan Panigrahy, an aid worker with the Indian relief agency
AWARE. ``The government says 10,000 people died in the Orissa
cyclone. I think 15,000 died in Ersama alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning up contaminated watering holes and rebuilding
infrastructure are part of CARE's rehabilitation program to help
the 15 million Orissans affected by the cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   On an ominously cloudy day, 500 of Ersama's villagers gathered
to rebuild a damaged road. The project was part of CARE's food and
work program, through which cyclone victims volunteer labor in
exchange for supplies such as cooking oil and a blend of cornmeal
and soya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following disaster situations such as the cyclones in Orissa,
people's suffering and rehabilitation efforts crucial to recovery
continue long after the media interest fades,'' said Bob Laprade,
who oversees CARE's programs in Asia and Europe from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The once-proud fishermen and rice farmers picked away at
Ersama's red clay with axes. They said they were fortunate to be
able to return home with food tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``How our life has changed!'' said farmer Kuanar. ``We were
poor, but earlier we had so many resources at hand. Now, we get by
with one meal a day. We go out of our villages looking for kinds of
work we have not ever had to do before.''
</P>
<P>
   Jillani Khan is lucky that he already had a job as a hotel
worker in Orissa's capital, Bhubaneswar. His $13 monthly salary is
all his wife and children have now for survival. He can no longer
depend on the fruits of his land for income.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared now of another natural calamity,'' Khan said.
``It's pointless thinking about what happened. But I am scared of
rebuilding. What if I lose it all again?''BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Village leaders were eager to talk to the CARE workers who
showed up at the road building site.
</P>
<P>
   As they huddled around CARE's Swain, a 70-year-old woman pushed
through the crowd, tears disappearing into the folds of her dark
cheeks. She wiped her face with the end of her turquoise blue
cotton sari.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man I adopted as my son took away my ration card. I have
no food, nothing to eat. I have to beg for my food,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sodari Sethi used to launder clothes to barter for food. Now, no
one can spare her anything or has time to deal with her problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mob culture here these days. It's definitely survival
of the fittest,'' Swain said. ``And the people who need it the most
don't always receive the aid. The guy living in the concrete house
will get a floor mat just as easily as the guy forced to live in a
collapsed thatch hut.''END OF OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Ersama villagers have one hope: that this year's monsoons will
rinse away the salt in the earth and replenish the greenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that God will provide,'' said Kuanar.
``Otherwise, we will be no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
