<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-BOB-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-08 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOB-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB': MORTAL BUMBLER TRIES TO SETTLE ETERNAL
CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Broadcast notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Please check local listings) 
(bl) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As God and the devil battle over an everyman named Bob Alman,
``God, the Devil and Bob'' thrusts one eternal mystery before us
with such insistence that it cannot be avoided. So, OK, why  &UR; does &LR; 
God look like Jerry Garcia? With his white hair and beard, T-shirt
and granny glasses, the resemblance is too blatant to be
accidental.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to figure out why this animated series has given God
the voice of James Garner. Wry, easygoing, reassuring, he is the
friendliest deity anyone could ask for. Alan Cumming, as the Devil,
slides from the onstage decadence of ``Cabaret'' into the great
tradition of English-accented villains from old Bible movies. With
his purplish face and horns, goatee and a black greatcoat, he is a
Goth alternative to the laid-back God. And French Stewart moves
smoothly from the bumbling alien Harry on ``Third Rock from the
Sun'' to the bumbling family man Bob. Yet this perfect casting only
proves that even God and Satan are nowhere without a good script.
</P>
<P>
   The series begins with a few promising, mischievous touches. God
and the Devil meet in a bar, where they choose Bob to prove that
the world is worth saving. A sign in hell reads: ``Tonight and
every night, Guy Lombardo.'' (If that doesn't scare you straight,
nothing will.)
</P>
<P>
   But before long, the rock-solid Bob has accepted his role and
all traces of mischief disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, I saved the world,'' Bob says as he walks in the door
one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not now, Bob,'' says his wife (Laurie Metcalf), displaying why
beneath its supposedly risky premise the series is just one more
benign and stale family sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the Devil and Bob'' may look like a cartoon, but it never
takes advantage of the freedom to be outrageous that animation
offers. This Devil is even more of a bumbler than Bob. Even when
Satan takes the shape of a boy who wants to date Bob's 13-year-old
daughter (in a future episode), there is no conflict, just
groan-inducing punch lines. ``You are never to see that boy
again,'' Bob tells her. ``He is actually Satan in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitched battle, in which evil doesn't stand a chance,
reveals the show's true reverence and the wrongheaded position of
the handful of stations that have refused to run it in prime time.
A station in Salt Lake City that will not carry it at all has also
refused to show ``Saturday Night Live,'' putting this little flap
in the category of fringe reactions that get way too much
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is that even for a sunny sitcom, the humor is
tired. In a future episode, God begins to tell Bob why evil exists,
but his voice is drowned out by a passing train. That joke was done
with more cultural savvy on ``South Park'' when Jesus, who has his
own talk show, was about to answer the same question, only to have
the television go full of snow and static.
</P>
<P>
   As for the God-as-Garcia look, the show's creators have said
that there is no specific reason behind it. Yet Thursday night when
God has to prove his identity to Bob, he morphs swiftly from Garcia
into the stereotypical picture of the Old Testament God merely by
growing his hair and beard longer and turning his T-shirt into a
robe. It seems that Jerry Garcia looked like God, not the other way
around, a mystery best left alone.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GOD, THE DEVIL AND BOB'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Thursday night at 8:30
</P>
<P>
   A production of Vanity Logo Productions and NBC Studios Inc. in
association with the Carsey-Werner Co. Matthew Carlson, Harvey
Myman, Marcy Carsey, Tom Werner and Caryn Mandabach, executive
producers.
</P>
<P>
   With voices of: James Garner (God), Alan Cumming (the Devil),
French Stewart (Bob), Laurie Metcalf (Donna), Nancy Cartwright
(Megan), Kath Soucie (Andy) and Jeff Doucette (Smeck). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
