<P>
   NY-POLICE-JURIES (New York) _ The testimony of the police is
often the bedrock of efforts to win criminal indictments and
convictions against suspects. In many cases, the outcome hinges on
whether a jury believes the account of a patrolman who makes an
arrest, an undercover narcotics officer who buys drugs or a
detective who elicits a confession. Over the last six months in the
criminal courts of New York City, prosecutors say they are seeing a
change: grand jurors in Manhattan and Brooklyn are intensively
scrutinizing the testimony of police officers. And in Queens,
juries are deadlocking in an increasing number of cases, a sign,
prosecutors fear, that jurors are questioning the veracity of
police testimony. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASIA (Washington) _ President Clinton on Wednesday sent
Congress the legislation that would usher China into the World
Trade Organization, setting off what promises to be a highly
divisive fight within the Democratic party that intertwines the
politics of trade and Clinton's final effort to stabilize relations
with the world's most populous nation. By David E. Sanger.
