<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LBJ:ALIFE-REVIEW-TEX     03-08 0316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LBJ:A </SLUG>
 LIFE-REVIEW-TEX 
LBJ in the middle years 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By JEFF GUINN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``LBJ: A Life'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Irwin Unger and Debi Unger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley, $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It would seem, by this point, that everything that can possibly
be written about Lyndon Johnson would already be in print. Thanks
to Robert Caro and Robert Dallek and Merle Miller and a dozen other
biographers, we know all about LBJ's poverty-stricken Hill Country
childhood, his father's failed political career, his mother's
obsessions, the courting of Lady Bird, the questionable campaign
tactics, the congressional and Senate careers and, finally, triumph
and tragedy in the White House. Why another LBJ book?
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin Unger and Debi Unger, the former a Pulitzer Prize
winner for ``The Greenback Era,'' do have new things to tell _ or,
at least, some additional insights missing from previous Johnson
titles. Although their takes on Lyndon the child and LBJ the
president are mostly rehashings, ``LBJ: A Life'' focuses a lengthy
middle section on Johnson as Senate minority, then majority,
leader. Insights into how Johnson could balance partisan politics
with sensible compromise are fascinating. It would be hard for many
Americans to imagine, but Democrat Johnson and Republican President
Dwight Eisenhower saw themselves as a pragmatic team out to
accomplish everything possible for rank-and-file citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``LBJ: A Life'' is pricey at $30, and for casual LBJ scholars,
Merle Miller's ``Lyndon'' may be a more enjoyable one-volume study.
But if you're a history buff whose book collection houses a shelf
or two of Johnson lore, add this title. It will make a valuable
addition.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor of the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
