<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHICH LIE DID I TELL': TOP HOLLYWOOD SCRIBE TELLS ALL. REALLY.
HONEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the introduction to ``Which Lie Did I Tell?: More Adventures
in the Screen Trade'' William Goldman says that he was inspired to
write the book by a student at Oberlin College. He was visiting his
alma mater and talking to a group of students about Hollywood when
an intense young woman asked him, `` Goldman, Goldman, do you
always begin your second theme by page 17?''
</P>
<P>
   The question stunned him, he writes, ``because, you see, I
didn't know what a second theme  &UR; was &LR; .'' He goes on: ``I literally
did not know what language she was speaking ... But she made me
realize, truly she did, that I would have to write another book
about screenwriting,'' the first having been ``Adventures in the
Screen Trade: A Personal View of Hollywood and Screenwriting''
(1983). ``Because movies are not about second themes or about
dialogue or pretty stars. Because if screenplays are structure, and
they are, then movies are story.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe Goldman's new book really was inspired by the young
woman's question, although that gratuitous ``truly she did'' makes
you wonder. ``Which Lie Did I Tell?'' (which is what a
self-important producer once asked to demonstrate his candor) is
certainly full of practical advice for the aspiring screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   In telling a story, enter it ``as late as possible,'' he keeps
reminding you. Dialogue is nothing, structure is everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great truths of the movie business is that movies
are  &UR; fragile &LR; ,'' he writes. ``And even the most successful are only
a step away from disaster. Every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to protect your writing time,'' he advises. ``The
easiest thing to do on earth is not write.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, Goldman illustrates his advice with compelling
stories about the films he has worked on. For instance, to show the
importance of not overburdening the audience with too many major
characters he tells how he went about streamlining the plot of
David Baldacci's novel ``Absolute Power'' by building up the
character of Luther Whitney, the master thief, played by Clint
Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the risks of overexplaining a character
(``Hollywood heroes must have  &UR; mystery &LR; ,'' he says), he spells out
the damage done when the professional hunter Remington in ``The
Ghost and the Darkness'' acquired a past.
</P>
<P>
   And he uses his experience with the screenplay of Stephen King's
novel ``Misery'' to make a variety of points, from the risks of too
graphic violence (in the novel the writer's feet are cut off; in
the film his ankles are merely broken) to the need of a relatively
unknown actress, as Kathy Bates was at the time the film was made,
to play an unpredictable madwoman like Annie Wilkes.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Goldman sprinkles his text with amusing, somewhat
pointless anecdotes, like the one about his obsession with the
shortness of many movie stars and his stalking of Sylvester
Stallone to learn he is only 5 feet 7. Or the one about a time he
spotted Greta Garbo in Manhattan accompanied by a woman wearing an
eye patch, and he asked the friend he was with, ``Did you see
that?,'' and the friend responded, ``Yes, wow, a lady with an eye
patch.''
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with Goldman's story of being spontaneously
inspired by the young woman's question is how closely ``Which Lie
Did I Tell?'' resembles ``Adventures in the Screen Trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, the new book includes many actual samples
of screenwriting, this time vignettes like the zipper scene from
``There's Something About Mary,'' which Goldman considers flat-out
the best film of 1998; the fake-orgasm scene from ``When Harry Met
Sally''; the morning-sickness scene from ``Fargo,'' among others,
and of course many samples from ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid,'' which Goldman still considers his best piece of work.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Adventures in the Screen Trade,'' this book includes an
original script by the author (it's perfectly dreadful) and
critical comments about it by various colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Like the earlier book, the new one is written in Goldman's
circus-poster language, full of italics and boldface type and
cliches and grotesquely mixed metaphors; it reads as if it had been
dictated, transcribed and only cursorily read over (``Tony Hopkins
came next. For me, along with Morgan Freeman, the two best actors
of the era.'')
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Goldman shows you the difference between being a
screenwriter and a writer, and that while he may be skilled at the
difficult art of visualizing a telling scene, he is uncomfortable
setting down expository prose. Once again, the bundle of
resentments of directors, producers, critics. Once again, about
himself (sometimes referred to as moi) the overweening modesty.
</P>
<P>
   At least the new book is no worse than its predecessor. Film
sequels ``are whores' movies,'' Goldman writes. ``And always will
be. . . . The pulse of what we write  &UR; then &LR;  is always this:
creative. The pulse for a sequel is always this:  &UR; financial &LR; . So
they are never of a similar quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing ``Which Lie Did I Tell?'' isn't a film.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHICH LIE DID I TELL?: MORE ADVENTURES IN THE SCREEN TRADE'
</P>
<P>
   By William Goldman
</P>
<P>
   485 pages. Pantheon. $26.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
