<SLUG> BC-LOWES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lowe's stores adds Alexander Julian home decor designs to
offerings
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lowe's Cos. is adding a trendy flair to its brightly
lit warehouse stores.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer has teamed up with designer Alexander Julian for a
home decor line. By summer, Julian's signature color schemes will
start popping up on wallpaper, paint, window treatments and floor
coverings at Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouses across the country.
In early 2001, Lowe's plans to add Alexander Julian cabinets and
countertops.
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta-based Home Depot and other home improvement
retailers, Lowe's is beefing up home decor to appeal to female
shoppers. Meanwhile, fashion designers have steadily expanded their
reach from consumer closets to the rest of the home.
</P>
<P>
   At Lowe's, Alexander Julian will join Laura Ashley's designer
products in paint, wallcovering and rugs. Beaulieu of America will
make Julian's licensed broadloom carpet, said Lowe's spokeswoman
Melissa Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's main designer labels in its warehouse stores are
Ralph Lauren paint and wallpaper by Raymond Waits and Carey Lind.
Most of the chain's home decor and designer brands are sold at the
Expo Design Center stores.
</P>
<P>
   The new designer line at North Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's
reflects a shift toward fashion and away from categories such as
consumer electronics. The Alexander Julian line is color-designed
to help consumers match a rug with draperies or paint, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to offer a solution-based approach,'' Simmons
said. ``A lot of people experience anxiety or confusion when
they're taking on a decorating project, and this will make it
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's tried a similar program in 1998 with designer Beverly
Murphy Home. The retailer dropped that program after testing it in
about 30 stores, Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
