<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THOMPSON-FILM-2TAKES-     03-08 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A SCREENWRITER TAKES CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Nouvelle Vague may have died quietly in the 1970s,
but its influence over French cinema lived on, above all in the
idea that young directors who aspired to be auteurs should write
their own screenplays. As a result few French cinephiles opted for
careers as screenwriters. Those who did depended on television for
regular work, and when they were hired for movies they received
little praise.
</P>
<P>
   Daniele Thompson was an exception. From an early age she watched
and learned from her father, Gerard Oury, a former actor turned
screenwriter and director of popular comedies. From 1966 she and
her father wrote 10 films that Oury directed. Along the way she was
also a co-writer of Jean-Charles Tachella's 1975 hit ``Cousin,
Cousine'' (for which she received an Oscar nomination) and more
recently of Patrice Chereau's ``Reine Margot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the recognition, something was missing. ``I
considered my work important; I didn't have a chip on my
shoulder,'' she said in an interview, speaking in the fluent
English she picked up in New York while married to an Englishman
for much of the 1960s. ``But as a screenwriter you have no power.
When you see a director making a terrible mistake in casting or
editing, you just have to hope he's right.''
</P>
<P>
   So, at the age of 58 and after more than 30 years in the
business, she decided to write a screenplay for a first-time
director whom she could influence: herself. Her movie, ``La
Buche,'' a gentle comedy about family life, was well received by
French critics and the public here last fall.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Now, with screenings at the Walter Reade Theater in New York at
9:30 p.m. on Saturday and 4:45 p.m. on Sunday, it is one of 16
films in Lincoln Center's ``Rendezvous With French Cinema Today,''
which runs from March 10 through March 19.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``La Buche'' means ``Yule Log'' _ or ``Christmas Cake,'' as
Thompson has provisionally renamed it in the United States, though
she may still opt for a different English title. Either way, it
tells the story of a French family of Russian and Jewish extraction
who are thrown together by the social custom that Christmas be
celebrated as a family. Parents and children who may avoid each
other all year find themselves summoned to share turkey and yule
log. Everyone, it seems, experiences ``hostile depression.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the parents, Stanislas (Claude Rich) and Yvette
(Francoise Fabian), have not spoken since they divorced 25 years
earlier: Stanislas, who played the fiddle in a restaurant
orchestra, never forgave her for running off with a classical
violinist. Their three grown daughters nonetheless decide that
since Yvette is alone after burying her second husband, both she
and Stanislas should be invited to a Christmas Eve dinner given by
Sonia (Emmanuelle Beart).
</P>
<P>
   The three sisters, though, have their own complicated lives.
Louba (Sabine Azema), who sings in a Russian restaurant, is the
eldest and unmarried, although she has a long-running affair with a
married man, Gilbert (Jean-Pierre Darroussin). Sonia, the middle
sister, has everything _ two children, beautiful home, designer
clothes _ but her husband is planning to run off with his mistress.
Milla (Charlotte Gainsbourg) is the rebel: she despises Sonia's
bourgeois lifestyle but her moodiness makes it difficult for her to
find a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   In the countdown to Christmas, the women discover that their
father has allowed a young man, Joseph (Christopher Thompson, the
director's son), to live in a large converted storeroom in the
family house in exchange for doing odd jobs and repairs. Joseph
needs a place to stay after moving to Paris from southern France,
where he has left his wife and small child. But he has other
reasons for enjoying rent-free lodging chez Stanislas.
</P>
<P>
   In developing the family choreography that follows, Thompson has
naturally tapped her long experience of storytelling (and recruited
her son, Christopher, as a collaborator to provide an insight into
his generation). But she also is quick to acknowledge influences,
from Woody Allen and Pedro Almodovar to Chekhov. ``In Chekhov, all
the characters are so weak, so full of faults,'' she said. ``Yet
they evoke such sympathy. You feel such tenderness for their
weaknesses and their struggle to find a reason for happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own family background was also useful, not so much in
imagining the three daughters ( Thompson was an only child and her
parents divorced when she was 18), but in creating the character of
Stanislas. He was inspired by her maternal grandfather, Roman
Jacowlew, who migrated to France from Russia at the age of 14 and
went on to create a tzigane, or Gypsy orchestra, with 14 musicians
and one singer, his French wife. Michel Legrand's lively music for
``La Buche'' is also a homage to Jacowlew.
</P>
<P>
   Jacowlew divorced his wife in the 1930s and survived the German
occupation of France by hiding in another woman's house for five
years. His daughter, Jacqueline, an actress, fled to the unoccupied
south of France with her boyfriend, Oury, whose father was another
Russian immigrant violinist, albeit classical. Daniele was born in
Monaco in 1942, but her father did not formally recognize her for
fear that she would be identified as a Jew. After Germany occupied
southern France in 1943, the family escaped to neutral Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson addressed French attitudes toward Judaism in a 1975
film she wrote with her father, ``The Mad Adventures of Rabbi
Jacob,'' but she said she was not interested in dwelling on that
issue in ``La Buche.'' Almost the only reference is a sarcastic
remark by Stanislas about the anti-Semitism of Sonia's in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to base my story on that,'' she explained. ``The
film is about little secrets. I think lying is very much part of
family life. We lie to our children by hiding the professional,
sentimental and sex problems of the couple. Then, when our children
grow up, they start lying to us. Parents are the last to know a
marriage is in trouble. Families are made up of love and lies. We
often know more about the lives of our close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So how does she like directing, having made a first film that
sold 1.5 million tickets in France and that won a Cesar, the French
equivalent of the Oscar, for Gainsbourg as best supporting actress?
</P>
<P>
   ``The new thing was that I had the power of decision,'' she
said, ``which I had never had before and which is a terrible
responsibility. In the past I would hope the directors were right;
now I hope that I'm right. I want to make another film. But I also
love the simple act of writing, of inventing situations and
dialogues. So I think I'll work on two screenplays, one for myself
and one for someone else, and do both at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   But she has another reason to feel upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're seeing the rehabilitation of the screenwriter,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after decades in which French directors routinely wrote
their own screenplays, Thompson is not the only screenwriter to
show it can be two-way traffic. Francis Veber, for instance, had a
hit in 1998 when he directed his own screenplay of ``The Dinner
Game.'' Agnes Jaoui and Jean-Pierre Bacri, both also actors, have
written several successful films, including ``The Same Old Song,''
directed by Alain Resnais (one of the few French directors who has
always used screenwriters). And last week, Jaoui's first movie as a
director of her own screenplay, ``La Gout des Autres,'' opened here
to excellent reviews and full theaters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
