<HEADLINE>
HIGHTOWER'S COMMENTARY A TOUGH ROW TO HOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If the Gods Had Meant Us to Vote They Would Have Given Us
Candidates'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Jim Hightower &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political essays &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if the presidential primaries aren't painful enough, Jim
Hightower has chosen to inflict upon us ``If the Gods Had Meant Us
to Vote They Would Have Given Us Candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an awfully cute, but prolonged, title for what essentially
is 350 pages of what we already knew.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower is a former Texas agriculture commissioner who fancies
himself a populist commentator. For those new to Hightower, imagine
political commentary from Gomer Pyle sporting a ten-gallon hat on a
head that's a few quarts low.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes off as goofy leftist idealism, a terribly naive,
preachy mess that panders shamelessly to the liberal souls of
America.
</P>
<P>
   His messages: Our leaders are in bed with the big-money boys;
NAFTA and a global economy are bad; and we need to rise up, buck
the system and reclaim America.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this comes from ``America's most popular
populist.'' It says so right there on the dust jacket of his
populist-priced $25 book.
</P>
<P>
   A populist, you recall, is someone who is looking out for the
``little guy'' and the ``working stiffs'' _ the kind of folks who
would be mightily insulted at the notion that they can't look after
themselves just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Look closer, and it is clear that Hightower is no populist. He
is a pro-labor liberal in denial. The worst kind.
</P>
<P>
   So this self-styled populist savior in a $500 Stetson is killing
trees to tell us that our presidential candidates are getting
contributions from ``the big boys on Wall Street''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, to borrow a quote from Jimbo hisownself: ``Golly
Pollyanna!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, now who out there didn't already know that you don't raise
$50 million for a run at the presidency with nickels and dimes from
schoolchildren and widow women? This is the system we have created.
Wall Street didn't do it to us.
</P>
<P>
   As for a global economy, this is a cold, hard reality. American
businesses are majority stockholders in foreign companies, and vice
versa. Hightower sees globilization as a step toward world
domination by the World Trade Organization. But his biggest gripe
is that the beneficiaries are ``the financial elite'' and not the
working stiffs he purports to represent, whether they asked him to
or not.
</P>
<P>
   The kicker is that, here in the midst of a booming economy,
Hightower wants nothing less than a new American Revolution to turn
back the political and economic clock to what he perceives as a
simpler, more honest and isolationist time when we worked the land
and sent Jimmy Stewart to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, this is simple-minded pap. .MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
