<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FULTON-PHOTOS-ART-2TA     03-08 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FULTON-PHOTOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT EDISON FULTON JR.: OH, THE PLACES HE'S BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 5,6,7,8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 23, sitting in a village in Afghanistan drinking salty
tea with a party of desert tribesmen, Robert Edison Fulton Jr.
asked for water. A boy ran into the road to get it, filling a jug
in a muddy puddle, then offered Fulton a cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to drink,'' he said, pausing, ``when a polliwog
swam to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 91, Fulton still looks surprised. A white-haired man with
eyes as blue and clear as a spring, he sat on a recent afternoon at
his desk in his studio in a rehabilitated barn in Newtown, Conn.,
where he lives with his wife, Ann. He was reviewing photographs
that in effect review his life. The desert is there, frozen in
time; Fulton, an inventor, photographer and sculptor, is still as
restless as sand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, as a young architectural student, Fulton set out from
London on a motorcycle and circled the globe, visiting 20 countries
and traveling 40,000 miles, arriving home to his parents' apartment
in New York City on Christmas Eve, 18 months later. He filmed the
trip on a 35-mm camera that looked more like a sextant. He had six
flat tires. He ran out of gas only once, just outside Munich,
Germany. In Greece he passed a man with a rearview mirror bracketed
to his shoulder who was wearing a sign that said, ``Walking Around
the World Backwards!'' Achievement is relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Long Journey Home,'' a selection of stills from the 4,000
feet of film Fulton shot, is being published next month by August
Press. His first exhibition of stills, photographs and sculpture
opens at Exhibit A, at 160 Mercer St in New York, on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice, very complimentary,'' he said, with a modest
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton has taken to thinking his thoughts out loud lately, in
written mottos posted on the beamed walls of his barn. ``Home Is
Not a House,'' a placard behind him read. ``Home Is a Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Home is also the skies. A self-taught pilot, Fulton is the
inventor of Gunairstructor, a World War II fighter pilots' training
device that was a successful precursor of current flight
simulators. He is the father of the Airphibian, a flying car
developed in the 1940s and featured in Life and Time magazines. His
Skyhook aerial rescue system, based on British railway mailbag
pickups, was used by the military, covertly, during the Cold War to
retrieve espionage agents, and as a special effect in the 1965
James Bond film, ``Thunderball.'' It was employed last in the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   The inventor has devoted his time more recently to aerial
photography, flying his P-51 Mustang upside down to get the best
shots, and to his sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton said that he knew of no relation to either Edison or
Fulton but that they had impelled his destiny. ``With a name like
Robert Edison Fulton, you can't be scared about being an
inventor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If life is a puzzle, he has kept most of the pieces, in
cataloged boxes and shelves of numbered albums, and objects like
the polar-bearskin rug, his Uncle Chester's, that he played on as a
child, and his 1937 Stinson airplane, which he is rebuilding, like
an extinct moth, in a hangar down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Some leave home to see the world. Some see the world and make it
their home. Fulton's expedition in 1932, as naive as it was
spectacular, was the first leg of the route that shaped his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would ask me, `Don't you get homesick?''' he recalled
of those encountered everywhere around the world. ``The answer was
yes.'' Of crossing 600 miles of Turkish desert, sleeping on dirt
beneath the stars and being woken by the rustle of caravans
traveling in the cool of the night, he said, ``I came to the
conclusion that, by Jove, this was my home, this world. The whole
of it, regardless of where I was in it. I think that's a helpful
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, after a year of postgraduate study in a Bauhaus program
at the University of Vienna, the young architect, encouraged by his
father to go east instead of west in returning home, set his sights
on the architectural treasures of the Mediterranean, the Middle
East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   He announced his plans at a dinner party in London. ``Oh, I'm
going to ride around the world on a motorcycle,'' he recalled
saying. ``You don't see much architecture through a steamship
porthole.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton stood in his Connecticut workshop recounting the story
next to the machine that took him. ``In those days, motorcyclists
were either policemen or bums,'' he explained. ``I wasn't a
policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   An older man at the party asked a series of questions. Impressed
with his enthusiasm, ``he called my bluff,'' Fulton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that he'd bought the Douglas Motorcycle Co. that
day,'' he said. ``He gave me the motorcycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The motorcycle was refitted with an extra gas tank, a tool box,
a camera case and a steel underplate that protected the crankcase
(and concealed a .32-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver). Fulton
learned to ride it in two days and left town, a suitcase and a
straw sun helmet on a rack between his handlebars. With Greece on
the horizon, he jettisoned his evening clothes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fulton's introduction to the classical kingdom changed his plans
to photograph architecture. Sitting in the shade of the Acropolis,
watching visitors' shadows cast on its columns, ``I became aware of
the fact that architecture was only a reflection of people,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``My camera was smarter than I was,'' he said. ``The further I
went on the trip, the more it kept changing from pictures of
architecture to pictures of people. They moved. They were alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton traveled through Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan, India, China
and Japan, on roads so rutted that the motorcycle stood on its own
when he got off, or roads so erased by dust or rain that he could
site the middle of nowhere easily by where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   In the Taurus mountains in Turkey, a man living in a rock hut
invited him to a game of backgammon, on an olivewood plank with
sticks and stones for pieces, over a meal of pomegranates and
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In China, he watched a man with a goatee as long as a kite tail
having his head shaved by a barber. Over a bowl of food, an
onlooker in the curious crowd that Fulton attracted everywhere
translated the roadside restaurant's menu into English for him.
``Lumps of flesh, boiled in oil, with a sweet and sour taste,'' he
recalled. ``I realized I'd been eating that since London. We're all
basically very much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton said that he was pleased to find that people were
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that in many cases people would greet me with a gun,''
he said. ``But as long as my wavelength was peaceful, I was
invariably treated like clan. They never shot at me _ that I know
of.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, he was hospitalized for jaundice. An Iraqi chieftain
was murdered in the next room by a rival, who had counted the
windows on the outside of the building to find him, and climbed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God the Arabs' math is good,'' Fulton said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did see architecture: from a 4,000-year-old Mesopotamian
temple, gnawed to ruin by the wind at the top and camels at the
base, to the Temple of Borobudur, in Java.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a robe at a writing desk in a Japanese country inn,
Fulton decided to go home, and to be there by Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   He cried when he kicked the stand on the motorcycle and crossed
his parents' Park Avenue lobby.
</P>
<P>
   If there were hardships, Fulton won't speak of them. Of
happiness, he recalled the daily luck of seeing a world about to
change forever with travel and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exploration is routine now,'' he said. ``It wasn't then. Ages
of ways of living and thinking were coming to a dramatic end.''
</P>
<P>
   At 91, it is possible to have been famous and forgotten, several
times over. The young partners, first-time publishers, who are
producing ``The Long Journey Home'' discovered Fulton last spring
through a benefit auction, to which he gave a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   With his adventurous trip, Fulton also proved to be a pioneer of
globalization, ``understanding the world, on a local level,'' he
said. It is not yet a place at peace, but Fulton said he hoped that
new abilities to communicate, like the Internet, would discourage
the suspicions he witnessed, and helped to dispel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was typical of the whole trip,'' he said, his voice sad
with hindsight. ``You would ask about the next village, and people
would say: `Oh, don't go there. Terrible people _ robbers,
thieves.' You would ask: `How do you know? Have you been?' And they
would say, `No, we've heard.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the next village,'' he explained, ``people would ask: `Who
are you? Where have you come from?' When you told them, they would
say, `Oh, terrible people _ robbers, thieves.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had heard,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
