<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TAX-SHELTERS-NYT &LR;      03-08 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SHELTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX EXPERT URGES TOUGHER PENALITIES TO DETER CORPORATE CHEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tough penalties Congress enacted to discourage
abusive corporate tax shelters are so riddled with loopholes that
they fail to deter tax cheating by large companies, Congress' top
tax expert told the Senate Finance Committee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During the first day of hearings on tax shelters and the use of
penalties and interest to discourage sham transactions, Lindy L.
Paull, chief of staff for the Joint Committee on Taxation,
testified that ``there is not a meaningful penalty facing someone
who enters these transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   She called for tightening the penalties and also for imposing
penalties on professionals who prepare abusive tax returns for both
individuals and companies generally at least as high as those
imposed on taxpayers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony came as the proliferating use of sham transactions
by large companies to evade taxes is gaining attention on Capitol
Hill, which over the last five years has focused on tax cuts and
criticism of the IRS. The concern has been stirred not only by
abusive tax shelters but also by complaints by four large American
insurance companies about a legal loophole that lets property and
casualty insurers stop paying income taxes by moving their
headquarters to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who is chairman of the committee,
described corporate tax shelters as a serious problem. He also said
he was worried that new laws sought by the Clinton administration
to crack down on sham transactions would give too much power to IRS
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, whose hearings in 1997 and 1998 on abuses by the
IRS led to a reorganization of that agency, said he expected it
would take a long time for his committee to decide what, if
anything, to do about corporate tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   One witness dismissed the idea that corporate tax shelters were
a problem. Kenneth J. Kies, who was Paull's predecessor as the tax
committee's chief of staff, said research by his employer, the
PricewaterhouseCoopers accounting firm, found no evidence that
corporate tax shelters now were any different from those a decade
or more ago. He said statements by Treasury Secretary Lawrence H.
Summers and other officials that abusive tax shelters were costing
the government billions of dollars a year were ``totally without
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Kies, whose firm is a leading promoter of corporate tax
shelters, including one that the Treasury closed last year after
declaring it a sham, said that a more serious problem was the taxes
owed by individuals and small businesses that the IRS failed to
collect.
</P>
<P>
   Paull and Jonathan Talisman, the acting assistant Treasury
secretary for tax policy, said they were troubled by the legal
loophole that allowed property and casualty insurers to stop paying
income taxes by moving to Bermuda. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of
New York, the ranking Democrat on the committee, mused about
whether ``we are entering an era of corporate expatriation'' with
companies moving their headquarters overseas to avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Paull and Talisman said their staffs were studying the Bermuda
tax shelter but had not yet figured out a way to have it closed
without creating other tax problems.
</P>
<P>
   These two witnesses and Peter L. Faber, a prominent New York
corporate tax lawyer, all described corporate tax shelters as a
serious threat to the income tax system, saying that the government
must halt them or contend with serious long-term revenue loss and a
breakdown of popular support for the income tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Faber said lawyers at his firm, McDermott Will &AMP; Emery in New
York, advised 50 of the top 100 corporations on tax matters and
were continually fielding questions about tax shelters being sold
by investment houses, the Big Five accounting firms and law firms.
</P>
<P>
   He said promoters of tax shelters often sold ``garbage'' to
chief financial officers, who are often not expert in tax matters
and who are increasingly inclined to buy these products over the
objections of company tax directors.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to testimony by Kies that the amount of corporate tax
revenue has been rising, except for last year when it fell 2.1
percent, Faber said: ``It is no answer to say that corporate tax
revenues are up or that they are a high percentage of corporate
profits. Were it not for corporate tax shelters they would be
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Faber and Paull both said they disliked the idea, promoted by
Talisman, of enacting into law the ``doctrine of economic
substance'' in tax matters. The doctrine, created by judges in tax
cases, holds that if a transaction has no purpose except to avoid
taxes it lacks economic substance and can be disregarded for tax
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should tread cautiously'' in defining tax shelters by
statute, Faber said, adding that ``some aspects of the problem are
better dealt with by regulations and judicial doctrines than by
legislation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
