<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 2 AGENCIES REORGANIZE, 3 ENTER DEALS AND 2 ALIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a spate of deals this week involving agencies and
companies that work with them, ranging from reorganizations to
acquisitions to affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson Partners in New York, an executive recruiter and
management consultant that specializes in advertising,
communications and marketing, is reorganizing to improve efforts to
find managers able to meet the challenges of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson is reconfiguring by naming leaders for two new
divisions. Norman M. Sherman, 51, a longtime agency and media
executive, becomes president for North America, overseeing
operations of offices in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., and New York.
Sherman has held senior posts at D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles,
part of the MacManus Group unit of BDM Inc., and was most recently
managing director at the Senior Network in Stamford, Conn., a
marketing services company focused on consumers age 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Peter J. Fitzpatrick, 41, becomes president for the
international division at Gunderson, after serving most recently as
human resources director for the international operations of the
American International Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our searches now are global, for people with global
expertise,'' said Steven G. Gunderson, chief executive at
Gunderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our traditional clients continue to grow,'' he added, ``and
the new players, the dot-coms, are looking for the same kind of
talent.'' Fitzpatrick noted that Gunderson had ``recently moved
executives from Singapore to New York, Taipei to North Carolina,
Chicago to Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   In another revamping, the FCB Worldwide unit of True North
Communications is combining its four offices in Southern California
to form a single agency with 300 employees and total billings of
$450 million from clients like Hilton, Mattel and Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harrington, 38, who had been executive vice president and
general manager at the FCB office in Costa Mesa, becomes president
at FCB Southern California, working with Scott Montgomery, 50, who
becomes executive vice president and executive creative director
after handling those duties for FCB Costa Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Also at FCB Southern California, Thom Miller, 51, who had been
executive vice president and general manager at FCB Los Angeles,
will be executive vice president and general manager, and Howard
Casavant, 47, who had been senior vice president and senior group
creative director at FCB Los Angeles, will be executive vice
president and senior group creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Thom McElroy, 38, who had been president and chief creative
officer at FCB McElroy in Newport Beach, will be president of that
operation as it becomes part of FCB Southern California. And Bob
Gale, 42, who had been senior vice president and group account
director for the FCB Field Service Network in Santa Ana, handling
Taco Bell, will retain those duties as the network becomes part of
FCB Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   FCB Southern California is seeking space in Orange County to
bring together the staff members who had worked at FCB Costa Mesa,
FCB Santa Ana and FCB McElroy. Employees at FCB Los Angeles will
move to the El Segundo area, where Mattel is based.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to acquisitions, Publicis SA in Paris bought DeWitt
Media in New York, a media services agency with 80 employees who
handle accounts with estimated billings of $400 million for clients
like Bacardi, BMW, Land Rover and the National Basketball
Association. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Gene DeWitt, 57, president and chief executive at DeWitt, will
become chairman and chief executive of a new U.S. division of
Optimedia International, the Publicis worldwide media planning and
buying network; the division will handle media duties for accounts
with estimated billings of $1.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second American acquisition by Publicis in a month,
coming after the purchase of Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis.
Publicis and a rival French agency company, Havas Advertising,
which last month acquired Snyder Communications in Bethesda, Md.,
are aggressively stepping up acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Hawkeye Communications in New York, an agency
that is forming a network of companies through a series of
acquisitions, is making another one. Hawkeye, started last year by
G. Steven Dapper, former chairman and chief executive of the Rapp
Collins Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group, acquired the Ffwd
Group in London and Haddenham, England, for undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Ffwd, which stands for ``Fast forward,'' according to Dapper,
has three divisions specializing in database marketing and services
for e-businesses. It is the first Hawkeye acquisition outside the
United States. Colin Glossop, 41, chief executive at Ffwd, will
continue in that capacity as well as help Hawkeye expand further in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In another acquisition, Omnicom, based in New York, acquired
majority ownership of Millsport LLC in Stamford, Conn., a sports
marketing agency. Omnicom, which has owned 25 percent of Millsport
since 1996, acquired an additional 35 percent for undisclosed
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Millsport has 60 employees and clients like GTE and Visa.
Michael Birkin, 41, president at the Diversified Agency Services
division of Omnicom, joins the Millsport board.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dentsu U.S.A. in New York, part of the Japanese giant
Dentsu Inc., formed a nonequity alliance with Oasis Advertising in
New York. The affiliation offers worldwide resources like research
to Oasis, which has 31 employees and billings estimated at $35
million from clients like Alitalia and Toyota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
