<SLUG> BC-BEERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta construction company acquires Las Vegas operation
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beers Construction hopes to win big in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta construction company with offices downtown has
acquired W.E. O'Neil Construction Co. of Nevada and taken control
of its projects, office and employees. The new Las Vegas office is
the first that Beers completely owns outside the Southeast. Last
year, a joint venture involving Beers opened an office in Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view it as an opportunity in terms of people in the office
and the work,'' said C. Roland Vaughn III, chief marketing officer
at Beers. ``There's nothing that says we have to stay in the
South.''
</P>
<P>
   A subsidiary of Skanska USA, Beers is one of the most-known
contractors in Atlanta, where its blue signs are found across the
metro area. The company built landmarks such as 191 Peachtree
Tower, Bank of America Plaza, Four Seasons, Swissotel, the Georgia
Dome and Philips Arena. It also will build the new TrizecHahn
Office Properties' 20-story office tower and a $350 million
retractable-roof football stadium in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Beers acquired the Nevada division from O'Neil Industries of
Chicago, a 75-year-old firm that owns construction companies in
Chicago; Los Angeles; Golden, Colo.; Addison, Texas; Phoenix; and
Tucson, Ariz. Vaughn declined to disclose how much Beers paid for
the Las Vegas operation.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition gives Beers instant expertise in building huge
hotels with casinos and more than 1,000 rooms. Vaughn said the
company can now compete for major hospitality projects.
</P>
<P>
   With the purchase, Beers inherits the $15 million renovation
project of the 5,034-room and suites MGM Grand Hotel and Suites in
Las Vegas. The renovation, expected to be completed in late summer,
will give the rooms an art-deco look, MGM Grand spokeswoman Shelley
Mansholt said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
