<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-FALLOUT-750&AMP;add-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `SUPER TUESDAY' SHAKEDOWN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This 800-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 750 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 975.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``p'' political news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By BRIAN KNOWLTON  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a dramatic sweep of Democratic primaries by
Vice President Al Gore and a series of one-sided victories by
Governor George W. Bush in the biggest Republican primaries, the
two candidates lost no time Wednesday in turning their attention
toward the general election in November, laying out the outlines of
their electoral platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Their chief rivals for the parties' presidential nominations,
meanwhile, were reported to be close to dropping out of the race.
Former Senator Bill Bradley lost to Gore in every Democratic
contest on Tuesday, even in his native Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain of Arizona had more to show from the
coast-to-coast Republican contests.
</P>
<P>
   He defeated Bush in the New England states of Vermont,
Connecticut, Rhode Island and Massachusetts. But his aides had
counted on victory in New York or Ohio, the biggest contests
Tuesday after California, to revive his flagging fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush won by close to 20 percentage points in California
and Ohio, and McCain could not come closer than 8 points in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain adviser called that a ``devastating'' showing, and
another aide said the senator would meet with friends and advisers
at his Arizona ranch to ``take stock of our losses.''
</P>
<P>
   His withdrawal appeared likely ahead of primaries Tuesday in the
South, where Bush is heavily favored.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reached out to McCain on Wednesday in an effort to heal the
breach opened by an often-bitter contest. ``He waged a good
campaign,'' Bush said from his home in Austin. ``He's a tough
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The third Republican candidate, Alan Keyes, failed to score in
double digits anywhere but Minnesota, often a maverick-minded
state. There, he won 20 percent of the vote, beating McCain for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   The compressed primary season thus effectively ended with the
expected candidates on top, but Bush suffered damage after a
surprisingly tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   The rough-edged Republican campaign looked likely to spill over
into the battle ahead, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a spirited contest,'' Bush said. ``I'm
looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor mocked Gore for saying Tuesday that he was
ready to attack the problem of unregulated ``soft money'' political
contributions. ``The first thing he needs to do is debate Bill
Clinton on soft money,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While calling for a loftier, issue-centered, campaign, each
candidate took hard swipes at the other.
</P>
<P>
   Gore challenged Bush ``to hold joint open meetings with me to
make this a contest of ideas, not insults,'' implicitly criticizing
the way the Republican contest had played out.
</P>
<P>
   He called for ``a campaign conducted in full daylight, and not
through secretly funded, special-interest attack ads, or smear
telephone calls from the extremist right wing.'' His references
were to Bush backers from the religious right whose support was
bitterly assailed by McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of his vulnerability for the aggressive fund-raising
tactics employed in 1996, when Gore took part _ unwittingly, he has
said _ in an illegal fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in Los
Angeles, the vice president sought to defuse the issue by saying
that he had ``learned from his mistakes'' and would fix ``a broken
system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush kept his fire turned on Gore. ``I will remind Al Gore
that Americans do not want a White House where there is no
``controlling legal authority,''' he said, mocking the legalistic
phrase Gore used to defend his fund-raising role in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In ``eight years of partisanship, gridlock and division,'' Bush
contended, the Democratic administration had done little to improve
schools, had weakened the nation's military capabilities and had
dallied as the Social Security retirement program faced a threat of
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very tough, no-holds-barred campaign,''
predicted Allan Lichtman, a history professor at American
University in Washington, ``because both Bush and Gore have shown
they'll do whatever it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lichtman predicted that with both sides seeking to lure McCain
supporters, each candidate would try to claim the mantle of the
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would position himself as a conservative reformer, ``the
guy who can fix Social Security, boost education, give some tax
relief,'' while Gore would present himself as a liberal reformer,
who would ``embrace campaign-finance reform, extend health-care
coverage and improve education,'' Lichtman said.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate again touched on those themes Wednesday. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 750, OR CONTINUE TO 975) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Opinion polls indicate that Bush and Gore will begin their push
to the election in November at rough parity. Lichtman said that at
the moment Gore, as the head of ``a united party at a time of peace
and prosperity,'' had a slight lead.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some reversal of expected roles after the often
harsh Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began a year ago with Bush the presumptive nominee of a
united party, with a great advantage in resources and a perception
of someone who was a very strong candidate able to make centrist
appeals'' while retaining the support of core Republicans, said
Thomas Mann, director of governmental studies at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was seen as an uncomfortable candidate, being forced
leftward by a strong challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mann said, ``Bush has been driven to the right, the
aura of invincibility has dissipated, there are questions about
just how ready he is for national prime time, he's got divisions in
his party and he's taken positions that limit his appeal among
independents and weak Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary season is far from over, but the Bush and Gore
victories place the two candidates in virtually unstoppable
positions. Colorado, Utah and Wyoming hold primaries Friday, and
Florida, Texas and four other Southern states vote Tuesday. Bush is
strong in both regions. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
