<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SMOLTZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz to undergo ligament-repair surgery; out for season
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ After five years of fighting his right elbow,
John Smoltz finally lost.
</P>
<P>
   Two arthroscopic surgeries, four stints on the disabled list, a
new arm angle and the addition of a knuckleball _ none of it could
prevent a tired ligament from tearing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Cy Young award winner is headed for
ligament-repair surgery, announced Wednesday. The Braves were left
wondering what it will be like to go through an entire season
without a member of the pitching triumvirate that has made them a
perennial World Series contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a chance I won't pitch again, but there's also
a great chance I'll pitch again and pitch well and have fun,''
Smoltz said. ``I haven't had a whole lot of fun lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz will be paid $7.75 million this year, with insurance
covering almost all of it for the Braves, and the club has an
option for next season at $8 million. Smoltz's past elbow problems
forced him to consider retirement before the season, but his
decision for surgery apparently signals that he's not ready to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz pitched two innings Sunday in his first outing of the
spring. Almost half of his pitches were knuckleballs. It was
evidence that his elbow was about to betray him, but not nearly as
telling as the pain he endured for five hours afterward. Smoltz
said he never felt a specific pop, but by that night he had a
pretty good idea what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Another trip through an MRI
</P>
<P>
   tube on Wednesday confirmed his fears. Dr. James Andrews will
rebuild his medial collateral ligament on March 23 in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Smoltz was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just look at it now like I've got three or four more good
years, rather than dealing with not knowing,'' Smoltz said. ``It's
definitely not the news a pitcher wants to hear, but at the same
time I am positive for the future, more so now than I was. I've
dealt with a lot, so I feel I can deal with this. I've seen already
guys from our team pitch after it. I'm just being as positive as I
can. And I'm getting a straightjacket fitted for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz won 145 games for the Braves in the 1990s, plus 12 more
in the playoffs and World Series. Together with Greg Maddux and Tom
Glavine, he gave the team the most reliable starting staff in
baseball for much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace somebody of his caliber,'' general manager
John Schuerholz said. ``What we're going to have to do, I told
Tommy (Glavine) and Mad Dog (Maddux) this morning, we'll have to
circle the wagons real tight.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate plans for filling his spot in the rotation involve
moving Kevin Millwood there. Terry Mulholland and Bruce Chen,
expected to battle for the fifth starting spot, may both make the
rotation. Steve Avery will be considered, although he is not fully
recovered from shoulder surgery in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll evaluate who we have here, how comfortable we feel with
how we make things work in John's absence and decide whether we
need to look outside the organization,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz has pitched 2,414 1/3 innings in his 12-year career,
third among Braves pitchers since the franchise moved to Atlanta,
behind Phil Niekro (4,533) and Glavine (2,660 2/3). He has pitched
another 181 2/3 innings in the posteason, and his 12 postseason
wins are the most by any pitcher in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The last Braves fans saw of him was in October, airing it out in
Game 4 of the World Series in Yankee Stadium. After three months of
throwing side-armed to thwart the pain, Smoltz had returned to his
over-the-top motion. ``John's one of the great pitchers who's ever
pitched in this game, one of the biggest big-game pitchers to ever
play,'' Chipper Jones said. ``It's a tremendous loss for us, but we
dealt with it before. We're going to have to deal with it again.
Somebody's going to have to step up. Somebody's going to have to
pitch well. We're going to have to score more runs, whatever it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz will join Kerry Ligtenberg and Odalis Perez as Braves
pitchers who have had the surgery in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   By this time last year, Andres Galarraga was already lost for
the season becausae of lymphoma in his back, and Ligtenberg was a
day away from blowing out his elbow in a spring-training game.
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot for Smoltz is that Ligtenberg pitched well
Tuesday in his first game back. He already has sought Ligtenberg's
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him if he wanted to be ready for next year he needs to
do it as quick as he can,'' said Ligtenberg, who regrets waiting a
month to have his surgery April 6 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The team takes another big blow inside the clubhouse where
Smoltz, a devout Christian and a fun-loving competitor in anything
from Ping-Pong to bowling, is one of the most thoughtful and
well-liked players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll miss him, but he's promised me he'll be around the
ballpark a lot, because he is a huge influence on our team,'' Bobby
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe his reaction to the news, Maddux said:
``Mourning for the Atlanta Braves.'' He paused and then said, ``And
the road golf schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to his scratch golfing partner with the best
connections at courses around the country. ``When you pitch in
pain, the game's not fun,'' Maddux said. ``I'm actually glad he's
getting it done. He's going to get a year off, a mulligan, and come
back stronger than he was before. I'm happy for him. I don't think
he's enjoyed the last couple years like the rest of us have,
because of his elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see SMOLTZ, E2
</P>
<P>
   refer to Bisher E2
</P>
<P>
   refer to notebook E3
</P>
<P>
   HEADER
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves pitcher John Smoltz will miss the 2000 season. An
MRI revealed a torn ligament in his right elbow. Smoltz, who had
elbow surgery in September 1994 and in December 1997, will be on
the disabled list for the fifth time since the beginning of the
1998 season:
</P>
<P>
   YearDays on disabled list
</P>
<P>
   1998March 29-15
</P>
<P>
   1998May 24-June 20
</P>
<P>
   1999May 17-June 1
</P>
<P>
   1999July 5-24
</P>
