<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC title door wide openBy Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officially, it is the Southeastern Conference Men's Basketball
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the 41st edition should sound like a stop on the PGA
Tour. Say, the Roy Kramer SEC Quad-Champs Open. With the emphasis
on ``Open,'' Kentucky tradition and recent tourney history
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day affair that returns today to the Georgia Dome could
be the most competitive in SEC tournament history. And maybe the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best league in the country this year,'' Florida's
Billy Donovan said. ``Maybe the best ever in SEC history. If you
can (advance) in this tournament, it speaks volumes about your
program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's anybody's tournament,'' Kentucky's Tubby Smith said.
Smith's 'Cats have won seven of the last eight SEC tourneys, the
last two commandingly under Smith in the Dome, in the city
Kentucky's come to call ``Catlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was good,'' Georgia's Jim Harrick said about to his
SEC baptism, ``but I don't think there's anything like what's going
on in this league. I legitimately think we have a chance to have
three teams go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the senior coach, 11 years in this league, and it's the
best I've ever seen,'' South Carolina's Eddie Fogler said. ``I'm
not going to say who's the best team. We've got four teams that can
say that _ quad-champs. No one else in the country can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not now, not ever. When Kentucky thoroughly beat Florida 85-70
Saturday, it not only gave UK a share of its 40th SEC
regular-season title. It also left Kentucky, Florida, Tennessee and
LSU each 12-4 in the SEC, the first four-way tie for a major
conference title. In 1995 in the Atlantic Coast Conference, Wake
Forest, North Carolina, Maryland and Virginia all finished 12-4,
but the ACC crowns its tournament winner as its conference champion
and does not recognize a regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got four teams up there at 12-4,'' Tennessee coach
Jerry Green said, ``and everybody that's been at the top has been
thumped at some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
