</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defending champions have problems
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody takes shots at the king, probing for cracks in the
armor, perceiving weakness even when none exists.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs, the defending NBA champions appear to
have a number of weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were the story of the year when they won the NBA title
last June. They captured the attention of the nation after starting
forward Sean Elliott had successful kidney transplant surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But problems have tarnished the Spurs' image, and, although they
appear ready to challenge for another title, they are a longshot to
repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers, Portland and Utah are ahead of the Spurs
in the Western Conference, with the Lakers and Blazers the class of
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Most of San Antonio's problems appear to be internal _ lack of
perimeter offense, the distraction of Tim Duncan's impending
free-agency and lack of domination by David Robinson. Now,
dissension surrounds point guard Avery Johnson. Once known as an
effervescent, over-achiever who fooled everyone by pushing himself
out of the minor leagues, Johnson came back to the Spurs twice
after they waived him and evolved into a key player on a title
team.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, ex-teammate Chucky Brown called him a ``snake in the
grass.'' Brown, now with Charlotte, who got his release from the
Spurs on Feb. 4, said Johnson who ruined his stay in San Antonio.
He suggested that Johnson was instrumental in the team's decision
to limit Brown's role and ultimately send him, uninjured, to the
injured list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to always make suggestions to (coach and general
manager Greg Popovich), so it's possible,'' Brown said after asking
for his release. ``I don't see him on any All-Star teams. ... But
you know, he's a man of God. God will deal with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last summer, owner Peter Holt told Johnson he was such a
long-serving and vital member of the organization that it was time
for him to move his entire family to San Antonio and make it his
permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   But near the trading deadline, Popovich tried to trade Johnson
to Charlotte for David Wesley or to the Clippers for Derek
Anderson. Johnson said he felt betrayed because he had always
supported Popovich. Johnson had complained about being benched in
crunch time in favor of Terry Porter, now injured. Then several
Spurs leaked the news that post-game grousing resulted in a brawl
after a game in Cleveland, with Johnson fighting backup forward
Malik Rose on the locker-room floor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Johnson must defend his honor as well as his game.
``When I was a below-average NBA player, nobody talked much about
me,'' Johnson says. ``But now, as you move up the ladder a little
bit, when you hit the game-winning shot (in the Finals), it's all
right to celebrate. But what about when people start putting you
under the microscope? And when one thing goes wrong, it's all blown
out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Duncan, Johnson will be a free agent. He is seeking a
three-year contract for $24 million. The Spurs are believed to be
offering one year at $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's one more problem than a defending champion needs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
