</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BILLELLIOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trio unlikely NASCAR owners
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Three Georgia businessmen are the most unlikely car
owners in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   MB2 Motorsports, which owns the No. 36 Pontiac driven by Kenny
Schrader, is owned by people whose resumes give little indication
of an inclination toward stock-car racing.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beard is an investment banker who used to work in the White
House. Read Morton is a lawyer who spent 16 years practicing law
with Billy Payne, and Nelson Bowers is a former football star
turned car dealer who says he knows nothing about the internal
workings of an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   Many Winston Cup car owners formed their teams after either
driving race cars or working on them. The road that the MB2 owners
took to Winston Cup ownership was paved with contacts made through
the National Symphony Orchestra, the 1996 Olympics and the Georgia
Bulldogs, among others.
</P>
<P>
   None had more than a passing interest in stock-car racing before
starting the No. 36 team four years ago. Their main sporting
passion was watching football games at their alma mater, the
University of Georgia. All three attended UGA during the mid-1960s,
but they didn't know each other until after they graduated. ``I was
on the board of trustees of the National Symphony Orchestra (in New
York), which is a pretty strange way to get into NASCAR racing,''
Beard said. He is an investment banker who grew up in Moultrie and
once worked as a deputy assistant to then-President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   While on the Orchestra board, Beard met a member of the Mars
family, which owns the Mars Candy Co. Mars has been involved in
NASCAR racing on and off for years.
</P>
<P>
   Through his investment banking, Beard knew Nelson Bowers, a high
school football star from Rossville who played linebacker for
Georgia until a fractured vertebra ended his football career.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers knew Rick Hendrick, a fellow car dealer who also owns
three Winston Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   Morton, Payne's former law partner, had done legal work for
Bowers and also knew Beard. Mars, which once had its Snickers brand
advertised on the No. 8 car in Winston Cup, was interested in
getting back into racing.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the three Georgians, Mars worked out a deal for
partial sponsorship of two of Hendricks' cars, but the candy
company also wanted a car of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks suggested that Morton, Beard and Bowers start their
own team for the 1997 NASCAR season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'If you guys are interested, I'll help you all I
can,' `` Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say we're like a fourth Hendrick team, but
that's just not true,'' Beard said. ``Rick's a great guy, but we're
our own team.''
</P>
<P>
   MB2 Motorsports' first move was to hire a general manager, Jay
Frye, and leave the racing to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're adjusting the spoiler, we don't tell them what to
do, and none of them ask our opinion,'' Beard said. Derrike Cope
was hired to drive the car for 1997, and Ryan Pemberton came on as
crew chief. ``Derrike was exactly what we needed _ somebody to put
us on the map,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   After Cope recorded two top-10 finishes _ one in the top five _
and finished 27th in points, the owners decided to take a bold step
for the 1998 season. They hired Ernie Irvan, who had 15 career
victories, to drive their car. But racing injuries, one of which
almost cost Irvan his life in 1994, came back to haunt Irvan and
MB2.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ernie got hurt the first time, we were on the verge of
doing something extremely, extremely good,'' Bowers said. ``We felt
like we were definitely players.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan missed the final three races of 1998 after a crash at
Talladega. He returned in 1999 but suffered a career-ending head
injury in a crash at Michigan. The team finshed the season with
Dick Trickle or Jerry Nadeau at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader has brought renewed optimism to the team, the owners
say. ``He provides stability, and that's what we need,'' Beard
said.
</P>
<P>
   A casual conversation with Frye led Schrader to leave Andy
Petree's team and drive the No. 36. ``I thought about it a little
bit and said, 'Hey, were you serious?' It all happened really
quick,'' Schrader said. ``They've never won, and I haven't won
since '91, but we feel like we've got everything it takes to win,
and we're going to set a goal of winning every time we go out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   All three owners say they expect to win soon, but they also
realize that racing is a tough business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not win the Winston Cup this year, but we want to do
well,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   The business-like approach to their race team, which has an
annual budget of just under $ 8 millon, has earned the three owners
the respect of NASCAR's insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, the sanctioning body's chief operating officer,
said Morton, Beard and Bowers are, ``a good addition to the NASCAR
family.'' Helson said. ``They want to be competitive, but they are
patient and are going about it in a methodical way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Clark, president of Atlanta Motor Speedway, said he is
particularly pleased to have a second team of Georgians _ along
with Dawsonville's Bill Elliott _ in Winston Cup in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta used to be the hub of racing, but now we're just
hanging on,'' Clark said. ``Winston Cup racing is a lot more
complicated than I ever dreamed it was,'' Morton said. ``And people
don't realize how much of a team sport it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It also can be exciting, Beard said. ``I sometimes find my hands
clenched during the races,'' he said. ``I have to get the fingers
on one hand to straighten the fingers on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
