<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International soccer notebook
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is not retiring, nor is he merely fading away. Lothar
Matthaus played his last game for Bayern Munich on Wednesday in a
4-1 win over Real Madrid to advance to the quarterfinals of the
European Champions League. But the score was hardly the story.
</P>
<P>
   Matthaus, 39, the most capped international male player ever,
will report to Major League Soccer's MetroStars later this week.
But the gritty left back bade an emotional farewell to club
football in his homeland and was the center of attention
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   After being named the German player of the year last year,
Matthaus said he wanted to close out his club career much like
another German legend and will follow Franz Beckenbauer to New
York. The MetroStars are hardly the Cosmos, the North American
Soccer League's lasting claim to fame. But for MLS, which begins
its fifth season later this month, an aging player apparently with
plenty of soccer left in him figures to be an asset.
</P>
<P>
   There were haggles between Bayern and MLS over his transfer, and
plenty of petulance from Matthaus, who has a reputation for being
difficult. But an Olympiastadion capacity crowd chanted and sang
his name all throughout the match, and Matthaus could barely fight
back tears when he was substituted in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Champions League: Barca, United advance
</P>
<P>
   Abelardo and Rivaldo scored as Barcelona qualified for the
quarterfinals in a 2-0 whitewash of Porto on Tuesday. The other
spot from Group A is up for grabs after Sparta Prague's 1-0 win
over Hertha Berlin, with Milan Fukal scoring in the 90th minute....
Manchester United moved into the lead in Group B and clinched a
quarterfinal spot with a 2-1 win over Bordeaux, coupled with
Valencia's 2-0 win over Fiorentina.
</P>
<P>
   England: Murdoch eyes Chelsea
</P>
<P>
   British Sky Broadcasting, the satellite company that holds live
Premier League television rights, has purchased a 9.9 percent stake
in Chelsea, making it the fifth English club to come into the
Rupert Murdoch empire. BSkyB, whose contract is up next year, also
owns a similar percentage of Manchester United, Manchester City,
Leeds United and Sunderland. Firms that want more than 10 percent
of a club have to go through British antitrust channels, a pitfall
that sank Murdoch's bid last year for a majority stake in
Manchester United. The moves are seen as a bid to capitalize on the
likelihood that teams soon will be able to sell their own TV
rights.... Manchester United on Wednesday became the first soccer
club in the world to be valued at more than one billion pounds
sterling ($1.6 billion U.S.) on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Inter tops Milan rival
</P>
<P>
   How many teams would love to have Ivan Zamorano, Chile's World
Cup striker, in reserve for a big derby match? Zamorano got things
rolling for Inter Milan with a 43rd-minute goal, and Luigi DiBiagio
struck in the second half in a 2-1 win over AC Milan. Inter, which
moves into third place in Serie A, is without the injured Christian
Vieri and Ronaldo. Also getting credit for Inter's strong run is
Uruguayan attacking midfielder Alvaro Recoba, who has scored 10
goals in 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Keller out for a month
</P>
<P>
   Kasey Keller, Rayo Vallecano's American goalkeeper, will be out
close to a month after dislocating his collarbone Sunday in the
club's 1-0 loss to Alaves. The Basque club, promoted this season,
surprisingly is in second place in the Primera Division....
Barcelona striker Luis Enrique could be out for three months with a
knee injury, probably ruling him out for Spain in the European
championships this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Tigres face replays
</P>
<P>
   The hot start by UNL Tigres in the Torneo Verano has come with a
price. The club has been told it must replay three matches because
of improper actions regarding the transfer of Donizete, a striker
who came from Vasco da Gama of Brazil. Tigres defeated Atlante,
Toluca and Monterrey, but those matches must be contested again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
