<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-08 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GETTING OVER IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the jailed D.C. Mayor Marion Barry came
roaring back to win re-election a few years ago, he delivered a
classic message to those he trounced: ``Get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how moderate Republicans, independents and dissident
Democrats can get over this week's decisive defeat of John McCain
by George W. Bush. Resist the temptation to blame McCain as
messenger for the GOP rank-and-file's rejection of his campaign
reform message. Tactical errors under stress had little to do with
McCain's defeat in New York, Ohio and California. Instead, face the
half-dozen lessons of politics 2000:
</P>
<P>
   1.  &UR; Pat Robertson rules. &LR;  The religious right, combined with GOP
organization leaders, determines the selection of Republican
candidates in most non-Eastern states. Barring a disastrous loss
this November, no insurgent is likely to win nomination without
that combination.
</P>
<P>
   2.  &UR; The supposedly outmoded strategy of swinging rightward for
the nomination and then to the center for the election is still
in-moded. &LR;  No Republican is likely to carry New York state without
doing well in Manhattan's moderate ``Silk Stocking'' district,
which McCain carried easily and which Bush needs.
</P>
<P>
   3. News for nattering nabobs:  &UR; Never knock negativism. &LR;  It still
works; attack ads accusing McCain of hypocrisy took their toll. But
not always: the New York Bush campaign's ``daisy spot'' _ charging
McCain with being insufficiently opposed to breast cancer _ hurt
Bush on Long Island, where Republican women did not take kindly to
the politicization of disease.
</P>
<P>
   4.  &UR; Jack Dempsey lives: The best defense is still a good
offense. &LR;  Savants despise complaining as ``off message'' or
whining. However, to escalate the complainant's counterattack and
then to attack that exaggeration (``He called me a bigot!'') works
as offensive defense.
</P>
<P>
   5.  &UR; Soft money talks. &LR;  Although the billionaire Wyly brothers
never slept in the Texas governor's mansion, their $2.3 million in
``independent'' final-weekend spots slamming McCain reached target
voters. Publicity about the secret source of soft money generated
no countervailing voter reaction, proving that _
</P>
<P>
   6.  &UR; Outrage is out. &LR;  Conventional wisdom about a majority's
unconcern about campaign finance reform was right. (Lobbyists may
take to wearing gold-plated iron triangles in their lapels.)
Democrats profess support for a soft-money ban as expiation for
unpunished Clinton-Gore sins of 1996, but would abandon it if they
took control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Do these six lessons of hardball mean that all those opposed to
forking over for favors _ the well-whipped, starry-eyed goo-goos of
the McCain Minority _ should fold their tents and silently steal
away?
</P>
<P>
   No. These centrist losers have become kingmakers. Practical pols
know that as the Mc.M. goes, so goes the presidential election.
Therefore, after one day of pouting and sulking and what-iffing,
McCain's crusaders should be looking to the movement's leader to be
power broker for a good chunk of campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, guilt-ridden about '96 fund-raising, promises everything
McCain wants. Bush, to augment his depleted war chest, promises
nothing, but invites McCain to ``team up.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes two to team up. One of McCain's fuzzier desires is a
pledge from Bush to run a clean campaign. I'd forget that; when
Bush gets the expected knee to the groin, he will respond with a
gouge to the eye. The most Bush can promise is to promptly
repudiate sleazy tactics by mud-slinging supporters.
</P>
<P>
   However, the senator _ with his loose network of followers, his
sizable bloc of delegates and with Gore's offer in his pocket _
should have more than a little leverage at this summer's GOP
convention. He should use it to extract specific compromises from
Bush on finance reform in the party platform _ some parts before
the election, more afterward if victorious.
</P>
<P>
   In the speeches nominating McCain in Philadelphia, and in his
own prime-time address to the delegates and the nation, a clear
message about breaking the iron triangle should be driven home.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is prepared to alienate his religious right by making a
substantive move to the reformist center, McCain should ``team up''
with enthusiasm. If Bush demands blind loyalty, McCain should pat
him on the back, loyally wish him well, and say, with Milton,
``They also serve who only stand and wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
