<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BRIDGET-JONES09-COX     03-08 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGET-JONES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dear Diary: The roof fell in and I'm in Atlanta. Does Bridget
Jones have days like this?
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She may be one of the few women in the world to dash
expectations by not turning out to be utterly helpless, chronically
inebriated and a bit daft.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, when British author Helen Fielding arrives nearly 10
minutes late for an interview, the explanation is rather mundane _
a phone call to deal with roof problems at her recently purchased
Los Angeles house _ but the delivery definitely is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit that when I walked in and saw it collapsed, my
instant reaction was to realize it was quite funny,'' Fielding said
Wednesday with a grin in the staid dining room of Midtown Atlanta's
Four Seasons Hotel, almost as if she were confessing to having a
dirty thought. ``I mean, here I thought I was very glamorous moving
to L.A., and I'm spending all my time with the roofing contractors
and wearing mackintoshes and mopping, mopping!''
</P>
<P>
   That is, in between counting her millions, turning her book into
a movie, and almost single-handedly empowering an entire generation
of young (and not-so-young) single women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones's Diary,'' which first hit U.S. stores in 1998,
has sold 4 million copies, the bulk of them to young women who
delighted in Fielding's comic take on her 30-something heroine's
mundane concerns, from doing as little as possible at work or with
her parents, to finding men and pantyhose that wouldn't run at the
first snag.
</P>
<P>
   For many women, it seems, ``Bridget's'' printed pages were more
akin to a looking glass or a precise readout of their private
thought patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because there's too much shoved at us, too many
images of perfection,'' said Fielding, who was in town to sign
copies of her just-released sequel, ``Bridget Jones: The Edge of
Reason,'' at the Chapter 11 bookstore at Peachtree Battle. ``You
don't read much in magazines about real human beings, about
kindness or wittiness or optimism, especially as it occurs in young
women. And so it comes to seem as if all you should be is
successful and beautiful and thin.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news _ or bad, depending on one's opinion of the first
book _ is that the sequel picks up a mere six weeks later. That
means Bridget is basically unchanged from the ``Rain Man''-esque
recorder of calories consumed, cigarettes smoked and anonymous
hang-up calls to ex-boyfriends who muddled her way through
``Diary'' _ although now, along with the omnipresent bottle of
Chardonnay, she also has such an addiction to relationship
self-help books she worries they may be sabotaging her chances of
having a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, it also means more of the same hostile reaction from
a significant faction who disliked ``Diary,'' particularly in the
United States. At its most benign, the criticism leveled by some
readers, journalists and social observers was that the Jones girl
was wearingly whiny and unwilling to change _ the sort of
all-too-familiar character many real-life women ditch as soon as
their parents _ or their college _ stop making them share a room.
Too much of the same old Bridget is the common theme of many of the
less glowing reviews to greet the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who like her, it's because she's like your
friend,'' said Fielding, adding that it would have been
intellectually dishonest to significantly alter Bridget's basic
character in the second book. ``People who don't like her,
honestly, it's a sort of almost political position they have on
her. If we can't laugh at ourselves, we haven't gotten very far,
have we?''
</P>
<P>
   At its most extreme, the criticism linked Bridget with TV's Ally
McBeal in a sort of ``you can never be too thin or too romance
crazy'' mode that was supposedly more of a threat to the women's
movement than Phyllis Schlafly. Fielding seems somewhat bemused by
the oversize, overheated reaction to what are, essentially, books
about small incidents, often dashed off in diarylike sentence
fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Head goes here
</P>
<P>
   But there's also a bigger issue at stake, according to Fielding,
who began writing ``Diary'' under a pseudonym for a London
newspaper. She defends her creation as a slightly exaggerated and
always empathetic encapsulation of the serious predicaments many
modern women face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did seem that there was this whole group of women that was
saddled with this image that was horribly out of date and really
unfair,'' said Fielding, a never-married, former BBC journalist who
admits only to being in her early 40s. ``It's ridiculous that women
in their 30s who are very good professionally, have made their own
lives, have got good lives, and have clearly had to make hard
decisions not to be married, felt like rejects. When it's a
question of being brave and not compromising.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Fielding lingua franca, these women became known as
``singletons,'' while friends who couldn't relate to them without
spouses and who constantly poked into their personal lives were
dismissed as ``smug marrieds.'' And now, as if poor old Bridget
didn't have enough people meddling in her life, two continents of
singleton sympathizers are in an uproar over the choice of blond
Texan Renee Zellweger to play the title role in the upcoming film
version of ``Diary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the clunking, Hollywood idiocy,'' wrote a columnist in
London's Independent newspaper. ``Casting her as a young and
perfect thing is like remaking `The Elephant Man' with Jude Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the casting controversy, Fielding is unflustered
and, well, un-Bridget-like.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very good in `Jerry Maguire.' She had that thing of
being able to look both beautiful and ordinary,'' said Fielding,
who wrote two early versions of the script for the movie, then
lessened her involvement this year because of the demands of
promoting the sequel. ``Besides, I can't be involved with things
like casting. It hits too close to home. I've got my own picture of
how everybody looks, and they don't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether she herself resembles Bridget Jones, the answer
appears to be a definite ... maybe. On one hand, Fielding says that
when she was a young student at Oxford, she recorded her daily
caloric intake on a calendar. On the other hand, she declined a
Swedish journalist's implied challenge to drink to excess in a
recent interview. ``I felt really mean, but I couldn't do that. I
had to get up early the next morning,'' Fielding recalled with a
laugh. ``I'm not sure how Bridget would manage on a book tour!''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
