r e BC-TV-GOD09-COX     03-08 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBC series sinks in spiritual lampooning
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   God looks like Jerry Garcia and talks like James Garner (who
supplies his voice). The Devil (Tony winner Alan Cumming) sits at
home in hell and shouts requests to Guy Lombardo, who performs
there with his orchestra nightly. And Bob (French Stewart, the
squinty one in ``3rd Rock From the Sun''), is a beer-drinking,
porn-downloading auto worker with a wife and two kids, all of whom
he loves, none of whom he understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the Devil and Bob,'' NBC's animated series premiering at
8:30 tonight (it moves to 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays next week), sets those
title characters in motion in hopes that some sulfuric,
faith-provoking high jinks will ensue. This is satire as parable,
``King of the Hill'' meets ``Oh, God!,'' a comedy that means to
walk some high ground while it takes some low roads.
</P>
<P>
   It already has ruffled feathers: Two NBC affiliates won't air
it, one in Idaho and another in Salt Lake City (which also has
never aired ``Saturday Night Live'' or the daytime soap ``Sunset
Beach''). But as created by former seminarian Matthew Carlson, who
used theologians as consultants, ``God, the Devil and Bob'' is
rarely engaging enough to enrage us, or enraging enough to engage
us. It works too hard at being casually mischievous; you can see
the seams that stitched together these jokes from a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's pilot, the weakest of the three episodes previewed,
opens with this premise: God is ready to destroy the world but
decides he won't if just one soul can show him it's worth saving.
He lets his devilish pal the Devil pick that soul _ Bob.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show me the world's worth saving and I'll save it,'' God
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like a lot of work,'' says Bob. ``What's in it for
me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I made the right choice!'' exclaims the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   And like that. There are moments when the spiritual lampooning
moves beyond mere church-vestibule cutups. ``You're supposed to be
a benevolent God?'' a put-out Bob rants. ``Let's look at the
record: You're vague, you're unknowable, you let good people suffer
and lousy people prosper. ... You call yourself a father _ you're
more like a deadbeat dad.'' Pause. ``I'm just blowing off steam.''
</P>
<P>
   But those moments are more likely to prompt I-get-it nods rather
than real laughs, unlike ``The Simpsons,'' say, where a joke's
hidden layers hit you long after you've already been floored.
</P>
<P>
   By the second and third episodes, the focus turns more to Bob's
family, which includes wife Donna (Laurie Metcalf), 13-year-old
Megan and 6-year-old Andy.
</P>
<P>
   Megan (Nancy Cartwright, the voice of Bart Simpson) emerges as
the character with the most delectable world view (``It's like
ears. If you look at an ear, just look at it for like five minutes;
it'll literally make you sick'), and one wonders if the creators
wouldn't do better by ditching God, the Devil and Bob, and just
giving us a show called ``Megan.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the Devil and Bob''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 tonight on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
