r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-08 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOTE: THERE WILL BE NO PERSONALS MOVED THURSDAY MARCH 9 for &LR; 
 &UR; MARCH 10. WILL RESUME SUNDAY FOR MONDAY.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE MAN'S TALE OF THE GREELY EXPEDITION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   rt,10p10 Historian  &UR; Leonard Guttridge &LR; 's new book, ``Ghosts of
Cape Sabine'' (Putnam's; $27.95), tells the story of 25 American
soldiers who set forth in July 1881 to establish a scientific base
in the Arctic. Their saga, which ended in tragedy and the deaths of
19 of the 25, includes tales of starvation, mutiny, shipwreck,
execution and, as the book reveals, cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   One of the central characters in the tale is  &UR; Frederick &LR; 
 &UR; Kislingbury &LR; , who began the expedition as second in command.
 &UR; Linda Kislingbury Cain &LR; , great-granddaughter of Kislingbury, lives
in Novato and owns many papers relating to the expedition,
including his diary and letters from him to her grandfather,
 &UR; Douglass Kislingbury &LR; . The letters reveal him to be a loving
father.
</P>
<P>
   On August 8, 1881, for example, the lieutenant wrote to his
7-year-old son describing the difficulty of navigation, the dangers
of ice floes, the shooting of a polar bear and attempts to hunt
seal.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, ``I have seen Santa Claus up here, Duggy, and have
made arrangements with him to have the Esquimaux make you a nice
pair of Esquimaux slippers. ... You must not be anxious about me if
ship does not reach us next year, as we have fully two years
supplies and can get back some way. I am in the very best of health
and weigh more than I ever did before. My appetite is inordinate
and am sanguine that I can get through this sort of life
successfully and unless afflicted with disease or sickness feel
that I shall come back a stronger and healthier man than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, as the expedition started to fall apart, Kislingbury
challenged the authority of its leader,  &UR; Augustus &LR; 
 &UR; Greely &LR; . Eventually, he asked to be reassigned and was relieved of
his commission, &LR;  but missed the boat to go home, his only
opportunity. He died on June 3, 1884, of disease and starvation,
although just before his death, Greely reinstated him.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half months later, after the six survivors returned
home, rumors of cannibalism made front-page headlines in New York
newspapers. Kislingbury's exhumed body proved their truth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TROUBLE WITH HARRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Muggles for Harry Potter, an amalgam of authors' groups,
anti-censorship groups, publishers and book councils, aims at
fighting censorship of Harry Potter books. The group went online at
www.mugglesforharrypotter.org this week in response to reports that
teachers in Zeeland, Mich., were trying to prevent children from
reading the books because they portray witchcraft positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Potter books are helping turn video game players into
readers,'' said Christopher Finan of the American Booksellers
Foundation for Free Expression. ``We can't allow censorship to
interfere with that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - After a banquet salute to &UR; Steve Martin  &LR; in New York last week,
 &UR; Kevin Kline  &LR;  told the New York Daily News: ``We have a short
memory. In England, Steve would be knighted Sir Steve. In China,
he'd be a national treasure. In America, he's merely rich.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Paul Rauber &LR;  forwards a Radio Free Europe report that  &UR; Igor &LR; 
 &UR; Zakharov &LR; , a Russian publisher, is out with a half-length version
of  &UR; Leo Tolstoy &LR; 's ``War and Peace.'' The new version is said to be
a first draft, completed in 1866, with ``more peace and less war.''
</P>
<P>
   - Women's Sports &AMP; Fitness reports that when  &UR; Brooke Shields &LR; 
and  &UR; Andre Agassi  &LR; were married, he taped a photograph of  &UR; Steffi &LR; 
 &UR; Graf &LR;  _ Agassi's current girlfriend _ on their refrigerator to
remind Shields to get into shape.
</P>
<P>
   - Phone book tales from Oakland, as per  &UR; Andrew Demcak &LR; : BART
Battered, Escorts Executive and Coin Operated Colonic.  &UR; Cary &LR; 
 &UR; Groner &LR; 's a fan of Rupture Service. And from Sonoma: Wedding
Welding, ``for those who aren't sure their marriages will last,''
suggests  &UR; Arrow Olesky &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Ambling along Post Street in San Francisco,  &UR; Jay Schaefer &LR; 
overheard one woman nimbly describing another as one of those
``suddenly successful young people.'' Has this four-word phrase
become part of our language, child of ``yuppie,'' grandchild of
``hippie,'' great-grandchild of ``beatnik''?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I turned 40, the roles I've been given are the best of
my career. Maybe Hollywood has finally figured out what to do with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sigourney Weaver &LR; , &LR;   &LR; 50 and bucking the conventional
poor-me-against-the-chauvinists wisdom, in Biography magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - ``I don't know that I have the courage not to have plastic
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  -  &UR; Sela Ward &LR; , 43, in USA Today last week.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
