of ice floes, the shooting of a polar bear and attempts to hunt
seal.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, ``I have seen Santa Claus up here, Duggy, and have
made arrangements with him to have the Esquimaux make you a nice
pair of Esquimaux slippers. ... You must not be anxious about me if
ship does not reach us next year, as we have fully two years
supplies and can get back some way. I am in the very best of health
and weigh more than I ever did before. My appetite is inordinate
and am sanguine that I can get through this sort of life
successfully and unless afflicted with disease or sickness feel
that I shall come back a stronger and healthier man than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, as the expedition started to fall apart, Kislingbury
challenged the authority of its leader,  &UR; Augustus &LR; 
 &UR; Greely &LR; . Eventually, he asked to be reassigned and was relieved of
his commission, &LR;  but missed the boat to go home, his only
opportunity. He died on June 3, 1884, of disease and starvation,
although just before his death, Greely reinstated him.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half months later, after the six survivors returned
home, rumors of cannibalism made front-page headlines in New York
newspapers. Kislingbury's exhumed body proved their truth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TROUBLE WITH HARRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Muggles for Harry Potter, an amalgam of authors' groups,
anti-censorship groups, publishers and book councils, aims at
fighting censorship of Harry Potter books. The group went online at
www.mugglesforharrypotter.org this week in response to reports that
teachers in Zeeland, Mich., were trying to prevent children from
reading the books because they portray witchcraft positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Potter books are helping turn video game players into
readers,'' said Christopher Finan of the American Booksellers
Foundation for Free Expression. ``We can't allow censorship to
interfere with that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
