<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PLAYER-SENTENCED-ART-     03-08 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYER-SENTENCED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL BASKETBALL PLAYER SENTENCED TO PRISON FOR FOUL PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo  NYT29  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Just over a year ago, 18-year-old Tony Limon was a
proud senior starter for the Bobcats, the South San Antonio High
School basketball team, and weighing the offer of a college
basketball scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he sits in a Bexar County jail cell here, waiting for a
decision on Friday on whether a judge will reduce his five-year
prison sentence for assault. Limon threw an elbow into an
opponent's face in a basketball game, breaking the player's nose.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of the sentence for Limon, who was already in
trouble with the law when the altercation took place, has surprised
many involved in school sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been isolated cases of civil lawsuits alleging that
a student used too much force in executing a play, but I've never
heard of a student being criminally charged before,'' said Robert
Kanaby, executive director of the National High School Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Alton Ballard, executive director of the Texas Association of
Basketball Coaches, said that in his 25 years with the association:
``This is a first. We've never seen a high school student or a
college student charged for something they did during a sporting
event.''
</P>
<P>
   In a jailhouse news conference last week, Limon accused his
coach, Gary Durbon, of encouraging the violence, saying Durbon told
him after the incident, ``It's about time someone drew some
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbon, who has coached for seven years at South San, as it is
called, denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is in a desperate situation and my name has been thrown
in as the scapegoat,'' Durbon said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place in January 1999, in a game between South
San and East Central High School of San Antonio. A videotape shows
Limon flagrantly striking Brent Holmes, an East Central guard, late
in the first half, and Holmes' head snapping backward before he
fell to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes also suffered a concussion and facial cuts. A month later
he filed an assault charge against Limon. Last week his parents
sued the South San Antonio School District and Durbon to recover
what they said was more than $6,000 in medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Limon stayed in the game, which East Central won, 100-73. Limon
scored 2 points and fouled out in the second half. After school
officials saw the videotape, however, he was suspended for the rest
of the season. Then legal authorities viewed the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the district attorney saw the video, he bumped the
charges from a simple assault to aggravated assault,'' said Jack
McGinnis II, one of Limon's lawyers, who came into the case after
the sentence. Also, the earlier legal problems of Limon contributed
to the sentence he received, said those involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month before the incident, he had been arrested at a
local shopping mall and charged with two counts of burglary. He
pleaded no contest and was placed on probation.
</P>
<P>
   When the assault charge came before the court last month, Limon
again pleaded no contest, expecting more probation, his lawyer
said. But on Feb. 7, District Court Judge Mark Luitjen sentenced
Limon to five years in prison. Luitjen did not return a phone call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas judicial process, Luitjen has until
Friday to enforce his sentence or to accept the more lenient
sentence of a brief time in jail followed by probation, both not to
exceed six months, which Limon's lawyers have requested.
</P>
<P>
   Although high school sports officials knew of no other such case
involving a criminal charge against a player during a
school-sanctioned sporting event, a Chicago teen-ager was charged
with battery last year for an incident seconds after a youth hockey
league game ended. In professional sports, a Canadian court on
Tuesday lodged one count of assault with a weapon against Marty
McSorley, a Boston Bruins defenseman, for an attack with a hockey
stick on a Vancouver player, Donald Brashear, on Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Durbon, whose father also coached at South San, said that none
of his other players had ever committed an act as violent as the
one by Limon.
</P>
<P>
   ``High school play is real physical these days, not that it
should be,'' Durbon said, ``but I've never had anything like this
happen before with any of my boys. I don't think Tony really
intended to hurt anybody. He just made a mistake that night and
went a little bit too far.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But McGinnis said the coaching staff at South San was at least
partly responsible for what happened, and he contrasted Limon's two
crimes to demonstrate what he said was the unfairness of the
sentence: ``In the burglary, Tony is nervous, he's worried about
being caught, he knows he's doing something wrong. But on the
basketball court, he's playing a game, he's being a teen-ager; he
obviously has no criminal intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after it happens, his teammates congratulate him, his
coach says `It was time for blood,' and they leave him in the game.
What does that tell a kid?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Durbon said that Limon was allowed to return to the game because
neither the coaches nor the officials saw the blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't teach that,'' Durbon said. ``We've never taught that.
The kids have always played within the rules until this.''
</P>
<P>
   But two former teammates of Limon's confirmed his version of the
events.
</P>
<P>
   One, Ray Pacheco, said he remembered clearly what happened when
the players returned to the huddle after Holmes was hurt. ``The
coach told Tony, `It's about time someone drew some blood,'''
Pacheco said. ``That's exactly what he said to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The other, Richard Gonzalez, said: ``Yeah, coach said it. He
always encouraged people to play real tough, to play real
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Pacheco and Gonzalez, who were coached by Durbon for four
years at South San and remain friends of Limon, now attend
Lindenwood University in St. Charles, Mo., the same university that
offered Limon a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis still holds out the hope that the judge will reduce
Limon's sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid has one indiscretion off the court and one
indiscretion on the court,'' McGinnis said. ``Now, instead of going
to college and changing his life forever, he gets five years in
prison. Just think of the lost opportunity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Ray Leach, Holmes' lawyer in the civil suit against the
school district, said: ``People need to look at the vicious nature
of the crime and the criminal history of Limon that powered the
judge's sentence in this case. It was a brutal assault any way you
look at it. If it had happened on a street corner instead of a
basketball court, he would have been arrested on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family went through a lot of anguish. They still have
questions about actions of the coaching staff that may suggest
there are more people than just Limon who need to be brought to
account for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lawsuit and accusations, Durbon said he bears no ill
feeling toward Limon and that he, too, believes the sentence is
excessive. ``Five years is way too harsh,'' Durbon said. ``He
definitely needs to learn a lesson, but I don't think the boy is
going to learn anything in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry with him, and I wish him the best of luck.
Because he still is one of my boys,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
