<HEADLINE>
FIRED NURSE LOSES DISCRIMINATION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts board that regulates nursing has
dismissed a nurse's complaint that he was fired because he spoke up
about working conditions that he contended were unsafe for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pointing out that we had undergone a downsizing and a
reduction in staffing, but we were expected to give the same
quality of care to patients, which is impossible,'' said nurse
Barry Adams. ``This is happening all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has attracted national attention among nurses because
of the issues they say it raises about the accountability of
nurse-managers who implement cost-cutting decisions to reduce
staffing or use inexperienced personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Adams filed charges against his supervisor, nurse Ann T. Poster,
alleging that her firing of him constituted unprofessional and
unethical behavior. He also alleged that she was guilty of patient
neglect for her role in overseeing a Cambridge, Mass. nursing home
unit where one patient died of an accidental morphine overdose and
other patients were victims of care-related mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Poster worked at Youville Health Care Center, an
extended-care facility that has since closed.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the Board of Registration in Nursing said Adams
had failed to prove that Poster fired him in 1996 because of his
repeated complaints about unsafe working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa M. Bonanno, the nursing board's executive director, said
the board believed Poster when she testified that she fired Adams
for insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saying she fired him totally in retaliation,'' Bonanno
said. ``I must say, the board doesn't find that to be any more
credible than the reasons she put forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams and his supporters were dismayed by the board's decision.
His lawyers said they may challenge it in court, using a rarely
used mechanism called a writ of mandamus to reverse state agency
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Barry Adams case doesn't raise these larger issues,
then the public should ask what case would,'' said Suzanne Gordon,
a journalist who often writes about nursing issues.
</P>
<P>
   David Schildmeier, a spokesman for the 20,000-member
Massachusetts Nurses Association, said, ``We're just outraged by
the decision.'' The association brought about 100 nurses to the
board meeting and held a demonstration on the street outside.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and his supporters said the nursing board is protecting
nurse-managers, while holding staff nurses accountable for lapses
in patient care.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonnano said, ``There really are no facts to support that.''
He said board staff members recalled a dozen cases in the past two
years in which nurse-managers were charged with license
infractions.
</P>
<P>
   In making its decision, the nursing board reviewed nearly 1,000
pages of documentation, officials said, including the transcript of
a National Labor Relations Board hearing in 1997 in which Adams
successfully challenged Youville Health Care for firing him.
Federal Administrative Law Judge Arthur Amchan found that Adams'
firing was ``an illegal . . . attempt to silence and retaliate
against him'' and ordered Adams and two other nurses reinstated
with back pay.
</P>
<P>
   The board could not substantiate Adams' specific allegations of
inadequate staffing levels, Bonnano said. But Adams' attorneys
complained that the board selectively ignored some of his evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally we can't challenge the weight they accord to each
piece of evidence, but we can challenge them on grounds that they
didn't consider all the evidence,'' said Mala M. Rafik, an attorney
for Adams. ``They can't just ignore evidence as they see fit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
