<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN IN PHILIPPINES BETWEEN PRESIDENT AND SECURITIES
REGULATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ A scandal in the Philippines over accusations that a
friend of President Joseph Estrada's engaged in insider trading
escalated Wednesday into a showdown between Estrada and the
country's top securities regulator.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his administration was considering legal
action against the Securities and Exchange Commission chairman,
Perfecto Yasay Jr., accusing Yasay of exceeding his authority by
ordering the stock market to close because of accusations that the
exchange was whitewashing an investigation into the case.
</P>
<P>
   Yasay had ordered the exchange not to reopen Wednesday after its
compliance department resigned on Tuesday. Department members
walked out to protest what they said were attempts by the exchange
to dismiss a report on price manipulation of the shares of the
gambling concern BW Resources. The report implicated eight local
brokerage firms and Dante Tan, a major shareholder close to
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Secretary Jose Pardo intervened, vowing to open the
exchange ``even if I have to open the doors myself.'' The
commission's four other members helped defuse the situation
somewhat by overruling Yasay's order, and Wednesday morning Pardo
appeared at the exchange in person to ring the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   But without a compliance department, it is unclear who, if
anyone, is monitoring the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Yasay did could be called economic sabotage,'' Estrada
said in a radio interview. The president's press secretary, Rodolfo
Reyes, said the president's lawyers had advised him that Yasay's
actions were illegal and that Estrada could suspend the commission
chairman, whose term ends later this month. Yasay could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors applauded the decision to keep the market
open, but the feuding did little to restore confidence in the
government's economic stewardship. The benchmark stock index
dropped nearly 3 percent to a 16-month low, and the Philippine peso
slipped to its lowest level against the dollar this year. Investors
are concerned that the corruption endemic under former President
Ferdinand Marcos has returned with the 20-month-old Estrada
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crony capitalism was a big problem under Marcos,'' said
Deborah Schuler, a senior analyst at Moody's Investors Service in
Hong Kong. ``The concern has been that it perhaps is coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Philippines escaped the brunt of Asia's financial
crisis in 1997 and 1998, the recovery has been weakened by swelling
public debt second only to Indonesia's, according to J.P. Morgan.
Earlier this week, the country asked the International Monetary
Fund to extend its access to $650 million in new loans and won a
deal to obtain up to $1 billion more in financing from the Asian
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The insider trading accusations involving BW Resources are one
of several situations plaguing Estrada's administration. Last
month, for example, the interior secretary and the head of the
country's police were charged with trying to fix a contract.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between Estrada and Yasay had been building for
some time. Relations between them had been tense since January,
when Yasay testified that Estrada had pressed him to clear Tan.
Estrada has denied placing any pressure on Yasay.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry began after BW Resources' shares rose 5,300 percent
just before it was announced on Oct. 11 that Stanley Ho, a Macao
gambling tycoon, would buy a 10 percent stake in the company and
become its chairman. The investment had been rumored for months,
and after the news, BW Resources' stock plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   The securities commission's report on the investigation, made
public last month, said there was enough evidence to support
charges of insider trading and price manipulation against Tan and
the brokerage firms. Tan has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter of resignation on Tuesday, Ruben Almadro, head of
the exchange's compliance department, accused exchange officials of
capitulating to political pressure and exonerating the companies
implicated in his department's report. The rest of the department
resigned in a separate letter of support for Almadro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
