<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GENOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      03-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENT ISSUE DIVIDES GENOME RESEARCHERS, DRUG COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The final phase of the Human Genome Project _ billed as
potentially the greatest advance in the history of medical science
_ has erupted into a tense war of words between federal researchers
racing to complete the task and the flamboyant president of a
biotech startup who wants to profit by giving drug companies an
early, private look at the genetic data.
</P>
<P>
   J. Craig Venter, president of Celera Genomics Corp., in an
interview with The Boston Globe Wednesday, charged the federal
government's US Human Genome Research Institute with wanting to
foil his business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Celera and the institute are both trying to complete the massive
task of deciphering all the DNA data in the human blueprint.
Scheduled to be finished later this year, the completed genome is
expected to spark new and radical advancements in medical
treatment, therapies and cures for diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The competitors chose widely different approaches in handling
the data. The government maintains that the DNA data should
immediately go into a public database where all can use it. Celera,
on the other hand, argues that unless drug companies can exert
patent rights over the gene data, they will not have an incentive
to invest in costly development of the new drugs and treatments
that the gene information could make possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government is working against the public and
against the US health system,'' said Venter, by insisting that the
gene sequence data be made public as soon as it's been obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Venter also said the dispute ``isn't about economics, it's about
who gets credit'' for deciphering the human genome, the largest
biology project ever undertaken. Celera, a company only 18 months
old which has already achieved a scientific milestone by
deciphering all the genes of the fruit fly, has developed a faster
method of reading out the DNA information in cells than the
techniques used by the government-funded genome centers, one of
which is in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Cambridge genome center, Eric Lander, suggested
earlier that Celera and the national genome institute, which is
headed by Dr. Francis S. Collins, collaborate on the final DNA
readouts rather than competing.
</P>
<P>
   But talks on the plan have been more off than on for months.
Most recently, a human genome project negotiating team and Celera
officials met last Dec. 29 in an effort to agree on basic terms for
working together.
</P>
<P>
   The mood after the meeting was ``pessimistic,'' said Kathy
Hudson, a policy official at the genome institute, in an interview.
Venter said that one reason things went sour was because Lander, a
highly respected geneticist at the Whitehead Institute in
Cambridge, was very reasonable about Celera's position and
therefore was ``kicked off'' the genome negotiating team. Hudson
responded that Lander was never on the team. Lander did not return
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the discouraging meeting, genome officials made
``innumerable attempts'' to reach Venter later to continue
discussions, but got no response, said Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Venter said he had been traveling and had tried to call Collins
on more than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, an exchange of letters between the government center
and Celera has accomplished nothing except to harden their
respective positions.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said that the negotiating team had not had a chance to
review Celera's March 7 letter in which it said its only
restriction is that ``other database providers would be prohibited
from providing or selling Celera's data as their own.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Venter said that Celera only wants to patent a
few hundred of the estimated 80,000 to 100,000 genes that are being
deciphered in the genome project. Celera's business plan, he said,
is to sell subscriptions enabling drug companies (at a cost of $5
million a year) and academic centers (at a much lower cost) to use
not only the raw gene data but Celera's high-powered computers and
methods of analyzing the function of the genes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the subscription plan, the companies have a certain length
of time to sift through the data and apply for patents before other
companies get to see the data. The genome institute objects to any
collaboration with Celera under which the company would be able to
exclude the public from the data.
</P>
<P>
   According to current estimates, the national genome center will
publish a ``rough draft'' of the human genome by this spring. A
rough draft would include about 90 percent of the DNA blueprint,
and a final, detailed version would be ready by 2003 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Celera says it will have most of the genome sequence deciphered
by the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
