<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS &LR;      03-08 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE ENDS FILIBUSTER ON CALIFORNIA JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of waiting, two controversial
Californians appear sure to get their day in court _ and their days
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday ended a filibuster led by conservative
Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., against Richard Paez, a U.S. District Court
judge in Los Angeles, and San Francisco lawyer Marsha Berzon. Both
are nominees for seats on the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Votes on their nominations are expected Thursday, and both are
expected to win Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   Paez has been waiting four years for a vote, longer than any
federal judicial nominee in modern history. Berzon, who specializes
in federal appeals cases and sits on the board of the American
Civil Liberties Union, was nominated more than two years ago. The
9th circuit court covers California and eight other Western states.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's two-day filibuster was crushed by an 86-13 vote largely
because it lacked the support of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., who promised Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., last November
that he would bring the two nominations to the Senate floor by
March 15. Buoyed by Lott's stance, Senate Democrats were able to
persuade most of their Republican colleagues to join them in ending
the filibuster. The overwhelming majority for stopping it was far
greater than the 60 votes needed.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the expected vote Thursday, Boxer said, ``This vote
has been much too long in coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate officials predicted that both Paez and Berzon, who have
the support of all 45 Senate Democrats, would win easily. Berzon
has appeared to have a comfortable number of Republican supporters
all along, but until this week Paez faced a close vote.
</P>
<P>
   The jurist picked up several key Republican endorsements on
Tuesday and Wednesday, including those of Sens. Orrin Hatch of
Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee; Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, and Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania, chairman of the Senate Veterans' Affairs
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank my Republican colleagues who I hope have shown the
light to other Republican senators,'' Boxer said. In fact, Sens.
Robert Bennett of Utah, Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island, James
Jeffords of Vermont and Gordon Smith of Oregon are said to be
leaning toward approval of the Californians.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives who have fought Paez and Berzon say they are
too liberal and would only add to an already liberal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 9th Circuit (Court of Appeals) is a big enough problem as
it is without appointing two more liberal judges to it,'' Smith
said in Wednesday's filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Paez of being a judicial activist, Sen. Jeffrey
Sessions, R-Ala., said he ``obviously believes that when a law
doesn't suit him, he has the right not to enforce it fully.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats noted that Paez has publicly stated he is against
any form of judicial activism.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also insisted that the liberal tag has been
unfairly applied to Paez and Berzon and that both in fact are
mainstream legal scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two candidates would be amazing assets to the 9th
Circuit Court, and I hope my Republican colleagues will make that
happen,'' Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that Hatch has called Berzon is one of the most
qualified nominees he has ever seen and that Domenici on Wednesday
said that ``the time had come for Mr. Paez to be appointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Domenici is right,'' Boxer said. ``The time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
