r e BC-HELLTOPAY-REVIEW-TEX     03-08 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELLTOPAY-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD `HILLARY IS POWER MAD' SONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREA AHLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hell to Pay: The Unfolding Story of Hillary Rodham Clinton'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Barbara Olson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regnery, $27.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look at a copy of ``Hell to Pay: The Unfolding Story of Hillary
Rodham Clinton,'' and the cover photo reveals that this will not be
a flattering portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Between the covers, former Travelgate federal prosecutor Barbara
Olson takes an unabashedly critical look at Clinton and her liberal
political background.
</P>
<P>
   The book attempts to chronicle what Olson calls Clinton's
``lifelong motivation'' for political power by describing key
turning points: her work on Watergate, her decision to move to
Arkansas and marry Bill Clinton, and, of course, her participation
in the Whitewater real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Olson introduces chapters with quotes from Saul Alinksy's
``Rules for Radicals,'' using the quotes as guiding themes. Olson
provides some new anecdotes about Clinton, such as the time she
tried to enlist in the Marine Corps, but not enough to avoid mostly
rehashing public knowledge. In particular, Olson relies heavily on
quotes from White House advisers and the first lady's friends _
quotes that we've often read elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell to Pay'' suffers from the lack of substantial original
research to back up Olson's acerbic observations. Those
observations will therefore fall flat with readers, other than
those willing to hate the first lady anytime, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Olson does offer several insights into Clinton's determined,
focused support of her husband's political aspirations as a way to
further her own platform.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Olson points out that Clinton tirelessly campaigned
to have her husband re-elected governor of Arkansas after he lost
the office in 1980. As soon as his new term began, she grabbed the
limelight as chairwoman of a commission to upgrade the state
educational system. Personal ambition was obviously not lacking.
</P>
<P>
   However, Olson lets her personal views color her writing so much
that she weakens her presentation for objective readers. ``Hell to
Pay'' is essentially a caricature of Hillary Clinton as a
power-obsessed liberal, just like the distorted photo on the
cover. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Andrea Ahles is a ``Star-Telegram'' business writer. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
