<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY09-COX     03-08 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voters fail to embrace Bradley's `radical' notion
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometime after he lost the New Hampshire primary,
Bill Bradley dropped a stock phrase from his standard pitch to
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is based on the radical premise,'' he had
frequently intoned, ``that you can say what you believe and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The homily embodied the new style of politics that Bradley said
he wanted to bring the country when he announced his insurgent
challenge to Vice President Al Gore in December 1998, promising
bold solutions to a few big problems.
</P>
<P>
   But following Tuesday night's drubbing across the country and
his expected withdrawal from the race today, it is clear that
Bradley badly overestimated the receptiveness of Democratic voters
to his message. And he failed to fully appreciate one of the cold
truths about American politics: Voters also want to like the
messenger.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems clear that Bradley's storied career as an Olympic
gold medalist, Rhodes scholar and NBA basketball player _ what
attracted so many core believers to his campaign _ was not enough
to overcome the reserved, cerebral demeanor he exhibited as a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake for a candidate to be as closed and as private
and as opaque as Bradley was,'' said Richard Winters, political
science chairman at Dartmouth University. ``Presidential candidates
have to appeal on a visionary level ... but I think they also have
to appeal on an emotional level. I don't think people felt
comfortable about Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bradley's legendary discipline and focus _ the personal
qualities that led him into the NBA Hall of Fame and into the U.S.
Senate _ became liabilities. From the outset, Bradley said he was
going to run only on his terms. He would talk about the issues he
cared about, and present them in a way that ``showed respect to the
American people.'' He could not and would not change his game plan,
even when it became clear that it wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of tactical rigidity loses battles,'' said Ross
Baker, a Rutgers University political scientist who has followed
Bradley's career for 25 years. ``You have to be able to depart from
the master plan. He seemed to just follow it very diligently.''
</P>
<P>
   It will always remain an open question whether Bradley _ or any
candidate _ could have defeated a sitting vice president at a time
of record prosperity and unemployment. No candidate has ever done
it in modern political history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains that we came within 5,000 votes of beating a
sitting vice president in New Hampshire,'' said Anita Dunn,
Bradley's commutations director and one of his top advisers. Dunn
blamed Bradley's defeat on the difficulty he had getting national
media attention after the New Hampshire primary, when press
attention was focused on Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither the message or the messenger were ever heard,'' Dunn
said. ``In the absence of hearing the message, voters went with the
known candidate, which was the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Bradley's strategy was premised on the gamble that Gore
would not emerge from President Clinton's shadow and that voters
would tar him with Clinton's scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gore, spurred by Bradley's early challenge, emerged as
a fierce competitor. He ditched his staid Washington wardrobe,
adopted a combative style of campaigning and captured the backing
of key Democratic voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's help, Gore secured the endorsements of organized
labor, the teacher's unions, prominent gay and lesbian groups and
leaders in the pro-abortion rights movement. African-American and
Latino voters remained loyal to Gore, despite Bradley's success in
wooing a few African-American celebrities to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a referendum on the Clinton administration on the
policy side,'' said David Bositis, senior political analyst at the
Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies. ``That made it all
but impossible to beat Gore unless something really bad happened to
discredit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the long odds, Bradley's margin for error was always
tiny.
</P>
<P>
   The first decisive blow occurred Oct. 13, 1999, when the AFL-CIO
endorsed Gore after intense lobbying from Gore and Clinton. Labor's
endorsement carried manpower and resources. Exit polling in Iowa,
New Hampshire and the Super Tuesday states showed that Gore carried
union voters by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   The labor endorsement was followed by a tactical blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike McCain, who completely ignored the Iowa caucuses and
instead focused on New Hampshire and South Carolina, Bradley
invested heavily in the Hawkeye State, hoping to exceed
expectations in a state that tilts heavily toward the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   More costly for his campaign, however, was that Bradley himself
spent almost three solid weeks in Iowa before the Jan. 24 caucuses.
He left Iowa a loser _ Gore trounced him by a 2-1 ratio _ and
arrived in New Hampshire with only eight days to generate new
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Paindiris, Bradley's Connecticut coordinator, said he
lobbied the campaign to get Bradley back to New Hampshire, where
his presence could also have had an impact on New England states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The missed opportunity was not staying in New Hampshire when
he was ahead,'' said Paindiris. ``That was a misstep.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, spent most of January in New Hampshire,
campaigning hard against the ``iron triangle'' of Washington
special interests and claiming Bradley's reform mantle for his own.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus was generating
huge crowds and excitement. Bradley was slow to recognize McCain's
threat and struggled over how to counter Gore's daily attacks
against his health care proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Five days before the primary, Bradley began an offensive against
Gore during a televised debate, questioning his integrity and
veracity on abortion and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   And only after New Hampshire did Bradley begin to contrast
himself to McCain. On the day New Hampshire voted, independents
helped propel McCain to a stunning 19-point victory over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley did not show a willingness to be assertive and
tough and aggressive until too late,'' said Kathy Sullivan,
chairwoman of the New Hampshire Democratic Party. ``People say they
don't like negative campaigning, but you still have to have that
willingness to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's big win over Bush, coupled with Bradley's four-point
loss to Gore, set Bradley on a course for almost certain defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain stole the thunder as the reformer,'' said former New
York City Mayor Ed Koch, a Bradley supporter.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also stole all the press attention, pushing Bradley off
the nightly news and deep into the media void.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for some renewed momentum, Bradley devoted six days to
winning Washington state's nonbinding primary Feb. 29. The loss
there only seemed to reinforce the idea that he couldn't win,
accelerating the perception that his campaign was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sucking for oxygen,'' said Pete D'Alessandro, who
helped direct Bradley's Iowa campaign, explaining the Washington
state strategy. ``That was where the next fight was, and we went
after it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Washington state loss, Bradley dropped his
counter-attacks on Gore and returned to the positive campaign he
had set out to run. Bradley's on-again, off-again strategy of
countering Gore's attacks remains a subject of intense disagreement
among his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had started attacking Gore a week earlier in New
Hampshire, he would have won New Hampshire and from there things
would have been different,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler (D-N.Y.), a
Bradley supporter. ``Six weeks of not responding was a fundamental
error.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bradley did attack Gore, first on his truthfulness
and then on his Democratic credentials, accusing him of being soft
on tobacco policy, abortion rights, gun control and affirmative
action. But the attacks always seemed awkward, ill-timed or
half-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is not used to running negative campaigns and he is not
good at it,'' said Martha Darling, who worked for Bradley in the
Senate and served on his Michigan campaign. ``Bill had only run in
New Jersey. Al Gore started running in 1988. He's got a lot of pros
on his staff. Bill has a lot less seasoned staff. It shows that
there is a certain lack of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine Bradley, Bradley's wife, said her husband simply
wasn't willing to sacrifice his principles for the sake of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the risk that Bill was willing to take,'' Bradley
said. ``Bill is who is, and so I don't think he could adjust to a
system that works like politics as usual. That's not Bill. He could
not reinvent himself as a politician as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
