u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-08 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A DELICATE BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton uses the term ``the trust
divide'' when she talks about the suspicion and hostility that have
created such a devastating gap between the law-abiding residents of
some big-city neighborhoods and the police officers who are
supposed to protect and serve them.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City at the moment, the situation is particularly
bleak. In the aftermath of the Louima and Diallo cases, there is
tremendous anxiety and frustration, even fear, in minority
neighborhoods like Soundview and Harlem and Bedford-Stuyvesant.
</P>
<P>
   Parents give their children lectures on how to respond if
approached by the police. Professional men talk about their
reluctance to carry a cell phone, lest it create a bulge that could
lead to a humiliating search, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Police-community relations are an unusual issue for a U.S.
Senate race. But unusual is the norm for this race between Rudolph
Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton, so get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee the other day, Mrs. Clinton said she wanted to add
her voice and influence to those who are attempting to bridge the
divide between the police officers, who have the difficult and
dangerous job of fighting crime, and the people in the
neighborhoods who feel they are treated unfairly and
disrespectfully.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the Louima and Diallo cases were not just
``horrific'' but symptomatic of problems in the city's overall
approach to policing. The real challenge, she said, is to adjust
the approach _ ``change the climate'' _ so that policing ``is both
effective and respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton referred specifically to a recent article by Fox
Butterfield in The New York Times that detailed how some cities
have achieved reductions in crime comparable to New York's without
the same levels of police aggression and confrontation, and without
the same deterioration of relations between the police and local
communities.
</P>
<P>
   There was an effort by the police in those cities to work  &UR; with &LR; 
community leaders, local residents, the clergy and even youngsters,
enlisting their support and help in the fight against crime in
their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   New York has scoffed at that approach.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the crime-fighting strategies launched in the
1990s required a two-pronged effort. There had to be a serious
crackdown on crime and quality-of-life offenses that would, among
other things, send a message ``to criminals and victims alike that
we're changing the way we do business.'' But there was also a need
for the police to respectfully engage the law-abiding members of
the community, thus making them part of the overall anti-crime
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other cities have done a better job on that second
prong of the strategy,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   So what's next?
</P>
<P>
   There will be increased calls, especially from members of the
clergy, for a closer working relationship between local communities
and the New York Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton strongly supports that effort. As she said in an
appearance Sunday at Riverside Church, ``In so many communities, no
institution has more influence than the neighborhood church, mosque
or synagogue. We must tap into this potential in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   This would not be an effort in a vacuum. There already are some
good working relationships between the clergy and local precinct
commanders, but they are not the norm. Those relationships can be
built upon.
</P>
<P>
   It would be enormously helpful if Giuliani at some point would
see the light and lend his considerable weight to a real effort to
improve police-community relations. But the effort will happen
whether he chooses to participate or not.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two years ago, the Kerner commission on the riots of the
1960s found the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``The abrasive relationship between the police and the minority
communities has been a major _ and explosive _ source of grievance,
tension and disorder. The blame must be shared by the total
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are faced with demands for increased protection and
service in the ghetto. Yet the aggressive patrol practices thought
necessary to meet these demands themselves create tension and
hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   That was March 1968. This is March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Now might be a good time to get started.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
