u a BC-CARDINAL-APOLOGY-BOS &LR;      03-08 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-APOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL LAW TO DELIVER APOLOGY FOR CATHOLICS' SINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cardinal Bernard F. Law on Saturday will express sorrow
for contemporary and historical sins of Boston Catholics, including
church members' treatment of Jews, blacks, non-Catholic Christians,
and alienated Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Law's decision to seek forgiveness for sins of Boston's
Catholics is inspired by remarks Pope John Paul II is scheduled to
make on Sunday, in which the pope plans to seek forgiveness for
``faults of the past,'' including aspects of the Crusades, the
Inquisition, and perhaps the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will focus on those situations in our history as a church
which, from the perspective of today, we look upon with sorrow and
regret, as we also beg God to forgive us our own individual sins,''
said Law, who is the Catholic archbishop of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The pope and the cardinal are each expected to stick to broad
themes, rather than listing specific events, because, Cardinal
Roger Etchegaray, president of the Vatican's 2000 Jubilee
Committee, said this week, ``a penitential act, however public it
may be, must not appear as a form of spectacular
self-flagellation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the archdiocesan newspaper, the Pilot, has acknowledged that
Catholic priests and nuns owned slaves, and that the Pilot itself
maintained a racist editorial policy during the Civil War. The pope
has admitted fault for violence against church dissidents,
religious wars and excesses of evangelization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledgements of sin are prompted by the start of Lent, a
period in which Christians are supposed to seek penance for sins,
and by the ongoing Jubilee year, an anniversary during which the
church is pausing for reflection on its first 2,000 years. Cardinal
Roger M. Mahony of Los Angeles issued his own apology to divorced
Catholics, women, gays, and victims of clergy sexual abuse in a
speech this week, and some other bishops are expected to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the themes of the Jubilee year for us is
reconciliation,'' Law said in an interview at the Cathedral of the
Holy Cross, where he will make his remarks in a homily during a
special vespers service of evening prayers at 7 p.m. Saturday. ``We
will be looking back to those moments when, through her members,
the church was not faithful to herself, to the message of Christ,
and it's a good thing for us. . .to name those things. It's a good
thing for us, and it's also a good thing to name those things for
others who share those memories with us and for whom they are
vivid.''
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated remarks by the cardinal and the pope are being
welcomed by representatives of groups who in the past have been
discriminated against or persecuted by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud the pope for his courage in standing up and saying
we can no longer afford to ignore the abuses we have been
participating in, and I'm glad to see he is encouraging his
archbishops to do the same,'' said Charles Turner, a member of the
Boston City Council who has been active on civil rights issues, and
who said other institutions acknowledge their historic treatment of
African-Americans. ``It's a very important spiritual and social and
political act.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy K. Kaufman, executive director of the Jewish Community
Relations Council of Greater Boston, is also pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pope has probably gone further than any pope ever in
terms of seeking forgiveness for past Catholic errrors, including
the treatment of Jews, and it's wonderful,'' Kaufman said.
``Reconciliation and forgiveness is always important.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics wonder if the church is going far enough,
particularly because both the pope and the cardinal insist that
they are not apologizing for the church, but for its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no news that Catholics have committed sins, but the issue
is whether official representatives of the church, like popes and
bishops, have sinned in ways that implicate the institution,'' said
Lisa S. Cahill, a Boston College theologian. ``More and more
frequently the pope and other representatives have been offering
quasi-apologies to groups that have been harmed by practices of
those within the Catholic church, but they're very careful about
staying away from attributing guilt to the church as a whole, and
that's a point of contention.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the archdiocese of Boston say the church itself
does not sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church as an institution has been faithful to the Lord,
but members. . .have themselves been sinners, and even, at times,
in the name of the church people have done things that are wrong,''
said Bishop William Murphy, Law's top aide.
</P>
<P>
   At the service Saturday, Law plans to speak broadly about sins
of church members in his homily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously our relationship across religious divides has not
always been what it should have been, or across racial divides and
linguistic divides,'' he said. ``We have a very appropriate and
correct knowledge about the fundamental equality of men and women,
but that hasn't always been lived out as it should be, and I hope
to address that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then church officials will recite a list of approximately 12
categories of sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be expressing sorrow for sins of anti-semitism, for a
lack of openness and collaboration with other Christians, for
slavery, and for a lack of outreach to Catholics who for one reason
or another are alienated,'' said Murphy, who is helping to draft
the list.
</P>
<P>
   In his homily Sunday, the pope is expected to allude to the
Crusades, a series of military expeditions from the 11th through 13
centuries in which Christians violently attempted to wrest control
of Jerusalem from Muslims, and to the Inquisition, a medieval papal
institution in which the church used torture, among other methods,
to find and punish heretics.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope is also expected to allude to Nazi Germany's campaign
to eliminate European Jewry in the 1930s and '40s, which the
Vatican described this week as a result of ``pagan ideology,'' but
said ``it must be asked whether the Nazi persecution of the Jews
was not made easier by the anti-Jewish prejudices imbedded in some
Christian minds and hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said the failings of Catholics must be understood in
historical context, but that the context does not supply an excuse
for sinful behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as Catholics have to be sensitive to the fact that to the
degree that we're guilty of racism, we are letting ourselves be
formed by the dominant culture, rather than being prophetic in that
culture, which we are called to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he is concerned about contemporary failings of
Catholics, which he said include a failure to advocate strongly
enough for the poor in America and abroad and a failure to oppose
strongly enough abortion, capital punishment, and euthanasia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
