<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CENSUS-NYT &LR;      03-08 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS IS SUBJECT TO MORE PARTISAN DEBATE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla . )  By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After weeks marked by peace and cooperation, the
partisan wars over the conduct of the 2000 Census have erupted once
again.
</P>
<P>
   As the Census Bureau has begun mailing questionnaires to nearly
120 million households, Republicans in Congress are complaining
that the bureau is stonewalling their effort to oversee how the
census is carried out.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Census Bureau officials say they are being
nibbled to death by requests for information from Congress, the
General Accounting Office, a joint Presidential/Congressional
Monitoring Board, the National Academy of Science and other
entities keeping track of how well the bureau is doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that many oversight entities want to have ``real
time'' information on census operations, meaning they want
up-to-the-minute data such as recruitment of staff, number of
questionnaires that have been mailed or returned and number of
households visited.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Democrats have begun criticizing Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee who,
after much prodding, has finally said that he opposes the use of
statistical sampling to supplement traditional methods of counting
residents.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their attacks, Democrats released copies of
memorandums written by Texas officials who, at one point in 1997
declared that ``all sides in the census debate concede that
traditional methods of calculation, which seek to identify and
count each individual resident, will never provide a full and
accurate portrait of the U.S. population.''
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the memorandums, Democrats hope to show that Bush
has adopted a partisan position regarding sampling that is actually
harmful to the interests of his own state.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the fireworks were centered in a hearing Wednesday
held by the House Subcommittee on the Census. The panel's chairman
grilled Kenneth W. Prewitt, the Census Bureau Director on his
agency's alleged unresponsiveness to requests by the GAO and other
bodies for information.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who is chairman of the subcommittee was
particularly incensed over a recent memorandum written by top
officials of the Census Bureau to the heads of local and regional
offices. In the memorandum, census officials said any official
delegations wishing to visit a local or regional office must submit
a written request two weeks in advance. The document also declared
that visitors be accompanied by senior Census Bureau staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a problem,'' Miller said ``Are you denying there is a
problem? This is going to affect respect for the census when we go
through this process. Unless we can get this information,
everyone's going to be suspect of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, retorted that top management of the census was already
spending up to one-third of its time responding to requests for
information for the subcommittee staff, the GAO and others.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a copy of the District of Columbia yellow Pages,
Prewitt said that his agency had already turned over one terrabyte
of information to the GAO which he said was equivalent to 50
million copies of the yellow pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how much information we all already giving to GAO,''
Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats ascribe a more partisan motive for the
Republicans' request for more ``real time'' information.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the census boils down to whether the bureau can
use statistical sampling to augment population counts that will be
used to draw Congressional boundaries, a process known as
redistricting. Sampling, which is an enhanced and more
sophisticated version of polling, is presumed to help Democrats in
redistricting since it will boost the number of minorities _ mainly
blacks in the inner cities and Hispanics in rural areas _ who tend
to be missed by tradition census methods.
</P>
<P>
   Population counts for use in redistricting must be delivered to
the states by April 1, 2001. In order to provide those counts using
sampling the Census Bureau must have finished employing its
traditional counting methods and started its sampling work by
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fear that Republicans are trying to delay the Census
Bureau enough that it will be forced to not use sampling techniques
in order to make the April 1, 2001 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican staffer who is very familiar with the party's
strategy gave some credence to that view saying that House
Republicans want the real time information on census operations to
make sure that the Census Bureau does not start its sampling work
too soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
