<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     03-08 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALL BOUNCES HUSKIES' WAY _ AGAIN _ AGAINST EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's tough to play hard and play well for 40 minutes
when you know you are supposed to lose _ when you know the other
guys are bettter.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston College-University of Connecticut basketball series
is a one-sided rivalry that is now reaching biblical dimension. It
makes Gore-Bradley look like a pick 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dukakis was a presidential candidate and Bruce Hurst a
Red Sox pitcher the last time Boston College beat UConn in
basketball (1988). Wednesday, in the hallowed hardwood house where
Bill Bradley was a winner, the Huskies kept the streak (23 and
counting) going with a 70-55 victory in the first round of the Big
East tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the Hukies think of the Eagles: When star guard
Khalid El-Amin was interviewed by Dan Patrick in ESPN Magazine,
Patrick asked if the Houston Comets of the WNBA would beat any team
in the Big East. El-Amin said, ``They'd give BC a run.'' When
Patrick noted that BC folk might be riled by the comment, El-Amin
said, ``Just being honest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we saw that,'' said BC senior captain Michael Cotton.
``Everyone's entitled to their opinion. Obviously, we are
outmatched by them. They are bigger, stronger, taller. But the
other stuff is just talk. We can compete with them, but it's tough
over 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early going Wednesday, the Eagles dared to dream. Al
Skinner's motley crew, playing without flossy freshman Troy Bell
(knee), BC bolted to a 12-3 lead over the defending national
champs.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm. Upset in the making? . . . Jesuit school performs a
miracle on 34th Street on Ash Wednesday . . . The most astounding
college hoop upset since Chaminade over Ralph Sampson's Virginia
powerhouse in the 1983.
</P>
<P>
   No. Huskie coach Jim Calhoun called timeout, spanked his cocky
lads, and UConn had the game tied at 14 three minutes later. Then
El-Amin hit a short baseline jumper and UConn never trailed again.
The peak lead was 68-48 and the Huskies outrebounded BC, 46-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn is a much more gifted basketball team than we are,''
admiited Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle senior guard Dwayne Pina said, ``Maybe their lack of
respect allowed us to jump out early. We saw what (El-Amin) said. I
guess we used that as motivation. We wanted to prove them wrong.
Next year hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Next season will be Skinner's fourth and the Eagles are going to
have to improve if they want to come back to this tournament. In
2001, the league tournament will cease to be all-inclusive and that
means another Eagle appearance in the basement will keep BC home.
</P>
<P>
   There is officially no one left (except student managers) from
the Jim O'Brien era. The Eagles have turned in seasons of 15-16,
6-21, and 11-19 in Skinner's three years on the job. Boston College
is the consensus worst team in the conference and it no longer
serves any useful purpose to think of the Final Four possibilities
if O'Brien had been allowed to keep the players he recruited. In a
town dominated by professional sports (and the accompanying
negativity cited by Skinner's old UMass backcourtmate, Rick Pitino)
Boston College basketball has become irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner doesn't mind the apathy, just Red Sox players never
minded playing in the background during April, May, and June back
in the days when the Celtics were good. Hiding in the weeds can
have its advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate people coming out and supporting us, but that's
not the reason I do this,'' said the coach. ``But this has been a
tough year, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's not worried about the UConn streak _ one that dates
back to the days when Dana Barros was throwing up threes against
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's real important,'' said the coach.
``These players have not experienced that. I don't have a problem
with the streak that exists. It's no reflection on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Michael Cotton has played his last game for the Eagles,
and like Billy Curley, Howard Eisley, Malcom Huckaby, Danya Abrams,
Mickey Curley, Bevan Thomas, and Antonio Granger before him, he
leaves the Heights without ever knowing what it feels like to beat
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
