<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      03-08 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND ARAFAT AGREE TO NEW TALKS, AT A LOW LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian and Israeli leaders agreed Wednesday to
resume their fitful peace talks this month in Washington, holding
to their self-imposed deadline of Sept. 13 for a final treaty
despite a long history of stop-and-go negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after the second of two meetings between
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, in the space of a day. The final session took place in a
hotel in the Palestinian-controlled town of Ramallah, which has
become the hub for Palestinian Authority ministries in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The previous face-to-face encounter between the two leaders took
place more than one month ago at the edge of the Gaza Strip and
ended acrimoniously. A few days after that summit, Palestinian
negotiators suspended the peace talks, expressing frustration with
both the scope and timetable of Israel's proposed withdrawal from
more of the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians complained that Israel had tried to dictate, rather
than discuss, the choice of territory that was supposed to be
handed over to full or partial Palestinian control earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton decided that a low-key approach, with low
expectations, was the best way to resume the talks, according to an
administration spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, James Rubin, the spokesman, said that
``this is the best way to give a kick-start to the process.'' He
added that ``even a good kick-start might not get it going.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks, which officials said are begin on March 18 in the
Washington area, will involve small teams of negotiators who are
charged with designing a blueprint for a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we needed more preparation at lower levels before
before getting the leaders together,'' said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   No details were released Wednesday about any Israeli concessions
made to induce the Palestinians back to the bargaining table, but
some officials from both camps said the Palestinians would be given
more say in determining which areas are transferred.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, President Clinton's peace envoy, played master of
ceremonies Wednesday. He called the leaders' private discussions
``very constructive'' and said that Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators would restart their work on a framework agreement for
peace after the Muslim holiday of Eid al Adha, which ends on March
16.
</P>
<P>
   During the monthlong hiatus in talks, both Egypt and the United
States made intensive diplomatic efforts to bring the sides
together. To underline the Egyptian role, Barak and Arafat are
scheduled to meet the Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak, in the
Sinai resort town of Sharm el Sheik on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Only after that meeting, officials said, could any details be
disclosed of the working understandings between Palestinians and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Body language, metaphors and gestures are all part of the
elaborate rituals of making peace in the Middle East, and on
Wednesday all three were put to use in the Barak-Arafat meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The location of the meeting, in Ramallah, was widely interpreted
as a concession to Arafat. It was only the second time, as far as
is known, that the Israeli leader ventured into a
Palestinian-controlled area for one of their regular summits.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring the negotiations for at least the first week or so
to Washington was also seen as a gesture to the Palestinians, who
have complained that Israel effectively downgraded the importance
of their track while pursuing more high-profile peace talks with
Syria in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's ambitious attempt to make peace on parallel tracks with
the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon, also has drawn criticism in
Israel as unrealistic and risky.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the effort has faltered. The Syrian talks have been
suspended since mid-January. Soon after they broke down, the
Syrian-backed Hezbollah militia stepped up attacks on Israeli
soldiers in southern Lebanon, bringing fierce Israeli reprisals
that served to unite normally squabbling Arab leaders behind both
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Israeli Cabinet voted to force Syria's
hand by pledging to unilaterally withdraw from southern Lebanon if
no peace agreement is reached by July. That pledge has unsettled
Syrian and Lebanese leaders, who have called it a devious attempt
to pressure them, but there has been no word yet on a resumption of
the Syria-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians and Israelis, whose negotiations were suspended
after the Syrian talks broke down, have been negotiating on and off
for nearly seven years. One of the main sticking points has been
the transfer of land in the Israeli-occupied West Bank to the
Palestinians, as set out in an interim agreement seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The next transfer was supposed to put another 6.1 percent of the
territory in the hands of the Palestinian Authority. If it happens,
Palestinians would control, either completely or in conjunction
with Israel, about 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than desert and thinly populated areas, as Israel had
proposed in the last round of talks, Arafat has demanded that the
next handover include land close to the disputed city of Jerusalem,
including the small Arab suburb of Abu Dis on a hillside
overlooking the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   The status of Jerusalem _ which Israel claims as its
nondivisible capital _ is supposed to be negotiated as part of the
final peace deal, but the shadow of that emotional issue hangs over
much of the calculations in the short-term.
</P>
<P>
   The land question will likely rear up again once the two sides
return to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian and Israeli officials have suggested that Israel
would offer 10 percent of the West Bank land, out of which Arafat
could choose the 6.1 percent that he wants.
</P>
<P>
   But it may still not be the populated areas near Jerusalem that
the Palestinians seek.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister David Levy said Israel had not committed to
turn over territory closer to Arab urban centers as an incentive to
bring the Palestinians back to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such promise,'' he told Israel Radio. ``Naturally,
they have their wishes about a number of revisions. The prime
minister heard them and is to formulate a proposal that he will
present it to the Cabinet.'' Arafat has demanded as well that
Israel transfer more land in advance of a final settlement, as
called for in the Oslo accord, but Barak, like his predecessor,
Benjamin Netanyahu, balked at giving up more land outside of the
terms of a final treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
