<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-GEORGEWBUSH-BIOGRAPHI     03-08 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGEWBUSH-BIOGRAPHIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GOV LOVE HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``W: Revenge of the Bush Dynasty'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Elizabeth Mitchell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion, $22.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrub: The Short But Happy Political Life of George W. Bush'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Molly Ivins with Lou Dubose &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $19.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Texas Gov. George W. Bush has discovered, the world loves to
skewer front-runners _ at the polls, in conversation and, most
assuredly, in print.
</P>
<P>
   We have already seen some books supposedly providing the
definitive literary look at Bush. Bill Minutaglio's ``First Son''
was reasonably objective; ``Fortunate Son's'' author, J.H.
Hatfield, who turned out to be an ex-con, floated ``deep source''
rumors about a Bush drug arrest that, upon investigation, didn't
seem to hold up. (Publisher St. Martin's press pulled ``Fortunate
Son'' from bookstore shelves.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush even weighed in with his own book: ``A Charge to Keep,''
which was ghost-written by a Bush staff member and naturally put
its subject in the best possible light.
</P>
<P>
   ``W'' and ``Shrub'' are, in their respective ways, extensions of
what has been offered before, except for the governor's own
version. Elizabeth Mitchell, former executive editor of ``George''
magazine, and Molly Ivins, superstar columnist of the
``Star-Telegram,'' examine the Republican presidential candidate
and find him wanting. They agree that Bush is a reasonably nice
fellow, but lacking intellectual depth and real moral commitment to
anyone other than the economic elite. They examine his oil business
and major-league baseball deals, determining that he gained maximum
financial advantage with minimal financial risk in both. It's fair
to say Bush supporters will not be pleased with either book.
</P>
<P>
   But ``W'' and ``Shrub'' have entirely different tones; it is
obvious that, except for ghostwritten autobiographies, books
published about presidential candidates in midcampaign are likely
to be critical. Criticism, or the hint of scandal, sells so much
better than praise.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``W'' comes across more as medium-researched magazine
fodder than extensive dirt-digging. Mitchell's magazine background
_ she's worked for ``SPIN,'' ``Glamour'' and ``Conde Nast
Traveler'' as well as ``George'' _ is evident in every skimpy
paragraph. In 334 pages, she attempts to chronicle the entire Bush
family history, starting when George kissed Barbara on the cheek
after escorting her to the prom at Andover. To cram everything in,
she can't use up too many words in analysis. More pages are
dedicated to Bush's successful race against Ann Richards than are
devoted to his performance as governor. When Mitchell quotes former
Bob Dole campaign worker Scott Reed as saying ``Half the people who
are for (Bush) can't tell you exactly why,'' that's as close as she
gets to in-depth opinionizing.
</P>
<P>
   Ivins, on the other hand, doesn't pretend to be objective about
the governor. In the introduction to ``Shrub,'' Ivins and co-author
Lou Dubose (editor of the ``Texas Observer'') cattily note ``if, at
the end of this short book, you find W. Bush's political resume a
little light, don't blame us. There's really not much there. We
have been looking for six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, for 179 pages, the Ivins/Dubose team takes every shot
possible: at Bush as a student, businessman, and politician. At
book's end, the authors conclude that Bush's ``reform'' policy
``means the end of democracy and a direct leap into oligopoly, rule
by the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrub'' comes off as an extended Molly Ivins column, which
ought to make it easy to decide whether you want to read it. Unlike
Mitchell and just about every other author of campaign-driven
political biographies, Ivins isn't trying to fool you about how she
feels; she's openly attempting to woo you to the anti-Bush side.
There's something to be said for that kind of honesty. Even Bush
supporters will have to admit that she and Dubose aren't being
sneaky. And they attempt to back up their one-liners with facts and
figures, though Bushites will argue that numbers can be twisted to
support flawed opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``W'' offers the only positive glimpses of Bush; Mitchell
includes a few touching lines about how, when one of Bush's West
Texas oil companies, Spectrum 7, was being acquired by a larger
outfit, Bush got on the phone and stayed there until he found jobs
for all his employees who otherwise would have been unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ``W'' nor ``Shrub'' will make any Bush supporters or
detractors switch camps. The latter title is more entertaining
reading than the former. Mitchell's approach is less extreme than
the Ivins/Dubose team's. We can be certain Bush won't read either
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
