<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-CREMINS-LOOKBACK-     03-08 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CREMINS-LOOKBACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fond farewell for Georgia Tech's Bobby Cremins
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As his visitor arrives, Bobby Cremins is furiously writing note
cards, trying to respond to a stack of letters about three inches
thick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's only two days' worth,'' Cremins said, pointing to the
letters. ``It's been incredible. If I didn't have all those
skeletons in my closet, I could run for public office.''
</P>
<P>
   The mail, most of it gushing with affection and appreciation,
represents just one of the tributes that have poured in since
Cremins announced that he was stepping down as Georgia Tech's
basketball coach after 19 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After making his decision, Cremins hoped to quietly coach his
final games and slip off to the golf course and the beach with his
wife, Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance. Cremins' friends in college basketball want his
final days as an ACC coach to be memorable.
</P>
<P>
   After making his announcement on Feb. 18, Cremins spent the rest
of the day and night on the telephone with friends. At 11 p.m.,
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to watch our game tomorrow,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike, don't say anything or do anything special,'' Cremins
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just watch the game,'' Krzyzewski said, and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when Krzyzewski walked onto the court at N.C.
State, he had abandoned his usual game attire for Cremins'
trademark blue shirt and yellow tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really touched me,'' Cremins said.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest coach Dave Odom honored Cremins and his wife before
the Tech-Wake game on Feb. 27. Two Wake Forest fans approached
Carolyn Cremins to say how much they will miss her and Bobby and to
thank them for how much they had done for the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, at North Carolina, Cremins asked Bill
Guthridge not to do anything special before the game. So, Guthridge
and former coach Dean Smith showed up at Tech's shoot-around that
morning and presented Cremins with a new putter.
</P>
<P>
   His former players have been calling. Dennis Scott, Kenny
Anderson and Brian Oliver, who led the Yellow Jackets to the Final
Four in 1990, were among the first. Oliver called from Italy. James
Forrest called from Greece. Karl Brown called from England. Matt
Harpring checks in from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been shocked at the response,'' Carolyn said. ``I knew
people liked and respected Bobby, but I figured we would just get a
couple of letters from some close friends. Neither of us ever
imagined anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, it's been kind of embarrassing,'' Bobby
Cremins said. ``I don't think too many losing coaches go out like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the point, his friends say. During 19 years in the
close-knit ACC, Cremins touched too many lives in a positive
fashion ever to be considered a losing coach _ no matter what the
recent record says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby will always be one of my favorites,'' former ACC
Commissioner Gene Corrigan said. ``The guy is genuine and likable.
I've never met another coach who didn't like Bobby. In a profession
like this, there are not many guys you can say that about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another tribute awaits Cremins when Georgia Tech faces Florida
State tonight in the first round of the ACC Tournament at the
Charlotte Coliseum. He remembers the warm ovation the Charlotte
fans gave Harpring in his final game in 1997, but isn't certain
what to expect tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Tech wins the tournament, Cremins' last game as an ACC
coach will be in Charlotte. It was also the site of his last game
as a college player.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, in the old Charlotte Coliseum on Independence
Boulevard, Cremins experienced his lowest moment as a player. Frank
McGuire's South Carolina team was good enough to contend for the
national championship, but in those days only the ACC Tournament
winner got a bid to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina was upset in the ACC finals by N.C. State,
suddenly ending Cremins' college career. Thirty years later, his
coaching career, at least for now, probably will end in the same
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty incredible, everything that has happened since then,''
Cremins said.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: The beach
</P>
<P>
   Cremins has made no immediate plans for his life after
basketball, other than heading for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get a beach chair, a double vodka tonic and watch
the NCAA Tournament,'' said Cremins, who hasn't ruled out a return
to coaching but says he's open to anything.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have urged him to take at least a year off, and Cremins
is inclined to do so. He remembers attending a luncheon with
then-Georgia coach Ron Jirsa, who was under fire in Athens. Cremins
was 51. Jirsa was in his late 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked horrible, and in comes Ron and he looked worse,''
Cremins said. ``Both of us were in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Georgia State coach Lefty Driesell entered the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefty comes be-bopping in there. He's in his 60s, and he looks
better than both of us put together,'' Cremins said. ``He told me
that taking a year off was the best thing that ever happen to him.
So maybe that's what I need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins' $1.5 million settlement from Georgia Tech will allow
him that freedom. But close friends say that taking time off could
be tough for Cremins. This was his 25th consecutive year of
coaching, follwing 15 years as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, it's going to hit Bobby that it's over,'' said
Kevin Cantwell, Cremins' assistant at Tech for the past 14 years
and at Appalachian State for six years before that. ``He's doing OK
now, but it's not going to be easy. The guy's life has been
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball has been my passion for so long, since I was like
12 years old,'' Cremins said. ``Can I replace it with something
else? That's what I've got to find out. I still think there is
something else out there for me. Maybe I can use this time to
figure out what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins says he is ``at peace'' with his decision but won't
totally relax until Georgia Tech gets another coach and his
assistants find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When those two things happen, I'm going to have as much fun as
I can,'' he said. ``But I think I need a break. I know I have to
get off the merry-go-round for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Cremins has suggested broadcasting as her husband's next
endeavor. Some people think that his unusual style and wit could
make Cremins the next Al McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember two years ago we were in New York for a game
against St. John's,'' she said. ``Bobby had a bunch of friends up,
and we were all going to go out to dinner after the game. But then
we lost, and Bobby didn't want to do anything. I told him if he was
in broadcasting, he could enjoy basketball, and it wouldn't matter
who wins or loses. What a nice life that would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins said he has not decided if he and his wife will continue
to live in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay in Atlanta at least six months or a year, but after
that I don't know,'' he said. ``We love Atlanta, but I wonder if we
should just get away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby doesn't want to be perceived as hanging around and
getting in the way of the new coach (at Georgia Tech),'' Carolyn
said. ``I love living in Atlanta and would like to stay. We'll take
some time and see how things work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Dream
</P>
<P>
   Cremins has done a lot of thinking since Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   He has thought about the players whose lives he has touched in
19 season at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   He has thought about the friends he's made in coaching, and how
those friends have supported him.
</P>
<P>
   He has thought about winning his first ACC Tournament in 1985,
and how he knew then that he had arrived as a coach. From then on,
Dean Smith and the rest of the ACC would have to take seriously the
funny-talking guy with the prematurely silver hair.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Cremins has thought about his parents. Robert and
Margaret Cremins came to America from Ireland as teenagers. They
met in New York, returned to Ireland, got married and then came
back to the States. They wanted their children to be Americans.
Robert Joseph Cremins Jr. was born on the Fourth of July, 1947. You
can't get much more American than that.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been gone for a while. He wishes they could be in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents spent their whole lives drilling two things into
me,'' he said. ``That was the Catholic religion and the American
Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins' parents would point to the picture of John F. Kennedy
that hung prominently in their Bronx home and talk more about the
American Dream. If that young Catholic boy can become president,
they told Bobby, you can do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young I never understood what they meant about the
American Dream,'' Cremins said. ``Now I do. Thanks to basketball,
I've lived the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Cremins dropped out of college and became a
bellhop at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel. At the urging of his father,
Cremins went back to school, got two degrees and embarked on an
extraodinary career.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the 52-year-old Cremins prepares to walk away from
basketball, the central focus of his life for 40 years, he is
financially secure and universally liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years from now, it won't matter how many games he won,''
Carolyn Cremins said. ``What will matter is how many people loved
him and cared about him. In that respect, I'd say he's a pretty
lucky guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
