</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ARABS-HOUSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI HIGH COURT RULES ARAB COUPLE CAN LIVE IN JEWISH AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for story slugged ISRAEL-MIXED-COUPLES on NY-BUDGET.) 
(bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that an
Israeli Arab couple could not be barred from living in a community
built solely for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark decision after more than four years of hearings was
hailed as an important step toward equality for Israel's 1 million
Arab citizens. It overturned longstanding policies intended to
promote exclusively Jewish settlements in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important ruling in the history of the
Supreme Court on the issue of equal rights for Arab citizens of
Israel, and it is a big step forward in the struggle for full
equality,'' said Dan Yakir, one of two lawyers from the Association
for Civil Rights in Israel who argued the case.
</P>
<P>
   Brought by an Israeli Arab couple who had been refused
permission to buy a plot or home in a Jewish cooperative settlement
in northern Israel, the case raised basic questions about whether
Israel could be both a Jewish and a democratic state, ideals
enshrined in its declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not accept the conception that the values of the State
of Israel as a Jewish state justify discrimination by the state
between citizens on the basis of religion or nationality,'' wrote
Judge Aharon Barak, the chief justice, in a ruling endorsed by
three of his colleagues on the five-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is not allowed to discriminate directly on the basis
of religion or nationality in allocation of state lands,'' Barak
added. ``Neither may the state discriminate indirectly'' in such
allocations.
</P>
<P>
   The case was brought by Adel and Iman Kaadan, an Israeli Arab
couple living in the town of Baqa al-Gharbiya, who had been barred
from joining Katzir, a cooperative Jewish settlement nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The bylaws of the settlement effectively bar membership by
Arabs, and the land in Katzir, developed by the quasi-governmental
Jewish Agency _ founded before Israel was established to promote
Jewish immigration and settlement in British-ruled Palestine _ was
allocated for use by Jews only.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state was not allowed by law to allocate state land to the
Jewish Agency to establish the settlement of Katzir on the basis of
discrimination between Jews and non-Jews,'' Judge Barak wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaadans, who have three children, said they wanted to move
to Katzir to escape the sewage in the streets and the overcrowded
schools of their town, which suffers from the neglect typical of
many Israeli Arab communities long lacking adequate budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers in Katzir raised objections, arguing that the Kaadans
would not blend into the social fabric of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a social fit,'' Dubi Sandrov, chairman of the
local council, asserted after Wednesday's ruling. ``There has to be
a binding glue in the first stages of the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Agency argued that its mission remained to settle
Jews across the country, especially in areas where the Jewish
population is sparse. In a brief to the court, it called Katzir ``a
link in a chain of outposts intended to safeguard the expanses of
Israel for the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Salai Meridor, the agency chairman, said after reading the court
decision that Katzir is in a part of Israel near the West Bank that
is heavily populated by Arabs, and that a Jewish presence there was
necessary to prevent an erosion of Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue is not equality,'' Meridor said. ``We're all
for equality. The question is how we ensure equality while also
making sure that areas with a massive Arab majority near the
territory of an emerging Palestinian entity will remain part of the
State of Israel. Along with equality, Israel must safeguard its
national and security interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Barakeh, an Israeli Arab legislator who has submitted a
bill to dismantle the Jewish Agency and the Jewish National Fund,
which also promotes land acquisition and settlement by Jews, said
the ruling had far-reaching implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unprecedented decision that undermines the basis of
the Jewish Agency as a body built on discrimination,'' he said.
``State land cannot be allocated to any body for purposes of
apartheid and racism. This moves Israel toward being a democratic
state for all its citizens, and not an ethnic democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ruling was read, the Kaadans embraced their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know today that this is a state of all its citizens,'' said
Mr. Kaadan, 44, a nurse. ``The meaning of this is enough
discrimination, enough racism _ give coexistence a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
