u i BC-CLINTON-SOUTHASIA-NYT     03-08 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOUTHASIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA IRRITATED BY CLINTON'S DECISION TO VISIT PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Indian officials reacted Wednesday with
understated disgruntlement to President Clinton's decision to call
briefly on their adversary, Pakistan, after a five-day tour of
India this month. Pakistani officials were happy and relieved.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation, India's prime minister, Atal Behari
Vajpayee, warned Clinton on Tuesday night that Pakistan's military
rulers would use his decision to claim legitimacy for last year's
coup _ and that is what happened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the army chief who has ruled Pakistan
since the Oct. 12 coup, told a Reuters reporter in Islamabad that
Clinton's decision ``vindicates the legitimacy of my government's
stand and gives credence to our aim to put things right in our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision came after weeks of infighting in his
administration. White House officials said the purpose of the trip
was not to sanction the coup, but to deliver a message to the
military rulers that they should restore democracy, ratchet down
the tensions with India and ban an Islamic fundamentalist group
that the United States has accused of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   While Vajpayee was not surprised by the decision, which had been
expected, and though he is aware that India will still be the main
event on Clinton's South Asia trip, he was nonetheless displeased.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have campaigned to isolate Pakistan since an Indian
Airlines commercial flight was hijacked Dec. 24 with what India
maintained was Pakistani military sponsorship. Indian diplomats
have been pressing the United States to declare Pakistan a sponsor
of terrorism and lobbying the president to bypass Pakistan on his
trip.
</P>
<P>
   When the president finally made his decision Tuesday, he called
Vajpayee to break the news before announcing it publicly. H.K. Dua,
a spokesman for the prime minister, said Vajpayee told the
president that his visit to Pakistan ``would give the military
regime a signal of support.'' Still, Vajpayee assured Clinton that
he would be warmly welcomed here.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Pakistan, which is smaller and economically weaker
than India, sought to put a bright face on the president's decision
to stop for a few hours in Islamabad. They said they believed that
Clinton would use his influence to help them resolve their
half-century-old dispute with India over the territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good feeling that President Clinton will urge India
to also take the path of negotiations and a peaceful resolution to
the Kashmir dispute,'' Tariq Altaf, a spokesman for the Pakistani
Foreign Office, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton has repeatedly stated that the United States will
not mediate the Kashmir conflict until India welcomes its
intervention _ something India has adamantly refused to do _ he has
also repeatedly said that South Asia is one of the most dangerous
places on earth because of India and Pakistan's festering, violent
clash over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Javed Jabbar, an adviser to Musharraf on national affairs, told
reporters in Multan, a city in the Punjab, that the talks between
Clinton and Pakistani officials would focus on Kashmir and other
basic issues. He called the president's decision to visit
``important for peace and progress in South Asia and it justifies
our stand.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was a blow to India's prime minister, who ``has
been continuously trying to malign Pakistan and encourage the U.S.
to declare it a terrorist state.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Pakistani press also painted the president's
decision as a victory over India. The News, an influential
newspaper that was formerly edited by the military regime's
ambassador to the United States, called Clinton's decision a
triumph for the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Washington has had a business-as-usual attitude toward
Pakistan's military rulers on the core issues at least, doubts were
persisting as to where exactly did it place the new political
arrangement in Pakistan,'' the paper said. ``President Clinton's
visit will, to a considerable degree, remove these doubts and will
help Musharraf stand on firmer ground internationally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
