<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TRADE-CHINA-HNS &LR;      03-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES PASSAGE OF CHINESE TRADE LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton formally asked Congress on
Wednesday to grant China permanent U.S. trading privileges, a move
that if approved could pave the way for the communist regime in
Beijing to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at John Hopkins University in Baltimore, Clinton
said establishing permanent trade ties would not only help open
long-closed Chinese markets to U.S. goods, but would hasten reforms
inside China, particularly in the area of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for approval look good in the Senate, where at
least 60 senators are expected to support it despite concerns about
human rights abuses in China and criticism from organized labor
that it will cost U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The labor and human rights issues are expected to provoke a
bitter fight in the House, however, especially among Democrats,
many of whom will side with organized labor in opposing permanent
normal trade relations, known as PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough to get the votes,'' said China trade
supporter House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. But he
predicted it will pass if Clinton can convince reluctant Democrats
to back it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton characterized it as a national security issue of
historic proportions. ``It is clearly in our national interest. It
represents the most significant opportunity that we have had to
create positive change in China since the 1970s, when President
Nixon first went there,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can work to pull China in the right direction or we can
turn our backs and almost certainly push it in the wrong
direction,'' he added, calling on lawmakers to choose engagement
with China over isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged Congress to act on legislation granting the PNTR
status by early summer to prevent the issue from becoming embroiled
in the politics of this year's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said the Republican leadership, which is united behind the
PNTR legislation, will do what it can to hold rank-and-file
Republicans together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to and expect to see us pass it,'' Armey told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
described the PNTR legislation as ``a good first step'' in helping
to open more of China's markets to U.S. exports ranging from
agricultural goods to cars and telecommunications. He called it a
``bread and butter issue for American workers, farmers and their
families'' that would also result in lower prices at home.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, China will no longer have to undergo an annual
review by Congress and the administration in order to have its
normal trade status renewed each year. By becoming a permanent
trading partner, China would be guaranteed the same low-tariff
access to American markets that nearly every other country enjoys
now.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent U.S. trading privileges would also help China in its
quest to become a member of the World Trade Organization, which is
instrumental in setting international trade standards. China,
however, would still have to win agreements from the European Union
and other WTO members before being invited into the global trade
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at John Hopkins, Clinton emphasized the importance
of establishing a permanent trade relationship with Beijing, saying
it will enable the nation to ``export products without exporting
jobs.'' He said the agreement worked out last year with China and
incorporated in the PNTR legislation would require Beijing to open
its consumer market, the largest in the world, ``in unprecedented
ways'' to U.S. goods and services. In return, he said all the
United States has promised to do ``is maintain the present access''
China now has to markets here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress passes PNTR, we reap these rewards. If Congress
rejects it, our competitors reap these rewards,'' Clinton said,
adding that Congress ``must understand the consequences of saying
no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't sell our products to China, someone else will step
into the breach and we'll spend the next 20 years wondering why in
the world we handed over the benefits we negotiated to other
people,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to boost congressional support, Clinton has allied
himself with a coalition of U.S. business interests with trade ties
to China, including the Business Roundtable organization and
National Chamber of Commerce. The coalition has already started
running television and radio commercials, warning that the upcoming
votes on PNTR amount to a decision about whether the United States
will pursue a policy of protectionism or engagement.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, organized labor and environmental groups,
traditional allies of Clinton and the Democratic Party, are leading
the fight against PNTR for China. They argue that it will likely
result in the loss of U.S. jobs and hurt the environment because it
does not require Beijing to adopt tougher labor laws or
environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders are warning some lawmakers that they could lose
union support in the November elections if they vote to approve
PNTR for China.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
