<SLUG> BC-AETNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHEASTERN ASSET MANAGEMENT ACQUIRES 6 PERCENT STAKE IN AETNA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Calif., Ill.)  By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southeastern Asset Management Inc., a money management company
based in Memphis, said Wednesday that it had acquired a 6 percent
stake in Aetna Inc. for $444 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Southeastern paid $52.46 each, on average, for most of
its 8.5 million shares between Jan. 6 and last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna rose $2.9375, to $54.125, on the New York Stock
Exchange Wednesday on the news of Southeastern's purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which slid to a 12-month low of $38.50 three weeks
ago, has rebounded since Aetna, the nation's biggest health
insurer, confirmed last week that it was considering a possible
buyout from WellPoint Health Networks, a California-based national
managed-care company, and the ING Group, a Dutch financial services
and insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Wellpoint and ING said they might offer $70 a share if they were
satisfied with Aetna's prospects after examining the company's
books.
</P>
<P>
   William Donaldson, who replaced Richard Huber as chief executive
of Aetna in a boardroom revolt on Feb. 25, has been meeting with
investment bankers and other advisers to consider strategies for
dealing with several trouble spots in Aetna's health care business
and other lines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that there was no guarantee that Wellpoint and
ING would actually offer $70. No competing bids have emerged for
the health care units, although several prospective buyers are said
to be interested in Aetna's international and financial management
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern, which manages the Longleaf Partners Funds, had
$13.4 billion under management on Jan. 21. Andrew McCarroll, a
spokesman for Southeastern, declined to comment yesterday on the
SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Southeastern's chairman, O. Mason Hawkins, looked
for stocks that were selling at 60 percent or less of their real
value, as measured by his research. By that formula, he seemed to
be valuing Aetna shares at more than $85 each, said Christopher
Traulsen, an analyst with Morningstar Inc., the investment research
firm in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must think that a transaction is going to take place,''
said Lori M. Price, a securities analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q. But Traulsen
said that Southeastern typically stuck by its investments for long
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern said in the SEC filing that it had paid as little
as $38.935 for Aetna shares on Feb. 18. Undeterred by the rise
after the Wellpoint-ING offer emerged, it bought 35,000 more shares
last week at $60.438 each. Shares were trading as high as $99.875
last May.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern said in the filing that its strategy was to
identify and buy stock in ``undervalued companies'' and then hold
discussions with executives of the companies and other interested
parties to suggest ways to make the shares reflect ``the company's
true intrinsic value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
