A0982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      03-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CLOSE HIGHER AS BARGAIN-SEEKERS ARE ACTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks staged a modest rebound Wednesday, overcoming
early jitters to close broadly higher as oil prices eased and a
Federal Reserve survey found inflation still limited despite
intensified pressure on wages.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain seekers scooped up shares of drug and other depressed
issues, including industrial stalwarts like Alcoa and International
Paper, after two days of battering that had knocked 571 points off
the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The index closed 60.50 points, or 0.62 percent, higher at
9,856.53, but was still nearly 16 percent below the record it set
in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also turned in a solid performance, with the
Nasdaq market gaining 49.42 points, or 1.02 percent, to 4,897.26,
just short of its peak last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting a little more rational and rotating into
companies that have been annihilated'' in the correction of
so-called ``old economy'' stocks, said Donna Van Vlack, chief
trader at Brandywine Asset Management. ``A lot of babies have been
thrown out with a lot of bathwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, suffering regulatory fears and, in some cases,
patent expirations, surged with the aid of recommendations from at
least three Wall Street houses. Bristol-Myers gained 4 1/4 to 47
3/4, Schering-Plough 3 5/16 to 33 13/16 and Pfizer 2 7/16 to 32
7/16. Others followed along, including Warner-Lambert, up 5 13/16
to 86 13/16; American Home Products, up 3 7/8 to 45 3/8, and Merck,
up 2 7/8 to 56 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines benefited from a sharp decline in the price of oil
after Saudi Arabia and Iran sent a strong signal of significant
production increases. Continental and Delta climbed nearly four
points each while AMR, parent of American, and U.S. Airways each
gained more than three.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Atlantic-Richfield, which gained 5 3/8, to 81, on
seemingly improved prospects for its acquisition by BP Amoco, most
major oil companies gave up fractions of a point following big
runups, but those engaged mainly in exploration fell sharply.
Schlumberger and B.J. Services lost more than five points each
while Halliburton lost more than four.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continued to favor companies offering shares to the
public for the first time. Wednesday's star was Crayfish, a
Japanese company that provides e-mail hosting services for
businesses. Its 4.35 million American depository receipts, priced
at $24.50, began trading at 96 and soared as high as 166 before
closing at 126 on volume of 7.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rebound in industrial shares, like Alcoa's 2 7/16 gain
to 67 3/8 and International Paper's 2 41/64 gain to 36 1/64, ``we
continue to think the tech stocks will lead'' the market, said Todd
Salamone, research director at Schaeffer's Investment Research in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that Cincinnati-based Procter &AMP; Gamble, which
plunged nearly 31 percent on Tuesday after warning of lower
profits, would skid further, along with other consumer stocks that
remain fairly expensive by historic standards. The stock fell 3
1/16 Wednesday to 57 15/16, less than half the 118 3/8 at which it
traded at its peak on Jan. 12. More than 37 million shares changed
hands compared with 68 million on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index advanced 11.08 points, or 0.82
percent, to 1,366.70, with 268 issues up, 218 down and 14
unchanged. Oracle was one of the biggest contributors, jumping 8
3/16 to 83 1/8, but other technology stocks were also strong. JDS
Uniphase, however, fell 11 3/4 after disclosure that Goldman Sachs
sold 816,819 shares last month.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues outnumbered
advancing ones, 1,537 to 1,445 on heavy volume of 1.22 billion
shares, just below Tuesday's _ the second-busiest on record. New
52-week lows swamped new highs by 253 to 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
