<P>
   POP-GROWTH _ Despite more than 2 million defections, California
continued to lead the nation in population growth from 1990-99, the
Census Bureau is expected to reported Thursday. A wave of
immigrants and a baby boom fueled a statewide gain of 3,333,694
residents in the 1990s. During the same period, the Census reported
that 2,170,790 Californians left the state for Las Vegas, Phoenix
and other U.S. destinations. More than half of those defectors were
from Los Angeles County. This is the last Census report to be
issued by the agency before it officially begins its 2000 count on
April 1. By Bill Hillburg.
