<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS &LR;      03-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS PERMANENT TRADE STATUS FOR CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Touching off an election-year battle that could
divide his own political party, President Clinton asked Congress
Wednesday to give China the same trade privileges that the United
States gives to nearly all other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent lawmakers a bill that would eliminate the annual
votes on whether to give China favorable trading terms. Congress
has always extended the favored status for China, but the annual
exercise gives critics a chance to attack China's human-rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Congress must approve the permanent trade privileges to
implement a tariff-cutting treaty that the Clinton administration
negotiated with China last year. The vote is also a key step toward
allowing China to enter the World Trade Organization, though the
WTO itself, and not Congress, has ultimate say over whether China
joins the international trading body.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote against (permanent trade relations) will cost America
jobs as our competitors in Europe, Asia, and elsewhere capture the
Chinese market that we otherwise would have served,'' Clinton told
a friendly audience at Johns Hopkins University's international
studies school.
</P>
<P>
   He said better trade relations will pay more than economic
dividends. The vote in Congress offers ``the most significant
opportunity that we have had to create positive change in China
since the 1970s, when President Nixon first went there, and later
in the decade when President Carter normalized relations,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am working as hard as I can to convince Congress and the
American people to seize this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts businesses exported goods worth $235 million to
China in 1998, double the value of 1993. China ranked as the
state's 17th-largest export market, according to the US Department
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Trade issues have been contentious in Congress in recent years.
Lawmakers have refused to give Clinton expanded powers to negotiate
trade treaties, even though four previous presidents had those same
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, prospects for the China measure have weakened
recently, as lawmakers reacted angrily to Chinese threats last
month to use military force against Taiwan. Those threats and other
signs of weakening support prompted Clinton to bring the measure to
Congress more quickly than the White House had planned.
</P>
<P>
   The issue could be particularly difficult for Democrats, who
must choose between supporting Clinton and siding with organized
labor, which opposes normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture, we still have some leverage associated with
the annual status review,'' said David Smith, director of public
policy for the AFL-CIO. ``We have a country that is without any
question the world's biggest violator of human rights. . . . Why on
earth is the appropriate response to this behavior to say, `We'll
give you a blank check and grant you normal relations?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Business groups say it is vital for lawmakers to approve the
measure so that the new trade treaty takes effect. That treaty
would sharply cut tariffs on a variety of products and make it
easier for US telecommunications, insurance, banking, and service
providers to reach Chinese consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking out all the stops on this thing,'' said William
Morley, chief trade lobbyist for the US Chamber of Commerce. ``This
is a top priority for the business community. It goes to the bottom
line of jobs and opportunities for our workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate historically has been more supportive of trade deals
than has the House. The House Democratic leader, Representative
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, has so far stated no position on the
China measure. The number two House Democrat, David Bonior of
Michigan, opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Clinton must do more to win support within his
own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're not going to get any help from Democrats in the
House unless the president gets the votes,'' said House majority
leader Dick Armey, Republican of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that voting against normal trade relations ``won't
free a single prisoner or create a single job in America or
reassure a single American ally in Asia. It will simply empower the
most rigid anti-democratic elements in the Chinese government. . .
. Our friends and allies would wonder why, after 30 years of
pushing China in the right direction, we turned our backs, now that
they finally appear to be willing to take us up on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
