<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TRINIDAD-CARNIVAL-REH     03-08 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRINIDAD-CARNIVAL-REHAB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRINIDAD, TAKING CARE OF THOSE WHO TAKE CARNIVAL TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad _ The half-dressed Carnival masqueraders
who had flowed through the streets like a glittering, feathery
river were gone Wednesday morning. Gone, too, were the body-rocking
calypso rhythms that had turned the city into a giant boom box.
</P>
<P>
   For Steve Richards, the worry was not what was gone, but who had
vanished. He runs Rebirth House, a drug rehabilitation program that
operates four recovery homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today what I have to do is a damage assessment,'' he said as
he prepared to survey his group's residences and see if anyone had
forgotten the 12 Steps of Recovery amid the dance steps of the
party that had just rolled through town. ``Carnival season brings
casualties. Those who don't resist that festive mood. The
temptation. They just paid the penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnival season, the weeks-long pre-Lenten party that was
crowned with two days of dancing and drinking this week, is not an
easy time for Richards or his 69 charges. He spent much of it with
some of them, running a safe haven in his group's downtown office,
where they watched the party glide by the front door with a sign
reading ``But for the Grace of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people celebrate Carnival without overdoing it, relishing
the steel-band symphonies, laughing at the bawdy and politically
charged calypso songs or preening and prancing in extravagant
costumes _ all things that are rightly a point of Trinidadian
cultural pride.
</P>
<P>
   Some lose themselves in the sensual smorgasbord, just as they do
at Carnival in Rio or Mardi Gras in New Orleans, before ushering in
the solemn season and looking for repentance with a cross of ashes
smudged on their foreheads on Ash Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a keen awareness among people like Richards
that the morning after, and the months after, bring their own
consequences that are both a reminder of mortal frailty and an
opportunity for new beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after Carnival it takes a while before admissions pick
up,'' Richards said. ``You realize, when you're an addict and your
addictions come again, you pick up where you left off. A woman
offers you a drink _ you want to prove yourself. The ego thing.
`How can I refuse a drink from a woman?'''
</P>
<P>
   At the Port of Spain General Hospital on Monday afternoon, the
throbbing music blasting from huge speakers strapped to the
Carnival trucks filtered into the emergency room, where doctors
treated everything from sprains to stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   One of those on duty, Dr. Joseph Olowe, said many of the
injuries were alcohol-related. Although the real rush of patients
comes after midnight, a different rush will come in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Carnival there is a high incidence of being free
sexually,'' he said. ``In two or three months' time the abortion
rate will go up. In nine months the birth rate also increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting concern over infection with HIV, the virus that
causes AIDS, and over unwanted pregnancies, public health groups
prepared for the season with an education campaign, and banners
were unfurled along many streets reading: ``Sex? Latex!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to see what kind of response the public has toward
that kind of awareness,'' Olowe said. ``That is beyond anybody's
control. You do the best to educate people. But at the point of the
decision in terms of moral practice, that is left to different
people's will.''
</P>
<P>
   At Rebirth House, counselors offered extra reminders and advice
to those who wanted to go out and join the festivities. They were
urged to attend more 12-step meetings and to steer clear of old
drinking and drugging buddies. Those who did not get to go out on
their own were still able to ``lime,'' or hang out, at the downtown
office and cheer the passing parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know if you lime with us, you won't have any beer,'' said
Vincent Megaries, a project coordinator at Rebirth House. ``They
can go to the park and see the bands and come back here to keep
themselves strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was difficult for people like Stephen Dey, who had just
joined the program after a two-month cocaine binge. Last week he
hit the number and spent his small windfall on cocaine, leaving him
exhausted and suicidal. Three days sober on Tuesday, he quietly sat
inside the shade of the group's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be here,'' he said. ``I stand out there and
people pass by, and I can smell the marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that the alcohol outside did not unnerve him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting urges as such for drugs,'' he said. ``Part of
my addiction is a sexual thing. You're seeing all these women out
there gyrating.''
</P>
<P>
   To learn how to enjoy these events and stay sober is the point
of the group's mission. Richards relishes the Carnival, but it is
more important to him that he show the residents that life
continues without drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dance and hug and kiss the women, but it's like a hobby, and
I know my limits,'' Richards said. ``No matter what you do, you got
to live outside there. You can't cloister yourself. You got to deal
with it out there. The world is not going to stop just because
you're a recovering person.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar belief inspired Bishop David Ibeleme, a Pentecostal
minister, to offer a Christian alternative to the sometimes lewd
calypso lyrics that float through the air this season.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year, he sponsored a ``Gospelypso'' concert at his
church last week, with songs that were more morally uplifitng.
Religion, he said, must exist in a cultural context, even if some
of his more conservative counterparts look warily at his love of
calypso.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity is not in a cultural vacuum,'' he said. ``It has
to embrace the culture of the people. That is the only way to
fulfill the Scripture that says, `Every tribe and tongue must come
unto him.'''
</P>
<P>
   While he knew that not everyone would attend the concert _ some
200 people showed up this year _ he held out the hope that the
message would penetrate even the hardest-partying people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is within the next few months after Carnival,
it tends to be easier for people to get to know God,'' he said.
``They done what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether out of repentance or respect, many people _ including
more than a few revelers _ filed into the Roman Catholic Cathedral
of the Immaculate Conception this morning to receive ashes. In the
weeks before, mainline religious groups urged the faithful to enjoy
the Carnival with dignity and respect for others. After all, to
lose yourself in joy does not mean you lose your soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something deeply spiritual about that abandon,'' said
the Rev. Christian Pereira, the cathedral's administrator. ``While
they abandon themselves to music and revelry, time does not matter.
You have in the spiritual life an abandoning of yourself to God,
giving yourself totally to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The season, he said, is a great leveler, when rich and poor and
people of all races unite, first in celebration and later in
solemnity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for a healthy society,'' he said. ``They say we do
not have that many people in mental hospitals here than in
countries that do not have Carnival.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
