<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-McCAIN (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says
that while he had gotten ``whipped,'' he has proven he can come
back from the brink of defeat. Meanwhile, Sen. John McCain returns
to his Arizona mountain home to consider his next move. While he
has not canceled Thursday's campaign stops in Colorado, he also has
left open the possibility of a third-party bid. By JOHN GONZALEZ
and CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MARRIAGE (Undated) _ Homosexuals and lesbians were facing
an uphill battle on an anti-gay marriage referendum in California.
But their fate was sealed when Republican presidential candidate
John McCain attacked religious conservatives, sending them to the
polls in droves. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH (Undated) _ Exit polls from Tuesday's national primary
paint a troubling picture for George W. Bush in the general
election, but it's a not a perfect scenario for Al Gore, either. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-2000 (Undated) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley has scheduled
a news conference Thursday, presumably to drop out of the
presidential race. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-CHINA (Washington) _ President Clinton formally asks
Congress to grant China permanent trading privileges, a move that _
if approved _ could pave the way for the communist regime in
Beijing to join the World Trade Organization. Clinton says
establishing permanent trade ties would help open up long-closed
Chinese markets to U.S. goods and hasten human rights reforms in
China. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-JUDGES (Washington) _ After years of waiting, two
controversial Californians appear sure to get their day in court _
and their days on the bench. The Senate ended a filibuster led by
conservative Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., against Richard Paez, a U.S.
District Court judge in Los Angeles, and San Francisco lawyer
Marsha Berzon. Votes on their nominations to the U.S. 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals are expected Thursday. By MARK HELM. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-LAUNDERING (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
declares war on money laundering in four regions of the country
that it calls ``high risk'' zones for such crimes: the
Texas-Arizona border, New York City and northern New Jersey, the
Los Angeles metropolitan area, and San Juan, Puerto Rico. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BANK-IMF (Washington) _ A congressional commission accuses the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund of being high-cost and
ineffective institutions and urges Congress to support major
changes in both. By PHILIP CAUTHON.
