<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BATTLE-TESTED' BUSH SETS SIGHTS ON GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Proclaiming himself ``battle-tested'' by the GOP
primary process, Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday said the nation
will soon see the ``stark differences'' between himself and Vice
President Al Gore, the leading Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, claiming that his Super Tuesday election victories in nine
states put the Republican nomination within his grasp, said he's
not ready to dismiss the faltering challenge of Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, one day after key losses in Super Tuesday primaries had
all but killed his chances for the Republican presidential
nomination, retreated Wednesday to his vacation home in Cottonwood,
Ariz., to reassess his political future.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's political director, John Weaver, said the Arizona
senator had set no deadline for himself, despite speculation that
he may withdraw from the presidential race before the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver also dismissed speculation that McCain, who has
demonstrated strong appeal to independent and Democratic voters
with his maverick, reform-oriented campaign, would launch a
third-party bid for the White House. But he declined to rule out
that option, despite McCain's earlier insistence that he will
remain in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain beat Bush in four states, Bush captured the vast
majority of delegates to the Republican National Convention; the
upcoming primaries, including Texas and Florida, will likely give
Bush the 1,034 delegates he needs to guarantee the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   To wrap up his quest, Bush on Thursday travels to Colorado,
Wyoming and Utah, all of which have primaries Friday. This weekend,
Bush ventures to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging news conference outside the Governor's
Mansion, Bush urged Texans to participate in next week's primaries,
even if he is assured of the nomination. His comments came after he
cast his own Texas GOP primary ballot for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't tell people who I vote for, but I voted for
myself,'' the governor said. Turning to his wife, Laura, he asked,
``How about you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for you,'' she assured him.
</P>
<P>
   Until he has the nomination secured, or until McCain abandons
his candidacy, Bush said he'll take nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the appropriate time, I want to talk to John (McCain) if he
wants to. And, of course, I'm going to be reaching out to the
people he energized for the primary,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who has been shifting attention to the general
election, said he's ready to focus on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel battle-tested, and that's what a lot of people wanted
to see _ whether or not I could come through a tough primary
intact. And I feel great. I feel like we've got a good chance'' in
November, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His differences with Gore range from budget policies to moral
stances, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are happy with the status quo in Washington, then
vote for Al Gore,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are happy with Al Gore and Bill Clinton _ the tone
they set for America _ then you've got a perfect person to vote
for,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has ``not yet thought about the timetable'' for
selecting a vice presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's made ``good progress'' in reducing pollution
in Texas, despite last year's record levels of air contamination in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston's a fast-growing town. There's a lot of automobiles,''
he said, adding that the records reflected ``one summer of
noncompliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Bush said he now would meet with a group of Log Cabin
Republicans, a gay GOP group. He said his earlier refusal to meet
with some of its leaders was based on his belief that the
membership would not support him.
</P>
<P>
   And asked if homosexuality were a sin, Bush said ``we're all
sinners. That's what I believe. That's why I sought and found
redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Weaver said the Arizona senator is not ``going to
walk away from what he cares about,'' referring to McCain's
campaign-finance reform and outreach messages.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver spoke with reporters aboard the McCain campaign's
chartered airliner enroute to Arizona from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Departing from his normal campaign practice, McCain flew on a
separate plane to his home state without the media and was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said that Wednesday was a ``day of rest'' and
reassessment for the senator, members of his family and key
campaign aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The options are obvious _ staying in, getting out or other
options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said McCain wasn't ready yet to cancel campaign trips,
scheduled to begin Thursday in Colorado and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Clay Robison contributed to this story from
Sedona, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
