<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     03-08 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO VERDICT TRIGGERS UNEASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was sick over the acquittal of four New York City police
officers last week in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   But Nehi knew that; that's how it is with friends. Even when
you're laughing, they know what you really feel is sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nehi, I was just thinking about you,'' I told him after my
husband handed me the telephone the other day. ``I was thinking,
you better be careful what you do with your wallet up there.''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed. He laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, we both wanted to cry, but we laughed the way we
always do when tears aren't enough to give you peace, that place
you search for when trying to understand why race causes people to
overreact _ to hate.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, laughter will get you there, make the
traveling easy, lift you to a new and gentler place.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, there's nothing funny about dying in a hail of
41 bullets because police officers mistake your wallet for a gun,
view you through a lens of criminality because of the color of your
skin. Nineteen times, they hit Diallo, who was unarmed. When he
finally slumped to the floor, his wallet fell out of his right
hand. Not a gun.
</P>
<P>
   After four weeks of testimony, a jury that included four
African-Americans acquitted the officers of all charges,
second-degree murder and criminally negligent homicide among them.
The officers do face a civil trial, a departmental review and,
possibly, federal civil rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   And so you laugh to keep from crying. It's the same sort of
feeling you get when you read the March issue of ``Essence''
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race on the Job,'' the headline screamed. ``How Black can you
be?''
</P>
<P>
   The implication in the question is that you can be too black, as
in sporting colorful head wraps, hanging black posters in the
office cubicle, or not black enough, as in talking ``proper'' and
avoiding the blacker brother in the mailroom.
</P>
<P>
   How black can you be? Truth is, how you answer, in many cases,
can literally make or break you in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   If you found it difficult to understand how four
African-Americans on the jury could vote for acquittal in the
Diallo case, then perhaps explaining the internal conflict some of
them feel might help explain.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Eric Warner said in his closing argument that Diallo
was doomed by the officers' perception of him, of black men in
general. You have to wonder whether the four black jurors were
operating under the same perception.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Nehi saw it. He lives near Albany, N.Y., where the
case was heard. Phyllis Allen lives in Fort Worth, and she shares
his view. So do I.
</P>
<P>
   They don't like it, don't think it's fair, but they know that
being accepted by the white establishment often means denying who
you really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe in the year 2000, we're still having this
discussion,'' Allen said. ``The race thing is never going away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as African-Americans buy into the same stereotypes
that the mainstream community has. And not as long as they fear
backlash for being themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the most successful African-Americans are not the
sellouts, as the article in ``Essence'' aptly points out. The most
successful blacks are those who ``don't consciously decide to be
black. They just are black.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen admits she once tried to fit in by being different at
work.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she says, ``I'm who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, if you're African-American and male, who you are can
be deadly, and the harder you look for reasons to laugh, the harder
they are to find.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
