<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL STUDY SUGGESTS SCALING BACK WORLD BANK, IMF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PHILIP CAUTHON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional commission Wednesday characterized
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund as high-cost and
ineffective institutions and urged Congress to support scaling back
their operations.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the commission, which helps formulate U.S.
policy toward the IMF, World Bank and other multination lending
institutions, drew praise from congressional Republicans and
criticism from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   To refocus the IMF and World Bank after years of expanding
functions, the International Financial Advisory Commission proposed
limiting the IMF to last-resort lending and tailoring the World
Bank to work only with impoverished nations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, chaired by Allan Meltzer of Carnegie Mellon
University, also recommended that both the World Bank and IMF, as
well as regional development banks, forgive the debts of heavily
indebted poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, acknowledged that
even if Congress backs the commission recommendations, the United
States alone cannot mandate reform of those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we intend to follow through with this and we have a moral
obligation to do so,'' Armey said. ``If we implement the
commission's recommendations, we will turn the IMF around.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission suggested that Congress encourage the IMF to lend
only short-term, last-resort funds at penalty rates to encourage
governments to first seek private bank loans
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the World Bank should shift its focus to providing
information and funds to reduce poverty in only the poorest of
nations, the commission said. It said that currently World Bank
funds often end up in wealthy countries or in the hands of corrupt
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   One commission member, economist Fred Bergsten, disagreed with
many of the panel's recommendations, saying they would undermine
the world economy and endanger U.S. economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority proposals would sharply increase the risk of
international economic disorder and dash the prospects of economic
development for millions of poor people,'' Bergsten said.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said that, while
the commission claims to support international lending
institutions, the commission actually aims to weaken them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when 700 million of the world's poorest people live
on a dollar a day or less, resources for the (lending institutions)
must be augmented, not slashed,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank media chief Caroline Anstey said the ``faulty
recommendations'' were based on flawed data.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we welcome review of the bank's work by both our
supporters and our critics, we find the results of this particular
review very disappointing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
