<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-LIMA-HNS &LR;      03-08 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-LIMA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Jose Lima learned his lesson a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pitching winter ball in the 1998-99 offseason, as he
had done the previous nine years, the Astros righthander decided to
take three months off.
</P>
<P>
   The result? ``I was hurting,'' Lima said, referring to soreness
in his right shoulder that bothered him for most of spring training
last year.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Lima again decided against playing winter ball when
he returned briefly to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he spent his days throwing with his younger brother
Frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different story,'' Lima said Wednesday after pitching
three innings in the Astros' 5-4 victory over the Florida Marlins.
``I think throwing some this offseason paid off. I feel like I can
be overpowering this year.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a guy who won 21 games last season, second in the
National League behind then-teammate Mike Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   In three spring starts, Lima has shown a midseason-like mastery
of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   His changeup has been effective. Manager Larry Dierker called
his slider Wednesday ``one of the best he's ever had.'' And Lima,
who never will be mistaken for a power pitcher, even claims to have
gained some velocity on his fastball, which in the past has been
clocked in the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm feels stronger,'' Lima said. ``I know I don't throw 100
mph, but I still can let hitters know I'm up there (on the
mound).''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Marlins scored two unearned runs off Lima in
the first inning after an error by third baseman Ken Caminiti. The
righthander followed by retiring seven of the final eight batters
he faced.
</P>
<P>
   He needed only 23 pitches against 13 hitters, inducing five
groundouts and three fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was typical Lima,'' catcher Tony Eusebio said. ``If you go
to the plate, you have to be ready to swing the bat or you're going
back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio, who has played in the Dominican winter league in the
past, said it's difficult for pitchers to adapt to a routine and
then stray from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for Latin players is they play a whole season in
the United States and play all winter to keep their body in
shape,'' Eusebio said. ``Lima didn't pitch last winter, and that
had an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the start of spring training last year, Lima
encountered soreness in his right shoulder. It was diagnosed as a
muscular problem that pushed back a couple of his scheduled starts.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has been impressed with what he has seen from a healthy
Lima this spring, particularly Sunday when he struck out four
batters and did not allow a hit in two innings against the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really looks great,'' Dierker said. ``He looks like an old
pro now. He's throwing strikes. He's ahead in the count all the
time. He's getting his slider over the plate. It's a better
breaking pitch than I've seen him have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive, Dierker said, is the fact Lima hasn't let
his newfound stardom become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming a starter two years ago, Lima has won 37 games,
including a career year last season when he went 21-10 with a 3.58
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging. Knowing how emotional of a guy he is
and how he likes the spotlight, I thought he might come down with a
little of the star syndrome and think he can walk out there and the
guys would just make outs for him,'' Dierker said. ``He hasn't done
that. He's been one of the first guys running laps to get in shape.
He looks like a guy trying to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Lima had in mind this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as long as I stay healthy and I keep my arm strength
I'll be fine,'' he said. ``I'm looking forward to another great
season.'' &QL; 
$$$
</P>
