<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORSOFTHEMOUNTAIN-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR A BETTER LIFE IN REVOLUTIONARY CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALAN COCHRUM 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Colors of the Mountain'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Da Chen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memoir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the clouds of tobacco fumes that hang above the heads of
its characters, Da Chen's ``Colors of the Mountain'' might well
have been named ``Smoke on the Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dia and I found a new spot behind the school wall, where we
met and chatted as he polluted his lungs with dark tobacco,'' Chen
writes of a youthful friend in his memoir of a south Chinese
boyhood. ``He told me the secret of the Dia tobacco. Since his
grandpa's time, they had kept a plot of land in their back yard the
size of a basketball court, where they grew broad-leaved tobacco.
The rich, bitter flavor was attributed to the fact that young Dia
each morning watered the plants with the contents of three full
night pots used overnight by the men in the Dia household. The
thick, smelly (urine) nourished the young plants and added a
special flavor not found with other growers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. I dare say it did. Still, the real cloud over Chen's life
comes not from burning leaves but from the fiery politics of Maoist
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rarely left our house to play because Mom said there were
many bad people waiting to hurt us. ... When I asked Mom why we had
to hide in our dark house all the time, she said that we were
landlords, and that the people outside were poor peasants who had
taken our house, lands, and stores. They were making us suffer
because the leaders were all bad. There was no fairness, no justice
for us. We had to be quiet, stay out of trouble, and wait for
better days to come. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never supposed to be a leader among other students. I
was born with a political defect that no one could fix.''
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Colors of the Mountain'' is not merely the recollection
of life in a place of harvesting rice by hand and traveling to
other towns by foot or overloaded bicycle. It is a memoir of hunger
for food, acceptance and knowledge, of a time when political
zealotry made it easier for an ex-landlord's son to make friends
among youthful ne'er-do-wells than among the teachers and pupils in
good standing at his village school.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the madness of the Cultural Revolution, intellectual
pursuits became anathema. But after Mao Tse-tung died, the societal
tide turned. A place in college became a consummation devoutly to
be wished, and Chen and his older brother poured themselves into
poring over their books in a fanatical effort to redeem themselves
and their family's sacrifices for them.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's writing style has neither the cant of a revolutionary
(hardly a surprise, given his background) nor the oddly formal
simplicity of Pearl Buck's ``The Good Earth'' or Elizabeth Foreman
Lewis' ``Young Fu of the Upper Yangtze.'' His China comes across as
an odd combination of the alien and the familiar. It is a world of
hardscrabble, primitive peasant life and hard-line,
all-encompassing politics utterly different from suburban America.
On the other hand, the ... um... ``colorful'' conversation of
Chen's youthful compatriots would fit in all too well at any U.S.
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colors of the Mountain'' is neither philosophy nor poetry. It
is a simple tale, bluntly and plainly told, of one youth's desire
to escape the scorched political earth of his home and find a
greener future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alan Cochrum is a writer and copy editor for the Star-Telegram
editorial board. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
