<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MOVES SWIFTLY TO MAKE CAMPAIGN FINANCE A PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore moved quickly
Wednesday to stake out the high ground on overhauling the campaign
finance system, saying he would make it a campaign priority.
</P>
<P>
   The move is an attempt by Gore both to woo the
soon-to-be-orphaned independent supporters of Sen. John McCain and
former Sen. Bill Bradley, both of whom are expected to leave the
presidential race shortly, and to shield himself on a subject on
which he himself is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who are disaffected and not willing
to be a part of our democracy,'' Gore said Wednesday morning on
CBS. ``We want to reach out and bring them back into the democratic
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been saying relatively kind things about McCain for
days, noting that he agrees with the maverick Republican on the
need to change the campaign finance system and buck big tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   His reiteration Tuesday of his earlier proposal that both
nominees debate twice a week and forego campaign commercials is
aimed, too, at luring independent voters, although that proposal is
popular with a number of voters across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   And his busy travel schedule over the next week _ to Michigan,
Illinois and Pennsylvania, among other places _ indicates he is
aiming for the voters in those big swing states, which may decide
the election. He was headed Wednesday night to Michigan, which
supported McCain in the Republican primary and holds its Democratic
primary March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning Gore acknowledged flat out that he would try
to go after McCain supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I will,'' Gore said on CBS. ``In fact, of the four
candidates who went into the semifinals last night, three of us
support campaign finance reform. And both Senator McCain and
Senator Bradley have spoken eloquently about the need for change in
the way campaigns are conducted. I agree with them very strongly. I
have made a point of it in my campaign as well. And I said in my
speech last evening, we're going to elevate the priority of this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A top Gore strategist said Wednesday that polls indicated that a
plurality of people who voted for McCain on Tuesday, at least in
California, could conceivably vote for Gore in the fall. ``We can't
win a majority of them, but we can win most of them,'' the
strategist said. ``We're obviously going to focus on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the all-but-certain Republican
nominee, has already said he plans to use the 1996 Clinton/Gore
campaign fund-raising excesses and Gore's fund-raiser at a Buddhist
Temple against Gore in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, while campaigning Wednesday afternoon at a diner, where he
ordered a chocolate milkshake, was asked if he would not rather
have voters forget about those events.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, as he shook hands with patrons at the Elliston
Place Soda Shop near Vanderbilt University. ``I want them to
remember what happened in both political parties, and I want them
to look to the future and ask the question, how can we protect our
democracy against undue influence from the kind of secretive,
special-interest, sneak attack'' that Bush deployed against McCain
in the last week?
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain was right to denounce that practice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp is betting that the battle between McCain and Bush
left some McCain supporters so embittered about Bush to make them
ripe for picking by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with trying to woo McCain voters to the Gore camp is
that McCain is more conservative than Gore on the emotional issues
of abortion and gun control. But oddly, one Gore strategist said, a
number of McCain backers were under the mistaken impression that
the Arizona senator favored abortion rights and gun control, as
Gore does; given that peculiarity, he said, the Gore campaign
intends to try to capture those voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp also expects to use McCain's criticisms about
Bush's tax-cut proposal against Bush. McCain, like Gore, has said
Bush's tax-cut proposal was too big and would put Social Security
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore said Wednesday morning: ``Governor Bush has a plan that
would spend a trillion dollars more than the non-Social Security
surplus. And John McCain has said during this campaign that
Governor Bush's plan would put Social Security at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was still working out the details of some of
the other proposals that Gore made during his speech Tuesday night.
These include his notion to use his campaign to spend time with
average Americans on their jobs, in their homes and at their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that he feels very comfortable campaigning with
people in a way that gets him in as close and direct contact as
possible, and he believes he learns from people,'' one Gore adviser
said. An aide said that these visits may start in a couple of
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
