<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-SCAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAN CONVICTED IN PERROT MEMORABILIA SCAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Texas man was convicted Wednesday of trying to
profit from the plight of cancer-stricken Houston Comet guard Kim
Perrot by soliciting autographed memorabilia for silent auctions
that never took place.
</P>
<P>
   Gene L. Price, 42, of Houston was convicted of one count of
conspiracy to commit wire and mail fraud and one count of wire
fraud after a two-day trial before U.S. District Judge Vanessa
Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   Co-conspirator Moses Mays Jr., 46, of nearby Missouri City
pleaded guilty last year to his part in the scam.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents began investigating Price and Mays last March, after
National Basketball Association officials became suspicious of a
charitable event the men claimed to be sponsoring to benefit
Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, 32, died Aug. 19 after a seven-month battle with lung
cancer. The point guard helped lead the WNBA Comets to their three
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Mays and Price asked NBA teams for signed jerseys and balls to
be auctioned at a benefit for Perrot.Doing business as Sports
Concepts, the two also sought donations of other items and
services, such as hotel accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   They told several players and NBA teams that they had scheduled
one silent auction for March 19, 1999, at the Westin Galleria Hotel
in Houston, and another a week later at the nearby J.W. Marriott
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The men got signed basketballs or jerseys from the Charlotte
Hornets, Miami Heat, Portland Trail Blazers and Minnesota
Timberwolves, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither auction was held, Mays and Price called NBA
teams to say their items had been sold. They also called other
teams who had not yet sent their promised items, saying Sports
Concepts had to send them to the winning bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Bonifas, manager of media services for the Comets, said
the team called the Women's NBA security office in New York when it
heard about the scam.
</P>
<P>
   Price had a prior criminal record on an unspecified drug
offense, officials said. Gilmore will sentence him June 12. He
faces up to five years in prison and $250,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Mays pleaded guilty in November. He was sentenced to 18 months
in prison and three years on supervised release.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
