<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH TROOPS IN KOSOVO SAY PEACEKEEPING LOOKS A LOT LIKE SIEGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA-MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ French peacekeeping troops were
securing their positions with sandbags and barbed wire in the
northern sector of this divided industrial town Wednesday, a day
after 16 of their comrades were wounded in one of its worst
outbreaks yet of ethnic violence. The mood was depressed, and not
least among the peacekeepers, who say they see no way out of the
quagmire of hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The main bridge that connects the Albanian southern part of the
city and the predominantly Serbian northern sector is now a mass of
razor wire. Swedish troops have moved in to guard the Albanian
side, and French troops watch the other. Only U.N. and military
vehicles were crossing Wednesday. No civilians ventured forth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the northern sector, French troops were busy
installing more defenses, filling shoulder-high fortifications with
earth from a mechanical digger and mounting more coils of wire on
top of sand-bagged positions on a street corner. Northern
Kosovska-Mitrovica is rapidly coming to look like a city under
siege.
</P>
<P>
   The French troops were hurt when Albanians hurled grenades at a
group of Serbs gathered close to an Albanian area. Seventeen Serbs
and seven Albanian civilians were also injured. Wednesday the
soldiers on duty in the area appeared sullen. They refused to talk
to the press, or to concede that they were in the area of attacks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the riverbank, where troops have built elaborate
protections around three apartment buildings to protect some 40
Albanians living inside, Serbs have inflicted injuries on the
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hatred here is not aimed at us,'' explained a French
captain on duty. ``We are just caught in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his men were injured when Serbs rioted in protest at the
return of the 40 Albanians, a small percentage of those expelled
from their apartments last month.
</P>
<P>
   But even if not directed at them, the captain observed, the
enmity runs very deep. One of his soldiers had his neck sliced by a
sharpened stone. ``Sharpening stones means there is real hatred,''
the captain said. ``It is too early to bring back Albanians here.
This is not something that can be solved at all quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The troops have surrounded themselves and the apartments with
dozens of armored vehicles and rows and rows of barbed wire. The
soldiers, dressed in full combat gear with body armor and visors on
their helmets, guard the entrance and listen patiently to angry
Serbs who come by to demand that the Albanians be sent away again.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extensive defenses, they could not prevent a rocket
attack on one of the apartment buildings Wednesday. Apparently in
retaliation for the grenade attacks and shootings earlier in the
day, someone fired a rocket-propelled grenade, just missing the
window of a seventh-floor apartment. No one was injured, but
residents, both Albanians and Serbs, felt the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian troops guarding the back of the building pointed out the
crater high up on the wall. Moments after the attack, they had to
deal with a crowd of cheering Serbs who gathered to celebrate it.
``These are guys who greet us every day and invite us for a
coffee,'' said the officer in charge. ``And then suddenly they
change into a mob. One guy leads them and they all follow. It is
very nasty _ even in Bosnia I have never seen people like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that French soldiers had investigated the attack and now
knew who had done it, ``down to his name and address.'' But he
criticized the task assigned to his unit to staff stationary
checkpoints and search people and cars going by. ``People begin to
hate us, you see?'' he said, as a Serb made an angry gesture at one
of the soldiers searching his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a reconnaissance unit,'' he said. ``It would be much
better to patrol the town than tie down two dozen men in one place.
Sitting here we cannot stop a rocket attack like that. Better to
patrol and then you can move to the spot when something blows up.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments mirrored the frustrations of the different
peacekeepers at the lack of a clear way out of their situation. The
deputy regional commander of the U.N. police service, John Adams,
also criticized the French military for preventing access to the
scene of the grenade attacks and shootings and to victims Tuesday,
Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said that although his police officers had primacy in
criminal investigations, the French had kept them from
investigating.
</P>
<P>
   His reaction gave another sign of the uneasy relations between
French troops and international police officers in the city _ and
of the lack of a convincing effort to beat the violence.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
