<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASIA-TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SENDS LONG-DELAYED BILL ON CHINA TRADE TO WARY CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday sent Congress his
bill to usher China into the World Trade Organization. He then
opened a new front in the debate on the subject in his own party,
arguing that opening up China's markets will undermine Communist
Party control.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the Johns Hopkins foreign affairs graduate school
here, Clinton tried to float above the bitter economic debate in
his party about the wisdom of the deal, and he said little about
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But he made an argument that opening up China's economy amounted
to a poison pill for China's communist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the new century, liberty will spread by cell phone and
cable modem,'' Clinton told a crowd that included students,
lobbyists and many members of Clinton's cabinet, who are now
calling members of Congress daily about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   When China joins the trade organization, the president said, it
will be obliged to make ``the tools of communication even cheaper,
better and more widely available.'' He added: ``We know how much
the Internet has changed America, and we are already and open
society. Imagine how much it could change China.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that since the deal was signed four months
ago, China's leaders have tried to control both what kind of
content Chinese can access via the Internet, and to prevent foreign
ownership of Internet-related companies. But to the Chinese leaders
who are trying to control the Internet in a country as vast and
hard to police as China, he said he had only two words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck!''
</P>
<P>
   The long-delayed transmission of the bill to Congress _ it
appeared timed to arrive after Vice President Gore had the
Democratic presidential nomination firmly in grasp _ set off a
battle within the Democratic Party that intertwines the politics of
trade, the presidential election and Clinton's final effort to
recast relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Only 50 to 60 Democratic members of the House appear prepared to
support the granting of permanent ``normal'' trade status to China.
That is the one legal prerequisite if American companies are to
benefit from the market openings that China promised in 13 years of
negotiation that ended last November.
</P>
<P>
   That means Clinton is dependent on support from House and Senate
Republicans to pass what may be the last major foreign policy
legislation of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He is getting little help from Vice President Gore, who, to
appease labor unions that vociferously oppose the deal, said three
weeks ago that he would negotiate something better if elected to
office. Gore later reiterated his support for the deal the
administration struck, but his aides did not return calls on the
subject Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the presumed Republican nominee,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, said Bush remains a ``vocal
supporter'' of China's entry into the trade organization, because
``it is in our interest, and it is in the interest of the Chinese
to grow an entrepreneurial middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the governor did not yet have a position on tying
passage of the bill to providing new arms for Taiwan, a movement
that several Republicans are considering as the price for their
support.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced Wednesday by Paul Wolfowitz, the dean of
the Paul H. Nitze School for Advanced International Studies, who is
one of Gov. George W. Bush's leading foreign policy advisers. But
Wolfowitz did not mention that Bush has been more vocal in his
support of the bill than Clinton's own vice president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's argument Wednesday that entry to the World Trade
Organization would loosen the hold of China's communist leaders is
bound to set off considerable debate, because it is far from clear
that China's economic openings have been matched by a political
relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made essentially the same argument in 1994 when he
reversed himself, and said that despite his campaign promises he
would no longer link the annual renewal of Chinese trade benefits
to its human rights record. Over time, he said, trade would
contribute to a lifting of political repression.
</P>
<P>
   But in the six years since then, according to the annual reports
published by the State Department, China's rights record has
worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risky argument because it leaves him vulnerable to the
charge that he's overplaying what this agreement will do in
China,'' said Nicholas Lardy, a China expert at the Brookings
Institution. ``It was a good speech, but there may have been too
much emphasis on what this will do to change China rather than why
it's in the national interests of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton spoke, his advisers foresaw a fierce battle in
Congress, where they are trying to win passage by mid-May, before
the congressional elections heat up. And Wednesday Clinton lost a
major ally: Rep. John P. Murtha, D-Pa., who is influential with his
colleagues on military issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to his colleagues, Murtha, who has consistently
voted to renew China's trading rights with the United States, said
he now believes it would be a mistake to lose the leverage of an
annual vote.
</P>
<P>
   He said his mind was made up when China recently threatened
``drastic measures'' and ``the use of force'' against Taiwan if it
was found to be indefinitely delaying reunification talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in our national security interest,'' he concluded,
``to condone and reward grossly irresponsible conduct by a country
that wishes to become a leader in the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been meeting with members of Congress for
several weeks to press his case, Democratic and Republican leaders
on Capitol Hill have complained that the White House was running
out of time _ and needed to send up a bill. Sen. Daniel P.
Moynihan, D-N.Y., and a supporter of permanent normal trade
relations, a status that most nations enjoy, complained two weeks
ago that the White House was running out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly part of that hesitation was the pressure on Vice
President Gore. But now that he has grasped the nomination, some
White House officials say they hope he will strengthen his support,
even if it means angering unions. ``Where is the AFL-CIO going to
run?'' one cabinet member asked Wednesday. ``To George Bush?''
</P>
<P>
   But the big issue is the Democratic members of Congress, who are
caught between labor, which vows to defeat anyone supporting the
bill, and business interests, which are launching an expensive
advertising campaign supporting it. That effort is led by
agricultural and technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, China is nervous that the bill will fail, and Chinese
officials have already launched an unusual lobbying campaign. One
senior Clinton administration official this week said he feared
that ``China's own efforts could backfire on us big time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton noted Wednesday that even if Congress votes against
normal trade relations, China will still get into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress can only decide whether the United States will share
in the economic benefits,'' Clinton said in his speech. A vote
against the bill, he said, ``will cost America jobs as our
competitors in Europe, Asia and elsewhere capture Chinese markets
that we otherwise would have served.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
