<SLUG> BC-SIMPSON-DA-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CANDIDATE MAKES CAMPAIGN ISSUE OF O.J. SIMPSON'S ACQUITTAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
(Eds.: See optional trim, optional ending.) 
 
By JULIE MASON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's a campaign ploy that might be more at home in Los
Angeles, but this is the Harris County district attorney's race.
</P>
<P>
   Over a photo of O.J. Simpson playing golf, local candidate
Michael Stafford takes his own swing in a new brochure mailed to
Republican primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exclusive!'' the ad says. ``If Michael Stafford had been the
DA, O.J. would be busting rocks, not hitting balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Black community leaders criticized the brochure, mailed to
80,000 voters for Tuesday's primary, as exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you do what you have to do when you are an
ultraconservative,'' said Deloyd Parker, director of the SHAPE
Community Center. ``If nothing else, it's a blink of the eye from
racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Stafford, first assistant Harris County attorney and one of five
GOP candidates vying for the seat, said he ``never considered'' the
ad could be racially divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he is someone rich enough and famous enough to use the
kind of evidence and expertise that the DA's office in Los Angeles
didn't have access to,'' Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.2 million
people and is the largest county in Texas. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Simpson, a former football star and broadcaster, was acquitted
of the 1994 slashing deaths of his ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson,
and Ronald Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   A civil jury later found him liable for the deaths and ordered
him to pay $33.5 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts divided public opinion. A CNN poll after the
criminal trial found 73 percent of Anglos believed Simpson murdered
his ex-wife, compared with 27 percent of blacks who thought so.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford's mailing also drew criticism from within his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think prosecutions in California have anything to do
with the race in Harris County,'' said Gary Polland, chairman of
the Harris County Republican Party. ``I don't know why it's been
injected into our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston radio personality and community activist Ada Edwards
questioned the relevance of invoking Simpson's image in a local
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too bad the race has become about who is the
baddest guy on the block,'' Edwards said. ``To highlight this in an
ad is ludicrous and insulting to the whole community, black, white,
man and woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker also noted the unintended irony of a law-and-order
candidate criticizing the same criminal justice system he is
working so hard to be a part of.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford, who once worked as a chemist for Atlantic Richfield
Co., makes the point in his campaign that he is familiar and
comfortable with new scientific methods being used in criminal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Simpson ad is relevant because under his watch, the
botched evidence and other foibles of the Simpson trial would not
happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DA's office should be one that stays up with the
technology because it's changing all the time,'' Stafford said.
``The Simpson case went bad because the prosecutors didn't have the
kind of expertise they needed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rice University political scientist and pollster Bob Stein said
the ad is probably Stafford's last big shot at building his name
with voters before Tuesday's primary election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is playing to rather a base emotional concern, in my
opinion,'' Stein said. ``In the Republican primary, of course,
there aren't going to be a lot of black voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican contenders for the race are Jim Leitner, a
defense attorney; prosecutor Chuck Rosenthal; Patricia Lykos, a
former criminal district judge; and Lloyd Kelley, former city
controller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Simpson criminal trial, meanwhile, has had lasting political
implications in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Garcetti, the district attorney at the time of Simpson's
trial, faces a runoff election to keep his seat after Tuesday's
California primary, a political uncertainty some have attributed to
public anger over Simpson's acquittal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
