<HEADER>
A1022 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OSCARS-BESTDIRECTOR-T     03-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-BEST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMINATION THE ONLY THING DIRECTORS HAVE IN COMMON
</HEADLINE>
 DIRECTOR-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Film directors can be judged on so many levels, it's a wonder
there's not more division over the Best Director race at the
Oscars. A good director finds the proper tone for a screenplay,
then _ with the cast and crew _ tries to bring it to fruition
through a variety of means: color scheme, musical score, art
direction, cinematography choices (including film stock), editing
pace and, of course, acting. Naturally, those elements vary from
movie to movie.
</P>
<P>
   A good director knows how to use the tools; for instance, he or
she can make a limited actor look better simply by accentuating
strengths and playing down weaknesses. A good director can
manipulate an audience without making the audience feel manipulated
_ or at least without making the audience resent being manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees in this year's Best Director race have such varied
styles that it's almost bizarre that they're nominated for the same
award. The person who did the best job of manipulating an audience,
though, was M. Night Shyamalan, who not only managed to make his
ghost story ``The Sixth Sense'' moody, creepy and forgivably
sentimental but surprised us with a plot twist so treasured that
audiences actually guarded it; even some people who recently saw
the movie say they're stunned that nobody spoiled it for them.
</P>
<P>
   Shyamalan worked from his own screenplay and got earnest
performances out of Bruce Willis and especially young actor (and
fellow Oscar nominee) Haley Joel Osment. ``The Sixth Sense'' is a
quantum leap from Shyamalan's first movie, the trite religious
drama ``Wide Awake,'' but that earnestness also works against him.
``The Sixth Sense'' made tons of money, but it's often slow and
takes itself very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   You can't say that about Sam Mendes' ``American Beauty,'' which
explores suburban dysfunction with a sardonic zing. Mendes brought
the bitter humor of Alan Ball's screenplay to life and drenched the
movie in bright colors that made the characters' lives look
appealing even though every character is a mess. Although Mendes
had great raw material to work with _ Kevin Spacey is close to
perfect as midlife-crisis poster boy Lester Burnham _ his
theatrical background sometimes showed through: Some of the
dialogue scenes reach a shrill, forced pitch that detracts from the
subtler moments.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes and Shyamalan look like the front-runners in this year's
Best Director race, but I feel a personal affection for Spike
Jonze, a guy who did some pretty cool music videos (notably the
Beastie Boys' ``Sabotage'' and Fatboy Slim's ``Praise You'') before
coming out with one of the year's most enjoyably weird movies,
``Being John Malkovich.'' Like Mendes, Jonze worked from a strong
screenplay (by Charlie Kaufman) but gave this surreal examination
of celebrity culture his own spin. He may be the only person who
could have perfectly executed a scene in which character actor
Malkovich goes inside his own head. But like Mendes, Jonze
sometimes lets his actors get too shrill, and he almost derails the
movie's goodwill during scenes in which obsessed puppeteer John
Cusack imprisons his not-so-passive-anymore wife (Cameron Diaz).
</P>
<P>
   Jonze probably doesn't stand a chance for the Oscar; his movie
is just too oddball, and it missed out on a Best Picture
nomination. It also seems unlikely that Lasse Hallstrom, who
directed the novelesque ``The Cider House Rules,'' will grab the
statue (especially when you consider that Hallstrom didn't receive
a Directors Guild of America nomination; the DGA winner, who will
be announced March 11, usually takes home the Oscar).
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mann, a director much-admired by his peers, stands an
outside chance at winning for the social drama ``The Insider.'' But
the movie didn't have the box-office clout of ``The Sixth Sense''
or ``American Beauty'' and isn't getting a pre-Oscar push like
those movies are.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: ``American Beauty's'' renewed box-office presence
helps Mendes snag a win; but don't be surprised if ``The Sixth
Sense'' upsets it for Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   Personal pick: Jonze's ``Being John Malkovich'' was just too
funny, weird and innovative to be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
