<HEADLINE>
`BATTLE-TESTED' BUSH SETS SIGHTS ON GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Story has been updated) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Proclaiming himself ``battle-tested'' by the GOP
primary process, Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday said the nation
will soon see the ``stark differences'' between himself and Vice
President Al Gore, the leading Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, claiming that his Super Tuesday election victories in nine
states put the Republican nomination within his grasp, said he's
not ready to dismiss the faltering challenge of Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   But sources in the McCain campaign said late Wednesday that the
senator would likely withdraw from the race Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, one day after key losses in Super Tuesday primaries had
all but killed his chances for the Republican presidential
nomination, had retreated early Wednesday to his vacation home in
Cottonwood, Ariz., to reassess his political future.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's political director, dismissed speculation
that McCain _ who has demonstrated strong appeal to independent and
Democratic voters with his maverick, reform-oriented campaign _
would launch a third-party bid for the White House. But he declined
to rule out that option, despite McCain's earlier insistence that
he will remain in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain beat Bush in four states, Bush captured the vast
majority of delegates to the Republican National Convention; the
upcoming primaries, including Texas and Florida, will likely give
Bush the 1,034 delegates he needs to guarantee the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   To wrap up his quest, Bush on Thursday travels to Colorado,
Wyoming and Utah, all of which have primaries Friday. This weekend,
Bush ventures to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging news conference outside the Governor's
Mansion, Bush urged Texans to participate in next week's primaries,
even if he is assured of the nomination. His comments came after he
cast his own Texas GOP primary ballot for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't tell people who I vote for, but I voted for
myself,'' the governor said. Turning to his wife, Laura, he asked,
``How about you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for you,'' she assured him.
</P>
<P>
   Until he has the nomination secured, or until McCain abandons
his candidacy, Bush said he'll take nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the appropriate time, I want to talk to John (McCain) if he
wants to. And, of course, I'm going to be reaching out to the
people he energized for the primary,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who$:X.H15en!%Q%9
</P>
