<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel Ships Fast Chip, Catches Up With AMD  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Driven by their intensifying competition for bragging rights in PC
processor speed, both Intel and Advanced Micro Devices this week
began shipping 1-gigahertz chips, well ahead of their previously
announced schedules.
<P>
   But PCs with the new chips will be scarce and expensive for
weeks and even months to come, and it may be even longer before the
average user sees any compelling benefit from them.
</P>
<P>
   A gigahertz is 1,000 megahertz, or 1 billion cycles per second.
The more cycles per second, the faster a microprocessor can chew
through its assigned tasks. The actual speed users experience on
real-life tasks, however, depends on a variety of factors,
including other aspects of a chip's design, the performance of
other PC components and, increasingly, the speed of the machine's
Internet connection _ not to mention the user's typing and thinking
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   AMD, which until recently had said its gigahertz processor would
ship after midyear, said on Monday that it is already shipping.
According to several industry sources, the company changed the date
of its announcement twice last week to make sure it would beat
Intel to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   That effort succeeded, but only by two days: Intel unveiled its
gigahertz Pentium III yesterday. Only a month ago, the company
declared that it would deliver such a chip this fall. But that was
before AMD garnered headlines worldwide by demonstrating an Athlon
running at 1.1 gigahertz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies have stretched to hit these speeds,'' said
Michael Slater, founder and executive editor of Microprocessor
Report, an influential industry newsletter. ``It's mostly a matter
of positioning between them.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD, which in the past has seriously challenged Intel only at
the low end of the market, is now ``determined to show that it's
leading the race,'' he said, while ``Intel very much wants to keep
them out of that position.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes, however, include profits as well as prestige,
because the fastest chips available traditionally command much
higher prices than ordinary PC processors. Since the actual cost of
producing the fastest chips is usually no higher, the difference in
price goes straight to the chipmaker's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's gigahertz Pentium III, for example, sells for $990 in
quantities of 1,000, while the same chip running at 800 megahertz
lists for $647, and a 500-megahertz version is only $193. AMD's
1-GHz Athlon is priced, for now, at $1,299; 950- and 900-MHz
versions, also announced this week, are $999 and $899,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either company expects to ship these chips in
high volume at this point,'' Slater said. ``The prices they've set
ensure that that'll be the case,'' he added, because they force
PC-makers to price systems above mainstream market levels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Compaq and Gateway, the first two companies to
announce gigahertz Athlon PCs, are charging $2,499 and $2,999,
respectively. Machines with the new Pentium III are even higher:
Hewlett-Packard's Pavilion 1G PC is $3,499, and IBM's Aptiva S 1GZ
is $3,348. Dell's gigahertz Pentium III model, dubbed the Dimension
Special Edition, takes the cake with an even more special price:
$5,999.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, buyers will get a lot of bang for all those bucks:
In addition to ultrafast processors, these systems come with 128
(or, in Dell's case, 256) megabytes of RAM, 30- or 40-gigabyte hard
drives, the hottest 3-D graphics accelerators, 17- or 19-inch
monitors and a host of other bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Intel and AMD tout the benefits of their new processors to
``digital content creators'' _ graphic designers and video editors,
for example _ and to scientists and engineers running demanding
technical applications. But both companies, as well as the PC
manufacturers, acknowledge that for now most buyers will likely be
affluent PC enthusiasts and gamers.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, however, said even these users would see only modest
speed-up compared to the performance already delivered by much less
expensive systems with slightly slower processors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, once there's a substantial installed base of PCs with
processors like these, they will change the nature of the
applications people write,'' he said, citing the possibility of
improved speech-recognition software and 3-D interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's always a considerable time lag _ for now even the
number of games that really take advantage of these processors is
pretty limited,'' he said. ``People who buy in now will pay a
substantial premium, and by the time the applications are
available, the systems will be much cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
