r f BC-ORACLE-ORACLE_SFCHRON     03-08 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-ORACLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chevron, Oracle, Wal-Mart Team Up to Provide Online Exchange
For  Shops 
 &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bay Area business giants Chevron and Oracle yesterday teamed up
with Wal-Mart subsidiary McLane Co. to create an Internet exchange
where convenience stores can order merchandise, manage inventory
and analyze sales patterns.
<P>
   RetailersMarketXchange.com, which should be up and running in
about three months, will automate and centralize a range of
operations for chain stores as well as stand-alone convenience
shops, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Such online exchanges are becoming de rigueur in the
business-to-business arena, in which the Web is seen as a way to
purchase goods and disseminate information more efficiently and
cost effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, which makes database software for high-powered corporate
networks, recently announced similar supply-chain portals with auto
manufacturer Ford and retailer Sears, and the Redwood Shores
company said more are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Using a standard PC and Internet browser _ already present in
the back office of 90 percent of U.S. convenience stores, the
companies say _ shop managers will be able to log onto
RetailersMarketXchange to purchase Twinkies and soda, check on the
store's supply of Visine, and break down sales of potato chips
month by month.
</P>
<P>
   Stores will also be able to manage accounting and human resource
data and download the latest corporate training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, Oracle and McLane _ which each have a minority stake in
RetailersMarketXchange _ say the venture will streamline operations
and cut costs, both for businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only will this lower cost for the consumers, but
inventories will be lower, food will be fresher, and things will
run smoother,'' Oracle Chief Executive Officer Larry Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle will bring its Oracle Exchange software suite to the
deal. Chevron will bring about 8,000 convenience stores _ or about
5 percent of the convenience store market nationwide. And McLane
will contribute its distribution expertise and ties to both
retailers and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   McLane of Temple, Texas, supplies food and other items to about
30,000 convenience stores in the United States including 7-Eleven
outlets and Texaco Star Marts.
</P>
<P>
   Although no other convenience store operators aside from San
Francisco's Chevron have signed on the dotted line, McLane
officials say other chains will be eager to join. They also believe
suppliers, like Philip Morris and Procter &AMP; Gamble, will join the
exchange to gain access to smaller chains or individual stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the world's first global exchange for the $200 billion
convenience and small store retailing market,'' said Chevron Chief
Executive Officer Dave O'Reilly. ``The big benefit here is to
leverage the Internet to create an efficient purchasing and
communications exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the venture could face some roadblocks from small
stores, which may not be tuned in to the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, there might be some issues with mom-and-pop
stores,'' said Aberdeen Group senior analyst Lara Abrams. ``For
them, there's a tremendous education process that needs to be
undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   RetailersMarketXchange plans to make money through advertising,
software licenses and by taking a piece of each sales transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Lisa Williams at Boston's Yankee Group research firm
said the exchange could potentially save corporations money in two
ways. First, by more efficiently controlling inventory, stores
won't pay for merchandise they don't sell.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, it creates ``a technology co-op,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of (each store or chain) buying their own piece of
procurement software, they have a shared infrastructure called a
marketplace where the entry costs of browsing are very low.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional companies are drawn to the online exchanges for
other reasons, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do they get the technology and the business
efficiency. They get to participate in the dot-com economy through
the creation of a dot-com marketplace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron stock edged up 6 cents yesterday, closing at $81.06.
Yesterday's news had a larger impact on Oracle stock, which rose
$8.19 _ almost 11 percent _ closing at $83.13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
