<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1030 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     03-08 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: so on.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Iowa, however, practice did not make perfect. And meanwhile
Gore was proving far more flexible a campaigner than anyone had
imagined. Terrified by Bradley's successes in fund-raising and
gaining media attention, Gore revamped his campaign, honed his
message and became a far more dynamic campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   The two armies had a decisive clash in Iowa at a debate Jan. 9,
where Gore used a remarkably effective technique: He called on a
farmer in the audience, Chris Peterson, asked him to stand up, and
then asked Bradley, ``Why did you vote against the disaster relief
for Chris Peterson when he and thousands of other farmers here in
Iowa needed it after those '93 floods?''
</P>
<P>
   The attack was deeply unfair, because Bradley had in fact voted
in favor of the flood assistance. He had voted against an amendment
for additional aid, but the Clinton administration had also opposed
that amendment until the last minute. Instead of pointing this out,
Bradley tried to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Bradley _ after rapturous initial coverage in the
press _ began to be portrayed in print and on the airwaves as
remote, out of touch and even arrogant and gruff. While other
candidates went out of their way to win the hearts and minds of
journalists, complimenting them on their questions with such
conviction that one might almost think they were sincere, Bradley
often greeted tough questions with scorn. And he seemed to think he
could manage the news, even though it regularly upended him.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had never disclosed that for the past few years he had
suffered an irregular heart beat, a common condition known as
atrial fibrillation. Aides said he planned to release full medical
information in January. But his heart interfered with that timing:
He had to check into a hospital in December when his heart began
thumping out of beat, and so the news poured out in a deluge that
made him seem both feeble and secretive.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gore won Iowa, 63 percent to 35 percent. It was not
particularly discreditable in a state like Iowa, but it came across
as a major defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Bradley found himself with another problem:
the far more glamorous candidacy of John McCain. In what is now
seen as a major error, Bradley had met with McCain in a joint
appearance to demand campaign finance reform, giving McCain
credibility at a time few were paying any attention to him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley were both running as insurgents against the
political system, and both were running in part on biography.
Bradley's Hall-of-Fame background had seemed about as amazing a
past as a politician could have, but McCain was the one candidate
who could trump him in that category.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, with its open primary, voters became excited
by McCain in a way that they did not with Bradley. Not only did
McCain siphon off votes of independents from Bradley, he also
siphoned away media attention. There might have been room for one
rebel with a great biography in the campaign, but there was not
room for two _ especially when the second sometimes had trouble
working a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of the New Hampshire primary, Bradley addressed a
raucous crowd of several hundred volunteers in a college gymnasium.
The supporters repeatedly interrupted Bradley to cheer and chant
their support, but each time he sternly waved his hands to hush
them.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Sheila Wellstone, wife of Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.,
tried to sustain that enthusiasm by doing an end run around
Bradley. Each time Bradley motioned for the crowd to be quiet, she
would raise her hands to urge fans to keep the applause coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bradley lost the New Hampshire primary by 4
percentage points. Labor unions _ which had vigorously campaigned
for Gore _ provided the vice president with the margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley had floated above politics, and he thought he could
float above the campaign,'' said Fred Siegel, a professor of
history at the Cooper Union for Arts and Sciences. ``Suppose
Bradley had come back quickly and suppose he had run campaign ads
with shots of the Buddhist temple'' _ a reminder of the illegal
campaign contributions raised when Gore visited with Chinese
Buddhists in California. ``He could have won New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's performance was still impressive for an outsider,
better than Eugene McCarthy's in 1968 that forced President Lyndon
B. Johnson to quit the race. But whereas Bill Clinton managed to
lose New Hampshire in 1992 and ``spin'' it as a victory,
proclaiming himself ``the come-back kid,'' Bradley was simply cast
as the loser.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the news the next day _ and in the next few
weeks _ was not about Bradley but about McCain's amazing 19-point
win in New Hampshire and his challenge to Bush. The Democratic race
had a five-week lull after New Hampshire, and so all attention
turned to the vicious battle on the Republican side. Bradley
vanished from the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign wore on, Bradley abandoned his focus on the
positive and began blasting Gore for distorting Bradley's record as
well as his own. But while Gore could knife an opponent with
warmth, grace and apparent reluctance, the newly negative Bradley
came across as petulant and strident, and his shift from one
extreme to the other seemed to be a case of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he felt things slipping away slightly, he did things like
going negative,'' recalls an old friend. ``But when he heard the
words he was saying and saw himself on TV doing this, I think he
got depressed. He hated himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The few photographers left covering Bradley became frustrated
that their standard photos _ Bradley waving exultantly to a crowd,
or shaking hands with a beaming supporter _ never saw light of
print. One photographer said that he found that the best way to get
newspapers to use his pictures was to transmit shots showing
Bradley looking alone or dejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want the rah-rah shots any more,'' the
photographer said. ``I realized I had to start sending shots that
reflected the tone of the stories, which was negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, perhaps the most memorable photo of the Bradley campaign
_ taken by a different photographer _ was a haunting shot of the
candidate on a ferry in Washington state, surrounded by commuters
but standing alone in his own world, gripping a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the collapse of Bradley's campaign obscures
its accomplishments. Bradley contributed mightily to setting the
Democratic agenda by pressing Gore to talk more than he had planned
about health care, poverty, race relations, gay rights and gun
control. Bradley also mounted an unusually potent challenge against
a sitting vice president in a time of economic plenty, briefly
shaking the foundations of the Democratic establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Bradley never managed to attract core
constituencies. Labor remained behind Gore, and so did most black
voters, in both cases repaying a sense of loyalty to the Clinton
administration. And unlike Gore, who over the course of the
campaign turned from wooden to flesh as surely as Pinnocchio in the
movie, Bradley never lost his reserve and rarely linked at an
emotional level with voters.
</P>
<P>
   In Tacoma, Wash., a few weeks ago, Bradley spoke to a group of
children and began interviewing them, eliciting vivid tales of
seeing people shot with guns. It was wrenching to listen to, but
when they finished Bradley simply nodded, turned away and returned
to his dry speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's oldest friends in Crystal City are saddened by this
inability to connect with voters, but not particularly surprised.
They describe him as a mix of his parents: Susan, vivacious and
fun, is reflected in the humor and warmth that he shows among small
groups of people, and Warren, the reserved, Victorian gentleman,
emerges in more formal settings such as a larger audience or a
television appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how he was raised,'' said Carol Cunningham, Bradley's
next-door neighbor in childhood. ``Years of conditioning would make
it very hard for him to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hugging your second-grade teacher? You've got to understand
how we were raised. She's a person of respect. You wouldn't hug
her. She's still Mrs. Thuesen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
