<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-EUROPE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Northpoint, Cisco Establish Joint Venture in Europe  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Cisco Systems and Northpoint Communications, two Bay area Internet
infrastructure firms, both launched major joint ventures in Europe
yesterday to expand their sales overseas.
<P>
   Cisco, the world's largest seller of data networking equipment,
announced plans to pump $835 million into a new company formed with
Cap Gemini Group, a technology consulting group in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Cisco said it will buy $671 million in Cap Gemini
stock and pour another $164 million directly into the new Cap
Gemini subsidiary, which will target European phone companies and
Internet service providers. Cisco will control 4.9 percent of the
new unit, which has yet to be named, and Cap Gemini will control
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini also said it plans to move 4,600 employees into the
new division, while Cisco will assign 50 to 100 employees to help
the venture with projects.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the investment, Cisco said Cap Gemini promised
to recommend Cisco's routers and other networking equipment to its
clients, something Cisco called a ``loyalty agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The move mirrors another Cisco joint venture with the Big Five
accounting firm KPMG. Cisco took a $1 billion stake, or 20 percent,
in the consulting arm of KPMG two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Volpi, Cisco's senior vice president of business
development, said such pacts are notable because ``one of the
traditions of (consultancies) is to be vendor-neutral.'' But he
said Cisco has such a large range of products and dominance in the
data networking market that customers do not normally object.
</P>
<P>
   The latest venture could also help boost Cisco's sales in
Europe. Cisco executive Bill Nuti told Bloomberg News that Europe
is expected to be Cisco's fastest-growing market, bringing in $10
billion in annual revenue within three years. European sales jumped
50 percent last year, trailing only Asia, Bloomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco shares rose 31 cents, to $132.38, yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Northpoint, the fast-growing San Francisco firm,
which provides high-speed Internet access over conventional phone
lines using DSL, or digital subscriber lines, teamed up with a
Dutch telecommunications firm to offer the service across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Both Northpoint and VersaTel Telecom International plan to pour
$50 million into the new venture, dubbed Versapoint. Northpoint's
chief executive and co-founder, Michael Malaga, 35, is stepping
down to run Versapoint, though he will remain Northpoint's
chairman. Chief Operating Officer Liz Fetter, who joined Northpoint
from US West in 1997, will take over as CEO. Previously, she worked
for Pacific Bell and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European market is just hungry for Internet access,''
Fetter said. Northpoint, which boosted sales from under $1 million
in 1998 to $21 million in 1999, expects to see similar growth in
Europe. Versapoint will start out with less than $1 million in
sales. It expects to have 500 to 1,000 workers in 18 months. By
comparison, Northpoint has about 1,000 workers, up from about 200
in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Versapoint will initially roll out DSL service to businesses in
Germany and the Netherlands, begin testing service in the United
Kingdom and France and soon expand to other industrial nations,
like Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Northpoint shares jumped $4.38, to $29.88, on the news.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
