<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE SPEAKS OF BRUINS' UNHAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ The locker room of the Boston Bruins ``is
not a happy place,'' Ray Bourque said Wednesday. ``And that's
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that ``negativity,'' to use Bourque's word, is due to a
team piling up loss after loss and going nowhere, but the former
Bruins' captain hinted at more, that he is far from alone in his
frustration about how far the once-proud Boston organization has
fallen.
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman was quoted by Russ Conway of the Lawrence
Eagle-Tribune Tuesday that his decision to leave the Bruins ``is
just the start of what's going to happen. The way things are,
players don't want to play in Boston any more. Nobody's happy here;
ownership doesn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque did not deny that he said these words when his new team,
the Avalanche, arrived in Edmonton after an 8-3 win over Calgary
Tuesday night in his first game with Colorado. However, Bourque
said, ``I do not recall going on the record'' with Conway ``and I
will have to take it up with Russ.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bruins spokesperson, apprised of Bourque's comments in the
newspaper, said general manager Harry Sinden ``did not believe Ray
said that.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, Bourque's words spoke only as loud as his
actions. By asking to be traded after 21 years with the Bruins,
Bourque not only sought to achieve a personal goal (winning a
Stanley Cup), but he also made a strong, loud, and concrete
statement that he was giving up on the Bruins. And if Bourque gave
up on the Bruins, who is left to keep the flickering flame?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not winning hockey games, there's a lot more
negativity,'' Bourque said after taking treatment in the Avalanche
dressing room at the Skyreach Centre for a slightly strained groin.
``It's tough . . . and there're a lot of factors to come into play
for that negativity.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, it seemed, the frustration piled up until it
was too much to bear. Bourque revealed how startling was his
transformation in merely the last year by reciting an anecdote from
the 1999 All-Star game when Wayne Gretzky asked him if he was going
to retire after the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Wayne I had another year left on my contract, not
knowing that he was going to retire. And I asked him the question,
and he said, `Sure,' but he didn't say one way or the other when he
was going to do it,'' said Bourque. ``But I never talked to him
about a trade, and what it was like to be traded, because I never
thought I'd be asking for a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bourque did precisely that two weeks ago, asking Sinden to
move him. The unthinkable had become the desirable. In one brief
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he was not alone on the Bruins with his
frustration. ``I think a lot of guys are frustrated,'' he said.
``We went into the year expecting to do a lot better than we did.
It's frustrating and disappointing when you don't get the job done.
You know, we were hampered by some injuries and I don't think we
had the depth to compensate for those injuries. And that was
probably a major problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A perennial major problem in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Bourque said, this time was different. The Bruins
seldom have had the top-to-bottom talent to compete with the NHL's
best teams. For years, the Bruins often overachieved with grit and
hard work. The Bruins seldom had the talent that Dave Andreychuk
saw on his very first shift on the second line with Colorado, on
the left wing with Peter Forsberg centering and Adam Deadmarsh on
right wing. Andreychuk, who came with Bourque from Boston to the
Avalanche, gushed, ``I couldn't believe how much talent was on the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Bourque said, his voice dropping to a low level,
``The frustration and discouragement grew to a point where I had to
make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked directly what it would take to return the Bruins to
at least some semblance of pride and success, ``It's deeper . . .
well, some changes . . .'' he began to say.
</P>
<P>
   But then he said, diplomacy once again returning to Bourque's
words, ``We had something good going the last couple of years, and
they have a good base of young talent. Now it's matter of keeping
that and bringing the right players in and just reinforcing things.
There's not much for them to get back to be competitive. For them
to get back to where they want to be might not take all that much
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But should there be organizational changes? Is the problem with
ownership? With the management of Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell?
Should those changes be made at the top levels before the Bruins
can be successful?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not for me to say,'' replied Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   No need for the words. Bourque's actions already had shouted
louder than any words. The most loyal and faithful Bruin no longer
saw any hope in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
