<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-MEDIA_SFCHRON &LR;      03-08 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MEDIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Defections Hit Upside as Magazine Tries to Get Its Buzz Back 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upside has been downsized.
<P>
   A wave of defections hit the magazine's top ranks last week, and
the recriminations continue. Editor in Chief Adrian Mello resigned.
Before company chief executive David Bunnell could even officially
announce Mello's replacement, however, five other staffers tendered
their resignations.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell says he fired at least two of the group, and in a way,
he's right: Features Editor Howard Baldwin and Senior Editor
Cameron Crotty had given two weeks' notice last Monday, then
arrived at work Friday to an e-mail from Bunnell telling them they
were fired. Executive Editor Galen Gruman also resigned and was
escorted out of the building for sending what Bunnell called
``poisonous e-mail.'' (Gruman said he merely posted his resignation
letter and those of some of the others.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sorry to see them go,'' Bunnell said.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, though. Most of the high-flying tech-biz magazines
are desperately hiring people, not losing them in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   While Upside is enjoying a strong year _ its news pages have
doubled and its ad revenues have nearly quadrupled, from roughly
$500,000 an issue to $2 million, according to Bunnell _ the
magazine is also trying to hold on in an increasingly competitive
marketplace. Although Upside was founded 10 years ago, making it
the grandaddy of the current wave of ``new economy'' magazines,
other upstarts like the Industry Standard, Business 2.0 and Red
Herring are doing a better job landing high-profile hires and
creating buzz about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the departures is Bunnell's desire to add more
``sizzle'' to Upside, while Mello and the team he brought on sought
to beef up the reporting with investigations and news that
executives could use in running their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Upside getting by more on style than substance,'' Mello
said. Bunnell says his new editor in chief, Jerry Borrell, ``is a
great networker with a lot of energy'' who will help Upside get its
own buzz back. In addition, the magazine launched an ad campaign
this week in AdWeek and Advertising Age magazines, and Bunnell said
Upside Media _ which includes a conference and online business _
will double its staff of 65 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Borrell joins Upside from Sumeria, a maker of multimedia CD-ROMs
that he founded and ran for the past eight years. Before that, he
worked with Bunnell at Macworld magazine _ Mello, Gruman and Crotty
are also Macworld alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell is a mercurial boss who is not afraid to assert his will
over his employees, and as he's turned 50, he hasn't mellowed. Last
year, one run-in ended with Bunnell firing David Coursey, his
conference impresario. Now Upside is on its third editor in a year,
and more than half the people on the masthead in the magazine's
March issue have left the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, it was arrogant of us to think that David would
treat us differently than other people,'' Baldwin said. As he joins
the ranks of people Bunnell has fired, Baldwin said, ``This is a
cool group of people. This is a clique I can go with.''
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, Bunnell had one former editor, Kathleen Doler,
e-mail me about her ``great working relationship'' with him. She
left the magazine when the offices moved from San Mateo to San
Francisco. Another former editor, Richard Brandt, remains on staff
as a columnist while he continues to ready a startup for launch.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell maintains the title of editor of Upside. While some of
the departed say that was largely a ceremonial role until recently,
Bunnell maintains he was always active in picking covers and
generating story ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers, though, say that as Bunnell began insinuating himself
more into the news operation, editorial employees grew disaffected,
which led to last week's five departures.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell attacked those who left as ``not very energetic. They
all left at 5.'' While Gruman disputed the charge, noting his
passion for the magazine, Baldwin acknowledged he left at 5 p.m.
daily _ but only because he arrived each morning at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vitriol and rumors that more departures are still on
the way, Bunnell maintains tremendous optimism. ``We had a little
bit of a hiccup, but things are good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's buoyed by a recent $2 million investment and an $8 million
loan; he's tripling the online staff; he's opening new sales
offices in Los Angeles, Seattle and Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and
doubling his New York office; and his events business is
``incredibly profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he's got a new editor hiring a new team at the flagship
magazine. He's a feisty independent taking on bigger publishers
like International Data Group, Conde Nast and Imagine Media.
``We're in for a battle,'' he said. ``Don't count us out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARKET MOVERS: &QL; 
Is MarketWatch.com gloating over the current woes of TheStreet.com?
And if so, is that an attempt to knock down TheStreet's stock price
to make it ripe for a takeover by MarketWatch?
</P>
<P>
   That's the scenario painted by a shareholder in TheStreet.com,
who e-mailed me with some keen observations. The backdrop is
TheStreet's announcement that it had hired an investment bank to
pursue strategic options _ the standard euphemism for putting a
company on the block _ and a New York Times report that MarketWatch
had made a bid to buy TheStreet, but that was denied.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mailer cited two stories that appeared on the MarketWatch
Web site, in which MarketWatch CEO Larry Kramer and Editor in Chief
Thom Calandra are quoted as saying TheStreet made a bad business
move by charging for information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really appears as if MarketWatch wants to make
TheStreet.com look bad, but that it doesn't want to make itself
look bad by admitting that its bid to buy TheStreet was rejected,''
said my e-mailer. ``That's fine, but using your own news site to do
this can't be ethical. It also looks like MarketWatch wants to use
its site to talk down the price of (TheStreet) and make it easier
for them to do a hostile takeover. If so, that's got to be against
the SEC laws.''
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a charge, and it has Kramer and Calandra hopping
mad. ``That really frosts me,'' Kramer said. He said he told his
reporters the same thing he's told others in the press for months,
that TheStreet publishes great journalism, but with a flawed
business model. MarketWatch gives its information away free, while
TheStreet has charged for most of its content.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Calandra noted, ``What did we report that others
haven't reported that could have hurt the stock of TheStreet.com?''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer and Calandra refused to comment on whether MarketWatch
was a suitor for TheStreet.
</P>
<P>
   My e-mailer may be wrong on one point: George Harmon, who
teaches business journalism at Northwestern University, said it's
not likely MarketWatch's comments could hurt TheStreet's stock
price. ``Is any investor going to act on that information alone,
when you know where it's coming from?'' Harmon asks. ``The public
now pretty well assumes that an awful lot of what they read in the
media is tainted by commercial concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's legal, though, Len Sellers, a professor of
journalism at San Francisco State University, agrees that
MarketWatch's ethics seem questionable. MarketWatch, Sellers said,
``considers as legitimate news the turmoil in a competitor's
business, especially when they're a possible takeover target? That
doesn't strike me as straight-up journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellers said editors are obsessed with the price of their own
stock, harming the quality of the reporting. ``It's like they're
pushed into the position of being their own billboards, given that
everything revolves around the stock, and the stock revolves around
the public's perception,'' Sellers said. ``Did you ever see the
Associated Press write demeaning stories about UPI? It just didn't
happen in the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID THAT? &QL; 
A few weeks back, I used the old saw about journalists' role being
to ``comfort the afflicted and afflict the comfortable.'' Someone
e-mailed to say I should have attributed that to its author, H.L.
Mencken. I had conducted some cursory research and couldn't confirm
Mencken's authorship, so I left it unattributed.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Chronicle librarian Kathleen Rhodes has done some digging
since then, and while she found that many people cite Mencken as
the originator of the line, she also found that Mencken himself
claimed no such credit. In a dictionary of quotations that Mencken
gathered and edited, he put the quote in, but cited the author as
``Anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Rhodes found, was that the line originated with
Finley Peter Dunne, an American journalist and humorist who lived
from 1867 to 1936 and who was best known for columns and books
written under the name of his alter ego, an Irish American tavern
owner named ``Mr. Dooley.''
</P>
<P>
