<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CALLING FOR HALT, GORE CHASES SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as Vice President Al Gore challenges Gov.
George W. Bush to stop raising the unlimited campaign donations
known as soft money, Gore aides are launching a program to help the
Democrats raise $35 million in such funds over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic fund-raisers have been invited to a luncheon
here later this month with Gore, who is expected to ask each of
them to raise at least $100,000 in soft money before the Democratic
convention in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, the party will host a tribute to President Clinton,
who has already raised more than $10 million for the Democratic
National Committee this year, virtually all of it soft money. The
May gala, presided over by Democratic fund-raiser Terry McAuliffe,
is expected to produce as much as $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Edward G. Rendell, the general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, told a group of donors on Tuesday night that
the party needed to raise $35 million before the convention in
August to finance a ``mini-campaign'' of television advertisements
designed to highlight policy differences with the Republicans. The
commercials, still in the planning stages, were expected to
emphasize gun control, reform of health maintenance organizations,
taxes and campaign finance, issues on which Democrats believed they
closely reflected public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell told the group, meeting at the home of New Jersey state
Sen. Raymond J. Lesniak, a top Gore fund-raiser, that he expected
Bush and the Republicans to raise and spend twice as much on issue
advertisements before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few months, Gore would hit the spending ceiling for
the primary season, and his top fund-raisers would focus almost all
their efforts on raising soft money from corporations, unions and
wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans were under way because Gore and his advisers were
certain that Bush and the Republicans would not agree to the soft
money cease-fire challenge issued by the vice president on Tuesday
night. Bush swatted away a similar offer from Sen. John McCain, his
all-but-vanquished primary rival, and he dismissed Gore's challenge
Wednesday as a stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to make America forget what went on in Washington,
D.C., for the past eight years,'' Bush said on ``Good Morning
America'' on ABC. ``Americans aren't going to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that his party would continue to raise soft money
as long as the Republicans did.
</P>
<P>
   With his nomination-sealing victories in Tuesday's primaries,
Gore became, in effect, the leader of the Democratic Party. The
party's fund-raising, polling, organizing and communications arms
would quickly come under his control and would turn their efforts
to electing him president. In return, Gore would share with Clinton
the job of solicitor-in-chief for the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Al's turn to step up to the plate,'' said one long-time
Democratic fund-raiser who insisted on anonymity. ``The president
has carried all the work'' of the Democratic National Committee.
``Now Al has to get out there and energize people to raise a ton of
dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore would have about $13 million in campaign funds to spend
between now and the Democratic convention in August, including $7
million in anticipated federal primary election matching funds,
aides said. Because Gore accepts federal matching funds, he must
limit his overall spending during the primaries to about $44
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who isn't taking matching funds and can spend whatever he
likes, has gone through virtually all of the $70 million he raised
for his primary campaign. He was embarking on a new money-raising
spree to support his efforts before the Republicans meet in late
July to formally nominate him for president. His top fund-raisers,
the Pioneers, will soon be shifting their efforts to raising
hundreds of millions of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican fund-raiser said that the aid of the Pioneers, who
each raised at least $100,000 in restricted contributions to Bush's
campaign, would be crucial in achieving the party's goal of raising
more than $175 million in soft money to support Bush and other
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As both the Bush and Gore campaigns shifted their sights to the
November elections, their supporters were devising ways to raise
what strategists say would be a record amount of these unlimited
and increasingly controversial contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the fund-raising equivalent of Sherman's
march through Georgia,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of
Democracy 21, a non-partisan group here that monitors campaign
spending. ``Donors beware _ they are coming for you, and the sky's
the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer said he had no expectation of Bush accepting Gore's
offer of a soft money cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of a soft money moratorium occurring this year
range from slim to none, with the emphasis on none,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A long-time Gore ally and fund-raiser said that the Democratic
National Committee has also created a ``federal victory fund'' that
would raise hard money contributions only for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between hard money and soft money is that hard
dollars, raised under federal limits, could be used to expressly
advocate the election or defeat of a candidate. Most soft money
could only be used indirectly, advocating positions that the party
supports and criticizing policies of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they have a contingency plan to raise soft money,''
the fund-raiser said. Clinton and Gore, as the party's two biggest
draws, would do the bulk of the soft-money prospecting, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
