<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
17 ARMS EXPERTS NAMED FOR U.N. PANEL ON DISARMING IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Seventeen international arms experts have been
chosen for a new commission charged with completing the disarmament
of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hans Blix, a Swedish lawyer and the former head of the
International Atomic Energy Agency, will lead the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council has until Thursday to comment on the names
proposed by Secretary-General Kofi Annan before the appointments
are formally made.
</P>
<P>
   The new panel, the U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection
Commission, is replacing the U.N. Special Commission, or Unscom,
which began the process of disarming Iraq in 1991 after the Persian
Gulf war. Iraq, which has to be certified free of prohibited
weapons before international sanctions imposed in 1990 are lifted,
stopped cooperating with Unscom almost two years ago and has not
signaled that it will allow a successor organization to operate
there.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new commissioners are three _ from Britain, Canada and
Finland _ who were also Unscom commissioners. The U.S. commissioner
on Unscom, Charles Duelfer, who was also its deputy chairman,
resigned last week. The United States apparently decided not to
renominate him.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. representative on the new board will be Robert Einhorn,
assistant secretary of state for nonproliferation, who has 25
years' experience working on arms control in government, the
Council on Foreign Relations and the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The list of commissioners, forwarded to the Security Council by
Jayantha Dhanapala, the undersecretary general for disarmament who
participated in the selection, has fewer strictly technical experts
or scientists and more political appointees drawn government
arms-control offices.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they will serve as an advisory board to Blix, who
became the new chief arms inspector for Iraq on March 1. He is a
full-time chairman. The commissioners are part-time consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is considered more broadly representative of the U.N.
membership than Unscom, which was dominated by experts from
industrial nations with advanced weapons systems. The new body has
members from Argentina, Brazil, India, Nigeria, Senegal and
Ukraine, as well as from Canada, Finland, Germany and Japan. All
five permanent members of the Security Council _ Britain, China,
France, Russia and the United States _ are represented, as is the
U.N. department of disarmament affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Blix, who said at a news conference last week that he intended
to use the commission as a sounding board, is creating a work plan
and an organizational chart, which are not expected to be completed
until early next month. At that point, Blix, the United Nations and
the commission's full-time staff will be faced with the challenge
of selling the plan to President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, David Albright, president of the independent
Institute for Science and International Security and a former
nuclear inspector in Iraq, said that based on Blix's record in
North Korea in the early 1990s, he might surprise critics who still
held him responsible for earlier missing a secret Iraqi program as
director of the atomic energy agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``In North Korea, it was quite clear that Blix knew he had to be
extremely determined,'' said Albright, who is writing a book on the
clandestine North Korean nuclear program. When Blix decided
international monitors there were not tough enough, Albright said,
``he brought in a more senior team that had gained experience in
Iraq at dealing with massive lying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He also pushed to have the best analytical methods used,''
Albright said. ``That was critical in uncovering evidence of North
Korean lying. He showed that he was more than able to confront
North Korea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MR.DEATH-TEX     03-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MR. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORAL BLINDNESS OF A `HUMANITARIAN'
</HEADLINE>
 DEATH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curiosity can be a filmmaker's greatest gift, and Errol Morris
appears to be blessed with more of it than anyone else making
movies today. Morris, who calls himself a ``nonfiction filmmaker,''
is obsessed with obsessives, fascinated with people who do jobs few
of us would dream of doing. With ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of
Fred A. Leuchter, Jr.,'' Morris may have found his most compelling
and tragic obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter, an unassuming-looking professorial type prone to
tweeds, ties and unstylish glasses, emerges as an odd sort of
humanitarian: a man who wanted to make the death penalty more
humane. An electrical engineer, Leuchter devised electric chairs
that did their jobs quickly and efficiently, making executions
safer for the executioners and as painless as possible for the
condemned. His expertise led officials to ask him to perfect other
execution devices _ gas chambers, lethal-injection contraptions,
even gallows _ and he succeeded with each, despite being most
comfortable with electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter's downfall came in 1988, when a neo-Nazi named Ernst
Zundel enlisted him in an attempt to prove that the Holocaust was a
hoax. Morris provides incredible footage of Leuchter visiting the
Auschwitz concentration camp, illegally taking brick and mortar
samples from what is now a Polish national monument, and doing the
most perfunctory lab tests before deciding that the extermination
of 6 million Jews couldn't have happened.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make sense,'' Leuchter keeps saying, as if
mass murder on any level ever makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Although Morris counters Leuchter's ``research'' with
witheringly dismissive commentary by Robert Jan van Pelt, an
architectural historian who points out dozens of flaws in
Leuchter's findings, Morris isn't out to discredit Leuchter. He
just wants to know what makes him tick, and why Leuchter, a person
on top of his morbid world, would risk his career by aligning
himself with such a questionable cause as Holocaust revisionism.
</P>
<P>
   Morris has been accused of condescending to his subjects, and
criticized for his interviewing method, which essentially involves
leaving the camera running until his subject says something stupid
or self-incriminating. But what comes through in ``Mr. Death'' is
that Morris genuinely likes Leuchter, even sympathizes with him,
although Morris has trouble comprehending why such an affable
oddball would have such dark fascinations.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you may think of Morris as a journalist, he's amazing
as a filmmaker; he's one of the few unique artists working today.
``Mr. Death'' has all his trademarks: nonstop, insistently ethereal
music; a carefully chosen hodgepodge of film stocks and colors;
images that act as counterpoint to what's being said, as well as
images that illustrate points in the most ironic ways. With his
unconventional style, he avoids the earnestness that plagues too
many documentaries (no wonder he doesn't like to be branded a
documentarian). With ``Mr. Death,'' he provides one of the best
depictions yet of how we believe only what we choose to believe,
and how closed-mindedness can be dangerous in more ways than one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A. Leuchter, Jr.'' is
rated PG-13 for adult themes and disturbing images. &QL;
</P>
