A1041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-NYT &LR;      03-08 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SAYS WAGE BILL RAISES MINIMUM TOO SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa.) (jt) 
 By MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a checkout clerk at his side, President
Clinton said Wednesday that a minimum wage increase set for a House
vote on Thursday would cut business taxes too much and raise the
pay of low-wage workers too little.
</P>
<P>
   Calling on the Congress to ``stop nickel and diming the American
people,'' the president urged lawmakers to increase the minimum
wage of $5.15 an hour to $6.15 over two years instead of three, and
to drop the proposed tax reductions of $122 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   To put the heat on the Republicans and highlight what is sure to
become an election issue this fall, Clinton held a rally on the
South Lawn of the White House with Democratic leaders of Congress
and Cheryl Costas, a clerk from Pennsylvania who is the sole wage
earner for her disabled husband and four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can you ask this woman to do?'' the president said
of Costas, who studies full time at a local university and works at
Colton Alba Grocery and Gas in Colton Alba, Pa. ``She's kept her
family together. Her husband has a disability. She's supporting her
four kids. She's going to school full time. Now, how can Congress
justify saying no to her?''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, many of whom oppose any minimum wage
increase, are scheduled to take up a bill on Thursday that would
raise the minimum hourly wage to $5.48 this year, $5.81 next April
and $6.15 in April 2002. Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority
leader, has called the legislation sponsored by Reps. John Shimkus
of Illinois and Rick A. Lazio of New York, both Republicans, ``the
least worst way to do the wrong thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats want to speed the increase over two years _ 50
cents this year and 50 cents in 2001 _ and drastically scale back
the tax reductions. The Republican plan would make sharp cuts in
the estate tax, accelerate a plan to make health insurance tax
deductible for the self-employed and reduce other taxes for small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The House measure is similar to a Senate bill passed in
February. A $1 increase in the minimum wage over three years was
included in bankruptcy reform legislation that passed, 83 to 14,
along with $76 billion in tax breaks over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Republican congressional leaders on Tuesday,
Clinton threatened to block any bill that provides for large tax
cuts or that spreads the raise over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they have written a compromise bill that helps
minimum wage earners but also provides benefits to the businesses
that must bear the increased payroll costs.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict over the minimum wage dates to 1938, when the first
such hourly wage was set at 25 cents as part of the Fair Labor
Standards Act. Since then, the minimum wage has been increased 19
times. The last change came in 1996 with a two-step increase that
raised the wage to $5.15 from $4.15.
</P>
<P>
   Each side in the debate points to statistics to back up its
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Clinton released a study by the National Economic
Council saying that 10 million workers earn less than $6.15 an hour
and therefore would benefit from the $1 increase. About 69 percent
of them are over 20 years of age, about 45 percent work full time
and about 60 percent are women, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponents, who maintain that an increased minimum
wage would mainly go to young people, point to studies saying that
two-thirds of the minimum-wage workers are part-time employees,
more than half are under 25 and only 8 percent are women who are
heads of households. Critics of a wage increase maintain that
businesses, especially small businesses, are hurt by the raises and
tend to lay off workers rather than increase their pay.
</P>
<P>
   Costas, whose pay was raised recently to $5.50 an hour from
$5.15, said her boss was not thrilled by her decision to go to
Washington to make the case for more pay. The owner of the store
told her, she said, that he would probably have to raise prices if
the minimum wage increase passed. She said she told him that the
economy was such that he could probably afford the higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
