<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-TURNOUT09-COX     03-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TURNOUT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia turnout far below forecast
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Democratic crossover voters stayed largely on their
side of the political fence _ or at home _ Tuesday, denying
Republican John McCain any chance at upsetting George W. Bush in
Georgia's GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of crossover voters, which had helped spur McCain's
early primary surge, proved to be one of the more salient insights
gleaned Wednesday from exit polls and other voting tabulations by
the pundits and party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the prognosticators cautioned not to read too much into the
primary results. After all, neither Bush nor McCain, nor Democrats
Al Gore and Bill Bradley paid the Peach State much attention before
Super Tuesday. And just more than one-fourth of Georgia's
registered voters even bothered to vote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a repeat come November's general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia will be extremely visible and we'll see a lot of the
candidates,'' said state GOP Chairman Chuck Clay. ``It will be a
toughly competed, fought-over state come November. It will
certainly be a donnybrook in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much of a tussle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only 929,443, or 27.3 percent, of Georgia's 3.4 million voters
hit the polls, according to unofficial returns. Elections officials
had predicted that 38 percent of registered voters would help
decide the Republican and Democratic presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet participation was significantly better than in the 1996
presidential primaries in Georgia when only 19 percent of
registered voters turned out. President Clinton, a Democrat, faced
no primary opposition that year, and Bob Dole handily won the GOP
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's vice president trampled Bradley on Tuesday, corralling
84 percent of the Democratic votes cast in Georgia. Gore bested the
former New Jersey senator in virtually every demographic category,
including male and female voters, whites and blacks, and across
income and educational levels, according to a CNN exit poll.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's victory wasn't as resounding, the Texas governor
still pasted the Arizona senator, 431,091 to 179,362. Mimicking
other primary tilts, Bush won handily among conservatives and the
so-called religious right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strategy of appealing to moderates, independents and
Democrats in states with open primaries fell flat in Georgia. Only
8 percent of GOP primary voters described themselves as Democrats,
according to the CNN exit poll. While McCain took a slight majority
of those votes, they were hardly enough to topple Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more surprisingly was Bush's majority support from
independent voters. The GOP's Clay also boasted that more than
twice as many Republicans voted as did Democrats, a rarity in a
Georgia primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear rejection of Clinton-Gore by Georgia voters,''
he said. ``Numbers don't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kirincich, executive director of Georgia's Democratic
Party, scoffed at that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the numbers don't lie,'' he said. ``But the vast majority
of Republicans turned out to be against the man (McCain) who's
probably the better general election candidate. Once again, the far
right wing is flying the Republican Party by itself. ... We've
learned that moderates win elections.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Georgia political scientist Charles Bullock
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is in much better shape right now than Bush. He was
challenged by Bradley, which pushed him toward the middle,'' said
Bullock. ``McCain forced Bush to the right and away from the
middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bullock notes that Georgia is becoming an increasingly
Republican state. Clinton, for example, narrowly lost Georgia in
the 1996 general election, after narrowly winning the state in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   All that bodes well for a spirited contest this summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will get visits from the candidates. We will see their
smiling faces on TV,'' Bullock said. ``And we'll be one of the
states up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
