A1043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CALIF-MARRIAGE-HNS &LR;      03-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN'S ATTACKS HELPED IN PASSING GAY MARRIAGE BAN 
 
By KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian activists knew recognition of gay marriage would
be a tough sell to California voters, but they contend that
presidential hopeful John McCain's attack on Christian
conservatives killed any chance they had in Tuesday's referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22, prohibiting California from recognizing gay
couples married in another state, passed with 61 percent of the
vote. Exit polls conducted by Voter News Service show that the
measure passed with broad support from men and women, and across
all racial and income groups. But Republicans backed it 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a very hotly contested Republican race that drew a
lot of excitement,'' said Wayne Besen, spokesman for the Human
Rights Campaign, a national gay activist group. ``On top of that,
John McCain's going into the heart of the Bible Belt and blasting
Falwell and Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That mobilized a lot of people who would vote yes to go to the
polls,'' Besen said. ``It certainly motivated members of the
religious right.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted by Voter News Service show that of white
voters statewide, about 9 percent identified themselves as
Christian conservatives _ the demographic mix that represents the
so-called religious right. Ninety-two percent of those voters
supported the gay marriage ban.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of those white, Christian conservatives said
McCain's attacks on Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson affected their
vote ``a great deal'' on Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure was destined to pass even before McCain stirred
up the ire of Christian conservatives, argues Bob Stern, president
of the Los Angeles-area Center for Government Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a simple proposition,'' Stern said. ``People understood
what it did, and in a sense, they wanted to send a message. And I
think most people understood it doesn't really affect anything.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The proposition stated, ``Only marriage between a man and a
woman is valid and recognized in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay marriage is not legal in any state, but 31 other states have
passed similar bans since the Hawaii Supreme Court raised the
possibility of legalizing gay marriage in 1993. California is the
third state to adopt the law at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Supreme Court ruled in December that homosexual
unions are entitled to the same benefits and protections as married
couples. The court ordered the state legislature to either legalize
gay marriage, or adopt a broad, domestic partnership law.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to pass the referendum became emotional, at times
focusing on the strained relationship between proposition author,
state Sen. Pete Knight and his gay son, David Knight. Opponents
even turned the advertising spotlight on father and son, alleging
that the elder Knight was forcing a statewide vote in response to a
family problem.
</P>
<P>
   In October, David Knight wrote a column in the Los Angeles Times
opposing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   His father, who tried to maintain a low personal profile on this
issue, then wrote in response that measure opponents ``should be
ashamed for exploiting a private family matter for political gain.
I think their tactics are reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People on both sides feel very strongly about this,'' Stern
said. ``I've very rarely seen lawn signs on statewide propositions.
Clearly the churches were very much involved and handing out these
(supporting) signs.''
</P>
<P>
   A new California law took effect in January allowing gays and
lesbians to register with the state as domestic partners, affording
some same-sex couples benefits _ such as hospital visitation rights
and health insurance coverage _ traditionally enjoyed by married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of a stereotype that California is one of the
most gay friendly states,'' said David Elliot, spokesman for the
National Gay and Lesbian Task Force. ``I'm not sure but that
there's too much weight put on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our movement does not begin in California, and it won't end in
California,'' Elliot said. ``Some state has to go first. Will it be
Rhode Island, Vermont, California? I don't know. But some state has
to go first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
