<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BIG12-OVERVIEW-HN     03-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12-OVERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It may never get any better than this.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Big 12 coaches agree that no fewer than six teams _ five of
them ranked _ have legitimate hopes of winning the league
tournament, which begins today with four first-round games at
Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   What makes matters most interesting is that No. 24 Kansas, the
lowest-ranked of the Top 25 quintuplets, may be the most likely
team to claim the title this weekend. And the league's
highest-ranked squad, No. 7 Iowa State, could be the least likely
to hoist the trophy Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The three teams ranked between Iowa State and Kansas _ No. 13
Texas, No. 15 Oklahoma and No. 17 Oklahoma State _ probably will be
three, four or five seeds in the NCAA Tournament. And all three
believe they will win the Big 12 bash.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a great, great weekend,'' Kansas
coach Roy Williams said. ``So many teams have a chance to win the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of a time where you have this many (NCAA)
Tournament-caliber teams at the league tournament. There's been
years where we've had two teams, three teams, maybe four teams
before there's a drop-off. But this year there are six. And a
seventh in the way Colorado can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, which has swept its way to victory in all three previous
Big 12 tournaments, gets to test one of Williams' theories that a
team not seeded among the top four can win four games in four days
to become tournament champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks entered each of the first three league tournaments
as the favorites _ twice as the regular-season champions at 15-1
and last year as a second-place team that had more depth than
regular-season champ Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Jayhawks are true underdogs, with three freshmen
in the starting lineup. Williams doesn't seem to mind, and he lists
three reasons his squad can successfully defend its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, because we believe we can,'' Williams said. ``Secondly,
we've had a history of going over there and playing well. And
thirdly, we do have some depth _ not as much as we had earlier, but
over a tournament played on consecutive days, I think that depth
does become a factor there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams sounds almost upbeat in analyzing his team's chances.
Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy is a little more reserved,
realizing his team is at a disadvantage because of its lack of
depth. But Eustachy thinks his team is not getting the respect it
deserves after winning the regular-season crown at 14-2 (with both
losses coming on the road in overtime).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if our team still gets the respect in spite of if
you look at the top (of the standings), there's nobody above us,''
Eustachy said. ``They have respect for our toughness, but in
general _ and I'm not talking about coaches here _ people don't
think we're the seventh-best team in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State seems to thrive on its perceived lack of respect,
though it knows it typically plays only its five starters in the
second half. Consensus Big 12 Player of the Year Marcus Fizer,
Jamaal Tinsley and Michael Nurse all have played at least 33
minutes in each of the Cyclones' last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at our size and depth, but how many people is
Missouri playing? How many people is Texas playing?'' Eustachy
asked. ``There are a few people that have the luxury of playing 10
to 11 guys. Most of 'em when you look at the box score are playing
seven guys; that's all you need. We like our chances as much as
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Rick Barnes' answer to Eustachy's question about the
Longhorns would probably be: ``As many as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas comes into the tournament in much better shape than it did
a year ago when, like Iowa State, it was a regular-season champion
with no depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no comparison to last year as far as how we are
physically at this point in the season,'' said Barnes, in his
second year at UT. ``We were crawling in last year. (Starting point
guard) Ivan Wagner was playing on one leg, and everybody else was
worn out. It took all we had to win the regular season. We had
nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   Longhorns forward Nnadubem Gabe Muoneke says he can feel the
difference in his body this time around and that fresh legs will
help. Texas, which pounds the ball inside regularly and may be the
most physical defensive team in the conference, expects to wear
teams down over the three days. Any team that gets to the final
against the Longhorns, should they make it there, will have a
difficult time answering the bell for the second half. That is when
7-foot center Chris Mihm (17.8 points, 10.8 rebounds per game),
Muoneke (13.6, 6.4) and Chris Owens (9.3, 5.5) should take over.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of taking over, Oklahoma's Eduardo Najera is about as
capable of doing that as any player in the conference, but he has
been getting help lately from the likes of Nolan Johnson, J.R.
Raymond and Hollis Price.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners sport the second-best overall record in the
conference at 24-5 and are the only team to have wins over Iowa
State, Texas and Oklahoma State. Kansas barely claimed a
three-point win over OU in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, which because of a pair of early losses was never in
first place in the league race, might be the most overlooked team
at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Sooners coach Kelvin Sampson doesn't want anybody to know
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's keep that a secret,'' Sampson said. ``We've hidden it
all the way to March.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
