<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-DETERRENCE-REVIE     03-08 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DETERRENCE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EXUBERANT EFFORT IN `DETERRENCE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 10 or later. Fact box below.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to overlook a lot of the flaws in the taut political
thriller ``Deterrence,'' simply because the drama at the core of
the story is so compelling. Essentially ``Fail Safe'' in a diner,
the movie follows a poker-faced U.S. president who must decide
whether to push the nuclear button and change history as we know
it. Writer-director Rod Lurie, a former film critic for KABC radio
and Los Angeles magazine, manages to keep things ambiguous enough
to let the audience draw its own conclusions about the characters'
actions. This is a thought-provoking movie sure to prompt some
heated discussion among moviegoers after the lights go up.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 2008. President Walter Emerson (Kevin Pollak) is in
the midst of an election-year campaign swing through Colorado when
a freak blizzard forces him and his staff to hole up in a
small-town diner. Emerson's appeal to voters isn't going so well.
He was an appointed vice president who took over the Oval Office
duties when the previous president died. From broadcast reports, we
learn the public does't consider him ``presidential.'' True enough,
Emerson looks (and sometimes acts) like the guy next door.
</P>
<P>
   Just four months on the job, Emerson has other problems as well.
North and South Korean forces are engaged in a standoff. U.S.
military forces are stationed along the 38th parallel, fearing a
Chinese attack on Japan. And then while stranded in the diner,
Emerson, his chief of staff Marshall Thompson (Timothy Hutton) and
national security adviser (Sheryl Lee Ralph) learn from a news
report that Iraqi forces have invaded Kuwait and are aiming
biological and chemical weapons at Israel, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   What to do, what to do? With most of the country's military
might focused on Korea, Emerson feels backed into a corner and
makes a monumental threat toward Iraq. The remainder of
``Deterrence'' explores the mechanics involved in such a decision,
as well as gradually revealing the motivations behind the
president's seemingly rash behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Pollak is a perfect choice to play the hard-to-read president,
who has the fragile temperament of a non-elected official with
something to prove to the American people. It's a wonderfully
written role, full of nuances and layers, and Pollak manages to
make him both a devil and a hero. (Your interpretation will
probably depend on your political leanings.)
</P>
<P>
   Lurie does a good job directing traffic in a movie that is
basically a single-location film. His limitations as first-time
filmmaker (as well as the movie's budget restrictions) betray him
in other areas, however, particularly the editing and camera work.
Shooting the first five minutes of the movie in black-and-white and
then abruptly shifting to color adds nothing of meaning to the
story.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, so good when it sticks to the crisis at hand,
veers into shaky territory when focusing on the ``average folk''
who happen to be in the diner during the standoff. These locals
are, for the most part, one-dimensional stereotypes, including a
white-trash, racist truckdriver and a French Canadian waitress
whose accent veers all over the North American map.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Deterrence'' is smart, suspenseful and engrossing enough
to overcome these problems is a testament both to Lurie's writing
and the unnerving nature of the movie's central story. This is a
bracing, cautionary tale, perfect for the charged climate of an
election year. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Deterrence'' (R; language, violence). &QL; 
The stars: Kevin Pollak, Timothy Hutton, Sheryl Lee Ralph. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Rod Lurie. Released by
Paramount Classics. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 41 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
