<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-NINTH-GATE-REVIE     03-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NINTH-GATE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEBODY SHOULD SHUT `THE GATE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 10 or later. Fact box below.) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes an imagination as perverse as Roman Polanski's to even
think of making a horror movie about reading. But it requires a
much richer vein of sick creativity to make the concept work, if it
can be done at all. Regardless, ``The Ninth Gate'' fails to do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Handsome and tedious, repetitive and pointless, much too long
and not the least bit scary, this beat-the-devil number stumbles
into all the bad genre traps that Polanski made superb fun of, lo
those many years ago, in 1967's ``The Fearless Vampire Killers.''
But here, the arcane puzzles, dopey chases, silly rituals and
unsatisfactory explanations that are the hallmarks of inept Gothic
storytelling are indulged with, if not dead seriousness, at least
deadly cinematic languor.
</P>
<P>
   And did I mention that the movie tries to make reading scary?
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Depp plays scummy New York rare books expert Dean Corso.
A completely mercenary lone wolf, he makes a nice living tricking
bereaved heirs out of valuable volumes for relative peanuts, then
reselling them to ruthless collectors or wised-up dealers. One of
his clients, wealthy publisher Boris Balkan (Frank Langella, even
more miscast than he was in that ``Lolita'' remake and taking every
opportunity to prove it), offers Corso an obscene amount of money
to authenticate a recently acquired addition to his satanic
literature library: ``The Ninth Gate,'' a 17th-century tome
purportedly co-written by Lucifer himself.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other copies are known to exist, and Balkan wants Corso
to go to Lisbon and Paris to compare them with his edition.
However, Liana Tefler (Lena Olin, channeling her murderous virago
from ``Romeo Is Bleeding,'' if not any of that performance's nasty
nutso joy), the widow of the man who sold the book to Balkan, wants
it back in the worst way. After the few people who can stand him
are killed, Corso hightails it out of Manhattan for a thrilling
European adventure _ which mainly involves, yes, reading, comparing
woodcut illustrations and walking around a lot.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is tolerable for about an hour. The film has a great
musty/decadent look (shot by ``Seven'' and ``The Beach's'' Darius
Khondji, designed by Coppola favorite Dean Tavoularis) and it
evokes some of that subtly eerie atmosphere of indefinable dread we
associate with such Polanski masterpieces as ``Repulsion,''
``Rosemary's Baby,'' ``Chinatown'' and ``The Tenant.''
</P>
<P>
   The film even reaches a divine moment of trademark comic
grotesquery at midpoint, when Corso encounters twin, wizened
Portugese booksellers (both played by Jose Lopez Rodero, a veteran
production manager making his acting debut) who orbit each other in
a weird symbiotic rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   But it's downhill from there. Depp's performance, which started
out with possibilities, grows steadily less interesting as Corso
reads his way into ever-deeper trouble; it's like watching a cipher
devolve into a non-entity.
</P>
<P>
   The film's pace picks up from moribund to frantic (to invoke the
title of another Polanski non-thriller where nothing of interest
happens) in the last half hour, and its precise visuals descend
into sloppiness, too. You get the feeling that Polanski suddenly
realized that the film should be over, but couldn't figure out
exactly how to put an end to it.
</P>
<P>
   The lovely, untalented Emmanuelle Seigner keeps making
appearances as kickboxing kind of guardian angel/demon babe
whenever Corso really needs help. It's never made clear what her
nameless character's purpose is, though it could accurately be
described as ``director's wife wanted a job.'' And it has been so
long since Polanski has made a decent movie, she was probably wise
to grab her chance while she still could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ninth Gate'' isn't going to do much for anybody's resume. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Ninth Gate'' (R; violence, sex, nudity, language,
drug use). &QL; 
The stars: Johnny Depp, Emmanuelle Seigner, Frank Langella, Lena
Olin. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed and produced by Roman Polanski. Written
by Polanski, Enrique Urbizu and John Brownjohn, based on Arturo
Perez-Reverte's novel ``El Club Dumas.'' Released by Artisan
Entertainment. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, two minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
