<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-OHIO-GOP09-COX     03-08 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GOP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush outside of election winning political middle, analysts say
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ On his last visit to Ohio before he thrashed
Arizona Sen. John McCain on Tuesday, George W. Bush politely
bristled when asked if campaigning for the Republican presidential
nomination had pushed him to the political right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no one pushes me,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but with the general election campaign all but
officially started, the perception right now is that Vice President
Al Gore, not Bush, occupies the political middle that is crucial to
winning Ohio and the nation Nov. 7, said political scientist Robert
Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will try to further that perception in Ohio later this
month _ a date is not certain _ with a visit to Cincinnati, said
David Leland, Ohio Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exit polls show that he (Bush) is quote, `too
conservative.' ... He is too far to the right,'' said Adams of
Wright State University. ``He is going to have to make some moves
to the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Another political analyst, John Green of the University of
Akron, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is further from the center than Gore,'' Green said.
``Bush has further to move.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic campaign, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
did not push Gore to the left in the same way McCain succeeded in
depicting Bush as a right-winger, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think very much that Gore is in command of the heights right
now,'' he said. ``Gore is where he should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, said Adams, ``is going to be playing that Bob Jones tape
over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams referred to Bush's campaign stop during the South Carolina
primary at Bob Jones University, where a ban against interracial
dating was recently rescinded and where leaders frequently have
made anti-Catholic statements.
</P>
<P>
   But, Adams said, there is plenty of time for Bush to move more
to the center by building on his record of achievement in Texas in
areas such as education.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Paduchik, executive director of Bush's Ohio campaign,
said Bush will emphasize his record, but disputed the notion that
the primary campaign has left Bush tarred as an extremist. Exit
polls from Tuesday's Ohio Republican primary show Bush did well not
just with conservatives but with all groups of voters, based on
factors such as age, income level, sex and religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has a long-standing record of being very
inclusive,'' said Paduchik.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush currently has no trips scheduled for Ohio, it will be
a ``very important state for him'' in the general election,
Paduchik said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Leland said Democrats have learned the hard way about
the dangers of being perceived as too far to the left or right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the perception of our party from 1968 to 1992,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Paduchik, Leland said that he expects education to be a top
issue both in Ohio and nationally during the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Paduchik said Bush also will emphasize cutting taxes and
strengthening the nation's defenses. Leland said Gore's issues will
include making prescription drugs a Medicare benefit for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
