<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NINTHGATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLANSKI FILM SO MEDIOCRE IT'S SCARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roman Polanski's new demonic thriller ``The Ninth Gate'' can be
digested in one of two ways. If it's viewed as pure horror fiction
(as many critics will see it) and compared with the likes of
William Friedkin's ``The Exorcist'' and Polanski's own ``Rosemary's
Baby,'' then it's pure drivel: silly, Satanic hocus-pocus plodding
along at a snail's pace without a genuine scare in sight.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's viewed with an inner smile and compared with
pictures such as Roger Corman's Lovecraft films and Polanski's own
``The Fearless Vampire Killers,'' then it's _ well, it's still
drivel, but it's certainly much more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Depp _ in another pale, gaunt, freaky loner role _ stars
as a somewhat unscrupulous book dealer commissioned by Frank
Langella, a wealthy, eccentric collector of demonic literature
(Peter Cushing could have arm-wrestled Christopher Lee for this
part in the old days), to authenticate a tome called ``The Ninth
Gate,'' rumored to be able to raise Old Scratch himself. Of course,
the only way to be sure is to track down the two other copies in
existence, and so begins a long, tedious search that will delight
the studious few who enjoy inhaling dust in musty libraries, but
will bore everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   His quest takes him overseas through decaying gothic mansions,
winding European cobblestone streets and sprawling, opulent estates
that merely disguise the decadence within. Murder, seduction,
intrigue and near-death experiences ensue as Depp discovers more of
the books' secrets, with each new clue threatening to transform his
duties into personal obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Depp is convincingly cold and intriguing, as expected. There
will be inevitable comparisons with his recent work in ``Sleepy
Hollow,'' but Depp makes more of the part than is written, and this
is hardly a retread. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Langella's delightful overacting borders on camp _ his
confrontation with a wealthy secret society of wannabe
devil-worshipers is particularly amusing. Lena Olin gives off some
heat as the angry widow willing to do anything necessary to
retrieve the book, but her character is so underwritten she's
almost another attractive piece of the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're laughing with or laughing at Polanski's latest,
you'll still leave wondering what possessed the man who made
``Chinatown'' and ``Repulsion'' to waste his time on this piece of
supernatural fluff. Maybe the devil made him do it; let's just hope
he doesn't make him do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ninth Gate'' is rated R for violence, profanity, brief
nudity, adult subject matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Ninth Gate'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Roman Polanski &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Johnny Depp, Frank Langella &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 133 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
