<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MAY BE A ROUGH ROAD FOR BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note this is an analysis) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush is justifiably proud that he
withstood the most spirited insurgency against a Republican
front-runner in a quarter-century and is now his party's
presumptive presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But the elation prompted by his coast-to-coast victories Tuesday
over John McCain must be tempered with the knowledge that he is in
far worse political shape nationally than when the primary process
began.
</P>
<P>
   Bush not only has lost his once-substantial national edge over
Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, but
also has seen his negative rating soar.
</P>
<P>
   True, die-hard Republicans remain enthralled with Bush. And the
ones who weren't so sure about his conservative credentials last
fall are now, in the wake of the McCain assaults, putting the Texas
governor on a pedestal only slightly below those reserved for
Ronald Reagan and Barry Goldwater. But, as the saying goes, where
else do they have to go?
</P>
<P>
   Bush is in trouble with the voters in the magic middle, which is
where he was headed with his ``compassionate conservative''
campaign until getting sidetracked in the snows of New Hampshire
and the false spring of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polling in state after state that voted Tuesday points to
trouble ahead for Bush as he seeks to reposition himself for the
general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a rough road.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 percent of voters in Republican primaries across the
nation Tuesday, presumably McCain supporters, said they would vote
for Gore rather than Bush in the November general election. Only
about half that many said they would vote for Democrat Gore rather
than McCain, if he were the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The continued popularity of McCain's reform agenda, especially
among independents, could put another dark cloud on Bush's horizon:
the potential re-emergence of a third presidential campaign by Ross
Perot. Most polling that has included the Dallas billionaire in a
three-way contests shows he pulls far more support from Bush than
from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Other disturbing findings for Bush along this line came in more
than 4,000 interviews with California voters as they left the
polls. The survey was conducted by Voter News Services, a
consortium operated by The Associated Press and television
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four percent of those voters identified themselves as
independents, key to any Republican hope of winning the Golden
State in the fall. McCain drew 32 percent of their votes, Gore 24
percent and Bush 21.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominously for the Texan, 40 percent of the voters
described themselves as moderates, with their votes splitting Gore
38 percent, McCain 31 percent and Bush 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that Gore has been helped by John McCain,'' said
Ed Sarpolus, a Michigan-based pollster. ``When you look at the core
swing vote, they're leaning Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 50 percent of the California voters said they were most
influenced by issues, with Gore beating Bush 36 percent to 28
percent among that group. For the 44 percent of voters more
interested in personal qualities, McCain led the field with 31
percent, but because of the margin of error he was in a statistical
tie with Bush (30 percent) and Gore (28 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The list of issues important to voters was also troubling news
for Bush. Sixty percent said Social Security and Medicare were
their top priority, with their votes going 40 percent to Gore, 26
percent to McCain and 19 percent to Bush. Only half as many voters,
30 percent, said a tax cut was the main goal for the next
president, but at least with these Bush was an easy winner, with 47
percent, compared with 22 percent for McCain and 19 percent for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And most worrisome for Bush in the state that provides 20
percent of the electoral votes needed to win the White House, was
the voters' view on whether he was knowledgeable enough to be
president: 48 percent said `yes,`` but 43 percent said ''`no.``
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about one in four voters said Bush did not have the
knowledge needed to serve effectively as president, according to an
AP review of the polling, with some states reaching California-like
levels, including more than 40 percent in Massachusetts and Vermont
saying ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, naturally, says he doesn't know what folks are talking
about when they ask whether he's moved too far to the right in the
primaries. But just compare where the Bush campaign thought it
would be once the nomination was in hand with where the Texan's
effort is now that he is on the cusp of claiming the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had planned to spend the next four-plus months jetting
around the nation visiting his fellow Republican governor-pals and
showcasing what he contends are his Texas successes that are ready
for national export: education and welfare reform chief among them.
And he would continue to hammer away at the need for a huge tax
cut, not because it's popular, as he says, but because it's the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   As the primaries _ and constant polling throughout the period _
have shown, Bush's tax cut plan is not that popular, with
Republicans or, even more noticeably, with independents.
</P>
<P>
   In several key states that voted Tuesday, exit poll interviews
with Republican voters found that ``moral issues'' were the key
concern for the upcoming national administration, often coming in
at twice the percentage of taxes or even Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
