<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT &LR;      03-08 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PUTS TROOPS ON ALERT, IN CAMPAIGN AIMED AT TAIWAN'S
ELECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAOHSIUNG, Taiwan _ With Taiwan's presidential election only 10
days away, China has uncorked its vitriol on the Democratic
Progressive Party candidate, Chen Shui-bian, calling him a
separatist and a silver-tongued liar. To hear Chen tell it, Beijing
is doing him a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a precedent here,'' he said in an interview during a
campaign swing that took him from Taipei to this southern port
city. ``The person China hates, Taiwan voters love.''
</P>
<P>
   When Beijing fired missiles into the ocean near Taiwan before
the 1996 election, hoping to scare people away from President Lee
Teng-hui, they responded by re-electing him in a landslide. Chen,
who is viewed as less acceptable to Beijing than either of his two
main rivals, said China's latest barrage of threats would play to
his advantage as well by raising the hackles of voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen Shui-bian is not Lee Teng-hui, and this is not 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with party officials, political analysts and voters
this week suggest that Chen's identification with the cause of
Taiwanese independence could hurt him, particularly among the
one-quarter of the electorate that is still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Chen is running neck-and-neck with Vice President Lien Chan and
James Soong, an independent. Chen's campaign manager figures the
election will hinge on 200,000 to 300,000 voters, who may not make
up their minds until they step into the polling booth.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, these people are being subjected to a daily
drumbeat from Beijing. On Monday, the Chinese army accused a
``prominent figure'' _ read Chen Shui-bian _ of pushing for
independence and said it had put its troops on alert to crush such
a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances should we be fooled by his sweet
talk,'' said the army's newspaper, Liberation Army Daily, in a
front-page editorial. ``One minute he is brazenly howling `Long
live Taiwan independence,' while the next he is using beautiful and
pleasant words to lie that he wants `good will, reconciliation,
vigorous cooperation and everlasting peace' with the mainland.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in Beijing, President Jiang Zemin told a group of
foreign journalists, ``If you seek Taiwan independence, it will be
a case of brother fighting brother.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those who is listening is Chen Yen-yang, 22, a political
science student at National Taiwan University. Chen, who will cast
his first vote in this election, said he always assumed he would
support Chen Shui-bian. But he starts compulsory military service
next year. That has changed his mind, and he now plans to vote for
Vice President Lien of the governing Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody around me, my family and friends, is talking about
the possibility of war between Taiwan and China,'' Chen said. ``I
can't ignore that.''
</P>
<P>
   His classmate, Chen Yu-wen, said, ``I think Chen Shui-bian
underestimates China's willingness to take military action against
Taiwan.'' She said she planned to vote for Lien because the
Nationalist Party ``understands China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to deal with them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's rivals have seized the chance to portray him as a threat
to peace. The Nationalists are running a newspaper advertisement
that shows a man in army fatigues, his face hidden by a black gas
mask, staring into a wall of flames. The figure represents Taiwan
in the aftermath of a Chen victory.
</P>
<P>
   Chen counters these charges by noting he is the only candidate
with a son who would be drafted into the military if Taiwan were
invaded by China. ``As a father, I understand the fear of parents
who don't want to put their children into danger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his zeal to appear moderate, Chen rivals even the
hyper-cautious Lien. If elected, he has pledged not to declare
independence, not to hold a referendum on the issue, and not to put
the phrase ``special state-to-state'' relations into Taiwan's
Constitution. Those words, which Lee uttered last July, infuriated
China and set off a war of words across the Strait of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Chen is the platform of the Democratic
Progressive Party, which calls for ``the establishment of a
sovereign and independent Republic of Taiwan.'' Chen insisted
Wednesday that such a move would come only after a plebiscite, the
timing of which would be up to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts dismissed Chen's more conciliatory tone
as a political ploy rather than a shift in his bedrock beliefs.
They said the fervor of 1996 _ in which Taiwanese people rose up to
defend their first native-born president _ was missing from this
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this country are no longer fanatical,'' said Wang
Jin-pyng, a Nationalist Party stalwart who is the president of
Taiwan's legislature. ``They believe that maintenance of stability
is the best policy. If the threats from China reduce Chen's support
by 3 percent, he will lose the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaohsiung is one of Chen's strongholds, and Wednesday night
thousands of his supporters turned out here for an earsplitting,
and defiant, rally.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Chia-shin, 27, who has a mix of mainland Chinese and native
Taiwanese roots, said she was supporting Chen: ``I like his humble
background,'' she said. ``I'm from a humble background too. People
would say I'm a nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who brought her 6-year-old daughter, said she did not worry
about China's hostility. ``China is not having any impact on my
decision,'' she said. ``I think Chen Shui-bian will be flexible
enough to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng Wen-shiung, a 47-year-old tailor, said the threats from
China would not intimidate him. ``We Taiwanese have the courage to
repel any invader,'' he said. But he added, ``Of course, some
people won't vote for Chen because of China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
