<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MISSIONTOMARS-TE     03-08 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MISSION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSION' ACCOMPLISHES ITS GOAL: ROLLICKING ADVENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 TO MARS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The previews for ``Mission to Mars'' are deceptive: They make it
look as if director Brian De Palma is ripping off ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' In reality he's ripping off virtually every
space-exploration movie of the past 50 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This turns out to be OK, though, because what De Palma is really
doing is paying tribute to old science-fiction movie serials, which
formed the roots of all the other movies De Palma steals from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tribute'' is one of those words people use when a ripoff is
entertaining, and ``Mission to Mars'' succeeds enough in that
department to make up for its myriad flaws, which include slow
pacing (unusual for De Palma), a wordy script, cardboard
characters, questionable science and a climax that a lot of people
will find way too touchy-feely. When De Palma meets the New Age,
it's a lot like the old age, but he punctuates the movie well,
giving us an action/suspense sequence every 20 minutes or so to
keep us watching.
</P>
<P>
   The movie introduces us to its characters quickly, with an
Apollo 13-style family barbecue. Woody and Terri (Tim Robbins and
Connie Nielsen) are cutesy husband-and-wife astronauts headed for a
Mars mission; their buddy Jim (Gary Sinise) lost his chance to go
when his wife (''NYPD Blue's'' Kim Delaney, seen in flashbacks)
died of some debilitating disease. Their other buddy, Luke (Don
Cheadle), gets to go in his place _ and he and his crew eventually
encounter what could best be described as an angry, carnivorous
Martian sandstorm.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems unfair that Sinise has to play the guy left behind
again, as he did in ``Apollo 13,'' just wait. his Jim gets to go on
a rescue mission, with Woody, Terri and comic-relief goofball Phil
(''Scream 2's'' Jerry O'Connell), and they encounter perils and
make discoveries of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Although De Palma is much admired as a craftsman, he is, in his
own way, just as much an actor's director. He tends to work best
when his movies have a well-defined lead player, whether it be
Sissy Spacek in ``Carrie'' or Nicolas Cage in ``Snake Eyes.''
Because ``Mission to Mars'' is more of an ensemble piece, De Palma
doesn't have as much of a grip, and vibrant actors such as Sinise,
Cheadle and Robbins look just the slightest bit lost. This may be a
result of the multiple-writer story and screenplay, which appears
determined to give all the main characters equal dialogue time, so
that nobody really stands out as first among equals, a Tom Hanks
did in ``Apollo 13.''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't matter; this isn't the type of movie you go to
for acting or plot. You go so that you can murmur ``cool'' to
yourself when De Palma and his crew come up with some new
eye-popping computer-generated effect (at times it seems like it
should have been an IMAX movie). And the actors' work looks better
when you realize that they probably did most of it before blue
screens, with effects added later. Because they're often confined
to their spacesuits, however, the movie occasionally begins
sounding like a radio play.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Mission'' lags, you can amuse yourself by counting all
the movie references De Palma has sprinkled throughout as if it
were a cinematic Where's Waldo? He can be so unabashedly derivative
that he's probably started borrowing stuff without even meaning to.
It also helps to think of ``Mission'' as what it is: a PG movie
aimed squarely at space geeks from junior high on up. They might be
the pickiest about its weird science, but they shouldn't let that
get in the way of its entertaining aspects. It's the most
thoughtful mindless movie to come along in some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' is rated PG for violence and scattered
profanity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Mission to Mars'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brian De Palma &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Gary Sinise, Tim Robbins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
