<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WEST-PRIMARIES-NYT &LR;      03-08 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 WESTERN STATES TO HAVE THEIR SAY, FAINTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story was previously skedded as MCCAIN-COLO) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The effort began three years ago as a way to give the
West a little influence in the presidential selection process. Gov.
Michael O. Leavitt of Utah led a vigorous bipartisan campaign to
create a Western primary day for the eight states just this side of
California.
</P>
<P>
   It never worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Any impact the region might have gained seemed to dissipate when
only Colorado, Utah and Wyoming agreed to schedule voting on the
same day _ Friday. And now that Tuesday's results in 16 other
states have all but assured Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas their parties' nominations, the drama seems
removed altogether, even though Bush was scheduled to be in Denver
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Sen. John McCain canceled his scheduled
appearances in Denver on Thursday and Colorado Springs on Friday,
and seemed about to announce his withdrawal from the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice of the West is going to be heard if only faintly,''
said Leavitt, a strong Bush supporter, arguing that victories by
Bush would increase his momentum going into the Southern primaries
next week. ``Is that relevancy? Yeah, I think that makes Friday
relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   As winner in all but four of the 10 Republican contests on
Tuesday, Bush was leaving nothing to chance. He planned to sweep
through the region on Thursday, with a rally at the Denver Broncos'
training center outside Denver in the morning, followed by
appearances at the Provo, Utah, airport and the Cheyenne Civic
Center in Wyoming's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a lot of phone calls,'' said Gov. Bill Owens of
Colorado, a Republican who has been working his state hard for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Freda Poundstone, who became the state coordinator several days
ago, said Wednesday that she had waited much of the day to hear
whether she should round up supporters to attend the scheduled
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have thousands of volunteers climbing the walls here,'' she
said before the cancellations. ``They would love to have him come.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's prospects in Colorado seemed bleak even before
Tuesday's voting. A statewide poll for The Denver Post published on
Sunday found that among 249 registered Republican voters, 55
percent preferred Bush as the party nominee to 29 percent for
McCain. Sixteen percent favored other candidates or said they were
uncertain. The margin of sampling error was plus or minus 6.2
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the three Western states for the Republicans are 91
delegates _ 40 in Colorado, 29 in Utah and 22 in Wyoming, which is
holding county caucuses to select half its delegates to the
national convention. The other half will be chosen at a state
Republican convention in June.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose path to the nomination is virtually clear after a
sweep of the 11 Democratic contests on Tuesday, has no plans to
visit any of the three states before the voting on Friday. He
appeared at a rally in Denver last week and has little to gain in
Utah and Wyoming, which have longstanding Republican traditions and
only a few electoral votes to offer, eight between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
