   (NYT24) PHILADELPHIA -- March 8, 2000 -- PA-FLOWER-SHOW -- On
Sunday, when the Philadelphia Flower Show opened, 50,000
spring-starved garden lovers moved through more than 100 full-scale
exhibits and 2,500 amateur entries like a sea of honeybees drunk on
pollen. A floral centerpiece with lava lamps, viburnums and tulips,
topped by an amaryllis, at the show. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- CIR-WIRED-HOMES -- For
decades, security companies have been wiring houses with central
nervous systems of motion sensors and computer controls. Now those
installations are adopting more sophisticated wireless technology
and will soon help residents manage things like the family computer
and the living room audio system. A wireless color video camera and
receiver from X10.com, left; X10's wallplate switch controls lights
and other devices using radio frequencies and existing electric
wiring. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- March 8, 2000 -- CLINTON-ASIA -- President
Clinton moments before his address on Asian policy at Johns Hopkins
University, Wednesday. Clinton sent Congress Wednesday the
legislation that would usher China into the World Trade
Organization, setting off what promises to be a highly divisive
fight within the Democratic party that intertwines the politics of
trade and Clinton's final effort to stabilize relations with the
world's most populous nation. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WELLBORN, Fla. -- March 8, 2000 -- FLA-AUTO-PILEUP -- A
body lies covered under piles of wood from an overturned truck
after a pileup on Interstate 10, about 90 miles east of Tallahassee
in northern Florida, Wednesday. Twenty-two cars and trucks slammed
into each other along the highway which was shrouded by blinding
smoke from a forest fire. Three people were killed and 21 injured,
authorities said. (Tim Davis /The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SOUTH EGREMONT, Mass. -- March 8, 2000 -- ENGLISH-BARN-2
-- Richard and Stephanie Stern had an English hay barn, circa 1540,
imported from Yalding, Kent, and reassembled as an addition to
their existing home. The addition, a three-story dining room-living
room crisscrossed with ancient beams, is at right in this outdoor
view of the Stern's home. (Chris Ramirez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SOUTH EGREMONT, Mass. -- March 8, 2000 -- ENGLISH-BARN-1
-- With the help of the architect John James (shown), Richard and
Stephanie Stern were able to reassemble an English hay barn, circa
1540, imported from Yalding, Kent. Reconstructed as a three-story
dining room-living room and crisscrossed with ancient beams, it now
stands, the room the Sterns imagined when they bought the barn,
sight unseen, for $60,000. But getting there has not been easy.
(Chris Ramirez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W -- A
good landscape starts with a wellthought out ground plan. Before
attempting to set anything down on paper, you must first consider
the terrain, the size and shape of the house, the soil composition
and the climate. You should also consider the needs and
requirements of your family. (Edward R. Lipinski/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 8, 2000 -- BRADLEY-2-- Bill
Bradley shakes hands with Otis Irvy during a campaign stop at
Emily's restaurant in Harlem last Saturday. Campaign aides said
Wednesday that Bradley has decided to end his quest for the
Democratic presidential nomination after a string of primary losses
to Vice President Al Gore. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 8, 2000 -- BRADLEY -- Bill
Bradley during a television interview Feb. 29. Campaign aides said
Wednesday that Bradley has decided to end his quest for the
Democratic presidential nomination after a string of primary losses
to Vice President Al Gore. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- CIR-GEEK-NOTES -- The new
Sony PlayStation 2 game console, introduced last week in Japan, has
already sold more than a million units there and is expected to be
equally popular when it reaches the United States this fall,
despite a list price of nearly $400. Besides its highly advanced
3-D graphics capabilities, its ability to play DVD movies with
surround-sound output and its broadband-ready Internet connections,
the PlayStation 2 can also play thousands of existing PlayStation
game titles. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- March 8, 2000 -- CLINTON-MINIMUM-WAGE --
Members of Congress and President Clinton applaude Cheryl Costas,
of Alba, Pa., in white, after she spoke about her experience
supporting two kids and a disabled husband on the minimum wage,
currently $5.50 an hour, Wednesday at the White House. Clinton
rallied Democrats to support a higher minimum wage on Wednesday and
vowed to veto a Republican plan that would delay the increase and
link it to $122.7 billion in tax cuts. (Justin Lane/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- NY-UNDERGROUND -- Over the
last year, MetroCard vending machines have begun appearing
underground. The touch screens are colorful and legible, so that
even a 6-year-old can read them. Masamichi Udagawa, center, Sigi
Moeslinger, and the MetroCard machine their small design studio
spruced up. (Chris Ramirez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 8, 2000 -- CIR-CENSUS-ONLINE --
Edison Gore, left, a field programs official at the Census Bureau,
said the agency prefers paper data collection. ``We know what's
going on there, and it's very controlled,'' he said. ``The Internet
is something new.'' With him is David Coon, the agency's survey
statistician. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- CIR-MODULAR-ROBOTS -- Mark
Yim is a Xerox researcher who has invented a modular robot, called
Polybot, that can change shape to resemble a snake, left, or a
spider, below. The promise of Polybot, and robots like it, is
versatility. ``The one advantage of the system is the ability to be
very mobile through unstructured environments,'' said Yim. (The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- March 8, 2000 --
KOSOVO-UNREST-2 -- Serb women walk past apartment blocks in the
northern part of the divided city where ethnic Albanians were
returned to their homes last week by NATO-led peacekeeping troops,
Wednesday. An estimated 800 Albanians live among the Serbs in the
northern part of the city but their lives are increasingly
precarious. Most of the violence of the last month has been centred
in the northern part to the city. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- March 8, 2000 --
KOSOVO-UNREST -- French troops with the NATO-led peacekeeping
operatin search a man trying to enter an area of apartment blocks
last Saturday in the northern section of the city where Albanians
were returned to their homes. An estimated 800 Albanians live among
the Serbs in the northern part of the city but their lives are
increasingly precarious. Most of the violence of the last month has
been centred in the northern part. (Andrew Testa/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEWTON, Conn. -- March 8, 2000 -- FULTON-PHOTOS-4 --
Robert Edison Fulton Jr., on his Douglas motorcycle during his tour
