<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- CIR-GREEN-STAMPS -- Remember
licking green stamps? Remember how the pages in the books got wavy
when you pasted them in? S&AMP;H green stamps (no, they've never gone
away) are trying to move online, and they represent a perfect case
study of whether something that succeeded in the physical world can
translate to the Web. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- PLASTIC-FURNITURE -- Nan
Kempner in her Park Avenue apartment last Monday contemplating an
orange injection-molded armchair design by Ron Arad for Vitra.
``The only plastic I want is plastic surgery,'' she said.
Plain-jane no more, plastic furniture is coming in from the patio.
But not everyone thinks that's good news. (Fred R. Conrad/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 8, 2000 -- BUSH-2 -- Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas marks his ballot as he voted absentee for the
Texas primary, Wednesday. The presidential primary in Texas will be
held on March 14. Bush declared a ``national victory'' in
Republican primaries Tuesday and immediately set his sights on
likely Democratic nominee Al Gore as a symbol of the the status quo
in Washington. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 8, 2000 -- BUSH-1-- Gov. George
