<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 03/08/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) CHICAGO -- March 8, 2000 -- IMMIG-JOBS-2 -- A man pushes
a cart past Industrial Stength Labor, one of several temporary
employment agencies in the area. The Immigration and Naturalization
Service has made crossing the border harder than ever. But once
inside the country, illegal immigrants are now largely left alone
as the INS now concentrates on picking up aliens who have committed
crimes. The rest are, in effect, allowed entrance to help American
employers fill jobs. (Todd Buchanan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) CHICAGO -- March 8, 2000 -- IMMIG-JOBS-1 -- Workers,
many of them Hispanic, wait for job assignments at Ron's Temporary
Help Services, Inc. The Immigration and Naturalization Service has
made crossing the border harder than ever. But once inside the
country, illegal immigrants are now largely left alone as the INS
now concentrates on picking up aliens who have committed crimes.
The rest are, in effect, allowed entrance to help American
employers fill jobs. (Todd Buchanan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) BETHESDA, Md. -- March 8, 2000 -- SCI-HUMAN-GENOME -- A
last minute merger negotiation between public and private
competitors in the field of human genomes has foundered in a clash
of principles and egos. Dr. Francis Collins, head of the National
Human Genome Research Institute, said that the Celera Corp., which
claimed in 1998 that it would sequence the genome from scratch,
``wanted to gain a monopoly on the human genome as a database.''
(Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- NY-MAYOR -- Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Wednesday that the Senate race in New York would be
decided on its own, not by presidential candidates. The mayor's
comments, about the political benefits he might reap from George W.
Bush, were in striking contrast to the view of Hillary Rodham
Clinton's advisers, who reacted with something resembling joy to
the prospect of the Texas governor at the top of the Republican
ticket in New York. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) UNDATED -- March 8, 2000 -- INSURANCE-SCAM -- The FBI
and insurance regulators are offering rewards for information
leading to the capture of Sholam Weiss, who fled in October.
Michael D. Blutrich, below left, was outside counsel for the
National Heritage Life Insurance Co., which Weiss looted,
prosecutors say. Blutrich later admitted his role in defrauding the
insurer and a variety of other crimes, and became a government
witness. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- March 8, 2000 -- CENSUS -- After weeks
marked by peace and cooperation, the partisan wars over the conduct
of the 2000 Census have erupted once again. Most of the fireworks
were centered in a hearing Wednesday held by the House Subcommittee
on the Census. The panel's chairman grilled Kenneth W. Prewitt, the
director of the Census Bureau, on his agency's alleged
unresponsiveness to requests by the GAO and other bodies for
information. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 8, 2000 --
AFGHAN-GIRLS-SCHOOL-2 -- Forbidden to learn in the first four years
of Taliban rule, 250 girls have flocked to a school that opened
three months ago in Kabul. Most of the girls are eager, as if
deprivation had left an indelible hunger for education. (Barry
Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 8, 2000 --
AFGHAN-GIRLS-SCHOOL-1 -- Education for girls was forbidden in
Afghanistan under the early years of Taliban rule. Among the pupils
at a school in Kabul are Kulsum, 5, who is learning the alphabet,
and Laili, 10, who used to disguise herself as a boy to attend
school. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) LOS ANGELES -- March 8, 2000 -- MCCAIN -- Sen. John
McCain may be seeking a pledge on campaign finance reform in
exchange for helping to unite the Republican Party behind Gov.
George W. Bush. McCain greeted supporters in Los Angeles after the
polls closed on Super Tuesday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) BOSTON -- March 8, 2000 -- MASS-BIG-DIG -- Boston's
``Big Dig'' is the nation's largest public works project under way.
The project includes a suspension bridge over the Charles River.
(Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) HANNIBAL, Mo. -- March 8, 2000 -- BRADLEY-3 -- Bill
Bradley on Wednesday decided to end his quest for the Democratic
presidential nomination after a string of primary losses to Vice
President Al Gore. Bradley waited to deliver a speech to supporters
in Missouri on Saturday. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- March 8, 2000 --
KOSOVO-UNREST-3 -- A Belgian soldier with the NATO-led peacekeeping
operation carries shields used during riot control past a house
with Serb nationalist graffiti earlier this week. The graffiti,
written on a building in the predominantly ethnic-Albanian side of
the city, symbolizes Serbian unity. After days of unrest,
peacekeepers in this industrial town in northern Kosovo say they
see no way out of the quagmire of ethnic hatred. (Andrew Testa/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SAN ANTONIO -- March 8, 2000 -- PLAYER-SENTENCED -- Just
over a year ago, 18-year-old Tony Limon was a senior starter for
the Bobcats, the South San Antonio High School basketball team.
Today, he sits in a Bexar County jail cell, waiting for a decision
Friday as to whether a judge will reduce his five-year prison
sentence for throwing an elbow at an opponent during a basketball
game, breaking the player's nose. The severity of the sentence for
Limon - already in trouble with the law when the altercation took
place - has surprised many. (Delcia Lopez/The San Antonio
Express-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- NY-JURIES-POLICE -- Over
the last six months in the criminal courts of New York City,
prosecutors say they are seeing a change: grand jurors in Manhattan
and Brooklyn are intensively scrutinizing the testimony of police
officers and other witnesses. And in Queens, juries are deadlocking
in an increasing number of cases, a sign, prosecutors fear, that
jurors are questioning the veracity of police testimony as police
misconduct scandals continue to dominate city headlines. A juror
examined his handbook and summons card. (Ruby Washington/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad -- March 8, 2000 --
TRINIDAD-ASH-WEDNESDAY -- After the half-dressed Carnival
masqueraders had turned the city into a giant boom box, Steve
Richards' worry was not over what was gone, but who had vanished.
He runs Rebirth House, a drug rehabilitation program that operates
four recovery homes. ``Today what I have to do is a damage
assessment,'' he said as he surveyed his group's residences to see
if anyone had forgotten the Twelve Steps of Recovery amidst the
revelry. (David Gonzalez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- DOCTOROW-CITY -- If a theme
runs through all of E.L. Doctorow's work, it is the past as
progenitor of the present. The persistent suggestion of his fiction
is this: From there, we got here. But in his new novel, ``City of
God,'' his 10th, he has taken a reverse tack. ``In this book, it
seems I've finally caught up to the present,'' Doctorow said his
latest novel. ``I've been very slow about it, but I finally made
it.'' (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 8, 2000 -- PORGY-OPERA-REVIEW -- So
beguiling is its songfulness that ``Porgy and Bess'' can conceal
how complicated it really is. But the production which opened the
New York City Opera's spring season Tuesday has larger ambitions.
It also poses more problems for the people who put it on. Alvy
Powell as Porgy and Marquita Lister as Bess at the New York State
Theater. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PHILADELPHIA -- March 8, 2000 -- PA-FLOWER-SHOW -- On
Sunday, when the Philadelphia Flower Show opened, 50,000
spring-starved garden lovers moved through more than 100 full-scale
exhibits and 2,500 amateur entries like a sea of honeybees drunk on
pollen. A floral centerpiece with lava lamps, viburnums and tulips,
topped by an amaryllis, at the show. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York
Times)
</P>
