<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LACK TOP GUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. - The Dodgers have the big boppers in the
middle of the lineup, but after a week of Grapefruit League games,
manager Davey Johnson is still in search of the energy he craves at
the top of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   He told Devon White and Todd Hollandsworth, competing for the
center-field spot, that the starter at that position would most
likely bat leadoff. Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek, who excelled
in the second spot of the lineup last season, would probably follow
in setting things up for Gary Sheffield, Shawn Green and Eric
Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a slow offensive start in spring training has Johnson
looking at what to do with the top of the lineup. And the answers
aren't exactly jumping out at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That table-setting mentality is just as important as the big
mashers,'' Johnson said. ``I'm looking at who can battle a pitcher,
work a pitcher, get on, make the pitcher work. A lot of times,
those guys are overlooked. I don't overlook them. It's just as much
an art, knowing how to get on as it is being able to hit it out and
drive them in. It's just as important.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem for the Dodgers is they don't have a leadoff
hitter. It's one of the negative byproducts of trading Eric Young
during the offseason, but something the Dodgers knew when the deal
was made.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth and White have each batted leadoff this spring,
but neither takes a lot of pitches. White admits he strikes out too
much for a leadoff guy but also points to his World Series titles
as proof he can be that important cog.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Grudzielanek, who has gap power and has become a
favorite of Johnson's, could bring the energy to the top of the
lineup. None of the three, however, possess high on-base
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, White and Hollandsworth combined to walk 94 times
in 1,223 at-bats last season. Young walked 63 times in 456 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely make mental notes of guys who can hit one or
two,'' Johnson said. ``Who are guys that work a pitcher, who are
guys that can drop one down, who are guys that hit behind a runner,
who are guys that take some pitches in a count to get on?''
</P>
<P>
   Orel kudos to Claude: Orel Hershiser has spent the spring
tutoring the young pitchers, but he wanted to make sure someone was
coaching (begin ital)him(end ital), so he talked to pitching coach
Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He adjusted my front (left) arm,'' Hershiser said. ``He got me
to get my front arm up a little higher, which keeps me closed
longer and makes me feel a little stronger. Instead of feeling like
I need to create some power, it feels like it's naturally there.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was three hitless innings Wednesday against Detroit,
a far cry from the battle he had in his first outing of the spring
last week against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Lefty Onan Masaoka, who sprained his left ankle
two weeks ago, is scheduled to pitch today... Though Chan Ho Park
gave up five runs on six hits in three innings, he wasn't
disappointed in his work. ``I threw a lot of changeups, and that
really worked, but I missed with a couple of fastballs,'' Park
said. ``I'm working on things, focusing on my changeup and my
mechanics.''... Dodgers managing general partner Bob Daly and Scott
Boras, agent for third baseman Adrian Beltre, played phone tag most
of the day and didn't meet about a multiyear contract....
Outfielder Kevin Gibbs, who is high on Johnson's list of young
outfielders, had another setback when he hurt his right shoulder
working out with a medicine ball. He was initially in the starting
lineup but was scratched and had an MRI performed. Results of the
test are expected today. Gibbs missed most of the last two seasons
with injuries.... The first round of cuts came and was reserved for
pitchers. Right-handers Robinson Checo, Hal Garrett and Brian
Stephenson, the godson of senior vice president Tommy Lasorda, were
sent to minor-league camp along with lefty Jeff Granger.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS UPDATE Today's games: Split squad vs. Kansas City,
Atlanta. When/Where: 10:05 a.m., Holman Stadium, Vero Beach, Fla.;
</P>
<P>
   Radio: XTRA 1150 AM (tape delay begins at 5:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: (Split squad vs. Kansas City, Atlanta) Right-hander
Kevin Brown remains at Dodgertown to face the Royals in his second
start of the spring. In his first outing, Brown allowed two hits in
three innings. Meanwhile, rookie righty Eric Gagne travels to Lake
Buena Vista, Fla., to face the Braves. Gagne, trying to win a spot
in the rotation, was erratic in his first spring appearance. He
gave up seven runs on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's result: Todd Hundley hit his first homer of the
spring, a two-run shot in the second, and Chad Kreuter had a
three-run double as the Dodgers (1-6) ended a six-game losing
streak with a 12-5 win over the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   - Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
