<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET OPENS NEW OPPORTUNITIES FOR WOMEN TO LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Jeanne Jackson surprised the retail community by
resigning from her high-profile post as head of the Banana Republic
division of Gap Inc. to take over the helm of Wal-Mart.com, a new
Internet store. The news was shocking because Jackson had been
rumored to be on the short list of executives who might one day
succeed the Gap's longtime chief executive, Millard Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, 54, saw her career possibilities differently.
``Mickey is the same age I am,'' Jackson said of her former boss.
``So unless he got hit by a bus, there was no way I was going to
succeed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet field was mainly the province of men just a few
years ago. But these days, women say they are finding opportunities
that are equal to or better than those found in more traditional
companies. Women were chief executives in about 6 percent of
Internet companies that venture capital firms financed during 1999
and, more impressively, held top management posts in 45 percent of
such start-ups, according to VentureOne, a research firm in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   That is a striking change from 1998, when women accounted for
only 21 percent of senior management positions and 4 percent of
chief executive posts at Internet firms receiving venture capital
backing.
</P>
<P>
   And the numbers are even more remarkable when compared with the
Fortune 500 companies, where women continue to make only marginal
gains. Women occupied fewer than 1 percent of the chief executive
slots among these giants, according to a 1998 census conducted by
Catalyst, a New York-based women's research organization. And women
accounted for only 3.8 percent of the highest- ranking corporate
officer positions.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of the Internet companies is ``definitely causing
a leveling of the playing field,'' said Denise Brosseau, the
president of the Forum for Women Entrepreneurs in San Mateo, Calif.
Brosseau argues that women will become chief executives more
quickly at Web companies because so many are now in senior
management positions. ``It is a pipeline issue,'' she said, ``and
we are really seeing women fill'' the executive vice president and
president jobs ``in record number.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the transformation of the Internet business
from one that is dominated by men to one that is welcoming women
seems to be the unquenchable need for talent. ``Frankly, I could
get a Martian hired if I tried,'' said Nancy Albertini, chief
executive of Taylor Winfield, a talent search firm specializing in
high technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet companies are also open to a wider array of
backgrounds for top managers than old-line businesses are. ``There
is a natural kind of title progression in large corporations that
is a well-defined process,'' and that takes about 20 years, said
Jay Hoag, managing partner of Technology Crossover Ventures, a
venture capital firm. ``But the Internet has changed that. Here, it
is take the ball and go play.'' Of the 46 companies Hoag financed
this year, seven had chief executives who are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a new game, the old rules don't apply,''
agrees Gayle Crowell, president of e.piphany.net. ``It is not about
creating the best products or technology, it is more about brand
building and knowing the consumer, and women are great at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowell argues that men raised in the old system might even have
a disadvantage in the fast-moving world of e-commerce. ``The
traditional financial skills can inhibit you in the Internet,'' she
said. ``I used to have whack-you-on-the-head sessions with the
guys. I tell them: `There are new rules. We are not going to worry
about profitability. We are going to worry about building the
biggest footprint possible.'''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many women in high posts at American corporations are
defecting to the Internet. Heidi Miller shocked the financial world
when she left the vaunted post of executive vice present and chief
financial officer for the megacorporation Citigroup to become chief
financial officer of Priceline.com, the ``name your own price''
Internet venture that lost about $1 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said her gender played no part in her decision to leave
but added that she suspected that her new environment would be a
better place for women to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've had a very good run, but that doesn't excuse what
I know to be real bias,'' Miller said of her experience at
Citigroup. She noted that Priceline and similar Web-related
start-up companies were smaller and under great pressure to produce
results quickly. ``When the going gets tough, everyone has to row
and everyone is treated better as a result.'' She added, ``I would
also expect that the legacy of culture that bred some of the bias
doesn't exist at new companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
