<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MARCH 9
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NY-INFANT-MORTALITY-NYT (moved on Monday, Feb. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Feb. 28,
about high infant mortality rates in central Brooklyn misstated the
surname of an associate professor of medicine at the City
University of New York who is an expert in infant mortality. She is
Tanya Pagan Raggio, not Paggio.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS-NYT (moved on Monday, March 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 6,
about herbal remedies misstated the location of the University of
Erlangen, the institution of Dr. Felix Stickel, who said the herb
comfrey can cause liver failure. The university is in Erlangen,
Germany, not Heidelberg.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-ARTISTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, March 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, March 5,
about ``Greater New York,'' a survey of new works at the P.S. 1
Contemporary Art Center in Long Island City, Queens, included an
erroneous reference from the museum for one artist. Do-Ho Suh is a
man, not a woman.
</P>
</TEXT>
