u a BC-TENN-SHOOTING-NYT &LR;      03-08 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER AND 2 FIREFIGHTERS DIE IN AMBUSH AT MEMPHIS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Two firefighters and a sheriff's deputy were
shot to death Wednesday when they were ambushed as they arrived at
a burning house where the body of a woman, apparently the wife of
the suspected gunman, was later found inside.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, identified as Fred Williams, a city firefighter,
was in custody Wednesday night at a hospital where he was treated
for wounds he received in an exchange of gunfire with police
officers after the killings.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Fleming, deputy chief of the Fire Department, said that
Williams had returned to active duty only a few days ago, having
been on leave under an employee assistance program. Fleming
declined to say what problem had caused Williams to take leave. But
he believed that Williams knew the firefighters who were shot, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect this,'' said H.J. Pickett, the Memphis fire
chief. ``We're here to fight fires. You want to say it's part of
the job, but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were unsure how the woman inside the house had
been killed. But neighbors and relatives said she was Williams'
wife, and her former husband, Herman Harrison, identified her as
Stacey Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said they received two emergency calls
from the quiet, upscale neighborhood shortly before 1 p.m. One,
apparently from the suspect, reported the fire, and the other, from
a neighbor, reported that shots had been fired. A sheriff's deputy
said that when the firefighters pulled up at the house, a man ran
out of the garage firing a shotgun and shouting: ``Get away! Get
away!''
</P>
<P>
   By the time a car from the sheriff's department pulled up a few
moments later, two firefighters had already been shot to death,
said sheriff's Deputy Don Wright. The driver of the sheriff's car,
identified as Deputy Rupert Peete, was fatally shot as he arrived
at the scene, and the car went crashing through a fence.
</P>
<P>
   The dead firefighters were identified as Lt. Javier Lerma, 41,
and Pvt. William Blakemore, both of Engine Co. 55. Williams was
assigned to a different firehouse, department officials said, but
may have worked with the victims at the scenes of previous fires.
</P>
<P>
   One other person was shot as well, a woman who happened to be
walking by the house. But her injuries were said to be not serious.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis police officers arrived shortly after the slayings, and
their gunfire wounded Williams in the lower torso. Surgeons at the
hospital treated his injuries, which were not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Crews, director of the Memphis police, said he suspected
that the fire had been deliberately set. But it was unclear whether
it was set after Mrs. Williams was killed, perhaps an effort to
cover up her death, or whether it was solely a means of luring the
firefighters to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, Mrs. Williams' former husband, said she married
Williams about three weeks ago. The relationship was not working
out, he said, and he had tried to get custody of his 8-year-old
son, who was living at the house. The boy was in school when the
shooting broke out and was later taken to stay with Harrison's
sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
