<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SENATE-JUDGES-NYT &LR;      03-08 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUDGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CLEARS WAY FOR VOTE ON STALLED JUDICIAL NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (bl) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Wednesday to end debate and move
to a final vote on two of President Clinton's nominees for federal
appeals court posts in California whose nominations have been
stalled for years.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader, moved aggressively to
block a rebellion in his party in order to fulfill his promise to
have a floor vote on the two nominees, Judge Richard A. Paez and
Marsha L. Berzon.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have been nominated for seats on the 9th Circuit
U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco, which covers California and
several other Western states. The Senate is expected to narrowly
confirm both, probably on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both nominees have come to symbolize the angry and divisive
politics behind judicial nominations. Paez, of U.S. District Court
in Los Angeles, was first nominated to the appeals court seat more
than four years ago, setting a modern record for the time a nominee
has waited for a final vote. Berzon, a San Francisco lawyer, was
first nominated more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two nominees are expected to win the approval of all 45
Democrats and at least six Republicans, including Sen. Orrin G.
Hatch, R-Utah, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Democrats campaigned to save the nominees, charging
that Republicans had purposely slowed the process of confirming
federal judges in the hopes of keeping as many seats vacant as
possible in the hope that a new Republican president would be able
to select the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch disputed that charge. Lott agreed to a vote on the
nominations by March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont, the ranking Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee, said he believed the Republicans had tried to
kill the nominations by preventing a floor vote because they would
be reluctant to vote against a Hispanic candidate in an election
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
