u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      03-08 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDEN JOINS GOP IN CALL FOR DELAY IN MISSILE-DEFENSE PLAN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding weight to a growing bipartisan movement, a
senior Democratic senator has warned President Clinton that he
should leave the decision on deploying a national missile-defense
system to the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., who is the ranking minority
member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, told an audience
of scientists on Friday at Stanford University that he did not
believe that the North Korean missile threat was sufficient to
warrant a vastly expensive system that was not technically proven.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Biden said deploying the system could not only severely
upset relations with Russia, but also encourage China to increase
sharply its warheads, prompting an arms race in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to make a decision on a national
missile-defense system in the summer. His top arms negotiators have
been talking to the Russians over six months about deploying the
system in a way that Moscow might find acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Biden stated his opposition after Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., on the
Foreign Relations Committee, called for a delay on the decision
until a new president took office.
</P>
<P>
   Henry A. Kissinger recently wrote that an election year was not
the time to proceed on national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Biden, who amplified his comments on Monday in an interview,
also cited election year politics as a reason for postponing a
decision. Biden said that he disagreed with White House advisers
who say Vice President Al Gore and the Democrats need to proceed
with the system to inoculate themselves against Republican
criticism of being weak on national defense and that the Democrats
would be most successful by campaigning on the strength of the
economy, and not allowing the Republicans to turn the focus to
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to cost $30 billion, and there has been no
national debate,'' Biden added. ``This doesn't make sense absent
public debate.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his opposition to Clinton's making a far-reaching
foreign-policy decision under such time pressure, Biden said he was
particularly uneasy with the missile-defense system because he
thought that it would essentially mean withdrawal from the
Antiballistic Missile Treaty of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   That treaty, which its advocates regard as the cornerstone of
arms control, forbids a missile-defense system that protects an
entire nation. The administration has been trying to persuade
acting President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia to amend the ABM
treaty so that Clinton could decide on a system without abrogating
the pact. The Russians have shown few signs of agreeing.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, Biden said he had an alternative idea to
answer the threat from North Korea's Taepo Dong missiles, which are
believed to be able to deliver strategic warheads to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Biden said an Aegis sea-based system with missiles based off the
North Korean coast would let the United States intercept the
missiles in their ascents. Such a system would not endanger the
whole fabric of arms control or threaten nonproliferation
safeguards in the way that a national missile defense would, Biden
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Biden spoke at Stanford, former Defense Secretary William
S. Perry was in the audience. Perry has also expressed reservations
about the system being the best way to counter the threat of
long-range missiles from North Korea and in Congressional testimony
favored the sea-based system off North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Biden said that he intended to discuss his arguments with
Clinton and that he would try to marshall support in the national
security community _ among high-profile former defense officials,
for example _ to focus added attention on his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed to the Stanford scientists to make their voices
heard ``in this highly charged political environment, with such a
momentous decision to be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
