u w BC-GORE-SATELLITE-NYT &LR;      03-08 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SATELLITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE PANEL SUPPORTS GORE SATELLITE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A satellite project initially proposed by Vice
President Al Gore and opposed by congressional Republicans appears
to have scientific merit to justify it, a National Academy of
Sciences task force said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which would deploy a satellite called Triana in a
high orbit to observe the entire Earth continually, could make
contributions to Earth and solar science at a relatively reasonable
cost, said a panel of experts assembled by the academy's National
Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   In a report requested by Congress last summer, the eight-member
panel said the scientific objectives of the $70 million project
``are consonant with published science strategies and priorities
for collection of climate data sets and the need for development of
new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   In a cover letter to the report, the panel, whose chairman was
Dr. James J. Duderstadt of the University of Michigan, said it did
not have the time and expertise to conduct a full cost-benefit
analysis of the project. However, it said: ``The task group found
that the cost of Triana is not out of line for a relatively small
mission that explores a new Earth observing perspective and
provides unique data.''
</P>
<P>
   The Triana project sprang from a 1998 idea of Gore to have NASA
fly an inexpensive spacecraft that would make continuous, live
pictures of the full, sunlit Earth from far out in space, something
that cannot currently be done. Gore said such views, constantly
made available to the world on the Internet and on television,
would encourage environmental consciousness and educational
programs.
</P>
<P>
   After initial studies that resulted in adding instruments to the
satellite and expanding its scientific mission, NASA found $30
million to start the program. But critics, including Republican
politicians and some scientists, immediately questioned the value
of the project, sometimes derisively called Gorecam or Goresat.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to continuously monitoring Earth in one view and the
amount of energy it gets from the sun and reflects into space,
Triana would also have instruments to measure ozone, cloud height
and the amounts of aerosols suspended in the air, from a vantage
point one million miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the Republican-controlled House approved a three-year
NASA financing bill that eliminated Triana financing. A
House-Senate conference committee later agreed to suspend spending
on the project and delay the satellite's planned launching to early
2001 from December while the panel from the independent science
academy studied its value.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Lane, the White House science adviser, Wednesday
praised the academy's report in a statement, saying it showed that
Triana could produce technologically sound results at a reasonable
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Triana is worthy of bipartisan congressional support and
should not be kept earthbound,'' Lane said, ``Instead, it should
fly as scheduled next year.''
</P>
<P>
   A staff member with the House Science Committee, which voted
last year along party lines not to finance the program, said
congressional opponents would have to study the new report before
commenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still questions as to whether this is the best use
of space research dollars, particularly when there are other worthy
areas of research that are not being adequately funded,'' said the
staff member, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
