<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH, WEAK IN NEW YORK, MAY NOT INVEST MUCH EFFORT
THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Memo to New Yorkers: Say goodbye to George W. Bush
and Al Gore. You are probably going to see very little of them in
the state between now and Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bush won a solid victory against John McCain in the
Republican primary in the state on Tuesday. But any chance that
Bush might bring his general election campaign into this Democratic
state this fall _ and there was a time when Bush's aides asserted
that such an unconventional strategy was under consideration _
seemed remote Wednesday as Democrats and Republicans reviewed the
decidedly limited contours of Bush's victory in New York's
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received 50.4 percent of the votes cast for his delegates,
compared with 43.8 percent for McCain, a respectable showing on the
face of it. But exit polls found that a full 38 percent of the
Arizona senator's supporters said they would vote in November for
the Democratic candidate if McCain was not the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is probably inflated by the polarization created by
the hard-hitting campaign that Bush pursued against McCain.
Nonetheless, it is a high number, and cannot be seen as good news
by Bush's supporters. By contrast, just 17 percent of supporters of
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey said they would vote for the
Republican nominee this fall if Vice President Al Gore won the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was ample evidence that Bush is a less than
compelling figure even within his own party, which is the minority
party in New York. Among Republican voters in New York City and on
Long Island, 21 percent said they would vote for Gore in November;
statewide, 22 percent of Republican women said they would vote for
Gore. By contrast, just 5 percent of Democratic women said they
would vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And only one-third of Republican respondents said that Bush says
what he truly believes, rather than what people want to hear _ a
sign that the attacks McCain made on him last week, and that Gore
has begun to pick up, had taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the problems go beyond the candidate himself: there
were strong indications in Tuesday's results that the New York
Republican Party's establishment, which supported Bush, is not what
it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's delegates (Republicans voted for individual delegates, as
opposed to the candidates themselves) lost across Nassau County,
the part of the state that once was the showplace of Republican
organization. The party is now wracked by infighting, and the
county's fiscal disorder has undercut the party's position there.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, these results suggest not a setback for Bush, but
a maintenance of the status quo, which is that New York tends to be
in the Democratic presidential column. A Republican presidential
nominee has not carried New York since Ronald Reagan in 1984
(though Bush's father lost by just 2 percentage points to Michael
Dukakis in 1988), and the Democratic Party has a 1 million vote
registration edge in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that New York seems very much on Bush's back burner is
the latest evidence of how his fortunes were turned as he struggled
to win the nomination, particularly as he campaigned among
conservative voters in South Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came to New York last October, and though a large part of
that was to raise money _ that is what usually brings Republican
candidates to the state _ he traveled aggressively across New York,
visiting poor and black neighborhoods and, presenting himself as a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly suggested that he was the kind of Republican who
would win New York, which, given Gore's status at the time, was a
suggestion that did not seem particularly far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers in New York insisted that nothing had changed,
and that their candidate's victory in Tuesday's primary meant that
he would be back in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, New York was in play for
the primary process,'' said Zenia Mucha, political adviser to Gov.
George E. Pataki, who ran Bush's New York effort. ``I think that
will continue in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   That view was not widely held Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be nuts to even try,'' said one of Gore's senior
advisers, who added that the vice president, accordingly, was also
not planning to spend much time in the state. ``It would be a waste
of money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mitchell Moss, director of the Taub Urban Research Center at New
York University, suggested that Bush's difficulties in New York
went beyond his base of Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   Moss said independent and Democratic voters might have been
soured by the tough campaign that Bush waged against McCain; the
tactics Bush used were the subject of much coverage and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paid a high price for winning New York,'' Moss said. ``Up
until this campaign, he'd been a `Mr. Clean' kind of candidate. I
think they have to concede New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Guy V. Molinari, the Staten Island borough president who
ran the elder Bush's 1988 presidential campaign in New York and who
also ran McCain's campaign in New York this past month, sighed in
discouragement when asked if he thought Bush could compete in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said he would enthusiastically support Bush if McCain
dropped out, but did not see after Tuesday's primary how Bush could
pose a real threat to Gore in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my doubts,'' Molinari said. ``Can we win it? I guess
the theoretical answer is yes. But I'm doubtful they'll target New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
