<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DEVIL-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC PUTS ITS FAITH IN THE CARTOON GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, God is Jerry Garcia. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Half the beat-up old VW minivans in Northern California must be
rocking in Grateful appreciation to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe these people knew it all along.
</P>
<P>
   God is a Garcia look-alike in the new animated series ``God, the
Devil and Bob,'' which premieres Thursday. He's white-bearded,
unflustered and totally casual in T-shirt, sneakers and rectangular
shades.
</P>
<P>
   His voice, though, is easily recognizable as James Garner's. And
it's Garner's voice, as much as the late Garcia's visage, that
gives the show its laid-back style.
</P>
<P>
   The other voice talent is just as impressive. Broadway star Alan
Cumming is the devil. French Stewart (``3rd Rock From the Sun'') is
Bob, a Detroit autoworker who becomes a comic battleground between
good and evil. Laurie Metcalf voices Bob's wife, Donna. Their
rebellious teenage daughter, Megan, sounds like Bart Simpson
because she's Nancy Cartwright.
</P>
<P>
   If only the writing were as sharp as the casting, ``God, the
Devil and Bob'' would be an answered prayer.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that God is losing his enthusiasm for humankind _ God
must have a TV set _ and accepts a sporting bet with Lucifer.
Humanity can save itself if it proves that it deserves another
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The devil gets to choose the person who will bear the burden of
proof, and the devil spots Bob guzzling beer on a barstool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Alman?'' sighs the Almighty. ``Not my best work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob takes some convincing, and even then hasn't a clue how to
save the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drink,'' Bob tells God in a moment of Job-like despair. ``I
swear. I download porn off the Internet _ I mean, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He heads home and announces, ``You'll never guess who I ran into
today.'' But his wife and daughter are quarreling and don't hear.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bob's contention that he's ``a messenger from God''
isn't readily embraced by anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In the show's third installment, it lands him briefly in the
Grassy Knoll Asylum, while Satan cheerfully assumes Bob's identity
and tries, without success, to seduce Donna.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Simpsons'' represents the manically funny end of the TV
animation spectrum and ``King of the Hill'' occupies the droll end,
then ``God, the Devil and Bob'' lies in ``Hill'' country.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, it's more humorous than broadly comic. There
are bits of broadax material _ in hell, Guy Lombardo's orchestra
plays ``Auld Lang Syne'' over and over. But the show scores better
with gentler japes. Here's God on teenagers: ``I get them till
they're 12; he (Lucifer) gets them till they're 20.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not a howler. No one will choke on his Cheetos watching
this amiably amusing show, but give it credit for one thing.
Thursday, at least, it supplants ``Jesse'' on the NBC schedule, and
that weighs in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, ``God, the Devil and Bob'' moves to 8:30 p.m.
Tuesday, opposite the ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' juggernaut.
At NBC, the time slot is also known as the Valley of the Shadow of
Death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
