<SLUG> BC-SUPER-GOPFOLO09-COX-2NDLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2ND LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Updates attribution in 4th and 5th grafs.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    McCain ponders ending campaign
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ The winner was out and about Wednesday. The
loser was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after he scored decisive victories, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas sounded the first notes in his fight for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Republican John McCain, who won just four of the 13 Republican
contests Tuesday, flew from Los Angeles to his cabin near Sedona
with the media in tow. McCain is weighing what to do now that the
Republican nomination all but belongs to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has scheduled a news conference for noon eastern time
today at which he is exected to temporarily suspend his campaign or
leave the race altogether.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has no campaign events scheduled after today, except for
an off-the-record barbecue with journalists at his rustic cabin
near Sedona. The primaries and caucuses Tuesday lived up to their
billing as the make-or-break round of voting, and Wednesday brought
a clear change in focus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was in Austin, where he voted for himself in next week's
Texas presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting McCain's decision, Bush is expected to campaign today
in Colorado, Utah and Wyoming, which hold primaries Friday. Texas,
Florida and four other states vote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Having put down McCain's stubborn challenge with the help of
conservative Republicans, Bush turned his attention to the
formidable task of winning support from centrist voters who have so
far shunned him for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He praised McCain, abandoning the vitriol that has marked their
increasingly contentious race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the campaign allowed him to show Americans that he
could ``come through a tough primary intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men spoke Tuesday night, a conversation Bush described
as ``good,'' but that McCain political director John Weaver called
``quick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will resolve any differences we have at a later date,''
Bush said. ``I'm confident we will be able to do so. He waged a
good campaign. He's a tough competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain touched a nerve, and that is people are sick
and tired of what's going on in Washington,'' Bush said. ``I also
touched that same nerve. That's why our party is energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is now going after Vice President Al Gore, who has said
keeping a Democrat in office is the best way to keep the economy
humming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to respond by saying if people are happy with the
status quo in Washington, then vote for Al Gore,'' said Bush. ``If
people are happy with Al Gore and Bill Clinton, the tone they've
set for America, then you've got a perfect person to vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Bush's running mate also intensified
Wednesday, despite the governor's protestations that such talk is
premature.
</P>
<P>
   Several names made the rounds Wednesday on an informal e-mail
network of Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   Included were Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, U.S. Rep. J.C. Watts
of Oklahoma, New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, New York Gov.
George Pataki, former GOP presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole,
U.S. Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, former Gen. Colin Powell and Sen.
Connie Mack of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said he would not accept the No. 2 spot ``under any
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
