<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SAID TO OFFER JOHNSON TO 6 TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jets, apparently trying to avoid a divisive holdout by its
star player, have shopped Keyshawn Johnson to at least six teams,
including every team with a top 5 pick in April's college draft,
according to one National Football League executive.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, the Jets' director of football operations, called
the Washington Redskins earlier this week to offer Johnson straight
up for the No. 2 pick in the draft. The Redskins declined. Parcells
then offered Johnson for the Redskins' No. 3 overall pick. Again,
the Redskins rebuffed Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who has continued, through a spokesman, not to comment
on trade rumors, told one NFL executive that the reason he was
interested in moving Johnson was because he was upset that Johnson
was not the kind of team player he thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   That, presumably, is because of Johnson's desire to have his
contract renegotiated, even though there are two years left on his
original six-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is underpaid by current market standards and his agent,
Jerome Stanley, has dropped hints since the free-agent signing
period began last month that Johnson closely watched the lucrative
deal that receiver Joey Galloway signed with Dallas ($42 million
for seven years). But the Jets are in a bind, only $1 million under
the $62.172 million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they abandoned their longstanding policy of not
renegotiating deals that have more than one year left and were
inclined to accommodate Johnson, they would have to make
significant changes to the rest of the roster to fit Johnson's
salary under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has told one teammate that he plans to sit out the
off-season workout program, which begins in less than two weeks.
And Stanley has privately hinted to the Jets that Johnson might
hold out when camp begins in July if his contract was not reworked.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley would not comment Wednesday on the trade rumors. Johnson
has not been available for comment since the trade talk began
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jets could still decide to keep Johnson, Parcells
seems to want to stockpile picks in an attempt to move up in the
draft. The Jets have the 16th and 18th picks in the first round,
but Parcells' moves indicate the Jets want to move into position to
select one of the top players in the draft: perhaps one of Penn
State's superb defenders, the pass rusher Courtney Brown or
linebacker LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets were to acquire more picks, they may try to package
them to try to acquire the No. 1 pick, owned by the Cleveland
Browns. Dwight Clark, the Browns' director of football operations,
has said it would take a huge deal to get their pick, but he told
The Baltimore Sun that three first-rounders would be a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Coach Brian Billick said the Ravens did not speak with
the Jets Wednesday. He said it was still up to the Jets to decide
how serious they were about trading Johnson for the Ravens' pick,
No. 5 over all. Billick said that discussions with the Jets are no
further along than the talks the team has had with at least 10
teams about their pick, although he maintained that he was
optimistic about a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten far enough that we laid out the parameters that
if they do decide they want to crank it up, we could move fairly
quickly,'' Billick said. ``Certainly we're interested. How serious
they are, they have to let us know. We can only linger with this so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will come a point where we will either move on or the
Jets will have to increase their interest. This needs to go to the
next level within the next day or two or we need to move on. We're
not going to be sitting here and be paralyzed by it. We have other
things to attend to. If this is going to happen, New York needs to
make overtures in the next 24 hours. We're not going to wait until
next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick said the Ravens would want to meet with Johnson and
Stanley before any deal was made. They had not received permission
from the Jets to do that Wednesday. At least with the Ravens,
Billick seemed to say, everyone needs to take a deep breath and
calm down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Keyshawn watch,'' Billick said. ``I was at a
function and everyone was waiting for my cell phone to ring. All of
a sudden I'm supposed to be in L.A. to talk to Keyshawn and I'm
not. I'm sitting right here. We're nowhere near there. I'm going to
have dinner with my wife, and I don't expect to be interrupted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
