<HEADLINE>
INJURY WAVE HITS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The Angels went about halfway into camp without
any serious health issues, but Wednesday things changed. Mo Vaughn,
Jarrod Washburn and Jeff DaVanon all had health problems Wednesday
of varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was scratched from Wednesday's game against the Rockies
because of a corneal abrasion to his left eye. He rubbed his eye
Tuesday night after pieces of drywall fell from the ceiling into
his eye. It happened at Vaughn's aunt's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he should buy his aunt a new house,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was given medication for the eye and is expected to be
back in the lineup today.
</P>
<P>
   DaVanon was examined by team physician Dr. Lewis Yocum in Los
Angeles Wednesday and was found to have a torn labrum in his left
shoulder. He sustained the injury last Friday diving for a ball in
a game against the Mariners. He is out indefinitely and the course
of treatment has not been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn has a strained left external oblique muscle, just below
the rib cage. Washburn, who is competing for a spot in the starting
rotation, also will be out indefinitely. He has struggled in his
two starts, particularly his last start on Tuesday when he gave up
three runs and five hits in 2 2/3 innings. He also walked four.
</P>
<P>
   ``His command was affected by how he was feeling,'' Scioscia
said. ``It's important for him now to take a step back.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a blow to Washburn's chances of making the starting
rotation, particularly because he was hampered by a similar injury
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, it's tough for him,'' Scioscia said. ``He had the
same thing last year. We had a talk with him and said let's take it
one step at a time. Obviously he won't get his next start. But as
of right now, Wash is still in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill threw three perfect innings in the Angels' 6-3 victory
over the Rockies Wednesday afternoon at Tempe Diablo Stadium. After
the game, Scioscia said Hill would be his opening day starter
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In the victory, Jim Edmonds and Garret Anderson homered.
</P>
<P>
   In a split-squad game at Phoenix, the A's beat the Angels, 7-2.
Ramon Ortiz started and gave up one run and two hits in three
innings, the only run coming on a home run by John Jaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``My location is very good right now,'' Ortiz said. ``Inside,
outside, my fastball, slider, changeup ... everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dickson followed Ortiz and didn't fare so well, allowing
three runs and six hits in three innings. Dickson, who is coming
off shoulder surgery, has regained his velocity but not his
command.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much time he needs (to regain his command), you never
know,'' Scioscia said. ``Some guys coming off injuries never regain
co don't think that's going to be the case with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Angels manager-pitching coach Marcel Lachemann
reacquianted himself with some old friends Wednesday at Angels camp
before going to work in his new position, as the Colorado Rockies'
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Being the pitching coach for a team that plays at
hitter-friendly Coors Field is not the easiest job in the world,
but Lachemann said the decision to take the job was easy because of
his relationship with new Rockies manager Buddy Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is Buddy being the manager,'' Lachemann said.
``We had a chance to work together at the Pan Am Games and it was a
great situation. We worked together well and accomplished a
difficult task. A chance to go where he was managing was an easy
choice, it wasn't a question of where.''
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann said he won't approach coaching the pitchers in Coors
Field any different than any other ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about pitching there is you still have to do the
same things as anywhere else,'' he said. ``Sometimes you get caught
up in where you're pitching and don't do the basic things, like
throwing strikes and getting ahead of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann said he still keeps a close eye on the Angels, despite
the sweeping changes to the scouting department and coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I agree with that part of it, but it's still a
good club, they have an outstanding lineup,'' he said. ``And they
have some fine arms. They'll surprise some people. I'm hearing
everybody is pleased with Mike (Scioscia). It's a question of guys
staying healthy. They've got a great lineup offensively and
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann, who was the organization's roving pitching instructor
last season, has a keen interest in the young pitchers battling for
starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be less than honest with you if I said I wasn't,'' he
said. ``I have a lot of time invested in those guys, so it's
natural to watch them and wish them well.''
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 12:05 p.m., Tempe Diablo Stadium
</P>
<P>
   Radio/TV: KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Brewers at Angels. Brian Cooper will start for
Anaheim against Milwaukee's Steve Woodward. Cooper, who went to
USC, is among the group of young pitchers competing for a spot in
the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's results: The Angels beat the Rockies, 6-3, and lost
to the A's, 7-2, in split-squad games. In the victory, starter Ken
Hill threw three perfect innings and Jim Edmonds and Garret
Anderson each homered. In the loss, starter Ramon Ortiz gave up one
run and two hits in three innings, but Jason Dickson followed and
yielded three runs and six hits in three innings. Outfielder Norm
Hutchins had two hits for the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
