<HEADLINE>
THE BAD NEW BRAVES: SMOLTZ OUT FOR THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Only the season will determine which part of the
anatomy will have a greater effect on the Atlanta Braves' attempt
to win their ninth consecutive division championship _ John
Rocker's mouth or John Smoltz's right elbow. The Braves could have
done without both.
</P>
<P>
   Already in a quandary over Rocker and his offensive remarks, the
Braves disclosed Wednesday that a large hole has developed in their
vaunted starting pitching rotation. Smoltz has a torn ligament in
his pitching elbow and will miss the entire season after having
surgery March 23. The Mets, the most serious threat to the Braves'
stranglehold on first place, immediately became the primary
beneficiary of Smoltz's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Although the elbow has caused Smoltz problems previously,
prompting several stays on the disabled list, the right-hander has
managed to pitch most of each season.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood, a 25-year-old right-hander who was the team's
most consistent starter last season, will replace Smoltz in the big
three, and the Braves plan to fill in behind him from pitchers on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to stay inside the organization; that's our
primary focus at the moment,'' General Manager John Schuerholz said
by telephone from the Braves' camp in Kissimmee, Fla. ``We don't
have plans to look elsewhere right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz mentioned Terry Mulholland, a journeyman left-hander,
as the most likely candidate to be the fourth starter. Mulholland
and Bruce Chen began camp competing for the No. 5 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Although the loss of Smoltz would seem to be a blow to their
status as the top team in the National League East, the Braves, no
stranger to it, have become adept at overcoming adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Mark Wohlers lost the strike zone, the
Braves found a successful closer in Kerry Ligtenberg. When
Ligtenberg went down for the season with an elbow injury a year
ago, the Braves put Rocker in his spot and enjoyed equal success.
Last year, they learned just before spring training that Andres
Galarraga, their power-hitting first baseman, had cancer and would
miss the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' Schuerholz said, ``we're getting practice at
this _ devastating injury news in spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves determine that Mulholland and Chen are not the
answer and decide to look elsewhere for a starting pitcher, they
would join nearly every other major league team. Schuerholz did not
preclude that possibility at some point, and said if a front-line
pitcher were available, he would talk to the team that was offering
him ``if they're not asking too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who is two months from his 33rd birthday, was on the
disabled list twice in each of the last two seasons with an ailing
elbow. He twice had arthroscopic surgery to remove bone chips from
the elbow, before the 1998 season and in September 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who pitches as long as he has and as many innings as
he has and puts that much strain on his elbow,'' Schuerholz said,
``there is the likelihood that the elbow or shoulder will give out.
He's a 200-plus-innings-a-year guy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Smoltz pitched last Sunday against Tampa Bay, allowing
three runs and five hits in one and two-thirds innings, he had pain
in the elbow. He had a magnetic resonance imaging test, which
showed a torn medial collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days have been the worst for me,'' Smoltz said in
Kissimmee. ``Just not knowing, trying a lot of things, trying to
get ready for the season, and then after that game, for about a
five-hour period, I felt pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   When he had elbow trouble last year, Smoltz tried to alleviate
it by throwing with a three-quarters pitching motion. He also began
using a knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who has a 157-113 career record, won the National League
Cy Young award in 1996 and has the best postseason record, 12-4,
among Atlanta pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
