<SLUG> BC-ELECT-OUTLOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH SET FOR FIERY RACE, STARTING AT ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to insert new 6th and 7th graf to include campaign events on
Wednesday and Thursday and new 15th graf to add some doubt on
whether candidates could really campaign every day.)  (DW) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strategists for Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush
said Wednesday that there would be no let up from the primary
season as they move quickly to define each other on the stump and
on the air in an unusually frenetic five-month run up to their
parties' nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns recalled how Bob Dole in 1996 and Michael Dukakis
in 1988 lay dormant in the summer before the general election,
allowing their rivals to gain the upper hand through television or
oratorical barrages. This time, officials on both sides said, that
will not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer competitiveness of the race _ early polls show Gore
and Bush running neck and neck _ also seems to be driving each
candidate to be engaged earlier and more forcefully than past
campaigns. Even if the candidates wanted to lay low, strategists on
both sides said, they could not because of the proliferation of
coverage on the Internet and on new cable television outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a continued focus on message each and every
day,'' said Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist. ``Virtually every
day, Bush will be somewhere in a position to comment on something
of significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, put it this way:
``Strap on your seat belt. The roller coaster ride has just begun.
If people think the pace has been intense up to this point, they
haven't seen anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore strategists said they could enjoy the luxury
of looking ahead because of their candidates' coast-to-coast
triumphs in a string of contests on Tuesday, the biggest primary
day of the year. Bill Bradley, after failing to win a single
contest, plans to quit the Democratic race Thursday while Sen. John
McCain, trailing badly in the Republican contest, may follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore showed no sign of slowing down Wednesday as he traveled
to Michigan and Minnesota, where Democratic delegates are being
selected in coming days. Bush basked in his victory by staying home
in Austin, Tex., as he prepared for stops Thursday in Colorado,
Utah and Wyoming, where there will be contests on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Each side is aggressively seeking the loyalties of the
independents and Democrats who flocked to Sen. John McCain, and
they are also battling over a small group of swing voters, mostly
in the Midwest, who are usually pivotal to the outcome. Strategists
in both camps said they were scheduling trips to the battleground
states of Ohio, Michigan, Illinois, Missouri, Pennsylvania, New
Jersey and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are also taking special steps to address their
own vulnerabilities. Bush, for example, is planning international
trips _ one possibility is trips to European capitals _ to
demonstrate his grasp of international affairs and military
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to win over McCain's supporters with an extensive
series of town meetings with independent and undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a year when not advertising but contact with the
people has actually matters a lot,'' said Robert Shrum, one of
Gore's chief strategists. ``You will see Al Gore doing a lot of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, advertising is at the heart of both campaign's
blueprints in the coming months. Bush is counting on a financial
advantage because he did not accept federal subsidies in the
primaries and therefore, unlike Gore, is not subject to spending
caps. But both the Republican and Democratic Parties are collecting
so-called unregulated soft money which officials in the two
campaigns said the parties would channel into issue advertising
intended to help or hurt Bush or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials do not like talking publicly about the plans
for television blitzes. Asked what his campaign had in store, Rove
said: ``We have flexibility. We have footage collected. And we have
thoughts developed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrum, even less direct, said, ``I don't want to talk about
that.'' Pressed further, he added, ``The Gore campaign will be
ready to do what it has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be, of course, some bluffing in the Bush and Gore
organizations. It is hard to picture the candidates maintaining
nonstop schedules until the conventions in late summer. Even so,
the candidates are clearly determined not to repeat the mistakes of
losers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   A telling sign of how quickly the campaigns have shifted to
general election strategies _ even before either candidate has
officially accumulated enough delegates to win the nomination _ was
in the victory speeches by Bush and Gore on Tuesday night. It is
customary in such addresses for candidates to refer only briefly to
the race ahead. But Bush and Gore spelled out what their advisers
said Wednesday would be basic themes for the general election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are racing to the center by highlighting their
more moderate stands. Bush is seeking to paint Gore as a creature
of Washington who, despite his deep involvement as vice president,
could not make sufficient progress on issues ranging from education
to health case. They will also remind voters of his ties to
President Clinton _ and of his own role in the 1996 campaign
finance debacle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a theme that Bush officials said they hope will reverberate
month after month, Bush declared on Tuesday: ``America must not
give Clinton-Gore four more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond attacking Gore, the Bush campaign is seeking to generate
appeal, especially among women, by stressing the ``compassionate
conservative'' message upon which he based the early days of his
candidacy. In particular, Bush's aides said they expect him to
speak frequently about education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, will emphasize his own credentials on the
education issue and seek credit for his role in presiding over the
hardiest economy in decades. On a host of issues, Gore will portray
Bush as intolerant and as a vessel for the religious right and
extremists. His aides said he will accuse Bush of being against gun
control, a woman's right to have an abortion, a patient's bill of
rights and against environment regulations. As Gore asserted on
Tuesday, he will ridicule the governor's economic proposals as part
of a ``risky tax scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Several strategists in both parties said the candidates acted so
aggressively to put forth their themes because their greatest fear
is that they will be defined by their opponents _ and forfeit the
opportunity to alter their images.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first guy to let down his guard loses in these races,''
said Alex Castellanos, a Republican media consultant. ``So I don't
see any fallow period any more in elections. The lesson Bill
Clinton taught everyone is you don't lay low. And Republicans have
learned that too.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their planned hectic campaign schedules, aides to Bush
and Gore offered some caveats. Their candidates, they said, could
conceivably take some time off. But they were careful to avoid the
word ``vacation,'' and to note that any respite would be only
brief.
</P>
<P>
   More than one aide recalled how after Dukakis captured the
Democratic nomination, he returned to his home state of
Massachusetts _ where he was governor _ and virtually vanished from
the national scene. For weeks, he tended mostly to state business
and rarely ventured beyond the western border of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Some strategists said they are not eager for the intense period
of stumping, but see no other option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the voters want to be inundated with political
campaigning every day for the next 35 weeks,'' said Haley Barbour,
an adviser to Bush and former chairman of the Republican Party.
``However, with 24-hour news television and the internet and the
vastly increased news outlets, I feel the press won't let it rest.
Every news organization is going to demand a Bush story and a Gore
story every day.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Andrew, the national chairman of the Democratic Party,
seemed eager for the action. Already, he said, the party has begun
making decisions on advertising ``based literally on hourly reads
on where the candidates are and where they're going _ we're looking
forward to continual engagement. It will be fluid and dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is the voters will tire of the
candidates. But that does not seem to weigh heavily in the
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is, if you're not keeping your periscope up that you
might be forgotten,'' said Ronald Kaufman, a Republican national
committeeman from Massachusetts. ``Overexposure is the last thing
to worry about. Not the first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
