u s BC-FBN-ESIASON-NYT &LR;      03-08 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ESIASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY NIGHT' SHIFT ENDS ESIASON'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling a need to reinvigorate ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC
Sports Wednesday purged the series of Boomer Esiason, the analyst
since 1998, as well as the longtime producer and director.
</P>
<P>
   ABC brought back Don Ohlmeyer, the producer of the show from
1971 to 1977, to light a spark under the 30-year-old show, which is
ABC's second-highest prime-time program and the highest-rated
football programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 11 months here, I've concluded it could be better,''
said Howard Katz, the president of ABC Sports, whose career started
as an assistant on the show in 1971. ``We're going to take it in a
different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz praised Ken Wolfe, the producer, and Craig Janoff, the
director, but said the production had begun to show a ``sameness.''
He added: ``I feel we have to make it special again. It has to be a
big event again. ''
</P>
<P>
   Katz and Ohlmeyer recognize the impossibility of recreating the
newness and singularity of ``Monday Night Football'' during the
1970's, when Howard Cosell and Don Meredith created a tense,
humorous and bizarre chemistry and Frank Gifford played a
combination straight man and human wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd caution anyone to believe that the goal here is to try to
redo what was done in 1973 and 1974,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``I think
there's a modern-day version of the day when `Monday Night
Football' was the epitome of sports television production in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prestige in bringing back Ohlmeyer, a legendary
producer-director who last year retired after a successful run as
the president of NBC's West Coast entertainment operations,
Wednesday's changes were stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way life goes,'' Esiason said, during a telephone
interview Wednesday. ``It's like being cut by a team. It happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, who produced ``Monday Night'' for 14 years and won 6 Emmy
Awards, said: ``We know we had a great run and a great Super Bowl
in January. It's a big surprise. But it's their prerogative.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and Janoff, who worked together on ``Monday Night
Football'' for 12 years, were dismissed by Katz by telephone
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaels, the play-by-play announcer for ``Monday Night
Football,'' said he understood Katz's rationale for hiring
Ohlmeyer. But he said: ``I've never worked with a better producer
than Kenny or a better director than Craig. This is very
emotionally difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz informed Esiason through his agent, Steve Rosner.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Monday Night Football'' overhaul comes at a time when the
season's Nielsen rating, a 13.7, was the series' historical low.
Yet by the end of its 17-game run, it was ABC's highest-rated
series and the third-ranked in prime time. But ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' has pushed ``Monday Night Football'' aside as ABC's
top program.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Monday Night Football's'' rating has fallen, its prime-time
ranking has increased, owing to the encroachment of cable, videos
and the Internet on the broadcast networks' share of the viewing
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the changes will increase the rating is unknown. But
Katz wanted to make an imprint on the program. He started his
career at ABC Sports as a production assistant on ``Monday Night
Football'' in 1971, working under Ohlmeyer. From 1983 to 1993 he
was president of Ohlmeyer's independent production company. When
Katz decided he wanted to change ``Monday Night Football'' last
December, he turned to Ohlmeyer. ``Are you out of your mind?''
Ohlmeyer asked. He was happily retired, honing his golf game. On
Sunday, he agreed to return.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels said he was flabbergasted when Ohlmeyer suggested to
him 10 days ago that he was considering a ``Monday Night Football''
redux. ``I said something like, `Are you daft?''' Michaels said.
``I lent no seriousness to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ohlmeyer must decide how to change the production of
``Monday Night Football.'' He wants to resuscitate the
unpredictability and danger that characterized the
Cosell-Meredith-Gifford years. ``There's a fertile field to plow
and to do it in an interesting, innovative way that will keep
people tuned in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will also have to determine whether to hire one or two
analysts. Michaels is not a big fan of a three-man set-up because
of the promotional announcements and other obligations that clutter
a broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to be the right three,'' Michaels said. ``A
good two is better than a mediocre three. A great three is better
than a great two.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for Michaels' new partner(s) starts with Jimmy
Johnson, the former Dallas and Miami coach, who was a sparkplug on
Fox's pre-game studio show for three seasons. Bill Parcells, the
former Jet coach who is the team's director of football operations,
is also a candidate, but his stint with NBC as a studio analyst,
then a game announcer, was not a glowing success.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ohlmeyer adds a third announcer depends upon whether he
finds someone with the kind of personality who can generate
controversy and verbal fireworks. But he will not choose one from
outside the sports realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to see Arnold Schwarzenegger do color,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason's two-year stint was rocky. He was hired in 1998 when
ABC couldn't lure John Madden from Fox and was teamed with Dan
Dierdorf. In his first season, Esiason fended off criticism that he
did not get along with Dierdorf.
</P>
<P>
   He became the sole analyst in 1999 when ABC did not renew
Dierdorf's contract, and was criticized for not being a superstar
broadcaster. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
