<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DISCOUNTS THE POTENTIAL IMPACT OF BUSH ON THE NEW YORK
SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent at NYT38 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday that the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee and the candidate he
endorsed, George W. Bush, would make little difference in the
outcome of his United States Senate race, but he added that if the
election were held today, ``I'd think he'd be a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's comments, however measured, about the political
benefits he might reap from Bush, were in striking contrast to the
view of Hillary Rodham Clinton's advisers, who reacted with
something resembling joy to the prospect of the Texas governor at
the top of the Republican ticket in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush was Rudy Giuliani's pick, and now they're joined
at the hip,'' said Howard Wolfson, Clinton's press secretary, in
what is certain to become a familiar theme. ``The mayor will have
to explain to New Yorkers why his candidate is anti-choice and
pro-gun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before Tuesday's presidential primaries, many New
York Republican officials said the mayor would be in a stronger
position in his Senate race if he had Sen. John McCain of Arizona
at his side in the fall, when Giuliani will need Democratic and
independent votes to beat Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Giuliani seemed to endorse that view by repeatedly
praising McCain and then spending only two hours in the same room
with Bush, who was in the state campaigning for a day and a half.
Giuliani's advisers admitted they had grown nervous that Bush's
embrace of religious conservatives would alienate moderate
Republicans in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday both Democratic and Republican strategists predicted
that Giuliani would campaign to the political center and rarely
appear with Bush, who in any case is expected to spend little time
in a Democratic state like New York that he is unlikely to carry in
November. Nelson Warfield, a Republican political consultant, said
that such a scenario would suit Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll be happy to have him change planes at Kennedy
Airport if he's flying somewhere overseas,'' Warfield said, ``but
don't expect him to stand on the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Adler, a Democratic political consultant, added that
``the nature of Giuliani's problem is that instead of the
presidential candidate carrying him, the presidential candidate
will be a monkey on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani strongly rejected that view, saying that New Yorkers
are often ticket-splitters, as they were in a 1992 race that
elected Alfonse M. D'Amato to the Senate, and that his race against
Clinton will have a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate election is going to get decided as a Senate
election,'' the mayor said at a news briefing at city hall. ``Just
the way it did in 1992, when Bill Clinton won the state by a
million votes and Al D'Amato won the state narrowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added: ``There are even theories that go around that
New Yorkers will vote for one party for the president and the other
for the Senate in order to balance things. That's as interesting a
theory as anything else. So I would not be overwhelmed by the
thought of who would be better for me, or who would be better for
Clinton on the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   In the briefing, Giuliani also made a point of praising Gov.
George Pataki, the man he needs to help him defeat Clinton. The
governor and the mayor have been feuding for weeks over Giuliani's
refusal to attack McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor and I have a very, very good relationship,''
Giuliani said. ``There are times in which our staffs have little
disputes with each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
