<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CRITICIZES CITY FOR MISSING GUN SAFETY TALKS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton criticized New York City on
Wednesday for failing to join more than two dozen cities, counties
and states that are trying to force gun manufacturers to improve
gun safety and tighten controls over gun sales through legal
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changes in the way guns are designed and manufactured,
marketed and distributed could save many lives in the future,''
Clinton said in an appearance at a lower Manhattan office building
with state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who is negotiating with
the gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, along with representatives from San Francisco, New
Orleans and other states and cities, has met several times since
last summer with gun manufacturers, asking them to add trigger
locks or other devices to guns they make to prevent them from being
fired accidentally, a spokesman for the attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   And the attorney general has asked the manufacturers to stop
distributing guns to dealers who have a history of selling to
criminals, said Scott R. Brown, Spitzer's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lost opportunity because New York City has
not joined in this effort,'' Clinton said. ``Probably the people in
New York City have as much or more to gain from such a code of
conduct and changes in the way that the gun manufacturers do
business as any people anywhere in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate in New York,
did not mention her probable Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. But Howard Wolfson, her campaign spokesman, said after
her remarks that Giuliani is to blame for the city's failure to
participate in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, Giuliani's press secretary, later rejected the
criticism. ``If Mrs. Clinton lived in New York City, she would know
that it is the corporation counsel that analyzes these issues'' and
would decide whether the city should join in such an effort, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna B. Goodman, a spokeswoman for Michael D. Hess, the
corporation counsel, said the city has not sued gun manufacturers
because it is still trying to assess the likelihood of winning such
a case. She said the city is prepared to participate with Spitzer,
a Democrat, in negotiations with the gun manufacturers, but it has
not been invited to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a separate appearance Wednesday before The Gay and
Lesbian Independent Democrats, a group in the West Village,
detailed her positions on a number of gay-related issues. She said
she supports extending health and other benefits associated with
marriage to domestic partners, allowing people to join the military
regardless of their sexual orientation and national legislation
that would outlaw so-called hate crimes, Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Clinton said she would back national legislation
that would bar an employer from discriminating against a person
based on sexual orientation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
