<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SMALL PRINT ARE CLUES TO BUSH'S DELEGATE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after their most tumultuous primary in memory, it was
clear Wednesday that New York Republicans' convoluted way of
awarding presidential delegates helped George W. Bush _ and equally
clear that even Bush supporters found that system wanting.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of the popular vote went to Bush's delegates,
to about 44 percent for Sen. John McCain's. Yet that tight contest
was not reflected in the race for the delegates, which, based on
unofficial returns, Bush appeared to have won, 67 delegates to 26.
</P>
<P>
   Such odd totals capped the state's first truly contested
Republican presidential primary in 20 years. It saw McCain surge
from far back in the polls to overtake Bush in a few weeks, then
slip under a barrage of negative television and radio ads. Turnout
on the Republican side was about 25 percent, far higher than the 14
percent in Bob Dole's lopsided victory over Steve Forbes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island, long a bulwark of the state's Republican Party,
went heavily for McCain, defying a party establishment that, from
Gov. George E. Pataki down to local committee members, had almost
unanimously backed Bush. Politicians and voters alike interpreted
the Long Island vote as a continuation of the revolt against the
Nassau County Republican machine that last year gave control of the
County Legislature to Democrats for the first time _ a revolt that
spilled on Tuesday into Suffolk County, as well, with McCain
victories there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a difference in the Republican Party,''
William Herbst said after voting for McCain in New Hyde Park. ``As
far as I'm concerned, it's the party of the patronage system,
especially in Nassau County.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush ran strongest upstate, while the two were nearly evenly
matched in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Republican primary was really 31 mini-contests: In
each of the state's congressional districts, each candidate had a
slate of three people running to be delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Voters cast their ballots not directly for the candidates, but
for delegates, whose names appeared in large type, with the
candidates' names in much smaller print below. Each voter could
vote for as many as three delegates, and most voted for slates,
essentially using all three of their votes for the same
presidential candidate. But some split their tickets, picking
delegate candidates from more than one slate.
</P>
<P>
   Most Bush delegates were well-known elected officials and party
leaders, while McCain's were nearly all political neophytes.
</P>
<P>
   In district after district that McCain carried, overall, Bush
managed to capture one of the three delegate slots, when that
delegate was a prominent figure: County Executive Robert Gaffney
and Rep. Rick A. Lazio in Suffolk County; county Republican
chairman Joseph Mondello in Nassau County; Councilman Thomas V.
Ognibene in Queens; Ronald J. D'Angelo, a local party leader and
perennial candidate in Brooklyn; and state Sen. Hugh Farley in the
Schenectady-Albany region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican primary voters are more inclined to be supportive
of their local elected officials and trust their choices of a
presidential candidate than someone they've never heard of,'' said
Zenia Mucha, a top adviser to Pataki, who helped coordinate Bush's
campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain supporters said the ticket-splitting showed that some
voters simply did not understand the ballot. And Mucha conceded
that perhaps the system should be changed, adding that the
questions raised about it were ``probably a very good, healthy
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians who ran as Bush delegates found themselves in
close races, facing the prospect of a loss that could damage their
prestige. ``I think we're going to change this system, because no
one wants to go through it again,'' said a Republican elected
official who was elected a Bush delegate. ``We took a lot of heat
for it, some of us dodged a bullet, and some of us didn't dodge
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most prominent downstate Republicans, state Sens.
Dean G. Skelos of Long Island and Roy M. Goodman of Manhattan, lost
their races to be Bush delegates, though Republican leaders said
the party would most likely find some role for them at the national
convention in Philadelphia this summer. Returns showed Mondello
barely hanging onto a delegate slot.
</P>
<P>
   The district-by-district voting meant that each district counted
for the same number of delegates, no matter how many Republicans it
held. In the 16th District in the Bronx, it took barely 500 votes
to be elected a delegate; in the 22nd District upstate, it took
more than 24,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
