<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-BIG-DIG-NYT &LR;      03-08 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-BIG-DIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TUNNEL PROJECT TO DIG DEEPER INTO STATE'S POCKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Grilled until their ears glowed pink, the top overseers
of Boston's ``Big Dig'' tried to explain to Massachusetts lawmakers
Wednesday how the project, the largest public works endeavor under
way in the country, came to be $1.4 billion over budget, and why
they did not disclose the overrun earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was billed as just a fact-finding session, but it
also afforded a chance for lawmakers to demand, in an echo of
public sentiment, ``How (italics)could(end italics) you let this
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, of course, that what managers call the
most complex urban infrastructure project in American history, a
scheme to sink Boston's raised Central Artery underground and
connect it to Logan Airport, would run over budget, even if that
budget, before the current overrun, was a monumental $10.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Bostonians were nonetheless more than a little surprised
last month when the media suddenly announced the projected $1.4
billion overrun, because James Kerasiotes, the project's supreme
boss and chairman of the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority, had been
saying for so long that the project would be on time, finished in
2004, and on budget.
</P>
<P>
   Recriminations followed. Federal auditors trooped to town.
Securities and Exchange Commission investigators contacted the
state treasurer. The United States Transportation secretary, Rodney
Slater, issued warnings of freezes on the federal part of Big Dig
financing.
</P>
<P>
   And, while no one was suggesting that the project be halted when
it was already two-thirds done, its engineering achievements were
suddenly obscured in a cloud of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   At the verbal whipping session Wednesday before lawmakers,
Kerasiotes apologized less for the overrun than for how people
found out about it, in media reports released before he could
develop ideas for a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one thing keeps me up at night,'' he said, ``and believe
me, I've had a few sleepless nights over the past month, it's that
we should have done a better job explaining this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not at all our intent to mislead,'' he said. ``There
would be no gain in doing so because the facts are the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those facts, as presented and picked apart for hours Wednesday,
amount to $1.4 billion in various unexpectedly high costs _ from
changes in construction contracts to a longer-than-anticipated need
for consultants _ that, over the last year, project managers
gradually came to realize could not be offset by other savings.
Kerasiotes described how he saved $500 million here and $100
million there in the project's early years, but cost-cutting
opportunities shrank, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All along, he said, project managers had ``pushed back hard'' on
cost pressures, cut staff and looked everywhere for savings, but
some things, like construction quality, could not be sacrificed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project by any measure has been a successful project,''
he maintained, particularly for one so complex that it employs
4,000 workers and is now, at peak construction, costing $4 million
a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very complicated,'' said Robert A. Havern III, chairman
of the Senate Transportation Committee, who noted that he had
learned all about cost pressures when he redid his kitchen. ``But
the accounting is not complicated. Revenues must match
expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing, said Sen. Mark C. Montigny, a Democrat and
chairman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee, ``gives us a
chance not only to form a constructive critique, but ultimately, we
have to decide where the money is coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the administration, and the project's many other
federal and state chiefs, had been reveling in its on-time
achievements. It has already opened a new tunnel, to Logan Airport,
and will ultimately link that new tunnel to the Massachusetts
Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The project, now at $12.2 billion, is much more than a mere
tunnel, of course. When it is done, it will have torn down the
elevated artery on which traffic runs _ or rather, usually crawls _
through the center of town, and replaced it with an elaborate
underground highway system. The project also incluses two bridges
across the Charles River, north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In the project's no-small-trick category: building the
underground highway right underneath where the elevated highway
continues to run; tunneling under a working railway line and
freezing the earth all around it so that the rails do not sink;
threading the highway above or below other existing rail, subway
and utility lines, both on dry-land sites and in watery spots;
installing monitoring systems smart enough to pick up and solve
anything from an accident to a fire on more than four miles of
underground road.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the project's managers must pull off another kind
of trick, the political kind: restoring the project's credibility
and public support.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes promised to overhaul the project's reporting system
to make sure more information was shared with lawmakers and other
monitors. And he did show signs of reform Wednesday when his
managers tried to convince lawmakers that really and truly, the
$1.4 billion overrun was all they expected until the end of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Are you, Kerasiotes was asked, drawing a line in the sand at
$1.4 billion?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from past experience that would be a mistake for me to
do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
