<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA REPORT: TEAMS ARE NOT SMILING AT LOCKER ROOM CAMERAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the National Basketball Association began an experiment
nearly two months ago of having coaches wear miniature microphones
during nationally televised games, the idea was to give fans a
perspective seldom seen in professional sports. The hope for the
NBA. and its broadcast partners, NBC and Turner Sports, was to
increase sagging ratings by using a fan-friendly device.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the NBA has angered players and coaches, who say the
use of microphones during games is intrusive. They are more peeved
at the notion of an unmanned camera being used in locker rooms at
halftime, which the league hopes to implement by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   The growing debate is whether the NBA is revealing too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong,'' Patrick Ewing, the players association
president, said after being informed of the plan to film teams
during halftime. ``We did not agree to it with the owners during
our labor negotiations and it's changing the work conditions.
Anyone can see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, NBC telecasts are down 14 percent from last season's
lockout-tainted season.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley refused to wear a microphone during last Sunday's NBC
telecast against the Lakers. The league decided Wednesday not to
fine Riley because of the short notice the Heat coach had before he
was informed he would have to wear a microphone. But beginning this
weekend, any coach who balks will incur fines beginning at
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very intrusive to the job of coaching,'' Knicks
Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``I think it negatively impacts the
coach, because you now have to really monitor what you say.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, Riley, Larry Bird and Jerry Sloan have echoed the
same sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern about fan interest,'' Van Gundy said. ``And
everybody in the NBA wants it to be an appealing product. But when
fans stop me to talk about the NBA, my sense is that they're not
really concerned about microphones, having a camera in the locker
room, the media have more access to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see great players, great teams, great rivalries,
great basketball and have great people for their kids to emulate.
That's my sense what the fans want. But there is obviously a
different sense by the people who make those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to use microphones was the brainchild of the league's
entertainment division, which has often used the device in its
video productions. But many people in the league wonder if it is
not an overreaction to a decline in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Coach Gregg Popovich ushered in the new era when he
was miked for a game on Christmas day. Since then, NBC's top
broadcasting team has used a microphone on at least one coach and
the lead referee during its weekend games. During the All-Star Game
last month, the two head coaches, Van Gundy and Jackson, were
miked, along with five players.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two weeks, cameras will be positioned in several
locker rooms ``on a voluntary basis,'' Russ Granik, the league's
deputy commissioner, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the coaches have some fair and legitimate concerns,''
he said. ``But hopefully they'll be comfortable with it as time
goes by. The goal is not get into strategy sessions, it is to let
fans get inside the locker room and see what's going on. It's a
judgment by people in that end of the business that this is
something that can enhance our telecasts. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, has labeled the
process ``like Big Brother'' and said he is considering taking the
matter before an arbitrator if the league does not quickly address
the players' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is they just can't change work conditions,''
Hunter said. ``What purpose does it serve to show a bunch of guys
sitting around the locker room?''
</P>
<P>
   Granik said he did not believe the league was violating the
collective bargaining agreement and said he planned to listen to
the union's concerns. He said the NBA would continue to use
microphones during at least one NBC telecast each weekend and one
game per week on either TNT or TBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this just improves the telecasts from the standpoint
of fans,'' he said. ``Wherever the ratings may be, if we can make
things better for the fans, they'll be more likely to watch
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Only snippets of conversation are used for each telecast, with
most choice comments being edited out by the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to be more cognizant of what you say when
you're miked,'' Van Gundy said. ``Even though they may not use it
on air, somebody hears it in some truck, who can then repeat it to
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is not the end, either. This is just going to keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``We're in the basketball business and that's
the problem right there. It's not show business. It's basketball.
That's why people watch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
