<HEADLINE>
RELIEVED MARTIN IS READY TO FOCUS ON GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casey Martin hopes that his best golf is still ahead and that
his legal battles are behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a federal appeals court upheld Martin's right to
use a cart in PGA Tour competition, he spoke publicly Wednesday for
the first time about the decision. The Tour, which has not decided
if it will appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, is expected to
announce its plans sometime after its policy board meeting next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't shock me if they pursued it,'' Martin said during
a teleconference with reporters. ``It would disappoint me, but it
wouldn't shock me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 27, has Klippel-Trenauney-Weber syndrome, a circulatory
disorder that causes severe pain and swelling in his right leg. He
won his lawsuit against the Tour in February 1998, when U.S.
Magistrate Thomas Coffin granted an injunction that required the
Tour to furnish him with a cart.
</P>
<P>
   Had the appeals court decision gone against him, Martin said, he
would have appealed to the Supreme Court. Instead, he can focus on
golf Thursday when he competes in the first round of the Honda
Classic in Coral Springs, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bigger relief than I thought it would be,'' Martin said
of the appellate decision. ``It's not like I thought about it every
day, but now that it's over it's a huge relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin recalled meeting with Commissioner Tim Finchem late last
year during an orientation for Tour rookies. Martin said Finchem
sounded confident that the appeals court would rule in the Tour's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt the longer it went, the better it was for
their side,'' Martin said. ``I was concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his leg has been sore all year, Martin hopes to play in
about 25 tournaments. He has played in five, with his best finish
coming in last month's Touchstone Energy Tucson Open, in which he
tied for 17th place.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will also play next week in the Bay Hill Invitational,
whose host, Arnold Palmer, had testified against Martin at the
trial. ``The irony is that he gave me a special exemption for his
tournament,'' Martin said of Palmer. ``It should be an interesting
week, but I'm grateful and looking forward to meeting with him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
