<SLUG> BC-YANKEENETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS INVESTORS BALK, YANKEENETS REDUCES LOAN AND RAISES RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Resistance from investors forced the company that
owns the New York Yankees baseball team and the New Jersey Nets
basketball team to cut back on the amount of money it wanted to
borrow and to increase the interest rate it will pay.
</P>
<P>
   The company, YankeeNets LLC, said Wednesday that it would issue
$200 million in seven-year bonds paying interest of 12.75 percent.
It originally wanted to borrow $250 million at 11.75 percent,
though the rate discussed with investors had risen to 12.25 percent
by last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the interest rate and the need of YankeeNets, we have
limited the offering to $200 million at an interest rate of 12.75
percent,'' Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for YankeeNets and a
director, said Wednesday. He said the company was ``pleased with
the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein had no comment on how the cut in the amount being
borrowed would affect the uses of the proceeds from the borrowing.
The preliminary offering document had said that only $15 million
would go to operations of the two teams, with $80 million set aside
to pay interest for the first three years and most of the rest
being distributed to the owners of YankeeNets.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the managing general partner of the
Yankees, had been scheduled to get about $40 million from the
proceeds of the offering and a related sale of a stake in the
company to unidentified investors. The cut in the size of the bond
offering appears likely to reduce his take by about $8 million or
more. Former owners of the Nets, who had to borrow large amounts of
money to complete the merger of the two teams and who planned to
use the distribution to repay those loans, will also receive less
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   First Union Securities was the lead underwriter for the
offering, with Merrill Lynch as co-manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
