<HEADER>
A1139 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MACHAUT-MUSIC-$ADV12-     03-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACHAUT-MUSIC-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN NOW, MUSIC IN THE FAMILY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 James M. Keller writes about music on staff at The New Yorker.  
 By JAMES M. KELLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most moderns, Guillaume de Machaut is a distant figure,
familiar only from textbooks. But the New York violin dealer
Dietmar Machold has a more personal response to the medieval
composer: he calls Machaut an ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   The instruments that pass through Machold Rare Violins, across
Broadway from Lincoln Center, are a far cry from the fiedels and
vielles of Machaut's day. Machold's recent clients are said to
include Vladimir Spivakov, Midori and Hilary Hahn, who each, by one
report in a famously tight-lipped business, may have paid as much
as $5 million for their Old Master violins. Machold declined to
comment on these matters.
</P>
<P>
   When he is not in New York _ or at one of the firm's offices in
Tokyo, Zurich, Vienna or Bremen, Germany _ Machold relaxes at
Schloss Eichbuchl, his home in Austria. It is in part a medieval
castle, its oldest portions having been dated to 1348, when Machaut
was in midcareer.
</P>
<P>
   Its owners have included the youngest sister of Napoleon and a
daughter of Marie Antoinette, and it is big enough to house
Machold's expansive collection of antique sports cars. A
Francophile whose literary preferences run to the 19th century,
Machold owns several recordings of Machaut's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you need a quiet moment in your day,'' he said,
``listening to the Machaut Mass provides the reflection you
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The family business goes back five generations, to 1859, when a
German Machold married into a family of luthiers. In the same
decade, several Macholds left for America. A member of that branch,
Roland Machold, lives in Princeton and was last year named
treasurer of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Machold, a genealogy maven, traveled to Germany in 1992
to chart the family's roots in the Thuringian village of Oelse (now
incorporated into Katzhutte, near Ilmenau). He asked a restaurant
proprietor whether anyone in town was named Machold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Yes, about 50, including the mayor,' so I knew I'd
hit the mother lode,'' Machold said. Over seven centuries, written
records seem to have strayed irretrievably. But Roland Machold's
conversations with the clan confirmed information that had come
down through both his and Dietmar's families: the Macholds were of
French origin but had fled religious persecution; musicians
blossomed regularly on the family tree, including a 16th-century
Johann Machold who rates an entry in The New Grove Dictionary of
Music and Musicians; and until recently, many still spelled their
name ``Machault,'' as did, everyone said, their famous ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring a reporter's disquisition on Machaut's
fascination with isorhythm, a system involving overlapping rhythmic
and melodic patterns, Roland Machold said that it sounded a lot
like what his son, Rob, was up to.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Machold, a biologist, spends his evenings playing drums in
avant-garde bands and obsessing about theoretical relationships
between music and mathematics. And sure enough, reached at his home
in Brooklyn, Rob Machold described a ``rhythmic slide rule'' he
recently invented to illustrate complicated superimpositions of
rhythms in various metric contexts.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting a rhythmically obsessed French composer of the 14th
century to a violin dealer and a theoretically inclined drummer in
the 21st requires a measure of faith. But as we celebrate what is
(for lack of documentary evidence) taken to be the 700th
anniversary year of Machaut's birth, we may choose to believe that
his legacy lives on _ in New York, no less _ through his notes, his
words and even his DNA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
