<HEADLINE>
MASTER CRIMINAL, SENTENCED TO 845 YEARS, CANNOT BE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Ariz., Texas, Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 37 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the pantheon of white-collar criminals, Sholam Weiss, a
rumpled businessman from New York, has earned his place among the
giants.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in Orlando, Fla., Weiss received what is believed to
be the longest federal prison term ever imposed: 845 years. He was
sentenced on racketeering, money laundering and fraud charges, all
from his central role in an immense fraud scheme that siphoned $450
million from an insurance company, leading to its collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But Weiss, 46, was not around to hear the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In October, while a jury in Orlando was deliberating on the
93-count indictment against him, the burly, bearded Weiss vanished.
Now, he can be found only on the FBI's Web site,
www.fbi.gov/mostwant/fugitive/janweiss.htm, where he is featured on
a wanted poster that offers a $95,000 reward for information
leading to his capture. Insurance regulators are offering an
additional $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   That Weiss, who built a lucrative plumbing supply business in
Borough Park, Brooklyn, became both a criminal mastermind and
international fugitive may seem curious to the casual observer. But
the authorities say that this father of five and grandfather of
three is no casual crook. Rather, they say, he has emerged as one
of the more gifted criminals, with a knack for fraud, fleeing and
hiding stolen millions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the federal authorities say they believe that Weiss has
more than enough money to live a comfortable life as a fugitive,
having fled with $25 million to $30 million of the insurance
company's money. The FBI has received some reports that place him
in Israel and others that put him in the United States. Some
evidence also suggests that Weiss, whose home is in Monsey, N.Y.,
could be in Austria, Brazil or Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weiss' corruption and dishonesty know no end,'' Judith K.
Hunt, an assistant U.S. attorney in Orlando, wrote in court papers
filed last month. ``Weiss is in hiding, enjoying his millions in
ill-gotten gains, while his minions face extended periods of
incarceration. The sophistication and scope of his frauds is truly
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheme itself _ in which a series of numbingly complex
mortgage and stock frauds were used to loot the National Heritage
Life Insurance Co. _ attracted little attention outside Florida,
where the majority of the insurer's mostly elderly policy-holders
live. But the federal authorities said it ranked as the largest
insurance company failure caused by criminal acts in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Weiss, 15 business executives and lawyers from
Arizona, Texas, Illinois and New York have either pleaded guilty or
been convicted in the fraud case in the last four years, and
several are already serving long prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   The federal authorities say the fraud began in the early 1990s,
when the group of businessmen and lawyers effectively hijacked the
insurer. Using an artful variation on a simple check-kiting scheme,
they bought the company with a check and then, once they had taken
over, simply lent themselves the money to cover the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   After taking control in 1993, the authorities said, Weiss and
several others stoked National Heritage into a juggernaut of fraud.
They bought up worthless stocks and mortgages in a series of deals
that sucked hundreds of millions of dollars out of the insurer.
Much of the money _ in cash _ just vanished. Millions more ended up
in accounts controlled by Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   When and where Weiss picked up his criminal skills is unclear.
He grew up in Borough Park, where his father ran a fruit stand.
Educated in a yeshiva, where he spoke Yiddish, Weiss finished the
equivalent of high school, but he did not learn English until he
was in his late teens. He began doing construction work as a young
man, and bought Windsor Plumbing Supply in 1974, when he was 20.
According to Weiss' testimony at trial, the company was then
bringing in about $275,000 a year. By 1986, Windsor was doing $20
million in business, with four locations in Brooklyn and a vast
showroom on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Weiss attributed it
all to long hours and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the decade, Windsor had spiraled into debt and
bankruptcy and eventually closed. By that time, Weiss had moved his
family to Monsey, and in 1989, after 14 years of marriage, he and
his wife, Goldie, separated.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor's failure apparently taught Weiss so much that he
started hiring himself out as a bankruptcy specialist, advising
other businessmen on how to work out their debts. It was then, in
1992, the authorities said, that Weiss met some of the people with
whom he would plunder National Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One was Michael D. Blutrich, a lawyer who was an owner of the
topless club Scores on East 60th Street, which was then controlled
by the Gambino organized crime family. Blutrich also served as the
outside counsel for National Heritage. He later admitted his role
in defrauding the insurer and a variety of other crimes, and became
a government witness.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Blutrich and his partner, Lyle K. Pfeffer, Weiss
became a regular visitor to Scores. There, he discussed business
with Blutrich.
</P>
<P>
   Both Blutrich and Pfeffer are now in the government's witness
security program, and the club has declared bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Heritage frauds were not the first time Weiss and
Blutrich faced legal trouble together. In 1994, Weiss was indicted
on mail fraud charges that he had falsely claimed that more than $1
million worth of bathtubs had been damaged in a 1986 fire at a
company warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   He went to trial in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, where
Blutrich gave false information to federal prosecutors in an effort
to prevent Weiss' indictment. But Blutrich's efforts, which he
admitted to when he pleaded guilty to a series of crimes, were for
naught. Weiss was convicted and sentenced to eight months in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who represented Weiss during his trial in Orlando,
Joel Hirschhorn of Miami, filed papers to withdraw from the case
after his client fled, and seems to wish he could forget the
episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall that name,'' he recently joked when a reporter
asked him about Weiss. But during the trial, his representation was
aggressive, despite a sometimes difficult Weiss, who was often
heard yelling at his co-defendants in the courthouse hallways or
talking on his cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Such was his client's churlish behavior that Hirschhorn felt
compelled to point out to the jury during his summation that
``Sholam Weiss is not on trial for being rich or rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' courtroom demeanor endeared him to neither judge, jury
nor courthouse officials. And courtroom observers were speculating
that Weiss would flee long before the October Sunday when he made
his routine call to check in with pretrial services and then
disappeared, jumping the $500,000 bond secured by his wife's house
in Monsey.
</P>
<P>
   At Weiss' sentencing on the National Heritage charges on Feb.
15, Judge Patricia C. Fawsett of Federal District Court in Orlando
said that given the magnitude and repeated nature of the fraudulent
acts, he should be removed permanently from society. Fawsett
devised the mammoth term by stacking one 20-year count on top of
another, because under federal sentencing guidelines, she could not
impose a life term.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not content with the prison time, Fawsett also fined
Weiss $123,399,910 and ordered him to pay $125,016,656 in
restitution to the policy-holders of National Heritage, which is in
receivership under the auspices of Donna L. Williams, the insurance
commissioner in Delaware, where National Heritage was chartered.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' office has also obtained a $339 million judgment
against Weiss in state Supreme Court in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm of O'Keefe &AMP; Lindgren of White Plains, N.Y.,
retained by Williams, has already recovered $175 million to $200
million from other defendants involved in National Heritage cases
and related civil lawsuits, according to Thomas K. Lindgren, a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   And the firm seems to be focusing as much energy on finding what
Lindgren says are Weiss' millions as the government is on finding
Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 priority at the present time,'' Lindgren said, ``is
to recover from Sholam Weiss the hundreds of millions of dollars of
ill-gotten gains in order to return them to the policy-holders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
