<HEADLINE>
MILITIA LEADER ACQUITTED OF PLOTTING TO KIDNAP BOY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bo Gritz, the former Green Beret commando and a leader of the
far-right militia movement, was acquitted Wednesday of charges that
he tried to kidnap a young boy from the parking lot of a middle
school in Suffield, Conn., in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A jury cleared Gritz and his co-defendant, Sheldon Robinson, of
all charges, including attempted kidnapping, conspiracy and
attempted custodial interference. They had been accused of plotting
the kidnapping of one of two boys whose mother had lost a bitter
custody dispute with her ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, in Connecticut Superior Court in Enfield, returned the
verdicts Wednesday after deliberating for more than two days and
apparently concluding that the prosecution had failed to prove that
Gritz (pronounced GRITES) had intended to do anything more than
draw attention to the custody case.
</P>
<P>
   As the verdict was read, Gritz, 61, a retired Army colonel who
is the host of a syndicated radio program, stood beside his lawyer,
David Kritzman, gave members of the jury a military salute and told
them, ``Thank you,'' Kritzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz, whose full name is James G. Gritz, and his son, James R.
Gritz, were arrested on Sept. 30, 1996, while sitting in a car in
the parking lot of McAlister Middle School in Suffield. The car
belonged to Linda M. Wiegand, the mother of two boys who attended
the school.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the car, the police found photographs of the boys, a
school floor plan, a class schedule and two-way radios. Wiegand had
appeared on Bo Gritz's radio program and accused her ex-husband of
sexually abusing the boys. Prosecutors accused Gritz of planning a
rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   Kritzman argued that his client had simply wished to publicize
Wiegand's plight.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, he said he thought the jury had paid
careful attention to the evidence. ``I think that the evidence
didn't add up to the commission of a crime.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a Texas businessman who traveled to Connecticut with
Gritz in September 1996, was accused of planning to use a private
plane to fly Gritz and the boys out of the state. Gritz's son is
facing separate prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
