<SLUG> BC-CHARACTER-ACTORS-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NOMINEES FOR HARDEST-WORKING ACTOR ARE ...  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Elizabeth Weitzman is the film critic for Marie Claire magazine.  
 By ELIZABETH WEITZMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some actors, nominated or not, it's the brightest night of
the year: Jim Carrey will hardly be ignored by the fawning cameras
and fans at the Academy Awards. But at home, we see only a small
fraction of Hollywood's acting population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awards season is hell,'' moans Christopher McDonald, one of
the many actors whose outfits won't be breathlessly assessed by
Joan and Melissa Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read the papers and go, `Oh, but what about
(italics)me?(end italics)'''
</P>
<P>
   True, he's not Tom Cruise. But did Tom Cruise appear in 23 films
during the '90s? McDonald did.
</P>
<P>
   Has Denzel Washington been in more than 80 movies? Maury Chaykin
has.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of this year's Academy Award nominees for best
actor, not one has matched the output of Stephen Tobolowsky in the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   If you've turned on a TV set or visited a cineplex in the last
two decades, you know his face, and Chaykin's and McDonald's as
well. They are the worker bees of the movie industry, among the
most prolific actors in Hollywood, according to a recent list
published in Variety. So even though they won't be burnishing any
acceptance speeches for Oscar night, it's time they had a moment in
the spotlight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN TOBOLOWSKY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his forthcoming movie, ``Bossa Nova'' (opening in May),
Stephen Tobolowsky plays a bald, gangly, maladroit lawyer who can't
believe anyone would fall in love with him; so he invents a new
identity as an Internet Romeo. In a way, it's the consummate role
for this actor. When he arrived in Hollywood from Texas in 1976,
the town's general response was summed up by the director Bruce
Beresford. ``He said I would never have a film career because I
wasn't photogenic,''
</P>
<P>
   Tobolowsky, 48, recalled in a telephone interview. He was asked
to change his name, and promised multiple gigs as soon as he grew
his hair back. Yet even when reborn as Steve Adams, who slathered
mud treatments on his head twice a week, he got no roles.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he decided to capitalize on what were seen as his
deficiencies. When he tried to seduce Bridget Fonda in ``Single
White Female,'' his too-lanky arms seemed to elongate repulsively,
like some poisonous spider's. The eyes that, by celebrity
standards, are just a little too prominent, hid all kinds of
secrets when he played a dissembling executive in ``The Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   And in his best-known performance, as the ultra-annoying
insurance salesman in ``Groundhog Day,'' he put it all together in
a perfect ode to the perennial bumbler. Tobolowsky embraces the
term ``character actor'' and its inherent gifts, which allow him to
pop up repeatedly, like the prize in a box of Cracker Jack. It's
enough for him that people he encounters often think he's
(italics)Their(end italics) insurance agent or, as in a recent
instance, their supermarket bag boy.
</P>
<P>
   If he has a complaint, it's about Hollywood's persistent lack of
imagination. The industry's reward for his memorable turn in
``Groundhog Day'' is to make (italics)him(end italics) relive the
same experience over and over: ``After that, people said, `Oh, this
guy does wacky comedy!' Now they alwayswant to make me a
goofball.'' When the studios do offer up some variety, it's usually
a request for ``the tough cop, the suspicious official or
somebody's dad or principal.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobolowsky does his best to find quirkier parts in independent
films. He'll play a sleazy telemarketer in ``Prime Gig,'' an
Orthodox Jew in ``Stanley's Gig'' _ ``I've done so many movies, the
names start to repeat themselves,'' he says _ and a bookie in ``The
Operator.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he notes that actors like Jim Carrey can't experiment as
freely with different genres, and that he would hate to have to
duck out back doors like Al Pacino, he prefers not to measure
himself against higher-profile colleagues. Instead, he draws a
parallel to the former Boston Celtics player John Havlicek: ``He
always started the game on the bench. If they wanted him to take a
few shots, he would. If they wanted him to play most of the game,
he could. Well, if they need someone who can pass the ball off or
rebound, I'm happy to do it. And if they need someone to score
points, I can do that, too.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAURY CHAYKIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With undisguised delight, Maury Chaykin says, ``There's an
extraordinary billboard up on Sunset Boulevard right now, with a
humongous photograph of my face.'' The ad is for ``The Golden
Spiders,'' the cable movie in which Chaykin plays the detective
Nero Wolfe, and it has given the actor a new pastime. ``I drive by
it constantly, back and forth, back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare show of vanity for an actor who specializes in
particularly unsavory characters.
</P>
<P>
   American audiences know Chaykin best for his startling cameos,
small but potent appearances in films generally populated by
extremely well-groomed stars. His breakout role was in ``Dances
With Wolves'': while Kevin Costner rode the prairies with head held
high, Chaykin melted in his own sweat as a jittery, suicidal
cavalry major. More recently, he clouded the high gloss of
``Entrapment'' with his performance as a dissipated underworld
figure with a comically monstrous pot belly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But if you really want to see what Chaykin, 50, can do, you had
best look north. After failing to find paying work in his native
New York, despite ``30 or 40 Off Off Broadway plays,'' he was
offered a job at an underground theater in Toronto. That was in the
mid-'70s, and he has lived there on and off ever since. In Canada,
Chaykin found audiences and directors _ including Atom Egoyan _ who
were willing to celebrate his lack of physical perfection, or
better still, ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   He received critical acclaim for a 1985 movie called ``Canada's
Sweetheart: The Saga of Hal C. Banks,'' and built a popular
following in projects like ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' in which he
gave an unexpectedly disturbing performance as a choleric,
cuckolded husband. The ultimate proof that Canadians now consider
Chaykin one of their own may be the Genie award _ Canada's
equivalent of the Oscar _ he captured in 1994 for his portrayal of
a deeply troubled Brian Wilson-like musician in the film ``Whale
Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaykin isn't shy about reproaching Hollywood for its insistence
on eye appeal: ``It's just brutal. You (italics)have(end italics)
to look great. It has nothing to do with the way most people are,
the way most people are built. It's sick.'' The actor certainly
doesn't shun American film, and the truth is that American film
doesn't shun him, either. His projects include a Wesley Snipes
action picture, ``The Art of War,'' and a recent Sundance entry,
``What's Cooking?,'' in which he plays Kyra Sedgwick's aging
father. But he harbors no illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't expect people to say, `Let's star Maury Chaykin in,
you know, the next Disney movie.' It's easier for me to make that
happen in Canada. I've played so many leading roles there. They
were not huge, box office-commercial films. But they were lovely,
beautiful films.'' And if those chances were ever to come his way
as often in the United States, Chaykin says, it would ``just be
gravy.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTOPHER McDONALD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do you do when you're one of the innumerable handsome men
in Hollywood, and you can't get anyone to notice you? You probably
start off in forgettable films like ``Grease 2'' or ``Where the
Boys Are '84.'' And if you're in the majority, you quickly fade
from view, as the next batch of comely hopefuls takes your place.
But Christopher McDonald, 44, found a different route.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a certain good look, they really can't use you
unless you're the lead guy, because you're almost like
competition,'' he observes. So McDonald has subtly subverted his
features, turning, for example, a naturally genial smile into an
ominous smirk. In fact, most of his characters seem resentful of
their good looks, as though they had been given a promise never
fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   As Darryl, Geena Davis's patronizing husband in ``Thelma and
Louise,'' McDonald captured a bent male ego desperately struggling
for control, playing him as a star quarterback long gone to seed.
And for ``Quiz Show,'' he examined the flip side of fragile
masculinity, as an ultra-smooth talk show host carefully masking
any emotion for fear of cracking the facade.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he will take on the bad-guy mantle again, as an evil
university provost in ``The Skulls''; later this year, in ``Requiem
for a Dream,'' he will portray a self-help guru partially based on
the undeniably slick Tony Robbins. ``My most memorable parts have
been when I wasn't afraid to say yes to playing the fall guy, the
cad, the alpha-villain,'' McDonald says, while admitting to some
frustration over typecasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Thelma and Louise,' I got offered every
hayseed-chewing, pickup-driving, wife-beating rat out there. Until
I had to say, `Are they serious?' I (italics)can(end italics) do
other things.'' But he adds: ``You'd rather take those parts than
not work. Being anonymous in this business is probably the worst
thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald is hoping that the typecasting is over now that he's a
regular on the new CBS drama ``Family Law.'' He plays a roguish
lawyer, and he has already begun to expand the part considerably.
Consequently, he is starting to see a difference in the way he is
viewed by audiences. ``It used to be: `Oh, man, you're that guy! In
that movie!' But now they say, `Hey, Christopher McDonald, my mom
loves your show!'''
</P>
<P>
   The next step, he hopes, will be a change in the industry's
opinion. He notes that one of the reasons he took the job was its
``potential to push me into leading man material.'' Imagining the
possibilities, he says, ``I've been one away from something huge
for the longest time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
