s e BC-EDWARD-ZWICK-AWARDS-A     03-08 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARD-ZWICK-AWARDS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOMINEE'S STORY: CHAMPAGNE AND SHEER TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)  
 (af)  
 By EDWARD ZWICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ You direct a movie. Or produce one. It's
taken you two to three years _ maybe even six or seven _ to get it
made. If it does well, you're thrilled. If the critics like it,
you're delighted. If both happen, you're terrified.
</P>
<P>
   Because now you start thinking about awards.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after Halloween, stories speculating on the contenders
begin to run nationally in what has become an endless stream of
entertainment news. In Variety and The Hollywood Reporter, the
daily trade papers that everyone claims not to read but that
everyone subscribes to, ``For Your Consideration'' ads appear.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them feature your picture. For a producer, writer or
director, this is secretly quite appealing. Suddenly you, not
Harrison Ford, are the star of your movie. Your sister from Chicago
calls, asking if she can meet Matt Damon at the after-parties. You
tell her to dream on. Someone in line at the supermarket tells you
your chances are pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Then your wife announces that awards are meaningless, that it is
all about the work, that the honor is in the doing ... and that she
has nothing to wear. Despite your every attempt to remain both
modest and unjinxed, you can't help but begin to speculate on the
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, your movie has been finished for months and you've
got time on your hands. If you're lucky, you've begun work on your
next. But more likely you are floundering in the nether world of
development, meeting with studios or actors, reading bad scripts or
writing worse ones. It's been a while since anyone has told you how
much they loved your movie. And so when the studio vice president
calls to say that the Golden Globe nominations are to be announced
the next day at dawn and do you want to be called at home, you say,
``I'll probably be up anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   And you are. It's 5:30 and you've been awake since 4. You listen
to the other categories without paying much attention. When at last
you hear your name, it goes by so fast you question whether it
happened at all. You go online and read the list again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   Now what? It's 6 in the morning and there's no one to call. You
hug your dog. You pace a bit. You wake your wife. You wake your
kids. Finally, you can't wait any longer and you call your parents,
who inevitably ask, ``What, exactly, are the Golden Globes?''
</P>
<P>
   In the office the phone is ringing. It's your agent. He always
knew you had it in you. Your lawyer is holding on another line.
Then your accountant checks in. And then pretty much everyone you
have ever met, including someone from summer camp in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of champagne arrives, from a producer who never returns
your calls. Baskets of muffins, flowers and fruit soon follow. By
the time the fifth basket is delivered, you are too busy reading
about yourself in The New York Times to pay much attention. You
say, ``Just put it on the desk,'' as you read your name again.
</P>
<P>
   The phone keeps ringing. Fancy people invite you to dinner
parties. There's even an offer or two. It's all come true, the
fulfillment of childhood evenings long ago _ you and your sisters
all in pajamas, eating popcorn and watching awards shows on
television. Already you can hear the words, ``And the nominees
are...'' It's a thrill that lasts at least as long as it takes for
the next thought to form in your head:
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Your stomach drops. You thought you were past the fear and
self-doubt. Instead, you find yourself facing the funhouse mirror
in which Hollywood conspires to make everyone, particularly those
who work in it, feel less than they are _ less beautiful, less
successful and less talented. Because the moment the envelope is
opened, you will cease being a nominee. And the chances are four in
five you will become a loser.
</P>
<P>
   So the weeks that follow, which should be the most fun of your
life, also become something of a nightmare. By New Year's Day,
every magazine, radio and television critic comes out with a Top 10
list, as does the National Board of Review (a venerable
organization that everyone has heard of, though no one knows why).
You are included on several. You are left off others.
</P>
<P>
   Your high school drama teacher calls with his analysis. So does
your cousin in Seattle who's ``in the business'' by virtue of
running a video store. You turn on CNN to check out the situation
in Chechnya and discover, instead, a half-hour special devoted to
handicapping the awards.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine editors, talk-show hosts, television critics,
everybody's an expert. Film by film, they deconstruct the
competition. Two of the films are comedies and comedies never win.
One of the films is too radical for the more traditional tastes of
the voters. Or too sexual. Or too violent. Against your will you
find yourself sussing out the competition. This guy will win
because he's old and almost dead and has never won before.
</P>
<P>
   No. It'll be the woman because women never win in this category
_ even though this particular woman has no particular talent. No.
That young first-time director will win because he's hip and cute _
as you used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of wooing voters, the studio employs an ``awards
consultant.'' It all boils down to how much to spend on the
campaign. In last year's race between ``Saving Private Ryan'' and
``Shakespeare in Love,'' Dreamworks and Miramax are said to have
spent more than $10 million, which is outrageous and indecent,
except when it's your movie.
</P>
<P>
   You win a Golden Globe: more phone calls, more champagne, more
muffins. But rather than congratulating you, people seem mainly
interested in your chances for an Oscar nomination. You attend one
of those fancy dinner parties, where you are seated next to Sidney
Poitier. He treats you like an old friend. Midway through dinner he
announces that yours is the best movie of the year. You've gone
from Golden Globe nominee to Oscar front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oscars are still a long way off and the orgy of
self-congratulation is just beginning. You dust off the script
you've been writing and try to get back to work, but your mind
drifts and you begin counting just how many academy members you
know personally. Pretty soon you just have to admit you've bought
in. You're on the awards spike. And the better the high, the worse
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The more excited you allow yourself to be about the possibility
of winning, the tougher it will be when they call someone else's
name. You realize your kids are beginning to hide the arts section
of the paper in the morning. For years you've marveled at Woody
Allen's refusal to participate in the awards ritual. Only now it
begins to dawn on you that it may not be moral courage or Olympian
disdain that keeps him away: he's probably too anxious.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And then you are nominated for an Oscar. Champagne, muffins,
etc. The accepted wisdom is that it's a privilege just to be
nominated. Indeed, you can't believe your name could ever be
mentioned in the same breath as the other nominees in your
category. But anyone who says it's a privilege to have your work
placed in a competition with an 80 percent chance of losing has
never lost anything. Not a spelling bee. Or a high school playoff
game. Or a girlfriend. You remember your baseball coach's words,
``Show me a good loser and I'll show you a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   In some essential way, we are all losers in Hollywood. It's hard
to think of any other bond that distinguishes us as a community. In
each of us there is something unfulfilled, some ache or deficiency
of character that leads us to fill a hole in the heart with the
love of strangers. Like the Scarecrow in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' we
imagine that what is broken in us can somehow be fixed by a ... by
a ... by a ... by an award.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony nears. Should you write a speech? Should you buy a
tuxedo? You decide to buy the tuxedo first and write the speech
later. You spend hours trying on tuxes and each one makes you look
like the headwaiter in a '30s movie. By the fifth tux it occurs to
you that you have done absolutely no work in the past week. And
when, on the day of the awards, you finally put on the cuff links
and the cummerbund and the bow tie, you find you look exactly like
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, you decide to write a speech. You realize
this may be bad luck. On the other hand you remember just how many
good films have been done in by appalling speeches. And so you get
to work. Your speech must be gracious, generous, humble, funny,
insightful, emotional and brief. You decide to put off writing a
speech.
</P>
<P>
   A white limo arrives outside your house at 3:30 in the afternoon
on the day of the awards. Neighbors peer out their windows as you
emerge, tuxedoed and blinking in the glare. Your son insists on
taking your picture and you are reminded of prom night. In the limo
are jars of jelly beans, which you begin eating by the handful.
</P>
<P>
   As you try to work on the speech you have put off writing, you
remember that, once upon a time, you were contemptuous of awards.
You've always believed that institutions have never been reliable
judges of art. In college you learned about the Salon des Refuses,
in which Impressionists like Manet and Pissarro were forced to show
their work independently after having been turned down by the
official exposition of the French Academy.
</P>
<P>
   As you take your seat in the auditorium, your wife takes your
hand. It is cold and clammy. She says something nice and calming.
But her tone reminds you of how you felt, one afternoon, while
awaiting the results of a CAT scan (``... the envelope please'').
You check the program to see how many awards precede yours: it's
hours away and except for the jelly beans, you've had nothing to
eat all day to compete with the two glasses of champagne now
roiling inside.
</P>
<P>
   As Billy Crystal tells a joke, your mind wanders. You ask
yourself why we, as a culture, have become so fixated on awards. Is
it America's insatiable fascination with winning? Is it just cheap
programming? Is it the sophisticated publicity machinery of a
multi-billion-dollar industry? Or is it a shrewd attempt to confer
upon the movies a legitimacy that may not be warranted by their
artistic ambitions? Have we, as a culture, become so accustomed to
being sold at, that we need this kind of public apotheosis to
determine a work's merit?
</P>
<P>
   What is ``Oscar-worthy,'' after all, but a sophisticated
marketing tool? Recently, you've begun to notice how, every time
the word ``Oscar'' is used in print, it must be followed by the
symbol signifying its trademark. What, exactly, are we all selling
here tonight?
</P>
<P>
   You realize that for the last two minutes you have forgotten to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Hours (and several trips to the bathroom) later, your category
is announced. The celebrity presenter says a few words about what
this award means, but you have stopped listening. You close your
eyes, trying to remember the joy you felt in first imagining the
film you would make, the exaltation and the compromise in the
process of making it, and the giddiness when the audience
responded.
</P>
<P>
   What you're most afraid of, you suddenly realize, is that this
might be the best work you will ever do and that you may never be
here again. As the list of nominees is read, a cameraman kneels in
the aisle and zooms in on your face. You imagine the close-up seen
by a billion people _ the rictus of a ridiculous and foreign smile
that has somehow immobilized your face.
</P>
<P>
   As the envelope is opened, the faces of your children suddenly
swim into your thoughts, all shiny and bright. You realize that
they are staying up very late to watch and that it is a school
night. Tomorrow, in fact, is your day to drive car pool.
</P>
<P>
   You hope it won't be a long night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
