<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-HOUSTON-MARQUETTE     03-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-MARQUETTE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ After so many games that went wrong, the Houston
Cougars finally got it right.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running their offense at the end with the patience missing so
often in an 11-game losing streak, the 12th-seeded Cougars upset
No. 5 seed Marquette 77-75 at the Pyramid on Wednesday in the first
round of the Conference USA basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the first time since the 1995 Southwest Conference
event, the Cougars get to stick around past the opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd suffered so much (in the losing streak) because we didn't
score enough in the last three minutes of games and didn't keep our
patience,'' coach Clyde Drexler said. ``This one was a long time
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   UH's most recent victory had been at the Pyramid, where UH
defeated Memphis 98-89 on Jan. 22. The Cougars could be excused if
they felt they had been waiting since the Ice Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't felt this good in a long time,'' said junior Chad
Hendrick (17 points, 7-of-12 shooting), who with seniors Kenny
Younger and Gee Gervin accounted for 52 of the Cougars' 77 points.
``We've been so battle-tested, we weren't going to let this one
slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger (21 points, 7-for-10 shooting, eight rebounds, two
blocked shots) staged one of his better performances after a
late-season slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to go home. We wanted to keep playing,''
Younger said. ``Finally, we got over the hump and put it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In becoming the first 12th seed to win a C-USA tournament game,
the Cougars (9-21) also took some of the sting out of being the
losingest team in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to play another game; that's the biggest thing,''
Younger said of today's quarterfinal meeting with Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've split with them the last two years,'' Gervin said.
``This game (with Marquette) has to give us a big confidence
boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin (14 points, five rebounds, three vital assists down the
stretch), like the other Cougars, felt it was the ability to stay
within the offense that enabled them to hold off the Golden Eagles
(15-13), who were within a point nine times.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the timeouts late in the game, we said, `Don't look at the
clock; just keep playing,' and that's how it happened,'' said
Bernard Smith. Smith played most of the game at point guard so that
Gervin could play off the ball; Smith also spent most of his 34
minutes defending Marquette's Brian Wardle.
</P>
<P>
   John Cliff (22 points), Wardle (20) and Cordell Henry (16)
scored all but 17 of Marquette's points from the perimeter, with
Cliff and Henry a combined 8-of-13 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Said Smith, ``I'd bet that's 20 of the toughest points Wardle
has scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Drexler, ``Whenever we thought we had a comfortable lead,
they hit some incredible shots. We didn't give anything to them.''
</P>
<P>
   UH shot 57 percent in the second half after a 43-percent first
half and needed every bit, since Marquette hit 54 percent in each
half. Younger and freshman George Williams accounted for five
baskets after offensive rebounds, another crucial factor.
</P>
<P>
   Marquette coach Tom Crean said, ``Our post defense was not our
best effort. They made us pay when we did not get back. Younger and
Williams are two future pros, and you have to pay attention to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Late three-point plays by Gervin and Younger (on Gervin's
assist) gave UH a 66-59 lead with 3:38 to go. Cliff scored from out
front, then hit a trey, and the Golden Eagles were within 68-64
with 2:56 remaining _ and the Cougars seemed poised on their
familiar high wire.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gervin, with the shot clock showing three seconds, found
Hendrick in the right corner for Hendrick's third 3-pointer. After
a Wardle basket made it 71-66,
</P>
<P>
   ``I reacted to the defense, and when they collapsed on me, I got
it to Chad when he was wide-open,'' Gervin said of the late-game
patience that had been missing.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
