<HEADER>
A1196 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-BELFOUR-TE     03-08 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDDIE `THE EAGLE' RUFFLES SOME FEATHERS WITH JAIL VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could have knocked the Stars over with a feather _ an
Eagle's feather.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's not as if they didn't know that Eddie ``The Eagle''
Belfour was a charter member of the cuckoo's nest, but still,
you're never quite ready for that 5 a.m. wakeup call from the Lew
Sterrett Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Domino's was closed.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a very mortified Eddie on the phone, trying to
explain to Ken Hitchcock, or Bob Gainey, or whoever he finally
reached, about his big night at, of all places, The Mansion, the
upscale Dallas hotel on Turtle Creek.
</P>
<P>
   He had to tell them that ``Eddie the Eagle'' had just become
``Eddie the Jailbird.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a nasty feeling that that's when the feathers really
flew.
</P>
<P>
   You know most of the gritty details by now, how Belfour, having
probably the best season of his career, went to The Mansion for
dinner. At some point female companionship was involved. A room was
taken. Too many drinks were imbibed. Not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Things went downhill from there. The unidentified woman told
hotel security that Belfour was scaring her and that she wanted to
leave. Those of us who have stared into those pale blue eyes during
locker room interviews can relate.
</P>
<P>
   She was escorted from the hotel, which apparently disappointed
Belfour greatly. Now who would share those tasty pillow mints with
him? He, too, decided to make his exit.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel personnel, already having called the local constabulary _
the cops _ attempted to detain Belfour, who reacted as if he'd
discovered a Holiday Inn Express towel in the bathroom. Police
arrived to find Eddie doing his Hulk Hogan impression on the
bellman. When they politely asked him to cease and desist, Belfour
threw a kick in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy dose of Mace, however, quickly convinced Eddie that
the evening had reached its zenith. Outfitted in a sparkling new
set of stainless steel bracelets, he was escorted to the
aforementioned Sterrett Center. Not exactly the accommodations, or
companions, Eddie had in mind when the evening began.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was charged with assault and resisting arrest. There was
an unconfirmed report that hotel officials have asked the police
not topursue the assault charge, a Class C misdemeanor. The
resisting arrest charge is a more serious Class A misdemeanor. The
Stars are taking the incident seriously, and they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation this serious and this dramatic, it's
dramatic for all the people involved, and while a lot of
responsibility will lie on Ed's shoulders, right now, all our
concerns are for everybody, '' coach Ken Hitchcock said at
yesterday's skate at the Dr Pepper StarsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Because the incident involved alcohol, the NHL's substance-abuse
team and Players Association are now in the picture. They will
investigate and react accordingly. From a hockey standpoint,
Belfour could face a suspension, a fine or a slap on the wrist. The
legal aspects are a bit more sobering. He could get a year in jail,
a $4,000 fine or both if found guilty on the resisting-arrest
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this was the first time the Stars have had trouble with
Belfour, Gainey answered cryptically, ``This is the problem that is
here today, so this is the one we are working on.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone had whispered a week ago that one of the Stars'
players was going to be involved in this type of incident, chances
are even the most casual fans would have fingered Belfour as one of
the top three suspects. After all, Craig Ludwig has retired.
Everybody knows that Eddie is the Stars' resident wild child. It's
the nature of the game and position that he plays.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when the Stars decided to give Eddie a few days off
this week _ rookie Manny Fernandez was already ticketed to start
last night's game _ they still tried to keep his structure in
place. Belfour is a man who needs structure. He needs to know where
he has to be and when he has to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a plan in place, a three- or four-day plan, that was
being administered, and Eddie was cooperating on it,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We knew exactly where we were going and the timetable that
was going to take place. Eddie would have been back in here Friday,
getting prepared to play. Unfortunately the timetable changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It changed when Belfour mixed a change in focus from on-ice to
off-ice with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Belfour is unaware of the inherent dangers
therein. Last year, Belfour swore off drinking during a three-month
drive to help the Stars win the Stanley Cup. His dedication paid
off handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who predicted that Belfour would not be able to
sustain that high level of play this season, that having finally
won his Cup, he would fall victim to complacency and contentment.
They couldn't have been further off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played three years here with us and he's never been
better, never had a better year, never been more consistent,''
Hitchcock said. ``You ask your goaltender to be competitive every
night, but he's gone beyond that in that he's won us hockey games.
He's gotten us points when maybe we should not have gotten
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has been brilliant, without question, the Stars' MVP
this season. But now he threatens to become a major distraction
just as the Stars are trying to focus on getting players healthy
for another run at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that our players view as another piece of
adversity that we have to overcome,'' Hitchcock said. ``This goes
above and beyond the game of hockey. It has to be addressed
properly and dramatically. This is serious life stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   When the phone rings at 5 a.m. and ``caller ID'' indicates that
somebody named Lew Sterrett is calling, it usually is. {Jim Reeves
is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.} nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
