<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLEGE-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES MORE COLLEGE ASSISTANCE FOR POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state should sharply expand its financial aid to
college students and continue to concentrate on low-income families
rather than the middle class, a panel of prominent educators and
former government officials appointed by the state Senate to study
financial aid said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, headed by Paul A. Volcker, former chairman of
the Federal Reserve Board, and Clifton R. Wharton Jr., former
chancellor of the State University of New York, said the state
should pay 100 percent of the tuition for the neediest students at
its two public universities _ SUNY and the City University _ rather
than the 90 percent it now pays.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding private colleges, the panel called on the state to
raise the maximum annual grant in its primary financial aid program
_ the Tuition Assistance Program, or TAP _ by more than 20 percent,
to $5,000 from $4,125 for undergraduates and to $1,500 from $550
for graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   In many of its recommendations, the panel seemed to be flouting
the wishes of the state senators who had commissioned them. Last
month, Sen. Kenneth LaValle, chairman of the higher education
committee, and the Senate majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, called
for more help for the middle class _ including making college
tuition tax deductible and allowing families earning up to $80,000
to qualify for TAP grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by the unanimity of the commission that the TAP
program was worth keeping and strengthening and that the emphasis
really ought to be on the underprivileged,'' Volcker said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel leaders expressed hope that their report might have
impact because it came as both the Senate and the Assembly were
discussing ways to expand financial aid to college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they've come up with their own initiatives, I have
more hope that they are going to take some action,'' Volcker said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Wharton met with LaValle, the primary architect behind
the commission, and other senators on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the panel's recommendations, Senate leaders
emphasized the overlap with their own proposals. Both the panel's
recommendations and those of the senators call for raising the
maximum grant for students at private colleges to $5,000 and
creating an agency to set higher education policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we want to make college more
affordable for more families,'' said John McArdle, a spokesman for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-member panel, known as the Commission on New York State
Student Financial Aid, also said state cutbacks in higher education
and TAP grants ``threaten New York state's ability to provide
sufficient and outstanding higher education opportunities to its
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel said that New York's ``economy and society have
benefited hugely'' from TAP. A study for the panel found that more
than 78 percent of TAP recipients in 1989 were still living in New
York seven years later, investing whatever talents they had in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said that while New York spent $700 million _
more than any other state _ on scholarships, the grants had not
kept pace with inflation. Students from families with taxable
income of $50,000 or less are eligible for TAP.
</P>
<P>
   Among its other recommendations, the commission called for the
state to eliminate the policy that reduces TAP awards to students
in their last two years of college and to raise support to private
colleges to at least $75 million, an increase of $27 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
