<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PHILA-FLOWER-SHOW-ART     03-08 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILA-FLOWER-SHOW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER NATURE WOULD BE AGOG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Just before the Philadelphia Flower Show opened
on Sunday under the banner ``Gardens for the New Millennium,''
Edward L. Lindemann, its director, felt like a chef who had planned
an impossibly ambitious menu and was suddenly hearing the guests at
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm thinking, `Why did I do it?''' said Lindemann, slumped
on a sofa in his second floor office at the Pennsylvania Convention
Center. ``It'' was taking the flower show, so to speak, 100 years
into the future, imagining what Philadelphia would be like if all
the people who fled to the suburbs returned to live and work in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Would windmills and solar panels provide clean energy? Would
people grow vegetables on roofs and collect rain for water? Would
music be more dissonant? Would art have a harder edge?
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a big order. No wonder this man looked tired. But
somehow it all came together by Sunday, when 50,000 spring-starved
garden lovers moved through more than 100 full-scale exhibits and
2,500 amateur entries like a sea of honeybees drunk on pollen.
Maybe it was a pine tree with gold needles that grabbed them, or
the charred rain forest, or the chartreuse viburnum blossoms and
impossibly curved tulips looking positively imprisoned in metal.
</P>
<P>
   Lindemann, who nudged his exhibitors to mix more theater into
their horticulture for this year's show, which runs through Sunday,
walked me though an exhibit by the American Institute of Floral
Designers that features 19 arrangements of plants and metal and
silvery paint that neither God nor evolution could have wrought in
a million years.
</P>
<P>
   He spread his hands before an altarlike structure dripping with
orchids and succulents. A gazing ball gleamed inside a box with a
round hole. A few pussy willows poked out, and there was a
scepterlike object covered with green leaves. ``I think that's
equisetum molded onto a ball,'' Lindemann said. ``I think this is
the perfect marriage of architecture and nature.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't quite see it, but we wandered on, along an undulating
path of plastic beads. A light show pulsed like a heartbeat, and
trumpets and timpani played an upbeat processional. Ginger blossoms
and balls of crumpled aluminum appeared to be sliding down a
waterfall of narrow refrigerator shelves. Acacia pods dangled from
a metal tower. Yellow orchids as delicate as butterflies hung from
a steel ball that looked a bit like Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to head for the woodland gardens full of redbuds and
dogwoods that are thankfully still at the show _ the nurseries and
horticultural schools apparently think the millennium won't look
all that different _ but Lindemann was moving toward the central
exhibit, ``An Urban Garden Neighborhood,'' by Philadelphia Green,
the Philadelphia Horticultural Society's urban greening program,
which started helping neighborhoods turn rubble-strewn lots into
gardens about 25 years ago. Philadelphia Green works with more than
800 community groups on projects that include planting street trees
and designing pocket parks. Proceeds from the show _ about $1
million last year _ help that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could do that much in 25 years, what could we do in 100
years?'' Lindemann asked. That question led to this year's theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem is vacant land,'' he said, referring to
the city's 30,000 empty lots and the flight of the middle class.
``So this is our vision of all those problems being corrected.
People come back to live in the city. They come for housing and
work and entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the designers also had concerns about a computerized world
in danger of becoming sterile, where even more people compete for
fewer resources. Thus ``every plant will become precious,''
Lindemann said. He strolled by a backyard with rows of
hydroponically grown coffee plants, and another where a city farmer
has planted every space with greens, apple trees and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of a green city infuses almost every exhibit. A video
shows how the area surrounding the Philadelphia City Hall looks now
_ treeless and made for cars _ and then transforms the same streets
to a world without traffic: a sea of flowers, shrubs and trees. A
piano solo by Keith Jarrett accompanies the transformation. (``It
came to me when I was driving home late one night,'' Lindemann
said.)
</P>
<P>
   Even Waldor Orchids caught the environmental fever this year.
This company can be counted on every year for a grand display of
perfect orchids, but this year it produced a tropical forest with
two diametrically opposed futures. One side blooms with thousands
of healthy plants; the other is a charred ruin of blackened trees
and dead orchids with a bulldozer parked in its midst. ``Extinction
is forever,'' one sign reads; another sums up the dead end of
``slash and burn'' agriculture, in which trees are cut down and
burned to make room for cattle and cropland.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry. Just around the corner are plenty of lush
plantings, waterfalls and fountains. J. Franklin Styer Nurseries
has an enormous clock rising over a landscape of trees made of
hummingbird feeders and blown-glass vases, and fountains that arch
like surgical tubes over a perfectly round pond.
</P>
<P>
   Stoney Bank Nurseries has some show-stopper plants, from a
camperdown elm to a winged euonymous with the most delicate of
green buds just beginning to flower. The art of forcing plants is
at its best here. And don't miss the graceful gate made of bamboo,
designed by Greg and Camille Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   After all the time travel into the future, I was glad to restore
myself in the bog gardens designed by the regional office of the
federal Environmental Protection Agency and a children's garden
full of fat tomatoes and pink and blue sweet peas set up by the
department of ornamental horticulture and environmental design at
Delaware Valley College in Doylestown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The usual magic is everywhere you look, from 5-foot zinnias to a
15-foot topiary giraffe. Samuel M.V. Hamilton's Clivia miniata,
which is the size of a Volkswagen bug, won a red ribbon this year.
And the North American Rock Garden Society did a bang-up job with
its tiny gardens in stone troughs. Clifton West and John Ray won a
blue ribbon for a little world of azure gentians, miniature
rhododendrons, saxifrage and primula.
</P>
<P>
   I used to grumble about flower shows. ``So fake! So silly!''
Then I realized that was the whole point and started to enjoy
myself. The lava lamps were fab. I wonder if I should enter that
cactus that looks like a brain next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Flower Show runs through Sunday at the
Pennsylvania Convention Center, 12th and Arch Streets. Hours and
information: (215) 988-8899 or www.philaflowershow.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
