<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SHARPTON-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON IS SENTENCED TO 10 DAYS FOR PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton was sentenced Wednesday to 10 days in jail
for blocking traffic on the Atlantic City Expressway last summer
during a protest against racial profiling by the New Jersey State
Police.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors dropped charges against 73 other protesters who were
among about 200 people who closed down the expressway on July 3, to
condemn state troopers for a pattern of stopping minority drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was prompted by an incident in April 1998 when two
state troopers stopped a van of black and Hispanic men and opened
fire when the van began to roll backward on the shoulder of the
highway. The troopers were indicted on charges of attempted murder
and assault after details of widespread racial profiling emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also helped bring about a federal investigation
into racial profiling nationwide, and led Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman to acknowledge that the practice was common among New
Jersey troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton seemed to welcome the sentence as a way to publicize
his cause. ``I think it's a small price to pay,'' he said, ``to
bring national attention to racial profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said that he would announce on Saturday whether his
lawyer would appeal. Otherwise, he must surrender within 20 days
and pay $310 in court costs. He would then spend 10 days in an
Atlantic City jail.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before Judge Bruce Weekes of municipal county court
Wednesday, Sharpton's lawyer, Michael Hardy, depicted his client as
a martyr and said Atlantic City would join the ranks of celebrated
cities of protest like Selma and Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant municipal prosecutor, Michael Mosca, argued that
Sharpton had to be punished and that the sit-in could have caused
delays for emergency medical vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In sentencing Sharpton, Weekes said: ``No matter how noble the
cause, you cannot commit an independently illegal act. There are
too many other ways'' to protest.
</P>
<P>
   Already scripting his days in jail, Sharpton said that he would
invite other civil rights activists to visit him there, including
the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Kweisi Mfume, the president of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
