<HEADER>
A1301 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-RODMAN-T     03-08 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-RODMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN'S LAST TIRADE MAY HAVE LONG-TERM BENEFITS FOR MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be a first for anyone to ever applaud Worm Rodman for
making sense, but ...
</P>
<P>
   On Mark Cuban, there was this latest observation from His
Wormness:
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't need to be hanging around the players like he's a
coach or something. That's like Jerry Jones, and it's dumb. That's
why the Cowboys went down. He needs to be the owner, step back and
put people in who can get this team in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. It's a direct hit for Worm, although Rodman turning his
studded tongue on his one local benefactor was yet another example
of the loose cannon Cuban hauled on board.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, the Mavericks' deck was de-Wormed yesterday.
No more Dennis. No more loose cannon. Rodman was released. Just
like that.
</P>
<P>
   For those attempting to connect the dots between the Worm's
sniping at Cuban and his quick exit, spare me the details.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban gets enough credit from here for not being that
thin-skinned. ``If I was worried about personal criticism, I
wouldn't have signed Dennis to start with,'' Cuban said last night.
</P>
<P>
   As he charts his Mavericks' ownership course, there is much to
like about Cuban, at least if you are grading on the curve. Instead
of doing a tip-toe into pro sports, Cuban has kicked down the door
and barged in with a rah-rah charm that prompts us in the media to
openly scoff. One problem, however, with us in the media _ we don't
buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   What Cuban has actually accomplished over the last three months
is amazing. He has personally connected with the rank-and-file
fandom, and in doing so, completely re-energized a franchise that
had been reduced to distant memory status by the paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Give Cuban some time to sort through ownership rights and
wrongs, while taking his bruises, and then judge him a year or two
down the road. At the moment, he's like a big goofy fan trying to
ace Ownership 101.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, Cuban claims to be following a ``basketball
first'' agenda. ``It made no sense to keep Dennis with us now being
out of the playoff picture,'' Cuban said. ``If we were three games
away from a playoff spot right now, Dennis would be here. But at
this point I'm not for Nellie \RDon Nelson\S keeping a kid on the
bench to play a 38-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's unsolicited ``advice'' for Cuban was an opinion-echo
from here that has been delivered more than once. Of course, Worm
is correct, but the additional impact was that Rodman bit the only
NBA hand that wanted to feed him.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis was in no-team land. His welcome is totally worn out in
this league. He was never going to work again until Cuban arrived
from Dot Com Geeksville to give Rodman one last stage to perform a
well-known act.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who eagerly informed Cuban of the mistake he
made in signing Rodman, the Worm's scolding of the owner in Seattle
was yet another example of evidence to the contrary. Rodman said
what needed to be said by someone other than the media.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Worm brought headlines to the Mavericks and put butts in
seats at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to timing, Rodman's release was perfect. Cuban
said from the start that when Dennis was no longer a basketball
fit, there would be no more Worm. And so he's gone. Here's why it
had to happen now:
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week or so, Rodman placed yellow police tape
around himself, establishing an off-limits boundary with the rest
of the team.
</P>
<P>
   During the latest string of losses for the Mavericks, Dennis
repeatedly retreated into a locker room mentality of ``it's their
fault, not mine.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own twisted logic, this was apparently Rodman's way of
showing leadership. Even in his best days, Dennis was a role player
on championship teams in Chicago. He is not a leader, and when he
attempted to be one in San Antonio, the results were not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Worm's strange finger-pointing had escalated over four
consecutive games, starting with the tough New Jersey loss
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Rodman arrived, the Mavericks had been surprisingly
successful, at least compared to normal standards, because of a
work ethic and because of a team concept. That last part would
surely have disappeared as Worm continually attempted to place
himself above a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Many voices will be saying, ``Told you so. Told you it would
never work with Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, however, it did work. Cuban plunged when he
insisted on signing Rodman, yet the initial splash was bigger than
originally thought. But Worm wore out his welcome by taking himself
far too seriously as a leader and player.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban listened to Rodman, so if he heard what Rodman said about
Cuban, then Dennis did the Mavericks a long-term favor.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it will be his last one. {Randy Galloway is a
columnist for the Fort Worth Star Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0480 </DOCNO>
