<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-COMPANY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER COMPANY PLANS THREE-UNIT CONVERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a decade of seeking to grow by merging with another
company, Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. is turning inward in a bid
to increase the company's value.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which until recently was attempting to merge with
Western Resources Inc., will now focus on remaking itself. KCP&AMP;L
executives hope the move will unleash more of the company's
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strategy makes sense; it isn't rocket science,'' said
Drue Jennings, chief executive officer of KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which must be approved by regulators, includes
converting KCP&AMP;L into a holding company with three units: power,
retail-distribution and deregulated businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The plan doesn't include finding a company to merge with _ a
cornerstone of the utility's strategy through the '90s _ although
KCP&AMP;L won't rule out a deal if approached.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially, the consequences are far-reaching.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L's power plant unit could find itself competing with other
utilities to supply electricity to the retail-distribution unit,
which would resell the electricity to the utility's customers. The
unit also could sell more power wholesale _ a market where price
isn't regulated _ and even consider building more plants to make
such extra power available.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution unit, by shopping around for power, could be in
a better position to woo customers to stay with KCP&AMP;L instead of
choosing another utility.
</P>
<P>
   The deregulated-businesses unit would mirror the utility's
current KLT Inc. subsidiary. The unit could raise public awareness
of KCP&AMP;L's other holdings, such as its 47 percent stake in a
fiberoptic company.
</P>
<P>
   At minimum, KCP&AMP;L executives think the reorganization will give
the company's valuation a boost by highlighting its various
businesses and giving them the flexibility to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sum of the parts is worth more than the whole,'' said
Bernie Beaudoin, KCP&AMP;L's president.
</P>
<P>
   For KCP&AMP;L employees, the proposed changes could affect how some
of them are paid, particularly in the power and deregulated
divisions. Some changes have already occurred in the deregulated
businesses, giving many employees ``pay for performance'' as part
of their compensation.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L's new strategy came about quickly after KCP&AMP;L in early
January ended its proposed merger with Western Resources. KCP&AMP;L had
expected the merged company to give it the size necessary to cope
with deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   But Jennings said doubts about the merger began to rise in the
second quarter of 1999 because of problems at Protection One Inc.,
the monitored-security firm that is 85 percent owned by Western.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing decline of Western's stock, which affected what
would be paid to KCP&AMP;L shareholders, sealed the deal's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too bad, but it had to be terminated,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all for naught. Some of the planning about how the
merged company would have been organized was salvaged and used in
KCP&AMP;L's current reorganizing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think the new structure could eventually attract
more suitors interested in one or more of the units. Others think
the utility _ after the Western merger failed _ was at risk of
being swallowed up by another company tempted by KCP&AMP;L's low stock
price, which at the close Wednesday was 23 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Ford, an analyst for ABN Amro, wrote after KCP&AMP;L parted
with Western that KCP&AMP;L's stock price didn't reflect the value of a
low-cost provider of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that value will be realized in the stock or another
suitor will emerge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ford, an example of increasing valuation is Digital
Teleport Inc., which is building a fiberoptic network. The company
is 47 percent owned by KCP&AMP;L but doesn't make much of a splash as
just part of KCP&AMP;L. But as a centerpiece of the
deregulated-businesses unit, Digital Teleport could draw more
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Though many details remain to be decided, the overall
reorganization will go forward, pending approval by Kansas,
Missouri and federal regulators. Those approvals could take up to
two years.
</P>
<P>
   No new state laws are required to form the holding company and
the three units, according to KCP&AMP;L. But future moves, especially
those that affect consumers whose service is regulated, could
require legislative action.
</P>
</TEXT>
