<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PONDER FUTURE WASHINGTON CONNECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The possibility of their former owner
becoming the next president intrigues the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a good thing,'' pitcher Darren Oliver said before
his workout yesterday morning. ``I might go into politics someday.
I could say, `Hey, I know the president.' It could only help, but
nobody would believe me anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who along with Rusty Rose headed the
ownership group that purchased the Rangers in April 1989, may have
secured his bid to become the Republican presidential nominee with
primary victories in California, New York, Ohio and four other
states on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explained manager Johnny Oates' smile yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man,'' Oates said. ``I think he's the right man
for the job. I take that back. I ``know'' he's the right man for
the job, and, yes, I feel very good today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's main challenger for the Republican nomination, Arizona
Sen. John McCain, is expected to pull out of the race soon. That
would leave Bush on track for a November clash with Vice President
Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, at least those who knew Bush when he was an owner,
like the idea of having someone associated with the team in the
White House, no matter his politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him,'' pitcher Kenny Rogers said of Bush. ``He was
always willing to do the things it took for us to be competitive,
but he never got in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Added left fielder Rusty Greer, ``I'd like to see him become our
next president, if for nothing else because I know him. He always
treated me well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush served as the Rangers' managing general partner before
being elected governor in November 1994. Bush then placed his
interest in the Rangers in a blind trust until Tom Hicks purchased
the franchise in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he isn't just endorsing Bush because of his former
association with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to what he has to say,'' Rogers said of Bush's
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he has discussed philosophies and shared ideas during
brief talks with Bush at The Ballpark in Arlington. He isn't
expecting the chance to offer any advice on how to beat Gore,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've offered to do anything I can to help him,'' Oates said.
``Hopefully, it wouldn't hurt him, but he hasn't called yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also made this prediction: ``I'm sure he wouldn't cause
as many distractions as the guy in there now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
