<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JURIES-POLICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS' TRUST IN POLICE ERODES IN LIGHT OF DIALLO AND LOUIMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For prosecutors, the testimony of police officers is
often the bedrock of their efforts to win criminal indictments and
convictions. In many cases, the outcome hinges on whether jurors
believe the account of an officer, like an undercover narcotics
officer who buys drugs or a detective who extracts a confession.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, juries have tended to accept the officers'
accounts without question. But during the last year, prosecutors
say, they have seen a change: Grand jurors in Manhattan have been
more intensively scrutinizing the testimony of police officers and
other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend for jurors to be more inquisitive, more
skeptical, asking for more information about the circumstances of a
police stop,'' said James M. Kindler, chief assistant district
attorney in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And in Queens, juries are deadlocking in an increasing number of
cases, a sign, prosecutors fear, that jurors are questioning the
veracity of officers' testimony as cases like the police shooting
of Amadou Diallo and the torture of Abner Louima continue to
dominate headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt in my mind that when it is generally
believed that cops are corrupt and engaged in brutality, that
perception will find its way into the jury room,'' said the Queens
district attorney, Richard A. Brown. ``I fear that that,
regrettably, may be occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   Because jury deliberations, particularly grand jury proceedings,
are secret, it is difficult to gauge the shift in jurors' attitudes
toward police testimony. So far, prosecutors say, the increased
skepticism has had little concrete impact. Grand juries in
Manhattan are indicting criminal suspects at the same rate as they
have in the past, and the number of hung juries in Queens remains
relatively small compared with the vast number of criminal cases
each year in the city.
</P>
<P>
   But several prosecutors said that in some cases, grand juries
had stepped beyond their authority by raising issues that, by law,
only a judge can decide, like asking whether officers were
justified in stopping or arresting a suspect, or whether they
collected evidence properly. At other times, officers have been
called back to answer additional questions.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said that if a dubious view of the police was
growing among jurors, whether such a view was justified or not,
steps should be taken to address it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police testimony is at the very heart of the criminal justice
system,'' said Gerald Lynch, a professor at Columbia Law School.
``If the public does not have the confidence in the police, then
acquittals or hung juries will become increasingly routine.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in jurors' attitudes has been most surprising in
Manhattan and Queens, boroughs whose residents are thought to have
a more favorable opinion of the police than those of the Bronx or
Brooklyn. In those boroughs, prosecutors said they had seen no
significant change in the way jurors treat the police.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney, Robert
T. Johnson, said his office's conviction rate had dropped and the
grand jury dismissal rate risen in recent years, but he said he did
not know why. Charles J. Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney,
said his office had seen no increase in grand juror skepticism or
hung juries.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said the department welcomed
aggressive scrutiny by grand jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A thorough review by a grand jury is commendable,'' she said.
``The Police Department doesn't shy away from that. It's a good
thing when grand jurors take their responsibility seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan prosecutors would not discuss specific cases and said
that grand jurors were asking more questions of all witnesses, as
well as of police officers. More than half of the witnesses who
appear before grand juries are officers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Queens district attorney, said the number of hung
juries in routine trials in Queens had risen sharply, particularly
in the last five months. He said that 9.6 percent of trials in 1999
ended in hung juries, with the increase beginning in the final
three months of last year. In the first two months of this year, 10
trials, or 23.2 percent of the total, ended in hung juries, he
said, a rate not seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm troubled by the increase,'' Brown said. ``I think because
of the perception that's out there, you're finding that jurors
oftentimes are questioning the credibility of police testimony,
perhaps a lot more than they've been doing in the past.'' He called
for the department to continue efforts to diversify the force and
increase training as a way to restore public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that police scandals had affected
jurors' perceptions of the police. Walter Mack is a former head of
the Police Department's Internal Affairs Division who helped
investigate corruption in Harlem in the early 1990s. During that
scandal inquiry, it was found that some officers lied under oath so
frequently that they coined a term for it, ``testilying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a reaction when the police are being
criticized,'' Mack said. ``Grand jurors and petit jurors are going
to be reluctant to accept what the police have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Vitullo-Martin, a jury expert at the Vera Institute of
Justice in Manhattan, praised the assertiveness of grand juries,
which she said were created as a buffer to allow citizens, not
prosecutors, to decide whether someone should be charged with a
serious crime. Vitullo-Martin, whose car was recently stopped in a
check on seat belt use, called the officers involved in that sweep
``astonishingly arrogant.'' She said an increased distrust of the
police could be an unintended byproduct of the Giuliani
administration's aggressive police tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any encounter with the police in which the police are
exercising their authority is bound to have an effect on a juror,''
she said. ``This may be the natural outcome of too many encounters
with the police.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2320EST &QL; 
