<HEADLINE>
QWEST MERGER TALKS WITH DEUTSCHE TELEKOM MAY BE REVIVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After negotiations by Qwest Communications International for an
acquisition by Deutsche Telekom essentially collapsed on Tuesday,
Qwest's chairman, Joseph P. Nacchio, spent much of Wednesday
putting together a proposal meant to bring the German company back
to the bargaining table, executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Qwest, a fast-growing long-distance communications
company, agreed to acquire U S West Inc., one of the American
regional Bell companies. People close to Deutsche Telekom said that
on Tuesday, the company essentially shut down its negotiations to
acquire Qwest because of fears over how much it would have to pay
for U S West.
</P>
<P>
   But the people close to Deutsche Telekom said that Wednesday,
the big German phone company received word from Qwest trying to
reopen the discussions and that it indicated it was willing to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Qwest's closing share price Wednesday of $53.4375, U S
West would receive nearly $47 billion under its merger deal.
Deutsche Telekom appears reluctant to match Qwest's offer for U S
West. But U S West has little reason to accept a lesser deal from
the German company. Qwest's market value is around $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For at least a year, Deutsche Telekom has been seeking ways to
expand outside its home market. As the company's Global One joint
venture collapsed last year, Deutsche Telekom tried to acquire
Telecom Italia, but Olivetti wooed that company away from its
German suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Through Tuesday, U S West had not met face to face with Deutsche
Telekom, according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   If Qwest is to succeed in reigniting its discussions with
Deutsche Telekom, it may have to finally bring U S West into the
talks as a full partner.
</P>
<P>
   Offering to bring in U S West could potentially help Qwest's
cause with the German company because it would help allay Deutsche
Telekom's fear that U S West might sue for interference in its
pre-existing deal with Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   But bringing in U S West would not necessarily serve Qwest's
immediate interest.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to Deutsche Telekom, that company
wants to minimize its involvement in splitting any spoils between
Qwest and U S West. So its past proposals have been made in a fixed
amount, leaving Qwest and U S West to decide how to split it. The
exact size of Deutsche Telekom's previous proposals was unclear
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Qwest kept U S West out of touch with Deutsche
Telekom, Nacchio could hope to make a better deal for his
shareholders than for U S West's. Bringing U S West into direct
contact with Deutsche Telekom could strengthen U S West's hand with
the German company at the expense of Nacchio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
