<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANUCKS-MCSORLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
VANCOUVER CANUCKS OPPOSE McSORLEY CHARGES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Outraged when the incident first happened, the
Vancouver Canucks were quick to accept the NHL's swift and severe
punishment of Boston's Marty McSorley for hitting Vancouver's
Donald Brashear in the head with his stick Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Mark Messier emphasized that the sport needed to
move beyond the ugly attack. The red-hot Canucks were doing that.
But, after learning that the British Columbia criminal justice
branch has charged McSorley with assault with a weapon, the Canucks
found themselves a bit bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   Some Canucks expressed concern yesterday that having the law
cross the line into the sporting arena sets a potentially dangerous
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shocked,'' Canucks right winger Alexander
Mogilny said. ``I've been playing 11 years in the league, and I've
never seen anything happen like this. It's hockey; violence is
synonymous with hockey. You put the equipment on, you take a chance
when you go out there. I think it was a shock for everybody really
because everything was being taken care of by the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL preferred the matter remain in-house. If convicted,
McSorley could face 18 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next case that comes up, it's a fine line between them
deciding to take it to court and the league dealing with it,''
Canucks defenseman Greg Hawgood said. ``I think certainly you're
not going out there thinking that if you do something that you're
going to get arrested. Next time, who's to make the judgment what's
over the line and what isn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven other NHL players have preceded McSorley into court for
on-ice infractions. All have been acquitted or handed minor
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Dino Ciccarelli, then of the Minnesota North Stars, is the most
recent player to appear in a courtroom for an on-ice incident. He
got one day in jail and a $1,000 fine for hitting Toronto
defenseman Luke Richardson on the head several times with his stick
in 1988. Now the question is whether criminal charges will prevent
a similar incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it will definitely provide a deterrent,'' Stars
forward Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``Those are extreme, isolated
incidents; none of that is good for the league.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-00 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
