<DOCNO> NYT20000308.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-AGE-HURTS-KAN &LR;      03-08 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGE-HURTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGE-HURTS-WHEN-YOU'RE-TRYING-TO-GET-YOUR-FOOT-IN-THE-DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 &HT;    c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Age discrimination is rampant, if not probably, then at least in
perception. Most 40-year-old-plus job hunters tell tales of
unanswered resumes, unreturned phone calls or unpleasant interviews
based on what they believe is age bias.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fraction of them take their claims to court, and an even
smaller fraction of the complaints are resolved in their favor. Age
bias is monstrously difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate interviewers know age discrimination is against the
law. Most are trained to avoid blatant age-related questions or
comments. Other than rejecting older applicants for being
``overqualified'' or ``too high-priced,'' little is said.
</P>
<P>
   Older job seekers are left with only the suspicion that their
age was a barrier. That's why I read with interest an age
discrimination study, ``No Foot in the Door,'' published last year
in the Journal of Aging &AMP; Social Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Using a systematic social science research technique, the Fair
Employment Council of Greater Washington and AARP sponsored four
pairs of job applicant testers. Each pair consisted of a
57-year-old and a 32-year-old, trained and equipped with equal
resumes and qualifications for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The pairs responded to 140 help-wanted ads and completed the
interview process, posing as actual job candidates, in 102 cases.
</P>
<P>
   The controlled study concluded: ``Older applicants received a
more favorable response than younger applicants in 1 percent of the
tests, while younger applicants received a more favorable response
than their older partners 42.2 percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The net disadvantage to older workers was 41.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``approximately three-quarters of the net disadvantage to
older applicants _ 31.4 percent out of 41.2 percent _ occurred at
the pre-interview stage. Thus, while older testers fared less well
than their younger counterparts in all phases of the application
process, the majority of their disadvantage arose immediately upon
contacting employers, before they could present their
qualifications fully. As the title of this paper states, they could
not get their foot in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiment also found that when employers used employment
agencies to screen applicants, the older applicants were treated
less favorably than their younger counterparts 84 percent of the
time, compared with 29 percent when no intermediary agency was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   But, after obtaining the statistical indication of age bias, the
testers' experiences couldn't add much detail. Explicit negative
comments to older applicants were reported in only 2.9 percent of
the interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And, in more indirect rebuffs, only 13.8 percent of the older
applicants were told their salary expectations were too high. Five
other stereotypes about older workers _ lack of energy, rigidity,
technological obsolescence, lack of motivation or physical
limitations _ were mentioned in even fewer cases.
</P>
<P>
   The study ended with the workplace perception that older workers
started with: Age hurts, and it's hard to know exactly how to stop
the ache.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
