<HEADLINE>
TONY GEORGE SCORES WITH FORMULA ONE AT INDY 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mere mention of Tony George's name usually is enough to trigger
an argument among motorsports fans.
</P>
<P>
   Most would agree that George's decision to bring the NASCAR
Winston Cup Series to the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in 1994 was
an act of sheer genius. Or given NASCAR's runaway popularity, a
no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Many would contend that George's decision to launch the Indy
Racing League in 1996, prompting a schism that continues to divide
and dilute domestic open-wheel racing, was an act of sheer
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are we to think about George's successful quest to lure
Formula One back to the United States, to the most famous address
in American motorsports? F1 will unpack its crates the week of
Sept. 24 at the corner of 16th Street and Georgetown Road in
Indianapolis, at the Speedway owned by George and his family.
</P>
<P>
   I'm lining up with Mr. George on this one, convinced the
permanent home IMS will provide and the current boom in motorsports
worldwide will make the inaugural United States Grand Prix at
Indianapolis a got-to-be-there event.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 F1 schedule begins in Australia this weekend with an
intriguing story line. Two-time and reigning World Driving Champion
Mika Hakkinen of Finland is in position to join Juan Manuel Fangio
as only the second driver to win three consecutive F1
championships. Hakkinen and McLaren International teammate David
Coulthard of Great Britain will be pitted against their storied
rivals, reigning constructors' champion Scuderia Ferrari, where
1994-95 F1 champion Michael Schumacher of Germany has been paired
with new teammate Rubens Barrichello of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The race at Indy will be Round 15 of 17 composing the Federation
Internationale de l'Automobile World Championship. The race at IMS
will cover 73 laps over a 2.606-mile road course carved into the
Speedway's infield. The course also will incorporate portions of
the 2.5-mile oval track, most notably the frontstretch, where the
cars will race clockwise from the bottom of Turn 1, past the yard
of bricks at the start/finish line and into Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, opposite of the direction used by
competitors in the IRL's Indianapolis 500 and NASCAR's Brickyard
400. Like the course its drivers will race on, F1 at Indy initially
figures to be an acquired taste. But George, the president of IMS,
is convinced that motorsporting America really does get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be a successful event,'' said George, who
brokered the deal to bring F1 back with Bernie Ecclestone,
president of the powerful Formula One Constructors Association.
``The key is to put on an entertaining race that will sustain that
interest. Formula One has been criticized for not having much of a
show, but I think they're aware of what it takes to be successful
in the United States, with competition for the entertainment dollar
being what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   F1's glory days in the United States were recorded during a
20-year run from 1961-80 on the famed road course at Watkins Glen
(N.Y.) International. But F1 exited the United States in 1991 after
the second of two poorly promoted and attended street races in
Phoenix. That followed earlier stops in Long Beach, Calif., Las
Vegas, Detroit and Dallas _ venues where the sport priced itself
out of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a following for Formula One in this
country, it's just waned a bit,'' said George, who added the
Speedway already has received more ticket applications for the F1
race than it did for the inaugural Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an early indication that it will be a different fan,''
George said, meaning a global fan. ``We're trying to expand our
customer base, and that's good. Formula One is not going to be as
profitable as the Indy 500 or the Brickyard 400. But as far as it
being a jewel in a crown, it's going to be every bit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevy change sets stage for `Aero Wars' rhetoric Expect a
weekend's worth of ``Aero Wars'' whining at Atlanta Motor Speedway
beginning tomorrow, when Chevrolet teams practice and qualify with
revised front air dams on their beleaguered 2000 Monte Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials announced Monday that Chevy teams will be
allowed to extend their front air dams two inches below the bumper,
with the intention of creating more front downforce. Through the
season's first three races, Chevy teams have complained that the
Monte Carlo is generating too much downforce on the rear end _
creating a lifting condition on the front of the car that reduces
traction through the corners and makes turning difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Petree, who fields the Monte Carlos driven by Joe Nemechek
and Kenny Wallace, said Tuesday morning that he honestly didn't
know what effect the ``kickout'' change will have on that
persistent ``pushing'' condition at the lightning-fast, 1.54-mile
AMS quadoval.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR is trying to do something to even out the cars,'' said
Petree, a former championship-winning crew chief with Dale
Earnhardt. ``It's the easiest, quickest thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Petree estimated the change could add 60 pounds of downforce to
the front end of the Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevy presented a car that we wanted \Rto NASCAR\S, and we
didn't get it,'' Petree said. ``They had some target numbers they
wanted us to hit ... and the car came in better than NASCAR wanted
to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roush, who fields five Ford Taurus teams, said he believes
that 65 pounds of downforce would make the Monte Carlo an
aerodynamic match for the numbers Dale Jarrett's Daytona
500-winning Ford posted during wind tunnel testing after the season
opener last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``So \RNASCAR\S just said, `OK, you guys \RChevy\S screwed up.
This will fix you,' '' Roush said. ``I think they gave them instant
relief on their problem. It's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Petree said he ultimately would like to see the Monte Carlo get
an extended nose, and its template reshaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lot of changes there,'' Petree said. ``We can
change this in a day and not change any of the templates. It's the
easiest thing right off, and we'll see what it does.''
QUICK HITS A financial casualty Rockwall-based TeamXtreme's
decision to replace popular John Hollansworth Jr. with Davey
Hamilton as its lead Indy Racing League driver was financially
driven.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of large associate \Rsponsors\S that were
tied to John that were lost,'' said John Lopes, team manager. ``We
had to do something from a financial standpoint to keep operation
of the team going. Davey's signing did make a significant financial
impact. We're also fortunate that Davey is a talented driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 37, is the only driver to have started all 35 IRL
races, including the 2000 season opener in January. He also is a
two-time championship runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth, a 36-year-old resident of Dallas, was the only
rookie to qualify for all 10 races last year. He also was the
fastest rookie qualifier at the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is to put John back in a car as soon as possible,''
Lopes said. But Lopes added that might not be until the 2001
season.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton will drive the No. 16 TeamXtreme Lycos G Force/Aurora
as teammate to rookie Airton Dare. Lopes said a major sponsorship
announcement is planned before Round 2 of the series at Phoenix
International Raceway on March 19. Wives plan marrow benefit Racing
wives Kim Labonte, Brooke Gordon and Jada Nadeau have schedule the
``Hendrick Wives Luncheon for Life'' at The Renaissance Worthington
Hotel in Fort Worth on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon will benefit the Hendrick Marrow Program,
established in 1997 after Hendrick Motorsports founder Rick
Hendrick was diagnosed with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   The program will feature a question-and-answer session with the
wives of Hendrick NASCAR Winston Cup drivers Terry Labonte, Jeff
Gordon and Jerry Nadeau, and a first-hand account from a marrow
patient.
</P>
<P>
   Seating is limited to 200 at $50 per person, or $500 for a table
of 10. To receive an order form, contact Scottie Lindsay at (704)
455-0555. Last laps A title sponsor for next month's NASCAR Busch
Grand National Series race at Texas Motor Speedway will be
announced during a news conference at the track this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   TMS' ticket office will put on sale less than 1,000 frontstretch
seats for the April 2 NASCAR Winston Cup DirecTV 500 beginning at 9
a.m. tomorrow. The tickets, returned by either season ticket
holders or corporate sponsors, range from $70 to $96. Tickets can
be ordered by phone at (817) 215-8500 or purchased in person.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte took over the Winston Cup points lead
for the first time in his eight-year career at Las Vegas Motor
Speedway Sunday. Reigning series champion Dale Jarrett, who trails
Labonte by only four points, had held the lead for the past 26
consecutive races dating to May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Cup champion Jeff Gordon, who won the March race at
Atlanta Motor Speedway in 1999 and two of the past three in
Hampton, Ga., has gone eight races without a top-five finish.
Including five races at the end of 1999, it the longest such streak
in Gordon's 226-race Cup career. Last words ``How fast is Atlanta?
Well, if your life flashes before your eyes there, you have to be
under 18 years of age to get it all in.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Andretti, Winston Cup driver, on racing around Atlanta
Motor Speedway
</P>
</TEXT>
