<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PORGY-OPERA-REVIEW-AR     03-08 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORGY-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PORGY AND BESS': GETTING MORE THAN YOU BARGAINED FOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So beguiling is its songfulness that ``Porgy and
Bess'' can conceal how complicated it really is. George Gershwin
called his piece ``a folk opera.'' The words might apply to
Carlisle Floyd's ``Susannah'' or the Douglas Moore ``Ballad of Baby
Doe'' _ both compact, simple in outline and beholden to the larger
musical impulses that shaped them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess,'' which opened the New York City Opera's
spring season on Tuesday, has larger ambitions. It also poses more
problems for the people who put it on. Gershwin's music begins at
the meeting place of black and Eastern European sensibilities,
namely, the American musical theater of the 1920s and '30s. But the
composer's assiduous studies of Southern culture and, more
important, his restless investigations into the European
avant-garde take him, for better or worse, beyond the aspirations
of an Irving Berlin or Jerome Kern.
</P>
<P>
   The operatic formula of principal singers in small handfuls plus
chorus is turned here into something almost impossibly dense.
Nearly every chorister in ``Porgy'' is an important solo performer,
and every principal a chorus member. Act I is a swirling street
scene with crap games, daily chores and flashes of extreme
violence, and it is here that the City Opera's new production
momentarily falters.
</P>
<P>
   The multiplicity is driven by Gershwin's unpredictable forward
movement and his insistence on taking popular-music harmony to the
point of near-atonality. So swept along are listeners by the sheer
charm of his materials that they tend not to notice the collision
courses on which all this sweet consonance has been set. Singers,
equally charmed and surprised, can find themselves on the wrong
pitch in unexpected keys; indeed, this is not easy music to sing.
Interestingly, Gershwin, deep in the embrace of Broadway and
Hollywood, was a fervent admirer of Alban Berg's ``Lyric Suite''
and made a point of paying homage to the composer while on a
European tour.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who arrived after intermission on Tuesday would have
thought themselves in the middle of a first-rate performance. By
this time, the vagaries of execution had passed. The orchestra
conducted by John DeMain seemed more settled into a style of
playing these players do not encounter every night. The singers had
ceased to press and fall into bouts of toneless shouting. Stage and
pit had found better ways of doing the same thing at precisely the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   This is, for the most part, a cast deep in quality. Anita
Johnson's pure soprano gave ``Summer Time'' its customary magic.
Angela Simpson's ``My Man's Gone Now'' was perhaps the grandest
moment. Dwayne Clark as Sportin' Life sang handsomely, and he is a
rubbery athlete onstage. Timothy Robert Blevins (Crown), an
excellent baritone, radiated the necessary menace. Kenneth Floyd
(Jake) and Sabrina Elayne Carten (Maria) had fine moments. Adina
Aaron's brief turn as the Strawberry Woman was winning indeed.
Porgy has much to compete with in the opening scenes, but Alvy
Powell's portrayal found its center later on. This is a powerful,
musicianly and well-directed deep voice. Powell, moreover, has a
presence: he occupies the stage when given the opportunity. Bess
was more of a problem. Marquita Lister has the looks and aura if
only she did not try so hard.
</P>
<P>
   Lister's overwrought behavior made Bess less a foxy loser than a
frantic neurotic. All that waving of arms, rolling of eyes,
clutching of brow and side-to-side staggering seemed to confuse
Gershwin's naturalistic opera with a low-rent production of ``Lucia
di Lammermoor.'' The voice is a little tired, but it can be very
effective. Lister might consider the possibility that Bess needs
less help.
</P>
<P>
   Tazewell Thompson (the director) and Julie Arenal (the
choreographer) see the Broadway side of ``Porgy.'' Ensembles become
elaborate dance numbers. They look fine _ as do the vivid fight
scenes _ but seem to pull ``Porgy'' out of its dramatic mood, the
story thread and its emotional baggage being interrupted if not
lost. If the choreography jars, however, it is valuable for
pointing out the contrariness of the piece itself, a ``folk opera''
in which high and low cultures are both partners and antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   The opera begins with built-in problems. When the music stops,
``Porgy and Bess'' falls into deep lulls. The visits of the police
are dead spots; purely spoken passages do not connect; they
separate. The City Opera's utilitarian set, borrowed from the
Sherwin Goldman production of the mid-1980s, will jibe with most
people's image of Catfish Row: a courtyard, ships' masts in the
background, three houses, one of which rotates to an interior. The
picnic on Kittiwah Island looks across the water to the Charleston
skyline.
</P>
<P>
   It is nice to have ``Porgy and Bess'' at the City Opera, a
company that by design and necessity minimizes spectacle and
directs our attention to other things. Performances will continue
in a steady stream. Perhaps Act I will have tightened. There are
some good singers here, and an opera that is both flawed and
profoundly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PORGY AND BESS'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in three acts by George Gershwin, libretto by DuBose
Heyward, with lyrics by Heyward and Ira Gershwin, based on the play
``Porgy'' by DuBose and Dorothy Heyward; conductor, John DeMain;
stage director, Tazewell Thompson; set by Douglas W. Schmidt;
costumes by Nancy Potts; lighting by Robert Wierzel; choreography
by Julie Arenal. At the New York City Opera.
</P>
<P>
   With: Marquita Lister (Bess), Alvy Powell (Porgy), Angela
Simpson (Serena), Timothy Robert Blevins (Crown), Dwayne Clark
(Sportin' Life), Sabrina Elayne Carten (Maria), Anita Johnson
(Clara), Kenneth Floyd (Jake) and Adina Aaron (Strawberry Woman). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
