<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: AUSTRIA PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Crowds demonstrated outside Parliament in Bern to protest an
official visit by Austria's foreign minister, Benita
Ferrero-Waldner, left. The decision to welcome Ferrero-Waldner runs
counter to the European Union's decision to freeze relations with
Austria because of the inclusion of the far-right Freedom Party in
its government. Switzerland is not a member of the union, and a
spokesman said it was traditional for the two neighbors to invite
new government members to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: JEWS UNHAPPY WITH POPE
</P>
<P>
   Several leading Jewish groups in Italy and the United States,
including the Anti-Defamation League, said they were not fully
satisfied with the apology that Pope John Paul II intends to give
Sunday for the historic errors of the Catholic Church. A Vatican
document outlining the theological precedents for the apology,
mentions, along with the Crusades and the Inquisition, the church's
past injustices toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: NAZI TALKS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   The government said talks would resume March 21 in Berlin to try
to resolve a bitter dispute over how $5 billion in compensation for
Nazi-era slave workers and forced laborers should be divided. The
sum was agreed upon last December, but two days of talks in
Washington this week failed to resolve the question of who should
be the largest beneficiaries. The forced laborers are mainly
non-Jews from Central and East European countries overrun by Nazi
troops.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUES CLAIM BOMBINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Basque separatist group ETA took responsibility for two car
bombings that have killed a Socialist Party leader and two security
officials since January. The rebels, in a statement in the Basque
newspaper Gara, also criticized two moderate Basque parties
competing in Sunday's general elections, while the leftist party
considered the rebels' political wing had not entered the race and
called on voters to abstain.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREANS VISIT
</P>
<P>
   North Korean officials ended a secret five-day trip to Ottawa,
an exchange for a similarly secret visit by three Canadian
diplomats to Pyongyang in December. North Korea does not have
diplomatic relations with Canada, whose troops fought in the Korean
War. The Canada visit is part of a wider North Korean thaw, which
includes the resumption of food aid by Japan and the establishment
of diplomatic ties with Italy.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPTIAN TIED TO PLOT
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian refugee arrested on charges of possessing explosives
and counterfeit money was part of a plot to bomb Israeli diplomatic
offices in Canada in a bid to press Israel to free Lebanese
prisoners, The Montreal Gazette reported. Citing Mountie
investigators, the paper said the Israeli Consulate in Montreal
received a bomb threat last week and that an informant named the
Egyptian, Tarek Adealy Khafagy, as part of a bomb plot.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA
</P>
<P>
   KHMER ROUGE TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The chief legal counsel of the United Nations,
Undersecretary-General Hans Corell, will go to Cambodia next week
to try to reach agreement with Prime Minister Hun Sen on setting up
a war crimes tribunal for the Khmer Rouge. Hun Sen wants to control
the tribunal; the United Nations says his plan does not conform to
international justice standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
