<HEADLINE>
USC RECRUIT WILL VISIT OTHER SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Travis Hanour's verbal commitment to USC is not
quite as solid as last week, as the 6-foot-6 guard from Laguna
Beach High has rescheduled a trip to Arizona for this weekend and
probably will visit Utah next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hanour committed to the Trojans on Feb. 27, and promptly
canceled his remaining recruiting trips to Arizona and Utah. But
Hanour said Wednesday that his father wanted him to visit those
schools before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to visit Arizona and maybe Utah after that,'' Hanour
said. ``Right now, I'm still committed (to USC). It doesn't really
change it. After I visit the other places, I'll be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanour, who averaged 25.7 points, 9.7 rebounds and 5.4 assists
at Laguna Beach, said he just wants to check out all his options.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if was definitely going to attend USC, Hanour said,
``I'm not really sure. Right now, USC is on top, but once I visit
the other places I'll be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanour was USC's No. 1 recruiting priority for the spring, and
the Trojans believe he can play point guard, shooting guard and
small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Practice at Sports Arena: The Trojans practiced Wednesday at the
Sports Arena, but it wasn't in response to the gas leak Tuesday
that forced part of the campus - including the Physical Education
building - to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   It just happened to be a day when the Sports Arena was available
for practice, and wasn't being used for another event. USC has
practiced there only a handful of times this season, because of
availability and cost factors.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for bid: USC coach Henry Bibby did not want to speculate
on whether the Trojans (14-14, 7-9) will make the National
Invitation Tournament, but said he would be happy to play in the
sometimes-maligned tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be disappointed if we didn't get in? Yeah,'' Bibby
said. ``I'm not like UCLA, I want to get into any tournament. If we
don't, that's life. That's something you live with. We determined
our destination before these last two games. I can't be upset over
what happens now. I don't have any control over what happens
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   What might have been? Bibby lamented the Trojans' late-season
slide in which they lost eight of their past nine games, and went
3-7 when leading scorer Sam Clancy was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tearing me up because I know how good we can be,'' Bibby
said. ``We've been close in games even without Sam. I couldn't ask
the other guys to play harder. Am I disappointed in the kids? No.
They have fought for me. I don't think there's any game I was
disappointed with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Women of Troy update: USC's women's basketball team is in a
similar situation to the men. It probably cannot afford another
loss if it hopes to secure a bid to the women's NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to win both games,'' USC coach Chris Gobrecht
said.
</P>
<P>
   USC has already notified the tournament it will not host a
first-round game, which means the Women of Troy (13-13, 8-8) could
conceivably play Pepperdine in Malibu if they make the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   USC vs. WASHINGTON Tipoff: 7 p.m., Sports Arena. TV/Radio: No
TV; XTRA-AM (690)
</P>
<P>
   USC (14-14, 7-9) update: The Trojans are trying to keep their
NIT hopes alive and need to sweep the Washington schools. USC
defeated the Huskies 81-79 in overtime on Jan. 8. Forward Brian
Scalabrine (strained hip) will play, as will guard Jeff Trepagnier
(swollen eye). Forward Sam Clancy had minor swelling this week
after returning from his broken-right-foot injury but is OK and
will play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (10-18, 5-11) update: The Huskies are just happy that
a disappointing season is coming to a close. Washington has
struggled but won two of its past four games, including a stunning
67-58 victory over Oregon at McArthur Court on Feb. 19. It is 6-7
on the road, and senior Deon Luton is averaging 15.2 points per
game.
</P>
<P>
   - Scott Wolf
</P>
</TEXT>
