<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-U.S.-1STLD-WRITEHTRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S NEW CHOICE FOR IMF CHIEF GETS TEPID RECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change spelling of Kohler to Koehler, and Hoerst to
Horst.)  
( mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defying warnings that history might repeat itself,
Germany began a diplomatic offensive to install one of its
nationals as head of the International Monetary Fund and received a
generally lukewarm reception Wednesday in both Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder began lobbying European neighbors
and the United States to support Horst Koehler, president of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, to head the IMF.
But Schroeder misjudged, if he expected that his nation's allies
would quickly rally around the new German candidate after the first
one he promoted was forced to give up a four-month quest to lead
the monetary fund.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton pointedly declined to endorse Koehler in a
telephone conversation with the German chancellor Tuesday. White
House officials said the president had a friendly conversation with
Schroeder in which he took a neutral position on Koehler's
qualifications for the job.
</P>
<P>
   European officials also have not rushed to Germany's side.
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini delivered a frank public
assessment in which he said that Koehler was ``less than had been
hoped for.'' A spokesman for British Prime Minister Tony Blair said
Europe had not rallied behind Koehler, who once served as a close
aide to Helmut Kohl, Schroeder's longtime rival and predecessor as
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   French and Portuguese officials made much more positive
comments. But it seemed unlikely that Germany could forge an
immediate, Europe-wide consensus that Koehler ought to be the
region's unified choice to lead the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Germany's decision to throw its considerable
political heft behind a new candidate and campaign publicly for him
will work this time. Some German allies, including the United
States, are eager to avoid the impression that they are picking
fights with Germany, and Koehler is widely considered a better
choice than the previous candidate, Ciao Koch-Weser, Germany's
deputy finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   But it also seemed possible that Germany, by choosing a person
who does not top the lists of Europe's most qualified and
politically prominent financial officials, had set itself up for a
another stinging defeat. That is especially true because both
European and American officials have put a high priority on finding
someone who can quickly command support and end the prolonged and
divisive search for an IMF managing director.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the 182 member nations of the IMF rebuffed
Germany when they denied Koch-Weser, a close ally of Schroeder, a
majority of their votes in an informal poll. Koch-Weser had the
backing of the 15-nation European Union, which has named every IMF
managing director since the financial institution was created just
after World War II. But Europe's support was tepid, and Clinton
went public with his vow to stop the German's candidacy after
months of quiet diplomacy failed to dissuade Germany from promoting
him.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other critics had argued that Koch-Weser,
a 25-year veteran of the World Bank and a specialist in poverty
relief, did not have the political stature or the financial
expertise to head the IMF, which has been likened to a world
central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler has considerably more financial experience and is better
known around Europe, but his background is in some ways similar to
Koch-Weser's.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, 57, was long allied with the Christian Democratic
Union, the party Schroeder defeated when he took power last year.
He served as an economic aide to Kohl, the longtime chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Koehler served in the No. 2 position at
Germany's finance ministry, the position Koch-Weser holds today. In
that job, Koehler helped manage Germany's financial relations with
Europe at a time when the region was working out the details of
monetary union. But he was better known for helping to arrange the
terms of unification with Germany's formerly Communist eastern
half, and then overseeing the massive injection of public funds
aimed at rebuilding the old East Germany. He also had a stint in
the private sector, managing Germany's federation of savings banks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Koehler now heads the London-based European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, a mini-World Bank that backs
development projects and businesses in Eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union. He took the post just after the quasi-public
bank wrote off tens of millions of dollars worth of loans when
Russia, its leading client, defaulted on its debt in the summer of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have declined to comment on
Koehler's candidacy. Moreover, they seem determined to avoid a
repeat of their role in defeating Koch-Weser, when Clinton publicly
played the heavy while some European countries hid their true
feelings behind the veil of European solidarity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But administration officials were also hoping that Europe would
select a candidate who would obviate the need for extended debate.
Among the several senior politicians in Europe talked about as
potential candidates are the current and former British chancellors
of the exchequer and the Italian finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support a European candidate, a candidate of maximum
stature, who can generate a consensus in Europe and support from
developing countries,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
Wednesday when asked about Germany's push for Koehler.
</P>
<P>
   Outside observers said that Koehler did have the resume of an
IMF leader.
</P>
<P>
   C. Fred Bergsten of the Institute for International Economics in
Washington said that Koehler had more financial expertise than
Koch-Weser and that he would do a good job at the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knock on him is this notion of stature _ that they want
someone who has had a Cabinet-level job in finance for the IMF,''
Bergsten said. ``There's also a sense that he hasn't really
distinguished himself at the EBRD.''
</P>
</TEXT>
