<HEADER>
A1334 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      03-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Steve Francis doesn't act like your run-of-the-mill rookie. And he
certainly doesn't play like one, either.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Francis sure sounds like a typical rookie when he discusses
one subject _ the Utah Jazz, which the Rockets meet tonight at the
Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Just like every other rookie _ especially a rookie point guard _
who has ever run into the Jazz, Francis has some definite opinions
about how Utah plays the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I think they're a dirty team,'' Francis said. ``I think
they do a lot of grabbing and a lot of pushing. Karl Malone does a
lot of knee-into-the-stomach (on drives) and stuff like that, so we
have to be prepared for that and be aggressive. We have a lot of
guys on our team who can get dirty, too. Hopefully, it'll be a war,
and we'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly can seem like war, what with all the bodies that
hit the floor during a typical Utah game.
</P>
<P>
   John Stockton brings the ball upcourt, running his man through a
forest of picks before finally introducing the defender to Malone,
whose rugged picks are legendary. And Utah's penchant for
``extracurricular'' activity is also usually a subject of
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley endured that initiation last year as a rookie
point guard, and he is helping to counsel Francis on maintaining
his focus against the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be so smart,'' Mobley said. ``That's the best
fundamental team in the league, so you have to be very smart up
there. Stockton is a smart player. He may not be as fast or as
athletic as the rest of the point guards out there, but he uses his
head, which is the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Utah players use a bit more than their heads. They
also use elbows, knees or whatever other body part seems to do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard for me to believe the first couple of
times (against the Jazz) that they would get away with stuff like
that,'' Francis said. ``But they've been playing that way for
years, and they have the respect from the league, and hopefully one
day I'll be able to get that respect from the league, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is sour grapes, even though two of Francis' worst
games have come against the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   No, Utah seems to relish every opportunity to run a rookie
through the meat grinder it calls an offense. And the overly
physical approach usually works.
</P>
<P>
   It has on Francis, who has averaged just 6.5 points in his two
games against Utah, making five of 18 shots and turning the ball
over 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both games that we've played them, I've had terrible games,''
Francis said. ``For me, I think I have to go in there with a
different mindset, that I'm going to play good defense and
neutralize John Stockton _ his passing and his scoring _ and
hopefully we'll get a victory up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets haven't won in Salt Lake City in more than three
years, since they beat the Jazz 75-72 on Nov. 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have been blown out twice this season by the Jazz,
losing both games by 16-point margins, something that grates on
Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game (at Utah), it was our second game of the season,
and I was so excited,'' said Francis, who had just eight points on
3-of-8 shooting in that 98-82 loss. ``In our second game, I
sprained my ankle in the second quarter and couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hobbling the whole game (finishing with five points on
2-of-10 shooting in a 103-87 loss on Jan. 8). This time I just want
to go up there and be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since the Rockets will turn the scene of the crime
into the scene of the cram, doing some extra pre-game work to help
everyone recognize and defeat the tedious (yet effective) Utah
offensive sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our shootaround meeting (at Wednesday's practice), and
we're going to have it again (before today's game) because we want
to emphasize that stuff,'' said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
``Early before the game, before the guys come out shooting, our
staff does a great job of talking to them about the particular
problems of that day.''
</P>
<P>
   And those lessons will be tested again tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (Utah's physical play) is kind of hard, and it wears on you
late in the game,'' Francis said. ``But once the fourth quarter
comes around, that's where I think good players get their energy
and just find a way to suck it up and be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
