<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' KENNY ROGERS PERFECT FOR THREE INNINGS BEFORE TIRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL and T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Kenny Rogers says he wants to throw his
fastball over the inner half of the plate with consistency this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's performance gave Rogers no reason to alter those
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers retired nine consecutive batters and recorded four
strikeouts through three innings before tiring in the fourth inning
of the Rangers' 8-6, 10-inning victory against the Minnesota Twins
in Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers required only 24 pitches to retire the Twins' first nine
hitters, and he benefited from pitching inside effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two guys had to chase down and away,'' Rogers said.
``If you work inside, it expands the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers surrendered two singles and a walk in the fourth inning
before being removed with two outs and a pitch count of 43.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to hit a wall around 40 or so pitches, and that's
what happened,'' Rogers said. ``You know it's going to happen
sooner or later, and you just try to push it back further the next
time out.'' \Nsubheds:Cuban pitcher interest The Rangers have
expressed preliminary interest in pitcher Adrian ``El Duquecito''
Hernandez, the latest Cuban defector being shopped to major-league
teams. Rangers scouting director Chuck McMichael said he plans to
attend a showcase tryout Tuesday in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``But beyond that, I don't know what our interest is,''
McMichael said. ``Right now, everything is preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 25, is no relation to the Yankees' Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez, but has a similar knee-jerk delivery that earned
him the nickname ``Little Duque.'' He had a 2.67 earned-run average
for a Cuban team last year and was part of the Cuban all-star team
that faced the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plunged into the Cuban market last month, signing
second baseman Jorge Diaz and third baseman Osmani Garcia. They
also offered more than $3 million to former Cuban pitcher Danys
Baez before he signed a four-year, $14 million contract with the
Cleveland Indians in November. \Nsubheds:Greer's ankle tested Left
fielder Rusty Greer's inflamed right ankle was tested in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Greer had to sprint to catch a shallow fly hit by Torii Hunter.
Greer is playing despite the discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not 100 percent, but he's ready to play,'' said Johnny
Oates, who expects Greer in today's lineup against the Boston Red
Sox. \Nsubheds:Waiting on Diaz The Rangers hope infielder Jorge
Diaz will arrive for camp this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers planned to introduce Diaz at a news conference
today, but visa problems will prevent him from arriving. The
Rangers signed the former member of the Cuban National Team last
monthand invited him to major-league camp as a nonroster player.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz played for Cuba's National Team from 1995-97 before
defecting in August 1998. Diaz moved to the Dominican Republic in
October after stops in Nicaragua and Costa Rica. \Nsubheds:Briefly
Closer John Wetteland (strain, right calf) received treatment but
did not throw. Reliever Mike Venafro (ligament strain, left middle
finger) played catch on flat ground. Pitcher Justin Thompson
(rehabilitation, left shoulder) reported no discomfort after
throwing 43 pitches from a distance of 55 feet. Second baseman
Jason Romano, perhaps the Rangers' best prospect not invited to
major-league camp, was 1-for-1 in Tuesday's minor-league game for
those who reported early. Regular minor-league camps open tomorrow
for pitchers and catchers and Saturday for other position players.
The organization scheduled its Rangers/Arlington Chamber of
Commerce Welcome Home Luncheon for March 31 at the Arlington
Convention Center. Manager Johnny Oates, his staff and members of
the Opening Day roster are scheduled to attend. The event will
include a silent auction and balloon bash for special prizes.
Tickets cost $45, and tables for 10 can be purchased for $450.
Tickets can be purchased by calling (817) 273-5100. Call (817)
273-5187 for more information.
</P>
<P>
</P>
