<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON FOLLOWING MARCH MADNESS THE HIGH-TECH WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Selection Sunday gets here, it might be a good idea to
check out the high-tech ways to track March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few recommendations for:
</P>
<P>
   Fans who want to be millionaires: Pick a perfect men's
tournament bracket starting on CNNSI.com (hoopschallenge.cnnsi.com)
on Sunday and win $10 million. The catch: You must be perfect
throughout the bracket, which means no misses and no lifelines from
Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   If you really need advice, ask Robert Segreti, a weather
forecaster at Vance Air Force Base in Enid, Okla. Of more than
402,000 entrants in ESPN.com's Men's Tournament Challenge last
year, Segreti did the best, forecasting winners in 46 of 63 games,
including the quarterfinalists and the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Official word: FinalFour.net offers all the official merchandise
and sanitized news, but the coolest section is its wireless
information (www.finalfour.net/2000/wireless). Users can find out
how to set up their digital cellular phones or hand-held computers
to track scores. Fans with cell phones can program their phone's
short message service to receive on-demand scores, tipoff
notification, scoring updates every four minutes, time remaining in
the game and top rebounding and scoring statistics at the end of
the game. For hand-held computers, such as the Palm VII, the site
offers a file to download to enable the device to track scores.
FoxSports.com and ESPN.com also provide updates for digital devices
for scoring updates.
</P>
<P>
   Desk-bound fans: CBS SportsLine benefits from its relationship
with CBS Sports with its March Mayhem
(cbs.sportsline.com/u/madness/2000) site. Its marquee feature is
Tournament LIVE, a multimedia application with real-time stats and
simulated fan sounds from the game. The bad news for
non-basketball-loving office managers bent on productivity: Audio
links to SportsLine Radio can be accessed on Thursdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   People who like to chat with coaches: Talk it up on Sunday on
The National Association of Basketball Coaches' official site
(www.nabc.com). Six coaches are scheduled for Chat Madness on
Sunday. Suggested question: ``What's up with Gene Keady's hair?''
</P>
<P>
   Stats geeks: CNNSI.com is promoting its section called
Statitudes (cnnsi.com/statitudes), which will have instant,
comprehensive statistics on everything from assists leaders to
offbeat stats.
</P>
<P>
   Cool multimedia: MSNBCSports.com users can follow each game via
its TotalCast feature. A popup window offers real-time coverage,
including play-by-play, shooting charts, statistics and photos.
</P>
<P>
   Running the office pool: Tourney Tracker 2000
(www.TourneyTracker2000.com) automates the office pool process with
a paperless bracket ... so no more wasting office supplies. The
tracker computes the contest based on the scoring options entered.
When the Sweet Sixteen is established, the tracker tells the pool
manager who has a chance to win by calculating results for every
possible scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Day-traders: In case the stock market didn't rock your world
enough this week, a San Francisco-based interactive fantasy sports
company features a game with a Wall Street twist. Through Sunday,
SPORTSDAQ.com members can build an online portfolio of tournament
teams and match it against an index of 100 of the hottest
technology stocks for prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Stock brokers: It doesn't include the teams, but ETrade's Market
Madness (etrade.com) has a tournament of 32 stocks divided into
four sectors. Starting March 20, players can earn points by picking
stocks that will perform the best in five progressive rounds. Grand
prize is $100,000.  &LR; subheds:Bytes Sports study: According to a
study released recently by New York-based Jupiter Communications,
consumers are expected to spend approximately $3 billion in
sporting goods, apparel, footwear and event tickets online in 2003.
The study also recommends that media companies focus on current
technology and not go overboard on broadband because less than 5
percent of the U.S. online population has home-based broadband
connections. On conference of TV and Internet, Jupiter found that
more than half of the online audience either sometimes or often
watches TV while online.
</P>
<P>
   New stuff: SportsLine.com is flexing its international muscles
with new sites for sports fans in Germany, Italy and Spain. The
sites focus on six to eight sports for each country, including live
scoring and analysis.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
