<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-08 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-870&AMP;ADD-1STLD-     03-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-870&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN APPEARS READY TO END CAMPAIGN  
 (Eds: Sub to insert 2 new grafs, one just before and one just after
the original 4th graf)  
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ After a day huddled at his vacation cabin with
family and senior aides, Sen. John McCain appeared ready to end his
maverick candidacy, canceling several days worth of appearances in
Colorado and Illinois and scheduling what his aides called ``a
major announcement'' for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement followed a day of discussions on his options
that aides had earlier said would focus on how the senator could
force the Republican party to embrace his reform agenda, most
particularly some form of campaign finance overhaul which was at
the center of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire is to make clear in departure _ if that is what it
is _ that he is serious about reform and his voters are serious
about reform,'' said an adviser. ``And the party in order to win
and pick up his voters is going to have to move that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a day filled with conflicting signs for the McCain
campaign. The senator and his top staff members were separated by
miles from the press corps that normally is constantly at his side.
And many middle- and lower-level staff members were uncertain about
how events were unfolding. The clearest sign came toward the end of
the day when the campaign abruptly canceled campaign events
scheduled for Thursday in Colorado, where Republicans will vote in
a primary Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent supporters said that they had urged McCain to
end his insurgent candidacy within days. But some of his aides were
still defiant on Wednesday morning. Before meeting with the
senator, some of his campaign advisers dropped hints of how
McCain's delegates could disrupt the Republican National Convention
this summer by forcing roll-call votes on his proposals or by
putting McCain's name into nomination, guaranteeing him a prime
speaking platform.
</P>
<P>
   While such battles have been staples of Democratic conventions,
there has not been one at a Republican convention in a generation.
The threat could persuade Bush to move in McCain's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will assess the campaign and the status of the campaign and
the reform movement he so cares about,'' John Weaver, McCain's
political director, said as he headed to McCain's vacation home.
``The options are obvious. Stay in. Get out. Or other options,'' he
added elliptically, referring to a third party bid.
</P>
<P>
   But other advisers said they thought McCain should be taken at
his word that he would be loyal to the party and by Wednesday night
it looked like he was ready to withdraw. Todd Harris, a campaign
spokesman, declined, however, to say what McCain would announce.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain met with his aides, Gov. George W. Bush was clearly
eager on Wednesday to move onto the general election battle against
Vice President Al Gore and indicated that he was prepared to paint
him as a partner in the ethical embarrassments and moral lapses of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up where his victory speech on Tuesday night left off,
Bush said in Austin, Texas, ``If people are happy with Al Gore and
Bill Clinton, the tone they set for America, then you've got a
perfect person to vote for.'' Bush was speaking of Gore, and with
palpable derision.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference in the garden of the Governor's
Mansion, Bush said of his Republican rival that ``John is going to
decide whether he's going to continue on and it's his choice. My
main opponent in this campaign will be Al Gore and our differences
will be stark.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of Bush's supporters in the Senate reached out to McCain's
allies in the hope of healing any rift between the Republican
rivals, enlisting the senator's cooperation for the general
election and uniting the party as best possible.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain signaled in his concession speech Tuesday night that
his wholehearted cooperation with Bush would likely come with a
price when he said, ``Our crusade continues tonight, tomorrow, the
next day, the day after that and for as long as it takes to restore
America's confidence and pride in the practice and institutions of
our great democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCain said that Kenneth Duberstein, a former
White House chief of staff under President Ronald Reagan, and Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., were relaying word to Bush's allies that the
governor had to take the initial step to heal the breach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that Governor Bush is going to need Senator
McCain, not just for John McCain, but for who and what John McCain
represents,'' Hagel said. ``He represents reform as much as any one
dynamic of who McCain is. John McCain is going to want to have a
voice in helping shape a reform agenda in the Republican Party as
we go into the election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of them will have to have a conversation about this
and about campaign finance's priority on a Bush agenda,'' Hagel
said. ``What I'm saying is that a reform agenda will have to be
there for McCain to get enthusiastically engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel emphasized that while he and McCain have talked several
times a day for the past several days, they have not discussed
whether McCain's support for Bush would be conditioned on his
stance toward campaign finance reform.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Bush triumphed over McCain from coast to coast except in
New England on Tuesday, he goes into the general election in a less
commanding position than Gore because he had to turn to the right
to defeat his rival. That has carried a political cost.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's victory in the critical general election state of
California, for example, exit polls showed Bush's win depended on
Republicans. He ran far behind both Gore and McCain among such
critical swing groups as independents and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   A joint front with McCain could help Bush repair some of the
damage and draw to his side the legions of new voters McCain drew
into the primaries. But several aides or advisers to Bush said that
the Texas governor was not offering up specific changes in his
position on overhauling campaign finance regulations simply to
placate McCain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
